<SLUG> BC-BKC-TCU-GONZAGA-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TCU GAINS FROM GAINOUS' JUMPER
</HEADLINE>
 For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WHIT CANNING 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ n an evening when Lee Nailon chisled
himself even deeper into the record book, TCU required a clutch
move from ailing Marquise Gainous to preserve a win.
</P>
<P>
   Gainous, who had not practiced in four days because of a sore
ankle, dropped in a short jumper with 19 seconds remaining to
finally seal a 90-87 victory against Gonzaga's persistent Bulldogs
at Daniel-Meyer Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, we kind of dodged a bullet,'' said TCU coach Billy
Tubbs, who watched his 24th-ranked Frogs (11-2) capture their sixth
consecutive win. ``This team has kind of developed a knack for
doing that and coming up with the right plays.''
</P>
<P>
   Playing their first game in 10 days, the Frogs captured their
16th consecutive home victory behind another huge game from Nailon,
who finished with 44 points and 14 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just happy we won the game,'' said Nailon, who topped 40
points for the fifth time in his TCU career and moved ahead of Jeff
Jacobs and James Penny into 14th place on the school's all-time
scoring list.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the bombardment from Nailon, the Bulldogs (9-4) refused
to go quietly into the night. Trailing by as many as 14 points,
they stormed back with 21 second-half points from beyond the
3-point arc to narrow the gap quickly.
</P>
<P>
   They held only one lead _ when Axel Dench (22 points) put them
up, 83-82, on a drive with 2:35 left, after which Ryan Carroll hit
a trey to put TCU back up by two. But it was tied at 87 with 59
seconds left and Gainous standing at the free-throw line.
</P>
<P>
   He hit one of two shots for an 88-87 lead, and then Shannon Long
got the ball back for TCU on a steal at midcourt.
</P>
<P>
   Then, with TCU maneuvering for a shot after an inbounds play,
Long got the ball to Gainous, who dropped in the winning shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just a play that worked,'' said Carroll. ``Marquise's
man left him to take Shannon, who was bringing the ball down the
baseline and just dished it off.''
</P>
<P>
   Gainous, who was recovering from an ankle sprain, looked pretty
good to Tubbs.
</P>
<P>
   ``He always does,'' Tubbs said. ``Actually, his ankle seems to
be OK now, but we weren't going to take a chance with it. Shannon
has been playing well lately, and he had another good game tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we've played one game since Dec. 12, and we definitely
weren't combat-ready tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not taking anything away from Gonzaga. They're a good
team, and they played well. We stopped hitting our shots in the
second half and they got hot, and kept coming back.''
</P>
<P>
   Nailon said he felt good coming in, but had no idea he was up
for a season-high game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just tried to play my game and take what was there,'' he
said. ``In the second half, I don't think we let up or coasted or
anything. They just packed it close inside with their zone, and the
shots weren't as open anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Tubbs said he was pleased with the win, and perplexed about the
Frogs' schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know who thought this thing up,'' he said. ``It sure
wasn't me. We have another game Saturday and then nine days off.
Then we open conference play with three straight road games.
</P>
<P>
   ``This sounds like something somebody in the WAC thought up.''
</P>
<P>
   TCU will play North Carolina-Asheville at 7:05 p.m. Saturday at
Daniel-Meyer Coliseum.
</P>
</TEXT>
