<HEADLINE>
NFL COACHING CAROUSEL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The domino theory thrives in the NFL coaching theatre.
</P>
<P>
   Even when five heads roll on one day, as they did Monday, you
still have to watch where they go, because they're liable to turn
up almost anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   And half the fun is watching the employed yet potentially
available coaches squirm for bargaining position. The biggest
problem is knowing where to begin. We'll start in Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   Former 49er President Carmen Policy, now the president of the
expansion Browns I'll get used to that phrase as soon as I get used
to St. Louis Rams has already interviewed the two hot assistants,
Vikings offensive coordinator Brian Billick and Broncos offensive
aide Gary Kubiak, and plans to interview several other aides before
he's through.
</P>
<P>
   He will also sit down with Ray Rhodes, the deposed Eagles coach.
But the man he wants is the man he hired to replace George Seifert
in San Francisco, Steve Mariucci.
</P>
<P>
   The latter was supposed to be close to signing a contract
extension with the headless 49ers the team is operating with an
interim president and a couple of secretaries when the lines of
communication suddenly went dead. Here's how much Policy thinks of
Mariucci: He offered the 49ers job to Mariucci, then the Cal coach,
from his car phone as he was pulling into Mariucci's driveway.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Assuming Mariucci leaves, the 49ers would likely offer Packers
coach and ex-49er aide Mike Holmgren the whole G.M.-Coach package.
Holmgren wants to sail his own ship, which Green Bay can't offer
because Ron Wolf is G.M. for life. Holmgren will have leverage,
because Seattle and Carolina could step up with the same kind of
offer. And if Bill Walsh is indeed returning as team
president/meddler, then Holmgren might flinch. Holmgren might try
to talk Rhodes into joining him in 'Frisco as assistant head coach,
with a promise that the coaching job is his sooner than later.
</P>
<P>
   Green Bay.
</P>
<P>
   The intrigue hear is icy. Once Holmgren leaves, Wolf will face
incredible pressure to promote Sherm Lewis, the black assistant
coach who has been passed over several times for head coaching
jobs. It doesn't help that Holmgren has anointed Lewis as the most
qualified assistant in the league. Truth is, Wolf might prefer
Rhodes to Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   The Seahawks want an experienced coach capable of serving as
G.M. and coach. Owner Paul Allen is willing to spend money, but
wants someone who has a clue about talent spending it. The first
move will be towards Holmgren, the second to George Seifert.
</P>
<P>
   Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Panthers owner Jerry Richardson doesn't feel he can hire an
assistant to replace Dom Capers. The fans' expectation got juiced
by that 1996 NFC title appearance, and the team has oodles of inner
turmoil. He's already spoken to Seifert, the man he wants. There's
no strong No. 2 candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   Art Modell, asked what kind of coach he wants, said he'd take
Hitler if he was available. Really. Mr. Modell, meet Ms. Schott.
The Ravens' short list includes Rhodes, Stanford coach Tyrone
Willingham and ex-Raiders coach Art Shell, who played his college
ball in Maryland. Al Davis reportedly has called several teams on
Shell's behalf. I wonder if that call comes with an admission that
Art took a bullet for Al over the Marcus Allen situation?
</P>
<P>
   All three men are black, and all three are qualified. But isn't
it curious that one team would have three black candidates in mind
at a time when several jobs are open? Is Modell paying off a debt
for Paul Tagliabue as part of his move? Is this some kind of faux
affirmative action ploy?
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh defensive coordinator Jim Haslett is the front
runner. Haslett will come cheap, which is the way owner Jeff Lurie
wants it. Lurie is odds-on to be the next NFL owner to cry that
can't make it without a new stadium and order moving vans. The L.A.
Eagles? Doesn't fly.
</P>
<P>
   San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Beathard reportedly will hire someone who is currently an
assistant and willing to go along with a short-term rebuilding
project entitled ``Leaf or bust.'' The Chargers had one of the
highest payrolls in the league, and Beathard wants to trim it.
Terry Donahue may not be interested in those terms, and vice versa.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   The word around the league is that the Bears have no clue who
they'll hire, that G.M. Mike McCaskey made an emotional decision to
fire Dave Wannstedt without having someone in mind to replace him.
Shocking stuff from a team that has eight wins the last two
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   There's speculation that Pete Carroll isn't totally safe in New
England, and that Norv Turner may be out in Washington once the
Redskins franchise is officially sold.
</P>
<P>
   Dick Vermeil was retained in St. Louis for reasons perfectly
understandable to Rams fans in L.A. Georgia Frontiere and John Shaw
didn't want to pay off the balance of his contract. Thus, Vermeil
will be given little help improving the roster and suffer the same
kind of season John Robinson had in his last year as coach of the
L.A. Rams.
</P>
<P>
   And while Billick and Kubiak are ``hot'' assistants, are they
truly the genii behind the Vikings and Broncos' success? Mike
Shanahan runs the Denver offense, and Terrell Davis would make any
offensive coordinator look brilliant. And Billick didn't have a lot
to do with Randall Cunningham's resurgence or the good fortune of
Randy Moss falling into Minnesota's lap.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
