<HEADER>
A2988 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-LOCKOUT-HNS &LR;      12-31 1033
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LOCKOUT-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MURPHY  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
With the NBA season on the verge of being canceled, the league's
players will put together one last proposal in an attempt to end
the 184-day lockout.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Billy Hunter, executive director of the National Basketball
Players Association, sent a memo to every player Wednesday, saying
he intends to present a final offer with the hope of sitting down
with the owners' negotiating committee for one last bargaining
session before the season is lost.
</P>
<P>
   ``The negotiating committee and I will put together our own
`final collective-bargaining proposal,''' wrote Hunter in his memo.
``I have called (NBA commissioner) David Stern and requested an
opportunity to present it to the owners' labor committee as soon as
they're available, and certainly before the Jan. 7 date that Stern
has set as the owners' deadline.''
</P>
<P>
   Stern said that if a settlement isn't reached by the league's
Jan. 7 Board of Governors meeting, he will recommend canceling the
season at that time. Hunter's memo is no doubt a response to
Stern's call for the players to request a vote on the owners'
latest proposal, which was sent Wednesday to every player in the
league.
</P>
<P>
   And with some players, most notably New Jersey All-Star Jayson
Williams, heeding Stern by openly calling for a secret ballot,
Hunter's memo attempts to outline the areas where he feels the
owners' latest proposal is lacking.
</P>
<P>
   It also concedes that the owners have made concessions, somewhat
surprising considering how acrimonious this labor war has been.
</P>
<P>
   ``We appreciate the fact that finally, on the six-month
anniversary of the lockout, the owners have begun to address our
concerns and removed some of the onerous new restraints they have
demanded,'' Hunter wrote. ``Still, the negotiating committee and I
do not believe that the owners have met us halfway yet, and we are
not prepared to recommend that you accept this proposal.''
</P>
<P>
   But Stern is urging players to do just that and sent a letter to
Hunter asking that the proposal, a summary of which was included
with the letter, be put before the union for a vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``While it is, of course, your prerogative to reject our
proposal the consequences of that decision will be so catastrophic
to your members that simple fairness suggests they be given a
chance to be heard,'' Stern wrote. ``Accordingly, we request and
strongly urge that you put the NBA's final offer to a vote of the
entire union membership.''
</P>
<P>
   Union president Patrick Ewing said that if that's what the
players want, that's what they'll get. But until the union hears
from the rank and file, there will be no vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the majority of the players call up and say they want a
vote, then we're bound to vote,'' Ewing said Wednesday. ``But
yesterday, we had a conference call and we put the question to them
if they want a vote. And as of today, no one has called to demand
that we put it to a vote.''
</P>
<P>
   Hunter's memo listed eight points of disagreement with the
owners' proposal, among which were not enough help for the
middle-class and minimum-salary players, a higher percentage of
revenues going to the players in the last three years of a six-year
deal, insufficient salary increases, and adding a fourth option
year as well as a right of first refusal on a fifth year to the
rookie scale.
</P>
<P>
   Also included was a ``list of horribles,'' a creatively named
category that listed the owners' demand to eliminate opt-out
clauses, void Bird-exception status if a player is traded in the
last year of his contract, and limit signing bonuses.
</P>
<P>
   ``It should not be hard to get a deal that makes both sides
equally contented _ or discontented,'' Hunter wrote. ``As I have
said in recent weeks, we are not very far apart, and the owners'
latest offer bridges some of the gaps. It is now a matter of
sitting down for a last bargaining session where we each can reveal
our respective bottom lines and engage in whatever trading may be
necessary to get a deal done.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a handful of players are beginning to voice their
discontent over the union's unwillingness to vote on the owners'
proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the truth,'' Williams said. ``NBA players are a lot
softer than they appear. These guys have been big their whole
lives, so they intimidate people by their size. They're soft deep
down. They're all teddy bears.
</P>
<P>
   ``They won't say anything in front of the public. But if you put
it to a secret vote right now, I think it would go (in the owners'
favor) because a lot of people want to get paid, a lot of people
want to start playing basketball.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams, one of the few high-profile players to speak out, also
took issue with Hunter's contention that if the owners' current
proposal were put to a vote, 85 percent of the union's 415 members
would vote it down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's a crock,'' Williams said. ``If Billy Hunter is
so determined that 85 percent would turn it down, then put it to a
vote. Right now. I'll go any which way these guys say, because if
you can't split up $2 billion, then everybody's an idiot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Put it to a secret vote. That will end it. Then no one can say
that Alonzo Mourning and Patrick Ewing (both members of the union's
negotiating committee) gave us a bad deal. Put it to a secret vote,
and we won't have that problem. We're all going to second-guess
this.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't give a damn how it goes. So put it to a secret vote.
Why not?''
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks' Herb Williams, a member of the executive committee,
took issue with Jayson Williams' stance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just hope that he would be more informed about the whole
process,'' Herb Williams said. ``I never remember him calling the
office or sitting down with anyone to talk about where the
negotiations were going.''
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia guard Allen Iverson perhaps summed up best the way
most people feel at this point.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I know is that I'm tired of this mess,'' Iverson said.
``I'm sick of it. All talk, and nothing is getting done. If David
Stern is going to cancel the season, then just cancel the season. I
want to play. But I don't understand what's going on.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
