<HEADER>
A2990 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-BLINEBURYCOLUMN-H     12-31 0806
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-BLINEBURYCOLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
FranBlinebury
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
NEW ORLEANS _ R.C. Slocum has always known this day was coming.
There were plenty of nights when he wished, prayed and hoped it
couldn't. Many happy afternoons on the football sidelines or in a
duck blind or out on a golf course when he almost had himself
convinced it wouldn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now,'' he said, ``it's time.''
</P>
<P>
   While his Aggies get ready to face Ohio State in the Sugar Bowl,
the Texas A&AMP;M coach steels himself for a much bigger test. On Jan.
13, his youngest son, John Harvey Slocum, 21, will undergo a heart
catheterization at Texas Children's Hospital in Houston in
preparation for major coronary surgery to repair a congenital
defect that was discovered at birth.
</P>
<P>
   ``What do you do? What can you say?'' asked Slocum. ``Like any
parent, I want to do anything I can. But now, all I can do is be
strong for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is precisely what R.C. has been doing for John Harvey all
these years as the family has dealt with the situation in
extraordinary privacy. Virtually no one in the A&AMP;M community and
only a very few of John Harvey's closest friends have been aware of
his condition.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always thought that it was important for John to grow up
living as normal a life as possible,'' R.C. said. ``I didn't want
everyone to treat him like he was defective. I wanted him to be
like every other kid and take part in life.''
</P>
<P>
   However, taking part in football, his father's life, was almost
always out of the question for John Harvey. When he'd take part in
games out in the yard, the other kids wanted to know why John
Harvey always had to call time out to catch his breath. And as he
grew older and his father took over in 1988 as the Aggies' head
coach, he had to deal with well-meaning questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Friends would see us together and ask him, `What position are
you going to play for your dad's team at A&AMP;M?''' recalled R.C.
``And he'd usually just say something about how he wasn't that
interested in football.
</P>
<P>
   ``It used to jerk at my heart when he was in those situations.
People didn't mean anything. How could they know that this was a
coach's son who could never play college football?''
</P>
<P>
   So Slocum got John Harvey interested in golf and took him on
hunting trips and over the past few years has grown accustomed to
his being the Aggies' biggest booster on the sidelines.
</P>
<P>
   And all the while, watching his youngest son deal with a clock
that has been ticking faster than those of the rest of us has given
Slocum perspective on his own high-pressure career and
under-the-microscope life.
</P>
<P>
   Too laconic, they said. Can't win the big battles, they
complained. Little did they know.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of my favorite sayings that I like to tell our players,''
Slocum said, ``is that it's not the bad things that happen but how
you react to them that matters.''
</P>
<P>
   So he swallowed the criticism of those nine- and 10-win seasons
and plowed ahead when the Aggies sank to 6-6 in 1996. He saw his
30-year marriage end in divorce in 1995 and dealt with the constant
knowledge that his son had a bad heart. But he stayed resolute, a
characteristic of his East Texas upbringing, the son of a refinery
worker who refused chemotherapy when diagnosed with cancer and died
in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``I grew up without a lot of material things but with a solid
Christian background,'' Slocum said. ``I was always taught that God
had a plan and even if there are times when the plan seems harsh,
you are never given more of a burden than you can carry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, I've had to sit myself down and have plenty of talks
over the years and tell myself the things I preach to my players.
You ask, `Do you really believe?' The conclusion is, yes, I do.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to have a trust somewhere. I know we'll only have
John Harvey for as long as God intends us to. I know there are
parents who lose children every day to car accidents, to leukemia,
to all sorts of things. I'll tell you, this has made me a better
father and, hopefully, a better man.''
</P>
<P>
   The years went by. The trips for checkups in Houston went from
monthly to semiannual, to annual, and eventually the mind plays
tricks and tries to tell itself the urgency has passed. But it
hasn't.
</P>
<P>
   In two weeks, John Harvey will have a tiny device inserted
through the veins in his leg up to his heart, where it will gather
information for future surgery. In April, he will have an
eight-hour operation as doctors will try to repair a hole in his
heart and make the organ pump more efficiently.
</P>
<P>
   But before that, on Friday night amid the the din of a crowded
Superdome, win or lose, the father will search along the Aggies'
sideline and exchange a glance, a look, maybe a grin with the son.
An expression of faith, a matter of heart.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-31-98 0025EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
