r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-LA-RAIDERS-LADN     12-31 0568
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-LA-RAIDERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L.A. COUNCILMAN WOOS RAIDERS, BUT FINDS LITTLE SUPPORT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Also moving in the ``a'' national and ``n'' California news
files.) 
BY RICK ORLOV  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Continuing his crusade to bring the Oakland
Raiders back to Los Angeles, City Councilman Nate Holden learned
firsthand Wednesday that not everyone likes the idea.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference in front of the Los Angeles Memorial
Coliseum, Holden tried to describe how Raiders owner Al Davis might
return the team, but a woman in a University of Southern California
T-shirt with five kids in tow kept interrupting.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want the Raiders,'' the woman proclaimed, as Holden
tried to halt television cameras from capturing her remarks. ``They
haven't won in God knows how long. We want a team that wins. A team
that will stay here.''
</P>
<P>
   The Raiders left Los Angeles after the 1994 season because
Oakland lured them away with a better deal to play there. Davis
also has claimed city officials never delivered on plans to upgrade
the Los Angeles Memorial Coliseum, where the team played.
</P>
<P>
   Holden _ wearing a black Raiders team cap _ tried to regain
control by saying he believed that Davis was prepared to return if
he wins a federal lawsuit against the National Football League in
which he is seeking to maintain territorial rights to Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked with Al Davis (Tuesday) night and again (Wednesday)
morning and he said he wants to come back to Los Angeles,'' Holden
said.
</P>
<P>
   However, the councilman indicated any deal with Davis should
include conditions to rebuild the Coliseum, similar to the plans
now being developed to try to draw a National Football League
expansion team. Under those plans, the Coliseum would seat 66,000 _
expandable to 80,000 for Super Bowls _ and hold 140 luxury boxes
and 10,000 club suites.
</P>
<P>
   ``I met with Al Davis when this was displayed in Kansas City,''
Holden said. ``He turned to me and said, It's four years too late.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we had done this in 1995, we would still have the Raiders
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Raiders spokesman Bruce Allen confirmed that Davis and Holden
had talked, but no decision has been made on returning to Los
Angeles. The Raiders are under a 16-year contract to play in
Oakland, but Davis has challenged the terms in a lawsuit separate
from the one filed in federal court.
</P>
<P>
   ``Councilman Holden has expressed great enthusiasm about the
Raiders coming back to Los Angeles based on his attorney's review
of our (federal) lawsuit against the NFL,'' Allen said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But, until that is resolved, no decisions have been made about
the team moving.''
</P>
<P>
   Holden said he believes that a decision in the court case will
be made in the near future, clearing the way for a Raiders
relocation.
</P>
<P>
   Also, he said he believes Davis would make a commitment to
remain in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me he would agree to sell a percentage of his team to
local entrepreneurs to show his commitment,'' Holden said. ``It's
not 50 percent, but 30 to 35 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   Allen said he would have no comment about that.
</P>
<P>
   Councilman Mark Ridley-Thomas, who has headed the Los Angeles
effort to land a new franchise to play in a remodeled Coliseum,
dismissed Holden's claims.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't sound like anything new,'' Ridley-Thomas said.
``It's just some headline hunting.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
