<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-31 00:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2993 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CA-POPULATION-LADN     12-31 0572
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CA-POPULATION-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CENSUS REPORT REVEALS BIGGEST ANNUAL INCREASE SINCE '92
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Will also move in the ``n'' California news file.) 
BY DOUGLAS HABERMAN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ California's population grew by 1.5 percent
between July 1, 1997, and July 1, 1998 _ the biggest increase for
the Golden State since 1992, according to a new U.S. Census Bureau
report.
</P>
<P>
   ``The luster is back on California again,'' said Jack Kyser,
chief economist for the Los Angeles Economic Development Corp.
</P>
<P>
   The rise reflects a slowdown in the number of residents moving
to nearby states, the bureau said.
</P>
<P>
   Central to California's growth and retention of people was job
creation in such key industries as entertainment, software and
international trade, and business services from advertising to
equipment rental, economists said.
</P>
<P>
   People are always lured to the state by the good weather, job
opportunities and societal openness, according to Kyser and Bruce
DeVine, chief economist for the Southern California Association of
Governments.
</P>
<P>
   ``The California lifestyle never went away _ the economy just
went into a terrible recession'' in the early '90s, DeVine said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Kyser said, the 1992 riots after the first Rodney
King trial and the 1994 Northridge Earthquake, coupled with
economic hard times, drove people out and kept others away.
</P>
<P>
   That's largely in the past now. California had the highest
numerical population increase of any state at more than 484,000
residents.
</P>
<P>
   For the 13th straight year, Nevada is the nation's
fastest-growing state, boosting its population by 4.1 percent in
1998.
</P>
<P>
   But California will take the top spot from Nevada, growing
faster than any other state between now and 2025, according to a
Census Bureau projection released last month. The state's
population is expected to rise to roughly 50 million by then.
</P>
<P>
   ``Much of the population growth in the rest of the West during
the early and middle part of the decade was due to a truly
phenomenal amount of domestic out-migration to other Western states
from California,'' said Marc Perry, a census demographer.
</P>
<P>
   ``But, with far fewer people leaving California now, this source
of population growth for other states just isn't there anymore,''
Perry said.
</P>
<P>
   From July 1997 to July 1998, even as California's population
jumped to nearly 32.7 million people, the state still suffered a
net loss of 89,711 residents to other states. But their departure
was more than made up for by the 268,685 people who moved here from
other countries, making California the state with the single
largest number of new immigrants and the highest rate of
international migration, the Census Bureau said.
</P>
<P>
   The state's number of births _ 526,785 _ was more than double
the number of deaths _ 223,066, which placed California among the
states with the largest rates of natural increase, the Census
Bureau said.
</P>
<P>
   This will create a host of problems, Kyser said. ``Where are we
going to put these people? How are they going to get to and from
work?''
</P>
<P>
   Local governments are going to have to work together to come up
with solutions, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Denser high-rise apartments may be one answer, DeVine said.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people say, How can we possibly accommodate the
population you're talking about?'' he said. ``We're pretty sure we
can do it.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-31-98 0029EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
