<DOCNO> NYT19981231.0010 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-31 00:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3000 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANTHRAX-ARREST-LADN     12-31 0815
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTHRAX-ARREST-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACCOUNTANT CHARGED IN ANTHRAX THREAT AT BANKRUPTCY COURT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Will also move in the ``n'' California news file.) 
(Daily News Staff Writers Jesse Hiestand and Sharline Chiang
contributed to this report.) 
BY DAVID R. BAKER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; A Calabasas, Calif., accountant has been charged
with phoning in a fake anthrax threat to a U.S. Bankruptcy Court in
Los Angeles on Dec. 18 in a ruse to delay a sanctions hearing
against him, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   Harvey Craig Spelkin, 53, was charged Wednesday with knowingly
threatening to transfer a biological agent under the Biological
Weapons and High Terrorism Act of 1989, federal authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   Spelkin faces a life sentence if convicted, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   FBI and Los Angeles Police Department officials said Spelkin did
not appear to be tied to any of 19 similar scares to hit Southern
California since October.
</P>
<P>
   ``This should serve as an example that we have the ability to
investigate and prosecute these cases,'' said LAPD Cmdr. Bruce E.
Hagerty.
</P>
<P>
   Spelkin was released on $50,000 bail after a 10-minute hearing
in U.S. District Court in Los Angeles. Asked to comment outside of
court, he said, ``No, thank you.''
</P>
<P>
   Spelkin walked out of the courthouse alone after agreeing to put
up his Calabasas home to cover the $50,000 bail. A preliminary
hearing date is set for Jan. 13. His arraignment was scheduled for
Jan. 19.
</P>
<P>
   ``Needless to say, you cannot make any more telephone calls of
this kind of nature,'' U.S. Magistrate Judge Rosalyn Chapman told
Spelkin, and then added he might want to ``see a counselor at some
point to see how you put yourself in this position.''
</P>
<P>
   Spelkin was scheduled to appear Dec. 18 for a hearing on
possible sanctions against him in relation to a company he had been
involved with, according to an FBI affidavit. The bankruptcy
trustee had accused Spelkin of embezzlement and perjury, but he had
avoided court appearances by allegedly fabricating illnesses,
accidents and the death of relatives, the affidavit said.
</P>
<P>
   En route to the courthouse, Spelkin called the court from a
roadside pay phone at 1:10 p.m., in an effort to avoid the hearing
in front of a judge 20 minutes later, the affidavit says.
</P>
<P>
   Spelkin admitted to investigators that during his phone call, he
said: ``You should check the air-conditioning system for possible
anthrax,'' according to the affidavit from FBI Special Agent
Stephen Moore.
</P>
<P>
   Spelkin also told investigators he dialed the same number five
minutes later and said, ``The previous call was a hoax, there is no
danger,'' Moore said in the affidavit.
</P>
<P>
   Next, Spelkin left a message on the judge's voice mail, saying
he had been in a car accident and could not make it to court, Moore
said in the affidavit.
</P>
<P>
   FBI agents began to investigate Spelkin following a tip from a
U.S. Bankruptcy Court clerk for the presiding judge in his case,
Kathleen T. Lax, Moore said in the affidavit. Spelkin came
voluntarily to FBI headquarters Wednesday, according to the
affidavit.
</P>
<P>
   He was arrested Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Court papers say that Spelkin was aware of the anthrax scare
that occurred the day before at an office building in the Westwood
area of Los Angeles that also was deemed a hoax.
</P>
<P>
   Upon receiving the threat at the court in the Los Angeles suburb
of Woodland Hills, authorities evacuated the building and
temporarily quarantined about 90 employees and visitors.
</P>
<P>
   The court stayed shut for two days while investigators searched
in vain for signs of the bacterium, which can kill if left
untreated after infection.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Spelkin's neighbors described him as reclusive.
They said Spelkin had been living in the 3500 block of Eddingham
Avenue _ in a weathered, slate blue, one-story house _ for at least
20 years. The Calabasas cul-de-sac is set against the hills
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors said he lives with his wife, a son and daughter _ both
teen-agers, and that the family keeps to itself.
</P>
<P>
   Carole LeVine, who lives across the street, said Spelkin was her
husband's partner in an accounting firm based in Sherman Oaks some
14 years ago. Since then, their families have not been in close
contact, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's extremely shocking. The (Spelkins) were very nice people,
private, but very nice,'' she said. ``I'm totally blown away.''
</P>
<P>
   In U.S. District Court on Wednesday, Spelkin, a portly
gray-haired man, wore wide-rimmed sunglasses while waiting about
two hours for his 10-minute bail hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Spelkin said he understood the charge filed against him, but
kept quiet when Chapman asked about his bankruptcy proceeding.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe you'd rather not say anything at this time,'' Chapman
said, as Spelkin whispered to his court-appointed lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's leave it at that, your honor,'' he replied. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-31-98 0044EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981231.0011 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-31 00:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3003 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STOLEN-ID-LADN     12-31 0490
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STOLEN-ID-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOS ANGELES COUNTY DA   TARGETS   IDENTITY   THEFT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Also moving in the ``n'' California news file.) 
BY PETER HARTLAUB  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ For the last two years, Mari Frank has spent more
than 500 hours and $10,000 to clear her name because a Ventura,
Calif., woman assumed her identity, stole her credit record and
racked up debt along the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``She got a red convertible Mustang in my name. ... I think
she's still driving it,'' Frank said.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said Frank was the victim of the fastest-growing
crime in America: identity theft.
</P>
<P>
   Starting on Friday, California will become only the ninth state
to prosecute identity theft as a felony. The new law is the latest
in a series of recent local and federal guidelines set up to
protect Americans from the misappropriation of a name, Social
Security number, driver's license or any other form of
identification for monetary gain.
</P>
<P>
   The Secret Service estimates that identity theft cost U.S.
citizens $750 million last year, up from $450 million in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``Identity theft is the fastest-growing crime in America, maybe
even the world,'' Los Angeles County District Attorney Gil Garcetti
said at a news conference Wednesday to explain the new law.
</P>
<P>
   Penalties will include prison sentences of up to three years and
fines up to $10,000.
</P>
<P>
   Until a year ago, there was no legal punishment in California
for identity theft. In January, it became a misdemeanor,
infrequently prosecuted by most district attorneys' offices in the
state.
</P>
<P>
   In July, a new civil law became effective, forcing credit
agencies to clear the records of identity-theft victims who can
present a police report documenting the fraud.
</P>
<P>
   Garcetti said the law will give his prosecutors the ammunition
they need to fight identity theft.
</P>
<P>
   Identity theft also became a federal felony this year,
punishable by up to 15 years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said increased use of computers, along with the ease
of getting a credit card by mail, is responsible for the rise in
identity crimes. But an identity thief doesn't need to be a master
hacker to get sensitive information.
</P>
<P>
   Frank, who suggests people shred discarded mail, said some
criminals find personal identity information in a trash bin.
</P>
<P>
   Frank said her alter ego, who was prosecuted under credit card
fraud laws and sentenced to a work furlough program, got the credit
information from a computer database that private investigators
use. Within a few months, the identity thief had obtained checks, a
driver's license and even business cards in Frank's name.
</P>
<P>
   After Frank found out about the crime, the Laguna Niguel,
Calif., lawyer spent hundreds of hours talking on the phone and
writing letters before her record was clean.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am the true, real Mari Frank and it was not very easy to
prove that,'' she said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-31-98 0048EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981231.0012 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-31 00:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3006 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANTHRAX-ARREST-1stLD-     12-31 0830
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTHRAX-ARREST-1stLD-WriteThru-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACCOUNTANT CHARGED IN ANTHRAX THREAT AT BANKRUPTCY COURT
</HEADLINE>
 
(Attention editors: Adds reporter credit in byline.) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
