<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-HUSKIES-COACH-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WASHINGTON FIRES FOOTBALL COACH JIM LAMBRIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BUD WITHERS  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   He took over his dream job on one of the most turbulent days in
the history of Washington athletics. His unexpected termination
Wednesday was equally tempestuous.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was only a few weeks ago that I was given a validation as
the coach of at least next year's football team,'' said a stunned
Husky football coach Jim Lambright.
</P>
<P>
   In a surprise move, UW athletic director Barbara Hedges fired
Lambright late Tuesday, ending his 35-year association with the
school as a player, assistant coach and head coach. He had served
six seasons at the top, taking over on a Sunday in August 1993 when
Don James resigned at the announcement of severe Pacific 10
Conference sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   Lambright, 56, was a part of 39 percent of the football games in
the school's history.
</P>
<P>
   As a buyout, he will be paid $176,000 _ representing one year's
base salary _ and $100,000 toward a $200,000 annuity that was part
of the four-year ``rollover'' contract he was given last winter.
Only one year of those four, however, was guaranteed.
</P>
<P>
   Hedges, who announced the firing at a press conference
Wednesday, had made a public defense of Lambright in November the
week before the Apple Cup. She did not offer a specific reason for
the dismissal Wednesday, saying it was a ``judgment call'' focused
on the ``future of the program.''
</P>
<P>
   Lambright, however, said with some bitterness that he had been
``warned two weeks ago there would be a meeting.'' He said some
wealthy donors undermined his regime, telling Hedges they would
withhold support for the school's capital-improvements campaign if
changes were not made at least within Lambright's staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``I listened to it,'' Lambright said, referring to the warning.
``But it meant I had to go start firing coaches and hiring somebody
else's impression of who should be on the staff and I don't do
that. That's not the way you run a program.''
</P>
<P>
   Hedges bristled at Lambright's version, saying, ``I did not
buckle under to anybody. There isn't one person I talked to who is
a major donor, an average donor, who has said to me, `I'm
withholding a donation because of this.'''
</P>
<P>
   The next-to-last day of 1998 brought a scene to the Don James
Center at Husky Stadium that was almost surreal. Lambright and
several family members, including his wife, Lynne, attended the
70-minute press conference.
</P>
<P>
   They heard Hedges speak for almost half of it, followed by
Lambright, who talked about, among other things, how much
recruiting of this year's high school seniors was going to be
damaged by the late timing of the action.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be tremendously affected, I mean tremendously
affected,'' Lambright said. ``I don't care how fast you bring
somebody in.''
</P>
<P>
   Hedges said she will hire a new coach as soon as possible, using
a small group of advisers for help.
</P>
<P>
   ``I consider it one of the best jobs in the country,'' Hedges
said. ``It's a fabulous program.''
</P>
<P>
   The assistant coaches have contracts that run until June 30.
Hedges said she wasn't sure whether any would actively try to
bridge the gap in recruiting before the hiring of a new coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``This decision affects many lives,'' Hedges said. ``For that, I
am truly sorry.''
</P>
<P>
   Lambright was Hedges' most visible hire, albeit of necessity.
Several days after he landed the job on an interim basis when James
stepped down, he was given a four-year contract.
</P>
<P>
   But Lambright and Hedges were never a great fit. Hedges has been
described as an administrator who cares deeply about image, while
Lambright often seemed to shoot from the hip, sometimes making
public comments that were ill-advised or subject to being
misconstrued.
</P>
<P>
   In November, when he suspended senior wide receiver Andre
DeSaussure for disparaging comments about Pullman the week of the
Apple Cup game, Lambright did not stop at a simple explanation for
his action. He continued to excoriate DeSaussure, saying, among
other things, ``The way he's been up and down in the program, it's
kind of symbolic.''
</P>
<P>
   Lambright was also criticized for comments after his last loss,
six days ago in the Oahu Bowl. He said he was displeased at the
fact the Husky scouts didn't give the front-line players an
adequate picture of Air Force's tactics.
</P>
<P>
   Recruiting in Washington also lapsed in Lambright's recent
years. The Huskies' best recruits often came from outside the
state, while highly sought local players such as Carlos
Pierre-Antoine (Notre Dame), Victor Rogers (Colorado) and Mac
Morrison (Penn State) went elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   The finishing loss to Air Force ended a UW streak of 21 straight
winning seasons. It left Lambright with a career head-coaching
record of 44-25-1, including 31-16-1 against Pac-10 opponents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very proud of that record,'' Lambright said. ``To go back
and do it much better than we did it, I'm not sure it could be
done.''
</P>
<P>
   Will he coach again, after 30 years on the same staff?
</P>
<P>
   ``I could see myself coaching somewhere else,'' he said. ``I'm
not sure my wife can.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
