<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-31 00:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3010 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI &LR;      12-31 1169
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UW ATHLETIC DIRECTOR SENSED FREE-FALL IN PROGRAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the Aloha Stadium press box before the Washington-Air Force
bowl game last Friday afternoon, Barbara Hedges talked cheerfully
and animatedly about the game, the team, the trip, the weather.
</P>
<P>
   She betrayed no indication that she was three days from the most
controversial, contradictory decision of her tenure as Washington's
athletic director.
</P>
<P>
   A month earlier, responding to media requests, Hedges gave an
unqualified endorsement of coach Jim Lambright's continued tenure,
saying that he also had the full support of the university
president.
</P>
<P>
   She also denied knowledge of a plan rumored to be led by
prominent Tyee Club power brokers Rick Redman and Ron Crockett to
buy out the balance of Lambright's contract, about $276,000, which
had been extended only last year.
</P>
<P>
   But by Tuesday, she fired Lambright and his staff, the most
publicly unanticipated axing in the modern history of Washington
football.
</P>
<P>
   Not that it was hard for Hedges, or anyone, to build a case
against Lambright.
</P>
<P>
   Not after the Huskies' lame performance in the Oahu Bowl, not
after the first non-winning season in 22 years, not after losing
Northwest supremacy to Oregon, not after repeated embarrassments on
big-time TV games, not after the numerous player-management
blunders that pickled his tenure.
</P>
<P>
   But almost no school fires a coach after a bowl game, in the
middle of recruiting season. Almost no school fires a coach with a
44-25-1 record. Almost no school fires a coach a year after a
contract extension unless there are major NCAA violations or a
breach of personal conduct, none of which are said to be pending.
Almost no school fires a coach for fractured syntax and incomplete
sentences, although the English Department had Lambright on
probation.
</P>
<P>
   And almost no school fires abruptly, without a shape-up warning,
a 30-year employee and alum who bailed out the program in its most
turbulent time.
</P>
<P>
   Unless, of course, the program is about to fall apart.
</P>
<P>
   That's what Hedges concluded. Not only were some powerful alums
threatening to withdraw financial support in the middle of Hedges'
pet project, a $70 million upgrade of athletic facilities, the
increasing loss of quality recruits, locally and regionally,
threatened to keep Husky football second-rate in the Pac-10 _ which
would make Hedges the next one out the door.
</P>
<P>
   Conversations on Wednesday with a number of former players close
to the program suggested that the loss of respect by some current
players for Lambright had reached a point where they could no
longer advocate for Washington with prospective recruits.
</P>
<P>
   Said one former player: ``Some of these guys have said that they
just don't like playing football for Washington.'' Said another:
``A lot of them still like Lambright, they just don't like what he
does.''
</P>
<P>
   A part of what isn't liked is also a part that drove program
backers crazy this year: Hiding behind sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the obvious tiredness of the excuse, it didn't play well
for two reasons: Lambright and several members of the staff had a
hand in the NCAA violations that created the Pac-10 penalties in
1992, and it was an indirect insult to the starting players.
</P>
<P>
   The scholarship reductions that limited this year's senior and
junior classes were hurtful, but not to the degree implied by the
coaches. And its deployment says to the starters, ``You wouldn't be
playing much except we were screwed by the Pac-10.''
</P>
<P>
   If Hedges needed a final straw, Lambright supplied it after the
embarrassing whipping by Air Force when he laid off the UW's
terrible defense to an ineffectual effort by the scout team in
duplicating the little-seen option offense. The scout team was
weak, Lambright said, because players who normally fill the jobs
are playing big roles in the sanction-devastated roster.
</P>
<P>
   Identifying the scout team as culprit in a bowl defeat might
have been a first in Division I-A coaching history. Turned out to
be the last refuge of a man desperate to avoid responsibility for
one of the worst losses of his tenure.
</P>
<P>
   So it could be said that the sanctions claimed another victim, a
second Washington head coach. But unlike Don James, who quit in
protest, Lambright protested too much, to the detriment of his
credibility.
</P>
<P>
   The sanctions soap opera was the kind of excuse-making and odd
behavior that burned up his coaching capital, leaving him no
protection for the inevitable down cycle in every D-1 program.
</P>
<P>
   Lambright had a peculiar self-absorption in which he took high
offense at those within and around the program who would disagree
or disparage. Along with his clumsy public treatment of departing
players such as Shane Fortney and Nick Lentz, he filtered much of
the experience through himself. According to a former player,
Lambright addressed the team before the ill-fated game at Nebraska
this way: ``Don't screw with me this week _ this is the biggest
week of my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Not exactly waking the echoes of Lombardi or Rockne.
</P>
<P>
   Lambright said Wednesday he ``bleeds purple and gold,'' but he
never seemed to understand that he often must make do with those
who don't, or at least don't see things exactly his way.
</P>
<P>
   Lambright tossed around the word loyalty Wednesday. He said he
thought his ``30 years deserved better,'' and he might be right.
But what he never understood was that while loyalty might be a
small reason to hire a coach _ it was part of what got him the job
when James quit _ it is no reason to keep a coach.
</P>
<P>
   Forget the imagery wrapped in raccoon coats and phrases like
``student-athlete.'' College football is as cutthroat a business as
any other big-time sports entertainment. Being loyal, being a
long-timer, being a local, it doesn't matter. This being America,
production matters.
</P>
<P>
   Ask Dennis Erickson. Ask all the fired executives at Boeing.
</P>
<P>
   Lambright said his only regret was that he ``might have been
more political.'' The words held as much disdain as if they had
been spoken by ex-Sonic coach George Karl, another guy contemptuous
of the game beyond the game.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for otherwise wonderful characters like Lambright
and Karl, modern sports are played on two levels. Besides what
happens on the field or arena, the game is also about alumni,
owners, media, corporations, rich fans and gamblers _ all far more
heavily invested in sports outcomes than when Lambright, Erickson,
Karl and their contemporaries first learned to love their games.
</P>
<P>
   Lambright was good for the way things were, not for the way
things will be. Unfortunately for her, Hedges came late to the
realization, moved abruptly, and now is operating out of
desperation to salvage the future of the UW's mammoth athletic
department machinery.
</P>
<P>
   She can only hope she plays the game better than Lambright did.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
