u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI     12-31 1081
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEATTLE FOOTBALL COACHES SHORT ON SAVVY BUT LOYAL TO THE END 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   First it was the Seahawks. Now it is the Huskies. The firings of
the head coaches of Seattle's two big football teams this week
leave us with little choice except to draw one parallel conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Erickson and Jim Lambright, who share Everett roots and a
life-long allegiance to football and the Pacific Northwest, have
been identified as inappropriate leaders for jobs both considered
their ultimate opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   In both cases, the fairy tale story had a rotten ending.
</P>
<P>
   These are local guys who made good, but their back-to-back
dismissals are an indication that both home-grown coaches lacked a
requisite level of flexibility, political savvy and public
relations smoothness.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, Lambright made reference Wednesday to how much
longer he has been at Washington than athletic director Barbara
Hedges, as if that negates her overall duty to act in the best
interest of the university.
</P>
<P>
   It was Lambright's job to convince Hedges, as well as the rabid
Washington alumni and fan base, that he could make the transition
from stalwart Husky assistant to Division I program leader, both
with his on-field accomplishments and administrative
responsibilities.
</P>
<P>
   It was Erickson's job to show he had the know-how to move from
college to the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   Neither man had been terribly convincing.
</P>
<P>
   That is why Erickson was turned loose Monday from a fast-tracked
NFL franchise that is hellbent on winning the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   That is why Lambright was abruptly fired late Tuesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Is it too coincidental that in their own hometowns, neither
Erickson nor Lambright was entrenched, beloved, connected or
convincing enough to sway all doubt about their abilities to lead
these high-profile teams?
</P>
<P>
   Probably not. Erickson, 51, and Lambright, 56, appear to share
similar old-school tendencies _ traits to be commended, unless
those traits get in the way of making swift changes when change is
needed.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, both Lambright and Erickson prize loyalty in their
assistants over urges to replace personnel, even when it seems
clear an upgrade is needed.
</P>
<P>
   Did Erickson know when it was time to make a change of special
teams' coach in '97?
</P>
<P>
   Did Lambright stubbornly refuse to take suggestion about the
need to make changes, even when the word was coming from his
friends inside university circles?
</P>
<P>
   Both Lambright and Erickson were adament in their departure
speeches this week. If loyalty is a negative, then sorry. Loyalty
is the key element in building their staffs.
</P>
<P>
   If Lambright chose to open himself up to dismissal rather than
lop off some heads to satisfy outside forces, he clearly was loyal
to the point of doing himself a disservice.
</P>
<P>
   He may be the head coach, but whose program, ultimately, is it?
Wednesday he found out and he was mightily ticked off.
</P>
<P>
   . ``I was tremendously surprised and shocked by my meeting with
Barbara since it was only a few weeks ago that I was given
validation as head coach at least for next year's football team,''
Lambright said.
</P>
<P>
   And when he was lobbed a softball question about whether,
looking back over his six years as head coach at Washington he
would do anything differently, he was as straight-forward and
politically unwary as ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think if I had to do anything over again, the only thing I
would second guess is that I wasn't more political,'' Lambright
said.
</P>
<P>
   This is the same fellow who popped off that Washington and not
Oregon would be a better candidate for the Cotton Bowl, even after
the Ducks had whupped the Huskies that season.
</P>
<P>
   Much is going to be made of the abrupt nature of Lambright's
firing, including whatever kind of pressure anti-Lambright boosters
were able to put on Hedges.
</P>
<P>
   The credibility of Hedges' reign at Washington hinges on her
authority and autonomy. That is why there will be unending intrigue
surrounding her seemingly sudden decision to fire Lambright, just
six weeks after giving him a vote of confidence and with so little
time to preserve the incoming recruiting class.
</P>
<P>
   Lambright was clear on his take: This was a dirty deal.
</P>
<P>
   But was it, really? The real issue is that, short of firing
Lambright directly after the Nov. 21 Apple Cup game, no time would
be a good time to fire him.
</P>
<P>
   Any time you make a coaching change, you throw your program into
turmoil.
</P>
<P>
   And until he won against Michigan State in last year's Aloha
Bowl, Lambright's job was on the line last December.
</P>
<P>
   The point is, Hedges seems completely certain that the benefit
of making the coaching change now outweighs the risk.
</P>
<P>
   One year vs. the future of a program that is worth $24 million a
year.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe this last season was Lambright's test. Maybe he just plain
did not pass it. It is possible, considering the way kicker Nick
Lentz left the school so unhappy; the way Lambright handled Andre
DeSaussure's outspoken comments about Washington State.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Lambright did not take any opportunity to raise the level
of his game to the satisfaction of Hedges, who was already
questioning his long-term future and who may have been aware that
the team was not responding to Lambright in a manner that appealed
to her.
</P>
<P>
   Hedges said her goal was to attract a new head coach who would
``manage the program in an exceptional manner.''
</P>
<P>
   Lambright may reject the politics for which a head coach at
Washington is judged. But when he decided to do this, he missed the
point of head coaching at a nationally acclaimed program like
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   It's not just all about winning. You can't insulate yourself in
the weight room and film room. You can't expect public relations
nightmares with some of your players _ including one with Rashaan
Shehee in which Lambright actually asked Shehee to lie as part of a
cover-up _ to go unnoticed forever.
</P>
<P>
   Two football teams in Seattle have decided to go in different
directions this week, meaning these are tough times for the Everett
guys who got their chance.
</P>
<P>
   But considering the premium being placed on raising the bar,
both at the Seahawks and at Washington, these are also good times
for an NFL franchise and a big-time Division I program that claim
to want nothing but the best.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, you can't complain about that.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-31-98 0056EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
