<SLUG> BC-NEWYEAR-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLIDAY INTERLUDE ISN'T SLOW FOR SOME WORKERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MAUREEN WEST  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The week between Christmas and New Year's is, for many workers,
the longest unofficial holiday.
</P>
<P>
   Not that everyone stays home, mind you. It's just that work
slows down and turns into extended lunches and staff parties: late
to work, early to leave _ long mysterious disappearances with such
hazy, later explanations as, ``Hi.''
</P>
<P>
   But while some have been savoring the season, there are some
jobs that only get tougher during the holidays. Firefighters are
scrambling from house fire to house fire as Christmas trees dry out
and explode under coils of hot wiring. Psychologists stack
unmarried parents like cord wood on their couches.
</P>
<P>
   Caterers, police, liquor store clerks, grocers, letter carriers,
exchange desk personnel are all a scurry.
</P>
<P>
   The pet-sitting industry, not normally one of the backbones of
Arizona's economy, rises to the rank of an economic powerhouse
during the holidays.
</P>
<P>
   In north Scottsdale, retirees Jim and Barbara Bristol are house
guests of the Kerner family's three Pyrenees dogs and four cats.
The Bristols are among the 100 pet-sitters employed by Pampered
Pets &AMP; Plants, all of whom are busy on jobs this week.
</P>
<P>
   Some pet-sitters just stop by homes to check on a pet while
owners are visiting relatives or hitting the slopes. Others, like
the Bristols, move into the pets' home to keep them company while
the family is away.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are crazy about their pets and they want the holiday to
be happy for them, too,'' said Jann Kemp, owner of the
animal-sitting business. The holidays are her high season, followed
by August, when only dogs and dog sitters remain in the city.
</P>
<P>
   Social dating services are also at full tilt during the
holidays.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll get 300 calls today and tomorrow _ more than any other
two days of the year,'' said Lynda Johncock, owner of Arizona's
Most Eligible Singles, a dating service she said caters mostly to
business owners, doctors and lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They will say, `I don't want to spend the holidays alone next
year, or with the person I was with this year.' '' The rush to
recouple continues in January, her biggest month.
</P>
<P>
   ``New Year's resolutions go something like this: start a diet,
save money and begin a relationship,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``New Year's Eve is very romantic.''
</P>
<P>
   The tax code is also very romantic, and nurses at some Valley
hospitals report that women close to delivering new deductions ask
for labor to be induced. And, after a stellar economic year, some
Valley hospital nurseries are overflowing with a record crop of
babies.
</P>
<P>
   Emergency rooms are also at high season, as everyone's regular
doctors are off, testing the greens in Scottsdale or skiing in
Colorado. Many doctors' offices don't keep regular hours during the
holidays.
</P>
<P>
   Another reason that emergency rooms are buzzing like cocktail
parties is that too much time at home means too many opportunities
to fall off ladders or jog on bad knees or see whether skating is a
skill you never forget.
</P>
<P>
   A powerful strain of flu is also sending many sneezing, dripping
people to emergency rooms. Good Samaritan Regional Medical Center's
emergency room, which normally serves 130 to 150 people a day,
handled 215 one day this week. Other Valley hospitals report
similar popularity. Snowbirds add to the numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Death, alas, does not take the holiday either. While some
people do try to hang on through the holidays, it's not always
possible.
</P>
<P>
   Nick Lutz, area manager for Service Corporation International,
which manages funeral homes in the Valley, says the two holiday
weeks have been busier than usual.
</P>
<P>
   They're not the only people trying to make a body look good.
</P>
<P>
   Hair salons are abuzz as New Year's Eve parties loom directly
ahead. Debbie Angulo, one of the owners of Changes hair salon in
Scottsdale, will be on her feet all day creating up-dos and
party-dos.
</P>
<P>
   Rhinestone bugs, she says _ butterflies, ladybugs, dragonflies
and spiders _ are the rage. Women want them woven into their hair
creations this year. It's style, she says. Angulo says the bugs
``do grow on you.''
</P>
<P>
   The Valley's five-star resorts also are filling up with thawing
customers from northern climes. Debi Bridges, director of public
relations for the Arizona Biltmore, says the joint is jumping. She
says it more elegantly, but the joint is jumping.
</P>
<P>
   As if they weren't busy enough, airline counters are also
dealing with people with frequent flier miles that fly away at the
stroke of midnight tonight.
</P>
<P>
   And the crazy stock market will close early today, as it did
Christmas Eve. It has been a frenzied week for many financial
planners as people are busy converting traditional IRAs to Roth
IRAs.
</P>
<P>
   Overseeing this hum of economic prosperity, Arizona's governor,
high from the 9th floor over the Copper Dome, contemplates the
needs of her people in the New Year as a new legislative season
arrives.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, she's out for the day.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-31-98 0106EST &QL; 
