<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-31 01:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3024 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-HOLIDAY_ARIZONA-N     12-31 0817
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-HOLIDAY_ARIZONA-NEBR-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILDCATS' HOLIDAY MAKES FOR BEST SEA SON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By NORM FRAUENHEIM  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ It was the end of a beginning.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona's beginning.
</P>
<P>
   The first, tangible piece in an emerging Arizona football
tradition wasput into place Wednesday night by a thoroughly gritty
and often crazy 23-20 Wildcats' victory over Nebraska in the
Holiday Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, it was a vintage Arizona performance in a wild,
improbable season. The Wildcats were up, down, on their heels,
reeling and yet never out.
</P>
<P>
   Ever resourceful, the Wildcats fooled the Cornhuskers, the
Qualcomm Stadium crowd of 65,354, expectations and momentum for the
last time in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Their victory over a leading member of college football's royal
family will have immediate impact.
</P>
<P>
   ``Arizona is a complete football team in all areas _ offense,
defense and especially special teams,'' said Nebraska coach Frank
Solich, who could havebeen casting a vote for Arizona's 1999
prospects.
</P>
<P>
   The Wildcats are sure to finish 1998 with a ranking among the
nation'stop five. With the loss Tuesday night of fourth-ranked
Kansas State, No. 4 lookslike a lock. And then, of course, there's
next year . The season-ending victory over Nebraska promises to put
the Wildcats in the hunt for the national championship.
</P>
<P>
   But there will be more about all of that later. A lot more.
</P>
<P>
   On this one night, the Wildcats proved that, yes, they were
unknown in September, underrated in October and unbelievable in
December.
</P>
<P>
   One number says plenty and says it 12 times. Once-beaten Arizona
finished with 12 victories for the first time in a history that
dates to 1899.
</P>
<P>
   But, for a while, it looked as if the Cornhuskers (9-4) would
finish a Cinderella season and leave Arizona again searching for a
way to be more than just another unknown program. For oh-so-long,
the A on the side of Wildcat helmets has stood for Anonymous.
</P>
<P>
   More anonymity seemed to be on the horizon when a difficult game
started with a lot of blown opportunities, all Arizona's. The
Wildcats were within Nebraska's 10 yard line three times in the
first half. They had two touchdowns _ a Keith Smith pass to Brad
Brennan and a 78-yard punt return by Chris McAlister _ nullified by
penalities.
</P>
<P>
   The No. 5 Wildcats could have had at least 28 points on its side
of thescoreboard at halftime. Instead, it had only nine, thanks to
three field goals by Mark McDonald.
</P>
<P>
   All the while, No. 14 Nebraska seemed to be exercising its
superior power on both offense and defense. There were a couple of
Kris Brown field goalsand a 35-yard TD pass from Eric Crouch to
Shevin Wiggins.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona should have been leading. But, there was Nebraska, ahead
at halftime, 13-9. For Arizona, there was a further complication.
</P>
<P>
   Reliable receiver Jeremy McDaniel was sidelined with a hip
pointer suffered in the first quarter. The Wildcats' dynamic
passing game had lost a keycomponent.
</P>
<P>
   What to do?
</P>
<P>
   ``To come back against Nebraska was huge,'' Arizona coach Dick
Tomey said. ``I told them at halftime that we hadn't been down at
halftime all season.I told them to keep their poise.''
</P>
<P>
   Old habits never die. Tomey was certain of the poise. His team's
inexhaustble pluck provided the rest. All season, the Wildcats
thrived on the improbable, if not the seemingly impossible.
</P>
<P>
   The first confrontation came late in the third quarter. The
Wildcats drove from their own 34 to Nebraska's 21 yard line. It was
fourth down and one yard to a drive-sustaining first. Time for a
field goal? Forget it. Instead, Kelvin Eafon got the call and ran
two yards on a sprained ankle for a critical first down.
</P>
<P>
   Three plays later early in the fourth quarter, Smith hit Brennan
with a15-yard TD strike that, this time, counted.
</P>
<P>
   But the game wasn't finished. With the unpredictable Wildcats,
it neveris. On the subsequent possession, Nebraska, held to 87
rushing yards, drove 68 yards with the capper a beautiful Tracey
Wistrom reception of a 4-yard Crouch pass.
</P>
<P>
   By then, however, Arizona knew its offense could move on the
feared Nebraska defenders. So it did. Smith, the gam'ss offensive
Most Valuable Player,was the key in a drive that started on the
Arizona 32. Three times, he ran quarterback keepers for 20, eight
and seven yards. At the end, there was Eafon once again with a
one-yard dive for the game's final score.
</P>
<P>
   But the game itself still wasn't over.
</P>
<P>
   Nebraska threatened once again. This time, however, McAlister
intervened for a play that summed an Arizona defense that adjusted
and utlimately stopped Nebraska's option attack.
</P>
<P>
   He jumped high in front of Wiggins for an interception of a
Crouch pass at the Arizona six. He returned it 24 yards to the 30.
</P>
<P>
   McAlister put an exclamation point on the end.
</P>
<P>
   Only the beginning is left.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
