<HEADER>
A3026 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-CASSTEVE-NS-COLUM     12-31 0659
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-CASSTEVE-NS-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VOL'S CREDENTIALS STUFF OF LEGENDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID CASSTEVENS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   According to the University of Tennessee media guide, running
back Travis Henry ran for 4,087 yards and scored 42 touchdowns in
his senior year in high school.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, sure he did.
</P>
<P>
   ``He ``did'','' said Bud Ford, Tennessee's sports information
director.
</P>
<P>
   No, he didn't. He ``couldn't'' have.
</P>
<P>
   For Henry to rush for more than 4,000 yards in 14 games, he
would have had to average 292 yards a game. High schools play
12-minute quarters.
</P>
<P>
   That's 6 yards a minute!
</P>
<P>
   Al, you don't believe it, do you?
</P>
<P>
   Al Wilson, the All-America Vols linebacker and Henry's teammate,
broke into a big I-know-it-sounds-crazy grin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, I believe it,'' Wilson said. ``Travis is ``real'' strong.
His legs are like tree trunks.''
</P>
<P>
   Legs like tree trunks.
</P>
<P>
   I see.
</P>
<P>
   Sorry. It didn't happen. But another Tennessee linebacker,
Raynoch Thompson, insists it did. ``Travis showed me the tape.''
</P>
<P>
   Was there an intermission?
</P>
<P>
   ``Four thousand eighty-seven yards'' and 42 touchdowns in one
season. Please.
</P>
<P>
   Sports stories are like fine wine. They get better over time.
Heroics are embellished. As legends grow, so do their
accomplishments. Joe Garagiola said Stan Musial ``could hit .300
with a fountain pen.'' Josh Gibson claimed Cool Papa Bell was so
fast he could get out of bed, turn out the lights and be back under
the covers before the lights went out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never exaggerate,'' golfer Chi Chi Rodriguez says. ``I just
remember big.''
</P>
<P>
   Sports stories about superhuman feats are best taken with a
grain of salt, unless you're on a low sodium diet.
</P>
<P>
   Travis Henry's 4,000-yard season sounds as if it falls somewhere
between a tall tale and a whopper. The feat simply cannot be
believed without eyewitness testimony.
</P>
<P>
   So I called Henry's hometown newspaper, the ``Frostproof News.''
The ``News'' is published weekly in Frostproof, Fla., which sounds
like an ideal place to live, especially if you're a grapefruit.
</P>
<P>
   No one answered.
</P>
<P>
   Four thousand yards. Get serious.
</P>
<P>
   According to the media guide, 5-foot-11, 215-pound Travis Deion
Henry, who will start for the Vols in Monday night's Fiesta Bowl,
led Frostproof to the state championship and set seven state
rushing records.
</P>
<P>
   Only seven?
</P>
<P>
   In one game he ran for _ ready for this? _ 436 yards.
</P>
<P>
   A ``Parade'' All-American, Henry rushed for 7,224 yards during
his high school career and scored 79 touchdowns. He also played
basketball and ran track.
</P>
<P>
   I called Frostproof High School.
</P>
<P>
   A secretary put me through to the field house and the office of
football Coach Richie Marsh.
</P>
<P>
   A student answered and gave me Coach Marsh's home phone.
</P>
<P>
   No answer there, either.
</P>
<P>
   I called the field house again and spoke to the helpful student
who identified himself as Grover Benton.
</P>
<P>
   Grover, do you know Travis Henry?
</P>
<P>
   ``He's my second cousin,'' Grover said. ``We played on the same
team his senior year.''
</P>
<P>
   Now we're getting somewhere.
</P>
<P>
   So, Grover. Travis didn't really run for 4,087 yards in one
year, did he?
</P>
<P>
   ``He sure did,'' Grover said, and you could hear the smile in
his voice. He began ticking off the names of the schools that his
cousin had run roughshod over that year. He sounded like a train
conductor calling out the whistle stops along the track. Pahokee .
. . Lake Butler . . . Avon Park . . . Sebring . . .
</P>
<P>
   So it's all true?
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure is,'' Grover said. ``I remember one game a guy had Travis
by the jersey and another defender was right in front of him.''
</P>
<P>
   What happened?
</P>
<P>
   ``He tore loose from the first guy and flattened the second guy
with his forearm. Best run I ever saw.''
</P>
<P>
   How long?
</P>
<P>
   ``About 70 yards.'' Grover laughed. ``Travis had plenty of
them.'' &QL; 
David Casstevens can be reached at david.casstevens(at)pni.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-31-98 0123EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
