<DOCNO> NYT19981231.0022 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-31 01:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3027 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-PHOENIXOPEN-BEERB     12-31 0757
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-PHOENIX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPEN HALTS SALE OF BEER AT 16TH 
</HEADLINE>
 OPEN-BEER BAN-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL HUFFMAN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In an effort to take some of the hearty out of party, organizers
of the Phoenix Open have decided to ban beer sales at the wild and
crazy 16th hole.
</P>
<P>
   The sponsoring Phoenix Thunderbirds also are attempting to set
up a ``no-fly zone'' over the tournament, which tees off Jan. 25-31
at the TPC of Scottsdale.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really not that big of deal,'' tournament chairman Ray
Artigue said Wednesday. ``The Thunderbirds enjoy a party as much as
the next guy, but we also have to be sensitive to all of our
constituents. This is about moderation, not prohibition.''
</P>
<P>
   Artigue added that cigar sales also will be banned throughout
the course to make the tournament more pleasurable for the majority
of fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that doesn't stop people from buying beer elsewhere and
bringing it to the (16th hole), or from people buying cigars off
the course and bringing them to the tournament,'' he said. ``There
still is a good time to be had by all, but we don't want it ruined
by people who are inebriated.''
</P>
<P>
   Artigue said the change was urged by the PGA Tour. According to
Tour spokesman Dave Lancer, the decision is tourwide rather than
just focused on the Phoenix Open.
</P>
<P>
   ``We encouraged Phoenix along with all of our other tournaments
to curb sales of liquor,'' Lancer said. ``It just makes sense when
you're trying to maintain optimum playing conditions.''
</P>
<P>
   The PGA Tour has received several complaints from marquee
players in the past about the near-maniac behavior at the 16th
hole.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Couples, who has yet to commit to this year's event, has
not played in Phoenix since 1990 and often describes the 16th as
``totally out of control.'' Tom Watson has suggested a beer ban on
several occasions.
</P>
<P>
   But most of the locals, such as Phil Mickelson, Billy Mayfair,
Andrew Magee, Tom Lehman and Mark Calcavecchia, have said they
understand the party-hearty flavor of the Phoenix tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have?'' Calcavecchia asked, somewhat in disbelief, after
being informed of the Thunderbirds' decision. ``Well, I guess you
can never say it's a bad thing, cutting people off. At the same
time, I always thought it was a great time. People get partied up
and really enjoy themselves at the 16th. I guess a few of (the
players) don't like it, but it's certainly not a disturbance to me.
I want them to keep screaming (`Get in the hole!').''
</P>
<P>
   Calcavecchia cited the ``shot heard round the world'' in 1997,
when Tiger Woods made a hole in one at the 165-yard par 3, sending
the crowd into a state of hysteria, beer cups flying everywhere
like a large flock of startled birds.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a pretty cool thing,'' he said. ``You kind of hate to
see the possibility of that being taken away.''
</P>
<P>
   Vince Gill also made a hole in one at the 16th in 1993, but not
to quite the same histrionics. Gill's ace came in the
pre-tournament Silver Pro-Am and won a Valley woman a new house in
Salt River Project's ``Home-In-One'' promotion.
</P>
<P>
   But Artigue argued that the Phoenix Open really had no choice,
as the atmosphere has gotten more raucous each year. He cited the
decision last year by tournament chairman Tim Grant, who cut off
beer sales at the 16th in the early afternoon of the final two
rounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's mostly the college element,'' he said. ``That's what
we're trying to tone down. In the past, we've had a few arrests
(for disorderly conduct and intoxication), but it really hasn't
been an enforcement problem as much as just a nuisance to some of
the players and fans who are focusing more on the tournament than
having a good time.''
</P>
<P>
   Artigue added that the decision to try to stop air traffic over
the course during the tournament is not yet a done deal. In the
past, various news helicopters, hot-air ballons and airplanes
toting advertising banners have crowded the sky, adding to the
circuslike atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're working with the (Federal Aviation Administration) to
try and create a `no-fly zone,' '' he said. ``I guess it sounds
like the Iraqi situation, but it is a distraction when someone is
trying to putt out and there's a helicopter hovering overhead or a
hot-air ballon gets a blast of gas.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though some of those blasts from the past apparently are on
their way out, Calcavecchia said he doubts it will have a major
effect on the tour's most well-attended event, which last year
attracted nearly 500,000 fans. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
