<HEADLINE>
ASU CRUSHES SAN JOSE ST., LEARNS COMBS HAS FRACTURES 
</HEADLINE>
 STATE-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 ASU 83, SAN JOSE STATE 46 
 By JEFF METCALFE  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nothing that happened after tip-off Wednesday night at Wells
Fargo Arena came close to the importance of the hours before
Arizona State beat San Jose State in women's basketball.
</P>
<P>
   With arguably its best player, Theresa Jantzen, yet to play
because of a fractured left foot, ASU learned that its other prize
freshman post player, Leah Combs, is out with stress fractures in
both legs.
</P>
<P>
   Combs, who has been playing through pain in her left shin since
the beginning of the season, will undergo a magnetic resonance
imaging today and remains hopeful of being able to play in the
Pac-10 opener against Southern California (4-5) on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all in God's hands,'' said Combs, who was more calm than
she expected upon getting the results of a bone scan five hours
before tip-off after hearing a talk by Oklahoma Congressman J.C.
Watts at the Fiesta Bowl Fellowship of Christian Athletes
Breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've become sort of immune to the feeling. It's something I
could push through,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But pain increased during the Christmas break, resulting first
in an X-ray that was negative then the bone scan and now the MRI.
</P>
<P>
   Even the return of senior forward Kisha White, who started 20
games last season, Saturday does little to soften the stunning news
about the 6-foot-2 Combs.
</P>
<P>
   Beating San Jose (2-10), the 11th lowest rated team in Division
I according to the Rating Percentage Index, without Combs is no
great shakes. The Devils (6-3) ran off 16 of the first 20 points
and avenged the worst loss (62-57 in 1996) of the three-year Coach
Charli Turner Thorne era, 83-46.
</P>
<P>
   Winning in the Pac-10 without Combs, who already has four
double-doubles, is the conference's fourth-leading rebounder (9.5
average) and averages 10 points, is an entirely different matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just have to be patient,'' said Turner Thorne, who is eight
months' pregnant and who kidded about the Combs news causing a
contraction or two. ``Obviously, we wanted to be fully healthy for
the Pac-10. If we have two of three (Combs, Jantzen, White), I'll
be happy.''
</P>
<P>
   The latest Jantzen X-ray shows her foot to have healed, although
she still is experiencing pain. The 6-3 forward could dress for the
USC game although still is doubtful to play.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot White, who averaged 8.5 points and 4.4 rebounds last
season, missed the first semester plus three games due to academic
ineligibility and a suspension for exceeding earned income by a
scholarship athlete. She is in better shape and should help in
rebounding, which Turner Thorne cites as an area in need of
improvement.
</P>
<P>
   ASU got better guard play than in last game, a 78-61 loss to UC
Santa Barbara on Dec. 21. The Devils also had help off the bench
from Georgie Lang, who tied her career high with 11 points, all in
the first half, Ebony Edwards and Aubrey McFadyen.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-3 start equals ASU's best since 1994-95. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SAN JOSE STATE _ Barrett 0-4 0-0 0, Dailey 5-11 1-4 11, McGee
3-5 1-4 7, Johnson 2-7 1-1 5, Gluhan 4-13 1-3 9, Modin 0-4 0-0 0,
