<HEADLINE>
SMITH REMAINS FURIOUS OVER DRAKE PUNISHMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Coyotes General Manager Bobby Smith is still livid over the way
Monday's game with the Los Angeles Kings ended, specifically how
Dallas Drake was mugged after his boarding major on Doug Bodger.
</P>
<P>
   Drake was immediately confronted physically by at least three
Kings players, including Ray Ferraro, Luc Robitaille and Sean
O'Donnell. Drake, who was suspended by the league Tuesday for four
games, got it the worst from O'Donnell, who wasn't penalized.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said referee Mick McGeough failed to control the
situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the ref's not going to deliver justice out there, then
those kind of things are going to happen,'' Smith said. ``What
O'Donnell was allowed to do was a joke. He circled the pack waiting
to get his shots in on Drake, and then he scratched up his eye on
top of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the refs aren't going to control this sort of thing, then
we're going to have to change the complexion of our team and deal
with it ourselves. Look, we've got guys in our organization . . .
We can deliver that kind of justice on the ice ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes will play the Kings two more times at home, on Feb.
10 and March 21. &QL;  &QL; 
Wayne's words &QL;  &QL; 
New York Rangers center Wayne Gretzky, who may have played his last
game in the Valley on Wednesday, has taken notice of the Coyotes'
hot start.
</P>
<P>
   ``First and foremost, you've got to have leadership and they've
got that with (Jeremy) Roenick, (Rick) Tocchet and (Keith) Tkachuk,
who are all solid,'' Gretzky said. ``Then you've got to have a
system, and obviously, the system they've implemented, everybody
seems to be following. I don't think you can play in this league if
you don't have mobile defensemen, and they've got that. Jyrki Lumme
was a good pickup for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``But on top of all that, you can't win in this league without
good goaltending, and they're getting great goaltending each and
every night.'' &QL;  &QL; 
Slap shots &QL;  &QL; 
Coyotes goalie Jimmy Waite remembers his first game against
Gretzky. It was during his rookie season, when he played for the
Chicago Blackhawks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was 19, and I actually stopped him on a breakaway,'' Waite
said. ``It wasn't the best move of his career, though. The puck
kind of bounced on him, and I was able to poke it away. But hey,
I'll never forget that play.''
</P>
<P>
   You'll never guess which NHL team Gretzky has scored the most
points against during his career. That's right, the
Coyotes/Winnipeg Jets. After Wednesday's game, he has 79 goals, 151
assists and 230 points against the franchise in 105 career games. &QL;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
