<SLUG> BC-OUT-ARIZONA_PRESERVE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESERVE A KEEPER  
 HUNTING, SCENERY WORTH TRIP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BARRY BURKHART  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRESCOTT _ It is one of the most beautiful ranches you'll ever
see _ this bit of paradise in the Williamson Valley 20 miles
northwest of Prescott.
</P>
<P>
   At 4,700 feet in elevation, this huge expanse of rolling hills
and upper desert grasslands is surrounded in the distance by
plateaus and lower elevation mountains.
</P>
<P>
   This is Long Meadow Ranch, which became a working cattle ranch
in 1872. Jim Puntenney, a retired dentist, now runs the ranch. His
grandfather purchased it in 1960. His father then ran it until Jim
Puntenney took over. He is part owner.
</P>
<P>
   By Arizona standards, these are big-time private holdings. In
most of the state, settlers laid claim to small acreages around
water sources, then leased federal land around them.
</P>
<P>
   This ranch has 4,800 acres of deeded land plus 640 sections of
grazing rights on Prescott National Forest. The private holdings
have been reduced from 7,000 acres when part of the ranch was
subdivided into 40-acre parcels for those who wanted to build homes
in this beautiful area.
</P>
<P>
   The ranch has another blessing _ water. The water table is high
on parts of the ranch, creating small ponds at water level. In
other words, no dams are needed to collect water.
</P>
<P>
   ``On some areas, you can sink a (fence) post hole, and the next
day it will be full of water,'' Puntenney said. The ground water
supply is so good that Puntenney harvests 10,000 bales of hay a
year. That's enough for him to sustain his considerable cattle
operation plus sell off high-quality hay.
</P>
<P>
   In 1918, a kit house, produced in sections, was sent to Prescott
and brought to the ranch. It still stands. It recently was painted
bright yellow and has tongue-and-groove oak floors with fantastic
grains and woodwork.
</P>
<P>
   There are other buildings on the ranch, of course, including
Puntenney's parents' place, which they no longer occupy, and a
couple of other places for guests.
</P>
<P>
   But there's another business here.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you are a cattle rancher, you're always always looking
for something else that will make some money,'' Puntenney said. ``I
started this hobby that grew into a business.''
</P>
<P>
   That hobby was a hunting preserve.
</P>
<P>
   Puntenney began his hobby in 1993 and it went through 1996.
There was a problem. Kent Henry's Arizona Hunt Club near Cordes
Junction was much closer to Phoenix. It, too, was classy.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Puntenney thought he was whipped. Henry was getting the
big corporate accounts. Puntenney said he put out only about 1,000
birds.
</P>
<P>
   But this year, Henry lost the club when the land he used was
sold for development. With the demise of the Arizona Hunt Club,
Puntenney is up and running full bore.
</P>
<P>
   Like Bob Henson's Pheasant Recreation near La Palma, Puntenney
offers pheasant and chukar hunting on his grasslands rather than
Henson's croplands. His birds are excellent. The pheasants have
full tails, and the chukars are lively. The facilities are
excellent.
</P>
<P>
   For the uninitiated, you pay for the number of birds his staff
puts out. Then you pass through the grasslands, trying to shoot as
many as you can.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd go bankrupt if hunters paid for the number of birds they
shot,'' Puntenney said. That means he has some bad shooters and
loses most of the leftovers to coyotes.
</P>
<P>
   Some preserves require membership, which demands a fee that
allows so many birds to be placed in the field. Puntenney is not
selling memberships. He charges by the number of birds placed in
the preserve.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, it costs $130 to put out four pheasants. Six
chukars cost another $100. If you have your own dogs, that's fine.
If you want a guide and his dogs, that's another $35 for the first
gun and $10 each for additional guns.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to stay there, two cabins are available. Both have
kitchens and bathrooms. Both rent for $100 a night and sleep five
or more.
</P>
<P>
   But that's not all. Because of the water table, the ranch offers
terrific waterfowl hunting, complete with blinds and decoys.
</P>
<P>
   That cost is $250 per gun for a guided trip. But Puntenney has a
waiting list.
</P>
<P>
   Long Meadow Preserve also has a sporting clays course and a tent
city for those who want to use it. Those who shoot there also can
take advantage of a waterway that offers excellent Gambel quail
shooting. These are wild birds. &QL; 
Barry Burkhart can be reached at barry.burkhart(at)pni.com via
e-mail. Long Meadow Preserve can be reached at (520) 778-9563. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-31-98 0129EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
