A3032 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-FIESTA-FLA &UR; ST-WAR     12-31 0637
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-FIESTA-FLA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WARRICK NOT TO BE IGNORED 
</HEADLINE>
  ST-WARRICK-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB COHN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Peter Warrick was upset, and he wore the mood like the No. 9 on
his back. The player Florida State Coach Bobby Bowden calls the
most elusive Seminoles receiver ever was finding out how elusive a
football can be when handled by a young, inexperienced quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's frustrating not to get the ball, but I can't go out there
and show I'm frustrated that I'm not getting the ball,'' Warrick
said after he caught one pass for 10 yards from Marcus Outzen in a
24-7 victory over Wake Forest on Nov. 14.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first start for Outzen, a sophomore replacing the
injured Chris Weinke. Outzen played OK against a pretty bad
defense. But the big test was the following week, the annual
bloodletting against Florida. The Seminoles needed a big game from
Warrick, but the question was not only whether Outzen could find
him, but whether he could deliver the ball.
</P>
<P>
   Here's the answer: Warrick had eight catches for 119 yards and a
touchdown. A former high school quarterback, he also threw a
46-yard touchdown pass off a reverse to Ron Dugans. Florida State
won, 23-12.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bigger the competition, the bigger plays I have to make,''
Warrick said. ``I feel I have to step up to another level.''
</P>
<P>
   Warrick has 61 catches for 1,232 yards _ a 20.2 average _ and 12
touchdowns. He's rushed 13 times for 85 yards and a touchdown, and
averaged nearly 14 yards on 15 punt returns. He is a first-team
All-American and was one of three finalists for the Biletnikoff
Award, the top prize for receivers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks to me like he might be the most dangerous receiver in
the country,'' Bowden said. ``He might be the hardest to tackle
that there is. You just don't hardly get him one on one. A sideline
and another man is what you need to tackle him.''
</P>
<P>
   When they're not breaking in a new quarterback, coaches plot,
plan and figure how to get Warrick, a 6-foot, 190-pound junior from
Bradenton, Fla., involved in the offense as much as possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you go into the game without planning to get him the ball,
he might not touch it enough,'' offensive coordinator Mark Richt
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the time, you can just call your normal game plan and
he'll get enough touches. But you can't leave that up to chance.
That happened in the Wake Forest game. I didn't do a good job of
making sure he got the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Warrick, whose 136 receptions and 2,583 yards in three seasons
both rank fourth in school history, came to Florida State with the
requisite glittering prep credentials and was a star almost from
the start. His first two years were terrific. But he still had a
to-do list this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the beginning of the year, I needed to improve my
consistency,'' he said. ``I feel like I came a long way. I matured
a lot. Right now, I feel like I'm at the top of my game.''
</P>
<P>
   Warrick became acquainted with Minnesota Vikings rookie Randy
Moss during Moss' brief stay at Florida State a few years ago, and
he shares Moss' confidence that borders on cockiness. Asked whether
he's as good as Moss, Warrick responded, ``No doubt.'' Then,
however, he showed a spark of humility.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I'm not 6-5 or nothing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Warrick said Moss gave him his beeper number, but he lost it. So
perhaps the two can get reacquainted next year in the NFL. Warrick
has another year of college eligibility remaining, but he also has
a baby daughter, A'Lyric, and he takes parenthood seriously.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to weigh my options,'' he said. ``I have to make
sure I make the right decision because it's an important time in my
life. . . . I still have my job to do here, but my family is
first.'' &QL; 
Kent Somers contributed to this report. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
