<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-31 01:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3033 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-FIESTA-TENN-PRICE     12-31 0521
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-FIESTA-TENN-PRICE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RECEIVER HAS FEW PEERS  
 TENNESSEE'S PRICE  STANDS OUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   At first, it wasn't easy being Peerless Price. Growing up in
Dayton, Ohio, his friends were usually relentless with him because
of his one-of-a-kind name.
</P>
<P>
   ``They all said it was a stupid name,'' said Price, who often
agreed in those days. ``They constantly asked me why I thought I
had no peers. I didn't understand it back then.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Price, the latest in a stream of outstanding wide receivers
at Tennessee, started playing sports in high school. Suddenly, it
was very cool to be named Peerless, especially in newspaper
clippings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started to realize it was a great name,'' he said. ``It
helped me stand out from the crowd. It's not like my name is Sean
or Mike, like so many other people. I really like it now.''
</P>
<P>
   Price's mother, Vinder Burress, wanted her son's name to be
unique. She started scouring through a dictionary, searching for
just the right name.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, she came across the winner. The ``Merriam-Webster
Dictionary'' defines Peerless as ``Having no equal. Matchless.
Supreme, superlative, incomparable.''
</P>
<P>
   Price joins the exclusive company of previous Tennessee
receivers Willie Gault, Tim McGee, Carl Pickens, Alvin Harper,
Anthony Miller, Stanley Morgan and last year's sensation, Marcus
Nash.
</P>
<P>
   ``I definitely wanted to be a part of the tradition they have
here with wide receivers,'' said Price, whose 147 catches, 2,298
yards and 19 touchdowns all rank third in Tennessee history.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told myself in high school that if Tennessee recruited me,
that's where I'd go. To be mentioned in the same breath with those
guys is incredible, more than I ever could have expected.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite what his name might indicate, Price has not been without
peers. He was a second-team All-Southeast Conference selection.
Florida State All-American wide receiver Peter Warrick is
considered the best receiver in the nation and may very well pass
up his final season with the Seminoles to apply for the NFL draft.
But it's not like Price, a senior, will slip out of contention for
NFL status.
</P>
<P>
   Price is expected to be selected sometime late in the first
round, which would make him the ninth Volunteers receiver to be
selected in the opening round, where Nash was taken by Denver
before this season, since Morgan became the first in 1977.
</P>
<P>
   Price, like so many Tennessee receivers, also runs for the track
team, a point that seems to attract great receivers to Knoxville.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't stop them from running track,'' Tennessee Coach
Phillip Fulmer said. ``A fast guy is a fast guy in the spring or in
the fall.''
</P>
<P>
   Price will put his talents on display for the final time in a
Tennessee uniform Monday night. If he outperforms Warrick, it could
be the deciding factor in the game that will determine the national
championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always think I'm better than anyone else on the field,''
Price said. ``I just want to show the world I'm just as good as any
other wide receiver.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
