<SLUG> BC-FBC-FIESTA-NOTEBOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VOLS COACHES DON'T DWELL ON MANNING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAOLA BOIVIN  and RICHARD OBERT  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Although his college football career ended a year ago, in many
ways, Tennessee remains Peyton's place.
</P>
<P>
   Although Volunteers quarterback Tee Martin is good friends with
predecessor Peyton Manning, he said Tennessee's staff made it a
point this season not to mention the former standout's name around
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It never comes up,'' Martin said. ``I know it's a conscious
effort on everyone's part around here not to do it, and especially
early on, I never heard it. I think it was their way of trying to
keep the pressure off me, and I'm grateful for that.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the biggest concerns about Manning's departure was the
loss of leadership. Defensive coordinator John Chavis said some
players took the concern personally.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have all the respect in the world for Peyton Manning,''
Chavis said. ``He's a great football player and a great young man.
But certainly, I think there were some players who felt like they
had some things they needed to prove.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Money talk &QL; 
 &QL; 
Although the Volunteers will receive about $3.8 million from the
Fiesta Bowl after revenue is shared among Southeastern Conference
schools, they expect to have a net profit of $850,000 after
expenses. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Quick hits &QL; 
 &QL; 
Freshman receiver Jermaine Kent was sent back to Knoxville for
``disciplinary reasons,'' Tennessee Coach Phil Fulmer said.
Although Fulmer didn't elaborate, he did say Kent is still on the
team.
</P>
<P>
   Among those visiting practice Wednesday was Arizona State Coach
Bruce Snyder. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Autograph seeking &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Florida State sophomore quarterback Marcus Outzen said he went
home during the Christmas break and dug up a 1990 Fiesta Bowl hat
that he had autographed that year by Coach Bobby Bowden. Outzen was
12 then and a huge Seminoles fan who saw Bowden as a celebrity.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main thing about him is what you see is what you get,''
Outzen said. ``He's a friendly guy, he's personable. That's how he
is with the team. That's how he is with strangers, the fans. That's
how he is with everybody. That's an unbelievable quality to have in
the position he's in, with people bugging him all the time.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Smash 'em &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Florida State offensive guard Jason Whitaker said he welcomes
Tennessee stacking up at the line to try to stop the run early.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to come out and smash them in the mouth and let them
know you're here,'' Whitaker said. ``It doesn't matter how many
people they stack in the box. You have to keep pounding them. If
it's three yards and a cloud of dust all night long, we'll take
it.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Streaking &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Florida State is looking not only for its second national title
in the '90s, but for a chance to keep a streak alive. A victory
over Tennessee will assure that the Seminoles finish no lower than
fourth in the final Associated Press poll for the 12th straight
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kids don't want to be the group that ends that record,''
offensive coordinator Mark Richt said. ``That streak means a lot to
this program. There are a lot of guys over the last 12 years
watching and hoping that streak continues.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
