A3037 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-HOLIDAY_ARIZONA-S     12-31 0578
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-HOLIDAY_ARIZONA-SMITH-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMITH GIVES WILDCATS BITE IN 2ND HALF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ Arizona may have two quarterbacks, but there was
only one Offensive Player of the Game Wednesday night in Arizona's
23-20 Holiday Bowl victory over the Nebraska Cornhuskers.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Keith Smith was determined to share the award with Ortege
Jenkins, just as the two shared the Wildcats' most visible position
through an improbable season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a saw, and I'm going to cut this right down the
middle,'' Smith said as he held up his trophy.
</P>
<P>
   But there was no doubt about whom it belonged to.
</P>
<P>
   Smith completed 11 of 19 passes for 143 yards and a touchdown.
He engineered two second-half touchdown drives, including the game
winner that running back Kelvin Eafon capped by diving 1 yard with
6:08 to play.
</P>
<P>
   Smith ran for 35 yards in the 68-yard drive, including a 20-yard
scramble that jump-started the march. He was clobbered on the play,
and Jenkins came in to take one snap.
</P>
<P>
   But this was Smith's team.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona Coach Dick Tomey, following his usual plan, brought
Jenkins off the bench in the second quarter with the Wildcats
holding a 9-0 lead. Smith had played well but not spectacularly,
and Arizona had come away with only three field goals from three
chances inside the Nebraska 10-yard line.
</P>
<P>
   But Jenkins fumbled when he was hit in the backfield, leading to
Nebraska's first points of the game, Kris Brown's 25-yard field
goal with 4:58 to play in the half.
</P>
<P>
   Nebraska scored 10 more points before the break. And the
Wildcats, with receiver Jeremy McDaniel out with a hip injury,
appeared to have run out of ways to move the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't taking advantage of our quick passing game,'' Smith
said. ``We came out right away in the second half and took
advantage of (wide receiver) Dennis Northcutt. Their defensive ends
were coming really hard and putting pressure on, so we had to get
Northcutt involved.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Arizona's offensive line took charge, and running back
Trung Canidate began to find running room. Smith moved the ball
with his feet as well as his arm.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always been a running quarterback, but our receivers are
so talented, we have to get them the ball,'' Smith said. ``I try to
stay patient in the pocket and make things work, but if there's an
opening there, like in the fourth quarter, I'm going to take it and
run.''
</P>
<P>
   With the Cornhuskers playing man-to-man defense, Smith waited
for Nebraska's linebackers to commit, and he was off.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was frustrating because we kept getting into the red zone
in the first half, and we couldn't get the ball into the end
zone,'' Smith said. ``We kept coming away with three points. I was
just trying to find a way to get it in the end zone.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith said the Wildcats knew they had to come away with a
touchdown on the decisive drive after Nebraska took a 20-16 with
10:55 to play.
</P>
<P>
   When it was over, nobody was happier than Jenkins, who was in
tears as he hugged Smith.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a great year, and this quarterback tandem did a
tremendous job,'' Jenkins said. ``There's no reason we can't make
it work again next year.''
</P>
<P>
   It's difficult to argue with the results _ a 12-1 record.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people were saying that this couldn't work,'' Smith
said. ``If we had two quarterbacks bickering at each other, a
season like this can't happen.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
