A3038 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-BICKLEY_COLUMN-AR     12-31 0727
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-BICKLEY_COLUMN-ARIZ-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VICTORY ON A DIFFICULT NIGHT VALIDATES CATS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN BICKLEY  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ Nothing shines like resiliency, the polish of effort
that won't go away.
</P>
<P>
   And this was watercolor to masterpiece, mush to Michaelangelo,
Crayon to the Louvre.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona never looked worse. Never looked so incompetent. Never
looked so much like a cat in a rainstorm.
</P>
<P>
   And somehow, when the gun sounded, the Wildcats never looked
better.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to finish in the top five,'' Arizona Coach Dick
Tomey crowed. ``This is a great football team.''
</P>
<P>
   Destiny may have been Ortege Jenkins spinning in air and landing
in the end zone. But this was all about desire. A team that sailed
on the winds of skill needing to prevail on heart. A team that had
to rise above a mountain of self-induced misery. On what could've
been the biggest night in the history of the program.
</P>
<P>
   When it was over, the Wildcats threw water coolers in the air
while Nebraska sulked off the field. They danced like fools,
soaking in the triumph. Jenkins cried like a blubbering baby. Then
Kelvin Eafon grabbed a microphone and led a wobbly chorus of the
school fight song.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, this was a much-needed jolt of respect for the
Pac-10. A victory that will leap out of the record books because of
their opponent, which, no matter the current plight, still is the
most storied team in the land. The kind that might take the program
and its recruiting to another level.
</P>
<P>
   A victory that proves Arizona is the best team in college
football not invited to the BCS.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, with a minimum amount of competence, this would've
been a blowout. Twice, an Arizona touchdown was nullified by
penalty. Another time, a wonderful opportunity _ four downs, ball
on the 2 _ was disrupted by unsportsmanlike conduct. Three times in
the first half, Arizona had the ball inside the 10-yard line. And
produced nine points.
</P>
<P>
   One of the silliest aspects of college football is the canyon of
time separating the seasons. The continuity of November is gone by
Christmas. Neither of these teams had played in more than a month,
and it showed.
</P>
<P>
   Penalty flags flying. Footballs that must've been coated with
petroleum jelly. Enough recovered fumbles to set a Holiday Bowl
record. Play-calling from Tomey and staff that was abominable.
</P>
<P>
   When Wilma the Wildcat, one of the team mascots, fell 20 feet
into the water Monday, cracking her head on the iron cleat of a
Navy vessel, the karma felt bad. When a pre-game sky diver toting
an Arizona flag fell on his backside attempting to land, you knew
there was trouble. But nothing so ominous as a four-point deficit
at halftime when there should've been a commanding lead.
</P>
<P>
   Then it all changed. Tomey wisely abandoned his platoon system
in the second half, and Keith Smith produced successive touchdown
drives in the fourth quarter. Eafon picked up a huge fourth-down
conversion, Brad Brennan plucked a clutch touchdown out of the air.
And the brilliant Chris McAlister, who fumbled an interception that
could've locked it up, atoned with an acrobatic pick in the waning
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Out of sure wreckage comes a win for the ages. They hit an
iceberg and found a way to shore.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona had been one of the most dynamic, entertaining teams to
grace college football in 1998. Jenkins' heroics against
Washington. Tomey's wife authoring a book called ``Balls.'' On the
same day that Ricky Williams rushed for 259 yards to set a new NCAA
record, Trung Canidate did one better, dropping 288 on the Sun
Devils. And the only thing separating Arizona from the BCS was a
fourth quarter against UCLA when the Bruins scored three touchdowns
on three successive plays.
</P>
<P>
   The Wildcats were unselfish to a fault. Jenkins, who
orchestrated a victory over ASU last year, one that might've saved
Tomey's job, had no dilemma splitting time with Smith. Canidate
shared the backfield with Eafon. A team content to be a team.
</P>
<P>
   A loss wouldn't have been right, not with the Fiesta Bowl in
town and the Cardinals going to the playoffs. Not when it would've
blown Arizona's shot at immortality.
</P>
<P>
   But in the end, Arizona simply wouldn't lose. Or let us forget. &QL; 
Dan Bickley can be reached at 444-8253 or at
dan.bickley(at)pni.com. via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
