<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-PREDATORS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS HALT THREE-GAME SKID 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALLEN LESSELS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE _ The Bruins needed a much better start. Got that.
</P>
<P>
   They needed something out of their top scoring line. Got that.
</P>
<P>
   They needed to reaffirm their commitment to defense. Did that.
</P>
<P>
   And it wouldn't hurt if they got a good bounce or two. Got
those, too.
</P>
<P>
   It all added up to a 5-2 win over the Nashville Predators in the
Bruins' first visit to Nashville Arena _ there's just something
funny about starting a hockey game to the strains of ``Rocky Top''
_ Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   That the Bruins had a 4-0 lead entering the final period and
things got away from them a bit took some of the satisfaction out
of the evening. But bottom line, a win is a win.
</P>
<P>
   ``To get a lead and to hold it,'' said goalie Rob Tallas. ``It's
something to build off.''
</P>
<P>
   Tallas and the defense shut down the Predators through two
periods and held on in the third. He finished with 27 saves.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins made their three-game losing streak history and
avoided their first four-game skid in more than a year, all the
more important given Thursday night's clash with the high-flying,
sharp-shooting Stars in the finale of what had been a rough road
trip.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Pat Burns took his best
it's-a-long-season-and-let's-not-get-too-wound-up-yet approach to
the team's recent misfortunes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not the end of the world,'' Burns said before the game.
``Every team has its bad sequences and we're probably on a bad one
right now.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins took care of that, for the moment, and now take on
the Stars, who are 9-0-3 in their last dozen games. They did it by
ending the first period up, 1-0, on a goal by Steve Heinze, who
also had two assists. They had trailed 1-0, 2-0, and 3-0 after a
period in the consecutive losses.
</P>
<P>
   They did it with two goals from Anson Carter, Heinze's linemate.
</P>
<P>
   They did it with a goal from Sergei Samsonov, who had been
scoreless in four straight games.
</P>
<P>
   They did it, from the start, with defense. They were outshot,
18-8, in the first period of Monday night's 5-1 loss to the
Capitals. Wednesday night, they turned the tables and outshot the
Predators, 17-8, in the first.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had so much jump in the first period, they didn't have a
chance,'' Tallas said. ``They really didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   And the Bruins did it with bounces. The most fortuitous came on
Carter's first goal, 61 seconds after Samsonov's, and pushed the
lead to 3-0 just 5:43 into the second period.
</P>
<P>
   Carter stole the puck as a Predator tried to break out of the
Nashville zone. Carter went in deep and tried to center a pass.
Defenseman Jan Vopat, diving into the play, deflected the puck over
goalie Tomas Vokoun and into the net.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Ferraro upped the lead to 4-0 at 8:35. He took a pass off
the boards from Joe Thornton, skated down the right side, and
blasted a shot over Vokoun's stick.
</P>
<P>
   That was all for the Nashville starter. Eric Fichaud came on in
relief.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why should I let him suffer any more,'' said Predators coach
Barry Trotz. ``We weren't giving him any help.''
</P>
<P>
   After a 2-1 setback at home to Philadelphia Dec. 23, the Bruins
had lost, 4-2, to the Islanders and to the Capitals.
</P>
<P>
   No time to panic. But time to try Tallas.
</P>
<P>
   And to try to get things going early.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this league it's tough if you don't get the first goal,''
Burns said. ``It's tough to win a game. It's a pattern now in this
league. We came out hungry, too. We wanted that first goal.''
</P>
<P>
   Heinze, who had gone nine games without a goal, got it. Samsonov
piled on. And Carter. And Ferraro. Then Carter, who got his second
on the power play with 28 seconds left before Nashville's Greg
Johnson scored with two seconds remaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't played with a lead for a while,'' said Don Sweeney.
``We think we've got things going in the right direction. But
you've got to play all 60 minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   On to Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   ``That'll be a real good test,'' Sweeney said.
</P>
</TEXT>
