r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-COWBOYS-GAILEY-TE     12-31 1573
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-GAILEY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAILEY REFLECTS ON FIRST SEASON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN LYONS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Chan Gailey is still uneasy with celebrity.
</P>
<P>
   But you can bet that people who stare at him in grocery stores
do not make him more uncomfortable than watching his team play
uninspired football in New Orleans or Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   With an attention for detail and a creative mind for offense,
Gailey, 46, has steered this expectation-weary club to 10 wins, a
playoff berth, and the NFC East crown in his first season. In a
wild-card game against the Arizona Cardinals on Saturday, the
Cowboys will be positioned to begin their chase of an unprecedented
sixth world championship.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with the ``Star-Telegram'' last week, Gailey
talked about the success, the adversity and the celebrity of his
first season as head coach of the Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   On his relationship with his players, he said, ``I think it's
good people don't get to know you too well. I don't want to get so
close to somebody that I can't tell them when there's a problem and
we've got to get some things straightened out.''
</P>
<P>
   On his relationship with the assistant coaches who were in place
before he was hired, he said, ``The first premise you have to work
on is, `Just because you don't know somebody doesn't mean they are
not a good coach.' ''
</P>
<P>
   And on his relationship with team owner Jerry Jones, Gailey
said, ``He's great. Jerry lets us do our jobs. He's involved. He
gets copies of the game plan. He sits in film review. He does what
every other general manager does. He loves the Cowboys. He wants to
win. He can't stand losing.''
</P>
<P>
   The rest of Gailey's thoughts:
</P>
<P>
   ``How have you handled the celebrity that goes with being head
coach of the Dallas Cowboys?''
</P>
<P>
   Gailey: I don't handle that very well. The hardest part for me
is not when people walk up and talk and say, `Hi, coach Gailey, I'm
Bill from Plano. It's great to meet you,' or `Good job,' or `How
about winning.' What gets me is when they stand over in the corner
and point. And you catch them out of the corner of your eye, and
you know they are pointing at you. I'd rather somebody come over
and speak. \RWhen they stare\S I get my bread and go. I'm not used
to any kind of status or recognition factor.
</P>
<P>
   ``You weren't on the job for six months when you had to deal
with the training-camp incident in the dorm room, where Everett
McIver's neck was cut. You were bombarded with questions every day
about it. Did you ever want to just break and tell what had
happened?
</P>
<P>
   Gailey: First of all, I thought that was our business. There are
some things that are our business and some things that are public
business, and I have to draw the line. There have been other things
taken care of in other matters that no one knows of. That one got a
lot of attention. But no matter how hard or how much pressure was
applied, I didn't believe it was in the best interest of the team
to talk about it. Where I got a little upset is that it kept coming
up when I had already said we were going to handle it as a team. I
guess pretty soon I have to realize I can't let that bother me. You
just keep answering the questions and nodding your head. It was
frustrating answering the questions, not how we're handling it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Cowboys are a team whose egos are matched only by their
paychecks. Has your perception of players such as Troy Aikman,
Michael Irvin, Emmitt Smith and Deion Sanders changed from the time
you took the head coaching job to now?''
</P>
<P>
   Gailey: I assumed that every one of those guys were good guys
that were looking for the best way to help this football team and
get back to the championship. I didn't let any prior stories, or
murmurs, or anything have an influence on me. I assumed that these
guys were going to be good and look good, and I expected the best
from them. And they have proven to be that way.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Troy Aikman wanted to come back a few weeks early from a
fractured collarbone, you were the one that told him to wait until
the Nov. 2 Eagles game. How has your relationship with Troy Aikman
been?''
</P>
<P>
   Gailey: First, I talked to Troy and said \Rresting\S `is the
smartest thing to do. Let's \Rnot play\S.' And he agreed. If he
would have fought, we'd have discussed it further. But once he saw
where the injury was, how he was feeling, when he needed to come
back, I think we concurred.
</P>
<P>
   It's got to be a mutual decision, because what happens if it's
not a mutual decision is you get a little bit of a crack in the
relationship. And you don't want little cracks to become big cracks
because, when another issue comes up, that widens the crack.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can you be the same, even-keeled person in big wins and in
gut-wrenching losses?''
</P>
<P>
   Gailey: I think when you are a leader, at the top, you are
supposed to create a sense of stability. I want the players to
know, that when things are going great, I'm going to be the one
that brings them back to earth, that reminds them where we are and
what we've go to get done. And when things are going tough, I want
to be the person that says, `Hey, we can still do this.'
</P>
<P>
   ``When the team is playing badly, why don't you ever berate
someone or call out a player in public?''
</P>
<P>
   Gailey: I don't believe in demeaning people, or in lashing out
in front of others and getting on a guy. If I've got something to
say to him, I'll bring him in here \Rhis office\S and say it to
him. I try not to publicly embarrass anybody.
</P>
<P>
   ``What did you take from the head coaches you were an assistant
under?''
</P>
<P>
   Gailey: \RFalcons coach\S Dan Reeves was very organized, very
matter-of-fact, very demanding about schedules and times. Everybody
was always headed in the same direction. That was a must. \RBroncos
coach\S Mike Shanahan was very innovative. He figured there were
different ways to do things, to take your people and stretch them
as far as they can be stretched, to put pressure on the defense.
\RSteelers coach\S Bill \RCowher\S lived on the edge. That's a
positive, not a negative. He was always like, `Just because it
hasn't been done doesn't mean we can't do it.' Five-wides, let's
try it. A lot of guys get conservative when they become the head
coach. Not him. He was always pushing the edge. After hanging
around him for a while, I realized, when you get a chance, don't go
conservative. That's not what got you there. Go for it. I
appreciate that.
</P>
<P>
   You cried when Star-Telegram columnist Jim Reeves asked how you
felt after winning your first game, 38-10, against Arizona on Sept.
6. What moves you to emotions like that?
</P>
<P>
   Gailey: Compassion moves me. Guys pulling together to do
something that people didn't think could be done, guys pushing
their egos aside to become a team player. My dad not having a
chance to be there at the first game. \RThinking\S about those
things grab you all at once. I don't show it unless it's brought
up. It gets you to a certain degree. After the \REagles\S game the
other day, I got close to that again, all the fighting, all the
tough times, all the adversity, the way the team responded to win
the division after some picked us to be third or fourth. To see how
they fought through a three-game losing streak to win was a great
thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``How has your relationship with Jerry Jones been?''
</P>
<P>
   Gailey: He's almost better in losing than in winning because
he's strong. When you are going through tough times, he comes in
here and sits in that chair and says, `Don't worry about it. We'll
get through it. We'll get it done.' Obviously, you are hurting as a
coach because you are not winning, or you've played bad. To have
somebody like Jerry, the owner, walk in and say, `Keep fighting,'
is a pretty big deal. And he's not saying, `You'll get it done.'
It's `we'll get it done.' Saying he's supportive does not give what
he does justice. It's much more than that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before you took the job as coach of the Cowboys, you
interviewed the staff that you'd inherit from the last coaching
regime. How have things gone?''
</P>
<P>
   Gailey: I'm not vain enough to think that the only guys I know
are the only guys that can coach. After looking at how the defense,
special teams and offensive line had played \Rin 1997\S, and after
visiting with Dave Campo, Joe Avezzano and Hudson Houck, I had a
very good comfort level about where our relationship would be. I
had a great feel for where their goals were, for where my goals
were, how I'd approach things, and how they'd approach things. That
was a nonissue in taking over, and since then, it has become a very
good working relationship.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coaches and players say they don't know if you are joking or
if you are serious when you address them sometimes. How has that
come up in your relationship with the players?''
</P>
<P>
   Gailey: I want to have as good a relationship as I can with all
the players without getting so close that they know exactly where
I'm coming from all the time and all of a sudden I become
vulnerable in this relationship. It's still a head coach-player
relationship. As much as I'd like for it to be otherwise, it still
takes on a head coach-player relationship and it's a business.
</P>
<P>
   Over a period of time that line moves and breaks down. But
initially I think everybody's got to know where I stand. Then that
line changes for each individual player. Some guys I'll have better
relationships with than others.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
