<HEADER>
A3042 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-SUGAR-TEXAS-A&AMP;M-T     12-31 0785
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-SUGAR-TEXAS-A&AMP;M-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AGGIES KNOW `FIRST' PRIORITY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ Win a championship, inherit a curse.
</P>
<P>
   That would be the glass-is-half-empty perspective of college
football historians, who understand the emotional baggage Texas A&AMP;M
will be carrying for frustrated fans in tomorrow's Sugar Bowl in
New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   It has been 10 years since a champion from the Big 12 South
Division or the former Southwest Conference won a traditional New
Year's Day game. A&AMP;M (11-2), ranked No. 8 in The Associated Press
poll, can end that streak by knocking off No. 3 Ohio State (10-1).
</P>
<P>
   The first step, said A&AMP;M tight end Dan Campbell, is to remember
a lesson learned during a season that saw the Aggies upend the two
highest-ranked opponents in school history after going nine years
without beating a Top 10 team.
</P>
<P>
   ``If God wanted you to look back, he'd have put eyes in the back
of your head,'' said Campbell, a senior from Glen Rose. ``What's
happened in the past is over. It doesn't affect today, so you've
got to look forward.''
</P>
<P>
   A&AMP;M coach R.C. Slocum drilled that message into his players'
heads before an Oct. 10 meeting with then-unbeaten Nebraska, a team
that routed A&AMP;M, 54-15, in the 1997 Big 12 title game. He warned
the Aggies about having too much respect for the Cornhuskers'
abilities, reminding them that ``lots of teams lose to the mystique
before they give themselves a chance'' to find out how they match
up physically.
</P>
<P>
   The Aggies responded with a 28-21 upset of then-No. 2 Nebraska.
A&AMP;M topped that effort with a 36-33 upset of Kansas State, then the
top-ranked team in the coaches' poll, to win the 1998 Big 12 title.
Suddenly, a school that had gone 104 years without beating a team
ranked higher than fourth in either college football poll had
knocked off No. 2 and No. 1 within seven weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike in past seasons heading into New Year's Day showdowns,
Slocum said these Aggies are confident, battle-tested in big games
and ``won't be in awe'' of the Buckeyes. That is why A&AMP;M players
adopt the glass-is-half-full approach, figuring an SWC expatriate
is long overdue to prevail on Jan. 1 and they simply find
themselves in the right place at the right time to end a decade of
disappointments.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's how we're approaching this game. I know I'm ready to
get another win under my belt and end this thing right,'' Campbell
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know we can beat good teams. We've done it,'' said A&AMP;M
tailback Dante Hall. ``There are no more self-doubts or questions.
The attitude has changed around here.''
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, A&AMP;M players left the field after a 29-23 loss to
UCLA in the Cotton Bowl willing to take solace in that they'd taken
the nation's fifth-ranked team to the wire. The days of
satisfaction with close calls against elite teams have ended in
Aggieland, however.
</P>
<P>
   Along with it, players and coaches hope to end the 10-year
drought on New Year's Day for former SWC schools. No team has
contributed more losses to that streak than A&AMP;M (four).
</P>
<P>
   Then again, A&AMP;M remains the last team from Texas to win on Jan.
1, when the Aggies knocked off Notre Dame, 35-10, in the 1988
Cotton Bowl. The way the Aggies see it, that makes them the most
appropriate choice to break the jinx.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time for us to win a big-time bowl,'' wide receiver Chris
Cole said. ``We've achieved some big goals this season. But that
would be the perfect finish. That would make this year really
special.''
</P>
<P>
   Only one thing can stop A&AMP;M, Campbell said. And it has nothing
to do with a fear of history or concern about extending some
unseemly trend.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it doesn't happen, it's just because they're a better team
than us,'' Campbell said. ``It would be sickening, because we've
had a heck of a year. And we don't want to end it with a loss.
After all we've accomplished this year, that's no way to go out.''
Decade of disappointments Texas A&AMP;M faces a unique challenge in its
Jan. 1 matchup against Ohio State in the Sugar Bowl. The Aggies
seek to end a 10-year drought in traditional New Year's Day bowls
by champions from the Big 12 South Division or the former Southwest
Conference. The list: YEAR LEAGUE BOWL RESULT 1999 Big 12 South
Sugar Ohio State 1998 Big 12 South Cotton UCLA 29, Texas A&AMP;M 23
1997 Big 12 South Fiesta Penn State 38, Texas 15 1996 SWC Sugar
Virginia Tech 28, Texas 10 1995 SWC Cotton USC 55, Texas Tech 14
1994 SWC Cotton Notre Dame 24, Texas A&AMP;M 21 1993 SWC Cotton Notre
Dame 28, Texas A&AMP;M 3 1992 SWC Cotton Florida State 10, Texas A&AMP;M 2
1991 SWC Cotton Miami, Fla. 46, Texas 3 1990 SWC Cotton Tennessee
31, Arkansas 27 1989 SWC Cotton UCLA 17, Arkansas 3
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
