<DOCNO> NYT19981231.0040 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-31 01:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3050 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-FLORIDA-STATE-DEF     12-31 0704
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-FLORIDA-STATE-DEFENSE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVEN WITHOUT STARS, FSU DEFENSE TOUGHER THAN EVER
</HEADLINE>
 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Florida coach Steve Spurrier deals in honesty. His comments
sometimes rankle. But even when it comes to discussing Florida
State _ he likes to call them ``Semis'' instead of Seminoles _
Spurrier grits his teeth and speaks his mind. Honestly.
</P>
<P>
   ``They clobbered us this year and last year we had about 500
yards against them,'' Florida coach Steve Spurrier said. ``If you
asked us, we'd say this year's defense is better than last
year's.''
</P>
<P>
   Last season, Florida State, with a defense that finished third
nationally, came within a victory over Spurrier's Gators of playing
for the national championship. And Spurrier's opinion is supported
by statistics.
</P>
<P>
   When the second-ranked Seminoles face top-ranked Tennessee in
Monday's Fiesta Bowl, they'll hit the field with a defense that
ranks No. 1 in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, Florida State benefitted from a strong pass
rush to shut down opposing offenses. But this season, the Seminoles
have had to rely on their secondary coverage. FSU has sacked the
quarterback ``only'' 40 times. The past two seasons, it had 64 and
67 sacks, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't put the pressure on that we did a year ago, two years
ago,'' Florida State coach Bobby Bowden said. ``If you're going to
do that, the coverage better be better, and it has been better.
</P>
<P>
   ``If somebody said, `What's the biggest difference in your
defense this year and the year before ... I think it's that our
secondary is playing better. The biggest difference this year is
we're covering better.''
</P>
<P>
   Last season, Florida State's secondary was short in numbers and
experience. Cornerback Mario Edwards and safety Sean Key were
serving one-year suspensions in 1997. Their return has been a
boost.
</P>
<P>
   This Florida State defense has depth and speed, but not a lot of
brute force. Defensive coordinator Mickey Andrews keeps his players
fresh; 33 players have seen action on defense and 23 have played in
every game. Andrews' heavy player rotation has at times concerned
Bowden.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I look out there and say, `Why in the world does he
have him in the game? This game's on the line and he's got the
third-string corner in there.' '' Bowden said. ``But they've got
them trained. They all can run and they're always fresh.''
</P>
<P>
   The numbers support that theory. Florida State has allowed just
45 points in the second half all season.
</P>
<P>
   The Seminoles' defensive unit doesn't have stars. In recent
years, Florida State has had No. 1 draft picks like Andre
Wadsworth, Peter Boulware, Reinard Wilson, Derrick Alexander,
Derrick Brooks and Marvin Jones. But the 1998 Seminoles do it with
depth.
</P>
<P>
   ``You probably can't say the defense right now has a
first-rounder, but if we were drafting defenses, I think you'd
draft Florida State's defense No. 1,'' Edwards said. ``Before the
season, Coach Andrews told us, `Guys, I think this is the best
secondary I've ever coached or had at Florida State.' Now we look
back 12 games into the season and we're the No. 1 secondary in the
country; the No. 1 defense in the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Not since 1993 has Florida State had a defense that is this
oppressive and dominating. And it's not just a coincidence that the
Seminoles are in position to win a national championship. Which is
what that '93 team accomplished.
</P>
<P>
   ``This bunch has accomplished an awful lot,'' Andrews said. ``I
think they would be lying if they said they haven't exceeded
expectations. To accomplish what they've done and the schedule
they've played is pretty amazing, I think.''
</P>
<P>
   The defense never rests Florida State's defense is first in passing
and total defense and second in rushing and scoring defense. A look
at how this Seminoles' defensive unit compares with other FSU
defenses this decade: Year Pts Yds/Rush Yds/Pass Yds/Gm TOs 1998 11
79 135 214 32 1997 15 52 189 241 32 1996 11 59 170 229 23 1995 18
132 213 345 35 1994 16 98 169 267 28 1993 9 98 186 254 24 1992 15
100 192 292 31 1991 15 83 198 281 37 1990 17 150 166 316 37 Note:
Points and yardage statistics are per-game averages.
</P>
</TEXT>
