A3054 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-TEXAS-BROWN-TEX     12-31 0844
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TEXAS-BROWN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAYERS PUT TRUST IN BROWN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE JONES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Can you pinpoint the moment Mack Brown turned the Texas football
program in the right direction, steered it back onto a road that
eventually led to the Southwestern Bell Cotton Bowl game against
Mississippi State?
</P>
<P>
   Was it the way he skillfully turned Ricky Williams' upcoming bid
for the Heisman Trophy into a unified goal, avoiding a potentially
divisive situation that could have elevated one player's importance
over that of the team?
</P>
<P>
   Was it after the potentially devastating losses to UCLA (49-31)
and Kansas State (48-7), when the Longhorns rallied behind a
redshirt freshman quarterback to run off a string of six
consecutive victories, including a plant-the-flag, 20-16 victory at
Nebraska?
</P>
<P>
   Or, after that streak came to a shocking end in a wild 42-35
loss at Texas Tech that wiped out hope of playing in the Big 12
Championship game, when his team again made an abrupt about-face to
stun Texas A&AMP;M (26-24) six days later before the largest crowd ever
in Royal Memorial Stadium?
</P>
<P>
   All perhaps. Or none of the above.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think one of Mack's best moments as a coach came the first
time he met the squad,'' Texas athletic director DeLoss Dodds said.
``I watched the kids' faces when he walked into the room and again
when he walked out. They bought into him very quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   Senior linebacker Dusty Renfro agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``After we lost to UCLA and Kansas State, coach Brown just kept
telling us that we were improving and that it was really tough to
play two of the best teams in the country right off the bat while
learning a new system and all,'' Renfro said. ``He told us just to
have a little perseverance and it would all work out _ and it did.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believed him then because we trusted him from the first
day. When he showed up in his cowboy boots and propped his foot up
on a chair and started talking _ we knew he was going to fit in.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Dodds, ``When we hired him, I thought he was as good as
I'd ever seen. He's proven to be even better than I thought.''
</P>
<P>
   The personable Brown has not only turned a program, but united a
sometimes fractious group of alumni and fans grown rancorous during
six roller-coaster seasons under John Mackovic.
</P>
<P>
   ``To have one man come in and change this whole town around and
get everyone back into Texas football has been exciting to be a
part of,'' senior wide receiver Wane McGarity said.
</P>
<P>
   Brown's first season at Texas has _ and hasn't _ exceeded his
own expectations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It might not have exceeded what I hoped coming in last
December,'' Brown said. ``But after I'd gone through spring
practice with the guys, I knew we weren't very good, were really
poor on defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``And after the first three games, we still had not made the
progress on defense we felt like we needed to make. And, we were
inexperienced at quarterback. Richard Walton hadn't played much _
and then he gets hurt \Rfirst quarter, UCLA\S.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I think considering all the circumstances of the year and
playing three of four top-10 teams on the road, it's been a super
year for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, as players have pointed to Brown's communication and
motivation skills and the way he immediately won their confidence,
he said one of his greatest concerns was how his new team would
respond to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing we were concerned about back in the spring was that
all these kids had been recruited by another staff. So we didn't
know them and they didn't know us very well,'' Brown said. ``It's
very hard to build up a good level of communication under those
circumstances. And if you don't have communication, you don't have
trust.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then, when you go 1-2, the trust is broken down even worse and
people start questioning themselves. We were really afraid that
after the lack of confidence we'd shown at the end of the previous
year, we might go back to the same thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown didn't let that happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's really good at explaining how things are,'' Renfro said.
``He really sees what's going on. He can tell what's going on just
by watching, talking to a few players here and there.
</P>
<P>
   ``He really likes to get inside and find out what's going on.
And when he's done that, he'll confront us with it and say, `This
is what has happened. And this is what we need to do to fix it.'''
</P>
<P>
   McGarity said that Brown has also been good about heading off a
problem before it becomes one.
</P>
<P>
   ``He realized that there could be a problem with us playing
top-10 teams back-to-back early,'' McGarity recalled. ``So he let
us know beforehand that win or lose, we had to realize we had the
whole season to play. So that's how we played it.
</P>
<P>
   ``And he also realized that if we're not having any fun, we're
not going to win any ballgames. He's a great motivator. He feeds
off us. And we feed off him. I don't know if this season would have
been any different if coach Brown wasn't here. It's hard to say.
But I do know he made a big difference.''
</P>
</TEXT>
