A3056 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-TENNESSEE-FIESTA-     12-31 1101
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TENNESSEE-FIESTA-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VOLS WORKED THEMSELVES INTO A TITLE FRENZY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tracing the origin of Tennessee's football success this season
leads in two directions.
</P>
<P>
   First, the Volunteers got a taste of championship champagne in
1997 when they won the Southeastern Conference championship.
</P>
<P>
   Second, after playing a slapped-around supporting role to
Nebraska's national championship in the Orange Bowl, the Volunteers
realized that neither their effort nor their work ethic was title
worthy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't play very well against Nebraska, and they just beat
the dog out of us and we just took our beating,'' junior center
Spencer Riley said. ``We used that as motivation.''
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee, a year after losing all-everything quarterback Peyton
Manning, is 12-0, top-ranked and playing for the national
championship. The Volunteers need a victory over Florida State in
Monday's Fiesta Bowl for the school's first national title since
1951.
</P>
<P>
   ``They forgot to tell the players they weren't supposed to be
this good,'' Tennessee coach Phillip Fulmer said. ``This team has
exceeded everybody's expectations. There were a lot of ifs about
this team. We had to replace Peyton, get our defensive line
healthy, replace three people in our secondary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their determination has been special. We said we didn't have
to be the best team in the country. We just have to be the best
team on the Saturdays that we play. Hopefully, we'll continue on
the Monday we play.''
</P>
<P>
   In Manning's four seasons, Tennessee won 40 of 49 games. But the
Volunteers' only championship came last year when they won the SEC.
That earned them a spot in the Orange Bowl against Nebraska.
Tennessee didn't put up much of a fight, losing 42-17.
</P>
<P>
   With the loss of Manning plus NFL draft picks Leonard Little,
Jonathan Brown, Terry Fair and Marcus Nash (all chosen in the first
three rounds), few people expected Tennessee to improve on last
season. The Volunteers, though, had other ideas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, we were kinda shocked about playing in a game like
the SEC championship game, the Orange Bowl,'' said junior
quarterback Tee Martin, who has been more than adequate replacing
Manning. ``We came out and didn't play very well in the SEC game.
Even though we won, it was kind of a negative, and we took that
feeling into the Orange.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we found out is what we had to do to get to the level of
the Nebraskas and the Michigans. We took that into spring practice
and the summer workouts. We had a different feeling coming into
this season. We knew what we wanted and we knew how to get it.''
</P>
<P>
   The goal of winning a national championship became a mantra as
the Volunteers spent the summer working in Knoxville. Nearly all of
the top players attended summer school and worked out. A three-hour
morning session included running, weight lifting and agility
drills. In the evening, it was seven-on-seven passing games.
</P>
<P>
   ``If somebody said we would have won another SEC championship
and be playing for a national championship, you'd say he was
crazy,'' senior linebacker Steve Johnson said. ``During the summer,
we made a commitment to each other to practice and work every day
to get better. We came together and jelled during the summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``When times got tough during the season, we'd look at each
other and challenged each other. We had spent all this time and
effort to get better. That's why we came to Tennessee, was to play
for championships.''
</P>
<P>
   It was during these summer sweat sessions that Tennessee's 1998
personality became genetic code. This would be a team with a
blue-collar work ethic, a team that would prove that it didn't need
stars to succeed. The Volunteers also developed a resiliency that
has bolstered them through adversity.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were probably the only people who thought we had a chance
of running the table,'' senior wide receiver Peerless Price said.
``We hadn't been this close in the past years. It all came together
because the guys worked hard together.''
</P>
<P>
   In the season opener, Martin drove the team from its
18-yard-line in the final 2:27 to set up a game-winning field goal.
In the next game, Tennessee finally got a meaningful victory over
hated rival Florida, a 20-17 overtime triumph in Knoxville. And,
after leading rusher Jamal Lewis was lost for the season with a
knee injury after Game 4, the Volunteers shrugged their shoulders
and got on with playing football.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of good teams have more than one way to win,'' Fulmer
said. ``But when you lose an impact player, there aren't a lot of
teams with the resiliency and the ability to overcome that kind of
loss.''
</P>
<P>
   The Volunteers' success also can be explained using a standard
from another sport. Often in college basketball, a team makes a
championship run after losing a star player. Examples: Virginia in
1984 and Utah in 1998 each reached the Final Four after losing
All-Americans (Ralph Sampson and Keith Van Horn, respectively).
</P>
<P>
   ``We have some guys who have developed into stars, guys who
could play in the NFL,'' Fulmer said. ``But we don't have a lot of
players who are nationally known. That's the approach we took and
the kids bought into it.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the beginning, the players were fighting for self-respect
and respect for the football team. It's caught on. I'm grateful to
the seniors and the captains for the way they went about their
business and how they hammered that point home.''
The replacement Volunteers Tennessee did not let the loss of
several significant players prevent it from going 12-0 and playing
in Monday's Fiesta Bowl national championship game. A look at the
players who replaced last season's top players: Pos. Player lost
Replacement player QB Peyton Manning Tee Martin
</P>
<P>
   Highlights: Completed 57 percent of his passes; 19 TDs, 6
interceptions WR Marcus Nash Cedrick Wilson
</P>
<P>
   Highlights: Second on team with 33 receptions, six for TDs DE
Jonathan Brown Shaun Ellis
</P>
<P>
   Highlights: 40 tackles, 1 sack, 6 tackles for loss MLB Leonard
Little Al Wilson
</P>
<P>
   Highlights: Moved from outside to inside, had 77 tackles, caused
five fumbles FS Corey Gaines Deon Grant
</P>
<P>
   Highlights: Team-high five interceptions, 82 tackles. SS Tori
Noel Fred White
</P>
<P>
   Highlights: 57 tackles, 1 interception RCB Terry Fair Dewayne
Goodrich
</P>
<P>
   Highlights: Team-high 10 pass breakups, 41 tackles TB Jamal
Lewis Travis Henry
</P>
<P>
   Highlights: 970 yards rushing, 7 touchdowns
</P>
<P>
   _ Lewis, a sophomore, suffered a season-ending injury against
Auburn in Tennessee's fourth game of the season.
</P>
