</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-USC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USC'S CLAIBORNE SET TO MAKE HIMSELF AVAILABLE FOR NFL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EL PASO _ USC junior linebacker Chris Claiborne said Wednesday
that he will select an agent ``soon,'' his first public
acknowledgment that he intends to make himself available for the
NFL draft.
</P>
<P>
   Claiborne said he will hold a press conference Monday at USC to
make his official announcement, which means today's game against
Texas Christian in the Sun Bowl will be his last as a Trojan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to try to pick an agent soon,'' Claiborne said, ``so
I can get to work and not be distracted. That's my main thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Claiborne said he should have an agent selected within two
weeks, and would like to avoid being represented by any large
agency or big-time representative.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to have one that's hands-on. I think it's a conflict
of interest when you go with somebody really big. Whose contract
are you going to do the best?'' Claiborne said. ``There's other
things I have to decide, like a money manager. The agent's job is
to get the contract. I'm not going to let one person do everything.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel I'm prepared for it. I have to find the best team of
people around me. Not only people who I respect but will reflect me
in the public. That people will say, `He's got a nice family. He's
a nice young man.' I don't want people to think, `Oh, I've got to
deal with this jerk.'''
</P>
<P>
   The intricate nature of Claiborne's comments demonstrates how
much thought he has put into turning pro. Claiborne said he will
also begin doing his homework on NFL teams to have some background
of each franchise that is interested in him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will study them,'' Claiborne said. ``All the way back to
1945. They will be blown away.''
</P>
<P>
   Claiborne had been steadfast in keeping his intentions secret,
prior to Wednesday's frank comments following USC's final practice
of the season.
</P>
<P>
   During a post-practice performance by the USC band in the Sun
Bowl, Claiborne directed it through its rendition of the school
fight song. As he ascended the ladder to lead the band, members
chanted ``one more year, one more year.''
</P>
<P>
   Those sentiments apparently fell on deaf ears. Claiborne is
projected to be a top-five draft pick and would probably not
increase his stock with another season of college football.
</P>
<P>
   He won the Butkus Award, which goes to the nation's top
linebacker, and recorded 107 tackles, six interceptions, including
two for touchdowns, along with 16 pass deflections.
</P>
<P>
   He was also USC's first unanimous All-American at linebacker and
the first Trojan to be a unanimous All-American at any position
since Keyshawn Johnson in 1995. He also earned Football News' 1998
Defensive Player of the Year award.
</P>
<P>
   But Claiborne has frequently felt shackled by the constraints of
the college game and opponents' desire to run plays away from him.
</P>
<P>
   Even while discussing TCU's option offense, Claiborne lamented
the thought of being double- and triple-teamed, something he
believes will happen on a weekly basis next season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I might not have many tackles (today). They might send three
or four people at me,'' Claiborne said. ``Hopefully, they're cocky
and they won't feel they'll have to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   USC coach Paul Hackett said earlier in the week that Claiborne's
chances of returning were ``50-50'' and that the linebacker was his
No.1 recruit for next season.
</P>
<P>
   ``To go out a year from now, with him winning a national
championship, which is our goal, is something that he'll never have
again,'' Hackett said. ``Pro football is going to welcome him with
open arms whether it be this year or next year. He's one of those
rare players.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, Hackett will likely have to focus on keeping wide receiver
R. Jay Soward in the fold, as he ponders joining Claiborne by
declaring early for the NFL draft.
</P>
<P>
   Claiborne said he had not spoken to Soward about the NFL, or
tried to influence his decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a personal thing that you shouldn't try to put on the
team,'' Claiborne said. ``R. Jay will do things his way. To try and
seek him out will not do any good.''
</P>
<P>
   Soward is expected to make his decision early next week,
although his father favors that R. Jay return for his senior
season. College players have until Jan. 8 to declare their
intentions.
</P>
<P>
   Notes: There's been one surprising lineup change for today's Sun
Bowl. Senior David Pratchard of Canyon Country will start at left
guard ahead of Jason Grain. USC offensive line coach Steve
Greatwood said the move was made because of Pratchard's performance
in practice, not because he is a senior.... USC will be the road
team and wear its white jerseys.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-31-98 0202EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
