<HEADER>
A3076 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-UCLA-DEFENSE-LADN     12-31 0794
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-DEFENSE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROSE WIN WOULD PUT BRUINS `GHOSTS' IN CLOSET
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ UCLA cornerback Marques Anderson emerged from the
training room a few weeks ago with a white bandage around his head
and a thick patch above his right eye.
</P>
<P>
   No, he wasn't preparing for the UCLA film school's latest
production, ``Saving Coach Aliotti.'' Pressed for an explanation,
Anderson chuckled and said it was a joke.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins' defense hasn't laughed much since it collapsed at
Miami, since it yielded 690 yards and 49 points and, many believe,
cost UCLA the national championship. Bitter and beleaguered,
players and coaches want to move on. But everywhere they turn, it's
thrown back in their face.
</P>
<P>
   At a Rose Bowl press conference Monday, defensive coordinator
Nick Aliotti was introduced as the offensive coordinator. When
linebacker Ryan Nece introduces himself on campus, people ask if he
plays offense or defense.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, the Bruins finally have a chance to end their
ignominious existence, a chance to answer their critics, get a jump
on next season and hold their heads high on Bruin Walk. They have a
chance, as linebacker Tony White said, to put ``the ghosts in the
closet.''
</P>
<P>
   UCLA may be playing Wisconsin in the Rose Bowl, but for the
maligned defense, this is the Redemption Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``To say we've been maligned might be an understatement,''
Aliotti said. ``Raked over the coals might be a better term. But
I'm not going to B.S. anybody. We didn't play against Miami, but we
need to put that behind us. It's been tough on me. This is an
opportunity to get some respect back.''
</P>
<P>
   Aliotti's job appeared to be in jeopardy immediately following
the Hurricane game. But coach Bob Toledo gave Aliotti a vote of
confidence after determining the problems weren't tactical but
fundamental: The Bruins were in the right place to make tackles;
they just didn't make them.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, UCLA devoted much of its Rose Bowl preparation time _
teams are allowed 15 postseason practices _ on rudimentary tacking
drills. But aside from tweaking the gameplan to counteract
Wisconsin's option attack, Aliotti has not made dramatic changes in
scheme or personnel.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is, we are who we are,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   They are talented but young, instinctive but uncertain and, most
of all, united in punctured pride. If nothing else, the criticism _
both internal and external _ galvanized the defense. In recent
weeks, they've vocalized their frustration with the disparate
reviews heaped on UCLA: The offense gets accolades; the defense
gets ripped. No one wants to be ``Ishtar'' forever.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, the Bruins can close the chasm.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will be a real character builder,'' said linebacker Tony
White. ``Besides maybe one or two guys, we've never played in a big
game like this.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we have a bad game, there will be a snowball effect. We'll
go into the offseason thinking about what we can do to turn the
defensive program around. If we have a good game, it closes the
door with the ghost in the closet.''
</P>
<P>
   Redemption is thickest for Aliotti and linebacker Brendon
Ayanbadejo, who missed most of the Miami game with sprained knee
ligaments. Afterward, several Bruins questioned the severity of
Ayanbadejo's injury _ a stunning, piercing blow to a passionate
senior who plays at dervish pace. He missed two weeks of practice
and, even now, is not completely healthy. But as the emotional
leader of the young defense, his presence is essential.
</P>
<P>
   ``We showed how bad we can be against Miami, and now we have to
show how good we can be against Wisconsin,'' Ayanbadejo said. ``We
have a lot to prove. We have to show what kind of character we
have, what kind of heart we have.''
</P>
<P>
   This week the problem isn't their hearts and heads, but their
knees, ankles and elbows. Starting nose guard Micah Webb ripped
knee ligaments against Miami and is out until training camp '99, at
the earliest. Ayanbadejo is not at full strength. Nor is defensive
end Pete Holland, who sprained elbow ligaments in practice and may
not play. Reserve nose guard Kory Lombard is doubtful with a
sprained ankle.
</P>
<P>
   Implausible as it seems, the Bruins are even younger than they
were before. True freshmen Anthony Fletcher and Ken Kocher will
start for Holland and Webb, respectively _ meaning eight defensive
starters are freshmen and sophomores.
</P>
<P>
   The line, so critical in slowing Wisconsin's mammoth tailback,
Ron Dayne, will feature a true sophomore and two true freshmen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Down the road, we have a chance to be really good,'' Aliotti
said. ``(But the injuries) mean more time for the freshmen. It's
the Puppy Chow defense.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
