r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-PEPPERDINE-SIENA-     12-31 0583
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-PEPPERDINE-SIENA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEPPERDINE FALLS TO SIENA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MALIBU, Calif. _ Kelvin Gibbs never heard of Siena until he saw
Pepperdine's schedule. Many of his teammates echoed it.
</P>
<P>
   Suffice to say, the Waves knew nothing of the Franciscan school,
had no idea of its upstate New York location in the Albany suburb
called Loudonville.
</P>
<P>
   Nor were they aware of the measles scare in 1989 at Siena, which
forced North Atlantic Conference to play its league tournament in
an empty building to alleviate fear of spreading the disease.
</P>
<P>
   However, they are all things the Waves should bone up on because
Siena, which now plays in the Metro Atlantic Athletic Conference,
holds a special piece of Pepperdine history.
</P>
<P>
   The Saints beat the Waves 85-76 at Firestone Fieldhouse on
Wednesday to win the inaugural Sparkletts Invitational, ending
Pepperdine's 10-game home winning streak and severely dampening the
festive mood of a win against Rhode Island 24 hours earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ``To beat a big-time team like (Rhode Island) and then to come
out like this... Siena is a good team, but I think we should have
beaten them,'' Gibbs said. ``We didn't play up to or ability, both
offensively and defensively.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead of the tournament setting up the Waves' last tune-up for
the West Coast Conference, a trip to San Jose State on Saturday, it
pushed Pepperdine's progress backward.
</P>
<P>
   No longer is the focus on gaining momentum. Rather the Waves now
must figure out a way to score consistently in a half-court offense
that isn't producing. That deficiency shined greatly late.
</P>
<P>
   Pepperdine, which led by double-digits in second-half, went
ahead 67-63 on a basket by Gibbs with 8:01 to play, but managed
just one field goal the rest of the way thanks to Siena's zone
defense.
</P>
<P>
   The Saints took the lead for good, 78-75, on a 3-pointer by
Isaiah Stewart with 2:38 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once they got up we didn't stay poised,'' said Pepperdine
forward Marc McDowell, who scored a game-high 18 points. ``We
started rushing our shots and didn't' take care of the ball. When
we're pressured we have to keep doing our thing instead of breaking
down and going one-on-one. You've got to stick to the game plan
more.''
</P>
<P>
   Siena (9-1) has won five straight, but coach Paul Hewitt, in his
second season of what is turning into a masterful rebuilding job
with the Saints, said he wasn't about to cut down the nets and
declare this the grandest of wins for the program.
</P>
<P>
   Heck, it wasn't even the best win this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have some qualities, like George Washington,'' Hewitt said.
``What it does is give our guys confidence they can go on the road
and win in a tough building. They have a long history here at
Pepperdine of having a strong home court advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   Notes: The field is tentatively set for next season's Sparkletts
Invitational, and again it could feature the return of a former
UCLA coach. Larry Farmer is expected to bring his Loyola-Chicago
team here next season. Colorado State is also slated to
participate, and Pepperdine officials hope to secure Princeton as
the fourth team in the next few weeks. But the tournament is being
moved to Thanksgiving weekend.... Siena's Marcus Faison was named
the tournament MVP. The all-tournament team was composed of Siena's
Brandon Fields, Pepperdine's Gibbs and McDowell and Rhode Island's
Lamar Odom and Antonio Reynolds-Dean.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
