<SLUG> BC-FBC-USCNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HACKETT HAS NO DESIGNS ON LEAVING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EL PASO _ USC coach Paul Hackett's name has surfaced in Chicago
as a possible candidate for the Bears' coaching vacancy, but
Hackett claimed Wednesday that he had no desire to return to the
NFL.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would think that no one would be shocked if my name was
thrown around in the NFL,'' Hackett said. ``It's an honor that
people felt that I did enough work as an assistant in the NFL to
merit being a head coach. It's flattering.''
</P>
<P>
   But Hackett repeatedly stressed that he was not considering
leaving USC.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am here. I just got here. I love being here. I've been there
and I want to be here,'' Hackett said. ``I would hope my name being
mentioned would be directly as a result of how well we do on the
field at USC.''
</P>
<P>
   Hackett's name has been tied to the Bears' job because of his
close friendship with Mark Hatley, Chicago's vice president of
player personnel. The pair worked together for three years in
Kansas City, and Hatley flew to Los Angeles to visit Hackett once
during the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why my name is being thrown around,'' Hackett said.
``He and I are good enough friends that he knows about my
commitment at USC.''
</P>
<P>
   Hackett said he has not been contacted by the Bears or talked to
Hatley.
</P>
<P>
   Hackett said he is frustrated that his name could arise for NFL
openings because of his pro background and become an issue during
recruiting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody is going to hammer us with it,'' he said. ``(UCLA
coach) Bob Toledo has never coached a down in pro football. Every
year it's going to come up. I'm going to get hammered.''
</P>
<P>
   Another commitment: USC received an oral commitment from
Courtney Morgan, a 6-foot-4, 315-pound lineman from Westchester
High. Morgan selected the Trojans over Michigan. He is USC's 11th
commitment.
</P>
<P>
   Familiar faces: Westlake High coach Jim Benkert watched
Wednesday's practice with former assistant coach Bill Culpepper,
who is the head coach at Clint High in El Paso. Culpepper was also
the head coach at Viewpoint in Malibu for one season. Two of
Benkert's former players _ wide receiver Billy Miller and defensive
lineman Bobby DeMars _ play for the Trojans.
</P>
<P>
   Coach in cast: Defensive coordinator Bill Young will wear a
large cast on his arm for the game, but he doesn't have a broken
arm. Young tore a ligament in his right hand after cutting it on a
piece of glass during a team barbecue.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks a lot worse than it is,'' Young said.
</P>
<P>
   Ticket tally: By Wednesday night, the Sun Bowl had sold 40,428
tickets. A walk-up of 4,000 to 5,000 is expected, meaning the game
could be close to the stadium capacity of 51,171.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
