</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-BASKETBALL-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOOKING INTO PAC-10'S NEW YEAR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Nine weeks and 180 games of what promises to be
the wildest, wackiest Pacific-10 season ever _ all in just four
questions and 900 words:
</P>
<P>
   How many dance?
</P>
<P>
   The Pac-10 will send between four and six teams to the NCAA
Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Stanford is the only bet-the-house lock. Despite injuries and
two early losses, the Cardinal remains the class of the conference
_ the only team capable of winning consistently on the road.
</P>
<P>
   Cal, Washington and Arizona probably have the combination of
talent and experience to earn at-large bids on Selection Sunday
(March 7), although losses to Boise State and Gonzaga could hurt
the Huskies.
</P>
<P>
   USC and UCLA are teetering _ neither destined for the NIT nor
guaranteed spots in the NCAAs.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans are 8-1 with 18 conference games left, meaning
they'll need 10 wins to have a chance at an at-large berth. Aside
from Kansas, a 29-point loss, USC played a poor non-conference
schedule (best win: at Nevada-Las Vegas) and that figures to
deflate its power rating come March.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans are a prime example of the importance of preseason
tournaments, which provide three games over and above the 27
allowed by the NCAA. With one or two extra wins in Alaska, Maui,
the NIT or Puerto Rico, USC would have had greater margin for error
in the Pac-10 and still hit the 18-win barrier.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins have a quality non-conference schedule (Maryland,
Kentucky, Oklahoma State, Syracuse, Louisville) that will bolster
their case with the Selection Committee. Historically, 18 wins and
a top-30 power rating are enough for an at-large bid. But 18 wins
won't be as easy as it seems.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins are 8-2 with the Pac-10, Louisville and Syracuse
remaining. Considering the inexperience _ their top 10 players are
freshmen and sophomores _ they could finish anywhere from 12-6 to
8-10 in conference play.
</P>
<P>
   As opposed to recent years, when protecting the homecourt and
splitting on the road was the accepted formula for success, the
Bruins this season should aim for seven wins at home and three on
the road. That gets them to 10-8 in the Pac-10 and 18 wins
(minimum) overall. Do that, and they're in.
</P>
<P>
   Who are the league's emerging stars?
</P>
<P>
   They weren't prep phenoms, they didn't dominate the recruiting
rankings, and they received little preseason attention. But these
five will emerge as impact players this year:
</P>
<P>
   Cal forward Sean Lampley. A 6-foot-7 sophomore, Lampley is
athletic, physical, relentless and a future star. He's second in
the conference in rebounding (11.3 per game) and should prosper
under Bears coach Ben Braun, who specializes in developing big men.
</P>
<P>
   Stanford wing guard David Moseley. A 6-4 junior, Moseley is one
of Stanford's best athletes and will play major minutes to
compensate for injuries to Mike McDonald and Ryan Mendez.
</P>
<P>
   Oregon State guard Deaundra Tanner. A 6-2 sophomore from
Inglewood, Tanner is the best player on the league's worst team,
equally adept at scoring, rebounding or directing what little
attack the Beavers have.
</P>
<P>
   USC guard Jeff Trepagnier. A 6-4 sophomore, Trepagnier is a
sensational athlete who has improved his fundamentals and gives the
Trojans' backcourt some much-needed size.
</P>
<P>
   Washington forward Chris Walcott. A 6-7 junior, Walcott is quiet
but effective around the basket and capable of hitting mid-range
jumpers.
</P>
<P>
   Where have all the (reserve) point guards gone?
</P>
<P>
   It may have no impact on the league race or their NCAA
Tournament fate, but Arizona and Stanford are tinfoil-thin in the
backcourt.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Terry and Art Lee will be asked to play 35 to 40 minutes
because of a dearth of depth; injuries, fatigue or foul trouble
could mean instant doom. Lee's backup, Mike McDonald, is out at
least another month with a foot injury, and Terry simply has no
established help. Arizona's reserve point guard is walk-on John
Ash.
</P>
<P>
   On which games will the season turn?
</P>
<P>
   Whether they're on Fox, Fox Sports West, Fox Sports West 2 or FX
or F-whatever, here are four games that shouldn't be missed.
</P>
<P>
   1. Cal at Stanford (Jan. 9). Bears hand Stanford its only loss
in Maples Pavilion.
</P>
<P>
   2. UCLA at USC (Jan. 20). Watch the Trojans beat the Bruins for
the first time in five years.
</P>
<P>
   3. Stanford at Washington (Feb. 18). Ready for a repeat of
Stanford's thrilling win last year?
</P>
<P>
   4. UCLA at Arizona (March 6). A tournament bid could be on the
line in this season finale.
</P>
<P>
   Pac-10 order of finish: 1. Stanford, 2. California, 3.
Washington. 4. Arizona, 5. (tie) UCLA and USC, 7. Oregon, 8.
Arizona State, 9. Washington State, 10. Oregon State.
</P>
<P>
   Comment: Cal was the second-place pick in this space long before
its victory over North Carolina in the Newell Challenge. The Bears
are experienced, they have superb guard play and one of the
league's best coaches. Oregon and Arizona State are comparable to
the seventh- and eighth-place teams in the ACC or Big Ten.
</P>
<P>
   All-league team: Arizona guard Jason Terry and center A.J.
Bramlett, Arizona State forward Bobby Lazor, USC forward Brian
Scalabrine, UCLA guard Baron Davis, Stanford guard Art Lee and
forward Mark Madsen, Cal guard Geno Carlisle and forward Sean
Lampley, and Washington center Todd MacCulloch.
</P>
<P>
   Comment: Terry and Bramlett are the best one-two senior punch in
the conference and will guide an otherwise young team to a solid
season. But don't expect 25 wins from the Wildcats. Like UCLA,
they're reloading this year.
</P>
<P>
   Scalabrine should win the Fred Hessler Newcomer Award, while
Arizona's Michael Wright and UCLA's Jerome Moiso will contend for
Freshman of the Year honors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
