<SLUG> BC-BKW-PEPPERDINE-UCLA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA WOMEN ROUT PEPPERDINE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ANEL LAJ  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Even without All-American candidate Maylana
Martin, the UCLA women's basketball team bounced back with an 85-51
nonconference win over Pepperdine Wednesday night at Pauley
Pavilion.
</P>
<P>
   The question of the night was could the ninth-ranked Bruins
(8-4) win without Martin, who was sidelined with a sinus infection.
In Monday's 85-80 loss to No. 17 Duke, Martin was 1 of 10 from the
field, and the rest of the Bruins couldn't produce enough offense
to beat the Blue Devils. Wednesday, UCLA got the offense it needed
from LaCresha Flannigan and Melanie Pearson. Flannigan, 9 of 16
from the field, scored 18 points, and Pearson, who was 6 of 6 from
the line, had a game high 19.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the turning point was when we picked it up
defensively,'' said UCLA coach Kathy Olivier. ``We got some easy
baskets just from our defense. Our defense was creating points for
us.''
</P>
<P>
   Pepperdine (8-4) came out strong in the first half and led by as
many as seven before the Bruins took over. With five minutes
remaining in the first half, UCLA used a 13-3 run to take a 43-31
halftime lead.
</P>
<P>
   Rasheeda Clark scored 12 points, and Kate Crane added 11 and
nine rebounds to lead the Waves. Pepperdine held its ground in the
first half, outrebounding the Bruins 25-18. But UCLA became more
aggressive on the boards and outrebounded the Waves 51-45 for the
game.
</P>
<P>
   Another offensive bright spot for UCLA was junior center Janae
Hubbard, who had a double-double with 16 points and 10 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   The victory ended a two-game losing streak for UCLA, which opens
Pac-10 play Saturday at Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the Pac-10 is good from one to 10,'' said Olivier. ``I
think that if we try to again take the easy route or think that
it's going to be an easy game it's going to be another wake up
call, and we don't want to go through that again. ``I think
consistency will not be a problem because (we'll) all be ready to
play ... If our post gets into foul trouble that will be trouble
for us. That will be an ugly situation. We got to stay out of foul
trouble. If we have Maylana and Janae in the game, and they're
effective, we can do some damage against anyone.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
