<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW CAREER FOR NICHOLLS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ Once upon a time, Bernie Nicholls had 70
goals and 150 points in a season playing for the Los Angeles Kings.
</P>
<P>
   But that was a decade ago, and less than a year after that epic
season the Kings traded Nicholls, who thus began a nomadic
existence that would take him from team to team for the rest of his
career.
</P>
<P>
   That career ended for Nicholls, 37, earlier this season, when
the San Jose Sharks basically pushed him into retirement. Nicholls
was disappointed at first, mostly at how the Sharks dealt with the
matter, but Wednesday night, he was back in the Forum as a San Jose
assistant coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was more a disappointment than anything,'' Nicholls said of
the circumstances that led to his retirement. ``It should have been
handled a little differently. I felt more disappointed that my mom
and dad didn't get to watch my last game. I didn't get any notice
(that it would be his final game).''
</P>
<P>
   Nicholls, who finished his career with 475 goals, had 327 of
those during his 7{ years with the Kings, along with 431 assists.
He is the fifth-leading scorer in Kings history.
</P>
<P>
   ``I loved playing here,'' Nicholls said. ``Even after I was
traded from here (in 1990, for Tony Granato and Tomas Sandstrom),
it was always fun coming back here to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Fiset close: Kings goalie Stephane Fiset is close to returning
to the lineup from the latest of the three groin injuries he's
suffered this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fine right now,'' said Fiset, who has appeared in only 10
of the Kings' first 36 games. ``Every day, I'm doing a little more.
I just have to stretch it after practice and ice it. But I'm
feeling pretty good about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Fiset said his training regimen before this season was the same
as every other year, and he's puzzled by the repeated injuries he's
suffered since the fourth game of the season, against Colorado on
Oct. 18.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been really frustrating,'' Fiset said. ``One day, you
feel good. The next day, you wake up and you're sore and you don't
know why. Nobody knows what's going on. I guess I'll just have to
deal with it all year long.''
</P>
<P>
   Loose pucks: Defenseman Doug Bodger missed the game because of
the cervical strain and bruised shoulder he suffered Monday night
when checked from behind by Phoenix's Dallas Drake. Garry Galley
replaced Bodger in the lineup. Bodger's injuries are not believed
to be serious, though he may miss Saturday night's game at the
Forum against Colorado.... The Sharks were without leading scorer
Jeff Friesen, who is sidelined with a shoulder injury, and veteran
winger Murray Craven, who has a bruised nerve in his shin.... Rose
Bowl opponents Cade McNown of UCLA and Bob Adamov of Wisconsin
participated in a ceremonial faceoff before the game.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
