NYT-12-31-98 0218EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981231.0061 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-31 02:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3085 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-HUSKIES-NEXT-SPI &LR;      12-31 0743
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-HUSKIES-NEXT-SPI </SLUG>
  
 xxx  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BUD WITHERS  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Barbara Hedges is justifiably proud of her record
hiring coaches at Washington. She appointed Ken Knutson to head up
baseball, Teresa Wilson as the person to shepherd the Husky
softball team to the College World Series, and she was sage enough
to recognize that Bob Bender was the cream of men's basketball
candidates in the UW pool.
</P>
<P>
   Now the UW athletic director must make the most monumental hire
in her seven-year tenure here, that of a replacement for Jim
Lambright. Her choice as football coach will hold the key to one of
the nation's wealthiest athletic programs, one with a four-year
waiting list for season tickets.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a major decision with huge implications,'' Hedges
said. ``I'm already starting to get phone calls.''
</P>
<P>
   Helping Hedges in an advisory capacity will be Don James, the
College Football Hall of Fame coach who guided the Huskies from
1975-92.
</P>
<P>
   ``She asked if I would help her with a list,'' James said
Wednesday night. ``I'll know the coaches, or I'll know someone who
will. I'm not going to be on the selection committee, but I'll be
willing to help.''
</P>
<P>
   Hedges isn't ruling out any NCAA Division I coach, but it is
more likely she hires a head coach from a school at a conference
level comparable to Washington's. She will, however, be reminded
that James was little known when the UW hired him from Kent State
in 1975.
</P>
<P>
   That may lead her to:
</P>
<P>
   (bullet) Gary Barnett, Northwestern. A facile figure among
boosters and media, he did the impossible and took the Wildcats to
the Rose Bowl in 1995, but has since fallen on harder times, and
the school's point-shaving scandal may dull his luster.
</P>
<P>
   Barnett has irked many Northwestern faithful for his frequent
dalliance with some top jobs _ he wanted the Notre Dame and Texas
positions in recent years _ so this might have to be done in
secretive fashion. He is popularly believed to covet the Colorado
job (he was an assistant there) whenever Rick Neuheisel leaves, but
Washington might appeal.
</P>
<P>
   (bullet) Barry Alvarez, Wisconsin. The former Notre Dame and
Iowa assistant has done his own miracle work, getting the Badgers
to the Rose Bowl twice in five years. Which could lead him to
conclude that everything he could do here, he can do there. Alvarez
is already being mentioned for NFL vacancies and his interest here
might be a longshot.
</P>
<P>
   (bullet) Gary Pinkel, Toledo. Hedges is almost certain to talk
to Pinkel, who has long considered Washington his dream job. He is
57-31-3 in eight years in the Mid-American Conference after leaving
his Husky job as offensive coordinator before the national
championship season of 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Pinkel, 46, played for James at Kent State and James'
recommendation would likely carry weight around Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really like Gary,'' James said. ``I watched him grow, all
the way from when he was a player to being a coach. He's just a
solid guy, a hard worker with a lot of character.''
</P>
<P>
   (bullet) Chris Tormey, Idaho. It's unlikely the Huskies would
dip as low as the Big West Conference, but the Vandals were
mentioned among the worst teams in Division I-A in August, and
Wednesday they shocked 16-point favorite Southern Mississippi in
the Humanitarian Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Tormey, 43, a Spokane native and Idaho grad, spent 11 years on
UW staffs spanning the James and Lambright regimes and was highly
respected.
</P>
<P>
   Another name making rounds is Virginia Tech's Frank Beamer. But
Beamer, a Tech alum, has a resume grounded in the South and
wouldn't appear to be the sort of fit Hedges wants.
</P>
<P>
   Others available include deposed Seahawks coach Dennis Erickson
and former Auburn coach Terry Bowden. But the pall over the '98
Seahawks likely would be among factors discouraging Hedges on
Erickson, while Bowden, like Beamer, would have to overcome
strictly Southern connections.
</P>
<P>
   Hedges, who expects to have a short list quickly, said she
wouldn't be opposed to pursuing a good candidate from the Pac-10
although she called that ``difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   Hedges said she would rely on an unnamed group of advisors to
assist in interviewing candidates, but that the decision will be
hers. She wouldn't specify when it will happen.
</P>
<P>
   Lambright earned a package of $566,000 including outside income,
and Hedges said, ``I would say the parameters would be similar.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
