<HEADLINE>
CSUN WOMEN HOLD OFF NORTHERN ARIZONA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEE BARNATHAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Lynda Amari let out a shriek of delight.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't because her Cal State Northridge women's basketball
team opened the Big Sky Conference with a 66-63 home victory over
defending co-champion Northern Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Nor was it because the Matadors (7-4) beat the Lumberjacks (6-5)
for the first time in the last 10 meetings. And while her game-high
24 points were nice, that wasn't the reason, either.
</P>
<P>
   No, her scream was because she opened up a tiny box and saw her
1997 State Junior College championship ring from her Ventura
College days. Several players and her coach made the presentation
after the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It does fit!'' she exclaimed. ``A $400 ring! That's gold and
diamonds in there.''
</P>
<P>
   Her Northridge coach, Frozena Jerro, responded, ``Dang, girl!
You'd better lock it up.''
</P>
<P>
   Northridge would be wise to lock up this victory because it
overcame its mistakes and made free throws in the final minutes.
With the next three conference games on the road in a six-day span,
the Matadors will need poise to come out in the title hunt.
</P>
<P>
   Amari had much to do with that. Edniesha Curry didn't start,
having been disciplined by Jerro. (Jerro called it ``minor''; Curry
didn't attend the postgame conference.) So Amari filled in and
scored nine points in about nine minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone had to take responsibility,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Then in the second half, after NAU had cut a 16-point deficit to
tie the score at 61 with 1:20 to play, Amari hit two free throws 10
seconds later to put the Matadors ahead for good.
</P>
<P>
   She also took seven rebounds and brought many in the announced
crowd of 374 to their feet with a loud block midway through the
second half.
</P>
<P>
   ``She displayed her versatility,'' Jerro said. ``We sent a
message to the Big Sky. We matured a lot today.''
</P>
<P>
   Curry, the only other Matador in double figures, finished with
12 points.
</P>
<P>
   NAU got 20 points off the bench from guard RaeAnn West, and
forward Jess LeBlanc became her school's career-leading scorer with
a field goal late in the first half. She finished with 10 points.
</P>
</TEXT>
