<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-SHARKS-WRITETHRU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS BEAT SHARKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(OPTIONAL: Adds quotes, details) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ When the Los Angeles Kings defeated the
Coyotes in Phoenix on Monday night, it was valid to wonder just how
significant the victory had been.
</P>
<P>
   Would the Kings respond in their next game with another solid
effort and another triumph?
</P>
<P>
   Or would the Phoenix victory merely be a positive blip in a
season of negatives?
</P>
<P>
   With a 5-1 victory over the San Jose Sharks before an announced
crowd of 10,918 at the Forum on Wednesday night, the Kings provided
an affirmative answer to the first question, and avoided having one
night's blip become another night's bleep.
</P>
<P>
   And just like that, the Kings (12-21-3) amazingly are just three
points behind Vancouver, which holds the final Western Conference
playoff berth.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel lucky,'' said center Ian Laperriere, who had two
assists, as did Rob Blake and Donald Audette. ``We're not the only
team that's been struggling. The only thing we can do about it is
keep winning.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kings got goals from Matt Johnson (yes, Matt Johnson), Ray
Ferraro, Yanic Perreault (on a power play), Glen Murray
(shorthanded) and Olli Jokinen. Murray's goal capped an evening of
outstanding penalty killing, and Jamie Storr made 31 saves as the
Kings won for the fourth time in their last five games, and for
only the fifth time this season at the Forum.
</P>
<P>
   After going more than two months without beating a Pacific
Division opponent, the Kings won a game within the division for the
second time in three nights.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Stern scored the only goal for the Sharks (10-16-8), as the
Kings held an opponent to two goals or fewer for the fifth
consecutive game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't generate too much offense,'' San Jose's Joe Murphy
said. ``We outshot them, but most of our shots were from the
perimeter. No one was going to the net. It was just a bad hockey
game by our club.''
</P>
<P>
   It took only 2:28 for the Kings to get on the scoreboard, with
Johnson scoring his second goal this season, matching his career
high. The 6-foot-5 Johnson parked himself in front of San Jose
goalie Mike Vernon, warded off the efforts of 6-2 Sharks defenseman
Bob Rouse, and redirected a cross-ice pass from Laperriere to give
the Kings the lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't miss him,'' Laperriere said. ``If you miss him,
you're blind. If our line can bring goals, it's just going to help
the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Johnson, who has six goals in 151 NHL games, ``I might have
had a bit of a step on Rouse. Lappy made a nice play and it went
in.''
</P>
<P>
   Before another three minutes elapsed, however, Sean O'Donnell
and Laperriere took penalties 28 seconds apart, leaving the Kings
two men short for 1:32. But aside from a Murphy shot that hit the
post, the Sharks did not threaten, and late in the period, Ferraro
padded the Kings' lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a big turning point in the game,'' Kings coach Larry
Robinson said of the penalty killing. ``It took the wind out of
their sails and gave us a lift.''
</P>
<P>
   Stern drew the Sharks to within a goal 7:43 into the second
period, but six minutes later, Perreault's power-play goal
re-established the two-goal margin.
</P>
<P>
   Murray sealed the victory midway through the third period with
his 15th goal, slipping the puck between Vernon's pads on a
breakaway for the 10th shorthanded goal by the Kings this season,
tying them for the NHL lead with Vancouver.
</P>
<P>
   Jokinen added his fifth goal three minutes later, his first
point in more than a month.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important,'' Robinson said of the victory. ``If you look
at our record at home, we've got to get a better record. It's
pretty sad when you've got a better record on the road than at
home.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just happy to get goals. We were playing pretty well
defensively. We just weren't generating anything offensively.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
