<HEADER>
A3097 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMMIGRATION-MITCH-SFC     12-31 0921
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMMIGRATION-MITCH-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 ILLEGAL IMMIGRANTS FROM NATIONS HIT BY MITCH GET BREAK  &HT;     By LOUIS FREEDBERG and APRIL LYNCH  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As part of a plan to provide relief to countries
ravaged by Hurricane Mitch, the Clinton administration said
Wednesday that it will allow as many as 150,000 illegal immigrants
from Honduras and Nicaragua to stay in the United States for the
next 18 months without fear of deportation.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we are doing is creating some breathing room for people
who are already in the United States the opportunity to remain so
that the rebuilding can take place in their countries,'' said
Immigration and Naturalization Commissioner Doris Meissner.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement came after weeks of intensive debate within the
administration about how best to respond to the disaster. The White
House had been under pressure to also provide relief to illegal
immigrants from Guatemala and El Salvador. But it decided only to
cover immigrants from the countries most directly affected by the
hurricane that displaced 3 million people and caused billions of
dollars in damage.
</P>
<P>
   Under the plan, Honduran and Nicaraguan immigrants who entered
the United States before Wednesday will be granted ``temporary
protective status'' until June 30, 2000. After that, they
technically would be subject to deportation, but Meissner said she
``would not want to speculate on what will happen at the end of 18
months.''
</P>
<P>
   The plan was welcomed by Nicaraguans and Hondurans, who must pay
a $175 fee for the new visas. An estimated 32,500 live in
California.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a real relief,'' said Antonio Herrera, 36, a Nicaraguan
living in South San Francisco. ``From here, I can keep working and
sending money home. Right now, they really need outside help more
than ever, and the people like me who are here can really do
that.''
</P>
<P>
   But the plan drew criticism from immigration experts and
advocates on all sides of the immigration debate. Some advocates
said the plan does not go far enough, because it does not grant
relief to the nearly 400,000 illegal immigrants from El Salvador
and Guatemala.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this is all the administration does, it will not be
sufficient,'' said Frank Sharry, executive director of the National
Immigration Forum in Washington, D.C. He said that 70percent of El
Salvador's rural economy had been destroyed, and that the
administration failed to come up with a plan that responded to a
crisis that will affect the entire region.
</P>
<P>
   Meissner said that almost all of those displaced by the
hurricane came from Honduras and Nicaragua. She also noted that
Guatemalans and Salvadorans who are currently in INS custody facing
deportation would not be deported for the next two months.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although there's been damage in El Salvador and Guatemala, the
vast majority of people have been able to return to their homes,''
she said. ``So there is a different situation on the ground, and
this immigration action is tailored to that.''
</P>
<P>
   But Demetrios Papademetriou, director of international migration
programs at the Carnegie Endowment for International Peace, said
the plan was the ``absolute minimum the administration could have
done.'' He predicted that the hurricane's devastation will trigger
large migrations of people throughout the region.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, some who favor more restrictive immigration
policies criticized the decision as essentially opening the door to
more illegal immigrants. Mark Krikorian, executive director of the
Center for Immigration Studies in Washington, D.C., said that after
the 18-month moratorium expires, there will be pressure to extend
the visas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Advocates are going to ask for an extension for another six
months, for another 12 months,'' said Krikorian. `'By the time
things get back to normal, these people will have put down roots,
and it is politically improbable that they will ever be deported.''
</P>
<P>
   But Robert Rubin, deputy director of the Lawyers Committee for
Civil Rights in San Francisco, said that the INS was using the
immigration law precisely as intended _ ``to provide important
protection at a time of danger, whether from political upheavals
and natural disasters.''
</P>
<P>
   The United States has granted temporary protective status to a
range of people, such as Bosnians and Sudanese who have been
victims of political upheavals. But this is only the second time
that it has offered these protections following a natural disaster.
The first was in 1996, after a series of volcanic eruptions almost
destroyed the Caribbean island of Montserrat.
</P>
<P>
   The most immediate effect of the plan will be to allow
immigrants to work legally in the United States. That presumably
will allow them to get better jobs and to continue to send money to
family members in their home countries.
</P>
<P>
   The immigration relief announced Wednesday is part of a plan to
prevent economic turmoil in the region, &LR;  and to avert a possible
surge of immigration to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has provided $75 million in emergency military
assistance. About 5,000 U.S. soldiers are in the region helping to
rebuild the most hard hit areas. In addition, several U.S. agencies
sent over $40 million in food aid. The U.S. Department of Housing
and Urban Development is helping to rebuild homes and the Treasury
Department has extended $50 million in debt relief.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must ensure that the relief efforts are aggressive and
comprehensive until the rebuilding is completed,'' Meissner said.  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
