r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KAELIN-LIBEL-SFCHRON &LR;      12-31 0465
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KAELIN-LIBEL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
O.J. SIMPSON PAL WINS IN U.S. COURT 
</HEADLINE>
   By BILL WALLACE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
    SAN FRANCISCO _ Brian ``Kato'' Kaelin, the O.J. Simpson
associate who won brief celebrity during the former football star's
murder trial, can sue a supermarket tabloid newspaper for
suggesting that he was a suspect in the case, a federal appellate
court in San Francisco ruled Wednesday.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Shortly after Simpson was acquitted of charges that he murdered
his wife, Nicole Brown Simpson, and her friend Ronald Goldman,
Kaelin was the subject of a story in the National Examiner
newspaper that was headlined: ``Kato Kaelin . . . Cops Think He Did
It!''
</P>
<P>
   Kaelin sued Globe Communications, the paper's publisher, but his
suit was dismissed by a U.S. district judge in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   In Wednesday's opinion, a three-judge appellate panel consisting
of Judges Barry Silverman, Dorothy Nelson and Betty Fletcher
overturned the district court ruling, saying it was simply wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hold today that a reasonable juror could find, by clear and
convincing evidence, that the headlines are defamatory, and that
(the Examiner's) editors acted with actual malice in their decision
to run a headline from which a reasonable juror could conclude that
Kaelin was a murder suspect,'' Silverman wrote on behalf of his
colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   The case will be sent back to the U.S. District Court in Los
Angeles for trial.
</P>
<P>
   Kaelin is a would-be actor who won brief notoriety as the
``houseguest'' who was staying with Simpson on the night that
Simpson's wife and Goldman were slain.
</P>
<P>
   The story published in the National Examiner one week after
Simpson was acquitted of murdering his wife and Goldman did not
support the headline. In fact, the story, which ran 17 pages inside
the tabloid, said that Kaelin was suspected of perjuring himself _
not committing the two murders.
</P>
<P>
   Kaelin demanded a retraction, but Globe refused. But when Kaelin
sued for libel in U.S. District Court in Los Angeles, his suit was
dismissed by Judge Dickran Tevrizian.
</P>
<P>
   Tevrizian said he threw out the action because Kaelin had not
proved the National Examiner's defamatory headline had been
published with actual malice. Malice is a crucial element in libel
cases, because slurs against public figures are legally actionable
only if they are published without regard for their accuracy.
</P>
<P>
   However, in its decision Wednesday, the appellate court panel
said that even the tabloid's editors said they did not believe the
headline was accurate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is undisputed that Globe (Communications) never believed
Kaelin to be a suspect in the murders. The fact that Globe ran the
headlines anyway ... is circumstantial evidence of actual malice,''
said Wednesday's Court of Appeals ruling.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
