A3180 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BASS-IMPEACHMENT01-CO     12-31 0855
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BASS-IMPEACHMENT01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Supreme Court should decide Senate's impeachment
jurisdiction
 &HT;    By Jack Bass
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Senate must insure the integrity of the process as it
confronts the articles of impeachment against President Clinton.
The first question the Senate should address is whether it has
jurisdiction to proceed.
</P>
<P>
   If the lame-duck House of Representatives had passed any other
legislation after the election, it would be dead. Is its authority
for impeaching the president different?
</P>
<P>
   The 20th Amendment to the Constitution, ratified in 1933,
shortened the time between congressional elections and members
taking office and was aimed at preventing a lame-duck Congress from
overturning the will of the people in the previous election. The
1998 election surprised pundits with its gain by congressional
Democrats. This outcome reflected national polls showing most
Americans don't want President Clinton removed from office.
</P>
<P>
   The same Republicans arguing against a Senate ``rush to
judgment'' by substituting censure for an impeachment trial made
their own rush by voting for articles of impeachment before their
numbers decreased when the 106th Congress takes office on Jan. 4.
Because impeachment is a political process, the House Republican
leadership had a right to make this political decision.
</P>
<P>
   But it is a question of unresolved law, not politics, whether
under the 20th Amendment the Senate in the 106th Congress has
jurisdiction to act on articles of impeachment passed by the House
in the 105th Congress. Although the Senate received the articles of
impeachment through its clerk, the senators took no action.
</P>
<P>
   This is a situation without precedent.
</P>
<P>
   This unique constitutional question is so grave _ a matter of
removing the president _ that the Senate and the American people
deserve an answer from the most authoritative source. That clearly
is the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   In an impeachment trial, the Senate acts not in a legislative
capacity, but a judicial one. It serves as judge and jury. As a
court of limited jurisdiction, the Senate lacks authority to try
the impeachment case if its action violates the 20th amendment,
even if both sides agree to a trial.
</P>
<P>
   Based on established principle, the Supreme Court does not issue
advisory opinions. But the genius of the law is its adaptability.
</P>
<P>
   A rarely-used procedure of the federal courts offers a means of
resolving the legal question of jurisdiction definitively. In its
judicial capacity, the Senate could certify the matter to the
Supreme Court as a question of law.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the Fifth Circuit Court of Appeals in 1963
certified as a question of law to the Supreme Court whether
Mississippi Gov. Ross Barnett was entitled to a jury trial for
criminal contempt because of attempting to thwart James Meredith
from breaking the racial barrier at the University of Mississippi
by enrolling under a Fifth Circuit court order. The judges on the
court of appeals had divided 4-4 on the question.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Judge John R. Brown of the Fifth Circuit said this case
``must be looked upon as one of the great constitutional crises of
the United States.'' The current situation arguably amounts to a
greater crisis.
</P>
<P>
   There's nothing to prevent the Senate, acting in its judicial
role, from certifying this question of law to the Supreme Court.
The Senate could ask both sides_the House managers and the
president's lawyers_to argue the case in written briefs. The
Supreme Court has the authority to accept or reject the case.
Although President Clinton as defendant has the authority to raise
the issue and get it to the Supreme Court, it would be easy for the
justices to say no_that it's the Senate's decision.
</P>
<P>
   As a legal and constitutional issue of overriding importance,
the Senate and the American people deserve to know from the highest
authority that the procedure to be followed meets the requirements
of the Constitution. That means a decision by the full Supreme
Court. The Senate and the nation might be served well by the
resultant delay providing a cooling-off period.
</P>
<P>
   If the Supreme Court approves Senate jurisdiction for a trial,
it can then proceed with unquestioned legitimacy. If not, the new
House of Representatives can decide whether to seek new articles of
impeachment, in the same manner as with any legislation that dies
at the end of a previous Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Those who argue against a rush to judgment are correct. Before
commencing a trial, the Senate owes it to itself and the American
people to move with dispatch to get an authoritative answer to this
unprecedented constitutional question of jurisdiction. As the final
arbiter of the constitution, the Supreme Court should accept its
responsibility to provide it.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Bass is author of two books about federal judges and civil
rights, ``Unlikely Heroes'' and ``Taming the Storm.'' His most
recent book is ``Ol' Strom: An Unauthorized Biography of Strom
Thurmond,'' co-authored with Marilyn Thompson.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
