<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-31 09:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3181 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BORDERS-COLUMN01-COX     12-31 0846
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BORDERS-COLUMN01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The newspaper loses one of its true strengths
 &HT;    By Gary Borders
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NACOGDOCHES, Texas _ One of the smartest, toughest women I've
ever met died last week. Lucille Fain passed away 12 days after
having a stroke while writing obituaries for The Daily Sentinel,
where she had worked for 62 years. As Ab Abernethy put it at her
memorial service, her friends know that's the way she would have
chosen to leave this earth _ quickly and without a lot of fuss and
bother.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not sure I can do justice to writing about Ms. Fain, not the
way Ab and Joyce Swearingen _ both of whom knew her much longer
than I _ did with their eulogies last week at the memorial service.
But I feel bound to try.
</P>
<P>
   All told, I worked with Ms. Fain (I never had the nerve to call
her Lucille to her face, even after I became her boss) for 11
years. For the last five years, her desk was the closest to my
office. About once a year, she'd come in and ask me if I still
wanted her to work at the paper. My answer was always the same: You
can work here until you don't want to anymore or until you die. I
always figured it would be the latter.
</P>
<P>
   You could set a clock by her routine. She was here by 7:45 a.m.,
would pick up the metro papers lying outside on the sidewalk and
knock on the door if it hadn't been unlocked yet. I tried to give
her a key to the front door or the combination to the side door,
but she didn't want either. She would come inside and make a fresh
pot of coffee, fill a cup with shredded wheat, grab the front
section of The Dallas Morning News and sit at her desk and read
every story. Often, I'd pick up the same section later in the day
and find holes where she'd cut out an editorial or story that
piqued her interest.
</P>
<P>
   Then she would work on her weekly history column, juggling her
work between a steady flow of visitors. After more than six decades
at the paper, she had built up a large contingent of fellow history
buffs who would arrive to discuss all manner of things. Often,
folks she'd never met would wander in, perhaps chasing a
genealogical connection and hoping she'd be able to help out. She
was always gracious and patient, though if under deadline she would
politely shoo them off and do the important stuff _ helping get out
the paper.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Fain was an inveterate letter writer, firing off missives to
politicians with whom she had found fault. She had to use my
printer, and often I would find her letters while looking for
something I had printed. I would read with amusement as she took
senators, presidents and congressmen to task with short,
to-the-point letters.
</P>
<P>
   Eight years ago, at age 76, she seamlessly adapted from using an
IBM Selectric to writing on a Macintosh computer. She viewed the
computer as a necessary evil, and I could hear her muttering
deprecations at it when it wouldn't act right. She hammered the
computer mouse like she was launching a nuclear attack. But she
learned the essentials _ the spell checker and the word count _ so
that she could warn the layout folks that we had 1,200 words of
obituaries, which would take up most of Page 2 the next day.
</P>
<P>
   Some days she would come in my office and announce that nobody
had died, and thus there were no obits. It was a standing joke
between us. I would look at her sternly and say, ``Well, Ms. Fain,
we're just going to have to do better than that. People will start
calling to accuse us of having discontinued running obits.'' She'd
laugh knowingly, since it's true that someone invariably calls when
we don't have any obits.
</P>
<P>
   She would leave by late morning and return in late afternoon,
usually after picking up her granddaughter at school. Then she
would write the obituaries for the next day's paper, calling the
funeral homes when she caught a name or town spelled wrong. Ms.
Fain very rarely got anything wrong in an obituary.
</P>
<P>
   Every Friday afternoon, she made the rounds of the building,
watering the plants, some of which have been in this building 20
years. I don't have a clue how they'll survive without her.
</P>
<P>
   The only argument I had with her was two years ago when I wanted
to do a story marking her 60th year at the newspaper. She would
have none of it. Nope, no way, she said. Find something else to
write about. I'm not interested in talking about myself, she told
me in no uncertain terms. She won the argument.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Fain is gone, but I can still smell her old-lady perfume, as
I called it, a thick floral scent wafting around her desk. Though
we all knew not long after she slumped forward in her chair that
she wouldn't be coming back, it still doesn't seem quite real. I'm
betting she's watching us now, worrying if we're getting the names
spelled right.
</P>
<P>
   All I can promise is we'll do the best we can without her.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Borders is editor and publisher of The Daily Sentinel in
Nacogdoches
</P>
<P>
   and editor of The Lufkin Daily News. His e-mail address is
gborders(at)conews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
