<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Air Force frees cash to build F-22 jets
 &HT;    By Stephen Pounds
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ The U.S. Air Force has released money to
begin building production versions of the F-22 Raptor stealth
fighter, including $94 million to Pratt &AMP; Whitney to build the
engines.
</P>
<P>
   Even as the Pentagon was giving the go-ahead to begin production
of the advanced aircraft, it was authorizing a study of
alternatives to the costliest Air Force fighter in history at $171
million a plane the fighter, which at $171 million is the costliest
in history. Air Force spokeswoman Gloria Cales said the study is
normal in weapons programs.
</P>
<P>
   The money approved this week by Secretary of Defense Defense
Secretary William Cohen will pay for Pratt's production of six F119
engines, four of them for two fighters to be built by Lockheed
Martin and two spares, according to the Air Force. The work is to
be completed by mid-2001.
</P>
<P>
   The engines will be made at Pratt's operations in Connecticut
but the F119 engine is under development and the program is managed
at Pratt's plant in northwestern Palm Beach County. More than 1,000
people work on the F119 engine here.
</P>
<P>
   With less fewer defense dollars being spent on new weapons
systems in the 1990s, the F-22 is one of only a handful of
multimillion-dollar projects being bought by the Pentagon. It also
is the bridge between the F-15 and F-16 programs, which have all
but ended except for overseas sales, and the Joint Strike Fighter,
an all-purpose jet for the military meant to supplement the F-22 in
the latter half of the next decade.
</P>
<P>
   The F-22 contracts had been delayed since October because
Congress required two prototype aircraft to complete 183 hours of
test flights before the money could be released. The hours were
completed in November, although test flights continue, Cales said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both of the aircraft in the test program are at Edwards (Air
Base in California). One is down for maintenance but the other is
still flying. The last time I heard, test flying is at 199 hours,''
Cales said.
</P>
<P>
   The Defense Department is expected to release another $189
million within days, Cales said. It will be used for partial
production of six more F-22 Raptors.
</P>
<P>
   Pratt's was the smaller of two F-22 contracts approved by Cohen.
Lockheed Martin received $503 million to build the Raptors, which
are being designed to be undetectable by enemy radar. Boeing is
also a major subcontractor.
</P>
<P>
   The Air Force plans to buy 339 F-22s at $62 billion. They are
expected to begin service in 2005. Pratt will make 678 engines plus
spares.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
