<HEADER>
A3184 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PARTY-ETIQUETTE01-COX     12-31 1915
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PARTY-ETIQUETTE01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    How to out-snob the snobby at any soiree
 &HT;    By Loretta Grantham
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ If you really want to outsnob the snobs
at your next soiree, check your pretense at the door (along with
your borrowed mink stole), and don't act like a snob at all.
</P>
<P>
   Old money, you see, doesn't need attitude. So to get folks
murmuring about whether your great-grandpa was an oil magnate,
steel baron or railroad tycoon, flaunt nonchalance _ graciously, of
course.
</P>
<P>
   ``The nicest, most unaffected people are almost always the ones
with the most money,'' says a maitre d' who's worked in Palm Beach
nearly 20 years. ``They don't make a scene for a certain table
because they expect it. And if it's unavailable, they don't throw a
tantrum. People who've grown up wealthy _ not the types who just
made a million on Microsoft _ have a certain quiet assurance
regardless of what goes on around them.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who have some money but want to appear like they have
more, they're the ones who'll storm out in a huff because of a
smudged glass.''
</P>
<P>
   Another observer of the rich and famous says you can spot
wannabes because they try too hard.
</P>
<P>
   ``They wear every piece of jewelry they own and will chose a
restaurant because it's listed in la-ti-da magazine,'' said Elaine
Oksner, retired head concierge at The Breakers. ``Then, they'll
come back from dinner and tell you what they had wasn't as good as
such-and-such a place in New York or L.A. They want you to know
they know what's `in.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Sure, these snobs may actually have bucks galore. But what they
lack is breeding, and that blows their cover.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can see them coming, loud and overbearing,'' she says.
``They're the ones with the same designer knit suit everybody's
wearing or the navy blue blazer and ascot they've seen on Robin
Leach.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the people with the most money are confident enough to
wear a creative, one-of-a-kind outfit they've picked up at a
high-end craft show. And they'd rather go to a restaurant with
interesting, offbeat cuisine or decor _ not one from a play-it-rich
guide.''
</P>
<P>
   So to appear cosmopolitan at a party, you needn't gush about how
fabulous the fois gras is at some horrifically pricey French cafe
you can't pronounce. Consider commenting on the fanciful Indian
``best kept secret'' you recently discovered (without saying it's
the only place you can swing because of the chicken curry
two-for-one).
</P>
<P>
   Editing yourself, in fact, is a clever strategy for outsnobbing
snobs. This makes you appear a tad more mysterious and limits your
chances for chagrin.
</P>
<P>
   ``People with money, especially money that's been around a
while, don't feel a need to impress, so you won't hear them go on
and on about clothes or homes or cars,'' says a Wellington
socialite. ``Sure, these things might come up in conversation, but
never in a forced, here's-what-I-have sort of way. That would be
obvious _ and rude.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps more than anything, rude (and arrogant) behavior is a
dead giveaway that you're of clock-punch mentality.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, say some confused soul mistakenly uses his salad
fork for the entree. Rather than raise an eyebrow or chuckle behind
his back with your table companions, consider using your salad fork
to make him feel comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   Critics say this reinforces the blunder, while others contend it
saves face _ even if it's not yours.
</P>
<P>
   ``New money is concerned about appearing at ease,'' explains the
veteran maitre d', ``while old money is concerned about making
others feel at ease.''
</P>
<P>
   Folks on the Forbes list, insiders say, also aren't afraid of
frugality.
</P>
<P>
   ``It goes without saying that the people with the most money are
the ones least likely to part with it,'' Oksner says. ``They're the
ones who're comfortable requesting a moderately priced wine.''
</P>
<P>
   And the ones who don't tip a king's ransom when their cars are
brought around, says a Palm Beach valet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't misunderstand, we're more than glad to take the money,''
he says. ``But we always laugh at the guy who hands over a 50 like
it's some big deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if you can hold your own among deep-pocket types by being
understated and gracious, a time may come when you can't pronounce
a menu item or are baffled by which bread plate is yours.
</P>
<P>
   Panic not. ``It's perfectly acceptable to point to something on
the menu and say to the waiter, `This sounds delicious, I think
I'll try it,' '' Oksner says.
</P>
<P>
   And, according to the Wellington socialite, if you make a faux
pas, 'fess up.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're unsure, the rule of thumb is to sit back and watch
what others do,'' she says. ``But if you do screw up, smile and
make light of it. A definite sign that you're out of your league is
acting like it's the end of the world. Take a deep breath, and have
another drink.''
</P>
<P>
   Just don't ask for Tom Perignon.
</P>
<P>
   DON'T WHINE ABOUT WINE: HOW TO ORDER CONFIDENTLY
</P>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Does the thought of being in the wine
spotlight give you the cold sweats? Follow along. You won't be an
oenophile (wine connoisseur), but you won't be an ``oh, no!-phile''
either.
</P>
<P>
   Nightmare situation No 1: You're asked to choose the wine. And
you're a Pabst Blue Ribbon kind of guy.
</P>
<P>
   Don't feel compelled to pick the most expensive bottle of any
category. Go with middle-priced wines, and stick to these solid
choices if you're in doubt:
</P>
<P>
   _ Merlot (mare-LOW): a red wine, it is a favorite among
sophisticates. Heavy enough for red meat, light enough for poultry.
</P>
<P>
   _ Sauvignon Blanc (saw-veen-YAWN blonk): Dry, light white wine
with herbaceous, ``grassy'' taste, good with fish.
</P>
<P>
   _ Cabernet Sauvignon: (CAB-ber-nay saw-veen-Yawn) A full-bodied
California red wine that goes well with red meat.
</P>
<P>
   Nightmare situation No. 2: You're toast! Everyone wants you to
lift your glass and say something about some jolly good fellow.
</P>
<P>
   _ Keep it short, sweet and sincere. Don't try to be funny. Raise
your glass and speak confidently.
</P>
<P>
   _ Remember the name of the person you're toasting and say it.
</P>
<P>
   _ Don't bang your glass against your tablemate's. Tap gently.
</P>
<P>
   _ If you don't drink wine, toast with the beverage you're
drinking.
</P>
<P>
   Nightmare situation No. 3: The sommelier (pronounced
soh-MAHL-yea, meaning wine steward) is coming at you. Do you sniff
the cork, squeeze the cork or bite it?
</P>
<P>
   He'll show you the label _ it should be the same wine you
ordered. Nod. He'll then uncork it and place the cork for you to
see. That's all you do: look at it. If it's wet, as it should be,
nod again. Do not sniff it; that will mark you as dolt. He'll pour
a small sampling and stand there, waiting for you to taste. Don't
ask him to ``fill 'er up!'' Hold the glass by the stem up to the
light _ you're looking at its color _ swirl slightly, sniff deeply,
then taste it, trying to suck in some air at the same time (but do
not slurp). Swallow. Tell him it's fine _ 99 percent of the time,
it is. Nod again, and he'll now pour for the table.
</P>
<P>
   If you're not a wine drinker, make eye contact with the
sommelier and shake your head, or quietly say ``no thanks.'' Don't
turn your glass upside down.
</P>
<P>
   _ Jan Norris
</P>
<P>
   TABLE TALK: AWKWARD MOMENTS BE GONE!
</P>
<P>
   The man next to you starts talking about how disappointed he is
with the effect of U.S. tritium production on Russian ratification
of START II. You: ``Don't get me started! I'll go on forever.''
</P>
<P>
   The conversation turns to an intellectual analysis of the
never-more-relevant political insights in James Joyce's Ulysses.
</P>
<P>
   You: ``Oh, if only I had time to read!''
</P>
<P>
   You're not sure whether you have already met the person you are
being introduced to.
</P>
<P>
   You: ``Nice to see you!'' (``Nice to meet you'' implies you
never met, and, busy soul that you are, you just might know them,
yes?)
</P>
<P>
   Someone points to your dress and asks, ``Is that a Versace or a
Valentino?'' (But you can't possibly tell them it's a Target _
tar-JEH.) You: (winking as if you're sharing a secret) ``You know
who it is ...''
</P>
<P>
   _ Shannon Colavecchio
</P>
<P>
   SAY IT WITH APLOMB (A-PLUM)
</P>
<P>
   Bouillabaisse: BOO-ya-bess (not boo-EEL-a-base-ee) _ French
seafood stew
</P>
<P>
   Chianti: key-AHN-tee _ a fruity Italian red wine
</P>
<P>
   Creme brulee: krem broo-LAY _ baked custard with burnt-sugar top
</P>
<P>
   Bruschetta: bru-SKET-ta _ tomato pieces on grilled bread
</P>
<P>
   Prix fixe: pree-fix or pre-feeks _ fixed-price menu
</P>
<P>
   Picadillo: pick-a-DEE-yoh _ ground meat and spices
</P>
<P>
   Arugula: ah-ROO-guh-lah _ a lettuce
</P>
<P>
   Paella: pie-EY-ya _ a Spanish seafood-rice combo
</P>
<P>
   Celeriac: (seh-LER-ay-ak) _ root vegetable
</P>
<P>
   Jicama: (HEEK-eh-ma) _ another root vegetable
</P>
<P>
   And you can always point to the menu item and say to the waiter
with an arched brow: ``Oooh, this looks intriguing!'' Then let him
do the explaining (and pronouncing). Or say, ``Could you please
describe this item to me?''
</P>
<P>
   THE PLACE SETTING (OR NEVER EAT SOMEONE ELSE'S ROLL AGAIN)
</P>
<P>
   _ Solids on the left, liquids on the right
</P>
<P>
   _ Don't put your purse or cellphone or anything inedible on the
table. A small purse goes on your lap, under your napkin. A larger
one can go on the floor under your chair.
</P>
<P>
   _ Between bites, place the knife in the upper right-hand corner
of the plate, never on the tablecloth.
</P>
<P>
   _ Put butter pat on your bread plate; don't butter your roll
directly from the butter dish.
</P>
<P>
   _ Break bread or rolls with your hands before putting on your
plate, and butter only the piece you plan to eat next.
</P>
<P>
   _ No cutting up food all at once; cut only what you'll eat in
the next bite.
</P>
<P>
   _ When done, lay the fork and knife as if they were clock hands
reading 10:20. Do not push the plate away from you. And don't toss
your napkin on your plate when finished _ it goes to the right of
the plate, folded.
</P>
<P>
   TIPS ON TIPPING
</P>
<P>
   A generous tip is now considered from 18 percent to 20 percent
of the total bill before tax. Do not tip the captain or busboys
because the waiter will split the tip with them. Tip the maitre d'
$5 to $10 once in awhile if you are a regular patron, but do it
subtly. Tip the wine steward 10 percent of the bottle price,
especially if he has helped you choose it. Also do this subtly.
</P>
<P>
   Tip the hotel doorman who gets you a taxi about $1 to $3,
depending on whether he stood out in the rain for you. When he
brings your car to the door for you, tip him $1 to $2. Avoid
overtipping just to show off.
</P>
<P>
   DO'S AND DON'TS
</P>
<P>
   Wear a Hard Rock Cafe or Planet Hollywood T-shirt only if you
own a piece of the restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   When in doubt, wear black. Cheap fabrics look pricier, fat folks
look skinnier.
</P>
<P>
   Never, never pull a mirror out at the table or tug at your
clothes or fluff your hair. It shouts, ``I'm insecure.'' Excuse
yourself to the restroom and take care of any problems.
</P>
<P>
   Carry a hanky. This way, you can avoid sneezing into a dinner
napkin or, worse, your hand.
</P>
<P>
   Want to make a good impression? Ask good questions and then
really listen. Everyone loves to talk about themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Sources: Jackie Whitmore, founder and director of the Protocol
School of Palm Beach. She has lived on the Island and worked at The
Breakers for six years.
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Stephenson, of Patricia Stephenson and Associates, a
West Palm Beach image consulting firm. She started image consulting
in Chicago in the mid-80s.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
