<HEADER>
A3189 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-KENNEDY-NYTSF     12-31 1167
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-KENNEDY-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 RFK
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Candid Biography of Robert F. Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   By C. David Heymann.
</P>
<P>
   Illustrated. 596 pp. New York: Dutton. $27.95.
</P>
<P>
   ------
 &UR; POLITICAL AFFAIRS
</P>
<P>
   BY JOHN JUDIS
</P>
<P>
   (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   When I was an editor of a Marxist theoretical journal in the
early 1970's, we often joked that we should add the words ``and
sex'' to the titles of our weighty essays to make them more
attractive to the general reader. It would be ``The Fiscal Crisis
of the State and Sex'' and ``The Triumph of Bourgeois Hegemony and
Sex.'' On that principle, though without a hint of humor, C. David
Heymann's biography of Robert F. Kennedy could have been called
``RFK and Sex.'' ``RFK'' amply covers Robert Kennedy's rumored
affairs, but there is also an orgy of details about the alleged
dalliances of John F. Kennedy, Joseph Kennedy, Edward M. Kennedy,
Peter Lawford, Steven Smith, Ethel Kennedy and Jackie Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   Heymann, the author of an ``intimate biography'' of Jacqueline
Kennedy Onassis and another of Elizabeth Taylor, writes
competently. But here his political account is entirely
conventional: Robert Kennedy, after his brother's death, emerges as
the tribune of a new ``humane 'liberalism.' '' This probably didn't
need reiteration. What is novel about this ``candid biography'' may
increase book sales but not the understanding of its subject. A
politician's sex life and love affairs can certainly be important
to understanding his character and his conduct in office. Garry
Wills in ``The Kennedy Imprisonment'' and Seymour M. Hersh in ``The
Dark Side of Camelot'' attempt to demonstrate that John Kennedy's
manner of dealing with women was symptomatic of a flaw in his
character and affected his Presidency. Heymann, too, occasionally
makes such connections, but they are overshadowed by a pageant of
unanalyzed naughty anecdotes.
</P>
<P>
   Most of two pages of a chapter called ``Sex,'' for instance, are
devoted to extended quotations from Doris Lilly, whom Heymann
describes as a ``society columnist'' (``One of Steve Smith's most
passionate affairs'' was with a woman ``who happened to be the best
girlfriend'' of one of the Kennedy brothers' lovers). We also hear
Truman Capote's musings about the size of the Kennedy brothers'
penises. ``I've seen an awful lot of them,'' he says, ``and if you
put all the Kennedys together, you wouldn't have a good one.''
Later we are treated to a former ballerina's claim that she saw
Robert Kennedy and Rudolf Nureyev ``kissing passionately'' in a
telephone booth.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the sheer wealth of Heymann's anecdotal material
demonstrates that Robert Kennedy did indeed fool around, but
Heymann often relies on single sources who turn out not to have
personally witnessed what they describe, or to have had an animus.
He recounts that Kennedy in the mid-1950's, when he worked for the
Senate Permanent Subcommittee on Investigations, would accompany
the Federal Bureau of Narcotics on raids in New York. Citing a New
York lawyer, Howard Diller, Heymann suggests that Kennedy took
drugs and raped women during these raids. But Diller's actual
statement involves third-hand information -- what he had heard that
agents ``purportedly'' said. Nor does Diller seem particularly
dispassionate. Kennedy, he says, ``struck me as basically
schizophrenic. . . . Caligula seemed mild by comparison.''
</P>
<P>
   Heymann casually endorses the theory that President John
Kennedy's assassination involved a ``second gunman and a
mob-controlled hit.'' And he speculates that Robert Kennedy's
killer might not have acted alone. If that weren't enough, he
introduces a new conspiracy involving Marilyn Monroe, with whom he
says Robert as well as John Kennedy had a love affair. Robert
Kennedy, he writes, ``very likely had conspired in the murder of
his former lover, the nation's premier cinema star.'' Heymann
relies on Peter Lawford's account of a conversation between Robert
Kennedy and Monroe's psychiatrist, Dr. Ralph Greenson: '' 'Marilyn
has got to be silenced,' Bobby told Greenson -- or words to that
effect.'' Heymann doesn't say how Lawford was apprised of this
private exchange, or remark on the telling qualification, ``or
words to that effect.'' He further claims that Greenson, at
Kennedy's prompting, gave Monroe an injection that, mixed with the
sleeping pills that she was taking, killed her. The police never
discovered evidence of the injection; Heymann explains this away,
of course, but I'll leave the details to readers interested in
tabloid speculation.
</P>
<P>
   Heymann often makes the worst out of Robert Kennedy's pre-60's
political career, calling it ``characterized by one savage vendetta
after another.'' But Kennedy's work for Senator Joseph R. McCarthy
was fairly tame -- he was mainly concerned with foreign vessels
trading with China during the Korean War -- and his crusade against
labor racketeering benefited the nation and the labor movement.
(Heymann sheds no light on the obvious question about Robert
Kennedy's tenure as Attorney General -- why he so energetically
prosecuted organized crime figures on whom he and his brother
relied in trying to get rid of Castro.)
</P>
<P>
   Heymann equally exaggerates the political virtue of the later
Robert Kennedy. He contends that John Kennedy's death transformed
Robert Kennedy into a kinder, gentler being. He contrasts Robert
Kennedy's humane liberalism with the ``reactive'' and ``supremely
pragmatic'' politics of his brother. But Heymann does not
appreciate the limits under which President Kennedy -- and by
extension his Attorney General -- had to operate. Kennedy barely
defeated Richard Nixon in 1960 and had to contend with a Congress
in which conservative Southern Democrats held the balance of power.
With John Kennedy's murder, Bobby Kennedy was not freed from his
brother's political shadow, but from executive responsibility. He
could say what he wanted, and could do so in a country and a
Congress that was, briefly, moving to the left.
</P>
<P>
   Heymann embraces the myth that if Robert Kennedy had lived we
would not have seen the Nixon and Reagan Presidencies. I don't
think that's likely. If anything, the Republicans were able to
exploit white reaction to the liberal passions for black
advancement that Bobby Kennedy so exactly embodied. While Senator
Edward Kennedy was, of course, crippled by Chappaquiddick, it is
worth recalling the similar false hopes that initially surrounded
his Presidential candidacy in 1980. But such historical judgments
are certainly debatable, and Heymann's interpretation of Robert
Kennedy's political career and legacy is defensible. What is not
defensible is the way he deals with the rest of Kennedy's life.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   John Judis is a senior editor at The New Republic.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
