<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-31 09:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3191 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-BABEL-1000&AMP;AD     12-31 1928
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-BABEL-1000&AMP;ADD-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 MAN FROM BABEL
<TEXT>
<P>
   By Eugene Jolas.
</P>
<P>
   Edited by Andreas Kramer and Rainer Rumold*
</P>
<P>
   326 pp. New Haven: Yale University Press. $30.
</P>
<P>
   ------
 &UR; LOST MAN OF THE LOST GENERATION
</P>
<P>
   BY ROBERT KIELY
</P>
<P>
   (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``For the most part we were not interested in social problems,
in economics or in any particular political complex. . . . We were
the Romantics of the 20th century.'' So wrote Eugene Jolas of the
cosmopolitan literary and aptistic world he inhabited, observed and
contributed to in the Paris of the 1920's.
</P>
<P>
   Given the legacy of World War I and the tensions building in
Europe at the time, the comment sounds arrogant and insular. Jolas
seems nostalgic, not apologetic, about a period of willful
blindness. Yet while it is true that nostalgia informs many moments
in this memoir of an extraordinary life in an extraordinary time,
Jolas was anything but a blind participant in events of the first
half of the 20th century. The statement is a typically honest
recollection by a person who did not forget the past or
sentimentalize the future, but who by disposition, personal history
and profession was an acute recorder of moods and events in rapidly
shifting times.
</P>
<P>
   Eugene Jolas was born in Union City, N.J., in 1894 of a German
mother and a French father from Alsace-Lorraine. His parents
returned to their native town of Forbach when Jolas was still an
infant. He was raised in a bilingual family, educated in German at
Roman Catholic schools and surrounded by French-speaking neighbors.
Nothing in his eventful life seems to have marked him more than
this early experience of a cultural and political border tense with
instability and burdened by a history of conflicting allegiances
and ideals. Even after he immigrated to America (he was a citizen
by birth), he continued to associate the word ``frontier'' with a
complex and fateful inheritance from the past rather than with
opportunity and hope for the future.
</P>
<P>
   Jolas returned to the Unitdd States at 15, lived with relatives
and took odd jobs as a messenger in New York City. Despite low pay
and hard living, he loved the variety and bustle of the city.
Instead of two languages, he heard dozens. He relished the accents
and atmosphere of Hell'{ Kitchen, Chinatown, Flatbush and Prospect
Park. When he heard the story of another immigrant boy, Joseph
Pulitzer, he decided to be a newspaperman. He wandered from city to
city taking any tasks a paper would offer, and between jobs he
slept on park benches, sharing hunger and stories with others out
of work. There is something Dreiseresque in the cold chaotic whirl
of Jolas's American city at the turn of the century, but there is
nothing of Dreiser in Jolas's outlook. He sounds more like the
Artful Dodger. Where others might fall into despair, he inevitably
finds reason for hope and even a kind of irrepressible
cheerfulness.
</P>
<P>
   His first serious job was with a German-language newspaper in
Pittsburgh. The teen-ager arrived hungry and alone in what at the
time must have been one of America's least appealing cities: ``I
arrived in Pittsburgh on a cold, snowy February evening. The tall
chimneys of the steel mills and glass factories pierced the sky.
Blast furnaces belched soot and smoke. I felt exhilarated by the
lurid cosmos, the cloudy world of industry, grandiose and
Dantesque.''
</P>
<P>
   Since Jolas began writing his memoirs in the 30's and continued
through World War II, it is possible that the older maj casts a
golden haze over the hardships of his youth. Still, his capacity
not only for survivah but also for taking genuine pleasure in the
unexpected shifts of fate that might have defeated a more fragile
psyche seems to have remained with him throughout his life. It is a
trait that helped make him one of the outstanding journalists of
his day and may have prevented his brooding American-French-German
philosophical poetry from possessing the originality and
authenticity of his English prose.
</P>
<P>
   The writing, even in this unfinished memoir, will strike any
reader. Jolas began dictating chapters to his wife, Maria, in the
late 30's or early 40's and continued intermittently until his
death in 1952. It was in the 1980's that Maria brought these papers
to uhe attention of the editors of ``Man From Babel,'' Andreas
Krames and Rainer Rumold.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever else he was doing, Jolas also found time to write
verse. His memoir is punctuated by samples of it. Strongly
influenced by the German Romantics and the French avant-garde, as
well as by Whitman and Hart Crane, he longed to universalize his
incurable homesickness -- for Europe when he was in America, for
America when he was in Europe -- and consequently his restless need
to keep moving, which he considered ``an immigrant neurosis.'' He
was obsessed by language, and, like many of his generation, he
borrowed Freudian terminology to label if not explain his inner
conflicts, including the linguistic ones between the literary and
the idiomatic, French and German, American slang and standard
English. ``Language became a neurosis,'' he writes at the outset as
if to alert us to the pathology that will provide consistency to a
life divided between continents and interrupted by two world wars.
</P>
<P>
   If language was his neurosis, he turns it -- much as he did the
sidewalks of New York, the smokestacks of Pittsburgh, the bordellos
of Savannah -- to his advantage as a reporter. In the 20's he found
himself writing for the Paris edition of The Chicago Tribune. He
seemed to be everywhere in Paris at once -- in the right hotel
lobby for the entrance of Gloria Swanson, in the right bar to
overhear drunken conversations of Zelda and F. Scott Fitzgerald, in
the right park to see Ernest Hemingway take his son for a walk:
``He usually wore workman's clothes and was always most careful to
avoid being taken for a literary man. . . . He seemed to have a
preference for intermingling his vocabulary with strong four-letter
words. Frequently, however, these gave the impression of being
carefully calculated.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-NYTBOOK-BABEL-2NDTAKE-NYTSF &QL; 
 &UR; UNDATED: carefully calculated.'') &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But Jolas was more than a literary gossip columnist. He was
deeply interested in the esthetic avant-garde of the 20's; he was a
defender of Dadaism and Surrealism and of any effort to break
language and the arts away from the cliches of conventional light
entertainment. Not long after his arrival in Paris, he was asked to
take over from Ford Madox Ford the writing of The Tribune's
literary column, ``Rambles Through Literary Paris.'' During
interviews and by attending readings, he met everyone -- James
Joyce, Francois Mauriac, Andre Breton, Gertrude Stein, Sinclair
Lewis, Andre Gide -- and quickly became not only an observer but an
actor in the Paris scene.
</P>
<P>
   His most important and influential contribution to the literary
life of the times was his founding and editing of Transition, a
journal dedicated to the publication of avant-garde works and, of
equal importance to the trilingual Jolas, the exposure between the
same covers of Continental, American and British experiments in
language. In a manifesto published in the third issue in 1927,
Jolas expressed himself with characteristic expansiveness: ``We
need new words, new abstractions, new hieroglyphics, new symbols,
new myths.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the closest and most important of his many literary
friends was Joyce, with whom Jolas shared a nostalgia for an
impossible homeland and a fascination with the meeting and mingling
of alien languages. Jolas became a defender of Joyce's radical
linguistic experiments and published excerpts of ``Work in
Progress'' (early fragments of ``Finnegans Wake'') in Transition.
But he also came to know a side of Joyce few outside his closest
circle of friends would ever see. He saw the lover of Italian
opera; the introverted celebrity who refused to be interviewed but
who could talk and sing into the night with those he trusted; the
aloof literary giant who wished readers would be more appreciative
of his humor (and said, ``in riso veritas''); the grieving father
tormented by his daughter's mental illness. Like all good
reporters, Jolas could capture a personality in a moment and a
phrase. Recalling an evening with Joyce in a Parisian restaurant,
he noticed at a nearby table Picasso, Breton and Jacques Prevert.
``Informed of their presence, Joyce did not look up.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Jolas's English was supple and fluent, some of his most
pointed vignettes depend on what he considered untranslatable
expressions. Whenever the French printer of ``Work in Progress''
heard that Joyce was about to send in yet another addition or
correction, he threw up his hands and shouted, ``Joyce, alors!'' --
so often that it became for him all one name. When the Paris police
booked several writers for an unruly clash between the Romantics
and the Surrealists, Jolas loved the fact that the official charge
was bagarre entre intellectuels. At the end of World War II, when
Jolas was in Germany working for the Office of War Information, he
encountered two Jewish brothers who had lost their father in
Dachau; he quotes but deliberately does not translate their words
to him: ``Wir mochten nach Israel auswandern.''
</P>
<P>
   A gain and again, Jolas reveals not only his sharp eye and ready
ear for a good story but also his sensitivity to human suffering
and injustice. Having cheerfully rejected politics in the
avant-garde carnival of literary Paris in the 20's, he, unlike many
others of the time, did not lurch toward Fascism or Communism in
the 30's. His experience of America had imprinted on him democratic
longings and a tolerance for difference that he eventually saw to
be in conflict with the idealized nationalism and racism of the
German Romantic poets he had once so admired. When he returned to
the frontier land of his parents to help establish a free press in
postwar Germany, he faced not only the devastation of people,
landscape and language but also a past poetic self that had been
deaf to what the mature journalist took to be chillingly clear. ``I
found a definite predilection among the Romantics for the
totalitarian state, for anti-Semitism and for . . . Pan-Germanic
dementia.''
</P>
<P>
   It would be too simple to say that in Jolas's conflicted life
the American journalist triumphed over the German poet, the
modernist over the Romantic, the practical good-humored survivor
over the melancholy dreamer. Outwardly this all seems to be true.
Yet the poetry of abstract angst continued to be written. And there
was a private, inner life -- marriage, children, his complex
relationship to Roman Catholicism -- that is barely touched on in
this action-packed memoir. Like so many modern expatriates, Jolas
took on many attributes of a new world without ever letting go of
the old. Finding Forbach, his ancestral home, in ruins in 1945, he
wrote: ``I realized that throughout my wandering life I had been in
constant flight from this land of restless frontier-shifting. . . .
And yet in the American world something had continued to live in me
that was part of this medieval night.''
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Robert Kiely, a professor of English at Harvard University, is
the author of books on modern and post-modern fiction.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
</TEXT>
