</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981231.0083 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-31 09:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3196 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-SCIFI-NYTSF     12-31 1224
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-SCIFI-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCIENCE FICTION 
 BY GERALD JONAS
</HEADLINE>
 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)
<TEXT>
<P>
   Religion has always been a problem for science fiction writers.
While they are occupationally biased toward rationality, their
stock in trade is imagining plausible futures -- and no speculation
about future societies can be complete without considering the
evolution of current belief systems or the advent of entirely new
religions.
</P>
<P>
   Yet few writers have taken this challenge seriously. When
religion has not served merely as a symbol of irrational reaction,
it has usually figured as window dressing -- a few hints of altered
rituals or creeds to remind the reader that this is indeed ``the
future.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the memorable exceptions: Walter M. Miller Jr.'s
``Canticle for Leibowitz,'' James Blish's ``Case of Conscience,''
Frank Herbert's ``Dune'' series, Gene Wolfe's multivolume ``Book of
the New Sun.'' Add to these Octavia E. Butler's PARABLE OF THE
TALENTS (Seven Stories, $24.95), which continues and deepens the
story she began five years ago in ``Parable of the Sower.''
</P>
<P>
   Once again, the protagonist is Lauren Oya Olamina, a
21st-century prophet, born, she believes, to bring a new kind of
truth to troubled times. Reeling from environmental, political,
financial and military blows, American society is just barely
surviving in the opening years of the next millennium. The
revelation that Olamina feels called upon to share can be summed up
in two sentences: ``God is Change'' and ``The Destiny of Earthseed
is to take root among the stars.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Earthseed'' refers both to her new faith and to the small
circle of believers she assembles through the force of her
personality and her writings, which consist of aphoristic verses
that couch revolutionary thoughts in deceptively simple words.
</P>
<P>
   Butler's narrative skills are impressive. We follow the rise and
fall of Earthseed's first communal home through a chorus of voices
that jump around in time, giving us contrasting perspectives on the
heartbreaking events that test the faith and will of the founding
mother, her family and her adherents. Most remarkably, the ideas
they espouse -- at the risk of their freedom and even their lives
-- are presented with the respect they deserve.
</P>
<P>
   The tenets of Earthseed arise from a thought-provoking
collaboration between the scientific and religious imaginations. As
the founder's husband notes, ``Olamina believes in a god that does
not in the least love her.'' Conceding that Earthseed ``isn't a
very comforting belief system,'' Olamina achieves prophetic stature
by insisting that in the long run the true test of a religion is
whether the solace it offers conforms with the nature of the
universe we live in.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its provocative title, PLAYING GOD (Aspect/Warner, $22),
by Sarah Zettel, disappoints, because the author fails to take her
stated theme seriously enough. In two previous novels,
``Reclamation'' and ``Fool's War,'' Zettel ranged across time and
space with the bracing confidence of a latter-day Asimov or
Heinlein. In ``Playing God,'' she focuses on the fate of a single
planet and, paradoxically, loses her way.
</P>
<P>
   In a not-so-distant future, human beings have averted the
destruction of the earth by splintering into competitive but
mutually respectful political and economic entities called
enclaves. A species of warlike aliens on a distant world has not
been so lucky: after nearly destroying their ecosystem with
biological and nuclear weapons, they find that their only hope for
survival is a worldwide makeover proposed by Bioverse Incorporated
Enclave. The project involves temporarily evacuating 1.3 billion
aliens to giant orbiting spaceships, followed by ``full-scale
bioremediation efforts to clean the planet up after two centuries
of extremely dirty warfare.'' As if that were not difficult enough,
the aliens suffer ``massive anaphylactic reactions'' from close
contact with humans, so attempts to keep the mutually murderous
clans from killing each other on the spaceships must be supervised
from afar.
</P>
<P>
   The humans who devote themselves to this project must respect
the alien culture while containing the aggressive tendencies
inherent in it. I wish I could report that Zettel successfully
dramatizes this problem. Unfortunately, she allows the situation to
deteriorate into open conflict, which she then describes in prose
that lacks the snap and conviction of her earlier books. Despite
page after page of dutifully detailed description, I never got a
clear picture of the aliens or their society. Even worse, I did not
much care what happened to the humans whose efforts to ``play god''
give way, in the end, to all-too-predictable melodrama.
</P>
<P>
   If you are unfamiliar with the work of Paul J. McAuley, his new
collection of stories, THE INVISIBLE COUNTRY (Eos/Avon, paper,
$13.50), provides a useful introduction to this engaging writer.
The title story, set in a grim near-future London, is told in a
noirish style that might be characterized as ``bio-punk.''
</P>
<P>
   A former professional biologist, McAuley conjures a world
ravaged by global warming and a breakdown in social order
exacerbated by the easy availability of intrusive biotechnology. In
a convincing demonstration of his stylistic sleight of hand, he
transmutes this nightmarish vision into a dream of utopia right
under the reader's nose, so to speak.
</P>
<P>
   Four of the nine stories in this collection evoke a future (also
encountered in McAuley's novel ``Fairyland'') in which ``dolls,''
gene-engineered humanoid creatures, serve as all-purpose slaves. By
coming at this painful subject from the point of view of society's
human outcasts, McAuley avoids the twin traps of facile moralizing
and maudlin sentiment.
</P>
<P>
   Another story, ``Recording Angel,'' shares setting and theme
with McAuley's recent novel ``Child of the River'' and casts some
light on the confusing background of that work, the first in a
promised trilogy.
</P>
<P>
   When I was 10 years old, I read a book entitled ``Tom Swift and
His Electric Elephant Gun.'' I can still remember the thrill
generated by the technological wonder of a superweapon that allowed
Tom to subdue a ponderous pachyderm without actually killing it. A
similar sense of wonder animates the recent crop of computer-driven
techno-thrillers, of which THE TERMINATION NODE (Del
Rey/Ballantine, $24), by Lois H. Gresh and Robert Weinberg, is a
suitably breathless example.
</P>
<P>
   An evil mastermind is killing off computer hackers faster than
you can say ``delete.'' Only the skills of a superhacker, Judy
Carmody, known to her online friends as ``TerMight,'' can save the
day -- not to mention the billions of dollars of electronic bank
deposits about to vanish forever at the click of a mouse.
</P>
<P>
   I would not venture a guess about whether this Internet-savvy
collaboration will stir feelings of wonder in today's young
readers. I can only report that the book's series of brutal murders
raised not so much as a hair on the back of my neck, since the
authors failed to breathe life into these victims before they were
dispatched.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
</TEXT>
