<DOCNO> NYT19981231.0085 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-31 09:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3198 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-SLANT-NYTSF     12-31 0991
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-SLANT-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 A SLANT OF SUN
<TEXT>
<P>
   One Child's Courage.
</P>
<P>
   By Beth Kephart.
</P>
<P>
   256 pp. New York: W. W. Norton &AMP; Company. $23.
</P>
<P>
   ------
 &UR; THE BOY IN THE BRIGHT GREEN HAT
</P>
<P>
   BY MARGARET TALBOT
</P>
<P>
   (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Childhood these days is often a land of diagnoses. Detours from
the developmental path can easily get a kid tagged with one new
syndrome or another. And as far as many parents are concerned, this
is an unmitigated good. These parents -- and we tend to hear a lot
from them because they speak up at school board meetings and
testify before Congress -- are grateful to have an explanation
like, say, attention deficit disorder for behavior that puzzles or
frightens them and are relieved to know that they are not alone. We
don't hear quite as much from parents who react to such labels with
tortured ambivalence, who wonder whether their child's
individuality has been reduced to pathology, and what might be lost
if it has.
</P>
<P>
   Beth Kephart is such a parent, and fortunately for us she is
also a gifted, even poetic writer. In 1991, when Kephart's son,
Jeremy, was 2, doctors concluded he had something called pervasive
developmental disorder not otherwise specified, a catchall
condition that might best be described as a milder and more
malleable form of autism. That Jeremy was different from other
children his age came as no surprise to Kephart or her husband, an
artist and architect. Jeremy spoke early, but his speech seemed to
stall at the naming stage -- ``Dino!'' ``Juice cup!'' ``Bathtub!''
-- and later deteriorated into echolalia, the tendency to repeat
what he had just heard. He was, more even than most toddlers, a
creature of habit, a fiend for order and patterns. He liked to
arrange his matchbox cars in color-coded pinwheels as intricate as
church-floor mosaics and could not abide having any of them moved a
fraction of an inch. For months he would not leave the house or
take a bath or go to sleep without donning a chartreuse fedora
several sizes too big that he had picked out for himself at the
local department store. Playgrounds were not easy places for him,
and new children -- new people in general -- often put him deeply
out of sorts. He preferred textbooks on medieval chivalry to
``Goodnight Moon.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor did Kephart, a freelance writer, have any real doubt that
Jeremy would need extra help, redoubled devotion, if he were to
keep one foot in the world as most of the rest of us know it. She
writes eloquently in ``A Slant of Sun,'' her first book and a
finalist for a National Book Award last year, of her panic before
his diagnosis and his first rounds of speech therapy, of the
moments when her sweet black-eyed boy seems to be sliding away from
her into some shadow land: ``There is an absence of things. Small
lights burning out. The creep of an indecipherable dimness. Jeremy
does not wave hello. Jeremy does not eat his food. Jeremy does not
look for us beneath the hood of his eyes; language is
disappearing.''
</P>
<P>
   But Kephart also knows that naming a child's syndrome is not the
same as helping him, and not the same as understanding him.
Pervasive developmental disorder, as she quickly comes to realize,
is another way for doctors to say that something is wrong but they
don't know what or why. It's not a diagnosis that entails an
obvious course of treatment, nor does it take into account the
aspects of Jeremy that those who love him wouldn't want treated.
``What, in the end, are you fighting for: Normal? Is normal
possible? Can it be defined? Is it best achieved by holing up in
the offices of therapists, in special classrooms, in isolated
exercises, in simulating living, while everyday 'normal' happens
casually on the other side of the wall? And is normal superior to
what the child inherently is, to what he aspires to, fights to
become, every second of his day?''
</P>
<P>
   ``A Slant of Sun'' is a memoir -- a personal and not a
prescriptive book -- but one of its strengths is that it makes us
think about these questions not just for Jeremy but for other
idiosyncratic children too. In her introduction Kephart writes that
Jeremy is now ``a successful second grader at a country Quaker
school,'' a boy with friends and hobbies and a philosophical bent
that prompts him to ponder aloud, ``Mommy, how are we supposed to
see God?'' And it is striking that while Kephart gives ample credit
to the various professionals -- speech therapists, play therapists
-- who helped Jeremy adopt a less solipsistic way of being in the
world, she is most moved by the ordinary people who saw and
appreciated him for what he was already.
</P>
<P>
   Kephart and her husband decided against special schools for
Jeremy, which they thought would only isolate him further. They
were willing to create a miniature mainstream for their son that
would be like the real mainstream, but kinder -- a milieu in which
he would always be listened to as he groped for more conversational
language, in which he would be given time to decompress when he had
been deep in one of his interior visions. In this enterprise,
though, they needed at least some confederates outside their own
tenderly solicitous household -- friends who would not regard
Jeremy's passions for trucks or knights or green hats merely as
symptoms, who would see something joyful in the whorls and ridges
of his distinctive sensibility. They did find some of these people,
not many, but enough -- a teacher or two, a baby sitter, the
handyman at school who just plain liked him. What these friends
offered might seem like the simplest of gifts. Kephart makes it
clear that it was anything but.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Margaret Talbot is a senior editor at The New Republic.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
