<DOCNO> NYT19981231.0087 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-31 09:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3215 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DEMPSEY-COLUMN01-COX     12-31 0603
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEMPSEY-COLUMN01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    For release Friday, Jan. 1
 &HT;    We'll all be sick of millennium talk soon _ very soon.
 &HT;    By Laura Dempsey
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   So do we start from scratch, or what? This isn't the first time
you've heard this, but hey: The end of the century is coming. It's
right around the corner, in fact, and by the time it arrives, it'll
seem like it's been here forever.
</P>
<P>
   How many times are we going to have to wade through the musings
and philosophications and roundups of the last thousand years? How
many times are we going to peruse a list of the accomplishments we
humans have achieved, the changes we've effected, the progress
we've made?
</P>
<P>
   That's right. Way too many.
</P>
<P>
   How many millennium calendars did you get for Christmas? And how
many times are we going to be reminded that the 21st Century
doesn't start until the year 2001? Face it, we're going to get sick
and tired of all things 2000, and it's starting right here, right
now.
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, try to forget the Y2K problem. Try to forget the
predictions of doom and disaster from techno-phobes and
techno-experts who say that our computer-dependent society will
come crashing to a halt. Forget what they say about ATM machines
not working after midnight on Dec. 31, 1999, or the nationwide
blackout that will result when power company machines read ``00''
at 12:01 a.m. on Jan. 1, and clink a collective ``huh?''
</P>
<P>
   Forget all that? No way. We're going to be reminded again and
again that stockpiling canned goods and bottled water is not such a
bad idea; that getting our prescriptions filled for a couple of
years in advance might be the prudent thing to do. Sure, President
Clinton has assured us that Social Security is ready, that the
checks will keep on coming despite the naysayers who tell us the
government computers aren't going to be ready. (President Clinton
wouldn't lie, would he?)
</P>
<P>
   In the midst of all ``World Is Ending'' signs, we're about to be
treated to page after page, newscast after newscast, Internet site
after Internet site, of ``The World That Was.'' There are plenty of
things to discuss. Just think of all the stuff we've invented since
1900.
</P>
<P>
   _ Air conditioning.
</P>
<P>
   _ Teddy bears.
</P>
<P>
   _ World wars.
</P>
<P>
   _ Computers.
</P>
<P>
   _Diet Coke.
</P>
<P>
   _ Rice Krispies for different colored holidays.
</P>
<P>
   _Postage stamps that peel.
</P>
<P>
   _ Madonna. Oh wait: She invented herself.
</P>
<P>
   It's going to be unbearable, especially for those born in the
'70s or '80s, who by nature resent any sense of historical
perspective. What about those kids walking around with ``00'' on
their letter jackets? They're ready. They don't need to be
reminded.
</P>
<P>
   The Census Bureau estimates that 64,000 lucky folks have a shot
at spanning three centuries. How are they possibly going to cope?
It's hard enough to explain the vinyl recordings stored (for
nostalgia) in the basement, or to tell our children that life
wasn't always lived on-line. Are they going to believe that Grandma
didn't ever have a chance to design her own Web site? This year
they're going to hear that, and a millennium's worth of more.
</P>
<P>
   It's going to be unbearable. And it's going to be enlightening.
So pay attention _ not that you have a choice. The media need a
hook, and there's never been a bigger one than the one that starts
today. The countdown. The big 365-episode show about everything.
The segments titled ``In Retrospect'' or ``The Last Thousand
Years.''
</P>
<P>
   Prepare yourself. It has begun.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
