<HEADER>
A3203 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-PAPERBACKS-NY     12-31 0934
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-PAPERBACKS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTEWORTHY PAPERBACKS 
 BY SCOTT VEALE
</HEADLINE>
  (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 CIRCUMNAVIGATION
<TEXT>
<P>
   By Steve Lattimore.
</P>
<P>
   Houghton Mifflin, $12 &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   The author's first collection of short stories is populated by
disaffected Californians stuck with menial jobs, empty lives and
dead-end relationships. In 1997 our reviewer, Scott Bradfield,
called this a ``funny, moving book'' that in its best moments is
``about the various jangled ways in which broken families manage to
operate.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SLAVES IN THE FAMILY
</P>
<P>
   By Edward Ball.
</P>
<P>
   Ballantine, $15.95 &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   Searching for the descendants of slaves owned by his ancestors
in South Carolina, the author confronts his heritage and the moral
consequences of slavery. His account, which won a National Book
Award last year, took him across America and to Africa, and
involved extensive interviews and research. ``There is much to
admire in Ball's very willingness to challenge the generations of
silence in his white family and to search out black kin whose
reactions he had every reason to fear,'' Drew Gilpin Faust wrote
here in 1998. In To 'Joy My Freedom: Southern Black Women's Lives
and Labors After the Civil War, by Tera W. Hunter (Harvard
University, $15.95), a history professor explores the valuable
political and social role played by black women after Emancipation.
In 1997 the same reviewer called this a ``celebration of struggle
and resistance.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE COCKROACH BASKETBALL LEAGUE
</P>
<P>
   By Charley Rosen.
</P>
<P>
   Seven Stories, $13.95 &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   This hymn to minor-league basketball follows a team of misfits
and whining wannabes as they ply their trade in the shadow of the
big time. The result is ``a racily entertaining novel'' that
``skillfully induces the reader to join 'the Brotherhood of the
Sacred Hoop,' '' Michael Anderson wrote here in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GEORGE ELIOT: A LIFE
</P>
<P>
   By Rosemary Ashton.
</P>
<P>
   Penguin, $15.95 &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   This revisionist biography combines the social context of
Eliot's fiction and a detailed analysis of her novels. ``Ashton is
a serious, persistent scholar, and the picture she gives of Eliot's
intellectual and emotional life is convincing,'' William S.
Peterson wrote in these pages in 1997. Jane Austen: A Life, by
David Nokes (University of California, $19.95), reveals how the
novelist wielded irony and razor-sharp observation as weapons to
skewer the constraining society in which she lived. In 1997 in the
Book Review, Claude Rawson praised the author for leaning heavily
on Austen's letters, which ``are wonderfully revealing, especially
strong on the texture of relationships and the tang of social
encounters.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PRINCE OF PEACE
</P>
<P>
   By James Carroll.
</P>
<P>
   Mariner/Houghton Mifflin, $13 &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   This densely plotted novel tells the parallel tales of an
American priest who gets caught up in the anti-Vietnam War movement
and what is portrayed as the metamorphosis of the Roman Catholic
Church in the United States into a cynically run corporation. ``The
stories are nearly irresistible,'' Webster Schott wrote here in
1984.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ASPHALT NATION
</P>
<P>
   How the Automobile Took Over America, and How We Can Take It
Back
</P>
<P>
   By Jane Holtz Kay.
</P>
<P>
   University of California, $16.95 &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   In this cranky polemic, an architecture critic describes how
unchecked motorized sprawl is threatening the nation's cities and
towns, its economy and its health. She ``largely succeeds in
proving that it is possible to get where we are going without
destroying where we live,'' Kenneth T. Jackson said here in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EATING CHINESE FOOD NAKED
</P>
<P>
   By Mei Ng
</P>
<P>
   Washington Square/Pocket Books, $14.
</P>
<P>
   Ruby Lee is a restless college graduate whose protective love
for her mother draws her back to her father's laundry in Queens.
Last year our reviewer, Lynn Karpen, called this an ``affecting
first novel'' that ``conveys the complexities of family life with
vibrant color and luminosity.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BOBBY REX'S GREATEST HIT
</P>
<P>
   By Marianne Gingher.
</P>
<P>
   Louisiana State University, $14.95 &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   It's 1961 in Greensboro, N.C., and Pally Thompson is about to
marry a man who wants to know how far she went with a local
country-music crooner whose hit song is all about his romance with
her. This ``richly detailed, often charming first novel . . .
lovingly evokes Pally's journey from innocence to maturity in a
town where gossip flourishes and ambitions fade,'' Ellen Pall wrote
here in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CITIZEN SOLDIERS
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Army From the Normandy Beaches to the Bulge to the
Surrender of Germany.
</P>
<P>
   June 7, 1944-May 7, 1945
</P>
<P>
   By Stephen E. Ambrose.
</P>
<P>
   Touchstone/Simon &AMP; Schuster, $16 &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   In this sequel to ``D-Day,'' the author's 1994 best seller about
the Normandy landing, he once again uses the experiences of
ordinary soldiers to re-create the bloody, often nameless battles
that led to the Nazi defeat. '' 'Citizen Soldiers' is an
unforgettable testament to the World War II generation,'' Carlo
D'Este wrote here in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GOD'S SNAKE
</P>
<P>
   By Irini Spanidou
</P>
<P>
   Vintage International, $13 &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   A young girl chronicles her anguished coming-of-age in Greece in
the 1950s as the daughter of an inflexible military officer who
treats her as if she were one of his recruits. This first novel
``freshly evokes the beauties and terrors of childhood,'' Nicholas
Bromell wrote here in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
