<HEADER>
A3212 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEA-LIFEBEAT-ART-NYTS     12-31 1212
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEA-LIFEBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEA FOR LIFE
</HEADLINE>
  Includes color photo of teapot and tea, available via e-mail. Call
212-499-3342. 
 By BEN STEELMAN 
 c. NYT Regional Newspapers 
 North American rights 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A cup of tea keeps the doctor away? Don't laugh.
</P>
<P>
   A symposium this fall (1998) in Washington heard evidence that
this 5,000-year-old beverage has health benefits beyond a warm,
contented feeling and a gentle caffeine buzz.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists from the U.S. Department of Agriculture reported that
tea is an important source of antioxidants, those chemicals that
keep oxygen and nitrogen compounds from damaging cells, thus
slowing the aging process and preventing some diseases.
</P>
<P>
   A typical cup of black tea _ the kind most Americans drink _
contains more antioxidants than some fruits and vegetables. Teams
from the U.S. National Cancer Institute and the Chinese Academy of
Preventative Medicine discussed findings that tea-drinking may
reduce the risk of some kinds of cancer in humans.
</P>
<P>
   There is even some evidence from the Netherlands that chemicals
in tea can lower levels of ``bad'' cholesterol in the bloodstream,
which might prevent heart attacks and strokes.
</P>
<P>
   All this good news needs to be taken with a grain of, er, sugar.
</P>
<P>
   The symposium was sponsored and publicized by the Tea Council of
the USA, an association of tea businesses and importers. Below the
headlines, scientists indicated that most of their theories needed
much more research for confirmation.
</P>
<P>
   Still the possibility of health benefits justifies a second look
at a drink whose popularity crosses the boundaries between dozens
of cultures.
</P>
<P>
   In a typical year, Americans drink enough tea to fill 160,000
backyard swimming pools, with plenty of pitchers to spare,
according to the Tea Council. Roughly half of Americans are
tea-drinkers, with the South and New Englanders downing far more
than their share.
</P>
<P>
   According to sociologist John Shelton Reed, 87 percent of
Southerners say they drink tea.
</P>
<P>
   ``I drink tea every day,'' said Moyra Stevens, a Scotswoman now
living and gardening in Wilmington, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   Down South, of course, ``tea'' usually means sugared iced tea;
two-thirds of Southerners say they prefer their brew sweet, and
they drink it year-round, even in the depth of winter.
</P>
<P>
   Such a widespread habit _ novelist Reynolds Price says iced tea
is as essential to the Southern lunch as fried chicken, cured ham
or green beans _ was formed surprisingly recently.
</P>
<P>
   Official histories credit British promoter Richard Blechynden
with inventing iced tea in 1904, meeting the demand for a cool
nonalcoholic beverage at the St. Louis World's Fair that year.
</P>
<P>
   Food chronicler John Egerton, however, thinks cool tea might
have caught on in parts of the South in the late 1800s, as
commercial ice-making became more widespread.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, not everybody downs his or her tea cold, and Orange
Pekoe, the type preferred in most Southern kitchens, is just one of
thousands of varieties of tea worldwide. It's possible to grow as
snobbish about tea as many aficionados do about wines or cigars.
</P>
<P>
   Legend has it that the Chinese Emperor Shen Nung invented tea in
the year 2737 B.C., after some leaves floated into a pot of boiling
water. Other sources claim that tea was brought to China by
Buddhist missionaries from India. In any case, China and India
still lead the world both in tea production and consumption.
</P>
<P>
   Tea leaves come from a bush or shrub, a botanical cousin of the
camellia. The best teas grow in tropical regions on mountainsides
at elevations between 3,000 and 7,000 feet.
</P>
<P>
   Teas come in three major varieties: black, green or oolong.
Black teas, accounting for 95 percent of the tea drunk in America,
are produced by crushing the leaves, letting them ferment under
special conditions and then drying or oxidizing them in ovens.
Dried, the teas are black and powdery; steeped in boiling water,
they take a red or amber hue.
</P>
<P>
   Green teas, a specialty of China and Japan, are steamed and
crushed, without the oxidizing process. The resulting teas are
green or golden in the cup.
</P>
<P>
   Oolong teas represent a sort of halfway point between black and
</P>
<P>
   green. The leaves are partially fermented, giving these teas a
greenish-brown color.
</P>
<P>
   Herbal teas, especially the decaffeinated brands, are not true
teas. They are ground from the flowers, leaves, peels, seeds and
other parts of plants and herbs such as chamomile, chrysanthemum,
thyme, peppermint, cinnamon or rosebud.
</P>
<P>
   TEA CEREMONIES
</P>
<P>
   Almost as important as the tea itself is the ritual behind it.
</P>
<P>
   In Japan _ which acquired tea from a Buddhist monk named Yeisi
sometime in the 1100s _ the tea ceremony evolved into an elaborate
social grace, in which tea-drinking (precisely three sips, no more,
no less, from a tiny, exquisite cup) becomes almost an
afterthought.
</P>
<P>
   Russians, who picked up the habit in the 1700s, turned tea into
an excuse for animated conversation, generally centered around
their distinctive samovars (from a Russian word meaning, literally,
``self-boiler''). In Russia, tea is strongly sweetened with sugar,
honey or jam.
</P>
<P>
   The Western nation that took tea closest to its heart, however,
was Merry Old England. The brew began to appear in London in the
late 1600s, patronized by King Charles II, who picked up the tea
habit while in exile in Holland and who married a princess from
Portugal, the foremost tea importer of the era.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, again, that particular English custom called ``tea'' is of
surprisingly recent vintage. History books attribute it to the
Duchess of Bedford (1788-1861), who needed an afternoon pick-me-up.
</P>
<P>
   Other sources credit the Industrial Revolution. Britons, then as
now, generally serve supper at 8 p.m. or even 9 p.m., Stevens
noted. The workers from the new factories of the 1800s and the
mines, however, needed some refreshment once their shifts ended
around 4 or 5 p.m. Thus, Stevens and millions of other Anglophiles
take a break around the world at 4 p.m. for a little tea with
perhaps a cookie or some cake. ``High tea'' takes on the character
of a small meal, often with roast beef, mashed potatoes and peas.
</P>
<P>
   The tea is always hot, even in the tropics: ``The heat actually
cools you down, strangely enough,'' Stevens said.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest mistake novice tea-drinkers make, is not to heat the
water enough. For good tea, the water must boil, at a temperature
of at least 212 degrees; coffee-grade water, at 180 degrees or so,
will not do.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens always begins by warming her teapot, pouring in some
water from her electric kettle, swirling it around inside, then
pouring it out through the spout.
</P>
<P>
   She prefers loose tea, which involves such apparatus as a
tea-strainer or tea ball. However, Americans have generally
embraced the 1904 invention of tea dealer Thomas Sullivan, also
introduced at the St. Louis World's Fair _ the tea bag.
</P>
<P>
   --------
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Ben Steelman writes for the Morning Star in Wilmington, N.C.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call New York Times
Syndicate sales representative NIRDI RELIS at (800) 972-3550 or fax
her at (212) 499-3382.
</P>
