<HEADER>
A3219 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MILLENNIUM-AMERICA-CO     12-31 1482
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILLENNIUM-AMERICA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EMBARGOED UNTIL SATURDAY, JANUARY 2. DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN.
 &HT;    RESENDING FOR THOSE WHO NEED IT
 &HT;    Israel's fate captures imagination of evangelical Christians
 &HT;    By Gayle White
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The names on a map of modern Israel ring with biblical
significance in the ears of American Christians. The ancient cities
and towns, mountains and rivers are the settings of the great
events of the life of Jesus Christ and his Old Testament
predecessors.
</P>
<P>
   For many conservative Christians, this identification has
translated into a strong support for Israel, even while they feel
obligated to try to convert Jews to Christianity. Sometimes
enthusiasm for Israel comes at the expense of their fellow
Christians of Palestinian heritage.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very pro-Jewish, pro-Israel,'' said the Rev. Jerry
Falwell, pastor of Thomas Road Baptist Church in Lynchburg, Va.,
and founder of Liberty University. ``I would say evangelicals are
the very best friends Israelis have in the whole world outside
their own family. Evangelicals are more committed to Israel than
some of the American Jewish community.''
</P>
<P>
   This commitment is rooted in years of Bible lessons, according
to the Rev. Timothy Weber, dean of Northern Baptist Seminary in
Lombard, Ill. ``I think at rock bottom, evangelicals care deeply
about Israel because they're steeped in the Bible,'' Weber said.
``So many evangelicals sat for years and years and years in Sunday
school rooms with Bible land maps on the wall and heard Bible story
after Bible story that, as a result, they have a proprietary
interest in Israel. In a way it belongs to them as much as to the
Jews.''
</P>
<P>
   Falwell, among Israel's best-known supporters, cites the Old
Testament and world history as the basis for his support.
``Basically God promised to bless those who blessed the children of
Abraham and curse those who cursed Israel,'' he said. ``I think
history supports the fact that he has been true to his word. When
you go back to the pharaohs, the caesars, Adolf Hitler and the
Soviet Union, all those who dared to touch the apple of God's eye _
Israel _ have been punished by God. America has been blessed
because she has blessed Israel.''
</P>
<P>
   But Falwell and some evangelical and Pentecostal Christians feel
a special tie with Israel not only because of the past but because
of the future. They see the land as ``ground zero'' for Jesus'
triumphant return to earth, as Weber describes it. They believe
Bible prophecy dictates that certain political and religious events
must occur in Israel to prepare the way for Jesus to come again,
and see recent history as steps toward the fulfillment of this
prophecy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Evangelical Christians in America have thought for centuries
that the nation of Israel was especially chosen by God and the
return of the Jews to Palestine and the establishment of the nation
of Israel in 1948 is viewed as a significant event,'' religious
broadcaster and former presidential candidate Pat Robertson said.
``Perhaps more significant is the Six-Day War, beginning June 5,
1967, which resulted in the Jewish people for the first time in
almost 2,500 years having control of Jerusalem.''
</P>
<P>
   Robertson says the reclamation of Jerusalem by the Jews signals
the culmination of prophecy by Jesus quoted in the gospel of Luke,
which says ``Jerusalem will be trampled on by the Gentiles, until
the times of the Gentiles are fulfilled (Luke 21:24, New Revised
Standard Version of the bible).''
</P>
<P>
   ``(The year) 1967 began what I could call the generation of the
end of the Gentiles,'' Robertson said. ``That terminates in 2007.
That is an important 40 years in the history of the world as far as
I'm concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   Robertson _ like most Christian leaders _ refuses to get into
specific predictions of when Jesus might reappear.
</P>
<P>
   The doctrine of a second coming of Christ is not peculiar to
evangelicals. It is standard in both Catholic and Protestant
traditions. End-times events are so important to Christians that
the field of study has its own name _ eschatology. But within
Christianity, many different scenarios have developed for just how
the present world will end. Denominations have evolved from
people's acceptance of one view over another, and a whole
vocabulary has evolved to describe beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   What all the scenarios have in common is the pervasive belief
that Jesus' return will happen in Israel.
</P>
<P>
   ``The symbolism is that his feet will stand on the Mount of
Olives,'' Robertson said.
</P>
<P>
   Tied to this belief is the political support for Israel to hang
on to its present boundaries and add more property. Historically,
say both Falwell and Robertson, the lands now called Gaza and the
West Bank were a part of the Promised Land God gave Abraham and his
descendants.
</P>
<P>
   In insisting that Israel give land to Palestine to spur on the
peace process, ``the United States is on the wrong side,'' said
Robertson, who went on to warn that President Clinton could
``unwittingly begin a series of events that could lead to
catastrophe.''
</P>
<P>
   The final battle will be a fight over Jerusalem, Robertson said.
``It'll take place when the nations of the world come up against
Israel and try to take Jerusalem away ... The whole thought is that
when Jerusalem is under attack, Jesus will come back.''
</P>
<P>
   The view that Israel is entitled to all of the West Bank, Gaza
and complete control of Jerusalem puts evangelicals at odds with
some of their Christian brethren of Palestinian heritage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because the evangelicals believe they know what's going to
happen and they know the players in the end-time events, anything
that doesn't contribute to that scenario is outside the will of
God,'' Weber said. ``Palestinian Christians just don't factor in.''
</P>
<P>
   The 10 percent of Palestinians who are Christian frequently feel
neglected by their fellow believers, according to the Rev. Fahed
Abu-Akel, a Palestinian Christian and founder of Atlanta Ministry
with International students.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Christians of Palestine and Israel feel forgotten by the
Christians of America,'' Abu-Akel said. ``Americans go there as
tourists and visit the place where Jesus was born in Bethlehem,
where he lived in Nazareth and was crucified in Jerusalem, and
focus on the past. They seldom get in touch with the living
Palestinian church today to see how they are doing, how they are
struggling and what are their needs.''
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, Abu-Akel said, ``American TV evangelists focus, most
of them, on Israel as a sign for the fulfillment of prophecy and
are completely insensitive to the issues of peace and justice and
the struggle of people for survival.''
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian Christians have found some support among mainline
Protestants. Because of the former British rule of Palestine, the
Anglican church is strong there. And Abu-Akel's denomination, the
Presbyterian Church (U.S.A.) is on record supporting a two-state
solution to conflict in the Middle East. ``That means an
independent Palestinian state in the West Bank and Gaza,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Christians who hold that view just don't take the Bible
seriously enough, Falwell said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I probably get more negative mail from Protestant and Catholic
Christians than I do from Arabs,'' he said. ``Most of them don't
believe in the inerrancy of the Bible. When you reject the
infallibility of scripture, then you can develop your own concepts
... Evangelicals, believing in the inerrancy of scripture, rather
choose literally to follow God's plan.''
</P>
<P>
   Mainline Protestants, Robertson said, ``regard Israel as just
one more country,'' while he and other evangelicals ``think of the
Jews as the chosen people of God and the return of the Jews to
their land as a matter of great significance from a Biblical
perspective.''
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian Christians and their supporters lack the
communication infrastructure of either the government of Israel
with its consulates and ministry of tourism, or the American
evangelical and Pentecostal Christians with their television
ministries, Abu-Akel said.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, the conservative Christians who offer Israel
unflinching support are also the most likely to feel the need to
convert the Jews to Christianity. At the very least, they believe
that Israel will go through continued tribulation and eventually
recognize Jesus as the messiah.
</P>
<P>
   ``The relationship is very, very complicated,'' Weber said.
``Most evangelicals who are politically involved in the support of
Israel have learned they've got to tone down the evangelism. And
conversely, Jews who accept evangelical support have got to kind of
forget that they know the reason for all this evangelical interest
_ that Israel plays a role in end-time events which will lead to
the complete victory of Jesus Christ in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
