<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-31 09:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3221 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MILLENNIUM-FUTURE-COX     12-31 0989
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILLENNIUM-FUTURE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EMBARGOED UNTIL SATURDAY, JANUARY 2. DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN.
 &HT;    RESENDING FOR THOSE WHO NEED IT
 &HT;    Christians a minority in land where Jesus dwelt
 &HT;    By Larry Kaplow
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BETHLEHEM, WEST BANK_Nisreen Zieneh isn't distracted by the
German tourists roaming about the cavernous Church of the Nativity
as she kisses her fingers and touches the low door frame of the
1,400-year-old basilica.
</P>
<P>
   After entering the church, believed by many Christians to be the
site of Jesus Christ's birth, the stylish young Arab woman kneels
and repeats the ritual, gently kissing her fingers and touching the
stone floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's where Jesus was born. I came because I want to pray to
him. He stands beside me,'' Zieneh said.
</P>
<P>
   This day, Zieneh has two requests: That Jesus support her in her
law school examinations and that he forgive her for not visiting
the church since her wedding there six months ago.
</P>
<P>
   She is one of the native Christians. Amid the more powerful
majorities of Jews and Muslims, it is Arab Christians who apply in
the modern world the religion that began here nearly 2000 years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   But their numbers are dwindling.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout history, political clout has determined the
subsistence of religion in the Middle East. Today, Christians are
without it, and in places like Israel, Egypt and Lebanon, they
suffer economic hardships and harassment because of it.
</P>
<P>
   There are an estimated 6 million to 10 million Arab Christians
in the Middle East, about 5 percent of the population, according to
statistics at the Jerusalem-based Christian Information Center.
While exact figures are difficult to come by, experts agree the
population has slipped steadily over the years.
</P>
<P>
   In Bethlehem alone, the ratio of Christians to Muslims has
undergone a complete reversal in the past 50 years _ from a 70
percent majority of Christians at the end of World War II to a 30
percent minority today.
</P>
<P>
   In Israel, some Arab Christian villages continue to thrive,
while others simply disappeared after the war that gave Israel its
independence in 1948. A tide of refugees, Christians and Muslims,
left Israel and later the West Bank and Gaza Strip when Israel
captured those territories in 1967.
</P>
<P>
   In Israel and the Palestinian-ruled territories _ home to
Jerusalem and Bethlehem _ Christians number fewer than 200,000
among a population of 5 million Jews and 2.5 million Muslims.
</P>
<P>
   Christian schools are now mostly populated by Muslims, churches
are surrounded by mosques and synagogues. Christians emigrate
frequently to the Americas.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reasons for the emigration are still there, in that
Christians are always going to be second-class citizens either in a
Jewish state or in a Muslim-majority state. They are never going to
be a force,'' said the Rev. Jerome Murphy O'Connor, a scholar at
the French Dominican School of Bible and Archaeological Studies in
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   A new trend in Bethlehem highlights the Christian predicament.
Over the last year, neon crucifixes have cropped up on a few
rooftops in this crowded city of 140,000 Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Rossing, former Israeli government liaison to the
Christian community, called the crosses an attempt at ``Christian
power.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They are between the hammer and the anvil,'' he said, in the
middle of the colossal struggle between the Jews and Muslims.
</P>
<P>
   Appearing historically after the Jews and before the Muslims,
Christians are like the overlooked middle child amid the region's
three faiths. But some Christians feel their religion's message may
be especially apt today, a period of unrest.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Lord's Prayer says to 'forgive their trespasses as you
would want yours to be forgiven,''' said Bernard Sabella, an expert
on the Christian population and a Christian Palestinian whose
family lost its house to Israel in 1948. ``I find it difficult to
apply this .. . it's difficult, but it's the way out.''
</P>
<P>
   But problems persist. Relations between Jews, Muslims and
Christians remain strained.
</P>
<P>
   In a controversial report, the Israeli government asserted
earlier this year that the new Palestinian National Authority
encourages Muslim persecution of Christians.
</P>
<P>
   Uri Mor, author of the report, says persecution is not overt.
But Muslims who desecrate churches or cemeteries are protected, he
said. Some who have converted from Islam to Christianity have been
harassed. He says Christians tell him privately that the
Palestinian Authority, led by Yasser Arafat, encourages their
enemies.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the politics of the region, Christians in Israel and
other Middle East countries have a support system that continues to
make them a major, if small, force in the region. They receive
millions of dollars in aid from Christians around the world, who
maintain about 700 churches, hospitals, schools and universities in
Israel.
</P>
<P>
   The local Christian community is a ragtag mix of ethnicity and
experience. There are Christian Palestinians who participated in
the anti-Israel Intifada uprising. Meanwhile, Israeli Arabs largely
stay out of the political fray. A Christian entrepreneur owns the
only Palestinian beer brewery, and another recently got the
franchise to produce Coca-Cola.
</P>
<P>
   In Beit Jala, near Bethlehem, social worker Heyam Aldaqamqa at
the Evangelical Lutheran Church is hopeful that this land where
Jesus once walked will remain a spiritual center for Christians
around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Her church, founded more than 100 years ago, is heavily
supported by churches in Germany and has a congregation of about
500.
</P>
<P>
   Its modern wing has a boarding school for children from broken
homes _ Christian and Muslim. Aldaqamqa said the children share
their holidays and hardships.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are one people,'' she said. ``We are Palestinians and we
have the same destiny.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
