<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-31 09:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3222 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MILLENNIUM-OVERVIEW27     12-31 0514
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILLENNIUM-OVERVIEW27-COX-rese </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    RESENDING FOR THOSE WHO NEED IT
 &HT;    One man, 2 millennia, 2 billion followers worldwide
 &HT;    By Gayle White
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Christians believe that through the birth of Jesus of
Nazareth, God became human.
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not he was God incarnate, Jesus changed the world.
History is full of the best and the worst of human actions in his
name: horrible wars and wonderful acts of kindness; persecution and
sacrifice; bigotry and unselfish love. Some of the world's greatest
art, music and literature have been produced and some of its most
prominent institutions of medicine and learning have been
established to honor him.
</P>
<P>
   Even the calendar changed to mark his birth. The celebrations
that will mark the beginning of the year 2000 will actually
acknowledge an anniversary of that event. Groups ranging from small
survivalist sects to the Roman Catholic Church are gearing up for
the moment.
</P>
<P>
   It all began in a small Middle Eastern town.
</P>
<P>
   ``The early Christians did not believe that the time and place
of the birth of Jesus had been left to chance,'' writes church
historian Justo L. Gonzalez of Decatur, author of ``The Story of
Christianity.'' ``On the contrary, they saw the hand of God
preparing the advent of Jesus in all events prior to the birth, and
in all the historical circumstances around it.''
</P>
<P>
   Jesus was born at a crossroads, historically and geographically.
Palestine back then was at the intersection of trade routes joining
Egypt with Mesopotamia and Asia Minor with Arabia. As a result, it
was often invaded.
</P>
<P>
   In the late first century B.C., Palestine was a ``rustic,
despised corner'' of the Roman Empire, Gonzalez said. A few hundred
years before, people had lived in city-states that determined their
identity, including their religion. But with the Roman Empire came
interaction of cultures and a new mobility.
</P>
<P>
   The time of Jesus' birth ``was a time of confused identities,
similar to now,'' Gonzalez said. ``Christianity came into that
fray.''
</P>
<P>
   It arose as a renewal movement within Palestinian Judaism.
Jesus' earliest followers saw their role as fulfilling the promises
of God, Yahweh, to Israel.
</P>
<P>
   The gospels of the Christian Bible say God performed miracles
through Jesus, beginning with his birth to a virgin and ending with
his resurrection after death. Perhaps one of the most amazing is
the growth of the faith that worships him. From 12 disciples,
according to Biblical accounts, it has increased to nearly 2
billion followers. One out of three people identifies with some
branch of Christianity.
</P>
<P>
   Although the exact date of Jesus's birth is unknown and
generally estimated to have occurred between 3 and 6 B.C., the
coming of the year 2000 still has great symbolism for Christians,
Gonzalez said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very good time for reflection, for recollection, for
thanksgiving and for repentance,`` he said. ``Every once in a while
you need to go back to your origins.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-31-98 0935EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981231.0104 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-31 09:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3223 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MILLENNIUM-SYRIAC-COX     12-31 0863
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILLENNIUM-SYRIAC-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EMBARGOED UNTIL SATURDAY, JANUARY 2. DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN.
 &HT;    RESENDING FOR THOSE WHO NEED IT
 &HT;    Few remain to speak `the Lord's language'
 &HT;    By Larry Kaplow
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ They still speak the language of Jesus Christ, but
few are left in the land where Jesus once walked.
</P>
<P>
   The Syrian Orthodox Christian community is so small that
observers question whether its traditions will continue to exist
here.
</P>
<P>
   Based in Damascus, Syria, communities of followers can be found
from Iraq to New Jersey. But what's left now in the land where
Jesus lived is a tight-knit, highly skilled community of between
1,500 to 3,000 in Jerusalem and Bethlehem.
</P>
<P>
   Should this group disperse, the Holy Land would be a little less
Christian _ and a lot less colorful.
</P>
<P>
   They are known for their ancient language, which they chant in
church and that older Syrian Orthodox still speak in their homes.
They are famous for their bagpipe parades, which they began a few
decades ago just to get some recognition.
</P>
<P>
   Recognition is essential in a region where religion is the most
important factor in peoples' identity. It usually determines with
whom they socialize and to whom they can turn for help.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am a deacon (in the church) but I am not religious. I have
to be involved in the church. It's a presence,'' said Syrian
Orthodox Elia Ahou, 39. ``You have to show that there are some
people in the community. We have to fight for our presence as
Syrians, and as Christians.''
</P>
<P>
   Ahou, an assistant hotel manager, sees his community facing a
squeeze similar to other Christians, a small minority in a land
dominated by Muslims and Jews. But, unlike other churches, the
Syrian Orthodox own little church land and have few institutions to
call their own.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, they are fighting for Jerusalem, the Muslims and the
Jews, and we are left with nothing,'' he said. ``At least we have
the holy sites, which show that we are part of this.''
</P>
<P>
   The focal point of Jerusalem's Syrian Orthodox community is its
St. Mark's Monastery, with a small, elegant church that is located
over what they believe was the house of the Virgin Mary and the
site of the Last Supper.
</P>
<P>
   Go to the daily Mass at the Church of St. Mark, surrounded since
the 1967 war by Jewish housing in Jerusalem's walled Old City, and
the clergy might outnumber the congregants. Their ceremony can seem
stern and intimidating. They chant in Aramaic and the bearded
clergy wear tight black hoods embroidered with small white crosses
for each of the 12 apostles.
</P>
<P>
   But afterward even a stranger might be able to sip tea in the
courtyard with the archbishop.
</P>
<P>
   On Sundays, several dozen show up at their cave-like chapel
behind the tomb of Christ in the Church of the Holy Sepulcher. It
is one of several chapels within the church.
</P>
<P>
   Some Syrian Orthodox speak in Aramaic. Sounding a little like
Hebrew, this is a modern form of the classic language spoken
throughout the Middle East in Jesus' time. Like a few other
denominations, the Syrian Orthodox speak the classic Aramaic in
their church ceremonies.
</P>
<P>
   Syrian Orthodox consider their ethnicity as Aramaean and Syrian
and say their lineage goes back to Abraham. Many note that, as they
were born here, they are also Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   The Syrian heyday in Jerusalem may have been during the Crusader
reign starting in 1099. What is now known as the Jewish Quarter of
the Old City was then called the Syrian Quarter.
</P>
<P>
   As late as 1915, there may have been 1,000 families in Jerusalem
alone. Now, there are maybe 150 families here and possibly 500 in
Bethlehem.
</P>
<P>
   Bernard Sabella, a researcher who made the last comprehensive
count of Christians here, doubts even those figures. He put the
total number of Syrian Orthodox at about 1,500 in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Emigration has taken its toll as the Syrian Orthodox escape the
troubled region. Like other Christians, they lost land and houses
to Israel in the 1948 and 1967 wars. The economy has been
perennially depressed. The last Syrian Orthodox school in Jerusalem
closed in 1967 and the last one in Bethlehem closed in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   It's especially tempting for Syrian Orthodox to leave. Most have
dozens of family members in other countries. Each speaks several
languages.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is not enough potential in this country,'' said Johnny
Goric, a 25-year-old Syrian Orthodox who speaks six languages and
is the executive chef at a foreign consulate.
</P>
<P>
   He has decided to stay and heads the Syrian Orthodox Club, which
provides activities for young members of the community.
</P>
<P>
   Syrian Orthodox hopes are pinned on the celebrations for the
millennium, when followers from around the world will be encouraged
to visit. They will try to raise money for a 40-unit housing
project and a program to spread Aramaic, or ``the Lord's language''
among their young people _ most of whom have given up the language.
</P>
<P>
   ``You cannot guarantee that what you feel in your heart you can
transfer to the next generation,'' said Jack Khazmo, an organizer
of the effort.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
