<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-31 09:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3224 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MILLENNIUM-SCENES27-C     12-31 1399
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILLENNIUM-SCENES27-COX-resend </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    RESENDING FOR THOSE WHO NEED IT
 &HT;    Ancient sites remain sacred places for Christians
 &HT;    WITH PHOTOS
 &HT;    By Larry Kaplow
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Church of the Nativity
</P>
<P>
   Site of Jesus' birth
</P>
<P>
   Bethlehem _ One must bend when entering the Church of the
Nativity. The large door was made into a small passage centuries
ago, in order to stop raiders from taking horses and carts inside.
Over the past 1,600 years, this church has been built, pillaged,
repaired, fortified, commercialized and, now, enveloped in urban
renewal.
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli army pulled out of the city in late 1995, leaving it
to the Palestinian National Authority.
</P>
<P>
   A mosque sits across the plaza, as this city for decades has
beenmostly a Muslim city. At prayer times, the amplified call from
the minaret reverberates inside the cavernous church.
</P>
<P>
   Now, forklifts and bulldozers lay stones in Manger Square, the
plaza in front of the church that has long been used as a bus
parking lot. The renovations, planned for the tourist boom expected
in 2000, will keep the buses out.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Sirk, a 56-year-old Methodist from Washington, D.C., says
he can imagine the presence of angels, who fanned out across the
surrounding hillsides to announce Christ's birth. ``I feel that my
faith has been strengthened,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The stone church sits over the cave in which Christ is said to
have been born. In that spot now, at the bottom of a small stone
staircase, is a dim cave-like room that houses a shrine. A hole in
the floor lets pilgrims touch the rock.
</P>
<P>
   Pilgrims file through. Some stop to pray, light candles or sing
hymns.
</P>
<P>
   Some are bothered by the construction and the souvenir sellers
outside. But they still find meaning in the church.
</P>
<P>
   The Upper Room
</P>
<P>
   Site of the Last Supper
</P>
<P>
   Bethlehem _ For Oregon Pastor Howard Loyd and his congregants,
this plain room in Jerusalem's Old City is not at all plain.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are common, ordinary, everyday people, but once we are
filled with the Holy Spirit we can change the world,'' he tells the
group from the St. Helen's Assembly of God Church.
</P>
<P>
   They stand in a close circle in the center of what is called by
many, simply, ``The Upper Room.'' They begin praying loudly and
separately, with some raising their hands above their heads.
</P>
<P>
   Part of a complex of 14th-century buildings constructed on
foundations more than 1,600 years old, the rectangular room has
vaulted ceilings, bare white walls and a plain stone floor. It
looks like it could be a large dining room.
</P>
<P>
   Many believe it to mark the location of Christ's Last Supper.
It's considered a ``traditional site,'' meaning that it is accepted
more by custom than by evidence.
</P>
<P>
   It is also believed by many to be the site where Christ sent the
Holy Spirit to descend upon his disciples during the Pentecost. The
event prompted the disciples to begin speaking in tongues, in the
language-- of all nations.
</P>
<P>
   Groups of Pentecostal Christians still, in their fervor, speak
in tongues in this room. The loud, bubbly, utterances echo off the
bare walls.
</P>
<P>
   Below this room is the traditional site of the Tomb of David,
the Jewish king. While Pentecostals exult above, Hasidic Jews, with
their side curls and hats, rock their heads in silent prayer facing
David's supposed resting place.
</P>
<P>
   Yardinit _ The Jordan River
</P>
<P>
   Site of Jesus' baptism
</P>
<P>
   Near the Jordan River _ There are lines most afternoons, people
wading their way through the railings and chains on the submerged
stone platform of this river.
</P>
<P>
   Only about 20 yards wide, this is near where the slow river
forms from the Sea of Galilee. Tall eucalyptus trees form a canopy
over the banks.
</P>
<P>
   But this is not a quiet spot. Groups from Canada, Great Britain,
and West Palm Beach, Fla., are being baptized today. The Canadians
shout ``Hallelujah,'' and the families of the British people
getting baptized sing gospel music with enthusiastic precision.
</P>
<P>
   A plaque says Christ was baptized near here. The original site,
near Jericho on the Jordanian border, was often too dangerous for
foreign pilgrims. So an Israeli kibbutz, a collective farm,
established this spot further north.
</P>
<P>
   Now, for $6 in the gift shop you can rent a white robe and a
towel, stand in line with your local pastor, and duck back in the
water of the Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your baptism is an expression of your personal relationship
with God,'' Pastor Keith Thomas told his congregants from the First
Baptist Church of West Palm Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Pam Wingate, of Wellington, Fla., came with her mother, husband
and two children. ``It's going to make my spiritual walk even
closer to the Lord,'' she said, dripping from the head-to-toe
immersion.
</P>
<P>
   Garden Tomb
</P>
<P>
   Site that many Protestants believe was the scene of the
crucifixion and burial of Christ
</P>
<P>
   Jerusalem _ Behind the wall on this busy street, the rumble of
buses is somehow replaced by the chirping of birds that flutter
among the olive, cypress and mustard trees. It's a large garden,
hilly enough to divide into small areas of valleys and peaks.
</P>
<P>
   In one plateau, with large umbrellas and benches, members of an
American church group testify to their feelings.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a long-haired, drug-abusing hippie boy,'' one husky man
announced, ``I never thought I'd live to see a day like this.''
</P>
<P>
   The site of the crucifixion can be seen from a raised deck that
overlooks a gritty outdoor bus terminal. Somewhere amid what is now
blacktop, legend has it, the cross was planted.
</P>
<P>
   A guide explains that the Romans crucified people at busy
crossroads, so this spot was probably ugly in Christ's time, too.
</P>
<P>
   On the other end of the garden, a room is carved out of a rock
cliff and inside, an indentation carved in the floor is thought to
be the place Christ's body was buried. A sign on the door states,
``He is not here, for He is risen.''
</P>
<P>
   Cesar Padilla, 63-year-old pastor at the First Hispanic Baptist
Church of Jonesboro, enters and kneels facing the stone slab. After
a couple minutes, he emerges, with a white handkerchief, wiping
tears from his eyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's such a beautiful experience to see the place where he was
laid, and that he didn't stay there, and that he is very much
alive,'' the Georgia man said. ``I thanked the Lord for the victory
he had over death and for the victory that is ours.''
</P>
<P>
   Church of the Holy Sepulcher
</P>
<P>
   Traditional Catholic, Orthodox site of Jesus' crucifixion and
tomb
</P>
<P>
   Jerusalem _ Packed amid the markets and mosques of Jerusalem's
walled Old City, the Church of the Holy Sepulcher creates a vast,
complex, universe of its own.
</P>
<P>
   The high, metal and wooden door is the only passage in or out.
After four years, the Israeli government has persuaded the
denominations that share the church to agree to an emergency door.
They guard their space jealously and to the letter of a
centuries-old treaty. For centuries, the key to the church has been
entrusted to an impartial, Muslim family.
</P>
<P>
   The church was first built by the Greek Orthodox in 335 A.D. It
was destroyed and rebuilt twice. The current structure has been
there about 800 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is not a stone or an arch or a corner that does not have
a legend or tradition,'' Israeli tour guide Josef Gilboa said.
</P>
<P>
   The dim, ornate church is a conglomeration of large sanctuaries
ringed by small chapels. Upon entering, there is a smooth stone
slab marking where, according to believers, Jesus' body was
prepared for burial.
</P>
<P>
   Up a steep staircase to the right is the elaborate, some say
gaudy, shrine covering the rock where the cross was planted. Jesus'
tomb is back downstairs, inside a small structure of deteriorating
rock now held in place by a cage of girders.
</P>
<P>
   There are many passages, chapels and levels. Many pilgrims do
not like the gaudy look of the chandeliers. Some resent the
infighting between the denominations inside. But the church
impresses, despite itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just an area of significance, you can feel it in the
air,'' Alan Howard, a 20-year-old psychology student at Morehouse
College in Atlanta, said on a recent visit. He does not care about
the garish decoration. The atmosphere is more important.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about God and religion,'' he said. ``There's a religious
feeling in the air.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
