</P>
<P>
   DAY2-RESOLUTIONS _ It's Day 2 of the Big Resolution, and you're
determined to keep it this time. So throw out the rest of the
holiday sweets, put on your sneakers and sweats, and ... sit down
and read a book _ one that will tell you how to succeed. (Kim,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) FOR SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   PARTY-ETIQUETTE _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ How to out-snob the
snobs at parties; from tips on tipping to ordering wine to table
talk. (Grantham, Palm Beach Post) MOVED FOR FRIDAY
</P>
<P>
   SIBLEY-COLUMN _ A form of New Year's festivity which has ever
puzzled me is the ``watch party.'' What, I used to wonder, when we
assembled at the country church on New Year's Eve, were we watching
for? Some of us would rush outside and stand, shivering in the
unexpected South Alabama cold, peering at the sky. We never saw
anything to mark the end of the 12 months and usher in a new
beginning. But we felt duty-bound to watch. (Sibley, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) FOR FRIDAY
</P>
<P>
   WARNER-ON-WOOD _ (Warner, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) FOR
SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   ALLSTARS _ Christmas is over, the tree is down, and maybe even
the house is clean for the first time since the holday madness
began. It's time to think spring and how you can spiff up the lawn
and garden. If you haven't placed your order for new seeds and
plants, it's not too late. And just what will be the hottest plants
on the market this spring? Thet new All-American All Stars, the
cream of the crop for new introductions, are out and just in time
for winter planting. We take a look at other new plants on sale
now. (Flanders, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) FOR SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   MARTIN-STYLE _ ATLANTA _ On Sundays he's a Dirty Bird. During
the remainder of the week, however, Atlanta Falcons wide receiver
Tony Martin acts more like a peacock. Ask Martin, the 14-2 Falcons'
second-leading receiver this season, who the best-dressed player on
the team is and he'll respond, nonchalantly, ``Myself.'' (Walton,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) FOR SUNDAY
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-MILLENNIUM _ How did you usher in 1999? Was Thursday
night another New Year's Eve of lukewarm pink Champale, slightly
scorched Jiffy Pop and Dick Clark on the tube? Hey, that's OK.
We're not passing judgment here. But no way is that going to cut it
come next New Year's Eve, when people worldwide will be partying
like it's, well, 2000. You need to start making your millennium
travel plans now. Already, the resorts at Walt Disney World in
Orlando are booked. Many cruises and hotels have been full for ages
_ London's Savoy Hotel started getting reservation requests 10
years ago. (Hamilton, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) WITH
ILLUSTRATION FOR SUNDAY
</P>
<P>
   MILLENNIUM-FORYOU _ Web site and info (Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) FOR SUNDAY
</P>
<P>
   MILLENNIUM-SOUTH _ Southerners who want to attend a memorable
millennium party that's close to home do have a few options,
ranging from a swank Memphis ball to a down-home blowout at
Opryland. Here are a few hot Dixie destinations for New Year's Eve
1999. (Hamilton, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) FOR SUNDAY
</P>
<P>
   AMERICANBEACH _ AMERICAN BEACH, Fla. _ On a blustery December
day, the village of American Beach, Fla. is so deserted it seems
almost haunted. If there are ghosts about, they are friendly ones
for MaVynee Betsch, the colorful, exuberant, unofficial mayor of
what was once one of America's few all-black beach resorts. A new
book by Atlanta native Russ Rymer, ``American Beach: A Saga of
Race, Wealth and Memory,'' celebrates Betsch's family, their role
in founding American Beach and the unique part the town has played
in African-American history and culture. (Williams, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) FOR SUNDAY
</P>
<P>
   SIBLEY-COLUMN _ Years ago I used to think only country and
smalltown people gathered when one of their number was in a
hospital. I understood because we in Creola regarded a trip to the
hospital as major, on a par with a trip to Roche Mortuary, the
final stop in many lives. City people are usually different, I
think . There are so many hospitals and so many doctors and it's
not always a grave, death-dealing malady that sends you to either.
But I tell you the country custom of relatives gathering can't be
beat. The other day I had an appointment at Piedmont hospital for
some tests, nothing fearsome, no drastic surgery, nothing
threatening. But my family decided I needed backup. (Sibley,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) FOR SUNDAY
</P>
<P>
   DULL-TASTE _ With a name like Dull, she had to be good. And she
was. Henrietta Stanley Dull _ plain old Mrs. Dull to the
generations of Southerners who took her classes and clipped her
newspaper recipes _ wrote just one cookbook during a long life that
began before Sherman marched through Georgia and ended after King
marched on Washington. It was a homely-looking volume, with a
matronly silhouette of the author, drawn by her daughter, on the
cover. Yet ``Southern Cooking'' was for much of this century the
definitive treatise on the subject. Seventy years after its 1928
publication, you can still find it at bookstores in a new printing
by Cherokee Publishing Co., the South's own Fannie Farmer
continuing to admonish cooks not to pour gravy over their fried
chicken. (Auchmutey, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) WITH
ILLUSTRATION FOR SUNDAY
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS
</P>
<P>
   REVIEW-IMAX _ ``T-Rex,'' new IMAX movie opening Jan. 1 at some
Imax theaters. (Ringel, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) FOR FRIDAY
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-MINIREVIEWS _ Mini reviews of all currently playing
movies. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED FOR FRIDAY.
</P>
<P>
   LATINROCK _ The rock en espanol movement is taking off, as
Spanish-language rock bands _ from Mexico, South America and
suburban Atlanta _ become a force to reckon with. A look at what's
shaping up as a cultural revolution, with bands such as Mana,
Bloque, Mandorico, Molotov, Los Amigos Invisibles, Cafe Tacuba and
others. (Dollar, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) FOR SUNDAY
</P>
<P>
   SKUBE-BOOKS _ Michael Skube's books column is not running this
week.
</P>
<P>
   REVIEW-ELVIS _ Review of Peter Guralnick's ``Careless Love: The
Unmaking of Elvis Presley.'' (Dollar, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
FOR SUNDAY
</P>
<P>
   REVIEW-MARILYN _ Review of Barbara Leaming's bio of Marilyn
Monroe. (Longino, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) FOR SUNDAY
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION
</P>
<P>
   Cox eds: This package will be the CoxNet Focus page for the
weekend of Jan. 9:
</P>
<P>
   MILLENNIUM-FUTURE _ BETHLEHEM, West Bank _ There is a new trend
in this old city. For about a year, Christians have been putting
crosses, usually lit electrically, on their homes and shops. It is
largely seen as a sign of a population that is free, but is a
minority and feels insecure. Christians are a divided minority. In
Israel, Arab Christians benefit from a healthier economy and some
even serve in the Israeli army. In Palestinian areas, they face a
military occupation and a stagnant economy _ driving many to
emigrate to the United States. But, 2000 years after it was founded
here, it would be a mistake to predict Christianity's demise in the
Holy Land. (Kaplow, Cox News Service) 25.
</P>
<P>
   MILLENNIUM-SYRIAC _ JERUSALEM _ Two thousand years later, you
can still
</P>
<P>
   hear the language. About 3,000 Syriac Christians cling to their
lifestyle in the walled city of Jerusalem and still practice
religion in Aramaic, the language of Christ. (Kaplow, Cox News
Service) 20.
</P>
<P>
   MILLENNIUM-AMERICA _ Two thousand years after Jesus's birth, the
relationship between his native people, the Jews, and his
followers, the Christians, is complex. Some evangelical Christians
are Zionists, believing that the Temple in Jerusalem must be
rebuilt so that Jesus can come again. But some of these same people
think they must proselytize the Jews. A look at American Christian
attitudes toward Israel and its people. (White, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) 30.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE/MEDICINE
</P>
<P>
   RIVER-RESTORE _ HABERSHAM COUNTY, Ga. _ Severe erosion along the
Soque River was causing the loss of100 tons of soil a year on
Justin Savage's farm in Habersham County in North Georgia. The soil
was washing into the Soque, a tributary of the Chattahoochee River,
making the stream unfit for fish and destroying its natural beauty.
Now, an intensive project by EPA and environmental groups is
restoring the natural flow of the river and the native vegetation
to bring the stream back to life. Already, native brown trout have
returned to the stream. Seabrook. The project is being watched
closely by water experts around the Southeast as an example how a
degraded river can be restored. (Seabrook, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) FOR SUNDAY
</P>
<P>
   AUS-ELECTRONIC-TONGUE _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Big companies want it to
test new food and drink products. The American military has
something more distasteful in mind: monitoring the disposal of
chemical and biological weapons. Competing with them to pick the
first practical and profitable use of an electronic tongue invented
at the University of Texas are four UT graduate business students
who won't get their degrees until May. (Stanley, Austin
American-Statesman) FOR SUNDAY
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
