<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-31 11:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3300 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHILDCARE-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      12-31 1557
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILDCARE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BETTER THINKING THROUGH PLAYING? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA F. MELTZ  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   To help my fifth-grade son study for a test, we head to the
playroom. While he executes soccer drills with an indoor ball, I
drill him on Colonial American history.
</P>
<P>
   Skeptical about this as a way to help a child prepare for a
test? I was at first, too. But I've stuck with it for two reasons.
First, it's fun. For Eli, anything that involves a ball is fun by
definition, even if he has to study at the same time. For me, it's
fun because the struggle is gone; I don't have to cajole,
negotiate, or threaten to get him to concentrate.
</P>
<P>
   I'm also testing out a theory.
</P>
<P>
   We've known for years that exercise is linked to fitness. With
children's obesity on the rise in the United States _ 14 percent of
6- to 11-year-olds were overweight in 1994, almost double the
number from the previous reporting period, according to the
National Center for Health Statistics _ parents have more reason
than ever to be concerned about diet and exercise. Indeed, a recent
study shows obesity can strike even our youngest children: 32
percent of preschoolers in a Florida Head Start program are obese,
according to Betsy Hernandez, a researcher at the University of
Florida.
</P>
<P>
   We've also known for generations that young children are more
cooperative and attentive after they run around.
</P>
<P>
   But now there's reason to think exercise does more than burn off
calories or burn up energy. The latest brain research indicates
that the more children move the body, the more they stimulate the
brain. In other words, exercise has the potential to increase
learning.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an area of research that parents and teachers aren't
sufficiently aware of,'' says educational psychologist, researcher,
and author Jane Healy of Vail, Colo. She says the brain and body
are not independent systems, but have connections that strengthen
each other. ``When you stimulate the cerebellum (through exercise),
you make your child smarter,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Healy sees physical movement as the gateway to cognitive
learning almost from birth. ``The infant who uses her hands to grab
something is learning not only how to get a toy into her mouth, but
also that persistence pays off. She's learning about space, time,
and cause and effect.''
</P>
<P>
   In the toddler and preschool years, a physical response to music
has been linked to reading and math skills. ``Music actually helps
organize the brain,'' says Healy, who is author of ``Endangered
Minds: Why Our Children Don't Think and What We Can Do About It''
and ``Failure to Connect'' (Simon &AMP; Schuster).
</P>
<P>
   The benefits of movement don't just accrue to young children.
Researcher Olga Jarrett of Georgia State University says
schoolchildren are better able to pay attention after they
exercise.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent study of fourth graders in an urban school, she
observed children who had recess some days but not others.
</P>
<P>
   ``On days when they don't have recess, the teacher's giving a
lesson and you look around the room and you see children half out
of the seat, swinging their legs, playing with their hair,'' she
says. Some children are more antsy than others, but all children
fidgeted at some point, she says. This inability to focus is
dramatically reduced on days when children had the chance to get
outside and play.
</P>
<P>
   Does this actually translate to more learning?
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett can only prove that lack of exercise correlates to
increased fidgeting but she's persuaded enough about the impact on
learning to be preparing a report urging this school to have daily
recess.
</P>
<P>
   Healy says recess is critical. ``Hanging from the monkey bars
actually helps reading skills,'' she says, because it stimulates
the cerebellum, which is responsible for balance as well as
language and higher-level thinking skills.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Exercise also changes the chemical balance in the brain to make
it more efficient, according to research at the National Institutes
of Health by neurochemist Candice Pert. This may account for why
children are happier after exercise.
</P>
<P>
   Not just any exercise will do, however. While gym and team
sports may give children cardiovascular activity that keeps them
fit and trim, it appears that only spontaneous exercise/play like
street hockey or double-dutch jump rope provides brain connections
that stimulate learning. ``In PE (physical education) and on teams,
it's adult-directed. Plus in PE, half the time can be spent waiting
your turn,'' says Jarrett. Her report will argue for both PE and
recess.
</P>
<P>
   Even solitary exercise has a lot going for it. Look at all Healy
says happens when a child is simply throwing a ball against a
pitch-back:
</P>
<P>
   --Since he's probably playing an imaginary game in his head,
there's self-monitoring going on, which builds the frontal lobes, a
big part of the attention system.
</P>
<P>
   --As he tries to calibrate his movements to change the way the
ball goes, he's helping to coordinate sensory systems in the back
of the brain, which are important for reading, writing, and math
skills.
</P>
<P>
   --If he messes up, there's an immediate consequence, so he's
learning about cause and effect, which involves the brain's
association areas.
</P>
<P>
   --If he's enjoying it, he's feeling successful and powerful,
which means chemicals in the brain are flowing in a positive way;
that will influence mood and make him feel better when he comes
inside to do homework.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez, who observed preschoolers' exercise patterns in
central Florida, urges parents to look at how children play in day
care. ``When they go out on the playground, are they getting pushed
on the merry-go-round and the swing or are they encouraged to run
around?'' she asks.
</P>
<P>
   She says even at this young age, children can develop sedentary
habits that set a pattern for the rest of their lives, affecting
weight patterns and mental acuity.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez worries not only about the kind of exercise children
get but the amount of exercise they aren't getting because they
spend so much time in front of TV and computer screens.
Pediatrician Joseph Hagan Jr. of Burlington, Vt., shares that
concern and makes it a point to talk to children of all ages about
the importance of exercise.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell them it should be fun, that they should run around with
their buddies and laugh,'' he says. ``But I also tell them that for
it to qualify as good exercise, they need to run enough so they
have to stop and catch their breath.''
</P>
<P>
   While the predominant reason Hagan recommends exercise is for
health and fitness, he doesn't doubt the benefits vigorous movement
has on mood _ he calls it ``emotional cleansing'' _ or that it
carries over to other activities like academics.
</P>
<P>
   William Dietz, director of the division of Nutrition and
Physical Activity at the Centers for Disease Control and
Prevention, agrees exercise and learning are related, even though
data are relatively new. His conviction is at least partly
influenced by his son. ``He needed to be physically active before
he could sit down and learn,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   I'm pretty convinced, too. My son is having a terrific academic
year. I can't prove that exercising while studying is part of the
reason why, but who's to say it's not?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
TIPS FOR PARENTS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --Researchers say latchkey children are among those who get the
least exercise. Even if they play a team sport, be sure to provide
time and opportunity for physical play that is child-directed.
Children who are home-schooled also may be at risk if parents don't
value exercise or allow for free play.
</P>
<P>
   --Unless it's unusually severe, cold weather is not a reason to
keep children from playing outside as long as they are dressed
properly. Children under 5 need one more layer of clothing than an
adult.
</P>
<P>
   --Movement therapy is critical for children who are physically
disabled, not only for medical reasons but also because it can
provide stimulation for the brain.
</P>
<P>
   -- Parents' exercise is a powerful model for children. How much
and what kind of exercise do you get?
</P>
<P>
   --Can you answer yes to these questions about your child's
exercise: Does she get at least an hour of exercise a day? Does she
have fun? In the course of a week, is at least some play
child-directed, not teacher- or coach-directed? Is at least some of
it what we would consider old-fashioned play: climbing a tree,
jumping rope, riding a bike, chasing, running, throwing?
</P>
<P>
   --Encourage your teen to continue to exercise beyond
participation in a team sport. Even at this age, there are still
mental and physical benefits to be had from exercise.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AFTERTHOUGHT _ Children with two or more siblings benefit from
having a place in the house where they can be alone, even if it's
just to experience peace and quiet. Some families build quiet time
into the family routine. (From ``365 ways to raise Great Kids'' by
Sheila Ellison and Barbara Ann Barnett, Sourcebooks Inc.).
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Barbara Meltz's e-mail address is meltz(at)globe.com. Her
columns are now on line at Boston.Com, keyword ``parenting.'' For
photocopies of past columns, send a self-addressed, stamped
envelope to Barbara F. Meltz, The Boston Globe, Box 2378, Boston,
MA 02107-2378. Please specify the column.)
</P>
</TEXT>
