<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRJOY-COLUMN-$ADV08-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAN ONE LOVE TWO MEN AT ONCE? 
 FOR USE FRI., JAN. 8, OR ANYTIME THEREAFTER.
</HEADLINE>
  By DR. JOY BROWNE 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   QUESTION: Is it possible to love two men at the same time? I
just heard from my ex-boyfriend (we broke-up over three years ago)
and I learned we still have feelings for each other. But it's awful
because I'm in another relationship (for one year) with a guy I
don't want to lose. How can I make a decision when I have feelings
for both? _ Ithaca, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   DR. JOY: Of course it is possible to love two people at the same
time. We love our friends, our children, our parents. But you want
to know if you can be in a relationship with two men at the same
time. And given the fact you are single, the answer is a qualified
yes.
</P>
<P>
   However, there are some problems with your question: Number one,
it sounds to me that your old boyfriend is a long-distance
relationship, which is poison, since it is primarily fantasy, and
number two, the current guy is compelling but not preemptive--not
enough to wipe the ex from your memory banks.
</P>
<P>
   How about taking a deep breath and evaluating Mr. Right
Now--your current relationship. If it seems to be working for you,
tell the ex-boyfriend that you would like to talk to him in a year
or so and see where you are then. Meanwhile, pour all energy into
your present relationship. If, after six months, it still lacks
luster, tell the current guy you need time off to see other people.
</P>
<P>
   It is possible to love two people at the same time; it is
possible to date two people; but it is impossible to be mated to
more than one.
</P>
<P>
   QUESTION: I'm 50 years old, married, with two children. For as
long as I can remember I've had a huge problem with my mother. She
is hard of hearing (and deals with it as one long pity party) and
is obsessed with her religion to the point that any conversation
leads quickly to a fire-and -brimstone sermon.
</P>
<P>
   She has been to a therapist. It didn't help because she refuses
to believe anything is wrong with her. I have been to a therapist
to help me deal with her. One of the strategies I've tried is to
set limits on the topics we may discuss, but in a short time she
disregards any limits and goes ahead regardless of who's feeling
she may hurt.
</P>
<P>
   I have tried to talk, write, send smoke signals, any method to
communicate with her so she'll stop this preaching and try and be
more of a mother. Because she's deaf, talking to her only ends up
in frustration.
</P>
<P>
   What more can I do? _ Ann Arbor, Mich.
</P>
<P>
   DR. JOY: Listen, kiddo, you are a 50-year-old 15-year-old. Part
of you still wants mom's attention and approval. You mom is smart
enough to get attention from you by being obnoxious. She has
probably been hard of hearing for a number of years but like most
of us, she hears what she wants to hear.
</P>
<P>
   Don't try to get her to change. Change your behavior. When she
talks about religion say ``If you don't stop, I will leave the room
for five minutes or hang up.'' Then don't back down. The issue is
to set limits and stick to them without being nasty, weepy, sullen
or sarcastic. Try being a bit more of a grown-up and see if she
doesn't follow suit.
</P>
<P>
   QUESTION: My 5-year-old granddaughter has been living with me
for most of her life. My son is her father; he never married the
girl's mother, who left her here with me in Seattle to go off to
school and then to Reno, Nevada. We have maintained a decent
relationship over the years, and I have made sure that my
granddaughter has contact with her mother.
</P>
<P>
   Now she's married and settled, and has another daughter, 8
months old, and tells me she wants to raise the two girls together.
I'm devastated, naturally, but I also want to do the best thing for
my granddaughter. What should I do? _ Seattle, Wash.
</P>
<P>
   A: It's a tough situation _ and not uncommon. It sounds like
your custody was an informal rather than a legal arrangement. And
in all fairness it seems your pseudo-daughter-in-law has gotten her
act together. In the long run it's best that she and her child live
together.
</P>
<P>
   Start your granddaughter with extended visits with her mom. Have
a therapist involved (split the cost equally) and see what happens
between the 5-year-old and her mom. It will help your granddaughter
to feel that her mom wants her, even though it will bruise your
heart.
</P>
<P>
   You will have time of your own with the child. In the next 10
years or so, I would not be surprised if she lands on your doorstep
again. In any event, you will never really lose her.
</P>
<P>
   -0-
</P>
<P>
   Questions may be sent to Dr. Joy Browne, c/o The New York Times
Syndication Sales Corp., 122 E. 42nd St., New York, NY 10168, or to
drjoy &LR; nytsyn.com. Questions of general interest will be answered in
this weekly column. Dr. Joy regrets that unpublished letters cannot
be answered individually.
</P>
