<HEADER>
A3311 &Cx1f; ttf-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BONG-BULL-NYT &LR;      12-31 1353
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BONG-BULL-NYT </SLUG>
  
 No. 500 for Dec. 31  
<TEXT>
<P>
   For Dec. 31, 1998. With only one more year until the big party,
the Burned-Out Newspapercreatures Guild advises getting those
vacation requests filed early or you'll be kissing the slot man to
celebrate the year 2000, and this is BONG Bull No. 500!
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHAT THEY WON'T DO TO GET INTO BONG'S 500TH. &LR;  Gerard Farrell,
who defected from the trade to take up arms in Texas A&AMP;M's
publicity office, recalled these possibly factual tales from the
newsroom:
</P>
<P>
   ``Our night city editor was formatting the police blotter one
evening and called me over to his desk. He'd gotten a grand jury
wrap-up from a bureau reporter in a county with a large Asian
population and wondered about the ethnicity of an
as-yet-unapprehended suspected crack dealer, based on the name.
Seems the list included a certain `Fnu Mnu Lnu,' which I pointed
out was actually cop shorthand for `First Name Unknown, Middle Name
Unknown, Last Name Unknown.'''
</P>
<P>
   Also from the cutting room floor, this story never made it into
Farrell's clip file:
</P>
<P>
   ``A police patrol sergeant offering the final, official, word on
the circumstances of a motor-vehicle accident: 'Vehicle No. 1 was
traveling westbound and vehicle No. 2, traveling northbound, ran
the red light and T-boned her ass.'''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ANOTHER TRIP DOWN MEMORY LANE. &LR;  Emery Jeffreys, web developer
for Modis Government Systems Division and ex of the Daytona Beach
News- Journal, ex Unipresser and other exes, advises all to forget
the dramas of the freight elevator.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do any of the young newsies remember chases? How about
rattling the chases that were not stored on turtles to see where
the floor man had his pint?''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPECIAL THANKS TO MIKE LINKSVAYER. &LR;  Getting to the 500th BONG
Bull would have been an even mightier chore but for the devotion of
our list wallah Mike Linksvayer of San Francisco, keeper of the
keys to the bewildering listserv software. Mike gets the message
out, sorts the ins and outs and catches all the bounces, and we're
grateful for his expertise and faithful service.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; IT'S ALL HOW YOU SAY IT. &LR;  Carissa Vanitzian discovers an
anagram, one of those curiosities that come of rearranging the
letters in a word, name or phrase to form new ones. Computer
software makes the game easy, and the Internet brings the world's
anagramists together. Consider this passage, its discoverer
uncredited:
</P>
<P>
   ``In one of the Bard's best-thought-of tragedies, our insistent
hero, Hamlet, queries on two fronts about how life turns rotten.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the dowdiest 11th-grade English teacher would give extra
credit for bringing the news that the anagram is almost as good as
Shakespeare's original:
</P>
<P>
   ``To be or not to be: that is the question, whether tis nobler
in the mind to suffer the slings and arrows of outrageous fortune
...''
</P>
<P>
   Or startle a simpler teacher, say algebra, with this anagram:
``Eleven plus two'' equals ``twelve plus one.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHERE BAD WRITING COMES FROM. &LR;  The collection in BONG Bull No.
498 wasn't by high school students, but by Washington Post readers
for a Style section contest a year or so ago. Once again, Internet
traffic peels off attributions of all things in record time. Thanks
for the tip to Thom Newlin, who adds, ``Keep up the good work,
season's greetings, and Happy New Year Y2K-1!''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THREATS DON'T FAZE US, MOSTLY. &LR;  Bill Tammeus, the Kansas City
(Mo.) Star's other genius, dropped a bag of Scrabble tiles and this
fell out:
</P>
<P>
   ``Be alerted: If my alma mater, the Missouri School of
Journalism, isn't mentioned in the historic 500th edition of BONG
Bull, I will not read it _ even to see if Missouri is mentioned.
And, though I cannot speak for all Mizzou folk, I bet I will not be
alone in my one-week boycott. Wishing you an excellent new year
full of wise choices, I remain, Your obedient servant, Bill
Tammeus, MU BJ '67.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; IN THE WORLD OF THE MOVIES. &LR;  From the United Kingdom, a
computerist named Emma notes a number of truths we learn from
watching movies. Others are invited to add to her list:
</P>
<P>
   All police investigations require at least one trip to a strip
club. All U.S. phone numbers begin with 555. All beds have special
L-shaped cover sheets that reach up to the armpit on a woman but
only to waist of the man beside her.
</P>
<P>
   And, once applied, lipstick will never rub off even while scuba
diving. The ventilation system of any building is the perfect
hiding place. You won't survive a battle if you show someone a
picture of your sweetheart back home. The Eiffel Tower can be seen
from any window in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   And, a man will show no pain while taking a ferocious beating
but will wince when a woman tries to clean his wounds. When staying
in a haunted house, women investigate every strange noise in their
most revealing underwear. Cars that crash almost always burst into
flames.
</P>
<P>
   And, a detective can solve a case only after being suspended
from duty. When alone, all foreigners speak English to each other,
but with an accent. You can always find a chainsaw when you need
one. Travel between any two points in New York City requires
passing the Statue of Liberty, Lincoln Center, Washington Square
Park and the New York Public Library.
</P>
<P>
   Suggest others at Emma(at)mcbridee.freeserve.co.uk
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OTHERS. &LR;  All reporters wear dirty trenchcoats, run impossible
bar tabs, have strings of shoeshine boys as snitches, dodge
multiple ex-spouses and at least two current lovers, jump the staff
car waiting list by sweet-talking the keys clerk, keep bourbon in
the lower drawer, live on cold coffee and malted milk balls, and
have drop-kicked at least four computer terminals into the alley.
How Hollywood gets away with promoting this fiction is outrageous.
In real life it's two computers, max.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMIX SECTION. &LR;  The Further Adventures of Herman ``Speed''
Graphic, Ace Photographer for the Chagrin Falls Commercial
Scimitar, and his Faithful Companion, Typo the Wonder Pig.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PANEL ONE: &LR;  As the evening approaches, the nattily dressed Deft
Duo gather their party toys and prepare for the New Year's
celebration as Typo vows, ``I'm telling you, Boss! At $300 a plate,
nobody from the paper is getting into this party but us!''
</P>
<P>
   Brushing pizza sauce off his trenchcoat, a deathbed gift from an
ancient mystic wire service executive editor on a fog-shrouded
eastern island, Speed frets, ``Hyperba Lee is an evilly resourceful
person, Typo! She didn't get to be Features Editor by following all
the rules!''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PANEL TWO: &LR;  In the luxurious Backwater Room of the Chagrin
Hilton, Typo marvels, ``I was right, Boss! There's nobody here but
bankers, lawyers and large advertisers, and it's easier to get to
the food from the window side of the buffet table if you don't mind
wading in the fountain! Hey, this is our fourth trip through, and
it ain't even midnight yet!''
</P>
<P>
   Munching a skewerful of meatballs, Speed wonders, ``... Large
advertisers, Typo!?''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PANEL THREE: &LR;  Typo spots danger and blurts, ``Features Editor
at 11 o'clock high, Boss! Roll right and get behind the busboy's
cart...!''
</P>
<P>
   Speed despairs, ``She's got the angle on me, and she's using
in-lines! I'm a goner, Typo...!''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PANEL FOUR: &LR;  The panel is obscured by pain stars, huge wet
drops, romantic hearts and huge ugly popout letters reading
``sa-MOOCH!''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PANEL FIVE: &LR;  In the ruins of the butter sculpture of Woody
Hayes and 24 pounds of Buffalo wings, Speed admits, ``We could have
predicted she would talk the rent-to-own furniture guys into
letting her sit at their table, Typo!''
</P>
<P>
   Typo counters, ``Sorry, Boss! But while she's bragging to
everyone at the diversity seminar that she got your first kiss of
'99, we'll be watching to see whose couches and chairs she plays up
in her interior decorating stories!''
</P>
<P>
   Unswayed by bacchanalian temptations (translation: Working on
New Year's Eve), BONG Chief Copyboy Charley Stough, Dayton Daily
News, 45 S. Ludlow St., Dayton, Ohio 45401 salutes NYTNS celebrants
worldwide. E-mail copyboy(at)dma.org. Phone (937) 225-2445 after 5
p.m. eastern. Fax 225-2489.
</P>
</TEXT>
