<HEADER>
A3314 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YEAR-AULD-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAKE-B     12-31 1332
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YEAR-AULD-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 (k and a coding)  
 UNDATED: ... Milli Vanilli.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Classical composers Alfred Schnittke, Earl Kim, and Ivan
Tcherepnin died, as did conductors Michael Tippett and Klaus
Kennstedt; tenor Richard Cassilly, soprano Leonie Rysanek, pianist
Leona DiDomenica, backstage presence Wanda Toscanini Horowitz; and
Shinichi Suzuki, who taught millions how to play the violin. The
Boston Symphony Orchestra mourned Joseph Conte, Patsy Cardillo,
James Whitaker, and Ruth Martin.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Last bows on Broadway
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On Broadway, the lights dimmed for Jerome Robbins, Dorothy
Stickney, Daniel Massey, Laurie Beechman, Theresa Merritt, Joseph
Maher, W. Benson Terry; playwrights Jerome Weidman, Marshall Barer,
Don Petersen, and Robert Marasco; and Roger Stevens, impresario of
Washington's Kennedy Center.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
The small screen set
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Corbett Monica, who died at 68, once predicted that television
would produce ``a comedy version of `Gilligan's Island.''' Flip
Wilson was comedy in its purest, most hilarious form, telling the
truth when he said ``What you see is what you get.'' Henny
Youngman, 91, said, ``Take my wife _ please.'' Jack Lord, 77,
barked, ``Book 'em, Danno!'' E.G. Marshall, 84, exuded more dignity
than real-life lawyers and judges. Esther Rolle, Phil Hartman, and
Peter Lind Hayes left the gift of laughter.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Leeds and Norman Fell did not have famous names but anyone
with a television set knew their faces. They died, as did a whole
supporting cast: Dick O'Neill of ``Cagney and Lacey,'' Mary Frann
of ``Newhart,'' Grandpa Jones of ``Hee Haw,'' Sylvia Field Truex,
Mrs. Wilson on ``Dennis the Menace;'' Richard Paul, the mayor in
``Murder, She Wrote,'' Michelle Thomas of ``The Cosby Show,''
Virginia Graham, a talk-show hostess, and Douglas Fowly, who was
Doc Holliday on ``Wyatt Earp.''
</P>
<P>
   Children's television lost its pioneers: Buffalo Bob Smith,
puppeteer Shari Lewis, Jeffrey Moss of ``Sesame Street,'' and Bob
Trow of ``Mister Rogers' Neighborhood.'' Joan Hickson, 92, was Miss
Marple on the BBC; Michael Zaslow starred on ``One Life to Live;''
and Clayton (Peg Leg) Bates, 91, hoofed on ``The Ed Sullivan
Show.''
</P>
<P>
   Henry Hampton, 58, showed what television could be because he
kept his eyes on the prize. So did Fred W. Friendly, the former CBS
News president, and William Workman, who helped start ``Face the
Nation.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
The world of arts
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Their legacy is their art: photographers Josef Muench and Linda
McCartney; sculptors Beatrice Roffman and Marshall Fredericks;
artists Eric Orr, Paul Strisik, Diane Kemp, Dean Fausett, Marshall
W. Joyce, and Bea Mandelman; and architects Harry Weese, Albert
Frey, Joseph Esherick, Anthony C. Platt, and Ronald L. Mace.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Science
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In science, noted mathematicians Andre Weil and Alberto Calderon
died, as did Nobel laureates Allan MacLeod Cormack, Frederick
Reines, Barton Derek, and George Hitchings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Academia
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The groves of academe mourned Edmund Gullion and William Curry
Moloney of Tufts, Janet Murrow of Mount Holyoke, Thomas Corwin
Mendenhall of Smith, William Griffith of MIT; Charles Donovan, Mya
Maung, and John V. Driscoll of Boston College; and Harvard's Ted
Wilcox, Gareth Green, Mary (Ingraham) Bunting-Smith, David Clarence
McClelland, David Bailey, Ramchandran Jaikumar, and May Cheever.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
The athletic set
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mark Belanger of the Berkshires was nicknamed Blade, a tribute
to his sure passage across the Baltimore infield. Other baseball
stars who died include Hal Newhouser, Dan Quisenberry, Dick Sisler,
Mike Fornieles, Harry Anderson, Jim Turner and Bob Thurman; and
executives Al Campanis and Gabe Paul. From 1960, Billy Sullivan was
the heart of the Patriots. The NFL also mourned Weeb Ewbank, Sid
Luckman, Clyde (Bulldog) Turner, Elijah Pitts, and Lionel Aldridge.
</P>
<P>
   They were the voices of the game: Harry Caray, Bob Starr, and
Jack Brickhouse brought baseball to millions; Win Eliot covered 50
years of sports for radio and television; Ray Scott narrated the
big Green Bay Packer plays; and Don Dunphy was always at ringside
for the big fights.
</P>
<P>
   Archie Moore was a classy boxer; Helen Wills Moody was a tennis
star of the 1920s and '30s; Syl Apps was a center for the Leafs in
their 1940s heyday; the NBA lost Knicks coach Red Holzman, referee
Richie Powers, and Tony Lavelli Jr., who played for the Boston
Celtics, then played his accordion at halftime; football mourned
Doak Walker; and the golfing world lost its Open-winning dentist,
Cary Middlecoff.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
The journalistic set
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The news business wrote obituaries for sportswriters Jim Murray
and Shirley Povich; investigative reporters Jonathan Kwitny,
William Lambert, and Sandy Hume, editors Eric Breindel, Caskie
Stinnett, Norman Isaacs, and Harry Ashmore; Ross Wetzsteon of the
Village Voice; Henry Tanner and Dick Shepard of The New York Times;
CNN's Don Harrison and John Holliman; ABC's Charles Arnot and Lou
Cioffi; Newsweek's Maynard Parker; the Chicago Tribune's Joan Beck
and Jean McGuinness; columnists Joe Harsch, Harriet Van Horne, Mike
McAlary, and Joe Spear; the AP's Tom Seppy and Sam Jones; Donn
Tibbetts of the Manchester Union-Leader, the Herald's Jane McNaney,
the Traveler's Alice Gaimster, Don Wilder of the Patriot Ledger,
John Cook of the Norwood Times, Irving Rogers of the Lawrence
Eagle-Tribune,and John Henry Cutler of the Duxbury Clipper.
</P>
<P>
   Cartoonist Reg Smythe created ``Andy Capp,'' Bob Kane begat
``Batman,'' and Otto Bettmann built archives that provided 10
million news photos.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
The local scene
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In Massachusetts, Frank Sargent brought dignity, humor and
courage to the governor's office. David Nelson, a federal judge,
and Kirk O'Donnell, a Washington lawyer, enriched public life and
their early deaths saddened many. Johnny Powers was among many who
enlivened Massachusetts politics: Tony Scibelli, Fran Doris, Jim
O'Brien, Julian Zuk, John Slater, and Ed O'Neill.
</P>
<P>
   Some who died symbolized their institutions: John Prescott of
the New England Aquarium; Bill Ohrenberger of the Boston school
system; Father Joseph Manton of Mission Church; Bill Carr of the
School Committee; Arthur Curley of the Boston Public Library;
Caroline Graboys of Brockton's Fuller Museum of Art; WBZ's Carl
deSuze; Judge Harold Flannery of the state appeals court; BC High's
Jim Kane; Brigham and Women's H. Richard Nesson; and Nando Ricci,
master potter at the Dorchester Pottery Co.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Williams brought jazz to Cambridge; Dom Pagliarulo was the
quintessential beat cop; James Hook started a lobster company;
Gerald Martino founded the men's shop Martini Carl; and Teddy Green
robbed banks. The Dorchester Day parade won't be the same without
``Boston Billy'' Melchin. And St. Elizabeth's Hospital will not
forget Father Charlie McCarthy.
</P>
<P>
   In South Boston, John Joseph was a beloved, hard-working family
grocer. Their neighbors will miss Boxford's Camilla Coolidge,
Newton's Joe Barry, East Boston's Anna DeFronzo, Roxbury's Edward
Cooper and Oscar Farmer, Dorchester's J. J. Concannon, Weymouth's
Catherine Peart, and Frances McNamara of Cambridge.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Globe men and women
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A newspaper is a family, too, and we notice the empty spaces at
the Globe's holiday table: Karen Avenoso, Doug (Globe Santa)
Crocket, Beats Wallace, Joe Harvey, Jean Dietz, Frank Yancey, Ed
Kelley, Harry Holbrook, Peter Anderson, Charlie Tarbi, Dud O'Leary,
Gary McMillan, Kitte Desmond, and George Collins.
</P>
<P>
   Also: Ruth Maloney, Robert Marshall, Paul Fitzgerald, Carl
Erickson, Leslie Allen, Mickey Weisenthal, Bob Walsh, Catherine
Pillsbury, Arthur Burke, Greg Dow, Charlie Bourke, Ed Hughes, Bob
Davidson, Dr. William Chapman, Forrest Kelliher, John Brennan,
Cliff Sundberg, Frances Dignan, George DeDonato, Bob Hall, David
Kneeland, Frank Abelli, Bob Wilson, Al Todesca, and Ed McGrale.
</P>
<P>
   All rest in the sleep of peace and ne'er shall be forgot, for
auld lang syne.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
