<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YEAR-AULD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REMEMBERING 1998'S AULD ACQUAINTANCES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (k and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARTIN F. NOLAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Robert Burns raised a cup o' kindness to those of auld
acquaintance, he suggested they not be forgot, for auld lang syne.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
------ &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Barry Goldwater, Bella Abzug, and George Wallace could, at one
time or another, push every emotional button on the political
spectrum, but they all shared a poll-proof passion for their
beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   As a boy in New Hampshire, Alan Shepard dreamed of the stars,
and as a man, he slipped the surly bonds of earth as an astronaut.
Florence Griffith Joyner, who streaked across the finish line with
three gold medals, died at 38. Dr. Benjamin Spock died at 94 after
a lifetime of political activism mixed with practical advice to
millions of parents.
</P>
<P>
   Mo Udall served in Congress with distinction and a wit badly
needed today.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Sinatra was Ol' Blue Eyes, the Chairman of the Board, and
a half-dozen other nicknames suggesting his mastery of popular song
as he squeezed and massaged each tune and lyric to hypnotic effect.
He died at 82, but in his prime, he was not the most famous
Italian-American voice in America.
</P>
<P>
   Johnny Roventini, 88, became the world's most famous bellboy
when he advertised a cigarette by hollering ``Call for Philip
Morris!''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
The political scene
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Michael Kennedy died in a skiing accident on New Year's Eve a
year ago. A few days later, Sonny Bono died in a similar accident.
Other voices stilled include: Lewis Powell, the retired Supreme
Court Justice; Senators Jennings Randolph, Floyd Haskell, Albert
Gore Sr., Abe Ribicoff, and Terry Sanford; Representatives Steve
Schiff, Dante Fascell, George Danielson, Charles Diggs, Chalmers
Wylie; political managers Matt Reese and Jack T. Conway.
</P>
<P>
   Billy Sutton and Dave Powers suffused the JFK era with laughter;
Carl Gorman was a hero as a Navajo ``code talker;'' Telford Taylor
prosecuted Nazi war crimes; Lu Conein was a CIA operative; Jim
McDougal was a Whitewater investor with Bill Clinton; Clark
Clifford was an adviser to presidents; Bill McCarthy ran the
Teamsters; Governor Lawton Chiles enlivened the politics of
Florida, as Paul O'Dwyer did in New York and Lenore Romney in
Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   Big-city mayors took their cities through tough times: Tom
Bradley of Los Angeles, Coleman Young of Detroit, Annette Strauss
of Dallas, and the Sicilian dynamo, Joe Alioto of San Francisco. A.
Leon Higginbotham Jr. fought for a vision of civil rights far
different from that espoused by Eldridge Cleaver or Kwame Ture
(Stokely Carmichael); Bebe Rebozo and Maurice Stans were buddies of
Richard Nixon; Thayer Illsey and Toni House labored to provide
public information in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
The world stage
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Across the world, dictators died: Cambodia's Pol Pot, Bulgaria's
Todor Zhivkov, and Nigeria's Sani Abacha. Heroes, too: Moshood
Abiola, Nigeria's most famous political prisoner; former French
foreign minister Maurice Schumann, a voice of the French Resistance
in World War II; Elias Freij, mayor of Bethlehem for 25 years; and
Constantine Caramanlis, who restored democracy to Greece in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
The literary set
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The world of letters lost Octavio Paz, Carlos Castaneda, Alfred
Kazin, Dorothy West, Cleveland Amory, Hammond Innes, Eric Ambler,
John Hawkes, Catherine Cookson, William Gaddis, Janet Lewis, Tamio
Kageyama, Wright Morris, Margaret Walker Alexander, Allen Drury,
Darcy O'Brien, R. L. Bruckberger, Lawrence Sanders, Walter D.
Edmonds, and Dominique Aury, author of ``The Story of O.''
</P>
<P>
   Kay Thompson created ``Eloise;'' Ted Hughes, Aimee Joan
Grunberger, and Jack Micheline were poets; Cary Reich, Arthur Link,
and Robert Lewis Taylor were biographers; Henry Steele Commager,
was a prolific and authoritative historian; Mary Steichen
Calderone,pioneered sex education; Paul Brooks was the editor at
Houghton Mifflin; and Michael Riordan, who died in Fall River at
60, presided over a literary hangout, the Lion's Head in New York's
Greenwich Village.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Big business, little business
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tinkerers and geniuses left their legacy in 1998. William
Russell Kelly started the ``temp'' business with Kelly Girls; Marc
Harrison helped design the Cuisinart; Walter Reimer invented bubble
gum in 1928; Otto Wichterle developed the soft contact lens;
Ferdinand Porsche Jr. built a sports car; Sherwood (Shakey) Johnson
began a pizza chain; Eddie Shipstad co-founded the Ice Follies;
Hazel Bishop left her mark in lipstick; Jheri Redding lathered up
shampoo; J. Gordon Lippincott helped craft the Campbell's soup
label and other corporate logos; Albert Lipper helped start Weight
Watchers; Harold Robeson invented an exploding dye pack to foil
bank robbers; and Robert Townsend, the former Avis rent-a-car
honcho, wrote the first and funniest of the inside-business books,
``Up the Organization.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
The film set
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The phrase ``singing cowboy'' evoked a paragon as pugnacious as
he was melodious. Rex Allen was such a role model, as was
baseball-and-broadcasting tycoon Gene Autry; and Roy Rogers, ``King
of the Cowboys.'' Blonde leading ladies died: Alice Faye, Irene
Hervey, and Penny Edwards; and blond leading men: Richard Denning,
Gene Raymond, and Lloyd Bridges, a durable presence wet or dry.
</P>
<P>
   Film also mourned scene-stealing character actors: the
eloquently brooding J. T. Walsh, Gene Evans, hero of Sam Fuller war
movies; the forever pixieish Roddy McDowall; Maureen O'Sullivan who
played other roles than Tarzan's Jane; Leonid Kinskey, the
bartender in ``Casablanca;'' and Mae Questel, the voice of Olive
Oyl and Betty Boop.
</P>
<P>
   Hurd Hatfield immortalized Dorian Gray on celluloid; John Derek
was an actor who tutored his beautiful wives; Robert Young
transferred movie stardom to long-running television fame. Behind
the cameras, Akira Kurosawa created Japanese classics; Alan Pakula
and Gene Fowler Jr. were directors; Freddie Young and Charles Lang
were cinemaphotographers; Lew Grade was a British mogul; Anatole
Dauman fathered the French New Wave; and Jean Marais was a 1950s
matinee idol in France.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Lost sounds of music
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In music, Tammy Wynette stood by her man and Carl Perkins sang
of his ``Blue Suede Shoes.'' Others who sounded their final note in
1998 include: saxophonist Benny Waters; pianist Floyd Cramer;
guitarists George Van Eps, and Attilla Zoller; singers Betty
Carter, Johnny Adams, O'Landa Draper, and Blue Lu Barker; trumpeter
Frank Motley; pianist Dorothy Donegan, bass player Bob Haggart,
Nashville producer Owen Bradley; blues drummer S. P. Leary; and
Junior Wells, master of the blues harmonica.
</P>
<P>
   Eddie Rabbitt, a country singer-songwriter, left, as did Bob
Merrill, who wrote the scores for ``Funny Girl'' and ``Carnival.''
Wendy O. Williams was the lead Plasmatic; Chico Ryan sang with Sha
Na Na; Carl Wilson was an original Beach Boy; Todd Duncan, was the
original Porgy in ``Porgy and Bess;'' and Rob Pilatus, was half of
the less-than-original Milli Vanilli.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
