<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNIFORM-RECREATOR-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HE MAKES UNIFORMS STITCHED WITH HISTORY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KENNEY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   RANDOLPH, Mass. _ When high school senior Henry Cooke marched
off to a Bicentennial reenactment in 1975, he could not have
realized that he was also on his way to a career.
</P>
<P>
   He was marching with the Randolph-South Suffolk Militia Company
_ ``a very grandiose name for a very small unit'' _ but still, he
said, he needed ``a proper uniform.'' What passed for proper in
those early days of Colonial reenactments was something put
together out of a commercial pattern book with the help of his
mother, who was not only a patient mother but a sewing teacher.
</P>
<P>
   ``By today's standards,'' Cooke said, ``it wasn't very great.''
Its design was based on an artist's conception of what a
Revolutionary War soldier's uniform probably looked like _ and it
was put together with inauthentic Velcro and zippers.
</P>
<P>
   But authenticity has become the rule as interest in ``living
history'' reenactments _ from 18th-century wars in New England, the
Civil War in the South and Midwest _ has grown. And today's high
standards for reenactor uniforms are as much the result of Cooke's
historical research as they are of his hand-sewn craftsmanship.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Take the rather plain-looking uniform of a common soldier in the
re-created 10th Massachusetts Regiment, a unit that Cooke helped to
organize, modeled on a light infantry regiment in Washington's army
that fought all the way down to Yorktown.
</P>
<P>
   It is of blue wool kersey, a heavyweight coating cloth, with
white facings _ but not just any old blue. It is as close to the
actual blue that historical research can achieve, based on three
sources: a contemporary print of a French artilleryman _ many of
the uniforms for Washington's army came from France _ and two
scraps of cloth that were discovered by purest chance.
</P>
<P>
   At the Kansas Historical Society's museum in Topeka, Cooke found
a small coverlet in which the padding was held in place by ties
that in turn were anchored by 1 1/4-inch circles of an indigo-dyed
blue woolen cloth. Quite likely, Cooke said, these scraps of cloth
came from cut-up uniforms brought along by New England settlers of
the Kansas Territory.
</P>
<P>
   But the clincher was a small black scrap of woolen cloth found
tucked inside a leather cartridge box in the collection of Don
Troiani, a Connecticut military artist. The box was known to have
belonged to a Revolutionary War soldier from New England.
</P>
<P>
   The scrap of cloth had been used to blacken the soldier's
leather gear but after Cooke cleaned and restored it, its original
indigo-blue color appeared.
</P>
<P>
   Then, with the color and texture known, Cooke had the cloth made
up by an English mill _ which also makes material for Ralph Lauren
and other designers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a beautiful thing,'' said Cooke showing off a sample of
the cloth, but there was one final step taken in the interest of
absolute authenticity. The dye was chemically formulated so that it
would ``degrade'' over time in the same way that the original cloth
did, acquiring ``a yellowish-greenish cast in areas exposed to
daylight.''
</P>
<P>
   For the white facings, Cooke also uses a kersey, but for the
lining he uses a coarse but thin _ and breathable _ worsted.
``Breathability was really important,'' said Cooke, ``when you were
wearing a couple of layers of wool.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The thread he uses to stitch the neat, 2-inch long buttonholes
is one of the very few concessions Cooke makes to modern
technology. ``Historically, they used a mohair thread,'' he said,
``but that's not readily available, so we use a coarse grade of a
silk twist thread.''
</P>
<P>
   For the buttons, Cooke had an original that was found in an
archeological dig at West Point where the ``10th Mass.'' was
stationed on and off for about five years. From that model _ with
the words MAS X REG on three lines circled by a border _ Cooke had
a local tool-and-diemaker cut a die from which he casts buttons for
his uniforms in pewter.
</P>
<P>
   ``These accidental finds,'' said Cooke, ``help us understand the
clothing that the common soldiers wore.'' And knowing what people
wore, he said, ``is a way of breathing life into the dusty pages of
history.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a nice, warm woolen uniform,'' Cooke said, laying out
his own 10th Massachusetts jacket on his worktable. ``But he's got
50 pounds of equipment on his back, and it's July, and he's
sweating profusely.''
</P>
<P>
   Cooke noted that the jacket has had 8 inches lopped off its
tails. ``They did that when they got to Virginia,'' he said. But
they kept the incongruous heart-shaped decorations on the bottom of
the jacket that concealed the hooks that held the tails up during
marches.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't really capture the stark terror of being packed in
ranks and under fire,'' Cooke said. ``But you can capture the
boredom and the misery of his everyday life.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It takes Cooke about 40 hours to make one of these jackets,
which sell for $2,000. A more elaborate officer's uniform can run
about $5,000. In all, he makes about a dozen uniforms a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started out making shirts, then jackets for fellows in my
own unit,'' said Cooke. ``They'd been prevailing on wives and
girlfriends and were lucky to get one set of clothes out of them
before they threw up their hands.''
</P>
<P>
   After graduating from Tufts _ and with a master's thesis on the
social evolution of the 10th Massachusetts _ Cooke found ``a dearth
of positions in museums'' and decided ``to stay with uniform-making
on a full-time basis until something better came along.''
</P>
<P>
   That was 14 years ago. From uniforms for his 10th Massachusetts
unit, Cooke branched out to make them for other reenactors _ the
pre-Revolutionary units whose uniforms were similar to the red
coats of British Army units.
</P>
<P>
   Besides creating uniforms for reenactors, Cooke makes them for
artists like Troiani, who uses live models in his paintings of
historic battles. Cooke recently completed a two-year project for
the Braintree Historical Society, researching and then making a
uniform like that worn by General Sylvanus Thayer, a Braintree
native who was superintendent of West Point from 1817 to 1830.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, as the interest of New England reenactors has
turned to the French and Indian War (1754-'63), Cooke has
researched and made the forest-green jackets for the re-created
Rogers Rangers. On a mannequin in his workshop is the brick-colored
jacket for an officer in the 40th Regiment of Foot, a British unit
that fought in that war.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cooke's workshop is the ell of an 1850s house on South Main
Street. Originally it was the home _ and workshop _ of a shoemaker
when Randolph, like several other South Shore towns, was a center
for a home-based shoemaking industry. Later, it was Cooke's
grandparents' home.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I'm continuing the use,'' Cooke said of the workshop ell.
``I'm bringing it back to manufacturing, just clothes instead of
shoes.''
</P>
<P>
   The ell houses boxes of buttons and bags of cloth samples, a
shelf of books on Colonial uniforms, a tray of needles and pins _
and a modern sewing machine on the worktable, used strictly for
interior seams.
</P>
<P>
   Along with uniform-making, Cooke does consulting and restoration
work for museums and private collectors.
</P>
<P>
   A recent consulting assignment for the Bostonian Society,
researching and making the uniforms for its current Boston Massacre
exhibit, has Cooke, as a costumed mannequin, appearing both in the
mob of city residents and as one of the British soldiers _ ``firing
on myself, as it were.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
