<HEADER>
A3327 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WALKER-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      12-31 0787
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WALKER-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWYER ADDS TO FAMILY'S PAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ADRIAN WALKER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Harvey Silverglate is dogged by worries that his strategy for
defending British au pair Louise Woodward badly miscalculated the
jury's reaction. Now he has miscalculated again, this time even
more grievously, by offending an innocent family during their
bereavement.
</P>
<P>
   Silverglate led a team of lawyers that represented Woodward, who
was rightly convicted last year in the death of the Eappens' infant
son, Matthew.
</P>
<P>
   Now he chooses to announce _ in an interview in Massachusetts
Lawyers Weekly _ that he had evidence he chose not to introduce
that might have shown that the Eappens' son, Brendan, who is now 5,
played a role in the death of his brother. But Silverglate also
chose not to disclose to the Weekly what that evidence is.
</P>
<P>
   That's right. Without presenting the merest speck of evidence, a
man who has spent years wearing out many a soapbox defending the
rights of the unjustly accused now publicly implicates an innocent
child.
</P>
<P>
   He begins by grumbling that he was never given credit by the
media for his gentle treatment of the Eappens, apparently believing
he should be lauded for not attacking innocent people who had lost
a child. He then moves on to his new-found evidence about how
Matthew Eappen died.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can tell you that we had some stuff, and I'm not going to
tell you what it was, that any fair person would have said that
it's reasonable for us to put on,'' Silverglate told the Weekly.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue of whether the older brother is well-behaved or not;
well, that's relevant. You're not calling a kid a murderer when you
(contend) that this kid might have pushed his brother and he might
have hit his head on a doorpost. That's relevant.''
</P>
<P>
   Let's recall, as if we could forget, that Silverglate had an
entire trial to float any theory he wanted.
</P>
<P>
   He chose to argue that Matthew Eappen died from an injury
suffered three weeks before. The jury, understandably, didn't buy
his theory that a baby could suffer an injury, crawl around seeming
fine for weeks, and then die. The jury, in fact, thought Louise
Woodward was a liar.
</P>
<P>
   It was Silverglate's singular accomplishment this week to extend
the pain and suffering of a family that has already suffered so
much. But Silverglate has already had the only thing any lawyer is
entitled to: his day in court.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Wednesday, Silverglate said the Eappens were
``imperfect people'' whose elder son was rambunctious. So what? In
the Weekly article, he raised the notion that Brendan might have
pushed Matthew into a doorpost. But Wednesday, he admitted he had
no proof that anything of the sort had ever taken place. It was
just a theory, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I certainly wasn't blaming the Eappens or Brendan,''
Silverglate said. ``My whole point was that you can't blame them _
and you can't blame Louise.''
</P>
<P>
   It's nauseating. But also transparent.
</P>
<P>
   Having served minimal time, Woodward is home free in England.
Silverglate remains the losing lawyer in the case _ and a sore
loser he is. So he must assure the world that he could have won.
It's not that he wasn't a good enough lawyer, or that the jury
didn't believe his case, or that he was defending a guilty client.
No. His only sin was being too nice a guy.
</P>
<P>
   And we didn't even appreciate it. What is wrong with us?
</P>
<P>
   Silverglate clearly remains incredulous that the jury didn't buy
his case. He actually said Wednesday he didn't raise his theory
about Brendan because he thought the scientific case he had
assembled was so overwhelming. He said he had expected an acquittal
in 30 minutes, and knew the jury had decided to disregard the law
when he didn't get it.
</P>
<P>
   Silverglate's arrogance is his own business. And it's his right
to continue to maintain his client's innocence.
</P>
<P>
   But the Eappen family is nursing a pain that will never heal.
This is a family that has suffered the death of a child, a circus
of a trial, then the dim-witted media martyrdom of a confused young
woman who was entrusted with the care of their baby and tragically
failed to live up to that trust.
</P>
<P>
   Silverglate said Wednesday that he was merely outlining
alternative theories of the case to a legal audience. But there's
nothing theoretical about this case. It's a matter of an infant's
death and a family's agony.
</P>
<P>
   Everything about this case was a tragedy. But that is no excuse
for a self-aggrandizing lawyer to start pointing fingers at young
children to soothe his own bruised ego. Here's one New Year's wish
for Harvey Silverglate: a heart.
</P>
<P>
   (Adrian Walker is a columnist with The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
