<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELLIS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE RUSH TO GET ON LINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN ELLIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There are two overriding demographics in the life of the
American consumer. The first is that no one has any time. The
second is that you're either on the Web or you're not. More than
anything else, these two demographics are taking the stock market
into unexpected places and changing the indices of value.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Charles Schwab Corp., the discount brokerage firm based
in San Francisco, achieved a market capitalization of $25.5
billion, making it the second-highest-valued brokerage firm in the
United States. (The first is Morgan Stanley Dean Witter). That same
day, Merrill Lynch had a market capitalization of $25.4 billion,
making it the third-highest-valued brokerage firm in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   As recently as three months ago, it was unthinkable that
investors would even consider Charles Schwab in the same category
as Merrill Lynch. Schwab was thought of as a discount house.
Merrill was considered a powerhouse. What changed? The answer is
simple. Charles Schwab is Web-savvy and Merrill Lynch is not.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, Barnes &AMP; Noble and Borders were on the verge of
dominating the book industry. Today, on-line bookseller Amazon.com
has a market value ($17.5 billion) that far exceeds the combined
value of both companies.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Disney Corp. bought ABC for $19 billion and
seemed well on its way to becoming the premier media and
entertainment company of its time. Today, America Online has a
market capitalization greater than Disney's, a financial advantage
that will likely grow in the months and years to come.
</P>
<P>
   Why? First, more and more Americans are getting on line. In
November 1996, the Voter News Service poll found that 25 percent of
American voters (who differ not much from nonvoters) were on the
Internet. In 1998 that number had increased to 40 percent. Assuming
that the trend continues, 65 percent of American voters will be on
line by November 2000. That's critical mass.
</P>
<P>
   Second, the cost of computing is getting cheaper by the day. It
is now expected that by the end of 1999, a high quality Pentium II
computer will cost roughly $500. By the year 2003, it is widely
assumed that a majority of American households will have as many
computers as people residing therein, just as most American
households now have more than one television set.
</P>
<P>
   Third, despite the almost unbelievable intransigence of the
regional Bell operating companies, high-speed Internet connections
will soon be available in most households. The days of 28 bits per
second are, no thanks to Bell Atlantic, coming to an end.
High-speed ADSL and cable modems should be standard features of
telephony (and commodity priced) by 2003.
</P>
<P>
   All of which is fueling the current ``dot-com'' frenzy on Wall
Street. Like other Wall Street crazes, this, too, shall pass. The
truth is that many of the dot-com companies will fail. They don't
have realistic business plans. They don't make a profit. In the
words of thestreet.com columnist James Cramer, ``most are just
rarefied press releases backed by cheap public capital.''
</P>
<P>
   Cramer predicts that 1999 will be the year of reckoning for the
dot-com sector. Having given e-commerce stocks a bye in 1998, he
says, investors in 1999 will begin to apply the same criteria to
dot-com companies that they apply to ``bricks and mortar''
companies. The comparison, he thinks, will cause a proportionate
correction in valuations.
</P>
<P>
   That's probably right. But the two key demographics will
continue to alter the arithmetic of valuation. A couple of weeks
ago, American Online's Robert Pittman released a survey showing
that AOL could double its price, charge a fee for e-mail, charge a
fee for instant messaging, and still keep its customer base.
Overnight, that would double AOL's profitability.
</P>
<P>
   AOL won't be doing that any time soon. It is focused on gaining
market share. Eventually, AOL knows that most Americans will look
to the Web to alleviate what market researchers call ``time
famine.'' This is the reason why the potential of companies like
AOL is so enormous. The demand for services that give time back is
insatiable.
</P>
<P>
   In its first incarnation, e-commerce was about disintermediation
_ a fancy term for cutting out the middleman. In its next
incarnation, e-commerce will be about bundling services that save
time or act as ``intelligent agents'' for consumers. All the while,
it will continue to deliver value and best prices. This year's
Internet Christmas shopping numbers are evidence of this emerging
trend.
</P>
<P>
   Companies that don't understand the dynamics of the new
demographics and the new technology will find it ever more
difficult to compete. A dot-com share price correction likely will
occur this year. But the larger dot-com correction is occurring
every day, and it is changing the rules of business and the
arithmetic of valuation.
</P>
<P>
   (John Ellis is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
