<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAMILY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESOLVED TO ESCAPE THE NEW YEAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LINDA WELTNER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hold on a minute, I'm gazing at my crystal ball.
</P>
<P>
   What lies ahead in 1999?
</P>
<P>
   Aaaaggh! I see a long line of newly outed adulterers and another
trial, full of sex and scandal, that will creep into our heads,
sleazy detail by sleazy detail. I see even more extreme weather,
evidence that global warming is turning our planet topsy-turvy.
We'll discover to our horror that another ubiquitous object of the
'90s is a probable carcinogen _ and do nothing about it. There will
be another ethnic slaughter, another famine, other shocking acts of
terrorism. Many more species will topple into the oblivion of
extinction. TV sitcoms will be even more stupid.
</P>
<P>
   Are you hiding under the couch yet? Is there anyone with half a
brain looking forward to spending the next 365 days in 1999?
</P>
<P>
   I'll admit we seem to have no choice, since death is such an
unattractive alternative. Unfortunately, alcohol and drugs are much
less effective, leaving far too many unavoidable moments of
sobriety between binges. But I have a plan, which I've already set
into action.
</P>
<P>
   I'm heading for the 18th century.
</P>
<P>
   I'm going there with a new friend named Claire, the heroine of
Diana Gabaldon's incredibly engrossing novel, ``Outlander.'' When I
first met her, Claire was taking a second honeymoon with her
husband, Frank, in Scotland. World War II had just ended and
Claire, a former army nurse, was hoping to renew a relationship
interrupted by a six-year separation. One evening, traipsing around
the local version of Stonehenge, Claire stepped into the cleft of
one of the tallest standing stones and emerged into the year 1743,
a time of clan rivalry, incipient revolution, powerful
superstition, and really old-fashioned men.
</P>
<P>
   By 20th-century standards, of course.
</P>
<P>
   I was stunned to find myself in the 1740s without my cell phone,
my conditioner, or any knowledge of Scottish history, but Claire
was such a trouper I just followed her lead. I watched her get
captured by one of her husband's ancestors, Captain ``Black Jack''
Randall, who was far less savory in person than he appeared in the
history books. Luckily, she got rescued by a couple of local
fellows, including a Scot named Jamie Frasier, the kind of hero
you'd get if you crossed Tom Hanks with Sylvester Stallone, or Brad
Pitt with Arnold Schwarzenegger, and he only took one bath a week.
</P>
<P>
   Claire adapts a whole lot better to the 1740s than I ever would,
but she was raised by her uncle, an archeologist whose travels from
one primitive site to another taught her the art of coping. Her
medical skills come in handy as well, and before you know it, she's
become a healer at Castle Leoch, all the while, of course, secretly
plotting to return to the stones and to her own century.
</P>
<P>
   Since Claire predates feminism and Jamie's never heard the words
``macho pig,'' she's forced to use epithets like ``barbarian'' and
``sadist'' when she gets mad. It's been fascinating to watch this
couple try to achieve a reasonable balance of power while avoiding
the soldiers pursuing Jamie and the villagers who want to burn
Claire as a witch.
</P>
<P>
   I can't seem to get these folks out of my mind. I think about
Claire in the shower, while I'm driving, and when I'm making
dinner. Because Claire came of age in the 1940s and I'm a part of
the 1990s, I brood about her greater adaptability. I wonder what
I'd do if I were in her place. I also think about the gulf between
daily life in the 1730s and my life today, trying to figure out
just how mixed a blessing progress is. I worry about what will
happen to her and Jamie next.
</P>
<P>
   You may think reading will provide only a temporary respite from
the next 365 days, but you're wrong. ``Outlander'' is 850 pages
long, and I'm reading it twice because the first time through, I
was too caught up in the action to savor the ways in which the
characters grow. When I'm done, there's the sequel, ``Dragonfly in
Amber'' (947 pages), and the sequel to that, ``Voyager,'' (870
pages), and ``Drums of Autumn,'' (Well, you get the idea). Gabaldon
has more books in the works.
</P>
<P>
   I'd rather spend my evenings with Claire than with Peter
Jennings. I'd choose the company of the warden of Wentworth Prison
over a member of the Judiciary Committee any day. Even when things
go wrong, at least they make sense. I like knowing who the bad guys
are.
</P>
<P>
   Do me a favor.
</P>
<P>
   Don't call me until the millennium arrives.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Linda Weltner's website is at www.shore.net(tilde)weltner)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
