<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-NOTES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN '98, THE MESSENGERS WERE THE MESSAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JURKOWITZ  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   What kind a year was 1998 for the news media? A mighty strange
one. It began with cybernerd Matt Drudge breaking the biggest
scandal since Watergate and ended with porno king Larry Flynt
forcing the resignation of the House Speaker-elect. Geraldo Rivera
went from a trash TV talkmaster to respected newsman. ESPN wiseguy
Keith Olbermann jumped to MSNBC to try serious news and _ in this
season of ``all Monica all the time'' _ returned to sports to
restore his self-respect. It was a year in which almost every line
between news and entertainment was blurred.
</P>
<P>
   So here, with the unerring clarity of 20-20 hindsight and in no
particular order, is a look at some of the major players that
shaped _ or distorted _ journalism during the past 12 months.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Willes: After the former General Mills executive became CEO
of Times Mirror Co. and later become publisher of its flagship, the
Los Angeles Times, he elicited gasps of horror with his vow to blow
up the sacred wall between a newspaper's editorial and business
departments. He's toned down the rhetoric, but encouraged major
collaboration between journalists and bean counters in an effort to
build circulation by as much as 500,000. If his experiment
succeeds, Willes will spawn scores of imitators. If he fails, in
his words, ``We risk being remembered as the crash dummies of
American journalism.''
</P>
<P>
   Matt Drudge: In one year, this self-proclaimed Walter Winchell
of the '90s has gone from anonymity to his own Fox News Channel
show. His master stroke was to pilfer and post Newsweek's Monica
Lewinsky scoop on his Web site in January, breaking the scandal
that has rocked Washington to its core. He posits himself as an
outsider in a ``turf war with the establishment press.'' And Drudge
is the most dramatic symbol of the emergence of cyberspace as a
major media force.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Kaplan: After years of enduring crummy ratings when there's
no O. J. freeway chase or Gulf War, CNN imported this former ABC
``World News Tonight'' executive producer to build numbers. Kaplan
hinged his ``appointment viewing'' strategy on ``NewsStand'' shows
pairing CNN and its Time Inc. brethren. But the June 7 debut
alleging the United States' use of nerve gas in the Vietnam War was
a disaster. Apologies were issued, heads rolled (even Kaplan's
momentarily wobbled), and CNN boss Ted Turner lamented that
``nothing has upset me more in my whole life.''
</P>
<P>
   Tina Brown: America's best magazine editor brought more
eyeballs, more buzz, and more red ink to The New Yorker before
suddenly resigning to become Miramax's multimedia guru. Everyone
seemed happy with the surprise selection of Pulitzer Prize winner
David Remnick to succeed her. And while traditionalists decried
Brown's fondness for popular culture and her proclivity for S&AMP;M
photo features, time will tell whether Remnick can match her feel
for the Zeitgeist.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Brill/Jackie Judd: The cocky founder of Court TV became
America's most ambitious media scold with ``Brill's Content''
magazine. His mission impossible is to sell a journalism trade
publication to a mass audience of 500,000 subscribers. Yet he may
never replicate the clout of his first issue, a strategically savvy
assault on Monicagate coverage in which he called the media ``an
enabler of (Ken) Starr's abuse of power.''
</P>
<P>
   Judd's ABC report on Jan. 23 of a semen-stained Lewinsky dress
became exhibit A for the loud chorus accusing the media of
recklessly reporting rumor. When the story proved true, Judd had
done her part to salvage journalism's credibility.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Scaife/Salon magazine: When Hillary Clinton complained
about a right-wing conspiracy, the reclusive Scaife became a
household word. The Pennsylvania publisher has donated hundreds of
millions to conservative causes, funding everything from reporter
Christopher Ruddy's allegations that Vincent Foster was murdered to
The American Spectator's dirt-digging on the Clintons.
</P>
<P>
   Conversely, the online magazine Salon became the White House's
favorite junkyard dog. First, it unearthed GOP House Judiciary
chair Henry Hyde's decades-old adulterous relationship. More
recently it alleged a ``personal history of marital infidelity,''
on the part of GOP Congressman Dan Burton, a Clinton foe who once
called the president a ``scumbag.''
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Smith/Mike Barnicle/Stephen Glass: Two star Globe
columnists and the New Republic Wunderkind departed after mixing
fact and fiction. Their cases generated paroxysms of introspection
in a media business desperately afraid of eroding public trust.
Little wonder then that American Society of Newspaper Editors
president Edward L. Seaton recently referred to the high-profile
spate of embarrassments as journalism's ``spring and summer from
hell.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Kevorkian and ``60 Minutes'': ``Is he dead now?'' With that
question to Dr. Jack Kevorkian, Mike Wallace punctuated the
decision by ``60 Minutes'' to broadcast the euthanizing of the
terminally ill Thomas Youk. A defiant ``60 Minutes'' staff said
they were only interested in sparking a meaningful debate on the
issue of assisted suicide and said the program ``performed a public
service.'' Angry critics accused ``60 Minutes'' of airing a
ratings-driven snuff film.
</P>
<P>
   Craig Unger: The Boston magazine editor refused to apologize for
a headline on a profile of Harvard's ``Skip'' Gates _ ``Head Negro
In Charge'' _ that enraged numerous black activists. Some observers
think the flap put the magazine back on the map with its suburban
readers. It certainly revealed how Boston's festering racial wounds
can reopen at any time.
</P>
<P>
   Viagra: Once the wonders of ``father's little helper'' hit the
media, it was a full-blown frenzy. A ``Nightline'' segment began
with a satisfied user extolling Viagra's virtues thusly: ``The
skies opened, and a bolt of lightning came down and God said, `I
love you.' '' The intense Viagra coverage illustrated the
newsworthiness of America's continued quest for better living
through chemicals. And it also served to remind us how many news
executives happen to be middle-aged males.
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Jurkowitz writes on the media for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-31-98 1133EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981231.0135 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-31 11:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3344 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      12-31 0617
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
'TWAS THE WEEK AFTER CHRISTMAS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SATURDAY, DEC. 26.
</P>
<P>
   Post-holiday sales. Too early to shop for next Christmas? Never
too early.
</P>
<P>
   To do: Make soup from leftover turkey. Throw out cookies, candy,
turkey stuffing, eggnog, etc. Round up used Christmas wrapping
paper, ribbons. Iron. Store. Write thank-you notes.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SUNDAY, DEC. 27
</P>
<P>
   Add up total spent on Christmas presents. Cut up credit cards.
Throw in trash. Re-think tossing out eggnog. Shame to waste. Latest
research shows eggs good for you. Retrieve cut-up credit cards from
trash.
</P>
<P>
   To do: Arrange bills in order of magnitude. Force self to make
full and frank inventory of holiday-related shortcomings. Vow to do
better next year. Iron wrapping paper. Order new credit cards.
Thank-you notes.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MONDAY, DEC. 28
</P>
<P>
   Check weight. Shift position slightly on scale. Check weight
again. Panic. Self-loathing. Chocolate. Latest research shows
chocolate good for depression. Find missing un-sent holiday cards
on shelf in fron hall closet. Send now? Three days after Christmas?
Throw out? Save `til next year? Tear hair out? Sort through
Christmas cards received. Who ``Phil and Loretta''? Re-read
nauseating Christmas letter from gloating college classmate. ``Dear
Friend, my life has been blessed...'' Ceremonial burning of letter.
Egg nog.
</P>
<P>
   To do: Arrange bills in alphabetical order. Put away unwanted
Christmas gifts for possible re-gifting. Iron used wrapping paper?
Inventory of holiday-related shortcomings? Diet. Thank-you notes.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TUESDAY, DEC. 29
</P>
<P>
   Remove ornaments from tree. Throw away broken ornaments. Note to
self: look into cat-proof christmas tree. Ripe for invention.
Possible goldmine. Place tree in specially-purchased giant plastic
bag. First, find specially-purchased giant plastic bag. No
specially-purchased plastic bag anywhere. Find five-pound gift
fruitcake in back of tree. Latest research shows fruitcake healthy?
Why not. Drag un-bagged tree through house. Toss out front door.
Haul out vacuum cleaner. Clean up needles. Why taking tree down now
more fun than putting it up? Sign of age? Eggnog. Fruitcake.
</P>
<P>
   To do: Arrange bills in order of payment due date. Put away
unwanted gifts for re-gifting. Full and frank inventory of
shortcomings. Weigh self. Diet. Thank-you notes.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WEDNESDAY, DEC. 30
</P>
<P>
   Consider groveling apologies to everyone offended in past year.
Think better of it. Throw away turkey. To hell with soup. Wonder if
leftover stuffing safe to eat. Botulism? Salmonella? Possible
e-coli? Eat stuffing. Break out chocolates. Surprise. Find holiday
wrapping paper left over from Christmas 1997. Also find
specially-purchased giant plastic bag for tossing out tree. Use to
store holiday wrappings from 1997. Forget about ironing used
wrapping paper. Toss in trash.
</P>
<P>
   To do: Arrange bills according to Dewey Decimal System. Make
more eggnog for New Year's celebration. Diet. Thank-you notes.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THURSDAY, DEC. 31
</P>
<P>
   Happy new year. Holiday movie? Which one? Impossible decision.
All blockbusters, instant classics, world-class thrillers, must-see
adventures. Store gifts for re-gifting. Try to remember who gave
what so won't re-give to giver who might re-re-give. Attempt full
and frank inventory of shortcomings. Give up. Egg nog. Chocolate.
Fruitcake. Champagne.
</P>
<P>
   To do: Shuffle bills. Close eyes. Pick one bill at random. Pay.
Make plan for celebrating false millennium. Write plan in datebook.
Remember to buy datebook. Diet? Thank-you notes?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Diane White is a columnist for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
