<HEADER>
A3346 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEDNOTES-SCI-BOS &LR;      12-31 0776
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDNOTES-SCI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
--HESITANCE ON TREATING HYPERTENSION FOUND  
 --FOODS' BENEFITS MISS MANY MOTHERS-TO-BE  
 --INFANTS' HEALTH RISES WITH MOTHERS' MILK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Hesitance on treating hypertension found
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While US physicians are more often criticized for being overly
aggressive in treating sick people, a new study in the current New
England Journal of Medicine suggests doctors may not be pushing
hard enough to control high blood pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Dan R. Berlowitz, a senior Veterans Administration health
official, and Dr. Mark A. Moskowitz, general internal medicine
chief at Boston Medical Center, followed 800 veterans treated at
four Massachusetts VA medical centers and a fifth in Providence.
About 40 percent had high blood pressure, or readings of 160/90 or
higher.
</P>
<P>
   Although these hypertensive men saw doctors on average six times
a year, in only one visit out of four, did doctors take some action
to increase their medication, which the study authors consider an
unacceptably low rate. ``Although physicians may have been closely
monitoring patients' blood pressure, they repeatedly delayed making
changes'' in medication, the doctors wrote.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our study clearly demonstrates that physicians are not
aggressively treating hypertension or taking the simple, necessary
steps to reduce high blood pressure in a patient,'' said Moskowitz.
He and Berlowitz say their findings _ involving patients with an
average age of 65 who visited VA hospitals and clinics in Bedford,
Lowell, Jamaica Plain, Providence, and West Roxbury _ probably
apply to the general population of older and hypertensive people.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Foods' benefits miss many mothers-to-be
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Large numbers of women in America apparently do not know of the
critical benefits that eating foods rich in folate and folic acid
can have in preventing birth defects, according to the January
Journal of the American Dietetic Association.
</P>
<P>
   As many as three-quarters of spinal and brain birth defects
could be prevented if pregnant women consumed adequate daily
amounts of the nutrients, found in foods such as spinach, pasta,
lentils, and breads and cereals, many of which are fortified with
folic acid, and pill supplements.
</P>
<P>
   But two studies in the journal found that 75 percent of
low-income women in Hartford, Conn _ and a majority of pregnant
low-income women in Atlanta _ had never heard of spina bifida or
neural tube defects and could not say which nutrients or foods can
prevent them. ``This worries me that women don't know about the
importance of folate, because it is such a simple solution to
problems that can cause such heartache,'' said Elizabeth Ward, a
Boston dietitian and author of an association book called
`Pregnancy Nutrition.''
</P>
<P>
   The National Academy of Sciences recommends all women of
childbearing age consume 400 micrograms of folate daily, which can
be achieved with a bowl of cereal and large glass of orange juice
for breakfast plus a good helping of green vegetables with dinner.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Infants' health rises with mothers' milk
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Another new study important to pregnant women and new mothers
bolsters the case for breast-feeding of infants.
</P>
<P>
   A team led by Jeanne Raisler, now of the University of Michigan
Nursing School, found a fairly clear ``dose-response'' relationship
between the extent to which infants got their nutrition from their
mothers and the rate at which they got sick with diarrhea, coughs,
or other illnesses requiring a trip to the pediatrician. The study
appears in the January issue of the American Journal of Public
Health.
</P>
<P>
   Raisler and colleagues followed 7,092 infants from the National
Maternal and Infant Health Survey found that those who were fully
breast-fed for their first 6 months had up to 30 percent fewer
illnesses than those who got most of their nutrition from formula
or prepared foods.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, infants' rate of illnesses dropped as the portion of
breast milk in their diet rose. The study took steps to factor out
other things that could affect their rate of illness, such as their
parents' economic status, infant birthweight, what month they were
born, and whether they went to day care or had older siblings or
people at home who smoke.
</P>
<P>
   While the study bolsters the case for breast-feeding among women
for whom it is possible, Raisler said follow-up studies should be
done to determine whether there is some minimum level of
breast-feeding _ say, 50 percent of the diet for 6 months _ that
seems to guarantee immunity against minor illnesses.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
