<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-PROJECT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOME PROJECT RESOLUTIONS FOR '99 _ AND HOW TO KEEP THEM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER C. HOTTON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   New Year's resolutions are made to be broken, which is a great
way to get a guilty conscience.
</P>
<P>
   But we have a little list. We've made up a list of resolutions
that you can keep. In fact, you'd better keep them, because if you
don't, your house and garden will disappear in a compost pile of
neglect.
</P>
<P>
   And, only one resolution for each month makes them easier to
keep and ready to start all over again.
</P>
<P>
   OK, tighten your belt, and here we go. &QL; 
 &QL; 
January &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Get rid of mildew. That's a funny resolution; doesn't mildew
grow only in warm weather, outdoors?
</P>
<P>
   Guess again. It doesn't grow in cold weather outdoors, yes, but
indoors it thrives with moisture, in living space and especially in
basements, and often in attics.
</P>
<P>
   Wherever you see it, attack it with bleach and water. Clorox is
a good bleach, but you can buy the same thing under Brand X for
less cost. Make a mix of one part bleach and three parts water and
paint this on all black smudges, little dots, and other suspect
surfaces.
</P>
<P>
   Be careful using bleach on upholstery or clothes, but almost
every other surface _ paint, varnish, stain, concrete, metal, _ can
take the bleach with aplomb. And, as always, wear skin and eye
protection when working with bleach.
</P>
<P>
   One drawback of bleach is that it can be very hard on bare wood.
</P>
<P>
   Some mildew fighters have found that Era, a Proctor &AMP; Gamble
laundry detergent with enzymes, is designed to remove protein
stains (grass, fruit, blood). Judson Escalant of Chatham found it
works well for mildew. Use it three parts water to one part Era, or
straight, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Baking soda in place of bleach also works on mildew. &QL; 
 &QL; 
February &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Keep the mildew away. This is a tough resolution because it may
be impossible to keep mildew away completely. It will grow where it
is warm and damp, and dampness can occur in many places. Outdoors,
it is a losing battle, and the best you can do is keep after it.
</P>
<P>
   But, you can try, indoors. The way to try is to elminate
dampness by ventilating house, basement and attic.
</P>
<P>
   Also, insulate walls and ceilings and floors, so that these
surfaces will be warm, and water vapor will be less likely to
condense on it.
</P>
<P>
   If you open windows for a few minutes twice a day, you wll
release a lot of the moisture, which is constantly being built up
indoors. And, you will not lose much heat at all.
</P>
<P>
   As for the basement, chances are fair to good that you don't
have to ventilate in winter, because there is less moisture in cold
air. But it's a must in summer.
</P>
<P>
   Also, you can paint some surfaces with a new Muralo paint that
claims to be mildew-proof. It's called Perma-White, both exterior
and interior, and in various glosses. Muralo guarantees that the
paint will be free of mildew for five years.
</P>
<P>
   That is a gutsy guarantee.
</P>
<P>
   Perma-White can be tinted to off-white and pastel shades. It is
a hard finish, helping to s make it mildew resistant because mildew
has a hard time growing on hard, shiny surfaces. That is why mildew
does not grow on glass, shiny metal, and glazed ceramic tile. &QL; 
 &QL; 
March &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Clean out, clean up, and clean down. Clean out the garage, the
basement, the closets, and the attic. If you haven't used something
in five years, throw it out.
</P>
<P>
   Except, of course, anything you think is valuable, antique,
sellable, and usable. OK, it's a lost cause and a broken
resolution. Put everything back. But neatly. Build an extra closet,
if necessary. Build an extra room for the closet, if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   At least you got everything clean.
</P>
<P>
   And so on, and so on, to: &QL; 
 &QL; 
April &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This one's easy, and maybe even fun. Get out in the garden and
grub, taking up winter debris and raking, spading, fertilizing,
seeding, and planting perennials and early annuals.
</P>
<P>
   This way, everything will be perfect for the coming glories of
spring and summer outdoors. Build and install bat boxes and bird
houses. Bird feeders, too, and keep them stocked.
</P>
<P>
   Consider yard ornaments, made of concrete and other
weather-resistant materials. They are large and small, and come in
every shape and form, whimsical to serious, with a fountain or two
thrown in for good measure.
</P>
<P>
   But be careful that you don't get too artsy-crafty, with
flamingos and other inappropriate animals. &QL; 
 &QL; 
May &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the perennials and annuals can wait until this month.
</P>
<P>
   Buy a mulching mower and don't waste all those grass clippings.
Use the mulching mower to grind up your leaves in autumn, too; you
can put them on the garden beds. &QL; 
 &QL; 
June &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Paint everything in sight; better yet, stain.
</P>
<P>
   The painting season is underway, and you can join all the
painters, painting siding, trim, decks, and outbuildings.
</P>
<P>
   Don't forget to scrape, sand, and wash what you are about to
paint, and think seriously about using stain instead of paint,
which doesn't seem to work well in many outdoor cases, peeling
before its time.
</P>
<P>
   You can also paint aluminum siding. Sand it to reduce gloss and
roughen the finish, wash with a strong detergent and water, and
finish with two thin coats of a latex house paint, or solid latex
stain. Pittsburgh Paints makes a latex paint specifically designed
for aluminum siding.
</P>
<P>
   Sonme authorities say you can paint vinyl siding, but I would
avoid that.
</P>
<P>
   You can use solid latex stain in place of paint. While it can
peel, it may not peel as much as paint.
</P>
<P>
   And, on bare wood, consider semitransparent stain, especially on
decks and deck floors. Semitransparent stain will not peel.
</P>
<P>
   Stain will last about five years, not as long as most paints if
they do not peel; but with luck, you'll have no peeling.
</P>
<P>
   And, above all, apply thin coats.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, oh! Resolution Alert! Wouldn't you know, the last six
resolutions were broken as we ran out of space.
</P>
<P>
   Well, they'll just have to wait until next Sunday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-31-98 1137EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
