A3360 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-SEALED-BOS &LR;      12-31 0720
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-SEALED-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EMOTIONAL CLAUSTROPHOBIA INSIDE ISRAEL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALISON BASS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
FROM A SEALED ROOM 
By Rachel Kadish 
Putnam, 356 pp., $25.95 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rachel Kadish's ambitious first novel begins in a sealed room, a
Jerusalem bedroom sealed against a feared Scud missile attack, the
kind that hit Tel Aviv and Haifa a number of times during the 1991
Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
   As quickly becomes clear in the book, the sealed room works as a
metaphor on several levels: an Israeli couple's stale marriage and
the stagnancy of peace talks between Israel and the Palestinians
(this is before the Oslo accords of 1993). But while Kadish begins
and ends her novel with that room, giving us a poignant and
surprisingly powerful tale in the changes that take place outside
it, she might have served her readers better by discarding the
metaphor, or at least not trying so hard to make it work.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that although Kadish begins the book with one
story _ about Nacham and Tami, the Israeli couple whose apartment
contains the sealed room _ she abruptly shifts gears after the
first chapter and spends the rest of the book weaving a tale about
an immature American student who is running away from her
strong-willed do-gooder mother, only to discover the dark
underbelly of Israeli society.
</P>
<P>
   Maya's relationships _ with her mother, who heals souls in the
bleakness of Brooklyn's slums; with Gil, her Israeli boyfriend
whose father's death in the Yom Kippur war leaves him deeply
flawed; and with her mysterious downstairs neighbor _ turn out to
be the heart of the novel. Readers who are patient enough to stay
with the book, despite its dry beginning and abrupt shift in story,
are well rewarded in the end.
</P>
<P>
   Kadish, who obviously has spent time in Israel and seems to know
the country and its people well, does a nice job in capturing the
sensibility of modern-day Sabras (native-born Israelis), their
ambivalence over the peace process, their unapologetic wit, and
their steadfast loyalty to the land and each other. She also
accurately depicts the religious and ethnic hostilities that divide
Israel, not only those between Jew and Arab, but between Jew and
Jew.
</P>
<P>
   When Maya moves out of the university dorm, where she is
attending a semester abroad, and into her boyfriend's apartment,
her roommates talk with disdain about the ``blacks'' who live in
her new neighborhood. The term confuses Maya, until she realizes
that it refers not to people with dark skin, but to the
ultra-religious Jews, who dress in black, are exempt from military
service, and are ostracized and indeed loathed by the country's
more secular Jews.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond her astute characterization of the broader cultural
milieu, Kadish is equally adept at building a tone of quiet menace,
as Maya becomes increasingly isolated from her university friends
and more dependent on Gil, a moody loner who may be talented as an
artist but has flunked his country's most important test: its
mandatory military service.
</P>
<P>
   Yet while Kadish carefully assembles the building blocks of what
is to become a dangerously abusive relationship, the most poignant
parts of the novel revolve around Maya's relationship with two
women: her mother, who is dying of cancer, and her elusive
downstairs neighbor, who is a Holocaust survivor and quite mad as a
result.
</P>
<P>
   The story of mad Shifra and what she wants from Maya the
American is perhaps the novel's strongest and most haunting
feature. Kadish sketches Shifra's life, as a young Polish woman
caught in the horrors of the Holocaust, with a lyrical touch, and
while her prose is sometimes disjointed and grandiose, it succeeds
in capturing attention in a way that Maya's relationship with her
abusive boyfriend, or her cousin Tami's airless marriage, does not.
</P>
<P>
   And in the end, it is not the metaphor of the sealed room or the
fact that Nacham and Tami's marriage suddenly blooms (as does the
Israeli peace process) as the room becomes unsealed that pack the
emotional punch in this novel. What ultimately proves to be most
affecting is what Maya learns about life from the two women in her
life _ her mother and her neighbor, who keeps trying
(unsuccessfully of course) to fix the unfixable and change the
unfathomable past.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-31-98 1138EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
