<DOCNO> NYT19981231.0142 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-31 11:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3362 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COMPUTERS-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      12-31 0683
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLUNDERS AND BRILLIANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Journalism is the first rough draft of history,'' the saying
goes. But we technology journalists write up the first rough draft
of prophecy. We wander in a wilderness of books, trade magazines,
and Web pages, listening for voices to guide us and our readers
down the True Path toward the Next Big Thing.
</P>
<P>
   I've already owned up to my most idiotic prediction of the year,
the inevitable failure of the Apple iMac. Some failure; I'm using
one of them right now.
</P>
<P>
   It's harder to grade my other judgments of the waning year,
since I don't usually make ex cathedra pronouncements of the sort
that got me in trouble with the iMac.
</P>
<P>
   Once in a while, I hit the bull's-eye. Back in February, I began
singing the praises of the free Linux operating system as an
alternative to Microsoft Windows. I even suggested that embattled
browser-maker Netscape Communications Corp. do a deal with a Linux
distributor to hit Microsoft where it hurts.
</P>
<P>
   From my keyboard to Jim Barksdale's brain. The Netscape CEO made
just such a deal in September with Red Hat Software Inc., the top
Linux distributor. The giant chipmaker Intel also signed on. And
now there are reports that IBM Corp. is talking to Red Hat about
providing worldwide customer support for Linux users. From geek
curiosity to major industry in less than a year; yes, I'd say I got
Linux right.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the columns that hit the target but miss the
center ring. I wrote that 1998 was to be the year of ADSL, a
dazzling technology that can download Internet data at millions of
bits per second over home telephone lines. Yet only a tiny handful
of consumers have ADSL service at home.
</P>
<P>
   I wasn't exactly wrong; my calendar was just running a few
months fast. Indeed, for computer firms and phone companies, 1998
was indeed the year of ADSL. At last, there's an industrywide
technical standard, so that everybody's ADSL gear will work with
everybody else's. Major computer makers, such as Compaq, now build
ADSL chips into some of their machines, and telephone companies are
just beginning to offer the service in cities like Washington, D.C.
Boston's due to go on line with ADSL in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Still, many in the industry doubt that consumers want high-speed
access. An October study from the Gartner Group predicted that by
the year 2003, nearly two-thirds of US consumers with Internet
access will still be using those slow telephone modems.
</P>
<P>
   I also ran way ahead of the curve in a March column in which I
sang the praises of network computers. Remember NCs? These cheap,
diskless devices, remotely controlled by powerful server computers,
were supposed to replace PCs in many corporate offices. Nearly
every tech expert in the land predicted they'd sell by the
millions. It just hasn't happened; dramatic PC price drops
eliminated a major advantage of NCs. Now most of the pundits have
turned on the NC makers with fangs bared.
</P>
<P>
   Not me. I still say they'll catch on. I can see hints that it's
happening. IBM just sold several thousand of them to a couple of
major companies. Here at the Globe, we're testing an NC from Wyse
Technology Inc. that could replace hundreds of old terminals
scattered throughout the building.
</P>
<P>
   NCs still have big advantages. Firms can save a fortune by
managing thousands of computer terminals from a central control
point. And millions of workers who merely need access to a few
basic computer functions shouldn't have to master a device as
complex and fragile as a traditional PC. The NC is an idea that's
too reasonable to die.
</P>
<P>
   So I've got a spectacularly bad prediction on the iMac, and a
Linux call that was so on-target it's spooky. Yes, my timing was
off on ADSL and network computers, but I bet those columns will
read like works of genius by next December. Of course, by then,
I'll have another year's worth of blunders to answer for.
</P>
<P>
   (You can send electronic mail to Hiawatha Bray at
bray(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
