u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-FIESTA-BOS &LR;      12-31 0731
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-FIESTA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOONER THAN EXPECTED, OUTZEN'S TIME HAS COME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. _ He's 20. He's excited, not nervous. That, says
Marcus Outzen, doesn't happen to him.
</P>
<P>
   Sounds good, doesn't it? Makes for a good story line, too.
Inexperienced sophomore quarterback comes off the bench in the
middle of the season and leads his team to the national
championship.
</P>
<P>
   Fairy tales, of course, can come true, which is what Marcus
Outzen feels will happen Monday night when Florida State meets
Tennessee for the national championship in the Fiesta Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   The original script, drawn up at the start of the season, had
Outzen, a 6-foot-2-inch, 220-pounder whose main duties included
running the scout team offense, sitting, watching, learning, and
ultimately waiting while Chris Weinke, a 26-year-old sophomore ran
the offense.
</P>
<P>
   That's the way it is at schools like Florida State. ``I was a
sophomore and I was going to sit and learn and wait my chance.
Everybody comes here thinking they can play, but not everyone can
do that.''
</P>
<P>
   At least not right away. So Outzen, who came out of the same
high school, Fort Walton Beach (Fla.), that produced University of
Florida Heisman winner Danny Wuerffel, came to FSU knowing he would
have to wait his chance.
</P>
<P>
   But even Outzen, who grew up rooting for the Seminoles, began to
wonder following what has become almost an obligatory freshman
redshirt year at FSU, when he saw not only Weinke, but Dan Kendra
ahead of him on the depth chart, both with a couple of years of
eligibility remaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was discouraged, but I never really considered transferring
out of here,'' said Outzen. ``I always wanted to be a Seminole.''
</P>
<P>
   Until midway through the Virginia game Nov. 7, Outzen was a
Seminole-in-waiting, playing only sporadically in mop-up duty
behind Weinke, who was quickly turning into an All-America type.
</P>
<P>
   Then Weinke went down with a neck injury that went from minor to
major when a burner eventually required season-ending, if not
career-threatening surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, it was Outzen's team in a very real sense. ``I've
always had confidence in myself,'' he said. ``I was never one to
get real nervous about things.''
</P>
<P>
   The Florida State coaching staff was. Weinke was untested when
he was handed the job following an injury that ended Kendra's
season before it started, and then Outzen had to follow Weinke.
</P>
<P>
   Outzen led the Seminoles past Virginia in relief and then to
wins over Wake Forest and archrival Florida as the starter. It
wasn't Heisman stuff, but it wasn't throw-up-your-hands-in-dismay
stuff either. He did his job.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a blue-collar worker,'' said Seminoles coach Bobby
Bowden. ``Do you remember (Billy) Kilmer? Who was that quarterback
at California . . . (Joe) Kapp? He's that kind of quarterback. His
ball wobbles. It flutters, but it gets there.''
</P>
<P>
   Outzen, only three games into a career that might return to
backup status next season if Weinke recovers, still has not picked
up all the nuances of playing for FSU. Like Weinke first did, he
sometimes throws the ball before he has to and makes some bad
decisions based on inexperience.
</P>
<P>
   Already he's getting advice from teammates such as tailback
Travis Minor, who has warned him to slide if he takes off on a run.
``He was looking at everybody like, `Slide? I don't even know how
to slide,' '' said Minor, who said it was an indication of Outzen's
personality, which is to take everything head on.
</P>
<P>
   For any quarterback, that can be dangerous. But with one game
remaining in a season that has surprisingly turned into another
championship run for the Seminoles, who seemed to have
self-destructed with a September loss to North Carolina State, why
not take gambles?
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll find a way to get the job done,'' said offensive guard
Jason Whitaker. ``When he was in high school he found a way to win
and he can do that here.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe he can. Maybe this was all scripted from the start and
Marcus Outzen shouldn't really be nervous about playing the No. 1
team in the country on national television for the national
championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``This,'' said Outzen with a smile, shaking the red crew cut
that has earned him the nickname ``Rooster'', ``is the most
exciting thing I could be involved in as a 20-year-old.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
