<SLUG> BC-NBALANCE-UNION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNION, NEW BALANCE STRUGGLE TOWARD FIRST CONTRACT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A union negotiating its first labor contract with New Balance
Athletic Shoe Inc. is questioning the Boston-based sneaker
company's vaunted commitment to US workers, arguing that New
Balance has increasingly turned to low-wage Chinese factories and
US temporary workers to make its shoes.
</P>
<P>
   New Balance has vigorously denied union charges that some of the
company's shoes were made in sweatshop factories in China.
</P>
<P>
   For much of its history, New Balance has portrayed itself as a
David that employs US workers to take on such sneaker Goliaths as
Nike Inc. and Reebok International Ltd., which routinely have their
shoes made at overseas factories with cheaper labor costs.
</P>
<P>
   In that context, the charges by the Union of Needletrades,
Industrial, and Textile Employees, or Unite, that many New Balance
shoes are made in China by underpaid workers would seem to be a
direct attack on New Balance's credibility.
</P>
<P>
   Giant Nike spends millions on superstar endorsements from the
likes of Michael Jordan. But to sell its shoes, New Balance has
appealed to US consumers partly on patriotic grounds, with a
red-white-and-blue sales pitch that sometimes talks up its
commitment to the American worker.
</P>
<P>
   New Balance says its commitment to American workers is
undiminished. As demand for its shoes has surged, production is up
both at its US facilities and at overseas factories, a company
spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
   For its part, Unite insists that the timing of its so-called
``expose'' of New Balance's ``exploitation'' of Chinese workers is
not an attempt to embarrass the company and win concessions at the
bargaining table.
</P>
<P>
   In using Chinese factories, including one with a history of
``sweatshop conditions,'' New Balance is no different from many
other US athletic footwear companies, according to Unite.
</P>
<P>
   A union representing 250,000 workers in the United States and
Canada, Unite won the right to represent about 70 workers at a New
Balance distribution center in Lawrence last spring and is now
negotiating its first contract with the company.
</P>
<P>
   Unite is the first union ever to represent New Balance workers,
the company said. All told, New Balance said it employs 1,600
full-time workers, most of them in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Unite contends that New Balance is trying to enjoy the best of
both worlds, marketing itself as committed to US workers at the
same time that it's exploiting cheap labor overseas.
</P>
<P>
   ``They try to present themselves as the good-guy alternative,
but they're just like Nike,'' said Unite spokeswoman Judy
Marblestone.
</P>
<P>
   In one case, Nike and New Balance shoes were made at the same
Chinese factory where workers were sometimes paid as little as 19
cents an hour, Marblestone said. ``New Balance has a responsibility
to these workers.''
</P>
<P>
   New Balance spokeswoman Katherine Shepard denied there had been
any exploitation. Not only does New Balance use a consulting firm
to ensure that overseas production complies with all human rights
standards, Shepard said, but New Balance's US shoe production is up
sharply.
</P>
<P>
   With five US factories, New Balance says it is the only major
athletic footwear company to make shoes in the United States,
though it often augments production by contracting work out to both
domestic and overseas shoe factories. Many of the New Balance shoes
made overseas are also sold overseas.
</P>
<P>
   For most sneaker companies, 1998 has been a wretched year. Only
Adidas and New Balance have escaped the nearly industrywide
doldrums caused by a weakening in demand, a shift in fashion
preferences, and the pro basketball lockout.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to many of its rivals, New Balance has enjoyed
double-digit growth for the last few years, Shepard said. Projected
sales for 1998 are $630 million, up 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Demand, she said, has outstripped New Balance's US capacity to
make shoes. At three Maine factories, 1998 production was up 15
percent, precisely in line with sales growth, she noted. But just
increasing domestic production was not enough; to meet demand, New
Balance also had to contract more work out to overseas factories.
</P>
<P>
   For years, New Balance has made its commitment to US workers a
big part of its marketing campaign, and it vigorously fought the
Federal Trade Commission, which objected to New Balance's use of
the phrase, ``Made in the USA,'' in its advertising.
</P>
<P>
   While a global economy has made it increasingly difficult for US
manufacturers to assemble their products entirely with US-made
components, New Balance agreed to reword some ads, though it
continues to highlight its commitment to American workers.
</P>
<P>
   It's this commitment that Unite is challenging. According to the
union's analysis of trade figures, New Balance's imports from China
were up 36 percent for the first nine months of 1998, when compared
with the same period in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   When Unite did a spot check of retail stores this fall, 66 of
the 119 New Balance shoes sampled were made entirely in China,
Marblestone said.
</P>
<P>
   Shepard said she couldn't comment on Unite's charges but said
that production has been up from all sources, domestic and foreign.
</P>
<P>
   A small percentage of New Balance shoes are made entirely in the
United States, and some are made entirely in China. Many shoes are
made in the United States, using some Chinese materials. In those
cases, the company has said previously that 70 percent of the
shoe's value in dollars and labor have come from the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Unite and the Massachusetts AFL-CIO said that they staged a
protest in Boston the weekend before Christmas near a Foot Locker
store, one of the industry's most important retail customers.
</P>
<P>
   At the Foot Locker protest, Kathleen Casavant,
secretary-treasurer of the Massachusetts AFL-CIO, said in a
statement: ``It's shameful that New Balance, a company right here
in our back yard, is profiting on the backs of workers suffering
sweatshop conditions in China and low-wage, no-benefit temporary
workers in Massachusetts.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, negotiators for Unite and New Balance are still
trying to iron out such contract issues as the use of temporary
workers in the Lawrence distribution center.
</P>
<P>
   The center opened 18 months ago, and New Balance is still trying
to gauge the appropriate size for the full-time work force, Shepard
said. Until that can be resolved, New Balance is likely to use
temporary workers off and on.
</P>
<P>
   Marblestone insisted there was no connection between Unite's
negotiations and its sweatshop protest. Unite has staged similar
protests against such retailers as Guess? Inc. and May Department
Stores Co., she said.
</P>
<P>
   As for the timing of the New Balance protest, she said Unite
waited until the holidays because that's the time of year shoppers
are out and most likely to notice a demonstration.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is all about the decent treatment of workers,'' said
Marblestone, who added that job security is another key issue in
the contract negotiations between Unite and New Balance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
