<HEADER>
A3374 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SKI-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      12-31 0890
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKI-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN SEARCH OF SNOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY CHAMBERLAIN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARRABASSETT VALLEY, Maine _ We spot the first snow on the
ground north of Waterville, sparse little patches of crusty white
on the brown farm fields. But at least it is cold now so that
skaters on the ponds offer some proof that winter has finally
arrived in the north country.
</P>
<P>
   As we gain elevation driving from Kingfield to the base of
Sugarloaf, the snow is thicker off the roadsides but still not
abundant enough to lend any whiteness to the dark pine woods on one
side nor the rock-strewn riverbed on the other. Even the
Carrabassett itself is low, a dry trickle in this dry northern
winter.
</P>
<P>
   And so it is with sinking expectations that we make the familiar
swing around the Oh-My-God corner for our first view of Sugarloaf
this year, its dark pyramidal bulk streaked with the white lines of
ski trails.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, white! Amazing as it seems, there is a ski mountain up
there.
</P>
<P>
   Much has been made about the reporting of ski conditions and the
trustworthiness of using adjectives. ``Skiing's great. Skiing's
lousy. Skiing's OK.'' What does it all mean? One person's ``good''
is another person's ``wretched,'' and so forth.
</P>
<P>
   The practice of describing ski conditions with summary
adjectives was dropped by the ski areas after a lawsuit some 20
years ago ruled that a skier was misled by the term ``excellent.''
</P>
<P>
   So for the reader/skier who's wondering what kind of skiing
really awaits as we head into the final weekend of the vacation
week, here is as non-summary strewn a description as we can
conjure. This was the skiing Tuesday, before any snowfall that has
been predicted for the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, the roads here are so bare that pedestrians around
the village have to actually watch out for cars. A bad sign. Normal
winter in a ski town the roads are so packed with ice the cars must
creep through the deep ruts and holes that pitch them up and down
like rocking boats.
</P>
<P>
   But now the roads are bare and dusty, what ice there was having
been washed away by last week's rain, leaving only the ash residue
used to aid traction. And it is with another sinking feeling that
we walk across the bare fields from the condo to the chairlift,
strung for half a mile from the base of the mountain down to the
condo cluster we are staying in.
</P>
<P>
   From chairlift height we see the real condition of this stingy,
constipated winter. The chairlift tract is a jumble of rocks and
stumps with just enough snow teasing it to make the scene really
ugly. Off to the left, several closed trails have the same teased
effect _ just enough snow to put a white tinge on the stubble and
rock. As if they are needed, ropes are strung across the trail
entrances.
</P>
<P>
   As the lift closes over the landing we slide off on snow _ real
snow, white, deep, and packed! Amazing!
</P>
<P>
   Even more amazing is the first run. It is 8:35 a.m. and Tote
Road winds out in front of us with groomed snow from side to side.
At this hour we have the trail pretty much to ourselves and as we
gain conidence that we are not going to ski off the edge of the
earth, we pick up speed. Every switchback turn, every rill and
drop, and the three faces on this 2 1/2-mile run are packed and
groomed. The snow is not deep underfoot, but the carving is easy
all the way down, and we finish the run with a fast runout back to
the quad.
</P>
<P>
   Next trail: Narrow Gauge, a classic cruiser, somewhat steeper
than Tote Road and with a steep headwall that skiers like to use to
launch themselves up to full speed. We hold back a bit over the
top, expecting ice, rocks _ whatever unfriendly things are usually
buried in snow. Except for one extremely steep face down a
whaleback where few windblown rocks appeared (in plenty of time to
avoid) the Gauge was covered with snow.
</P>
<P>
   With confidence buying a bit of speed now, we launched down the
headwall. Snow still! All the way onto the flatter runout to the
lift. It was as good a run as we have had on the Gauge, one of
Sugarloaf's bread and butter trails.
</P>
<P>
   Now, truth to tell, with 35 of over 100 trails open, the crowds
did gang up on the lower quad (one 15-minute wait was the longest
of the day; the rest were under 10) and on some of the trails. Tote
Road became a bit zooey by mid-morning, and the Gauge was busy, but
not claustrophobically so.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side, Ramdown and Widowmaker were busy at times,
and the cover began to get skied down everywhere by midday. But
then, a fortuitous combination of diminishing crowd and warming
temperatures made the afternoon skiing a delight on most of the
open acreage.
</P>
<P>
   We are not here to kid you. At this writing ski country is in a
serious snow drought. Small southern areas without snowmaking are
hurting desperately. But snowmaking areas in the northern states
and the Berkshires have been cranking the snowguns for an unbroken
two weeks now, and you do not have to be some diehard nut case to
find plenty of skiing pleasure on the slopes at this very moment.
</P>
<P>
   Is it ideal? Hell no. And perfection in the form of a few
foot-deep dumps is undoubtedly on the way. But, as is the case at
Sugarloaf, and all the major resorts where snow production is the
primary focus, the skiing is surprisingly good.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
