<DOCNO> NYT19981231.0149 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-31 11:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3376 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SKI-YEAR-BOS &LR;      12-31 1191
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKI-YEAR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPILLS AND CHILLS IN 1998 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY CHAMBERLAIN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The big skiing and snowboarding stories kept coming all year,
from a righteous boycott of the Olympic establishment by a
super-athlete, to a misguided righteousness that led to big-time
crime in the Colorado Rockies.
</P>
<P>
   _JANUARY _ The year started with the untimely and wholly
unnecessary death of Michael Kennedy who, as he played a game of
pass football on Aspen Mountain with family members, skied into a
tree, dying instantly from head injuries. Weeks later, when Sonny
Bono died in a similar collision with a tree, the age of safety
helmets was given a huge boost that is obvious on the slopes today.
</P>
<P>
   _JANUARY _ The great ice storm of '98 may have been a nuisance
around the Boston area, but it was absolutely paralyzing in the
north country, ruinous to trees, farmland, and buildings, and it
took the electric power grid down for over a month in some areas.
It was a momentous storm, with exactly the right mix of moisture
and temperature to maintain a prolonged icing that built an
ever-thicker coating for at least eight hours.
</P>
<P>
   Life was disrupted in Maine, New Hampshire, and Vermont, but no
industry was harder hit than skiing. The ice storm came after a
meltdown period, so that some ski areas were out of business for a
month.
</P>
<P>
   Hardest hit by the storm was the state of Maine, which regards
as heroes the legions of electric power workers from all over the
country who converged on the Pine Tree State and worked until
spring getting the power grid put back together.
</P>
<P>
   _JANUARY _ As snowboarding was making its debut in full medal
Olympic competition, Norwegian Terry Haakenson, considered by most
observers to be the best halfpipe rider in the world, announced his
boycott of the Nagano Games, largely, he said, because the
International Ski Federation and the Olympic organizers were trying
to use snowboarding to market the Games to a younger generation.
Meanwhile, said Haakenson, Olympic officials are corrupt, old men
entrenched in their jobs who live a life of luxury off the efforts
of athletes who are forced to live in Spartan quasi-military
conditions. Haakenson followed through on his threat and never
showed up at the Games, and his charges, that once seemed
exaggerated, have gained credence with recent revelations of
corruption at the highest levels of Olympic management.
</P>
<P>
   _FEBRUARY _ Those who had been at the Alpine World Championships
in Nagano in 1996 warned of extremely fickle weather in the
mountain ski venues, weather that could switch from wintry blizzard
conditions to warm monsoon rains and back again within a matter of
hours. Sure enough, Olympice ski racers encountered weather that
switched from wintry blizzards to warm monsoon rains within hours.
It was clear that the Olympic site slection committee had again
rolled the dice with Nagano, and just made it under the wire. By
the Games' end, all five make-up days built into the schedule had
been used.
</P>
<P>
   _FEBRUARY _ Picabo Street finally stood on the highest step of
an Olympic medal platform as, following a training crash and
concussion a week before the Games, she won the Super-G, fulfilling
her promise as the hottest female speed skier in the history of the
US Ski team. That career all but ended a month later when Street
suffered a high-speed crash in the last World Cup downhill, with
knee injuries so severe she was forced to take off this year from
racing. Street said she likely will not ski speed events again,
though she is still considering trying to make the technical team
so she can race when the Olympics come to the US in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   _FEBRUARY _ Even as Alberto Tomba, the most famous ski racer of
all time, wound up his Olympic career with an inglorious fall in
the slalom, a new boffo, larger-than-life ski racer was coming on.
Austrian Hermann Maier may have been the fastest downhiller in the
world, but it was his famous flight and agony-of-defeat
crash-landing for which he will be best remembered in Nagano. Maier
hit a badly banked lefthander going way too fast, flew sideways off
the hill, and landed in a snow fence 300 yards down the course.
Said the former bricklayer with a grin: ``It wasn't Lufthansa, but
it wasn't bad.'' Maier went on to take gold in the Super-G.
</P>
<P>
   _OCTOBER _ Vail will recover from the $12-million arson fire
that wiped out several buildings, including a large summit
restaurant, but the environmental movement was dealt a lasting
blow. As the damage to buildings and lifts was being assessed, a
group calling itself Earth Liberation Front (ELF) claimed
responsibility for the fires, which they set in protest of an
880-acre expansion plan into the wilderness designated as lynx
habitat. Though no lynxes have been spotted in the area for 25
years, ELF said in its note: ``Putting profits ahead of Colorado's
wildlife will not be tolerated. This action is just a warning.''
</P>
<P>
   With the World Alpine Championships at Vail just a month away,
officials have stepped up security, importing police from the
overseas countries represented by competing ski racers. Regular
patrols will be on duty to make sure ELF doesn't make good on its
threat before an international audience.
</P>
<P>
   _OCTOBER-DECEMBER _ With plans to move on to the more lucrative
world of pro ski racing, Tommy Moe, the 1994 Olympic downhill
champion, announced his retirement on the heels of teammate AJ
Kitt. Weeks later, the third US downhill veteran, Kyle Rassmussen,
also retired after years of complaining about life on the road away
from his young family.
</P>
<P>
   The plot thickens. Kitt and Moe formed a team to compete in the
pro Ford Downhill Tour, but in training last week, Kitt broke his
wrist in a high-speed crash, and is out for the season, leaving Moe
partnerless on the eve of the first race at Aspen. Moe then called
Rassmussen, who hasn't been on skis all year, and who threw some
belongings together and made it from California to Aspen the night
before the race.
</P>
<P>
   Beating veteran Olympic champions such as Leonard Stock and
Peter Wirnsberger from Austria, Luc Alphand from France, Conrad
Cathomen of Switzerland and Felix Belczyk of Canada, Rassmussen won
the Aspen race last Sunday with an average speed of 78-plus miles
per hour, 1.4 mph faster than Alphand and Wirnsberger. Moe placed
fourth.
</P>
<P>
   _OCTOBER-DECEMBER _ The tears flowed freely in Italy when
favorite son Alberto Tomba announced his retirement. After 50 World
Cup wins (second only to Ingemar Stenmark with 86) and five Olympic
medals in three games, Tomba, 33, decided to hang up his skis. The
impact on the World Cup scene is severe, according to marketers at
recent races at Alta Badia and Siestre, Italy. On days when Tomba
used to race, 15,000 boisterous, bell-banging, flag-waving fans
would turn out to cheer La Bomba, often to victory. Now, alas, the
last two Italian World Cups drew a scant 1,000 fans, even though
Italy fielded two strong skiers. To a lesser extent, said World Cup
observers, Tomba's absence is being felt at venues throughout
Europe.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
