<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-31 11:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3380 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-$ADV05-     12-31 1122
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-$ADV05-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A WALK IN THE SNOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Tuesday Jan. 5)  
 By SUSAN SWARTZ   
 Santa Rosa (Calif.) Press Democrat   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As we trudged across the flat, wide expanse of Squaw Valley via
snowshoes, I grumbled to my companions that we were working harder
at having fun than anyone else in the valley, except for maybe the
hiker we passed who was carrying his dog. The dog had apparently
pooped out and was ready to hit the lodge and take a nap. We were
starting to feel like the dog on this first venture on snowshoes.
</P>
<P>
   To us it felt like hiking with ankle weights and wet jeans,
particularly going uphill, which is where we unwisely began our
experiment. Actually we didn't go straight up a hill, we snowshoed
straight to the bottom of a hill through a parking lot. Then we
were so hungry we decided to eat half a sandwich each and then went
up the hill.
</P>
<P>
   In our group there were three who normally prefer skiing _ one
downhill, one cross-country, one who will do both.
</P>
<P>
   We all are fairly fit. We were ready to try something that is
supposed to be the newest thing in the snow. But we were whipped by
the first hour. The downhiller begged to take off her shoes and go
stand in line for hot drinks. I was remembering that the first time
I tried cross country skiing I also whined, and so I insisted we
push on.
</P>
<P>
   That's when we hit the flat part of Squaw Valley, which might
have been a good starting place but we'd given our all on the
hills.
</P>
<P>
   There's nothing to it, they had told us at the rental counter.
``Just walk,'' said the rental clerk who pointed out the door.
</P>
<P>
   They have this mantra, the snowshoe people, which you read in
every magazine story and advertisement about the sport. It is, ``If
you can walk, you can snowshoe.''
</P>
<P>
   They're right, but it's not a graceful walk. It's a hampered
walk, more lurch and drag, at least at first.
</P>
<P>
   The clerk rented us boots to go with the snowshoes. I've since
learned that it's better, even advisable, to use your own hiking
boots. They're broken in, they're comfortable and as long as
they're waterproof they'll work just fine.
</P>
<P>
   The boots we rented were the same that snowboarders use _ fat,
wide shoes that give you cartoon feet. So maybe we were having as
much a problem adjusting to them as to the snowshoes underneath.
</P>
<P>
   We decided the hardest part of the sport, after the energy
expenditure, is bending down to put the snowshoes back on after
they slip off the boots.
</P>
<P>
   That is not supposed to happen, I have since been told.
</P>
<P>
   All grumbling aside, the best part of being on snowshoes is that
you take yourself right into the middle of a Christmas card picture
and are virtually alone. There is no great gang of snowshoers
breathing down your neck. If you want, it can be just you and the
snow, the waterfall, the birds.
</P>
<P>
   The guy at the rental center said ``purists don't use ski
poles'' so we didn't ask for them, but not being purists we
actually could have used them. I've since read that ski poles can
help you scoot uphill and save the legs.
</P>
<P>
   Compared to cross country skis, it's easier to get uphill on
snowshoes _ you feel a little like Spiderwoman - but it's not as
much fun coming downhill. Nordic ski centers and ski resorts across
the country are all starting to offer snowshoeing as a sideline.
Most ski rental places in the Lake Tahoe area rent snowshoes and
encourage them as an inexpensive alternative to skiing, a good
aerobic workout and something to do when the snow isn't good enough
for skiing.
</P>
<P>
   The December snow at Tahoe, so far, has been good for both, but
Victoria Crummy at Dave's Rentals in Tahoe City said snowshoes work
in almost any snow.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have conditions that aren't conducive to skiing you
can snowshoe. And you can go anywhere.'' She started to say the
thing about ``If you can walk...'' but added that ``you do have to
take a little bit wider step than regular walking.''
</P>
<P>
   She, like most, say you don't need lessons, although there are
places like the Royal Gorge area at Donner Summit that advertise
guides, and presumably, with that, a little guidance.
</P>
<P>
   It's a workout. Melanie Griffith reportedly boasts that she
lifted her butt by three inches taking a daily snowshoe running up
Aspen Mountain.
</P>
<P>
   A writer for Health Magazine figured if you snowshoe a 20 minute
per mile pace on packed snow you burn about 510 calories an hour.
If it's loose snow you burn twice as much.
</P>
<P>
   People who live in the mountains and can't bear to give up
jogging for the winter naturally take to snowshoes and there is now
a special jogging snowshoe that is smaller and narrower than the
regular ones.
</P>
<P>
   The snowshoe frame is made out of lightweight space-age metals
and plastics. The bindings which hold the boot are made of rubber,
plastic or synthetic fabric. Underneath the shoe are crampons, the
steel teeth that bite into snow and ice for traction. Most
snowshoes are about a foot and half long, 6 to 8 inches across. The
shoes don't look like they have a right and left, but technically
the binding buckle is usually on the outside.
</P>
<P>
   The beauty of snowshoes is you can pick a spot and walk off,
although Royal Gorge allows snowshoers to use their cross country
ski trails as long as you stay off the groomed part.
</P>
<P>
   Other Tahoe rental places, like Dave's which has four locations
renting snowshoes, will provide lists of good snowshoes sites like
state park land.
</P>
<P>
   The same kind of common sense is advised as cross country. Bring
a map, compass, sunglasses, flashlight, and matches. Also an energy
bar and water bottle. So far there is no dress requirement for
snowshoes. Layers like you use in cross country skiing will work,
including long underwear, tops and bottoms in a polypropylene or
polyester synthetic, wool or synthetic blend pants with waterproof
nylon overshell; warm shirt or fleece with sweater and windproof
nylon shell; polypropylene sock liners under wool socks; waterproof
boots; waterproof gaiters over the boots; wool or fleece cap and
face mask, and wool or fleece gloves with overmitts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people just wear layers on top and jeans with gaiters,''
said Crummy.
</P>
<P>
   A friend who is an avid downhiller said he can't imagine why
anyone would want to snowshoe unless you lived in the mountains and
needed a way to get from your house to the garage.
</P>
<P>
   But that may be the way of all trends. You go through an awkward
period and gripe and then you either mush off or keep trying it
until you flaunt it.
</P>
<P>
   We're thinking of trying it again.
</P>
<P>
   (Susan Swartz is a staff writer and columnist for The Press
Democrat in Santa Rosa, Calif. Her e-mail address is
sfswartzpressdemo.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
