<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-1998-MOVIES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DON'T BELIEVE THE HYPE; 1998 WAS A GREAT YEAR FOR MOVIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By AMY BIANCOLLI  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Don't believe anyone who says 1998 wasn't a corking-good year at
the movies.
</P>
<P>
   Critics l-o-o-o-ve to carp about subpar films and crushed
expectations and directors or actors or studios on the verge of
precipitous slides.
</P>
<P>
   As usual, there were great films and there were bad ones, and
there were pundits poised to comment on each and every one. And, as
usual, the year drew to a close with dour talk of slim pickings at
Oscar time.
</P>
<P>
   A weak field of pictures, they say. Too many bombs. Too few
standouts. Too much money blown on big-studio dross.
</P>
<P>
   Phooey. Balderdash. Cow manure. Bunk.
</P>
<P>
   So rich was the recent movie year that coming up with the
obligatory 10 Best List was an absolute snap. It took five minutes,
tops.
</P>
<P>
   The only problem was choosing a mere 10; on reflection there
were half a dozen others that deserved a berth.
</P>
<P>
   And that's taking into account the delayed Albany market, which
won't see a handful of Oscar-caliber, end-of-'98 releases until a
month or so into '99.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gods and Monsters,'' ``A Civil Action,'' ``The Thin Red
Line,'' ``Affliction,'' ``Central Station,'' ``Waking Ned Devine''
_ all are drumming major Academy buzz, and none have yet opened
anywhere near my hometown. We're patient souls, we Northern
moviegoers.
</P>
<P>
   All the same, it's been a most rewarding spell at the cineplex.
</P>
<P>
   It was a nice year for Elizabethan drama (``Elizabeth,''
``Shakespeare in Love,''), for World War II films (``Saving Private
Ryan,'' ``Life is Beautiful,'' the coming ``Thin Red Line''), for
political satire (``Bulworth,'' ``Primary Colors''), for
traditional animation (``The Prince of Egypt,'' ``Mulan''), for
computer-bug animation (``A Bug's Life,'' ``Antz'') _ and for the
Fiennes brothers, Joseph and Ralph, who lent their talents to no
fewer than three of the top-10 films listed below. They are:
</P>
<P>
   1. ``SAVING PRIVATE RYAN'': ``Ryan'' was the big-wow movie of
the year, a masterfully ghastly World War II film that opened with
a graphic 25-minute D-Day sequence of unforgettable power and gore.
Steven Spielberg's hyper-realistic direction, paired with a
transparent performance by Tom Hanks, made this the movie of the
moment, of the summer and of the year.
</P>
<P>
   2. ``LIFE IS BEAUTIFUL'': Another World War II film, this one _
directed by and starring beloved Italian comic Roberto Benigni _
managed to find bittersweet comedy in the Holocaust. Benigni played
a Jewish bookseller, trapped in a concentration camp, who shields
his young son from Nazi horrors by turning them into an elaborate
game. The result was a profoundly touching ode to parental love.
</P>
<P>
   3. ``THE TRUMAN SHOW'': The evils of television have rarely been
so cunningly detailed; not since ``Network'' has a film so
brilliantly plumbed the Machiavellian depths of the boob tube. Jim
Carrey turned in a subtle, un-Carrey-esque performance as Truman
Burbank, a young man who slowly realizes that his home is a sound
stage and that his life is literally a soap opera. Peter Weir's
masterpiece also gave us the year's most surreal image: Carrey
climbing, Magritte-like, along a wall of painted clouds.
</P>
<P>
   4. ``A BUG'S LIFE'': ``Bug'' wasn't just the best
computer-animated arthropod movie of the year (forget ``Antz'') _
it was one of the best, giddiest animated movies ever. An insect
spin on ``The Magnificent Seven,'' this irresistible Disney-Pixar
production gave us eccentric multilegged characters voiced by a
whip-smart cast (Kevin Spacey, Dave Foley, Denis Leary, Julia
Louis-Dreyfus). Hilarious and perfect.
</P>
<P>
   5. ``ELIZABETH'': This revisionist-feminist take on England's
Virgin Queen was also a vicious, gripping thriller. Indian director
Shekhar Kapur's English-language debut featured a breathtaking Cate
Blanchett as Elizabeth, a smouldering Joseph Fiennes as her lover
and a crackling Geoffrey Rush as her politically savvy, morally
skewed advisor. It exploded every prejudice we ever had against
period films.
</P>
<P>
   6. ``LOVE AND DEATH ON LONG ISLAND'': Though it was released so
long ago (back in March) that it doesn't feel like a '98 release,
Richard Kwietniowski's compassionate, quietly funny look at a
stuffy Englishman's (John Hurt) mad crush on an American teen idol
(Jason Priestly) was one of the year's sweetest pleasures. Hurt was
devastating as the obsessed Giles De'Ath (pronounced ``Day-Ath'');
Priestly was good and cool. The result was Thomas Mann's ``Death in
Venice,'' transformed by American pop culture.
</P>
<P>
   7. ``THE PRINCE OF EGYPT'': Whodathunkit: a sophisticated,
adult-oriented, biblically themed animated musical featuring
neither upbeat anthems nor cutie-pie anthropomorphic sidekicks. And
who would have guessed that DreamWorks' superlative take on the
life of Moses, deliverer of Israel, would be such a deeply touching
film? Val Kilmer voiced Moses; Ralph Fiennes voiced the Pharaoh
Rameses; the rest of us voiced amazement.
</P>
<P>
   8. ``SHAKESPEARE IN LOVE'': The year's other insanely watchable
Elizabethan film also featuring Joseph Fiennes (again in
heaving-chest mode), also boasting Geoffrey Rush in a vivid
supporting role. But where ``Elizabeth'' shows the grim, gruesome
side of the 16th century, John Madden's ``Shakespeare in Love''
incorporates lyrical eroticism with bursts of wacky lightness.
You've never seen a drama _ or a comedy _ like this before.
</P>
<P>
   9. ``BULWORTH'': Warren Beatty's outrageous rap-riff on the
moral bankruptcy of modern politics didn't do too well at the box
office, but so what. It's a shocking bit of filmmaking, this tale
of a suicidal Congressman (Beatty) who hires a hit-man to do him
in, then adorns hip-hop clothing and raps his way to prominence. Go
figure.
</P>
<P>
   10. ``MEN WITH GUNS'': John Sayles' hard, unwavering study of
South American terrorism was a rough piece of celluloid, made with
(mostly) unknowns and scripted in numerous tongues. ``Saving
Private Ryan'' notwithstanding, it contained some of the most
harrowing footage released in '98 and it concluded, against all
hope, with a nod toward redemption.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, a few Honorable Mentions: ``Beloved,'' for Oprah
Winfrey's tragic plainness and Jonathan Demme's metaphoric
direction; ``Out of Sight,'' for George Clooney's star turn
(finally) and Steven Soderbergh's bemused direction; ``Mulan,'' for
Disney's David Lean-inspired animation and girl-power message;
``The Spanish Prisoner,'' for the Rubik's Cube in David Mamet's
brain; ``One True Thing,'' for Meryl Streep's spectacularly gauged
performance as a woman dying of cancer; ``Primary Colors,'' for
John Travolta's unnerving impersonation of Bill Clinton; and
``Touch of Evil'' and ``The Wizard of Oz,'' for bringing back the
joys of movies past.
</P>
<P>
   Good year? Nah, it wasn't a good year. It was great.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-31-98 1221EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
