<DOCNO> NYT19981231.0153 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-31 12:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3418 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YE-BESTFILMS-TEX     12-31 1111
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YE-BESTFILMS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIDDEN AMONG THE CHEESY BLOCKBUSTERS WERE SOME PLEASANT SURPRISES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ELVIS MITCHELL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Put ``Stepmom'' and ``Patch Adams'' out of your mind. Because if
you do, you'll find it's been a better year for movies than you
might expect.
</P>
<P>
   This occurred to me as I sat in on a TV panel discussion where a
man railed about the standard issues. ``Hollywood is bankrupt of
ideas,'' he said, confident that no one had ever thought to utter
such a remark.
</P>
<P>
   Considering that two of the most idiosyncratic and distinctive
movies of 1998 _ ``Home Fries'' and ``Rushmore'' _ came out of the
studio system, I had to agree to disagree. (''Rushmore'' is even
from the studio that released ``Armageddon.'' ) And that's not even
mentioning the best picture of the year, ``Out of Sight,'' the
silky and entertaining adaptation of the Elmore Leonard novel,
which showed that the glimmer of talent George Clooney displayed in
Robert Rodriguez's ``From Dust Till Dawn'' wasn't a fluke.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Sight,'' Clooney gave a grown-up movie star performance. Of
course, there was the added enticement of Scott Frank's script and
Steven Soderbergh's purposeful direction _ not to mention Jennifer
Lopez's seductive confidence.
</P>
<P>
   The panelist then attacked ``There's Something About Mary,''
acting as if it were a sign of the eve of the millennium.
Certainly, ``Mary'' isn't much of a movie, but to attack it on
grounds of bad taste is absurd. If you're a 12-year-old, you've
grown up with what used to be called bad taste. You watch ``South
Park'' and sing along to the ``Kenny's Dead'' video. You can catch
the ``Master of My Domain'' episode of ``Seinfeld'' when you get
home from school. Bad taste has become the order of the day.
</P>
<P>
   1998 also had more odd coincidences than any year in recent
memory. There were two films on World War II made by major
directors: Steven Spielberg's masterful ``Saving Private Ryan,''
which, with its constant, harrowing stream of shock, was staged
like a horror movie, and Terrence Malick's ``The Thin Red Line,''
an allusive adaptation of the James Jones novel.
</P>
<P>
   There were also several movies on that ``somebody's watching
me'' theme. ``The Truman Show'' featured Jim Carrey, giving his
first non-tricked-up performance on the big screen, as a man whose
entire life had been a television show. Producer Jerry Bruckheimer
scrambled his team into motion to produce the garishly enjoyable
``Enemy of the State,'' in which every move that Will Smith made
was tracked with surveillance equipment, something he's no doubt
used to by now.
</P>
<P>
   ``Enemy'' almost cleared the metallic aftertaste of one of the
year's worst coincidences, the near-simultaneous release of ``Deep
Impact'' and ``Armageddon,'' which was also produced by
Bruckheimer. As knuckle-headed as Bruckheimer's ``Con Air'' _
perhaps the stupidest, and loudest, movie ever to run through Dolby
labs _ ``Armageddon'' pitted its macho
foreign-object-hurtling-toward-the-Earth story line vs. ``Deep
Impact's'' small, more emotional goofiness.
</P>
<P>
   Macro vs. micro. Or is that Kraft's macaroni &AMP; cheese vs. micro?
In terms of which was worse, it was too close to call, especially
in the kind of competition that no one in his right mind would want
to judge.
</P>
<P>
   The most suspect coincidence of the year was when DreamWorks'
``Antz'' and Disney's ``A Bug's Life'' happened to hit theaters
within a month of each other. Suspect because ``Antz'' was an
answer released before ``Bug's Life'' posed the question: Is there
a satisfying movie to be made using computer animation in the wake
of ``Toy Story''? ``Antz'' proved there definitely ain't two of
'em.
</P>
<P>
   It's definitely unique when two major directors choose the same
kind of material for release in the same year, and for both movies
to end up as the most anticipated pictures of the year. Malick's
return to the cinema with ``Line'' after a self-imposed 20-year
exile came just as a ``Ryan'' backlash began to surface.
</P>
<P>
   ``Line'' will add to this year's
a-tree-falls-a-phone-call-it-joins-all-synchronicity. Nick Nolte's
finely calibrated bluster _ it was once said that if John Wayne
could act, he'd have been Nolte _ is one of the notable
performances in ``Line.''
</P>
<P>
   Nolte turns in a risky, tuned-in job in ``Affliction,'' which
we'll also see here early in 1999. His work makes 1998 the first
year in a while that's likely to result in an actor getting Oscar
nominations in both lead and supporting categories. (We last saw
this in 1983, when Jessica Lange notched nominations for starring
in ``Frances'' and co-starring in ``Tootsie.'')
</P>
<P>
   It's too bad that, in a year with a number of independent films
worth talking about, no one bothered to call 1998 The Year of
Independent Film. (Maybe it's because that overused benediction has
worn thin to the point of transparency.) 1998 saw the release of
``Gods and Monsters'' _ a bio-pic based on a novel about the life
of horror film pioneer James Whale _ a movie so independent that
production shut down because they ran out of money.
</P>
<P>
   It also happened to be one of the year's best films. As was
Darren Arenofsky's ``Pi,'' a slender-budgeted cyberthriller that
also fell into the paranoiac subgenre of ``Truman'' and ``Enemy.''
</P>
<P>
   If any film defined independent, it was Todd Solondz's
``Happiness.'' This cruel, powerful meditation on urban loneliness
_ Solondz's sole theme thus far _ forced pseudo-indie October Films
to put its money where its mouth is. October blinked over the
subject matter _ or rather, its parent company, Universal did _ and
dropped ``Happiness'' after financing it. (You'd think that
Universal would have had better things to find offense in, like
releasing ``Meet Joe Black.'')
</P>
<P>
   Even the ambitious failures, like ``Beloved,'' the lovingly made
if miscalculated adaptation of Toni Morrison's novel, had something
going for them. In ``Beloved,'' it was the extraordinary level of
the performances _ Danny Glover has never been better, and Thandie
Newton and Christine Elise shone. (''The Thin Red Line'' is a
bigger failure, and will be taken far more seriously.)
</P>
<P>
   Warren Beatty's mess of a political satire ``Bulworth'' broke a
sweat trying to return political discourse, and passions, to the
movies. In a year in which political discussion had nothing to do
with the way the country is run, the ideas running through
``Bulworth'' at least seemed original.
</P>
<P>
   (Elvis Mitchell is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7614. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
