<SLUG> BC-NAMES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICHAEL AND KAITLYN WERE TOP NAMES OF 1998 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARSHA GINSBURG  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Move over Andrew and Megan. Here come Madison,
Tyler and Alexis. And don't even try to mess with Michael.
</P>
<P>
   Among American parents favorite names for newborns in 1998,
Michael was the most popular _ for the 35th year in a row. Kaitlyn
reclaimed its No.1 spot for girls after being bumped out of that
position by Sarah last year, according to BabyCenter of San
Francisco, an Internet company that offers on-line baby gear and is
a resource center for expectant and new parents.
</P>
<P>
   But Andrew, which broke into the top 10 list last year, fell
from its No.9 spot and was replaced by Tyler in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Among girls' names, Madison made it to the 10th spot on the 1998
10-best list. Jessica _ which hogged a top spot for most of the
decade _ and Megan were squeezed off the top 10. The other eight
favorites for girls were Emily, Sarah, Hannah, Ashley, Brianna,
Alexis, Samantha and Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   After Michael, which means ``he who is like God,'' the biblical
names of Jacob and Matthew came in second and third, followed by
Nicholas, Joshua, Christopher, Brandon, Austin, Tyler and Zachary.
</P>
<P>
   BabyCenter reported the list after analyzing more than 1 million
Social Security registrations during the first eight months of the
year as well as surveying 2,500 new parents who used the web site.
The South of Market on-line company, which also published the list
of top 100 names of each gender, said the numbers came from all
over the country.
</P>
<P>
   If the most popular boys' names seemed _ no offense guys _ a
little stuffier, it's because parents, especially fathers, seem to
take less chances with boy names, according to Lara Hoyem, a
spokeswoman for the firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Men are less interested in naming babies generally, but their
interest rises more often when having a son,'' Hoyem said. ``Men
are more conservative ... Men are like, `You've got to be kidding.
You're not going to spell it that way.'''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps mindful of the nya-nyas and the other name calling they
grew up with on the playgrounds, baby boomers in general haven't
been as adventurous with names in recent years. Forget Freeddom
John from the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   What parents seem to be doing instead, says Hoyem, is giving
children more traditional or classic names, but spelling them in
unusual ways. Emily, she said, came up on the list with a variety
of spellings, including Emilly and Emmily. Some parents opted to
make Alexis, Alexus, like the car. Then there's Kaitlyn, whose
Greek origin means ``pure.'' Parents spelled it Caitlyn, Katelyn
and Catelyn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Creative spellings are huge,'' said Hoyem of this year's
trend. ``Parents are trying hard to figure out a unique way to give
their baby a name that isn't so unique. I guess this is how parents
are being risky.''
</P>
<P>
   The company also found some other trends: so-called geographic
names _ such as Dakota, Sierra and Savannah _ are on the rise.
Hoyem also has seen old-fashioned names from the turn of the
century _ including Emma, Hannah, Isabella and Anna _ moving up the
list. Traditional men's names are also being given to girls, she
noted, including Taylor, Bailey and Sidney.
</P>
<P>
   Hoyem said what's unknown is whether the national trends match
each region of the country. She found out by talking to an expert,
for example, that William is the No. 1 boy's name in the south, and
predicts it will become more popular nationally over the next few
years.
</P>
<P>
   Hoyem noted that only about 8 percent of those surveyed named
their children after a relative or friend. Most said ``uniqueness''
was their biggest concern.
</P>
<P>
   ``Society is more informal (about last names) and it's more
important now to have a unique first name,'' she said. ``Before
children weren't seen as individuals. Now they are. They're not
just the child of Jack and Jane.''
</P>
</TEXT>
