<SLUG> BC-TV-RESOLUTIONS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOU SAY YOU WANT A RESOLUTION ... 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TIM GOODMAN  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   There may have been an errant resolution last year right about
this time that had something to do with not writing columns about
New Year's resolutions.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, and you're looking a lot slimmer.
</P>
<P>
   That about settles it then.
</P>
<P>
   Let's keep focused, people, and get these things resolved:
</P>
<P>
   UPN: You will think twice _ maybe three times _ before giving
the green light to a comedy about a black butler to Abraham
Lincoln.
</P>
<P>
   All of us will one day, without prodding, sit down and watch
``Unhappily Ever After'' on The WB, just in case someone can figure
out why it's still on.
</P>
<P>
   Calista Flockhart: You will admit your problem and you will eat.
</P>
<P>
   Pop culture writers: You will stop this nonsense about whether
Ally McBeal is or is not a feminist role model. She's a character
created by a man to be entertaining, period.
</P>
<P>
   NBC: You will show up on this list quite a bit. Resolved. Next
you will admit that paying the ``Mad About You'' stars a million an
episode was a pretty obvious mistake, given that anyone who watched
the show knew it was as fresh as a piece of vending machine carrot
cake.
</P>
<P>
   We will all vow to stop being enablers and cease this ludicrous
viewing of ``Dateline NBC.''
</P>
<P>
   NBC: In turn, you will stop blowing up cars or stretching
faux-shocking stories throughout an hour.
</P>
<P>
   Stone Phillips: During the May sweeps you will admit what
everyone already knows: That you are a replicant from ``Blade
Runner.''
</P>
<P>
   Those who are not already, will begin watching ``Buffy the
Vampire Slayer,'' because it's so pop culture savvy that no one who
loves quality _ and quirky _ television should miss it. What more
could you want than a splendid mix of action, comedy, romance and
cynicism?
</P>
<P>
   People who like ``The Nanny'' will agree to wear red arm bands
so we can see them coming.
</P>
<P>
   ABC: Knowing that your new shows are rounding into their own,
you will silently but swiftly rid yourself of ``Home Improvement.''
</P>
<P>
   We will all watch more golf on television and we will love it.
Well, some of us will more than others.
</P>
<P>
   We will only watch Congressional hearings if those taking the
pompous high road are subsequently defrocked by Hustler and paraded
in front of the C-SPAN cameras.
</P>
<P>
   Felicity: You will get drunk and have sex with someone at your
college, then wake up the next day with a major headache and
supreme guilt. Welcome to the real world, babe.
</P>
<P>
   Some kid on ``Kids Say the Darndest Things'' will rise up and
tell Bill Cosby: ``It's shows like this that are driving me and my
peers to the Internet and GameBoy.''
</P>
<P>
   CBS: You will stop apologizing for the fact that most of the
viewers you have are older.
</P>
<P>
   NBC: By showing ``pro'' wrestling you will admit, in public,
that you are taking on a lot of water and the panic and fear can
not be turned back anytime soon, thus explaining and exposing
yourself.
</P>
<P>
   We will take a yoga class or read, maybe, instead of watching
``Touched By An Angel.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox: You will stop showing animals attacking people, any video
of any kind where a car crashes, magicians giving away their trade
secrets or people being kicked ``accidentally'' in the groin.
</P>
<P>
   And all the networks will stop forever the use of ``World's
Scariest'' in their titles.
</P>
<P>
   Andy Rooney: You will, with great patience and attention to
detail, cut your eyebrows.
</P>
<P>
   The History Channel: You will at least try to cut back on the
Hitler documentaries.
</P>
<P>
   We will, despite all of our highbrow rantings, sit down with a
beer and watch a double episode of ``Cops'' at least eight or so
times a season.
</P>
<P>
   And if the location is Las Vegas or there's a domestic
disturbance, we'll have two beers and possibly invite some friends
over.
</P>
<P>
   ``Biography'': You will, just to be different, become a little
more in-depth.
</P>
<P>
   TV programmers (you've got a lot to improve on, so sit
patiently): You will take fewer meetings with people who have
already delivered to you really bad TV shows. You will not, in a
knee-jerk moment, program more ``news'' magazines. You will tell
the truth to the young writers on your shows: ``This is not good
enough. Nor funny enough. Try again.''
</P>
<P>
   You will not copy other shows, particularly lousy ones. Not all
of your female characters will be thin. Your gay characters can
actually, you know, kiss and have sex. You will cancel an older,
lame show instead of ``infusing'' it with new characters.
</P>
<P>
   You will stop marketing all of your shows to teenagers. You
will, at least once a week just for practice, say ``Good Lord
that's a stupid idea. Get your ass out of my office.''
</P>
<P>
   You will not, under any circumstance, allow Tony Danza to be on
television ever again.
</P>
<P>
   Lifetime: You will program shows for women, because that's what
you say you do.
</P>
<P>
   USA Channel: Not all of the women in your movies will be
defenseless and in peril.
</P>
<P>
   Fox Files: You will cancel yourself, out of shame.
</P>
<P>
   We will all stop watching MSNBC until they come up with
something other than ``Investigating the President.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, we will all turn the channel if something about
President Clinton, Monica Lewinsky or Kenneth Starr comes on.
</P>
<P>
   Whoops. That one's already resolved.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Springer: To learn a lesson and prove that you do have a
soul, you will allow yourself to be bludgeoned by several of your
guests.
</P>
<P>
   The networks: You will no longer give sweetheart deals that
result in horrible shows like ``Jesse'' and ``Encore! Encore!''
</P>
<P>
   CBS: You will schedule in sweeps, because the people demand it,
a bout between Sammo Hung and Chuck Norris.
</P>
<P>
   The networks: You will not release 40 or more new shows in less
than a month next September. You will not release 15 or more shows
during the ``midseason'' to cover for your mistakes. You will not
air reruns all summer, leaving us hanging.
</P>
<P>
   We will all lose a little weight this year. Except Calista
Flockhart.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Tim Goodman is the television critic for the San Francisco
Examiner, P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic
mail address is goodman(at)examiner.com).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
