<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES98-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THERE'S SOMETHING ABOUT HOLLYWOOD: THE HIGHS, LOWS OF '98  
 (ADV: WITH MOVIES98-BEST AND MOVIES98-WORST) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB FENSTER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - The Hollywood shuffle: Take one step forward by going
two steps back.
</P>
<P>
   If we want to peek at the kinds of movies we'll see over the
next two years, we have to look back only at the trends that made
1998 another box-office bonanza at the movies.
</P>
<P>
   - Hollywood does Hollywood: ``The Truman Show,'' ``Holy Man,''
``Ringmaster'' and ``Pleasantville'' played upon our obsession with
TV, while many movies dealt with the moviemakers: ``Gods and
Monsters,'' ``Love and Death on Long Island,'' ``Billy's Hollywood
Screen Kiss,'' ``The Tango Lesson,'' ``Orgazmo,'' ``Celebrity'' and
``Twilight.''
</P>
<P>
   Why does Hollywood turn its cameras inward? For the same reason
writers write about writers: It's something they know.
</P>
<P>
   - Private Ryan saves war movies: ``Saving Private Ryan''
reopened national debate about patriotism and the terrible
sacrifices demanded by war. It also changed how Hollywood will make
war movies.
</P>
<P>
   From now on, all directors will have to face the brutal choices
of war: Do they go the ultra-realistic route that Spielberg took?
</P>
<P>
   - Dumber and, well, worse: The dumb-comedy genre got even dumber
as stupid pictures cashed in.
</P>
<P>
   The smart Adam Sandler (``The Wedding Singer'') was popular but
not nearly as popular as the dumb Adam Sandler (``The Waterboy'').
</P>
<P>
   ``There's Something About Mary''became the biggest surprise hit
of the year by combining dumb gags with outrageous stunts. Stuck
zippers will be the cream pies of the future.
</P>
<P>
   Will movies try to outdumb each other? Yes, but they're already
doing that. From now on, filmmakers will be challenged to come up
with grosser-than-Mary stunts.
</P>
<P>
   - Kids have a great year at the movies: ``A Bug's Life'' is
soaring, followed by other well-made, family-friendly ventures:
``Antz,'' ``The Rugrats Movie,'' ``The Prince of Egypt,'' the
second ``Babe.'' Also on the plus side: ``Mulan,'' ``Paulie,''
``The Parent Trap,'' ``Madeline'' and ``Barney's Great Adventure.''
</P>
<P>
   This coming year, we can expect more computer animation and more
attempts to spin off kids' TV shows into movies.
</P>
<P>
   - Blacks don't: Serious films about experiences of Black people
took a big hit when ``Beloved,'' ``He Got Game,'' ``How Stella Got
Her Groove Back,'' ``Why Do Fools Fall in Love'' and ``Hav Plenty''
did not attract enough moviegoers of any color.
</P>
<P>
   That means we'll see even fewer Black films with depth and more
quick-hit pictures, such as ``Rush Hour'' starring fast-talking
Black comics.
</P>
<P>
   _How do you tell satire from the real thing? Obsessed with
Washington politics, Hollywood produced three satires of the
Clinton years: ``Wag the Dog,'' ``Bulworth'' and ``Primary
Colors.''
</P>
<P>
   Although ``Wag the Dog'' became a phrase of political currency,
these films did only so-so box office. So, we may not get too many
Washington comedies in the next two years.
</P>
<P>
   Other than what the politicians come up with on their own, of
course.
</P>
<P>
   - Classics stay classy: Studios continued to mine classic novels
for material: ``Cousin Bette,'' ``Les Miserables,'' ``Washington
Square'' and ``Mrs. Dalloway.''
</P>
<P>
   Although these movies don't bring in big box office, the studios
don't have to pay for the book rights because they're already in
the public domain.
</P>
<P>
   Classics also lend class to studios that make their real money
off violence and dumb jokes. Besides, they've got to do something
with those storerooms full of costumes.
</P>
<P>
   - Got to dance, don't have to sing: Although musicals were
scarce, movies kept dancing. ``The Tango Lesson'' and ``Gadjo
Dilo'' introduced passionate dancers from Argentina and Romania,
respectively, while ``The Last Days of Disco,'' ``54'' and ``Dance
With Me'' tried to revive disco fever.
</P>
<P>
   Is there a swing-dance movie in the works?
</P>
<P>
   - Duel winners: Dueling movies continued the trend of rival
studios making similar pictures around the same concept, with both
succeeding at the box office.
</P>
<P>
   Two asteroid movies (``Deep Impact'' and ``Armageddon'') and two
ant movies (``Antz'' and ``A Bug's Life'') did not cancel each
other out. People simply went to see both.
</P>
<P>
   In Hollywood, it's not stealing if everyone makes money.
</P>
<P>
   - Oscar may come late: Looking ahead, a few big films will still
make a run at the 1998 Oscars because they opened in LA in
December.
</P>
<P>
   Those contenders include a World War II drama, ``The Thin Red
Line''; ``A Civil Action,'' starring John Travolta as a crusading
attorney; and ``Hurlyburly,'' with Sean Penn and Meg Ryan in a
story about drug addicts. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-31-98 1255EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981231.0157 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-31 13:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3449 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES98-BEST-AZR &LR;      12-31 0774
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES98-BEST-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BEST OF THE BEST FOR 1998  
 (ADV: WITH MOVIES98B AND MOVIES98-WORST) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB FENSTER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Here's a list of the best movies of 1998:
</P>
<P>
   1. ``Saving Private Ryan'' _ The biggest impact film of the
year, Steven Spielberg's masterpiece follows a squad of D-Day
survivors on a doomed mission to rescue a single soldier from
behind enemy lines.
</P>
<P>
   This is the most authentic and one of the most heartbreaking
films ever made about the inevitable slaughter in mechanized
warfare. No filmmaker has ever captured the frenzied panic of
ground battles in so much intense detail.
</P>
<P>
   By focusing on a few men and what they endure, ``Saving Private
Ryan'' becomes the narrowest but deepest war epic yet.
</P>
<P>
   It galvanized the nation and will influence filmmakers for
generations.
</P>
<P>
   2. ``Life Is Beautiful'' _ The rarest of films: one that can
make you laugh and cry at the same time. This bittersweet tale
about a happy-go-lucky clown trapped in a Nazi concentration camp
combines classic slapstick comedy with heart-wrenching poignancy.
</P>
<P>
   It's all the more remarkable because the writer, director and
star, Italy's Roberto Benigni, hasn't shown this kind of sublime
talent in previous films.
</P>
<P>
   3. ``Shakespeare in Love'' _ This comedy, with the Bard as the
hero of his own romantic fantasy, is a smart, bawdy romp about
love, sex, actors, sword fighting and the curious ability of a
woman to be both Juliet and Romeo.
</P>
<P>
   By vividly, lustily bringing Shakespeare's times to life, the
movie will introduce a new generation of movie lovers to a master
of both tragedy and farce.
</P>
<P>
   4. ``Beloved'' _ The year's most challenging drama, this
adaptation of the Toni Morrison novel uses a woman's horrific
plight during slavery to examine the psychological destruction
inflicted upon women by the men who wield the power in this world.
</P>
<P>
   The movie played mostly to women, although its lessons are
directed toward men. Or, as star Oprah Winfrey says when Danny
Glover claims he never mistreated a woman in his life, ``Well, that
makes one of you.''
</P>
<P>
   5. ``A Bug's Life'' _ Is it a kids' cartoon? Or an adult comedy?
Everyone is laughing too hard to figure out the difference.
</P>
<P>
   This second film from the computer-animation wizards who created
``Toy Story'' is teeming with jokes flying off in so many
directions that repeat viewings won't wear out the humor.
</P>
<P>
   The producers even came up with a clever marketing gag: changing
the funny outtakes over the closing credits in midrelease.
</P>
<P>
   6. ``Bulworth'' _ An outrageous comedy in which Warren Beatty
(as writer, director and star) insults everyone _ or if he missed
anyone, it was by accident.
</P>
<P>
   Beatty plays a U.S. senator who suddenly starts doing the
unthinkable: telling the truth about politics to the American
people.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wag the Dog'' got more press, but this satire struck closer to
the reason so many Americans have grown cynical about politics:
They should be.
</P>
<P>
   7. ``Gods and Monsters'' _ Strange, memorable drama about two
men with nothing in common _ the aging director who created the
original ``Frankenstein'' movie and a young gardener running from
himself _ who become key players in each other's lives.
</P>
<P>
   This thought-provoking film is full of psychological surprises
that highlight the difficulty and importance of finding out who we
really are.
</P>
<P>
   8. ``Sliding Doors'' _ The most innovative romance in decades,
this English film shows how the small decisions we make in our
lives can change everything.
</P>
<P>
   The movie cleverly follows a woman (Gwyneth Paltrow) down the
dual paths of her life, based on the simple switch of making or not
making a train.
</P>
<P>
   This fascinating film will get you thinking about the workings
of fate in your own life.
</P>
<P>
   9. ``Mrs. Dalloway'' _ Dutch filmmaker Marleen Gorris
(``Antonia's Line'') turns Virginia Woolf's novel into an intricate
evocation of the interplay between daily life and the free-floating
tempo of memories.
</P>
<P>
   Watching the movie about an aging Englishwoman in the 1920s is
like curling up inside a great book.
</P>
<P>
   10. ``Waking Ned Devine'' _ The comedy for people who complain
they don't make grand old comedies the way they used to.
</P>
<P>
   This tale of two schemers trying to con themselves a share of
the Irish lottery is a delightful charmer, full of Irish wit and
winsome humor.
</P>
<P>
   Five films that would have made the best list if we counted by
15s instead of 10s: ``Gadjo Dilo,'' ``The Tango Lesson,'' ``Men
With Guns,'' ``Waco: The Rules of Engagement,'' ``Babe: Pig in the
City.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
