<HEADLINE>
LANGUAGE PROFESSORS CONTINUE TO FIGHT THE `CULTURE WARS' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By KEAY DAVIDSON  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The Cold War ended long ago, and the Vietnam War
even longer, but ``culture wars'' are boiling hotter than ever on
American campuses.
</P>
<P>
   At U.S. colleges and universities, political radicals,
feminists, lesbians, blacks and other groups are scrutinizing
American life in imaginative new ways, ranging from scholarly
studies of lesbian detective novels to Marxist theories of loves
and sexuality.
</P>
<P>
   The trend angers some old-fashioned professors, mostly tenured
scholars who foresee apocalypse in the latest campus trends: drama
teachers who'd as soon discuss Quentin Tarantino as Aristophanes,
Marxist scholars who excoriate imperialist attitudes in
Shakespeare's ``The Tempest,'' and ``queer theorists'' who
deconstruct homophobic messages in classic literature.
</P>
<P>
   These and other trend setters strutted their stuff at this
week's Modern Language Association of America (MLA) conference in
San Francisco. For anyone wishing to plug into the intellectual
Zeitgeist, the annual MLA conference is the place to be.
</P>
<P>
   In a session titled ``Can We Talk? Is Dialogue Possible Between
the Cultural Left and Right?'' academics tried to cool down
passions on both sides.
</P>
<P>
   Both leftists and right-wingers on campuses have tended to
indulge in ``demonization of their opponents,'' charged an
organizer of the session, English Professor Donald P. Lazere of
California Polytechnic University at San Luis Obispo.
</P>
<P>
   He argued that if both sides calm down, then they might realize
they have ideas in common. For example, he argued, the late Marxist
philosopher Herbert Marcuse's book ``One-Dimensional Man,'' a Bible
for 1960s radicals, criticizes mass culture in ways similar to
Allan Bloom's ``Closing of the American Mind,'' a best-selling
critique treasured by political conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   During a question-and-answer session, though, the semi-civilized
atmosphere crumbled into accusation hurling. Several women in the
audience repeatedly demanded that a panelist explain why he had
omitted Virginia Woolf's name from a list of his favorite
novelists.
</P>
<P>
   At another point in the session, a man in the audience stood and
complained that a top official of the MLA, the controversial
Columbia University scholar Edward Said, had written a ``snide and
intemperate'' letter in the organization's journal. ``This man is
going to be the next president of the MLA?'' the man asked
incredulously. Said was not present.
</P>
<P>
   Of the hundreds of MLA sessions this week, most were standard
academic stuff, such as ``Edith Wharton and Her 1920s
Contemporaries'' and ``Marlowe and Shakespeare: The Anxiety of
Influence.''
</P>
<P>
   But a fair share of this week's sessions might sound goofy to
mainstream, middlebrow Americans who prefer Tom Clancy, People
magazine and Martha Stewart to Jacques Lacan, Lingua Franca
magazine, and the always-unhappy films of Todd (``Happiness'')
Solondz.
</P>
<P>
   For example, MLA sessions included discussions of
``posthumanist'' values in the ``Swamp Thing'' comic; of ``Robots
in Early Brazilian Science Fiction''; and of the deeper meanings of
celebrity autobiographies by Roseanne, Marilyn Manson and ``Lone
Ranger'' Clayton Moore.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-31-98 1307EST &QL; 
