<SLUG> BC-ONLINE-CALENDARS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERNET COMPANIES PUSH ON-LINE CALENDARS AND ORGANIZERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MATT BEER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ This coming year, two San Francisco-area
Internet companies are betting that on-line customers will abandon
paper-based or hand-held electronic organizers and keep track of
their lives on the World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   Companies like Mountain View-based Visto and Woodside-based
Magically Inc. have posted Web sites that feature personal on-line
calendars and telephone number managers a user can access from any
computer with a Web browser.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents of these Web applications argue that these sites will
be a success because of the openness of the wired crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``Twenty years ago, you were a nobody if you didn't have an
unlisted phone number,'' said Rao Machirajau, chief technology
officer with Magically Inc. ``Now, everybody has a Web page where
they're spilling their guts. So keeping things like appointments
and telephone numbers on-line is no big deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Users of these Web-based organizational tools can store
information ranging from telephone numbers to addresses and even
events calendars on the sites by entering the data onto a
datebook-like template. Magically and Visto then store the
information on servers that are accessible on any computer logged
into the Internet. The information is protected by a password
selected by the individual user.
</P>
<P>
   Besides calendar and phone number services, sites like
Magically's MagicDesk (www.magicaldesk.com) and Visto
(www.visto.com) are trying to lure subscribers with free e-mail and
on-line data file storage areas.
</P>
<P>
   The hope is that users will be so enamored of the service that
they'll eventually subscribe to the premium pay sections of these
personal information sites. These sites include larger data storage
areas and capabilities to synchronize the on-line information with
a computer's personal information manager program, hand-held
machines like the Palm Pilot and, eventually, cell phones and other
portable devices. These upgrades cost about $10.
</P>
<P>
   ``By having your information at a central point on the Web, you
can walk up to any computer and access it,'' said Steve Cox, vice
president of marketing for Visto. ``I have this saying: It's the
content, stupid. It's not the computer.''
</P>
<P>
   Cox said these services allow workers to become more portable,
enabling them to move back and forth between home and office with
ease.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a service that frees people from having to not schlepp
around disks or use other devices to carry their information back
and forth from the office,'' said Cox.
</P>
<P>
   It's also an idea that has caught the attention of major Web
portal sites, like Yahoo, which has posted its own calendar and
phone service. Excite and Lycos are expected to launch their own
versions of the service early next year.
</P>
<P>
   But the success of these services may be hampered by the usual
Web complaints: Privacy and speed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Information software and other devices are fast,'' said
Bridget Leach of Giga Information Group, an information technology
research firm based in Cambridge, Mass. ``The Web is slow and some
people won't want to deal with that.''
</P>
<P>
   Leach said concerns over privacy could also hamper the growth of
the on-line personal information market.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be some hesitancy putting such personal information
up on the Internet,'' Leach said. ``But there were those concerns
about e-mail, and it didn't stop people.''
</P>
<P>
   Financially, both firms are banking on private capital to get
off the ground. Magically is a closely held company funded by
several venture capital firms in Hong Kong and an undisclosed
telecom company, according to Machirajau. The site went on-line
Dec. 21.
</P>
<P>
   Visto is also a closely held company, funded with Silicon Valley
venture capital, including a July infusion of $9 million from New
Enterprise Associates, a VC firm that has computer pundit Stewart
Alsop on its board, Cox said.
</P>
<P>
   Peggy O'Neill, an analyst with Dataquest, a San Jose-based
market research company, said the main beneficiary of these new
organizer sites will be the sites themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are what we call `sticky applications,''' O'Neill said.
``The Web sites want people to get dependent on them and keep
coming back. If you spend a good two hours on a Saturday entering
your phone numbers and appointments at Yahoo, you're not going to
want to do that again if you're thinking about switching your home
page. It worked with free e-mail. It'll probably work with these
new services.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
