<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HER RESOLUTION IS A RERUN: NO MORE TV
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ah, a new year.
</P>
<P>
   New goals, new energy, new lifestyle, new life.
</P>
<P>
   Less weight, less stress, less conflict, less mess.
</P>
<P>
   No analyzing, no scrutinizing, no whining, no fear.
</P>
<P>
   And no TV.
</P>
<P>
   None. Zip. Nada.
</P>
<P>
   Really? Really.
</P>
<P>
   Last time lasted a month. Or was it two?
</P>
<P>
   Three weeks, actually.
</P>
<P>
   That's Marifeli. On the phone from Arlington, Texas. Again. Same
time last year, right, Marifeli? ``It's happening this time,'' she
promises, chuckling. ``No ... really ... I'm serious.''
</P>
<P>
   Serious about kicking her TV habit. Serious about dropping
``Ally McBeal'' from her diet.
</P>
<P>
   Serious about saying ``See ya'' to ``Everybody Loves Raymond''
(''I just love his brother'') and ``JAG'' (''Is he fine or what?'')
and ``Early Edition'' (''Did you know she's the first Buffy?'') and
``Touched by an Angel'' (''It inspires me, you know?'') and ``Law &AMP;
Order'' (''Ben Bratt'') and ``Friends'' (''Chandler just cracks me
up'') and ``ER'' (''It grosses me out. ... but I like that'') and
``Spin City'' (''the gay guy and the straight guy are so funny'')
and ``that show with Sarah Jessica Parker. You know. The one about
sex.'' HBO's ``Sex in the City? ``Right. Love that,'' says
Marifeli. ``It's my life. ... That will be a hard one.''
</P>
<P>
   Marifeli is divorced and the mother of a precocious 5-year-old.
Time's ticking, she says. Too much of it spent in front of the tube
and ``not talking, just zoning out'' with daughter Eliza, who
already has her own 8-inch-screen TV perched on top of a colorful
Mickey Mouse dresser. A giant stuffed Teletubby sits on top of the
TV, waving its little hand, as if to say, ``C'mon.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's Po,'' Marifeli says. ``Or Tinky Winky. You know, the
green one.'' (That's Dipsy, actually.)
</P>
<P>
   In Marifeli's three-bedroom home near Lake Arlington, there are
three other sets. One each for the living room, the bedroom, the
kitchen. ``It's a little one, though,'' Marifeli says about the
kitchen set, which keeps her company while she cooks. ``Plus, it's
black and white. That doesn't count.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course not.
</P>
<P>
   Marifeli sounds like a habitual TV watcher with a bad case of
the guilts. She's like a chain smoker who can't quit. An alcoholic
who needs a lift. A drug addict who needs a fix.
</P>
<P>
   Marifeli's morning pick-me-ups: Katie Couric on ``Today,'' some
``SportsCenter,'' some ``CNN,'' a tiny bit of ``Good Morning,
Texas'' while heading out the door. (''You like the new girl? I
think she's trying too hard.'')
</P>
<P>
   Evenings are devoted to a prime-time menu, most of which she
tapes for viewing after Eliza has been tucked in bed.
</P>
<P>
   Taping, says Marifeli, is the most efficient way to consume TV.
You can fast-forward through the commercials. ``I also move right
on through the secondary stories that aren't working,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Huh? ``Do you watch `Fantasy Island'? On that, there are two
major stories and then a side story, usually about that fat guy and
the skinny guy who help out the fantasy guy. So I sit on my couch
and fast-forward every time they come on and stop when one of the
main-story people appear.''
</P>
<P>
   And? ``And that cuts an hour show to 35 minutes. I do the same
with `JAG' with (stories about) that pudgy assistant, and `Cupid'
sometimes, with the roommate, even though he's got this great body
and nice smile. ...''
</P>
<P>
   So she's able to cram a couple dramas and a few sitcoms in a
two-hour slot. During late-night, she spot-checks talk-show guests,
flipping back and forth from the talkers to ``Nightline,''
depending on the subject. Marifeli's weekends revolve around the
tube as well. She's pulled away when hanging out with Eliza, but
evenings and late at night, she leaps into her sleep gear, cuts off
the lights, arms herself with tea (winter) or ice cream shake
(summer) and a remote.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's soothing,'' she says. ``And intimate.''
</P>
<P>
   Intimate enough to call Benjamin Bratt ``Ben.''
</P>
<P>
   And you'll be able to give this up?
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah,'' she promises. ``Although ...''
</P>
<P>
   Although?
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw this ad the other day about Eddie Murphy. I just love
him.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The PJs.'' Airs Jan. 10 on Fox. It's ``Good Times'' in clay
animation. Murphy is a producer and voice.
</P>
<P>
   ``That looks really, really funny,'' she says. ``Maybe I'll
check that out just to see. And the Sarah Jessica Parker show,
since that's cable. That doesn't really count.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course not.
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Parish Perkins is television critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7862 or e-mail:
kpp(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services
on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
