<DOCNO> NYT19981231.0162 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-31 13:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3480 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PHOTOGRAPHYFORDUMMIES     12-31 1200
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHOTOGRAPHYFORDUMMIES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DON'T FORGET THE CAMERA AND NINE OTHER INCREDIBLY EASY TRICKS OF
THE TRADE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RALPH LAUER 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The trip is costing you a fortune, not to mention the dysentery
you've had to deal with, the bus ride that almost ended in a
1,000-foot free fall into a ravine and the communal bath you took
with what seemed to be a tribe of herders.
</P>
<P>
   But it is the opportunity of a lifetime, and here you stand,
looking at the most beautiful scene since the creation of the
heavens. You reach for your camera and realize it's ... on the bed
... in the hotel room.
</P>
<P>
   Photography mistake No. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Don't leave home without it. And don't leave the hotel without
it either. Looking like a tourist geek is a small price to pay for
pictures that will let you remember your trip for a lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   To get started in your photo-taking, you need to purchase a
camera before you leave home. Here comes that walk into the camera
store, a look down that long aisle of lenses, all looking back at
you. Now you know how Monica feels. To simplify, I will limit this
to discussion of 35mm cameras, although most of the photo tips
apply to other formats as well.
</P>
<P>
   The quality of cameras, as with most things, is proportional to
the amount of money you are willing to spend. A $1,500 single-lens
reflex camera (the ones where you see through the same lens that
the film looks through) and zoom is capable of creating
higher-quality images than that handy disposable number, but how
you use either camera determines how well your photos come out.
</P>
<P>
   The more-expensive version will have more bells and whistles
enabling you to do more, but under optimum light conditions, the
images from the expensive camera won't be substantially better than
the images from a less-expensive camera.
</P>
<P>
   Disposables have plastic lenses, fixed shutter speeds and
apertures, and some even have built-in flashes. Their drawback is
that you can't make any adjustments for the changing conditions of
light you will encounter.
</P>
<P>
   Point-and-shoot cameras are a step up from disposables, giving
you improved quality in lenses, and a camera that makes some
adjustments for different light conditions, while still offering
the simplicity of just pointing the camera and pressing the shutter
release. They come in a variety of styles and sizes, with some even
being waterproof. Most have built-in flashes and some include data
imprinting, so you can record the date and time of an exposure.
</P>
<P>
   The ultimate option is the SLRs, or single-lens reflex cameras.
These are the ones professionals and wannabes have hanging around
their necks. They give you control of the shutter speeds (how fast
the picture is taken), the aperture (amount of light the lens lets
in), and the ability to change lenses. Some will have built-in
flashes, but most don't. The price of the gains made in quality and
flexibility is paid in size, weight and cost, with some of these
types of cameras costing more than $2,000.
</P>
<P>
   After you've settled on your camera, the next thing you need is
film. If you're using a disposable camera, then it's already in
there. If you're using something else, this is where things can
start to get complicated. You must choose between slide and
negative films, and each comes in varying speeds (sensitivity to
light).
</P>
<P>
   For most travelers, negative film is the best bet, because we
all want prints to hang on the refrigerator to impress our friends
with all the places we have seen. Leave the slide film to the pros,
who are the ones who need to reproduce stuff in those slick
magazines.
</P>
<P>
   As far as ISO (that's the speed of the film for the wannabes), a
quick guide is to use one that goes as fast as your subject. If
you're taking pictures in bright daylight of slow-moving subjects
like that German castle or the Great Wall of China, then a
100-speed film will give you the finest grain and best detail. For
medium-speed subjects, like that spitting camel at the pharaoh's
tomb, a 200 or 400 speed will be fine. And then if you have one of
those fast subjects, like Uncle Bob running with the bulls in
Pamplona, then 800 will be your favorite, because you probably live
on the wild side and this film's ability to shoot at night during
those wild carnival parades in Rio will come in handy. Just
remember that there is going to be a bit more grain in those shots.
</P>
<P>
   Now we come to aiming that infernal camera.
</P>
<P>
   Don't shoot straight into a light source; it gives the camera a
false exposure and will silhouette whatever it is you're trying to
photograph. If you have a hard time looking directly at it, then
the film will be squinting just like you.
</P>
<P>
   When you travel, you want the picture-taking as simple as
possible, so let those automatic settings do what you paid for them
to do in the first place. In most situations, the cameras are
perfectly capable of setting the exposures.
</P>
<P>
   Try to fill the frame with your subject, getting as close as
prudently possible. You are not going to want a wide-angle close-up
of a lion on the Serengeti plain since that would put you within a
paw stretch of being dinner.
</P>
<P>
   The more colorful the scene the better, so make sure your travel
partner has not just started dressing like a goth princess, unless
you're at a Transylvanian castle.
</P>
<P>
   Try framing the most important subject matter off-center, such
as a third left or right, to prevent that perfect symmetry of a
face like a bull's-eye in the center of the photo.
</P>
<P>
   The most important thing to remember is to shoot photos of
subjects that are important to you, because these are your
memories, not the local visitors bureau's photos.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Lauer's Top 10 rules for pleasing photos:
</P>
<P>
   1. Always carry your camera with you. If you want pictures, you
need the camera.
</P>
<P>
   2. Don't forget that darn lens-cap thing. The world is real
black to the film if you don't take it off.
</P>
<P>
   3. Fingers belong behind the lens. Thumbs make remarkably
unattractive photos, so be careful that you hold the camera so no
part of your hand is visible to the lens.
</P>
<P>
   4. Don't put everything in the center of the frame. You paid for
the rest of the film so you might as well use it.
</P>
<P>
   5. Try to look at the world from a different viewpoint, either
high or low.
</P>
<P>
   6. If things are moving fast, you need to hold still.
</P>
<P>
   7. Keep the camera dry; lake plunges, rain and spilled Cokes
will ruin your equipment.
</P>
<P>
   8. People don't have to be photographed from a distance. Most
don't bite, so you can get close. Ask first, if you feel
uncomfortable. Holding the camera up and pointing at it and then at
the person you would like to shoot is the international code for
``Can I take your picture?''
</P>
<P>
   9. There are beautiful things everywhere, so don't limit
yourself to tourist destinations.
</P>
<P>
   10. Shoot what you like, not what everyone else does.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Ralph Lauer makes his living shooting colorful, full-frame
photos of slightly off-center subjects for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram's feature sections. You can call him at (817)
390-7051. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World
Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
