<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-31 13:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3492 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YEAREND-SPOCK-TRIBUTE     12-31 1309
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YEAREND-SPOCK-TRIBUTE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SPOCK-MARKED GENERATION  
 EDITORS: EMBARGOED UNTIL SUN., JAN. 3 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (This article has already moved to Centerpiece clients. To
publish as a ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased _ the
rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S., Canada and the Pacific: NIRDI RELIS in New York at
1-800-972-3550 or 212-499-3333; fax, 212-499-3382. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-996-0075;
fax, 310-996-0089. 
 &HT;    
 By MARGARET TALBOT  
 FROM: The New York Times Magazine  
 &HT;    More than any other figure of our time, Benjamin Spock embodies
the cultural contradictions of expertise _ and of our dependence on
it. His most famous piece of advice _ ``Trust yourself. You know
more than you think you do'' _ was the opening of a book that by
its seventh edition had bulked up to almost 900 pages. Inside were
detailed instructions on everything from managing colic to
inculcating idealism.
 &HT;    He set out to write a book that would be ``unauthoritative,
uncondemning and unscolding,'' and in many ways he succeeded. He
made it a point of honor to incorporate the criticisms of readers _
from suburban mothers who thought he was too stern about what one
called the ``miraculous'' pacifier (he later endorsed it for fussy
babies) to feminists who thought his use of the pronoun ``he'' to
describe the baby was sexist (after 1976, the baby is frequently a
``she'').
 &HT;    But this modesty of tone only reinforced h is authority. If he
had not revolutionized the dispensation of child-rearing advice in
this way _ making it seem less harsh and directive toward parents,
making it friendly _ we would not have today's veritable industry
of such advice. We would not have T. Berry Brazelton or Penelope
Leach, Spock's most obvious heirs, but neither would we have more
than 2,000 how-to books for mothers and fathers and even
grandparents, a cacophony of expertise that sometimes makes it
almost impossible to hear your own small voice.
 &HT;    There were child-rearing books before Spock published ``Baby and
Child Care'' in 1946, but they could never have worked for the
postwar generation, never have sold the astonishing 50 million
copies that his have sold. His predecessors had little interest in
psychological growth or self-expression. Nor did they treat
demonstrative familial love as a sort of secular religion, in the
now-familiar way that Spock and his followers would. Luther Emmett
Holt's ``The Care and Feeding of Children,'' first published in
1894, was still in print between the wars, a hoary classic urging
strict dietary habits and expeditious toilet training.
 &HT;    In 1928 Holt was joined on many home bookshelves by John
Watson's ``Psychological Care of Infant and Child,'' a staunch
behaviorist blueprint that stressed regimentation in eating and
elimination, warned parents not to hug or kiss their children and
blamed mother-love for a generation of mollycoddled complainers
unfit for the rigors of modern capitalism.
 &HT;    It was never at all clear whether many parents actually took
such Draconian advice. It was clear that they resented being told
they should. Indeed, pediatricians in the '30s and '40s were
increasingly ``confounded and annoyed,'' as one of them recalled,
``by the large numbers of distraught, angry and frazzled mothers''
who complained they could not stick with the rigid feeding
schedules then in vogue (``don't watch the baby; watch the clock,''
as the slogan had it) and who resented the ``objective'' training
methods advocated by Watson and his ilk.
 &HT;    Watsonism had begun to give way to the child-centered,
Spock-sanctioned approach that would have us, say, walk our colicky
babies for hours in the middle of the night rather than let them
cry it out, or painstakingly ``kidproof'' our houses rather than
swat a toddler who menaces the porcelain.
 &HT;    Feminists have pointed out that this labor-intensive paradigm is
in some ways more subtly punitive too, since women who feel they
come up short may blame themselves for a failure of maternal
instinct rather than of mere technique. But it is worth remembering
that the discipline of listening to your baby howl when she was
hungry was oppressive in its own way.
 &HT;    All those angry mothers storming their pediatricians' offices
had something to be angry about. What they did not have was a
popular voice of authority to whom they could turn for
confirmation. And that, of course, was where Spock came in.
 &HT;    With the first edition of his book, Spock gave voice to this
backlash against emotional asceticism in child-rearing _ a wry and
tolerant voice, soothing but never condescending. That is why the
charge that it was he who sired the hippie generation with his
``permissiveness'' was always so bogus.
 &HT;    The baby doctor eventually emerged as a leading critic of the
war in Vietnam and a champion of civil disobedience, and when he
did, campus demonstrators began brandishing signs reading ``I was
raised on Dr. Spock.'' But the equation never had much evidence in
its favor.
 &HT;    Spock was no advocate of loosey-goosey, anything-goes
child-rearing, and he repeatedly tried to correct the misimpression
that he was. He doubted the efficacy of physical punishment, but he
believed in the parent's mission to civilize, and his own two sons
remembered him as exacting and judgmental, a stickler for table
manners. As adults, they resented his strictness, but they turned
out fine. Both became husbands and fathers.
 &HT;    The elder son, Michael, is a former director of the Boston
Children's Museum. John Spock is a partner in a construction
company in Los Angeles. Spock himself went through a late-life
evolution. At 73, he divorced his wife of 49 years and married Mary
Morgan, a much younger, somewhat bohemian woman.
 &HT;    They led a nomadic life, partly in a Winnebago they called the
Tortoise, and adopted a macrobiotic diet, which he credited with
prolonging his life after a small stroke. He had come full circle _
back to a belief in the morally edifying effects of simple food and
fresh air that his formidable mother had tried to instill.
 &HT;    The paradox that makes Spock such a man of our time is that for
all the precious encouragement he did provide over the years, he
and his imitators have also helped to undermine the confidence of
many parents. You see subtitles like ``How to Be Natural'' and
instantly become self-conscious. You're told to relax into
parenthood, and the more often you're told, the less relaxed you
feel, and the more likely you are to turn to other sources of
professional advice.
 &HT;    Readers took notice of this tendency even in the '50s, but in
the last decade or so it has intensified. Even fewer of us live
near mothers or fathers or aunts or grandparents whose daily
counsel we can rely on, and even more of us spend enough time away
from our children each day to feel that we must get to know them
anew each evening.
 &HT;    In a recent interview, Spock said that babies ``learn very soon
that their mother has less conviction than the baby has. This is
why there are so many pesky children who are arguing with their
parents all the time. It's wrong for children to be brought up
thinking they can bully and shame their parents into silence. But
it's also hard on parents.''
 &HT;    Maybe the best favor we could do for ourselves, and the best
tribute we could pay to Spock, is to stop buying parenting books.
Or OK, maybe just one. His.
 &HT;     c.1998 Margaret Talbot  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Margaret Talbot is a senior editor at The New Republic.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   -------------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
