<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-31 13:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3515 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YEAREND-GWALLACE-TRIB     12-31 0901
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YEAREND-GWALLACE-TRIBUTE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GEORGE WALLACE: WHAT HE STOOD FOR  
 EDITORS: EMBARGOED UNTIL SUN., JAN. 3 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (This article has already moved to Centerpiece clients. To
publish as a ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased _ the
rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S., Canada and the Pacific: NIRDI RELIS in New York at
1-800-972-3550 or 212-499-3333; fax, 212-499-3382. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-996-0075;
fax, 310-996-0089. 
 &HT;    
 By Nicholas deB. Katzenbach  
 FROM: The New York Times Magazine  
 &HT;    I met George Wallace only twice _ very publicly _ and I have no
idea whether his latter-day denials of being a racist at heart are
true or not. What I do know is that his political career was
founded on racial discrimination, and that he left a political
heritage that exploits racial feelings for political gain.
 &HT;    Both of our meetings _ at the ``schoolhouse door'' in 1963 and
in the Oval Office in 1965 _ were calculated by the governor to
enhance his political role as a leader of white supremacy in
Alabama and in the South generally. The stand in the doorway at
Tuscaloosa fulfilled a campaign pledge and gave him huge national
exposure through television.
 &HT;    It had no substance; nobody, including Wallace, had any doubt
that Vivian Malone and James Hood would be admitted to the
university. That reality _ and perhaps the fact that on a very hot
day Wallace made me stand in the sun while he was in the shade _
made me angry at his posturing for political purposes. But given
the potential for violence on the part of Klan-related racists, we
felt we had no choice but to allow him to demonstrate his
identification with all those who opposed desegregation. We were
confident that he would eventually step aside.
 &HT;    Wallace met with President Johnson on a Saturday morning in 1965
to discuss problems of racial tension in Alabama. We thought he
requested the meeting to argue that racial integration would not
work and would lead to more civil disorder. The times were
difficult. That morning there were pickets on Pennsylvania Avenue
assailing the president.
 &HT;    Wallace hoped to exploit these demonstrations for his
segregationist ends. Feeling the anger of many whites at the
continuing civil rights demonstrations _ despite enactment of the
1964 Civil Rights Act _ he thought, mistakenly, that he could
embarrass LBJ into being critical as well. The president was the
better politician. He used the occasion to announce the
voting-rights bill in the Rose Garden _ while the Governor used the
back door to avoid the TV cameras.
 &HT;    But Governor Wallace was no slouch at politics. He sensed the
enormous white resentment in the North and West as well as the
South - especially among blue-collar workers and farmers _ of black
leaders, of black social and economic progress and of perceived
special treatment under the civil rights laws.
 &HT;    He recognized too that old-fashioned Southern racial politics _
``out-segging'' the other candidate _ was not politically viable in
the North and, after passage of the Voting Rights Act, in the South
either. He had always, as governor, posed as the candidate of the
working man _ the white working man _ and he took his image
national as a third-party candidate in 1968, winning five states
and 13 percent of the popular vote.
 &HT;    Baldly stated, that extraordinary achievement was based on race,
on the resentment of whites toward blacks. But race was not
Wallace's theme as it had been in Alabama earlier in the '60s. He
chose crime, welfare, aid to developing nations and the like -
issues his audience could easily recognize as racial without that
having to be stated. And he cynically exploited that
identification.
 &HT;    Unhappily, that success was not ignored by major party
candidates, and race continues to be exploited, as it was by
Wallace, by national candidates vehemently denying racial prejudice
and carrying no segregationist baggage. Crime and welfare are
identified by many people as race problems; after all, you need
only look at the disproportionate number of blacks in prison or on
welfare.
 &HT;    Both issues have some legitimacy irrespective of race, which
facilitates their use as surrogates for prejudice. To take only a
particularly crude example from the 1988 presidential campaign of
George Bush: the use of Willie Horton in TV ads to discredit Gov.
Michael Dukakis. Wallace claimed that none of this was about racial
hatred, and perhaps that is true.
 &HT;    But using nonracial issues, which much of the public nonetheless
sees as problems of black inferiority, exploits racial feelings for
political purposes and subverts the political process through
denial of racial prejudice. Frankly, I preferred the George Wallace
who stood in the schoolhouse door, spouting nonsense about states'
rights and the Constitution as he defended segregation. At least
that stand, however misconceived, was honest.
 &HT;     c.1998 Nicholas deB. Katzenbach  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Nicholas deB. Katzenbach was deputy attorney general in the
Kennedy administration and attorney general in the Johnson
administration.) &LR;
</P>
