<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MURDER-RATE (Washington) _ The nation's murder rate fell in 1997
to its lowest level in three decades, with the bulk of the decline
occurring in large cities, the Justice Department says. The sharp
increase in the late 1980s and the decline in the 1990s stem from
the rise and fall in gun violence by younger Americans. By ERIC
ROSENBERG. (For release Saturday at 4:30 p.m.).
</P>
<P>
   Editors: The following columns moved Wednesday for Friday and
Sunday:
</P>
<P>
   For Friday:
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ A bipartisan consensus is emerging
that if President Clinton is not convicted in a Senate trial, he
should be censured with some punishment that goes beyond verbal
chastisement. It's called censure plus. But finding a politically
acceptable way to give Clinton an extra kick when he's down is
complicated. By MARIANNE MEANS.
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday:
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   THOMPSON-COLUMN (Washington) _ Senate machinations over the fate
of Bill Clinton demonstrate how wise Congress was to reject the
imposition of term limits on members of the two houses. By ROBERT
E. THOMPSON.
</P>
