<SLUG> BC-SPACECHIMPS-960(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHIMPS RETIRED FROM SPACE PROGRAM FACE UNCERTAIN FUTURE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LARRY BINGHAM 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ The sign says Primarily Primates. It is the only
clue that more than 500 monkeys, chimpanzees, gibbons, capuchins,
langurs and one very large orangutan are living out their
retirement behind a chain-link fence down a gravel road on the
outskirts of town.
</P>
<P>
   This is the nation's largest and oldest monkey and ape
retirement village. It's about to become home to some of the
world's most famous chimpanzees.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Air Force gave up ownership of its 141-member chimp
colony last year, acknowledging the contributions of the animals
who tested the safety of space travel before man, but sending their
descendants off without a pension check.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the chimps will go to a research company, some get to
retire here. But as they settle in, so does the reality that, in
the long run, there's no money to feed them, no money to care for
them, no money to build enclosures for the others.
</P>
<P>
   The lucky aren't so lucky after all.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   The Air Force's chimpanzee colony was born in the 1950s, when
the first animals were captured in the African jungle and brought
to the United States. They were dubbed ``the astrochimps.''
</P>
<P>
   Ham was 3 years old and 3 feet tall when scientists shot him
into space on Jan. 31, 1961. He flew at 5,000 miles an hour to a
height of 155 miles above the Earth before his space capsule
plunged into the Atlantic Ocean.
</P>
<P>
   A Marine helicopter fished the capsule out of the ocean 420
miles from where it was launched at Cape Canaveral, Fla. Scientists
found him inside _ unharmed.
</P>
<P>
   Three months after Ham the chimp became the largest animal sent
into space, astronaut Alan Shepard followed him. A year later, a
chimp named Enos rode the Mercury space capsule twice around the
planet two months before John Glenn made his famous orbit.
</P>
<P>
   The Air Force credits the chimps with making inroads in space
travel. They also cite the contributions of chimp studies involving
ejection seats, G-forces and sleep deprivation.
</P>
<P>
   But in the early 1970s, the Air Force stopped using chimps for
research. It leased the entire colony to Albany Medical College,
which over the past 40 years has leased and loaned the chimps and
their descendants to scores of other biomedical research centers.
</P>
<P>
   Today, none of the chimps trained for space travel is alive. Ham
and Enos died in the 1980s. Minnie was the last. She died in March.
</P>
<P>
   Exactly what has happened to the other Air Force chimps is
something of a mystery to the caretakers at Primarily Primates, the
9-acre sanctuary where some of the chimps will retire. Many of the
documents have been purged.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the chimp research is so secretive and so harmful to
chimps that labs don't want you to know exactly what they're
doing,'' said Wally Swett, president of the sanctuary.
</P>
<P>
   Swett and his staff know that one chimp, Betty, was a subject in
sleep studies and motion sickness projects in 1964 and 1965;
nutrition and kidney studies in 1969; and eye-refraction studies
from 1963 to 1970. And they know she has been used for breeding
since 1976.
</P>
<P>
   They know Penny was 8 years old when she was used for an
estrogen study, 11 when used to study arthritis, and 24 when
injected with a human breast tumor extract three times in 1982.
</P>
<P>
   The few pages of biographical information provide hints about
the other chimps: Dee was inoculated with hepatitis B in 1974;
Clair underwent an experimental surgery in 1968; Violet was part of
a kidney biopsy project; Cliff was a psychology test case; Heidi
was used to study rapid decompression; Sierra was part of a puberty
study.
</P>
<P>
   Swett talks about his newest residents, the Air Force chimps,
while chopping vegetables in a yellow kitchen in a cinder-block
office. It's time for the morning feed, and blue buckets sit on the
floor around him, full of sweet potatoes, broccoli, carrots,
apples, bananas and monkey chow.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, with less than two weeks left, we did our proposal. We
literally did it the night before,'' Swett said. ``We did it
because that 31 (of the chimps) are well-deserving vets. They've
earned a well-deserved honorable discharge after years of service
to humans.''
</P>
<P>
   As one of four founding members of Primarily Primates, Swett was
in San Antonio 20 years ago when the group took in three squirrel
monkeys whose only crime was acting like monkeys instead of the
pets their owners expected.
</P>
<P>
   Swett has watched the land behind a chain-link fence fill with
primates. His group has saved them from roadside zoos and freak
shows, animal shelters and pet farms, and research laboratories.
Forty of the retirees here are chimpanzees.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
<P>
   One of the chimps here is from a Moscow circus, another was on
display at a Panama racetrack, and another was found in a
Pittsburgh basement, bolted to the floor by a 6-foot-long chain.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the chimps came from a Pennsylvania company's hepatitis
vaccine study. Others came from a medical school's colon cancer
studies. Seven ornery males are veterans of the Matthew Broderick
movie ``Project X.''
</P>
<P>
   One chimpanzee, Sherry, arrived with only three fingers on her
hands, and no explanation why.
</P>
<P>
   Air Force officials said they knew Primarily Primates had
rehabilitated chimps, and the group's experience was one factor
that helped it win possession of the chimps. The group might have
won custody of more chimps, but the 31 were all it could afford.
</P>
<P>
   The remaining 110 were given to a New Mexico research center,
the Coulston Foundation, which has leased many of the chimps during
the past 40 years. The Coulston Foundation will add the Air Force
chimps to 650 others used for research in the treatment of
arthritis, AIDS, hepatitis, diabetes and Alzheimer's. It is the
largest facility of its kind.
</P>
<P>
   Swett sat on the committee that tried to persuade Congress to
retire the chimps with an endowment that would ensure their care.
It would have cost taxpayers $37,000 per chimp, or $6.4 million.
But the proposal came in 1992, at a time of military cutbacks, when
Air Force employees risked losing their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it was rejected.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   The first 10 Air Force chimps that came to Primarily Primates
live in an enclosure built for a group of chimps that was coming
from a Louisiana lab that closed. Those chimps have been bumped to
another sanctuary.
</P>
<P>
   The other 21 are at the Coulston Foundation, and that's where
they'll stay until Primarily Primates builds more enclosures. If
the group doesn't raise enough money, it will have to house the
chimps in small cages, put them to sleep or give them to the
foundation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's scary to think about,'' said Stephen Rene Tello,
corporate secretary for Primarily Primates. It's Tello's job to
worry about how the group will house, feed and care for the retired
chimps.
</P>
<P>
   His organization used to rely on publicity to stir the support
of the group's 11,000 members. But this time, the media have
focused primarily on the 110 other chimps, and the fight over their
control. A third group that lost in the bidding process has
challenged the Air Force's decision to award chimps to the Coulston
Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   The retiring chimps have been forgotten in the feud.
</P>
<P>
   Primarily Primates has raised money to retire tamarins, langurs,
gibbons, capuchins, even an orangutan named Punkin. But this time,
the group has $150,000. It needs $2.8 million.
</P>
<P>
   So Tello wrote newsletters to his group's members, and as he
did, the first 10 retirees came in a truck down the gravel road to
the sanctuary. They were lured into their new homes with apples and
marshmallows, while the male chimps in enclosures around them
strutted and posed.
</P>
<P>
   Swett and Tello learn more about them every day. Connie is
missing a finger, and Joan has a knot on her head. Clair has a lazy
left eye, Dee is affectionate, and Gigi has a steel plate where a
piece of her skull was removed.
</P>
<P>
   The chimps are adjusting well. Tello watches them interact,
climb, explore. He found them sleeping together the first night,
huddling on the same shelf to stay warm during a Texas freeze.
</P>
<P>
   This is how retirement should be, Tello says. It's a long way
from outer space.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   To donate, call Primarily Primates Inc. at (830) 755-4616. Or
write PPI, 26099 Dull Knife Trail, San Antonio, TX 78255.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
