<HEADER>
A3544 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-1998-SPI &LR;      12-31 1977
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-1998-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
'98 WILL BE REMEMBERED FOR UNCONVENTIONAL HOLLYWOOD FILMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   When they write the cultural history of the '90s, it seems
eminently possible 1998 could go down as one of the decade's more
audacious and interesting movie years, if not a major turning point
in the Hollywood cavalcade.
</P>
<P>
   It was a year in which more money was taken in than ever before
by a progression of bloated, overproduced and prototypically
tasteless Hollywood blockbusters: films like ``Armageddon,'' ``Deep
Impact,'' ``Dr. Doolittle'' and ``There's Something About Mary.''
</P>
<P>
   It was also a year in which the American independent movement
produced, according to a CNN estimate, more than 1,000 films,
almost all of which were amateurish and unreleasable: an
incomparable glut of low-budget mediocrity that fueled the least
memorable Seattle International Film Festival in memory.
</P>
<P>
   Also on the downside is that 1998 was a year in which more and
more foreign film industries edged toward collapse, including
once-healthy Hong Kong _ up until this catastrophic year the
world's second-largest film exporter.
</P>
<P>
   Hidden among all the happy statistics at year's end, a
pessimistic critic could also find unmistakable signs of an
industry in trouble: fewer tickets sold, too many screens built,
too much product for the existing audience, increasing studio
reliance on big-budget stupidity.
</P>
<P>
   And yet ...
</P>
<P>
   And yet it was also a year in which Hollywood filmmakers seemed
to launch their own in-house rebellion against the tyranny of the
system. Again and again in 1998, we saw major studio films (many of
which, sadly, failed at the box office) that at least tried to be
original, daring and provocative.
</P>
<P>
   Filmmakers such as Steven Spielberg, Warren Beatty, Brian De
Palma, Peter Weir, Steven Soderbergh, James Ivory and perhaps a
dozen others flouted the conventional wisdom of '90s filmmaking to
take huge risks and try something new in terms of story and
structure.
</P>
<P>
   The year produced perhaps the greatest barrage of unconventional
and original films since Hollywood's last golden age of the early
'70s. This was the year's true movie phenomenon. Despite Eddie
Murphy and ``Armageddon,'' Hollywood stretched itself in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   It is particularly telling that in this year of impeachment and
political trauma, the movies gave us three brilliant and
entertaining political comedies _ ``Wag the Dog,'' ``Primary
Colors'' and ``Bulworth'' _ that collectively define our national
malaise.
</P>
<P>
   The year also seemed to produce at least one excellent film in
every genre, including one of the greatest war films of all time
(``Saving Private Ryan''); the most captivating swashbuckler in
ages (``The Mask of Zorro''); an exquisitely touching western
(``The Horse Whisperer''); and a shrewdly seductive intellectual
thriller (``The Spanish Prisoner'').
</P>
<P>
   This was the first year in the '90s in which I had no trouble
coming up with a 10-best list.
</P>
<P>
   In no particular order (and leaving out films like ``The
Apostle'' and ``Wag the Dog,'' which opened in '98 but are
officially 1997 releases), my favorites were:
</P>
<P>
   Bulworth _ This hilarious, uniquely thought-provoking political
satire about an imbalanced U.S. senator who challenges the system
was the year's most daring and outrageous comedy and a film that
could have only been made by a director/star with Warren Beatty's
clout, audacity and liberal commitment.
</P>
<P>
   Saving Private Ryan _ Steven Spielberg's World War II epic about
a squad of soldiers on a dubious mission just after the Normandy
landings is one of Hollywood's greatest war movies: perhaps the
only one that has ever captured the true horror and utter
helplessness of combat.
</P>
<P>
   A Soldier's Daughter Never Cries _ This exquisite domestic drama
based on the life of expatriate author James Jones in Paris of the
'60s was the most successful Merchant-Ivory production in years and
that rare Hollywood film that actually celebrates a functional
family.
</P>
<P>
   Nights of Cabiria _ The seven-minute ``lost'' sequence added to
Fellini's 1957 masterpiece made this revival the one ``director's
cut'' that justifies itself: the new footage helped fill out the
heroine's character, sharpened Giuletta Masina's immortal
performance and made a great film even greater.
</P>
<P>
   Hands on a Hard Body _ Shot on video with a budget of about 50
cents, this account of a bizarre endurance contest sponsored by a
small-town Texas auto dealer was often brilliant, always totally
engrossing and hands down the year's best documentary.
</P>
<P>
   Out of Sight _ Steven Soderbergh turned Elmore Leonard's caper
novel into an off-beat and totally entertaining star vehicle that
was visually innovative, structurally fragmented, and wonderfully
determined to go against expectations at every turn.
</P>
<P>
   The Leading Man _ Almost no one saw it, but John Duigan's slice
of West End London life was arguably the movies' most thoroughly
enjoyable, intellectually intriguing and effortlessly sexy
contemporary backstage theater comedy-drama since ``All About
Eve.''
</P>
<P>
   Shakespeare in Love _ This Oscar-bound, what-if romantic comedy
about the Bard of Avon finding the inspiration he needs to write
``Romeo and Juliet'' was a voluptuous romance, a delightfully goofy
historical pastiche and the year's most witty and sophisticated
comedy.
</P>
<P>
   The Truman Show _ Jim Carrey pulled off the year's most
remarkable change-of-pace role as the poor soul who discovers he's
the subject of a reality-based TV show in this funny and profoundly
moving religious parable directed by Peter Weir.
</P>
<P>
   The Mask of Zorro _ Who says Hollywood can't make a rousing,
romantic, utterly irresistible historical swashbuckler of the old
school? The movies' umpteenth retelling of the legend of the Robin
Hood of Old California was all of this and more.
</P>
<P>
   THE WORST
</P>
<P>
   And (also in no particular order), the 10 worst were:
</P>
<P>
   Vampires _ John Carpenter's latest movie bloodbath was a
disturbing parable that deliriously communicates the joy of ethnic
cleansing (the victims are vampires, but they look and die just
like people) and seems otherwise designed to bring out the absolute
worst in its audience.
</P>
<P>
   Beloved _ This endless, almost incomprehensible, Oprah
Winfrey-produced film version of Toni Morrison's post-Civil War
novel almost requires a second viewing to fully appreciate what a
botched job of basic storytelling it was. The year's biggest
disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   Armageddon _ It may be the year's biggest grosser, but this
grindingly unoriginal, $100 million video game about the near-end
of the planet was moronic, filled with overblown and unnecessary
special effects and annoyingly played for wisecracky guffaws and
chest-pounding heroics.
</P>
<P>
   Krippendorf's Tribe _ This lewd, scatalogical, shockingly amoral
and numbingly overacted (by star Richard Dreyfuss) farce about an
anthropology professor who fakes a research project was the new
Disney company's idea of fun for the whole family in '98.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Marshals _ Ploddingly scripted, unimaginatively directed
and agonizingly predictable, this continuation of 1993's ``The
Fugitive'' _ with Tommy Lee Jones back as Inspector Gerard _
outdistanced ``Speed 2'' as the decade's worst sequel to a good
movie.
</P>
<P>
   Wide Awake/Simon Birch _ Something about the sheer clumsiness
with which these two films _ both about the consciousness-raising
of a young boy _ were calculated to be ``inspirational'' makes them
stick in the mind as landmarks in uninspired movie sappiness.
</P>
<P>
   Mafia!/BASEketball _ These two comedies from the Zuker-Abrahams
gang _ the first a spoof of ``The Godfather,'' the second a send-up
of professional sports in America _ proved that the strain of movie
satire that began with ``Airplane!'' 18 years ago has now been
completely played out.
</P>
<P>
   The Impostors _ Few comedies of 1998 fell quite as flat as this
Stanley Tucci-directed farce about two '30s-era New York actors on
the run who take refuge on an ocean liner populated by the most
charmless and unfunny ensemble of characters since ``Ship of
Fools.''
</P>
<P>
   The Odd Couple II _ Talk about beating a dead horse. This
collection of tasteless old-age jokes _ the nadir of the '90s
Matthau-Lemmon ``Grumpy Old Men'' cycle _ was so depressingly
vulgar and painful to endure that it erased all one's good memories
of the Neil Simon original.
</P>
<P>
   Two Guys and a Girl _ James Toback's three-character ode to
love-and-commitment in the '90s was an incomparably bad movie: so
shallow and empty, so overflowing with pretentious and unbelievable
dialogue, and finally so boring, that it played like a slap to the
face.
</P>
<P>
   THE REST
</P>
<P>
   Five other good movies: ``Gods and Monsters,'' ``Love and Death
on Long Island,'' ``The Spanish Prisoner,'' ``The Horse Whisperer''
and ``Primary Colors.''
</P>
<P>
   Five other bad movies: ``Hugo Pool,'' ``Nightwatch,'' ``The
Alarmist,'' ``My Giant'' and ``Sliding Doors.''
</P>
<P>
   Five disappointments: ``Firelight,'' ``Prince of Egypt,'' ``What
Dreams May Come,'' ``Pleasantville'' and ``The Chinese Box.''
</P>
<P>
   Five reasons why science fiction is a dying genre: ``Deep
Impact,'' ``Sphere,'' ``Star Trek: Insurrection,'' ``Lost in
Space'' and ``Phantoms.''
</P>
<P>
   Five good foreign films: ``Passion in the Desert,'' ``Gadjo
Dillo,'' ``Life Is Beautiful,'' ``The Chambermaid'' and ``Beyond
Silence.''
</P>
<P>
   Five bad foreign films: ``The Life of Jesus,'' ``Happy
Together,'' ``Live Flesh,'' ``Nil by Mouth'' and ``Post Coitum.''
</P>
<P>
   Five noble failures: ``Palmetto,'' ``Twilight,'' ``Men With
Guns,'' ``Homegrown'' and ``Snake Eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   Five guilty pleasures: ``Velvet Goldmine,'' ``Dangerous
Beauty,'' `The Newton Boys,'' ``Mercury Rising'' and ``Why Do Fools
Fall in Love?''
</P>
<P>
   Five Oscar-worthy performances by an actor: Tom Hanks in
``Saving Private Ryan,'' Warren Beatty in ``Bulworth,'' John Hurt
in ``Love and Death on Long Island,'' Ian McKellen in ``Gods and
Monsters,'' John Travolta in ``Primary Colors.''
</P>
<P>
   Five Oscar-worthy performances by an actress: Gwyneth Paltrow in
``Shakespeare in Love,'' Cate Blanchett in ``Elizabeth,'' Emma
Thompson in ``Primary Colors,'' Kristin Scott Thomas in ``The Horse
Whisperer'' and Meryl Streep in ``Dancing at Lughnasa.''
</P>
<P>
   Five Oscar-worthy performances by a supporting actor: Edward
Norton in ``The Rounders,'' Oliver Platt in ``Bulworth,'' Jeremy
Irons in ``The Man in the Iron Mask,'' Jude Law in ``Wilde'' and Ed
Harris in ``The Truman Show.''
</P>
<P>
   Five Oscar-worthy performances by a supporting actress: Halle
Berry in ``Why Do Fools Fall in Love?,'' Catherine Zeta-Jones in
``The Mask of Zorro,'' Claire Forlani in ``Meet Joe Black,'' Leelee
Sobieski in ``A Soldier's Daughter Never Cries'' and Scarlett
Johansson in ``The Horse Whisperer.''
</P>
<P>
   Good star chemistry: Harrison Ford and Anne Heche in ``Six Days,
Seven Nights,'' Denzel Washington and Annette Bening in ``The
Siege,'' George Clooney and Jennifer Lopez in ``Out of Sight,''
Natasha Richardson and Dennis Quaid in ``The Parent Trap'' and Kris
Kristofferson and Barbara Hershey in ``A Soldier's Daughter Never
Cries.''
</P>
<P>
   Best adaptation of a literary classic: ``Mrs. Dalloway.''
</P>
<P>
   Worst adaptation of a literary classic: ``Cousin Bette.''
</P>
<P>
   Best action sequence: The two car chases of ``Ronin.''
</P>
<P>
   Best remake: ``The Parent Trap.''
</P>
<P>
   Worst remake: ``Dr. Doolittle.''
</P>
<P>
   Five revivals worth reviving: ``Picnic at Hanging Rock,''
``Shock Corridor,'' ``Touch of Evil,'' ``Gone With the Wind'' and
``Women in the Dunes.''
</P>
<P>
   Best animated film: ``Antz.''
</P>
<P>
   Worst animated film: ``Quest for Camelot.''
</P>
<P>
   Face of the year: Gwyneth Paltrow.
</P>
<P>
   Worst documentary: Tie: ``Full Tilt Boogie'' and ``The Big
One.''
</P>
<P>
   Most critically overkilled blockbuster: Tie: ``The Avengers''
and ``Godzilla.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
