<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-1998-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOOKING AT THE '98 TV SEASON, CONSIDER SHOWS' OTTER POSSIBILITIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Spawning a hit show isn't easy. TV series fail for all sorts of
reasons. Bad writing. Bad acting. Bad scheduling. Bad breath.
</P>
<P>
   Even bad lettering can doom a promising show. For want of the
right consonant or vowel, a show can shrivel and die before the
audience has had the chance to embrace it and love it.
</P>
<P>
   Consider these 10, all of which premiered during a hit-starved
1998 but will never see 1999 because their titles may have been off
by just one letter.
</P>
<P>
   1. Original title: ``The Closer.'' Should have been: ``The
Closet.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead of playing a hotshot ad executive in another ho-hum
workplace comedy, Tom Selleck could have plowed fertile new ground
as a middle-age gay man who strikes out on his own in the cutthroat
world of personal-organization specialists.
</P>
<P>
   2. Original title: ``Prey.'' Should have been: ``Trey.''
</P>
<P>
   The original premise was on the right track, focusing on a new
superspecies of humanoid that threatened to eat the rest of us
mortals for lunch. With a more straightforward title, and with
William Gates III playing himself, this series might have opened
new doors (and a few windows) in television drama.
</P>
<P>
   3. Original title: ``Maximum Bob.'' Should have been: ``Maximum
Bod.'
</P>
<P>
   Beau Bridges was enjoyable as Elmore Leonard's quirky Southern
judge, but Pamela Anderson Lee might have fleshed out the role more
fully.
</P>
<P>
   4. Original title: ``Kelly Kelly.'' Should have been: ``Kelly
Killy.''
</P>
<P>
   This sitcom from The WB had Shelley Long playing a stuffy
academic (first name: Kelly) who marries an earthy fireman (last
name: Kelly). With a simple title revision, the network could have
tapped into that elusive 18-to-72-year-old demographic hooked on
aging French skiers.
</P>
<P>
   5. Original title: ``Ask Harriet.'' Should have been: ``Ash
Harriet.''
</P>
<P>
   This undercooked turkey on Fox was about a male sportswriter who
gets canned but manages to stay employed by masquerading as a
female advice columnist. Big yawn. If it had been about a woman who
disposes of cremated remains _ no matter the risk or the prevailing
winds _ wouldn't you have tuned in?
</P>
<P>
   6. Original title: ``Push.'' Should have been: ``Tush.''
</P>
<P>
   ABC could have kept the original premise: world-class athletes
striving to make it to the Olympics. A more honest title would have
avoided confusion among those who thought it was about drug
dealers, thus guaranteeing more viewers tuning in to see those
spandex-wrapped glutes.
</P>
<P>
   7. Original title: ``House Rules.'' Should have been: ``Horse
Rules.''
</P>
<P>
   NBC missed a bet by packaging this as another monotonous buddy
comedy. Had it gone with the recent trend toward courtroom shows,
complete with Mr. Ed as the presiding judge, it might have a
stableful of Emmys by now.
</P>
<P>
   8. Original title: ``The Simple Life.'' Should have been: ``The
Wimple Life.''
</P>
<P>
   This is one of two Martha Stewart sendups CBS tried in '98. (The
other was ``Style &AMP; Substance.'') Neither caught on. But if Judith
Light had played a nun with a penchant for gilding the convent's
doorknobs, CBS might have something to run in place of ``Becker.''
</P>
<P>
   9. Original title: ``Damon.'' Should have been ``Demon.''
</P>
<P>
   Damon Wayans as an undercover cop? Mildly amusing, but hampered
by unreasonable expectations when a show is named after the star.
With Wayans playing the keeper of hell's fire, the pressure is off
and it's only a matter of time before he's reunited with Jim
Carrey's bizarro fire inspector from their ``In Living Color''
days.
</P>
<P>
   10. Original title: ``Significant Others.'' Should have been:
``Significant Otters.''
</P>
<P>
   Rather than another steamy soaper a la ``Melrose Place,'' Fox
would have been wise to go with its current strength: reality-based
programming such as ``World's Wildest, Wackiest, Scariest
Refrigerator Magnets,'' or whatever.
</P>
<P>
   Who could possibly resist a weekly series about the mating
habits of a dysfunctional family of web-footed aquatic mammals?
</P>
<P>
   Ok, so here's my favorite new shows of 1998:
</P>
<P>
   1. ``Sports Night,'' ABC. Smart, fast-paced and oh-so-appealing.
</P>
<P>
   2. ``Maximum Bob,'' ABC. Dared to be wacky and politically
incorrect, and it got the ax.
</P>
<P>
   3. ``Felicity,'' The WB. Keri Russell gives the savviest network
a winner.
</P>
<P>
   4. ``Cupid,'' ABC. Cool idea from newcomer Rob Thomas; an
Emmy-worthy effort by Jeremy Piven.
</P>
<P>
   5. ``Dawson's Creek,'' The WB. Slowing down a bit, but it was an
auspicious start.
</P>
<P>
   6. ``Will &AMP; Grace,'' NBC. Supporting players lift this one above
the mass of mediocrity.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-31-98 1409EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
