<TEXT>
<P>
   Weekend Section stories from The New York Times News Service for
Friday, Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   PERMANENT-COLLECTIONS (New York) _ In terms of material things,
there's no place like New York and no time like the Christmas
holidays. The movement of people heading for the city's major
blockbuster art exhibitions in their final days produces
object-oriented human gridlock. Right now it feels like the whole
world is here on a class trip. If you desire an esthetic experience
that doesn't threaten life and limb, the city is rife with
relatively quiet, empty places to contemplate outstanding works of
art and related visual phenomena, places slightly or way off the
beaten path _ be they the less-popular galleries of the
Metropolitan Museum of Art or the Brooklyn Museum of Art; the
city's only indoor earthwork (Walter DeMaria's ``New York Earth
Room'' in Chelsea) or the great scale model of New York City at the
Queens Museum of Art. By Roberta Smith.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MOVIES &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   HOLIDAY-MOVIES (Undated) _ Critic's notebook: To a movie critic,
the holiday season now ending might be summed up in a single
Shakespearean phrase: ``the winter of our discontent.'' Hollywood
has come up sadly short this season in releasing movies that
combine mass appeal with high artistic merit. End-of-the-year
crowd-pleasers like ``Stepmom,'' ``Patch Adams,'' and ``You've Got
Mail'' are no match against ``Titanic,'' ``Good Will Hunting'' and
``As Good as It Gets,'' the previous holiday season's prestige
blockbusters. For audiences in search of holiday movies, here are
10 films currently playing that are worth a look. They are listed
in order of preference, with special attention given to worthy,
underrated acting performances. By Stephen Holden.
</P>
<P>
   DJEMA-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``Port Djema'': Eric Heumann,
director; in French, with English subtitles. Reviewed by Anita
Gates.
</P>
<P>
   FILMS4KIDS (Undated) _ Assessing the current cinema for children
of different ages.
</P>
