A3571 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WORKPLACE-VIOLENCE-HN     12-31 0921
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKPLACE-VIOLENCE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PASSIVE AGGRESSIVE EMPLOYEES ALSO A DANGER AT WORK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MICHAEL LOPEZ  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Workplace violence has become such a powerful
concern in recent years that a phrase, now almost a cliche, has
been added to the office lexicon: ``going postal.''
</P>
<P>
   While it is workplace murders that draw most of the media's
attention, they are rare compared with the work force weaponry of
passive aggression: gossip, rudeness, condescension and the cold
shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   Employees smart enough to realize that shoving or threats leave
the door open for easy retaliation have adopted covert ways to get
back at supervisors, colleagues, subordinates or the entire
company, according to a new study that examines who commits these
misdemeanors and why.
</P>
<P>
   Psychologists and employee assistance programs see the traumatic
results of aggression in their counseling sessions.
</P>
<P>
   ``People will come in daily _ and I'm not exaggerating _ with
stories of what bosses have done to them, what co-workers and
subordinates have done to them, what customers have done to them,''
said Rudy Nydegger, a clinical psychologist in private practice and
professor of psychology and management at Union College in
Schenectady.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's harmful, in so far that it interferes with job
satisfaction or morale,'' he said. ``This will impact people's
willingness to be at work, willingness to go the extra mile. It may
go so far as to impact productivity.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert A. Baron, a professor of management and psychology at
Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute, Joel H. Neuman, director of the
Center for Applied Management at the State University of New York
at New Paltz, and Temple University professor Deanna Geddes
surveyed 452 anonymous employees in six states to test their
central hypothesis that hostility and difficult behavior, like
``dirty looks'' or failing to return a call, are far more common
than threats or physical attacks.
</P>
<P>
   While the researchers anticipated one finding _ that workplace
violence is not rampant _ they also learned more about the factors
behind hidden aggression: that perceived injustice is strongly
associated with such hostility, which tends to be committed by
society's high achievers.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers' findings will be published in the scientific
journal Aggressive Behavior this spring.
</P>
<P>
   Baron, the author of 39 textbooks, including ``Human
Aggression,'' said he began to grow concerned about six years ago
when he started reading media accounts of violence, which he feared
was beginning to suggest an epidemic.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, three dozen people have died over the past 13 years at
post offices nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   But disgruntled co-workers account for just 4 to 6 percent of
1,000 workplace deaths reported annually, according to the National
Institute for Occupational Safety and Health.
</P>
<P>
   Though the U.S. Postal Service now bears the brunt of the
violent stereotype, Neuman maintains there is no evidence to
demonstrate that the post office, the largest civilian employer,
has an inherent condition that triggers violence.
</P>
<P>
   He and his co-researchers set out to tally the daily aggression
that is much more familiar to employees. (If a Top 10 list of
pettiness can seem harmless or even comical, remember the last time
someone seemed to grimace when you made a suggestion at a staff
meeting.)
</P>
<P>
   In the survey, more than a quarter of employees said they are
occasionally on the receiving end of some hostility once a month or
less: belittling criticism or backbiting, for instance.
</P>
<P>
   Fewer _ 16 percent _ said they are the occasional victims of
roadblocks, such as the missing memo or being overlooked for
meetings. Only 2.7 percent said they experience overt aggression _
assault, theft or threats.
</P>
<P>
   Perceived unfairness prompts these acts, the researchers found,
and the people who commit them have a surprising profile: They tend
to have Type A personalities. Perfectionists, yes, but also
hurried, pressured and irritable.
</P>
<P>
   These passive-aggressive retaliations, much like a spouse's
selective memory about doing their half of the chores, exact losses
that can't be counted.
</P>
<P>
   Think of the last time you withheld a cost-saving suggestion,
merely out of spite. ``This doesn't show up on a balance sheet,''
said Neuman.
</P>
<P>
   Covert aggression ``siphons off human energy. The energy ought
to be going to the job. I shouldn't be worrying about what the
person in the next office is going to do to me,'' Baron said.
</P>
<P>
   Both passive and aggressive people need lessons in
assertiveness, said Erica Sufrin, an associate professor at Albany
Medical College.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's direct communication, it's timely communication, it's
polite communication, it's clear communication. It's communication
that gets you where you want to go,'' said Sufrin.
</P>
<P>
   Passive people get stuck because they fear confrontation. One of
my jobs is to show them how to interact assertively and not have
confrontation,'' he said. ``For the aggressive folks, there's a lot
of emphasis on putting into words, early on, what they are feeling,
to themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   In an era that has seen its share of staff shortages and
downsizing, counselors and researchers say that the powerful, free
tools of courtesy and respect go a long way toward minimizing
workplace trespasses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just saying you're sorry when something terrible happens to an
employee can go a long way to reduce some of that anger,'' said
Neuman.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
