<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OIL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRANSMONTAIGNE OPENS BEACHHEAD IN UPSTATE NEW YORK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ALAN D. ABBEY  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   RENSSELAER, N.Y. _ TransMontaigne Inc., a major player in the
national oil distribution industry, has opened a beachhead in
upstate New York with the idea of linking it to a growing national
network that could include future local acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   The Denver-based firm said its TransMontaigne Terminaling Inc.
unit has purchased the Sunoco Inc. petroleum products terminal
located on the Hudson River at Rensselaer.
</P>
<P>
   Sale price of the operation was not released, in part because
details of the deal include Sunoco's continued use of the facility
for trucking and other purposes.
</P>
<P>
   TransMontaigne president Richard Gathright said the Sunoco
purchase comes on the heels of his company's purchase of a major
Northeast and mid-Atlantic distribution operation from Louis
Dreyfus Energy Corp. of Wilton, Conn. The Dreyfus unit, whose
closest terminal is in New York City, is part of the global S.A.
Louis Dreyfus &AMP; Cie. of France.
</P>
<P>
   Gathright said the Sunoco facility ``is really to support an
existing business for our company. Our whole goal is to put
together a supply network for major oil companies. Our grid is now
from the Rockies to the East Coast.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunoco spokesman Bud Davis said the terminal had been on the
market for some time.
</P>
<P>
   Gathright said the firm is looking at other local facilities and
businesses for possible acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   Sunoco will continue to use the facilities under a long-term
terminal services agreement and will base its local trucking
operation there.
</P>
<P>
   The Rensselaer terminal facilities include 510,000 barrels of
storage capacity, three truck-loading racks and a recently rebuilt
dock capable of handling both barges and ocean-going tankers.
Products currently handled at the facility include premium and
regular gasoline, low-sulfur diesel and heating oil.
</P>
<P>
   TransMontaigne, operating through wholly owned subsidiaries,
provides services to the petroleum and chemical industry from
locations of production and manufacture to utilization.
</P>
<P>
   According to Hoovers Inc., TransMontaigne gathers, transports,
stores and markets refined petroleum products and crude oil. It has
four natural gas gathering and processing facilities that are
capable of processing 85 million cu. ft. of natural gas a day.
</P>
<P>
   The company's TransMontaigne Transportation Services subsidiary
owns and operates more than 740 miles of oil pipeline, as well as
10 storage facilities in seven states with a total storage capacity
of about 4.8 million barrels.
</P>
<P>
   The company, with 375 employees, had fiscal 1998 sales of $1.97
billion, up 69 percent from the previous year. Net income was $7.6
million, with profit growth of 17.4 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
