<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-31 14:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3607 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZ-BOOKS-TEX     12-31 1070
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-BOOKS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALLIANCE WAVE OF THE FUTURE FOR TAKING PRIMARY POSITION IN AN
INDUSTRY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TERESA MCUSIC c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Giants are beginning to walk the earth.
</P>
<P>
   They are coming in the form of $1 trillion companies, uniting on
a global scale from top-flight leaders in individual countries.
</P>
<P>
   But they aren't conglomerates, multinationals or merger
creations. They are a breed of business much sleeker, more powerful
and easier to group and run together.
</P>
<P>
   They're ``alliances.''
</P>
<P>
   And they have been exploding in the 1990s, said author Cyrus
Friedheim, vice chairman of corporate consultant Booz-Allen &AMP;
Hamilton. The new enterprises will focus all their resources on
dominating one, or a few, fields. They will restructure whole
industries, change their economics, and turn the basis of
competition upside down, Friedheim writes. They will, collectively,
have all the capabilities necessary to win in a tough, competitive,
global marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   Friedheim writes his observations of the new business form in an
enlightening book, ``The Trillion-Dollar Enterprise: How the
Alliance Revolution Will Transform Global Business'' (Perseus
Books, 253 pages, $25).
</P>
<P>
   An alliance, simply put, is a group of companies that form a
network that, in turn, operates as a single company. But the
grouping is far more efficient, especially in use of its capital,
than the typical merger and acquisition.
</P>
<P>
   As Friedheim writes: ``It is consolidation without huge
investment, battles over ownership, postmerger headaches, and
regrets. The investment dollars can go into building market
positions, new products, capacity, and capabilities for enterprises
rather than for shares of an acquired company.''
</P>
<P>
   Alliances are also far easier in global operations, Friedheim
writes. The headaches over starting a company's presence abroad or
working with foreign regulatory boards in an acquisition can be
avoided when striking this other form of relationship agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Many companies are finding this method appealing, Friedheim
writes. He labels the 1990s as the dawn of the age of
collaboration.
</P>
<P>
   By 1995, more than 10,000 alliance formations were being made
annually. The rate is expected to double by the turn of the
century, Friedheim writes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are moving from highly parochial, well-guarded,
impermeable, turf-conscious castles to collegial, sharing,
permeable, flexible, moving areas of influence and
responsibility,'' he writes.
</P>
<P>
   Who is doing this? Friedheim sprinkles numerous examples
throughout his book, including such efforts as General Motors and
Toyota building a plant in Fremont, Calif. Pepsi and Lipton have
aligned to put Lipton products in Pepsi's distribution system. An
example found in the Fort Worth-Dallas area is the planned
agreement between British Airways and American Airlines.
</P>
<P>
   Another major source of alliance agreements is with the major
emerging market of China. Virtually any new business in China has
to work with a partner in the country, Freidheim says.
</P>
<P>
   Along that line, Freidheim writes that of the 20,000 alliances
formed globally between 1994 and 1996, about 75 percent were made
across national borders. Interestingly, the United States trails
the rest of the world in these global alliances, producing only
about 54 percent of its total during that time. In comparison, 90
percent of alliances in Europe and the Pacific Rim were made across
borders.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, however, alliances in the United States have
taken hold, Friedheim writes. In 1998, the U.S. average more than
doubled to more than $50 million in alliance investments from the
year before. But this country still lags in its skills for this
type of deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should expect very high growth in alliance activity in the
United States, a relative newcomer, as it catches up to Europe and
Asia,'' Freidheim writes. But ``European and Asian companies
indicated (in a survey) that their U.S. counterparts were behind in
the critical skills of integration planning and implementation.''
</P>
<P>
   Hence the need to read Friedheim's book, which provides not only
an excellent overview of a major business trend, but also a
textbook look at how to form the alliances, and then manage them.
</P>
<P>
   He also offers two looks at the future of the huge partnerships,
one bright and one dark, that provide thought-provoking
possibilities that economists, politicians and other people of
influence should analyze in the wake of the emerging giants.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   BLURBS
</P>
<P>
   ``If It's Broken, You Can Fix It: Overcoming Dysfunction in the
Workplace''
</P>
<P>
   By Tom E. Jones
</P>
<P>
   AMACOM, $24.95
</P>
<P>
   Do any of your employees have unstable relationships, harmful
habits, poor organization or lack of confidence or are unable to
make good choices? Chances are good that they may be what
behavioral scientists call ``dysfunctional.'' Organizational
development specialist Tom Jones discusses the increasing problem
of dysfunctional people in the work force, an area where typical
management concepts will likely fail. The book discusses how to
identify dysfunctional people and how to get the most out of them.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Kiplinger's Practical Guide to Your Money''
</P>
<P>
   By Ted Miller
</P>
<P>
   Kiplinger Washington Editors, $29.95
</P>
<P>
   Author Ted Miller is the editor of Kiplinger's Personal Finance
Magazine. In this book, he discusses money from soup to nuts,
covering all of the basics, including buying a home, car, college
education, life and health insurance and investments. With 720
pages, this book does more than just supply simple answers. But the
book is still just a primer, albeit a well-done one; don't expect
in-depth coverage.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``The Five Temptations of a CEO: A Leadership Fable''
</P>
<P>
   By Patrick Lencioni
</P>
<P>
   Jossey-Bass, $20
</P>
<P>
   This is the first business fiction piece by Patrick Lencioni,
president of a management consulting firm based in San Francisco,
but the plot line is similar to other books written to illustrate
business situations. A lone chief executive officer, troubled about
an impending board meeting in the morning, finds hope and
redemption talking to a janitor on a train home. A quick read that
might touch a few managers, if they bother to read it.
</P>
<P>
   (Teresa McUsic reviews business books for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
