<HEADLINE>
SAN FRANCISCO REOPENS CITY HALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GERALD D. ADAMS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ When San Francisco's City Hall, the peoples'
palace, reopens its gilt doors Jan. 5 for the first time in four
years, old-timers will recognize the place _ bits of it, that is.
</P>
<P>
   They'll find the mayor back in his usual spot in the east wing;
the Board of Supervisors in the west; and the city attorney in her
southeast corner alongside the mayor _ though only with some of her
deputies.
</P>
<P>
   Almost all other departments and hearing rooms have shifted
locations.
</P>
<P>
   Designed by architect Arthur Brown in the French Renaissance
style, City Hall is considered by many experts to be San
Francisco's most beautiful structure.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the building, which was constructed in 1915, had
become obsolete in an age when everyone from high officials to low
clerks need computers, FAX machines and video equipment to
function.
</P>
<P>
   The 1989 Loma Prieta earthquake rattled plaster from the walls,
drove the mayor and supervisors out to temporary quarters and
forced $293 million in renovations to the old domed building.
</P>
<P>
   While less conspicuous than the glittering gold leaf on City
Hall's restored dome, which rises to 301 feet, higher than that of
the nation's Capitol, many details now enrich the interior.
</P>
<P>
   Three early-day birdcage style elevators, out of service for as
long as most people can remember, have been restored to public use,
re-gilded and outfitted with high-speed cabs. Lead crystal
chandeliers have been recast in southwestern France and oak
paneling has been installed here and there to improve acoustics and
appearance.
</P>
<P>
   Airy sky-lighted spaces on the main floor will be open to the
public. High above, on the fourth floor, hand-crafted architectural
details provide the wandering mind a break from the daily grind of
city business.
</P>
<P>
   On the first floor, the awesomely scaled rotunda, together with
the grand stairway that leads to the Board of Supervisors chamber,
has been cleaned and polished. The offices of the assessor and
recorder are still on the first floor but take less space than in
the old days. Some of their staffs have been moved to an upper
floor.
</P>
<P>
   The most startling changes affect the building's first floor
light courts, areas rarely seen by the general public. As City
Hall's bureaucracy grew in size, these huge (60 feet by 120 feet)
skylit spaces became off limits to the public as they came to be
crammed with desks. They are now open spaces, available for
walk-throughs, receptions, exhibits or simply adding to the
esoteric experience of a palatial interior.
</P>
<P>
   The south light court is being outfitted for exhibits as a
museum of San Francisco history.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere on the first floor, gold-trimmed birdcage-style
elevators have been rebuilt to high-speed velocity. None has been
available for public use for many years. There are six other
elevators of more recent vintage.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Willie Brown and his assistants will occupy the same
second-floor suite overlooking Civic Center and Polk Street as the
city's mayors before him. A new addition to the executive suite is
a large conference room intended as a place where the mayor can
meet department heads and hold negotiation sessions with the likes
of labor leaders and real estate developers.
</P>
<P>
   Clark Manus, principal architect of the team that designed the
renovation, said the public will find a City Hall that has been
``brought it back to its original glory.''
</P>
<P>
   In a pre-opening tour, Manus pointed out details that otherwise
might go unnoticed by the casual visitor: new chandeliers that
conceal fluorescent lights and are operated by motion detectors;
new carpeting; the addition of two stairways between the basement
and first floor; a surrounding concrete moat, part of the seismic
reinforcement project, that would allow the huge structure to move
several feet during a major earthquake; and accessibility ramps for
handicapped persons on the second floor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
