<SLUG> BC-FOOD-CHOCOLATE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUTHOR DAZZLES WITH CHOCOLATE COOKBOOK 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: See FOOD-CHOCOLATE-RECIPES) 
 
By DAI HUYNH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Rich and smooth, chocolate tickles the throat and
seduces the senses.
</P>
<P>
   ``People love chocolate not only because it tastes so good, but
it also feels so good. It's just one of those things that
captivates people,'' pastry guru Nick Malgieri says.
</P>
<P>
   Malgieri's love affair with the cocoa bean started long before
the prestigious Peter Kump's New York Cooking School named him
baking program director.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father would buy me chocolate bars as a little boy,''
recalls the New Jersey native.
</P>
<P>
   Later, the first-generation Italian-American started stockpiling
chocolate recipes while his teen-age buddies were collecting Marvel
comics and U.S. stamps. So it's a little wonder the 51-year-old
Malgieri wrote ``Chocolate: From Simple Cookies to Extravagant
Showstoppers'' (HarperCollins, $40).
</P>
<P>
   ``My primary goal was to put all those chocolate recipes in one
place so I can get to them easily,'' he says, only half-joking.
</P>
<P>
   Illuminated by glossy color photographs, the richly illustrated
book is a chocolate bible. It features 380 chocolate recipes,
ranging from crusty pies and creamy puddings to melt-in-your-mouth
cookies and elaborate cakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to collect my thoughts on chocolate and share them
because I think some of what I do with chocolate is unique,''
Malgieri says.
</P>
<P>
   Adding new twists to old standards is Malgieri's signature. Take
his simplified version of the Swiss chocolate meringue cookies, for
example. The traditional recipe requires whipping the egg whites,
then pouring hot sugar syrup over them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a nightmare to do,'' says Malgieri, who discovered that
heating and whipping the sugar and egg whites together works just
as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a lot more simpler and straightforward to do, but it
doesn't sacrifice the essential taste or texture of the recipe.''
</P>
<P>
   Interspersed with simple step-by-step recipes using three or
four ingredients are challenging creations such as the lavish
yogurt poppyseed cake with white chocolate frosting and a luscious
frozen chocolate bourbon souffl.
</P>
<P>
   Among Malgieri's favorites are the Supernatural Brownies, a
discovery he stumbled upon while making a batch of old-fashioned
brownies for a party.
</P>
<P>
   ``To make enough for everyone, I increased all the ingredients
by 50 percent _ except for the flour,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't just take the brownies out of the pan and add a cup
of flour. They were already in the oven.''
</P>
<P>
   The brownies ended up even fudgier and were a hit with everyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can find recipes all over if you're looking,'' Malgieri
says with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Take the time he found a recipe for ``the world's greatest
brownies'' scribbled on an index card next to a train-station
garbage can.
</P>
<P>
   And once, Malgieri bribed a Sicilian abbess with a food
processor in exchange for a pistachio couscous recipe. ``It's
unique in all the world. I was trying like crazy to get this
recipe,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, they didn't give me the recipe, but they did produce the
nun that makes the recipe, and she was willing to answer questions
about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether making couscous or chocolate eclairs, Malgieri
recommends using the best ingredients available.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't make something good out of ingredients that aren't
good,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
