<HEADLINE>
TOPS IN FOOTBALL, BOTTOM IN GRADUATING PLAYERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Saturday, Jan. 2, 1999; normally moves Friday)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DERRICK Z. JACKSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; (Last of two parts)
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee is the top-ranked college football team in the country
going into this weekend's major bowl games, but in my third annual
Graduation Gap Bowl, it is one of the lowest ranked in the
classroom. Tennessee had the second-worst graduation rate out of
the teams that were either ranked by the Associated Press or were
picked to play in the holiday bowls.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee's graduation rate of 27 percent was second only to the
20 percent of Arkansas. Tennessee had the fourth worst graduation
rate for African-American players, 15 percent, the sixth worst
graduation rate for white players, 48 percent, and the third worst
gap between the graduation rates of African-American players and
the general student body (15 percent vs. 56 percent).
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee was hardly alone. Of the nation's top 12 ranked teams,
eight of them (Tennessee, Ohio State, Kansas State, UCLA, Florida,
Texas A&AMP;M, Arkansas and Georgia Tech) were also among the worst 13
in graduation gaps between African-American players and the general
student body. They had gaps of at least 30 percentage points, way
above the Division 1 average of 13 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Texas A&AMP;M had the largest gap, with a 68 percent student body
graduation rate and 20 percent for its African-American players.
</P>
<P>
   This season, Tennessee head coach Phillip Fulmer said, ``There's
more pressure on coaches now than ever before. It's amazing. Right
now you have to win the division. Then you have to win the
conference. Then you have to win the conference again: the
championship game. Then you hope that you're going to (win a major
bowl game). Otherwise you have not had a great season.''
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee is No. 1 on the field. It it also No. 2 in the
Graduation Gap Bowl. What Fulmer can never say out loud is that it
is easier to handle the pressure to win when he is under no
pressure to graduate his players. The following are the rankings of
the 47 teams on the field and off.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Associated Press Top 25
</P>
<P>
   1. Tennessee, 2. Florida State, 3. Ohio State, 4. Kansas State,
5. Arizona, 6. UCLA, 7. Florida, 8. Texas A&AMP;M, 9. Wisconsin, 10.
Tulane, 11. Arkansas, 12. Georgia Tech, 13. Virginia, 14. Nebraska,
15. Michigan, 16. Air Force, 17. Notre Dame, 18. Syracuse, 19.
Georgia, 20. Texas, 21. Oregon, 22. Penn State, 23. Missouri, 24.
Miami, 25. Mississippi State
</P>
