<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FREEDOM-RIDER-4 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE MAN'S CRUSADE FOR THE POOR OF THE SOUTH 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-ART-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: Three photos are being sent to NYTNS clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchases by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.)  
 (Eds.: Wil is cq)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WIL HAYGOOD  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAGLE ROCK, Va. _ A man who lives atop a mountain here communes
with the dead. He swears they've told him _ the dead that is _ to
rid America of its poor.
</P>
<P>
   So he travels rural roads, into towns that don't show up on
maps, into towns you've never heard of.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes he'll be driving, down through the Georgia pines,
across that endless Mississippi Delta, and he'll feel his body get
to aching, he'll feel the sleep climbing up into his eyes, he'll
wish he were twenty years younger. But he just keeps going. Rolling
toward the poor.
</P>
<P>
   Once, right here in Virginia, he drove the car into a ditch.
Asleep at the wheel. Three weeks later he was up, rolling again.
Trying not to think about the busted ribs, the broken hand, or the
dark things the doctor had said about his heart. The dead _ slave
ancestors buried in a plot 30 feet from his front door here _ won't
let him be. ``I can feel them,'' the man says.
</P>
<P>
   Old Harris Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   Old William Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   Old Emma Ray.
</P>
<P>
   Little Emma Ray.
</P>
<P>
   Little Emma was Emma Ray's namesake and daughter. Poor thing:
she died in infancy.
</P>
<P>
   The world hardly knows the man on the mountain, though he may
have done as much to lift the hearts and raise the sights of the
Southern black poor as any man alive.
</P>
<P>
   His name is Donald Anderson. He's an intellectual. He's kind and
generous. He's also vain _ and, with his wobbly cowboy walk, lofty
manner, and green eyes, something of a curiosity to almost everyone
he meets.
</P>
<P>
   But if he can be absent minded about the small things, Anderson
is a demon about the big picture: Poor folk will rise. And from
that dream has grown an organization _ inspired by the resolute
localism of the British House of Commons and the ideals of Thomas
Jefferson _ that, for thirty years, has been quietly bringing true
grass-roots democracy to rural communities across America's South.
</P>
<P>
   He calls it The Assembly _ a network of mini-parliaments, formed
of 50 citizens each, that is built anew in every town Anderson
enters, that first shadows and then dislodges the traditional
government structure. He works in the tradition of other ground-up
community organizers, but his targets are among the toughest, and
his methods and passion uniquely and entirely his own.
</P>
<P>
   In the beginning, everywhere he went, it seemed, folk tugged at
his elbow, dropped words into his ears, told him he couldn't
sweet-talk his way into rural communities as an outsider and
organize them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did it forty-one times,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   For thirty years, in unknown places, in misbegotten towns.
</P>
<P>
   There he stands, in the homes of poor folk, shaking hands that
have lifted contaminated well water that very morning, telling men
who have trouble with the alphabet that they can sidle right up to
Thomas Jefferson and his beliefs and make something large of
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   He's seen barely literate souls, men and women, transformed into
leaders. In some counties whole political structures have been
upended, turned around, set loose in new directions.
</P>
<P>
   There are moments, too, when his whole vision gets reduced to
the simplicity of goodwill _ a warm coat found and draped around
the shoulders of a woman living in a shack the cold wind owns.
</P>
<P>
   In all, his assemblies have brought $20 million in development
to the rural South, but he hasn't been feted at one testimonial
dinner. He hasn't had one medal draped around his neck. He seems
not to mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``All he cares about is a roof over his head,'' says Wyche
Fowler, the former US Senator from Georgia whose friendship with
Anderson dates back 35 years.
</P>
<P>
   Now Anderson _ whose National Community Development Organization
has previously concentrated on the American South _ is moving
north. He wants to reopen the debate about the crumbling cities of
America. The other week he was in Cleveland. Then Washington, D.C.,
where his organization is headquartered. Washington might well be
the nation's largest think tank, where, day in and day out, the
problems seem to outfox the thinkers. There he was, under the roof
of an urban church, eyes gleaming, telling mothers and fathers who
live on a street where crime has started to creep badly to hold on,
telling drug addicts that Thomas Jefferson is getting ready to
march into their lives.
</P>
<P>
   He's been on this road before. He was there in the Sixties, when
there was footstomping and rage on behalf of the poor. But then the
political climate changed, the rage quieted. A lot of the marchers
went home.
</P>
<P>
   As for Donald Anderson, he kept dreaming. Then he came down off
the mountain, tossing off the highclass dreams his own parents held
for him _ breaking their hearts without meaning to _ and swearing
to cure a nation of what ails it, rumbling against time as the dead
men and women who sleep near him _ ``the folks in the back yard,''
he calls them _ kept whispering, driving him. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Seeds of hope &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The plan was to slip into rural communities, where the citizens
were often distant and disconnected from one another. He planned to
organize in groups of 50. Each group would elect officers and
representatives. Collectively, an Assembly would be drawn from the
group representatives. The Assembly itself would agree on one
problem _ sewers, schools, housing _ and attack it with unity and
vigor.
</P>
<P>
   It was early 1968 and Donald Anderson was looking for someplace
to test his vision.
</P>
<P>
   ``Martin told me about Surry,'' Anderson says.
</P>
<P>
   That Martin.
</P>
<P>
   They'd met in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   An impoverished old Virginia farming town, Surry had long been a
place where blacks outnumbered whites, yet a black had never held
elective office. In 1959 public school officials _ with the state's
blessing _ boarded up the schools in nearby Prince Edward County
rather than integrate. The move ignited ``massive resistance''
across the state to integrated public education. In Surry whites
pulled their children out of the schools. All-white private
academies flourished.
</P>
<P>
   When Anderson reached Surry, he met Walter Hardy, C.C. Pettaway,
and Thaddeus Lane. Three black men. Three poor men.
</P>
<P>
   Hardy and Pettaway had risen to become community leaders. Hardy,
who had worked as a gardener and a chauffeur for a well-to-do white
family, was working at a packing plant. Lane was scuffling as a
small farmer. Pettaway got by on welding work.
</P>
<P>
   Three common men. Donald Anderson saw royalty in them. But they
were suspicious of him.
</P>
<P>
   ``They thought I was a communist,'' remembers Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   ``He came here as a surprise to us,'' says Walter Hardy. ``Came
here with a white secretary. That was a no-no in this area. We
didn't know if he was fly-by-night or what. He came here with a
set-up we had never heard of, talking about the British House of
Commons.''
</P>
<P>
   Three men, and not a one without scars.
</P>
<P>
   For years C.C. Pettaway had been quiet as stone. Then they let
the schools go to ruin rather than integrate. He had children, and
they needed to learn, to grip schoolbooks. When the schools finally
reopened, whites didn't return. Somehow a lot of the public
education money got siphoned off into those all-white private
academies. Quiet no more, Pettaway went to court and sued.
</P>
<P>
   Quiet, too, until he couldn't stay away from the restaurant any
longer.
</P>
<P>
   Not long after the ``Whites Only'' sign finally came down at the
Surry House Restaurant, C.C. Pettaway ambled inside. He ordered a
steak. He waited a long time, but it finally came. He sat there,
joyful as a man at a feast. It wasn't the steak, which was actually
a bloody mess when he knew good and well he had ordered it
well-done. It was just knowing it was his.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-31-98 1510EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
