<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPCL-FREEDOM-RIDER-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ATTN EDITORS:  

</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: Three photos are being sent to NYT clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchases by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.)  
 For Immediate Release
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; When Donald Anderson first shared his dreams of lifting the
hearts and raising the sights of the South's black poor, a lot of
people rolled their eyes and closed their doors. But that didn't
stop him. Now, after 30 years, his ``Assembly,'' a network of
mini-parliaments, has transformed once disenfranchised men and
women in small, forgotten towns into leaders. Anderson works in the
tradition of ground-up community organizers, but his targets are
among the toughest, and his methods and passion uniquely his own.
His story is written by Wil Haygood and photographed by Bill
Greene, of the Globe staff. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FREEDOM-RIDER (Eagle Rock, Va.) -- Donald Anderson, with his
vision of poor black people in &UR;  &LR; the South gaining a hold on their
lives and government, is making a difference. By Wil Haygood. (4
takes) PHOTOS &UR;  &LR; (3)
</P>
<P>
   For questions, contact  &UR; Frank Perrotta  &LR; at the Boston Globe,
 &UR; 617-929-2597. &LR;  All files will bear the BOS designator and move
under the General National (a) category code.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Boston Globe &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
