<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981231.0196 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-31 15:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3670 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FREEDOM-RIDER-2ND &LR;  &UR; TA     12-31 1311
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FREEDOM-RIDER-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 EAGLE ROCK, Va.: ... it was his.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hardy's awakening began when he entered the service.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know I had a country until I went to the Army,'' says
Hardy. ``White officer said to me, `This is your country too.'
Being from little ole Surry, I didn't realize that.''
</P>
<P>
   For years Lane and Pettaway and Hardy wanted to do things,
dreamed of doing things. But even with blacks a clear majority in
Surry, they couldn't crack the ranks of office holders. Truth be
told, they'd never raised a loud voice. They thought Surry would
always be Surry.
</P>
<P>
   Then came Donald Anderson. This stranger to Surry spelled out
his vision in detail, and before long infant hope was born of his
words.
</P>
<P>
   ``They know what they want,'' Anderson says. ``They want jobs
for their community. They want better housing. They want recreation
to take the youths off the street. What they want is a better
society.''
</P>
<P>
   So it went in Surry: every month, an Assembly meeting. And every
month, another little community feud stamped out in favor of unity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes,'' explains Walter Hardy, ``you talk about peanuts
and corn at the same time. But with the Assembly, you weren't
allowed to talk about peanuts until you got the problem of the corn
solved.''
</P>
<P>
   After three years, in 1971, the Surry Assembly announced a slate
of candidates to run for board of supervisors. Surry had never had
a black on its five-member board of supervisors, and now three men
_ common men _ were running. And all three won.
</P>
<P>
   In time, too, Thaddeus Lane, an unschooled farmer, a man who
remembers paying a $1.50 poll tax to cast his first vote years ago,
would win election as county treasurer.
</P>
<P>
   ``A minor rebellion,'' Donald Anderson called it.
</P>
<P>
   Hardy and the other black board supervisors had no experience
with power. ``We finally knew we had to stop criticizing,'' says
Hardy. ``We had to govern.''
</P>
<P>
   So they brought in experts to offer them technical advice. They
applied for and received foundation funds to help them attack
county poverty. They brought in a doctor. They got funds to build a
clinic.
</P>
<P>
   The Surry schools were in scary shape. Most of the white
children had been pulled out, and even many rural black kids stayed
away, their parents fearing violence. But in time, propelled by
priorities set in the local Assembly, the Surry school system
revolutionized itself. Good teachers came and stayed. An all-black
school system began to integrate itself as whites poured back into
the system. Surry High School went from last in the state in test
scores to the top third on national standardized tests. Today, 95
percent of Surry graduates go on to further their educations.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Williams is principal of Surry High. If he could work 40
hours a day, he would. It's the kids; they elevate him. He'll see a
knot of kids coming down the hall toward him and it's like
something warm and righteous flowing into him. He'll start
backslapping. He'll start complimenting. He'll start goading.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hi, Mr. Williams.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, Mr. Williams.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Now this boy here could be brilliant,'' Mr. Williams says,
pulling a kid toward him. ``Gotta stay on him though. Gotta stay on
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Some mornings Frank Williams will be sitting in his office and
the phone rings and it's Don Anderson on the other end. He's coming
into Surry, now. He forgot to call yesterday to make an
appointment, and he's sorry. But he's on the way and he's got some
think tank folks with him and a congressman and a corporate
executive and he can't wait to show them the school, to show them
the classrooms, to share the latest news of the latest test scores
with them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just say, `OK, Don, anything for you,' '' says Williams.
</P>
<P>
   And then there's Anderson, whooshing into the building, quick
hellos to Frank Williams and others, then bolting down the hallway
with his visitors, pointing out kids, poking his head in
classrooms, interrupting the classrooms with his giddiness, talking
in that stop-and-go-like fashion of his _ ``Well, uh, hi, uh, well,
uh, isn't this beautiful!'' Kids getting a good education. It fills
him like helium. Then he's turning, galloping toward the exit
because he's running late for his next appointment. And there's
Frank Williams, standing in the middle of the hallway, smiling,
shaking his head, one eye on the backside of the vanishing Anderson
and the other eye on the kids coming toward him.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first glance you don't know how to take the brother,''
Williams says of Anderson. ``But once you understand where he wants
to go, the man becomes a giant . . . In the old days we had a
saying. `That brother's been touched.' Don's been touched. You
don't know why.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
`He had an epiphany' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The man who would change the lot of America's poor and
disfranchised has never known a day of poverty in his life. ``We
had cars during the Depression,'' Donald Anderson says, twin
touches of pride and arrogance in his voice.
</P>
<P>
   He was born 66 years ago in Pittsburgh, into a family of Negroes
who walked with arched backs, who flaunted their college degrees.
``We did not hobnob with the humdrum,'' as Anderson puts it.
</P>
<P>
   His mother, Celeste, was a teacher, his father, Russell, a
biologist enamored of microscopes, bugs, and genetics.
</P>
<P>
   An aunt was a psychologist. An uncle had an advanced genetics
degree. Another aunt, Helen Baker, would become the first black
woman to attend the University of Maryland law school.
</P>
<P>
   And then there was Uncle Sylvester Anderson, who didn't have
credentials to flaunt, but who taught young Donald another kind of
lesson. Sylvester was a river rat in Virginia, where the family's
lineage began. An old black man who beat the last march of slavery,
but who heard enough stories to pass along. Donald Anderson would
sit across from Uncle Sylvester and just stare. His uncle seemed
ancient to him. It was Uncle Sylvester who saved money to buy land
on a mountaintop in Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   So Donald Anderson's childhood, wrapped as it was in the
travails of black America, was nevertheless rich in example and in
lessons.
</P>
<P>
   Like the one Helen Baker taught him. Diagnosed with a rare form
of cancer as she was about to enter law school, she was given a
year by her doctors. She was blessed with 20 more. On her deathbed
she turned to her nephew, Donald, and with a clarity that was
fairly stunning, summoned up words that would stick with him: ``I
knew that every day I woke could be my last. That meant this
minute, this hour . . . was the most important one. Therefore,
whoever is standing in front of me is king of the world, if kings
are important.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson's father was, he says, ``a brilliant man.'' Also
something of an intellectual pioneer in a race-divided land. He
lectured widely overseas and in his own land, though he knew, when
in America, to travel with a blanket and sheet. Jim Crow didn't
make exceptions for the exceptional, and often Russell Anderson
would wind up bundled up outside.
</P>
<P>
   By 1943 the Anderson family had relocated to Washington so
Russell Anderson could begin a medical internship at Freedman's
Hospital (now Howard University Hospital).
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, heady minds were rolling in and out of the
Anderson home. Mordecai Johnson, the influential president of
Howard University, would visit. So would Howard Thurman, the
renowned minister. Young Donald Anderson heard their echoes, saw
their footprints.
</P>
<P>
   But the boy, even with sisters and a brother, a mother and
father, grew lonely. ``Whenever we moved onto a street, all the
`best friends' were already taken,'' he remembers.
</P>
<P>
   The friends he did find were between the hardcovers of books.
His sisters and brother would be outside playing, and Donald would
be upstairs, reading, aloud: Victor Hugo, Edgar Allan Poe,
Alexandre Dumas and, above all, Shakespeare.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
