<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981231.0197 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-31 15:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3674 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FREEDOM-RIDER-4TH &LR;  &UR; TA     12-31 1224
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FREEDOM-RIDER-4TH </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 EAGLE ROCK, Va.: ... he says.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   But still the connection was made. Slowly but surely
Mississippians began signing on to the Assembly, or investing it
with their hopes.
</P>
<P>
   Two among them live on a road in Lamont, Mississippi. It's a
road that leads to a shack, that is really a home, a good home,
because two people who've never left each other's side live there.
</P>
<P>
   Jeanette and Leeandrew Priest's children are all grown, living
elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``Got a daughter in Jackson,'' he says, making Jackson sound far
away as Paris, France.
</P>
<P>
   There's a three-inch layer of green sewage running through the
backyard, around the sides of the house. Odessa Carter, who lives
across the road, who was the first recruit for the Assembly in
Lamont, is standing with Claude King next to the Priests, looking
down on the sewage, shaking her head, vowing that the Assembly will
do something. She mentions putting pressure on the local health
commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   The couple don't know how they hold on. They hold on by holding
on to each other.
</P>
<P>
   Back on the road, Claude King had said that the Assembly in
Lamont will have to get every eligible voter registered. When
that's done, he said, there will be a face to face meeting with
Lamont health officials. ``It's a powerful tool,'' King says about
voter registration.
</P>
<P>
   Claude King's next stop is a restaurant in tiny Marks,
Mississippi. He's looking for Robert Jamison, the Assembly's man in
Marks. Jamison eventually shows, and he's hungry. Soon enough,
there's a plate of food in front of him: lima beans and corn bread
and candied yams and fried chicken. A glass of ice tea, sweetened.
</P>
<P>
   ``You go through rural areas, and you have people who don't even
know elections are going on,'' Jamison says, vowing that the
Assembly will change all of that.
</P>
<P>
   An hour later he's on Cotton street _ Martin Luther King once
visited Cotton Street, and someone spotted tears streaking his
cheeks in front of a shack without running water. Now Jamison
stands in front of another shack with green slime that's formed its
own ravine. ``Still,'' he says, turning the clock back and turning
it forward, ``people are living like this.''
</P>
<P>
   He's vowing to do something, to have the people energized by the
Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   Jamison's got an office downtown. Sometimes it'll be crowded:
mamas with sons in jail who need help. Mamas whose cupboards at
home are empty of food. People who need jobs. The oil mill in Marks
used to employ 500 people. Now it's down to 90 praying souls who
hope they'll have a job next week, next month, tomorrow. Soon,
Jamison believes, the hungry will be turned into parliamentary
officers. Assembly believers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They love the idea,'' Jamison says about Marks citizens who've
been introduced to the Assembly. ``The Assembly is set up so a
person can express his ideas. Everybody can get up and say their
peace.''
</P>
<P>
   Thirty miles from Marks _ as the Mississippi crow flies _ lies
Glendora. It's Johnny B. Thomas's town. Everybody calls him Johnny
B. He used to work over at Parchman Penitentiary. As Southern
penitentiaries go, Parchman used to be the scariest. Johnny B.'s
daddy did time at Parchman for killing a man outside a grocery
store in Glendora. Victim was a black man so he only got five
years.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Johnny B.'s got the Assembly up and running in Glendora.
He's putting together a library. He's got three books so far. He
had some officials in recently for an economic summit. They held
hands and prayed at the end of the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Poverty, unemployment, housing, you name it,'' Johnny B. says
as far as plotting tasks for the Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   Simply working together is as much a revelation as the prospect
of getting things done.
</P>
<P>
   ``We blacks came from the plantation,'' the mayor says. ``We've
been totally taught not to do anything together. Back in '68 I came
off the plantation. My momma got lucky enough to get a little piece
of land and got us out.''
</P>
<P>
   A cottony darkness is falling across the delta now. Claude King,
Donald Anderson's man in Mississippi, is heading home.
</P>
<P>
   In Mississippi, everyone has a story. Some just haunt. Some are
beautiful.
</P>
<P>
   Here's Claude King's story.
</P>
<P>
   Virginia, his wife, got sick a few years back. By then they were
separated. Night after night he'd visit her in the hospital.
Sometimes she'd be asleep when he arrived, asleep when he left. But
watching her lying there on crisp white sheets, he started falling
in love again, with Virginia, with the woman he had married, then
distanced himself from. One day, in the hospital, he told himself
that as soon as she got better, he was going to ask her to move
back in with him, to become husband and wife again. One evening he
left. The phone rang at home. When he got back to the hospital
Virginia was dead.
</P>
<P>
   Not long afterward, Brian, one of his sons, was walking down a
road, was hit by some speeding fool, and killed. King just cried.
He didn't have enough faith left in him to fill a teacup. Then
Donald Anderson called, told him he needed him in Mississippi, told
him he was important, told him they could save some souls.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don's different, sure enough,'' Claude King says. ``But you
gotta love him.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
`On the verge of glory' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Donald Anderson doesn't know why, but he's looked at poor
people, folk with less than fifty bucks to their name, and he's
felt energized, emboldened, strong as an ox all over again.
</P>
<P>
   He's put 60,000 miles on one car, driving from county to county,
state to state. He's felt like a traveling preacher.
</P>
<P>
   This is what he likes most: the improbability of it all. How to
explain Thaddeus Lane, uneducated, now the Surry treasurer? How to
explain Robert Jamison, going in and out of the Marks jail in
Mississippi?
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to organize the whole South,'' Donald Anderson says.
</P>
<P>
   To him, it's all made perfect sense: the tragedy of Shakespeare
and American slavery; the pure honest gesture of reaching down and
helping the poor; the love of family, those living, those dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not everyone,'' he says, ``who can look down over the
plantation on which their ancestors were slaves.''
</P>
<P>
   His friends sometimes wonder if he's a happy man. He's never
married, there are no children. ``No one woman would stay with
Donald,'' says his sister Dorothy.
</P>
<P>
   But what seems missing from Anderson's life is no match for what
he has made of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're on the verge of glory,'' he believes.
</P>
<P>
   Russell Anderson is dead. Died in Florida, free as the wind. His
son Donald brought him here, to the mountaintop, placed that
learned and super-educated man in the ground. With the slaves.
</P>
<P>
   Old Emma Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   Old Harris Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   Little Emma.
</P>
<P>
   A green-eyed man sat down one day and wrote some verse, apropos
of nothing, save perhaps, life, death, and all the rain that comes
in between. The verse, framed, hangs in his mountaintop home. On
good bright afternoons, the sun slides into the cabin and catches
the words cleanly, lighting them:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(begin poetry style) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If We Shall Die
</P>
<P>
   And Pass Away
</P>
<P>
   Merge with the earth
</P>
<P>
   As if we have not lived
</P>
<P>
   Then Why?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(end poetry style) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He's down off the mountain now, cemetery dirt on his shoes,
heading for Washington, where he knows he'll find some poor folks,
kings and queens to him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-31-98 1516EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
