<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-31 15:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3679 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUTO-COLUMN-$ADV02-BO     12-31 1266
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTO-COLUMN-$ADV02-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN WINTER, EXERCISE A LITTLE MORE CARE ON THE HIGHWAY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Saturday, Jan. 2, 1999   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN R. WHITE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (If the material presented here today looks familiar, it is
because the author has offered winter driving advice in this space
before and continues to do so annually.)
</P>
<P>
   In New England along about now, snow is likely, covering
windshields and roads. We can expect, as a matter of course,
freezing rain, sleet, wet snow, powdery snow, wet roads, icy roads,
an overabundance of salt and sand on the roadway, slush, slop,
bitter winds, and other winter miseries _ sometimes all in the same
day.
</P>
<P>
   You can't do anything about the weather, but you can help
yourself cope with it. There are two common hazards in winter
driving: 1. Poor visibility; 2. Reduced traction. There are a
couple of universal rules that apply: 1. Start early and take your
time; 2. Don't make any sudden moves.
</P>
<P>
   Visibility is something you can improve. That ice or snow on the
windows is an obvious place to start. Start the engine, turn the
heater on to its highest temperature setting, and put it in the
defrost mode. Turn on the electric rear-window defroster, if you
have one. If it is just frost on the glass, start scraping the side
windows while the windshield is getting warmed by the defroster _
do the windshield last; it will have had time to warm and will be
the easiest.
</P>
<P>
   Don't forget to clean side view mirrors.
</P>
<P>
   With snow, start with the roof, then the windows, then the front
and rear deck, then the lights and bumper areas.
</P>
<P>
   Why not just the windows and let nature take care of the rest?
What you leave on the roof may slide off and block your rear view;
it may fly off and bother another driver. What you leave on a rear
deck may slide down to the bumper, depending upon the shape of the
car. Today's bumpers act like shelves on many cars, holding snow
and blocking tail or stop lights. If you don't pay attention to
keeping bumpers and lights clear, those following may never know
you're trying to stop until it's too late. And you might earn a
citation _ the court kind, not the award kind.
</P>
<P>
   If you are driving in rain, snow, fog, or overcast conditions,
make yourself more visible by turning on headlights (not your high
beams, please). The rule of thumb should be: If the wipers are on,
the lights are on. In some jusrisdictions, that's the law.
</P>
<P>
   On the road in winter, reduced speeds are often advisable, even
when it isn't raining or snowing. In below- or near-freezing
temperatures, water on bridges will freeze before the rest of the
roadway, presenting a hazard. Any sort of precipitation increases
hazard.
</P>
<P>
   Rain reduces visibility and road friction. (Road friction is
friction between your car's tires and the road and is what allows
you to move and to exercise control of the car.) Icy rain or slush
is worse than summer wetness. Avoid jackrabbit acceleration, hard
braking, or any sudden moves that can result in a skid. If you do
skid, it is most likely that it is the rear wheels that have lost
grip. Attempt to steer in the direction the car is sliding. With a
manual transmission, disengage the clutch and coast; with an
automatic, just take your foot off the gas _ don't try to fiddle
with the shifter. As you regain control, be gentle with steering
wheel and accelerator. As the tires regain grip, adjust the
steering to the direction you want to travel.
</P>
<P>
   If the front wheels are sliding, a less common occurrence
compared with rear-wheel skids, declutch a manual gearbox, remove
your foot from the gas pedal. Don't try to steer, straighten the
front wheels, and wait for them to regain traction as the car
slows. Of course, this all assumes you have a little room for
maneuver; skid on the Mass. Pike in rush hour and you are almost
certain of sliding into something solid.
</P>
<P>
   In rain or slop, you may encounter hydroplaning, especially if
you're speeding. If the tire can't shed water fast enough, a wedge
of water builds up ahead of it, and a film of water is established
between the tire and the road _ your tire is no longer in contact
with the road, and there is no friction. Don't move the steering
wheel. Do get off the gas, declutch a manual, and let the car coast
until it regains traction. Hydroplaning is less likely with
front-wheel drive, but it does occur.
</P>
<P>
   In snow, keep plenty of distance between you and the driver in
front. Signal early and don't rush. You are better off following
the beaten track, even though it is often more slippery in the
polished ruts. The ridges of packed snow tend to guide the car in
the established track. If you must pass, you will need more room
than usual and may have trouble crossing those ruts. Approach the
ruts at a shallow angle at a speed only slightly higher than the
rest of traffic so as to avoid a skid.
</P>
<P>
   Most drivers know about snow, slush and ice, but there is one
slippery situation that seems to escape the notice of many:
saline-soaked pavement. In temperatures near the freezing mark,
roads that have been heavily salted to eliminate the inconvenience
of snow can be especially hazardous. That salty solution remaining
after the snow melts is somewhat viscous _ oily _ and can be as
dangerous as ice.
</P>
<P>
   Salt also complicates visibility. Before you start out, be
certain your windshield-washer reservoir is full and the wiper
blades clean. A paper towel run along the edge of the blade will
pick up an often surprising amount of crud that otherwise would be
spread all over the windshield.
</P>
<P>
   Braking in snow or slush can be hazardous, so allow enough room
to avoid the need for panic stops. Anticipate stop signs,
intersections, traffic lights (assume they're about to turn red;
they probably are). Apply the brakes gently. In an emergency,
resist the urge to slam the pedal and hold it there. Your brakes
will lock the wheels, and the car will skid. Hit the brake fairly
hard, then ease off to the point where you have braking action but
not wheel lock. Slow pumping _ squeezing of the pedal _ is
effective.
</P>
<P>
   If you have antilock brakes, the opposite applies. Slam the
brake pedal and hold it down _ hard. Do not pump antilock brakes.
The result could be a loss of control. Antilock brakes prevent
wheel lock, but they don't add traction. How quickly you can stop
determines how fast you should be driving.
</P>
<P>
   If you are not going to stop in time, and can't steer around all
hazards, look for something soft to hit (not a pedestrian) _
sliding along a snow bank may slow you enough to prevent major
damage in a collision. It is better, too, to risk sideswiping a
parked vehicle than to hit a vehicle moving toward you.
</P>
<P>
   If you get stuck in the snow, don't sit there spinning your
wheels _ it will make things worse. It can also overheat the tire
to the point of explosive blowout. Do shovel snow away from the
wheels or use sand, ashes, or traction mats to help regain footing.
In most cars, only one wheel at a time will spin, but you can trick
a rear-drive car into using both wheels _ pull on the emergency
brake a couple of notches.
</P>
<P>
   Rocking back and forth is the usual prescription for working out
of this kind of difficulty, but you can really ruin a transmission
doing it. The tendency is to reverse direction before the wheels
have stopped spinning. With an automatic, the wear and tear can put
you in a transmission shop; with a manual, you can take years off
the clutch. The wheels should be completely stopped before
shifting.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
