</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YEAREND-SADDAM-AMERICA-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVEN THE IMPERIAL UNITED STATES MUST ACCEPT A GLOBAL COMMUNITY 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (This has already moved to clients of Flora Lewis' weekly
column. To publish this ``separate buy'' article, it must be
purchased _ the rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New
York Times Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S., Canada and the Pacific: NIRDI RELIS in New York at
1-800-972-3550 or 212-499-3333; fax, 212-499-3382. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-798-0970;
fax, 310-798-7338.) 
 &HT;    
 By FLORA LEWIS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;     EDITORS: Flora Lewis, the former foreign-affairs columnist for
The New York Times, will be honored Jan. 22 in New York by the
OVERSEAS PRESS CLUB, with its ``Lifetime Achievement Award.'' For
more information and a bio, contact John Stickney, New York Times
Syndicate, 212-499-3341.) 
 &HT;    .....................
 &HT;    PARIS _ The confrontation with Iraq is an example of the dilemma
the United States faces when it is determined to act on its own and
fails to persuade key powers to participate, or at least to
withhold a negative judgment.
 &HT;    Far from forcing Saddam Hussein to concede that his power has
been ``degraded'' by bombing, as Washington has proclaimed, the
recent U.S.-British attack brought the reaction of deliberately
provoking further conflict. Far from shrinking, Iraq attacked U.S.
and British planes imposing the no-fly zone.
 &HT;    Evidently, Hussein feels that if he pushes hard and cleverly
enough, he can wedge away all but Great Britain from supporting the
United States. He is aware, as Washington avoids making clear, that
the United States can bomb alone but it can't enforce effective
sanctions alone.
 &HT;    It is likely that, overplaying his hand as usual, Hussein will
wind up without the added indulgence and sympathy he seeks from
both the Arab world and the rest of the U.N. Security Council. The
impasse will continue. But it will have shown that he can still
demonstrate defiance.
 &HT;    And the United States will have been obliged to admit, as it did
implicitly with its limited attack to ``degrade'' but not to oust
Hussein, that unilateral action doesn't achieve what it wants.
 &HT;    But unlike previous empires that wanted control and tribute, the
United States doesn't have a very clear idea of what it wants. That
is not just a lack of strategic vision or lucid articulation of
policy; it is in the very nature of this new way of trying to
organize the world.
 &HT;    Washington doesn't have a plan to impose. That will have to
emerge bit by bit from coalition debate.
 &HT;    But what matter _ on the eve of the 21st century, America calls
itself ``the indispensable nation'' and, indeed, while it can't do
whatever it wants anywhere in the world, nothing constructive can
be done without it.
 &HT;    Back in the mid-1900s, soon after World War II, Henry Luce, who
had founded the Time-Life empire, proclaimed the next 100 years as
``the American century.'' A generation later, it didn't look like
that at all. The Cold War, Vietnam and a challenging Third World
sapped American confidence and made its people ponder the risks of
involvement. The bountiful era seemed ended.
 &HT;    Now, once again, the American role is indisputably preeminent.
There has never been such a pile-up of power. Political, military,
economic, cultural, technological _ America is dominant in every
field. Even some American analysts call it an empire because it
parallels the power of classical Rome in its ability to prevent any
other nation or group of nations from imposing their contradictory
will.
 &HT;    But if the United States is imperial in reach and weight, it is
a unique kind of dominance unknown to history _ one consciously
based on a coalition of resources and wills that must constantly
seek convergence. This coalition is open to all who wish to join,
and there are endless appeals to the ill-defined ``international
community'' for support and legitimation.
 &HT;    When the United States does not take adequate account of the
perceived interests of its various partners, it feels limits on its
power one way or another. Those limits are both internal and
external, but the constantly felt need to rally others shows that
Washington does acknowledge such a thing as an international
community, and one which is taking on substance.
 &HT;    Consider the ``new strategic concept'' being devised for NATO to
announce on its 50th anniversary in April. NATO was formed for the
straightforward purpose of deterring, and if necessary defending
against, a Soviet attack on Europe.
 &HT;    Its success has made that goal obsolete. But its members do not
consider NATO obsolete and must therefore find a new definition and
role. Over the years, the alliance has already evolved, and with
the admission in April of new members formerly in the enemy Warsaw
Pact, it will take another important step in being transformed from
a defense pact to a collective security pact.
 &HT;    But the United States is proposing much broader language for the
new strategy, calling for the defense of members' interests in the
world at large. This is an approach that the French, for example,
consider nothing short of the United States proclaiming itself a
global policeman.
 &HT;    Despite its power, the United States will undoubtedly need to
settle for a more modest commitment.
 &HT;    American responsibilities in parts of the world outside Europe
are not often well-defined and institutionalized. They are
nonetheless recognized. What is also apparent is that this American
role, more than ever before, is being played with _ and through _
the international community, and cannot succeed otherwise.
 &HT;     c.1998 Flora Lewis  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ------------------- &QC;
</P>
