<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ULTRASOUND-BONES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ULTRASOUND HEALS BONES ULTRAFAST; JUST ASK TROY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CAROLYN POIROT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sound medicine should get some credit for the fact the Cowboys
are hosting Saturday's NFC playoff game against the Cardinals at
Texas Stadium _ ultrasound, that is.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys' perfect sweep of the NFC East had only just begun
when Troy Aikman fractured his left clavicle in a run-in with the
Denver Broncos on Sept. 13.
</P>
<P>
   With low-intensity ultrasound to speed rehabilitation _ and a
great offensive line to help protect against further injury _ the
Cowboys' superstar quarterback is back in the game with his
precision passes back on target.
</P>
<P>
   Aikman's collarbone continues to heal, thanks, in part, to the
Sonic Accelerated Fracture Healing System, a battery-operated,
hand-held device that delivers ultrasound pulses directly to the
fracture site. Aikman has said he uses the gadget for 20 minutes
each day.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike electrical stimulation devices that use energy currents
in a similar way to heal older, ``nonunion'' fractures that refuse
to mend, the SAFHS is specifically designed to speed the healing of
new or fresh breaks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is absolutely different from other therapeutic ultrasound.
It uses the same intensity as a fetal sonogram, so it is obviously
very safe,'' says Pat McBrayer, president and chief executive
officer of Exogen, the New Jersey-based company that manufactures
the product. ``What's happening at the cellular level is that the
pulsating ultrasound is creating a mechanical force on the bone to
help stimulate new bone growth.''
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, low-intensity ultrasound produces minute
mechanical strains within the fracture and improves blood flow to
the fracture site to stimulate the healing process, according to
reports presented at last summer's annual meeting of the American
Academy of Orthopaedic Surgeons.
</P>
<P>
   The new device, which is available by prescription only and
costs a hefty $2,500, is, says McBrayer, popular among professional
and weekend-warrior athletes and is also recommended for the
elderly, whose bones sometimes have difficulty healing.
</P>
<P>
   If the patient is going to be in a cast, a hole is cut in the
cast above the fracture and capped (much like a gas cap on a car)
so that the cap can be removed to admit the pulsating sound waves.
When a cast is not indicated, as in Aikman's case, the small
ultrasound transducer is held against the skin, directly over the
injury.
</P>
<P>
   Studies published in the Journal of Bone and Joint Surgery
indicate that the device cuts healing time by an average of 38
percent and is 93 percent successful.
</P>
<P>
   Exogen also counts Antonio Freeman of the Green Bay Packers,
former Dallas Stars' star Greg Adams, Dallas Mavericks player Kurt
Thomas and Olympic luminaries Picabo Street and Dominique Moceanu
among its celebrity patients.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ultrasound speeds up fracture healing so it is prescribed a
lot for athletes to get them back to their sports more quickly,''
says Dr. Paul Freudigman, a Dallas orthopedic surgeon who turns to
the SAFHS mostly for complex fractures at risk for nonhealing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ultrasound provides mechanical stimulus to the bone cells,
which the cells translate into an electrical environment more
conducive to healing,'' Freudigman says. ``You use it on fractures
that are difficult to heal with traditional methods _ and
athletes.''
</P>
<P>
   (Carolyn Poirot writes on health issues for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
