<DOCNO> NYT19981231.0203 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-31 16:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3743 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AMERICANBEACH03-2TAKE     12-31 1031
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMERICANBEACH03-2TAKES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EMBARGOED UNTIL JANUARY 3
 &HT;    New book, old spirit drawing attention to historic resort
 &HT;    By Mike Williams
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AMERICAN BEACH, Fla. _The Ritz-Carlton hovers on the north
horizon, a symbol of elegance and excess, while to the south,
luxury condominiums crowd the oceanfront as far as the eye can see.
</P>
<P>
   In the middle, between the manicured golf course developments
and posh, gated neighborhoods, a half-mile stretch of gorgeous
beach is lined with boarded-up businesses and modest homes, many of
them fallen into disrepair. On a blustery December day, the village
is
</P>
<P>
   so deserted it seems almost haunted.
</P>
<P>
   If there are ghosts about, they are friendly ones for MaVynee
Betsch, the colorful, exuberant, unofficial mayor of what was once
one of America's few all-black beach resorts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right there is the little bar where Ray Charles and Duke
Ellington would play,'' she says, pointing toward a low brick
building with grass growing over the few parking spots in front.
``And that lot over there, that used to be the home of the first
black female mortician in the state of Florida. I tell you, baby,
it was unreal.''
</P>
<P>
   Founded in 1935 by Betsch's great-grandfather, black insurance
magnate and millionaire Abraham Lincoln Lewis, American Beach
thrived during the 1940s and 1950s. With segregation barring them
from beaches elsewhere, African-American vacationers came here by
the bus loads on summer weekends, filling the cottages, the small
motel and the juke joints.
</P>
<P>
   But just as segregation led to American Beach's birth,
integration nearly killed it.
</P>
<P>
   With other, previously all-white beaches suddenly open to blacks
in the 1960s, the crowds dwindled. Homes went untended as owners
grew old or moved away. Businesses shuttered their doors or opened
only on summer weekends.
</P>
<P>
   Now, though, American Beach is struggling back to life. A few
homes have been built, and other dilapidated structures have been
refurbished. A determined group of homeowners has applied for
grants and begun beautifying the streets by adding palm trees and
landscaping.
</P>
<P>
   The unincorporated village has become part of the Florida Black
Heritage Trail, drawing tourists and history buffs. There is a move
to list American Beach as a National Historic District and to
safeguard it from overdevelopment with a special zoning
designation.
</P>
<P>
   And MaVynee Betsch, a striking woman who once sang opera in
Europe but who now lives an eccentric's life roaming her
great-grandfather's town, has become something of a celebrity.
</P>
<P>
   A walking history book
</P>
<P>
   A new book by Atlanta native Russ Rymer, ``American Beach: A
Saga of Race, Wealth and Memory'' ($25, HarperCollins) celebrates
Betsch's family, their role in founding American Beach and the
unique part the town has played in African-American history and
culture.
</P>
<P>
   There is also a documentary film about the town scheduled to air
on public television in the next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The anthropology department at the University of Florida has
discovered us,'' said Betsch, her voice bursting with pride.
``We've got graduate students writing papers about us and bus loads
of students coming for tours. I love it.''
</P>
<P>
   And so must the students. It's not every day they meet a walking
history book, a woman raised into Jacksonville's upper class black
society in the 1940s who became a classically trained singer,
toured Europe and then mysteriously dropped out to lead a
back-to-nature life in the
</P>
<P>
   dilapidated lap of her family's past glory.
</P>
<P>
   Betsch is a presence: She fills the space around her with a
natural grace and energy. She also looks nothing like any other
person walking the oak-canopied roads of Amelia Island, where
Hilfiger-clad joggers jostle among the luxury cars and golf carts.
</P>
<P>
   Now 63, Betsch's skin is as smooth as a 20-year-old's. Her eyes
are clear and piercing. She dresses in felt wraps or wool Mexican
serapes over sweat pants, one arm dangling stacked bracelets,
fingers festooned with seashell rings. The other hand sports
18-inch fingernails, which she usually keeps clutched to her middle
for protection.
</P>
<P>
   And then there is her hair _ gloriously gray-black, nearly 8
feet of it, teased into what Rymer called a ``cock's comb'' over
her head, then tucked under the collar of her serape and bundled at
her side.
</P>
<P>
   She usually wears a black lace headband, and a tiny dot of a
silver earring pierces one nostril, with four or five more lining
her ear lobes.
</P>
<P>
   Matching her appearance are her voice, rich and radiant, and her
words, erudite but earthy and radical to the core. Her feminism and
eco-warrior outlook must leave her piney woods neighbors in Nassau
County _ the ones driving the beat-up pickups and building the
condos for the rich folks _ scratching their heads in puzzlement.
</P>
<P>
   RV with an attitude
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, she feels a kinship with the good old boys,
whom she sees as allies in the fight against the polo-clad,
BMW-driving types who frequent the Ritz and Amelia Island
Plantation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baby, these rednecks from Fernandina drive by and give me the
thumbs up,'' she says. ``They come to American Beach to fish. They
know what it's all about. They know we're trying to keep what we've
got here. The developers are over there with their eyes sparkling.
They want this beach. But it's the only public access left around
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Most days Betsch can be found in the Titan RV given to her by
her sister, former Spelman College president Johnnetta Cole. The
vehicle is parked at the foot of Lewis Street, rusting, grass
growing up around the tires, the sides plastered with bumper
stickers bearing such zingers as, ``Politicians and diapers need to
be changed often for the same reason,'' and ``Flush Rush.''
</P>
<P>
   Betsch has turned the RV into an ad hoc shrine, even going so
far as to scrawl in magic marker on the side, ``Black Heritage
Museum.'' Inside are stacks of documents, articles, books, T-shirts
and other ammunition for her wars to preserve her town from the
looming forces of homogenization.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   AMERICAN BEACH, Fla.: of homogenization.
</P>
<P>
   Genuine love of life
</P>
<P>
   Asked about Rymer's book and the attention it has brought,
Betsch laughs, a high cackle brimming with delight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm loving it,'' she says. ``The book signings, the guest
appearances. I used to have it in Europe, but over there I was even
more exotic _ I was the only black in town. I'm getting a kick out
of it coming around again.''
</P>
<P>
   Betsch clearly loves her gypsy's life. No car, no possessions to
speak of, not even a permanent roof to sleep under. She regularly
bivouacs in the dunes, lulled by the crashing surf that dazzled her
as a girl. She is like a biblical prophet, wandering in the
wilderness, striking dumb her opponents with insights from another
plane of consciousness.
</P>
<P>
   Once wealthy, accustomed to a diva's life in Europe, she gave
away all of her money to environmental causes _ whales, rain
forests, Earth First, you name it. She doesn't seem to miss the
money at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``The right whales are back, and look, they named one for me,''
she says, holding up a T-shirt touting the cause of the giant
endangered mammals, which winter off North Florida.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't find Betsch in her RV-turned-shrine, you'll most
likely find her walking the streets of American Beach, her
orange-splashed toenails protected only by flip-flops, her serape
wrapped tight against the winter chill, her face a positive light
of energy. Puppies and kittens come out on the sidewalks to greet
her, sometimes trailing as if she were Mother Nature.
</P>
<P>
   If Betsch has to go to a County Commission meeting in Yulee, 15
miles distant, she bums a ride with a friend. She does that a lot,
taking to the microphone to rail against the latest depredations of
the developers, to argue against cutting down trees to widen roads
or dismantling old bridges where poor people like to fish.
</P>
<P>
   At such meetings, the unfamiliar openly gape, but the old hands
greet her warmly. She is treated with something of bemused
affection _ at least by some _ and respect by most, who know she
will be there, doggedly fighting for every tree, bird, bush and
grain of sand on American Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Rymer, who spent a few years living in nearby Fernandina Beach
to research his book, ``adores'' Betsch.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, ``she loves the book,'' he said, noting that they
talk frequently by phone since Rymer now lives in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``She really has an occult sense. She doesn't believe in cosmic
accidents. I think she probably believes I was part of her
great-grandfather's plan, that A.L. Lewis thought it was time for
this chapter to be written.''
</P>
<P>
   Betsch's latest dream is to obtain an unoccupied building near
the entrance to American Beach as a permanent home for her ad hoc
museum.
</P>
<P>
   She shrugs off reports of recent troubles at the beach. Last
summer, crowds of black youths got so rowdy that sheriff's deputies
cracked down, even blocking the road into town for several Sundays,
outraging some residents but pleasing others upset by the noise.
</P>
<P>
   There has also been some nasty infighting between various
factions in American Beach, with one prominent leader of a group
generally opposed to Betsch cozying up with developers _ at least
to hear Betsch tell it.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're using the old divide-and-conquer strategy,'' she says.
``They're trying to split us.''
</P>
<P>
   However, all of the factions seem to agree on Betsch's bedrock
principles: preserving American Beach's history and stopping the
march of mega-development. Even Betsch's opponents have printed
brochures extolling the town's history and want only single-family
residences in American Beach _ no condos or high-rises.
</P>
<P>
   Rymer hopes the growing historical consciousness and the
advocacy germinated by Betsch will save American Beach. His book
portrays how that worked for Eatonville, another all-black town
near Orlando, where homage to writer Zora Neale Hurston has helped
revive the town, bringing scholarly conferences, an annual heritage
celebration and a sense of identity.
</P>
<P>
   He also says the town's struggle to hold onto its unique history
has lessons for mainstream America as well, where he sees the
forces of greed and commercialism threatening to overwhelm more
traditional cultural values.
</P>
<P>
   ``American Beach really is a last vestige of really important
history,'' Rymer said. ``America will be much smaller if it
disappears, and it won't be much larger if it's replaced by another
nine holes of golf course.''
</P>
<P>
   Betsch vows that will never happen, not as long as she draws a
breath _ and not after that, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're going to scatter my ashes over NaNa'' _ her name for
the giant sand dune that towers over the village _ ``and I'll come
back to haunt them if they don't leave us alone,'' she says,
laughing.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Williams writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
