<HEADER>
A3748 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MARTIN-STYLE03-COX     12-31 0535
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARTIN-STYLE03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EMBARGOED UNTIL JANUARY 3
 &HT;    Martin leads Falcons on fashion front
 &HT;    By A. Scott Walton
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ On Sundays he's a Dirty Bird.
</P>
<P>
   During the remainder of the week, however, Atlanta Falcons wide
receiver Tony Martin acts more like a peacock.
</P>
<P>
   Ask Martin, the 14-2 Falcons' second-leading receiver this
season, who the best-dressed player on the team is and he'll
respond, nonchalantly, ``Myself.''
</P>
<P>
   The depth of his passion for clothes _ and the extent of his
wardrobe _ came to light recently when Martin and his Los
Angeles-based personal clothier, Troy McSwain II, spent an
afternoon selecting fabrics for a new batch of suits. Though he
buys his shoes and sportswear from upscale retailers around the
country, Martin has most of his suits made-to-measure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Troy's made at least 20 suits for me already,'' Martin said.
</P>
<P>
   The closets in Martin's Atlanta penthouse are sizable enough to
run pass patterns in. McSwain estimated that, between the
receiver's homes in Atlanta and Florida, there's probably more than
$1 million worth of clothing.
</P>
<P>
   Before choosing which fabrics his newest suits would be made of,
Martin had to first weed through his existing wardrobe to see what
needed augmenting. The task proved as daunting as beating Deion
Sanders in single coverage.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mom was supposed to do this,'' Martin muttered as he
attempted to arrange his clothes by color.
</P>
<P>
   And what colors there were: Martin doesn't shy away from wearing
bright yellows, red or purples or bold stripes or plaid patterns
any more than he would avoid running pass routes over the middle.
</P>
<P>
   ``My style is different,'' he said. ``I get away with wearing
things other guys couldn't.''
</P>
<P>
   McSwain interjected: ``I'd call Tony's style funky but
distinctive. He doesn't want anything ordinary. I've got to go to
the crayon box to keep him satisfied.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin said his mother _ a voracious shoe collector _ instilled
in him the clotheshorse gene. He added that his dress-to-impress
inclinations don't stem from a desire to impress women (he's
recently became engaged to actress Lisa Raye) so much as he feels
in competition with other men . . . especially his teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``You ask anybody on the Falcons, and they'll tell you I can put
on anything and be sharp in it. I always want to look better than
the next guy; I am going to stand out.''
</P>
<P>
   Ask any of McSwain's clients, and they'll say his work is of
standout quality.
</P>
<P>
   When performers Boyz II Men stepped on the Grammy Awards stage
in white sequined suits and handmade white alligator shoes not long
ago, McSwain was the man behind their sartorial splendor. ``I
called my shoe vendor. He just happened to have some white
alligator,'' he recalls.
</P>
<P>
   For fighter Mike Tyson's upcoming return to the boxing ring in
Las Vegas, McSwain is making white suits for at least 25 members of
Tyson's entourage. ``It's kind of a new coming,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   A. Scott Walton writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Jackie White of Knight -Ridder Newspapers contributed to this
article.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
