<HEADER>
A3750 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MILLENNIUM-SOUTH03-CO     12-31 0717
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILLENNIUM-SOUTH03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EMBARGOED UNTIL JANUARY 3
 &HT;    The South bids a warm welcome to new century
 &HT;    By Doug Hamilton
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ While New York, London and Paris cemented their
millennium-celebration itineraries months ago, many cities around
the South have taken a pokey approach to the occasion.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta's ambitious ``Carnivale of Lights'' festival is still
seeking investors, leaving First Night, the annual alcohol-free
gathering, as the only confirmed large-scale event for the City Too
Busy to Plan. Likewise, in Alabama, the one definite big bash is
Mobile's First Night party. (For information on First Night events
around the country, call 617-357-0065 or visit
http://www.firstnightintl.org.)
</P>
<P>
   Southerners who want to attend a memorable millennium party
that's close to home do have a few options, ranging from a swank
Memphis ball to a down-home blowout at Opryland. Here are a few hot
Dixie destinations for New Year's Eve 1999:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Asheville, N.C.: Like its walk-in fireplaces, the Grove Park
Inn's Grand Millennium Celebration promises to be colossal.
Beginning Dec. 29, the elegant hotel will host three days of nearly
continuous entertainment by musical acts such as Percy Sledge, the
Drifters and Cleo Laine, plus comedians Robert Klein and David
Brenner. During the last minutes of 1999, visitors will hear the
taped premiere of ``The Grove Park Inn Grand Millennium Suite,'' a
newly commissioned work by North Carolina composer David McHugh
that traces the history of Western music. Cost: $4,000 per couple,
$599 per child. 1-800-438-5800.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Nashville: Countrified resort Opryland pops the cork on its
Grand Celebration 2000 on Dec. 30. Three days of festivities
include a champagne brunch Dec. 31; a ``New Year's Day Sports
Spectacular'' featuring multiple big-screen TVs for football
viewing; and ``Country Salute 2000,'' a New Year's Day dinner and
country music concert. The $1,999-per-person price tag includes
accommodations at Opryland Hotel. 1-888-976-2000.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Orlando: Though Walt Disney World has yet to firm up details
for its millennium party, rest assured it'll be anything but
low-key. Park officials have announced plans for a 15-month
celebration beginning Oct. 1. They promise it will rival the
similarly lengthy 25th-anniversary blowout of 1996-97. There are
also New Year's Eve parties scheduled for Disney's satellite parks,
MGM Studios and Epcot. In deference to sleeping fauna, the
festivities at Disney's recently opened Animal Kingdom park will be
relatively sedate. 407-824-4321.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Memphis: The Junior League of Memphis has selected the
handsome Peabody Hotel as the site of its 1999 Crystal Ball, a
benefit to raise money for community projects. Ball
``sponsorships'' range from $500 per couple for admission to a
lobby gala to $30,000 (minimum contribution) for a suite at the
hotel, valet parking for 10 cars and invitations for 20 guests to
the Crystal Ball Sponsor Party. 901-452-2151.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  New Orleans: If you're not up to the boozy excesses of Bourbon
Street, you may want to book passage on the Delta Queen's
Millennium Cruise. The venerable steamboat, which has been
chartered by the AAA Rochester Travel Agency for the occasion,
leaves New Orleans on Dec. 29 and travels up the Mississippi before
returning Jan. 3. A New Year's Eve party is planned, though
entertainment has yet to be finalized. $1,350 per person includes
onboard accommodations.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Charleston, S.C.: Guests of the opulent Charleston Place hotel
can celebrate in style at the Millennium Gala, which includes a
five-course dinner, free-flowing champagne and music by the
Charleston Symphony Orchestra. $2,000 buys you admission to the
party and accommodations for up to 12 nights from Dec. 25 through
Jan. 5. 1-843-722-4900.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Jekyll Island (Ga.): The Victorian-style Jekyll Island Club
Hotel plans to lure revelers to the coastal Georgia hot spot with a
lavish millennium package including accommodations for three
nights, a six-course New Year's Eve dinner for two and the first
breakfast of 2000. Price: $1,100 per room, double occupancy.
912-635-2600.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Hamilton writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
