<HEADER>
A3751 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SIBLEY-COLUMN03-COX     12-31 0600
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIBLEY-COLUMN03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EMBARGOED UNTIL JANUARY 3
 &HT;    Medical tests no match for loving family
 &HT;    By Celestine Sibley
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Years ago I used to think only country and small-town
people gathered when one of their number was in a hospital.
</P>
<P>
   I understood, because we in Creola, Ala., regarded a trip to the
hospital as major, on a par with a trip to Roche Mortuary, the
final stop in many lives.
</P>
<P>
   City people are usually different, I think. There are so many
hospitals and so many doctors, and it's not always a grave,
death-dealing malady that sends you to either. But I tell you the
country custom of relatives gathering can't be beat.
</P>
<P>
   The other day I had an appointment at Piedmont Hospital for some
tests, nothing fearsome, no drastic surgery, nothing threatening.
But my family decided I needed backup.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will come,'' said one of my grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   ``No need to,'' I said. ``They'll put me in some lab place and
you in a waiting room, and it will be very boring.''
</P>
<P>
   John, my eldest grandson, said, ``Bird (his cousin) will be
there. Talking to Bird doesn't bore me . . . much.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Aw, don't bother,'' I urged. ``No drama, no excitement. Their
television set probably doesn't work. Their magazines are last
year's, and they don't tell you the result of their test for three
days.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We will come,'' one of them maintained.
</P>
<P>
   And they did. I looked down one of those long, carpeted
corridors, and there was the most beautiful throng I ever saw _
what we call ``the Original Four,'' my first grandchildren. Two are
brothers, the others a brother and sister. They are very close to
the same age.
</P>
<P>
   I took them to swim. I rode them around in a pickup truck. I
stood by bellowing warnings when they learned to drive the riding
mower.
</P>
<P>
   I took them on picnics and down the road to visit a neighbor's
goat _ known to the four as ``the biddy-go.'' We made kites
together and flew them in Capt. Erle Miles' pasture.
</P>
<P>
   I got some of them their first haircuts, a tremulous business,
which worried them all. ``I might cry,'' said the haircut victim.
``He might cry,'' reiterated his cousin.
</P>
<P>
   But he didn't cry, and he's been getting haircuts, now and then,
ever since. Not regularly enough by grandmother standards, but not
tear-inducing for him.
</P>
<P>
   Memories swamped me as I caught up with them _ all so big and so
beautiful. The boys are all 6 feet 3 inches tall and more. The girl
a shade under 6 feet. They stood tall, and they peered into my face
anxiously.
</P>
<P>
   I kept hugging them, more than they cared for, I know, but they
put up with it and made jokes to divert me. And then we walked down
toward the place of tests together.
</P>
<P>
   I suddenly felt invincible. With this crew at my side, lab
technicians with needles couldn't hurt me. Doctors' reports held no
disquietude.
</P>
<P>
   It's what country people have always known. You need your
kinfolks with you when you are poorly.
</P>
<P>
   A doctor told me in some Asian countries families come with
their ill to a hospital and camp out on the grounds, setting up
cook fires and bedrolls. The ill recover faster if they have loving
relatives standing by, the doctor said. I believe it.
</P>
<P>
   Later, I reported to my daughter in Omaha, Neb., how ``the
mob,'' as we used to call them when they were 4 and 5 years old,
came through. ``I'm glad we raised them,'' I said. ``Me, too,'' she
said. ``I think of that every day.''
</P>
<P>
   Celestine Sibley writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
