<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-31 16:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3752 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-MILLENNIUM03-C     12-31 0897
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-MILLENNIUM03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EMBARGOED UNTIL JANUARY03
 &HT;    Celebrating 2000
 &HT;    By Doug Hamilton, Illustrations by Vernon Carne
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ How did you usher in 1999? Was Thursday night another
New Year's Eve of lukewarm pink Champale, slightly scorched Jiffy
Pop and Dick Clark on the tube? Hey, that's OK. We're not passing
judgment here. But no way is that going to cut it come next New
Year's Eve, when people worldwide will be partying like it's, well,
2000.
</P>
<P>
   And don't be put off by those naysayers who point out that the
millennium doesn't start until Jan. 1, 2001. Nobody except maybe
Stanley Kubrick is waiting until then to celebrate. There's just
something about a curvy two followed by three fat zeroes that
screams ``turning point!''
</P>
<P>
   You need to start making your millennium travel plans now.
Already, the resorts at Walt Disney World in Orlando are booked.
Many cruises and hotels have been full for ages _ London's Savoy
Hotel started getting reservation requests 10 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bigger is better'' is the unofficial motto of the festivities.
Liberally applying phrases such as ``once-in-a-lifetime
opportunity'' and ``symbolic milestone,'' travel agencies and event
organizers are vying to rties, such as those in New York, Sydney
and Rio, everybody is going for bigger and better,'' says Nick
Hanna, author of ``The Millennium: A Rough Guide to the Year 2000''
(Rough Guides, $8.95). ``There also seems to be a significant
convergence of grand themes that are central to some of these
projects. The environment features prominently, as do questions
regarding how we relate to each other and the world, the future of
work and play, the meaning of change and so on.''
</P>
<P>
   High-flown notions, those. Speaking of elevated ideas,adventure
tour organizers Blyth &AMP; Co. will offer, among other excursions, a
trek up Africa's Mount Kilimanjaro, timed to reach the summit Jan.
1, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe subconsciously, people are connecting a personal journey
with the millennium,'' ventures Blyth managing director Peggy
Foster. ``People are saying they've always wanted to do something
like (climb Kilimanjaro) and they feel that this is a significant
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, once-in-a-lifetime opportunities timed around
symbolic milestones don't come cheap. The Kilimanjaro hike will set
you back $7,595 a bargain compared with some options.
</P>
<P>
   Want to rent a Times Square hotel for New Year's Eve? All you
need is $3 million, and the Millennium Broadway, a 580-room luxury
hotel in the heart of New York's party zone, can be reserved for
you and yours. Don't want to be in the same time zone, much less
neighborhood, as Dick Clark and his follow-the-dropping-ball
routine? Scots Castle Holidays will let you play ``Braveheart'' at
one of several castles in Scotland within hurling distance of
Edinburgh's boisterous hogmanay celebration. Rental fees for the
week (Dec. 29-Jan. 5)start at $10,000.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe you prefer a more mobile soiree. Intrav offers an
around-the-world trip on a chartered Concorde. Beginning Dec. 24,
the 18-day journey whisks you to Hawaii, Australia, Egypt, India,
Kenya and, on New Year's Eve, Hong Kong. Cost: $75,000.
</P>
<P>
   You'll only have to pony up $30,000-plus for accommodations on
Silversea's Millennium 2000 cruise to the South Pacific, which
promises two New Year's Eve parties, one on each side of the
international date line. Along that longitudinal marker, you'll
find two sites _ New Zealand's Chatham Islands and the island
nation of Kiribati _ claiming to be the first place on Earth to
greet the millennial dawn. But since neither is well-equipped to
handle visitors, a better bet may be Samoa, which is unchallenged
in its boast of being the last place in the world to celebrate the
occasion.
</P>
<P>
   If your body is as in shape as your bank account, you might make
your mark by riding a bicycle around the world. The Odyssey 2000
tour leaves Los Angeles on Jan. 1, 2000, and travels to more than
50 countries in 366 days. And no, you don't pedal to all of them _
27 plane flights will get you to your cycling destinations. It'll
set you back $36,000, but, hey, you get a free bicycle.
</P>
<P>
   But you don't need big bucks or toned legs to join the global
party. For Drumming in the Year 2000, all you need is something to
beat. Organized by the All One Tribe Foundation of New Mexico, the
event begins at midnight in the last time zone. Participants around
the planet will then commence banging drums for one disquieting
hour.
</P>
<P>
   And what would a celebration of the 2,000th anniversary of the
birth of Christ be without a giant pagan party? Organizers of One
Million Pagans aim to lure legions of ``earth spiritualists'' _
Wiccans, shamans and other ``free thinkers'' _ to the California
desert Dec. 30, 1999, for a few days of concerts, workshops and
rituals. At midnight on New Year's Eve, they will form a circle to
``heal the earth and project a positive future,'' according to the
Web site. Event director Thor, a.k.a. Dave Francis, won't give the
exact location for fear of recriminations. But, he says, ``there
will be a lot of pagans descending on the Palm Springs area.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that pink Champale doesn't sound so bad after all.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Hamilton writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
