<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-31 16:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3753 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DULL-TASTE03-COX     12-31 1432
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DULL-TASTE03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EMBARGOED UNTIL JANUARY 3
 &HT;    Mrs. Dull: The Atlantan who wrote the book on Southern food
 &HT;    By Jim Auchmutey Illustrations by Walter Cumming
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ With a name like Dull, she had to be good. And she
was.
</P>
<P>
   Henrietta Stanley Dull _ plain old Mrs. Dull to the generations
of Southerners who took her classes and clipped her newspaper
recipes _ wrote just one cookbook during a long life that began
before Sherman marched through Georgia and ended after King marched
on Washington. It was a homely-looking volume, with a matronly
silhouette of the author, drawn by her daughter, on the cover. Yet
``Southern Cooking'' was for much of this century the definitive
treatise on the subject. Seventy years after its 1928 publication,
you can still find it at bookstores in a new printing by Cherokee
Publishing Co., the South's own Fannie Farmer continuing to
admonish cooks not to pour gravy over their fried chicken.
</P>
<P>
   ``She boiled Southern food down to its essence and put it
between the covers of a book that she wanted to last a long, long
time. And it has,'' says food historian John Egerton.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Dull died 35 years ago this month in Atlanta. She was part
of a progression of cookbook authors _ all women _ who set the
canon of Southern food: Mary Randolph in the 1820s (``The Virginia
Housewife''), Sarah Rutledge in the 1840s (``The Carolina
Housewife''), Annabella Hill in the 1860s (``Mrs. Hill's New Cook
Book''), Abby Fisher in the 1880s (``What Mrs. Fisher Knows About
Old Southern Cooking''). Mrs. Dull added to their collective wisdom
and updated it for a new century of gas ranges and electric
appliances. As the last year of that century begins, it seems
fitting to remember the woman who was for so long the reigning
authority on Southern cookery.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been making a scrapbook,'' her 77-year-old granddaughter
said when I phoned. ``Would you like to see?''
</P>
<P>
   Mary Frances Woodside, one of Mrs. Dull's seven grandchildren,
dragged out a musty box of keepsakes when I visited her Buckhead
town house, and we quickly covered the floor with them. Yellowed
tear sheets of her Atlanta Journal food column. Neatly scripted
notes for her talks, the pages bound by rusty safety pins. Her
working copy of ``Southern Cooking,'' stuffed like a goose with
recipes and memos fastened to the pages with straight pins and
bobby pins.
</P>
<P>
   ``She made the prettiest food,'' Woodside said wistfully, as she
leafed through the volume. ``She made a cake for my birthday when I
was in college. Three tiers with peach blossoms on it. I can still
see her forming the petals by hand and laying them out on wax
paper.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sis Hennie,'' as Woodside called her, made everything from
scratch, but she didn't think badly of those who couldn't spare the
time to do likewise. Once, when she saw her granddaughter fixing
biscuits from a tube, she assured her that it was all right. ``You
do what you have to do in this world.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Dull was proof of that.
</P>
<P>
   She was born during the Civil War on a plantation near
Dublin(Ga.), in the Middle Georgia countryside the Union Army would
soon ravage. At 6, she learned to cook corn pone on an open hearth.
As a young woman, she married a Virginian named Sam Dull and
settled in Atlanta. He took ill and became an invalid, leaving his
wife to support their six children.
</P>
<P>
   ``Suddenly I found I had to be the bread winner,'' she told a
women's group years later, according to the brittle notes her
granddaughter still has. ``I knew how to make good things to eat
and have them made. I mastered a gas range. I made it work for me
and talk for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Dull's oven started talking in the late 1890s when she sold
cakes and pies to fellow members at First Baptist Church of
Atlanta. She was soon one of the city's most sought-after caterers.
In 1910, the Atlanta Gas Light Co. hired her to travel around the
state conducting cooking schools for housewives who needed
assurance that the new gas ranges were safe and easier to use than
wood stoves. She spoke in auditoriums to assemblies that numbered
in the hundreds.
</P>
<P>
   ``You had to have a ticket if you wanted to see Mrs. Dull, and
they weren't that easy to come by,'' says Anne Kilpatrick, a
retired Atlanta dietitian, who attended several of her sessions as
a girl in Athens(Ga.). ``To me, she represented authority. You'd
hear housewives say, 'Well, Mrs. Dull says ...' and that would
settle it.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1920, Mrs. Dull approached the new Sunday magazine of The
Atlanta Journal with a proposal to do a cooking column. The editor
assigned a young staffer, Margaret Mitchell, to coach her on
writing. Every week the page would appear under the same headline _
``Mrs. Dull's Cooking Lessons'' _ with a different photo of the
author, looking as serious as a heart surgeon, as she cracked eggs
or mixed batter. On the bottom of the page, she conducted a
``chat'' with her readers, exchanging recipes and housekeeping
tips.
</P>
<P>
   The column led naturally to the cookbook _ 350 pages and 1,300
recipes that form a snapshot of a transitional era when Southerners
were moving from farm to city, but still knew how to wring a
chicken's neck.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at the recipes, she's really a link between the
19th and 20th centuries,'' says Damon Fowler, the Savannah(Ga.)
culinary historian. ``On one hand, she's forward-looking; she has
this tomato sherbet that would be very chi-chi at a nouvelle
Southern restaurant today. On the other hand, she still has this
connection to the land; she tells you how to deal with a real
possum.''
</P>
<P>
   He isn't kidding. On Page 55, Mrs. Dull gives instructions for
cleaning and cooking the oily little marsupial: ``Scrape well _
remove feet, tail and entrails _ like you would a pig. Cut off
ears, remove eyes and head if desired.''
</P>
<P>
   When I read the recipe to Woodside, she made a gagging noise and
changed the subject to her grandmother's squash casserole.
</P>
<P>
   In print, Mrs. Dull can come across as a stern schoolmarm who
doesn't brook any small talk. ``She didn't want to be chatty or
trendy,'' Egerton says. ``She wanted you to pay attention because
she was only going to tell you once.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Dull was apparently much warmer in life. Friends and family
remember her as a vivacious, short little thing who ate lightly and
liked big hats and read her Bible everyday. She never learned to
drive, preferring to call Yellow cab. She was unfailingly polite,
so much so that when the newspaper asked her to step down in 1945,
because of her age, she was terribly upset but never said a harsh
word to the college-trained home economist who replaced her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure she thought I was a straggly little ole gal,'' says
Grace Hartley, the food writer who took her place. ``But she
wouldn't dream of saying anything because she was a Southern lady.
So she just tried to ignore me.''
</P>
<P>
   The irony is that Hartley, who ended up writing for the Journal
even longer than Mrs. Dull, was very much a child of her cooking.
``I grew up on her recipes,'' she says. ``We took the Journal by
rural route, and my mother had a drawer full of those columns.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time she left the paper, Mrs. Dull's book was hitting its
stride. The first edition, published by the small Ruralist Press in
Atlanta, had sold a modest 14,000 copies. But in 1941, the New York
publishing house of Grosset &AMP; Dunlap picked up the title and moved
more than 150,000 copies in a dozen years _ a remarkable figure for
a regional cookbook, then or now.
</P>
<P>
   The title went out of print after Mrs. Dull's death, at 100, in
1964. For some reason, Grosset &AMP; Dunlap never renewed the
copyright. The family earns nothing from the facsimile edition that
Cherokee Publishing has brought out in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   ``That book never made her rich,'' her granddaughter says.
</P>
<P>
   A few years after she retired, the Journal sent a reporter to
interview Mrs. Dull at her Morningside home on the occasion of her
90th birthday. He found her cooking, as usual. But there was
something troubling her, something elemental to Southern cooking
that she feared she had omitted.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, I was so mortified the other day,'' she said. ``I
looked for turnip greens in my book and I found I'd left them out.
I owe them an apology.''
</P>
<P>
   No, Mrs. Dull, you didn't owe turnip greens an apology. They're
on Page 91, with kale and collards, right where you put them before
most of us were born.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Auchmutey writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
