<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-31 16:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3755 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LATINROCK03-COX     12-31 1125
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LATINROCK03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EMBARGOED UNTIL JANUARY 3
 &HT;    A new wave of Latin-influenced groups is poised to take the
world of pop music by storm
 &HT;    By Steve Dollar
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Rock 'n' roll has a new pronunciation.
</P>
<P>
   It's with an n.
</P>
<P>
   Often ignored by radio and MTV and underplayed on the pop
charts, the rock en espanol movement _ rock bands from Latin
America and elsewhere that sing in the Spanish language _ is
becoming a force that could change the face of popular music in the
next decade.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the best-known such groups still seem part of a distant
phenomenon. Yet bands as distinct as Mana, Cafe Tacuba, Los
Fabulosos Cadillacs and Plastilina Mosh have all played to Atlanta
club audiences. They also sell surprising numbers of records, a
fact reflected in the creation of a new category, ``Latin
Rock/Alternative,'' at the 1998 Grammy Awards.
</P>
<P>
   Mana, a Mexican rock act whose Police- and U2-influenced pop has
made it an arena-size attraction, has sold more than 500,000 copies
nationwide of its latest CD, ``Suenos Liquidos'' (Warner Bros.). Of
those, 1,685 copies were sold in local stores monitored by
SoundScan. That sum, the band argues, should be tripled since it
doesn't include the independent ``mom and pop'' outlets that are
the music's stronghold.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our turn has come,'' says Maribel Schumacher, vice president
for Latin music at Warner Bros., where her duties include
developing the U.S. market for Spanish-speaking rock acts.
``Everybody's a little tired of alternative music. This is
something new. Maybe 10 years ago, Hispanics were not considered
the greatest, the hippest, the coolest, but now the environment is
more hospitable. I remember friends dying if their parents spoke to
them in Spanish. Now, everybody's comfortable in their skins.''
</P>
<P>
   The success of a group such as Mana, which built its U.S.
following through years of touring the backwater circuit, does,
however, reflect a generational shift. Traditional, ballad-driven
forms, such as ranchero, are a part of its sound, but have been
powerfully modernized. ``A lot of kids that have grown up in the
U.S., whose parents have hard labor jobs, they don't identify
themselves with this type of (older) music,'' says Alex Gonzalez,
Mana's drummer. ``That's why these kids have hooked up on rock en
espanol. They say: This represents my culture and my age. It's
music that makes me feel proud.''
</P>
<P>
   Rock en espanol is showing up on the recording industry radar
screen at a time when pop music has become increasingly
multilingual. The youth culture watchdogs at Spin picked ``the
global pop underground'' as its No. 2 music trend of last year,
citing such ``internationalist'' stars as France's Air and Japan's
Cornelius as leading examples. If, as the rise of hip-hop and DJ
culture suggests, traditional rock music is waning, the movement
provides an exciting new context.
</P>
<P>
   ``Music from other places doesn't sound so strange anymore;
there's a nice homogenization going on in society,'' says Yale
Evelev, who runs Luaka Bop, a 10-year-old Warner-distributed label
launched by former Talking Heads singer David Byrne as a kind of
hip, multicultural outpost. Its eclectic roster includes Colombia's
edgy, antic Bloque, New York's high-energy King Chango and
Venezuela's nutso Los Amigos Invisibles. ``And rock en espanol
groups have changed. They used to be fairly derivative: the Latin
(answer to) the Police, Peter Gabriel, R.E.M. Groups now have real
strong identities, culturally based. They bring something to
music.''
</P>
<P>
   Importantly, much of it thrives on the outsider cache that has
always been a mark of integrity to young fans, whether the genre is
punk rock, rap or metal.
</P>
<P>
   ``This scene is so fresh,'' says Louisiana native Randy Ebright,
the 21-year-old ``crazy gringo'' in Molotov, a Mexico City-based
act whose frantic raunch is influenced by the Beastie Boys.
``People in Mexico are trying to be pioneers. Groups that are
coming up don't rely on radio at all.'' Ebright came to Mexico with
his parents six years ago, got deeply involved with the underground
rock scene and stayed behind when they returned to America. ``Where
I'm from,'' he complains, ``the whole scene is all saturated: the
music business is one big Nike commercial.''
</P>
<P>
   So don't expect to hear ``Rap Soda y Bohemia,'' Molotov's
version of Queen's ``Bohemian Rhapsody,'' on the radio anytime
soon. Though rock en espanol acts are infiltrating the alternative
rock market _ Molotov joined the ska and punk roster on the extreme
sports-themed Warped Tour; Argentina's Los Fabulosos Cadillacs
toured with swing's Cherry Poppin' Daddies _ they haven't
established a strong presence on the airwaves, in any language.
</P>
<P>
   Spanish-language radio typically broadcasts three formats
_tropical (island music, like salsa); Mexican regional (ranchero,
banda, Tex-Mex); and pop (Selena, Luis Miguel, Jon Secada). As
Warner Bros. Schumacher notes, ``Rock doesn't fit in unless it's a
ballad, a very romantic ballad. These artists didn't have their day
in the sun.''
</P>
<P>
   When Mana played Oakland, Calif., where it drew 13,000 fans,
drummer Gonzalez says, ``We were promoted on urban radio stations,
not Latin. That's going to be the future.''
</P>
<P>
   With more a potential Spanish-speaking audience of 30 million in
the U.S., the crossover potential works both ways. The
Atlanta-based septet Mandorico attracts an enthusiastic crowd of
Anglo and Latin fans to its local club performances, which fuse
reggae, hip-hop, Latin jazz and Afro-Caribbean rhythms in fiery,
upbeat dance tunes. ``We're just regular old American kids,''
confesses vocalist Jesse Lauricella, 23, a New Jersey native who
got turned onto rock en espanol during a six-month visit to Mexico,
and studied Spanish literature at Georgia State University(Ga.).
Though, he adds, the group's conga player is Puerto Rican.
``Spanish sounds better in the context of the music that we
create,'' he says. ``It's a beautiful language, it flows better.''
</P>
<P>
   Mandorico's bilingual audience is a sign of the times. ``You now
have third-generation Hispanic kids who straddle both sides of the
fence who speak among themselves in this hybrid language:
Spanglish,'' Schumacher says. ``And their peers understand them
because they're not just hanging out with Hispanics, they're
hanging out with everybody. I think they're going to start creating
their own music, their own sound. It's going to enter the
mainstream a little bit like rap did in the '80s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody thought it was a trend,'' she adds, ``and, hey, it
didn't go away.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Dollar writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
