<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-31 16:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3757 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REVIEW-ELVIS03-COX     12-31 1092
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-ELVIS03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EMBARGOED UNTIL JANUARY 3
 &HT;    `Careless Love' eyes downward trajectory of the shining star of
rock 'n' roll
 &HT;    By Steve Dollar
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sad, sad, sad. Tracing what seems a grand and irrevocable arc
through an American life that, finally, became an American tragedy,
music historian Peter Guralnick has produced the second half of his
colossal biography of Elvis Presley. To read it, to dip into its
careful accumulation of details, to ride that downward spiral as
the pure unleashed icon devolves into a drugged-up, constipated
kitsch machine, is to marvel. And to mourn. Because if Elvis
somehow channeled the truest, most incandescent passions of the
republic, if he really was the definitive figure Guralnick insists
he must be, and this is what happened to him _ then, damn, what
would happen to the rest of us?
</P>
<P>
   Of course, you've read it all before. The Presleyan Saga has
taken on a near-biblical aura in the two decades since the singer's
death in 1977. But if that implies holiness or reverence, it's of
the oddest, most contradictory kind: What demigod is born again in
the public imagination to mysteriously haunt Midwestern fast-food
chains? Only the most populist sort, I suppose, and Guralnick's
understanding of that is part of what makes ``Careless Love'' so
involving.
</P>
<P>
   That, and Guralnick's stamina for research. Picking up where he
left off four years ago with ``Last Train to Memphis: The Rise of
Elvis Presley,'' this most sympathetic critic and celebrant of
American roots culture copiously illustrates how the singer, having
changed forever the face of popular music, gradually evaporated.
Now that rock 'n' roll, by any account, is well into its 40s, the
story of the adolescent immortal who becomes a middle-aged
self-parody is so common as to be a cliche. But Elvis was a pioneer
in this sense and, instead of dying young and sealing his fate in
the amber of legend, his decline and fall was played out in the
tabloids. He died a joke: some fat guy striking a karate pose in
his bulgy white jumpsuit, dripping sweat from his ridiculous
mutton-chop sideburns, his speech slurred and addled. Viva Las
Vegas!
</P>
<P>
   Good, obsessively readable chunks of ``Careless Love'' are
devoted to this pathology. Depressing as it is, Guralnick's
approach redeems Elvis as a human, not a myth or a punch line, and
calmly, methodically makes coherent what often had been obscured by
the almost ``X-Files'' level of paranoid fantasy associated with
the King's Final Years. The clearest parallel _ and not merely
because of their mutual contributions to the history of Las Vegas _
is to Howard Hughes. By the end, Elvis had become the dysfunctional
Midas of rock 'n' roll.
</P>
<P>
   The beginning of the end is where the book starts, as Presley
temporarily suspends his career to join the Army in 1958 after the
death of his beloved mother, Gladys. Nothing was ever the same
after that. ``The artistic choices he faced when he returned to an
interrupted life were far more ambiguous than the good fortune he
had so innocently embraced,'' Guralnick writes in his introduction,
``and he never came fully to terms with the burden of decision
making that those choices placed upon him.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, also made clear is that Elvis enjoyed being Elvis. He was
an accomplice in that which recurs throughout ``Careless Love'':
the machinations of his Machiavellian manager, Col. Tom Parker; the
insulating kowtowing of his crowd of good old boy hangers-on, the
so-called ``Memphis Mafia''; the cheesy movies; the accommodating
parade of young beauty queens; the boredom and the prescription
pill dependencies _ which is what numbed and killed him; his
obsession with guns and police work (reaching its climax in a
hilarious, near-absurdist recount of Presley's brazen tete-a-tete
with President Nixon); the never-ending search for some deeper
meaning to it all.
</P>
<P>
   The meaning, always, was in the act. The act of being Elvis. As
fans know, there were moments when the long, slow car wreck of his
career appeared to be averted. His 1969 sessions with producer
Chips Moman at American Studios in Memphis, which became the
latter-day classic ``From Elvis in Memphis'' (a.k.a. ``The Memphis
Record''), was one of those moments when the singer reclaimed the
gospelized grandeur of his country-soul roots. The other was his
notorious 1968 Christmas broadcast on NBC. This was Elvis living up
to his promise.
</P>
<P>
   ``He loved to sing for people,'' says bassist Jerry Scheff, who
recounts his first meeting with Presley as he joined his stage band
in 1968. Scheff overcame his doubts about a performer he didn't
really like, summing up why in simple terms that stand as a fitting
epitaph: ``He loved to knock people out.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  REVIEW
</P>
<P>
   Careless Love: The Unmaking of Elvis Presley. By Peter
Guralnick. Little, Brown. $27.95. 767 pages.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: The second and final volume of an exhaustive,
enlightening biography of the king of rock 'n' roll.
</P>
<P>
   First look: An Excerpt
</P>
<P>
   Nighttime was the worst; he dreaded sleep, even as he dreaded
that sleep would never come. Over and over he dreamt the same
dream, a variation, in one form or another, of the nightmare that
had haunted him ever since success first arrived unbidden at his
door. The core of the dream never changed: all his money was gone,
the fans had abandoned him, the Colonel was gone, he was alone.
What would the fans think when they read (``Elvis: What
Happened?'')? he pressed Billy (Smith, his cousin) again and again.
He started constructing elaborate defenses in case someone should
yell something at him while he was onstage. ``At first he thought
he'd just say that a lot of things had been written about him, good
and bad, and that he was not a perfect person.'' Then he decided
maybe he should concede that it was true, he took certain
medications, but that he needed them, and to prove it he would
introduce Dr. Nick onstage. Finally, he settled on a strategy of
limited confession, which would conclude with the statement that
``After this tour I'm going to take time to get myself straightened
out.'' But only, he made clear to Billy, if the issue came up in a
manner that he just couldn't sidestep _ ``if the audience . . .
started booing and throwing things.''
</P>
<P>
   _ From ``Careless Love: The Unmaking of Elvis Presley'' by Peter
Guralnick
</P>
<P>
   Steve Dollar covers jazz, pop music and culture for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
