<HEADER>
A3758 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REVIEW-MARILYN03-COX     12-31 0574
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-MARILYN03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EMBARGOED UNTIL JANUARY 3
 &HT;    Sad, savvy Marilyn a co-conspirator in her own ills
 &HT;    By Miriam Longino
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's hard to imagine another book about screen idol Marilyn
Monroe. What could possibly be new about the troubled, talented
sexpot who has become as much a part of American pop culture as
baseball, the Big Mac or Elvis?
</P>
<P>
   Incredibly, though, this biography by meticulous researcher
Barbara Leaming (``Katharine Hepburn,'' ``Orson Welles'') sheds new
light on the life, career and death of one of America's most
enigmatic screen actresses, particularly on the events and state of
mind that led to her decisions and, hence, her legacy.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't the ``little girl lost'' so often painted by people
ranging from Gloria Steinhem to Norman Mailer (``Marilyn: A
Biography''). Certainly Monroe was a victim _ of a mentally ill
mother who tried to smother her in her crib, of powerful men who
exploited her sexually and, ultimately, of bloodsucking courtiers
who gladly provided her with enough Nembutal to numb her forever.
But Leaming also reveals that Marilyn was a top-rate user and
manipulator herself.
</P>
<P>
   After sleeping her way into film roles, Monroe appears to have
made every decision based on how it would affect her career and
acceptance into the rich and powerful circles of Hollywood. Her
husbands were not so much mates as they were escorts into that
world: Baseball hero Joe DiMaggio gave her insights into how to
negotiate contracts and make money, and playwright Arthur Miller
provided the legitimacy of the Broadway theater that propelled
Monroe from ``movie star'' to ``actress.'' Even the famed Lee
Strasberg, founder of New York's elite Actors Studio, comes across
as an egomaniac who saw Monroe as his meal ticket in Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, however, it was Monroe's fear of abandonment _
fueled by a childhood spent bouncing from one foster home to
another _ that sabotaged every relationship she formed, prompting
her to look for love in all the wrong places, most famously in the
arms of the ultra-powerful womanizer John F. Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   Leaming's detail sets this biography apart from the shelves full
of other Monroe books. The author not only describes each shade of
blond in Monroe's hair as she goes from bit-part bimbo to
top-billed bombshell but also knows what photographs the actress
kept at her bedside (a portrait of Abraham Lincoln) and can call on
an inventory of each tight outfit she paraded before the public _
and why she chose to wear each.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps more than unraveling the mystery that is Monroe, Leaming
provides an uncanny glimpse into the inner workings of 1950s
Hollywood, where women were viewed as sweet things rather than
savvy businesswomen. Monroe's legitimacy as an actress could never
eclipse her bustline, and so, in the end, she became the Barbie
everyone perceived her to be. By the time she died naked in a
Hollywood bungalow, a telephone dangling from her hand, her efforts
to reach beyond her image were as flat as a dial tone _ an American
tragedy, but one of her own making.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  REVIEW
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Monroe. By Barbara Leaming. Crown. $27.50. 464 pages.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: New insight into a much-told tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   Miriam Longino covers radio, country music and pop culture for
the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
