<HEADER>
A3766 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRUE-MURDER-HNS &LR;      12-31 0964
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRUE-MURDER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUSPECTS IN REPORTER'S MURDER RECANT PART OF THEIR CONFESSION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SUSAN HAYWARD  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   GUADALAJARA, Mexico _ Two Huichol Indians charged in the killing
of San Antonio Express-News correspondent Philip True have recanted
their story that they strangled him for taking photographs of their
homeland without permission.
</P>
<P>
   The suspects _ Miguel Hernandez de la Cruz and his
brother-in-law Juan Chivarras _ still admit choking the Mexico City
bureau chief. But they now say it was because a seemingly drunk
True threatened Hernandez' wife and children, and kicked him when
he approached his ranch in the highlands of Jalisco state the
morning of Dec. 4.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he spoke Spanish, then maybe I could have understood, but
he didn't speak Spanish,'' said Hernandez, 24, addressing the
Fourth Criminal Court on Tuesday. His statement was obtained from a
tape recording of the hearing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then he enters my house and kicks me. Then I thought, maybe he
is going to take something or violate my wife or children,''
Hernandez said.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez and Chivarras, 28, were arraigned Monday on murder
charges. Investigators said the men admitted killing True, who
spoke fluent Spanish, because he offended them by taking their
pictures.
</P>
<P>
   However, Horacio Vega, the lead investigator in the case,
dismissed the suspects' latest statements, saying Mexican criminal
suspects often retract their confessions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It happens in 85 percent of the cases. Nearly all of them
change their declarations,'' said Vega. ``It's something unique to
our judicial system.''
</P>
<P>
   Investigators said both men participated in the murder.
</P>
<P>
   According to his new story, Chivarras was vaccinating cows when
Hernandez asked for help in burying the body. He said they left
True's camera and backpack close to the body.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't take anything from the gringo,'' Chivarras said.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities said the two had True's camera when they were
apprehended. True's backpack and some other possessions were also
recovered, but it remains unclear who possessed the items. His
binoculars and wallet remain missing.
</P>
<P>
   The two men said True was killed about 9 a.m. on Dec. 4.
Investigators have said the time of death was Dec. 6 at 8 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   An accomplished photographer and avid hiker, True, 50, was
combining a vacation with a reporting trip about the Huichol
Indians who live in virtual isolation in villages and ranches in
the Sierra Madre Occidental mountains. But his 100-mile, 10-day
trek was cut short halfway through his expedition.
</P>
<P>
   True's wife alerted authorities when he didn't call or return as
scheduled on Dec. 10.
</P>
<P>
   Margarito Diaz Martinez, a Huichol Indian, discovered True's
body Dec. 14 in Chapalagana Canyon while he was hunting for
javelinas. Diaz hiked out of the remote canyon to alert others.
</P>
<P>
   When a rescue team returned two days later, True's body had been
moved and buried in a makeshift grave near the Rio Chapalagana. His
backpack, camera and other belongings were missing.
</P>
<P>
   The two suspects said in their Tuesday declaration that they had
buried the body right away after dragging it to a hillside and
throwing it over the edge near the river.
</P>
<P>
   The men live far from where True was found, and moving his body
would have involved dragging him several miles through difficult
terrain to the canyon.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials said they are watching the case closely but had
no comment on the latest developments.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are observing, following closely but from one step back,''
said Judith Bryan, spokeswoman for the U.S. consulate in
Guadalajara, the capital of Jalisco state.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with the Guadalajara daily Publico on Tuesday,
the men said they were beaten after being arrested in their home by
``green judicials,'' which reporters here interpreted as meaning
army soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   Vega denied that the two were abused in any way.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, officials from the State Human Rights
Commission have begun an investigation into the facts surrounding
the arrest of the two suspects, who showed no external signs of
physical abuse when they were brought before cameras on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (STORY COULD END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The case, which has grabbed headlines across Mexico, has been
plagued by several errors by state authorities.
</P>
<P>
   The first was an autopsy conducted by the Jalisco medical
examiner on Dec. 16 that determined True was strangled. The autopsy
noted there was tearing of the rectum, indicating possible sexual
abuse. But investigators said on Monday the damage was caused by
the body being dragged after death.
</P>
<P>
   Federal prosecutors ordered a second autopsy that was witnessed
by a forensic pathologist contracted by the FBI. Results of that
autopsy, performed Dec. 19 in Mexico City, have not been released.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are concerned about the investigation, and we ask the
Mexican government to clarify the status of the case,'' said
Express-News Editor Robert Rivard. ``More than 10 days have passed
since the second autopsy was conducted, yet the family and this
newspaper are still awaiting the results, or a plausible reason why
results are not being released.''
</P>
<P>
   Several unsourced newspaper reports have also said True had a
very high alcohol level, which his wife, Martha, friends and
colleagues because True dismiss, since, according to them, the
reporter did not drink.
</P>
<P>
   In Jalisco state, many Huicholes have been shaken by True's
murder and fear it will reflect badly on their friendly ancient
culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope there are no repercussions in our culture and
community,'' said Carlos Salvador Diaz, a high-school teacher. ``I
don't want people to think we are killers.''
</P>
</TEXT>
