<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-31 16:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3786 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LYNCH-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      12-31 0740
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LYNCH-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REFLECTIONS ON THE PAST YEAR AND HILLARY RODHAM CLINTON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN LYNCH  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ As this year draws to an end _ a rough year for
the country in general and for many of us in particular _ I find
myself thinking back to a sunny June day nearly four years ago. I
was in Washington, attending a luncheon in a congressional office
building. Hillary Rodham Clinton sat a few tables away, waiting her
turn to speak.
</P>
<P>
   She's a smallish woman, trim and quick to smile in such
settings. She got up, delivered a few well-chosen phrases and sat
down again, smiling and seemingly ill at ease with all the
attention.
</P>
<P>
   I was struck by that. Here's this blazingly bright Yale lawyer,
the first lady of the land. Yet she struck me as almost shy as she
spoke before a few hundred people. Not at all what I'd expected.
</P>
<P>
   And, maybe, not at all what I thought I was seeing. Maybe that
shyness was only a studied act, a refined bit of political
theatrics. And certainly it seemed a marked contrast to the
confident, almost brittle woman I'd seen on television _ the one
who had told Steve Croft of ``60 Minutes'' through a plastic smile
that she wasn't Tammy Wynette, standing mindlessly by her man
despite the magnitude of his sins against her.
</P>
<P>
   That is, however, precisely what Hillary Clinton has done all
through this year. Confronted with one of the most public and
humiliating betrayals that any married woman has ever endured, she
has stood relentlessly by her man, smiling that same smile, and
asked the nation to forgive him as she claims she has forgiven him.
</P>
<P>
   Well, nobody knows what goes on inside anybody else's marriage.
Bill Clinton's penchant for philandering was no secret when he ran
for president, and most Americans were willing to ignore it as long
as his wife was willing to do the same.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody could have predicted that Clinton's weakness for young
lovelies in thong underwear could provoke such a towering national
crisis. And certainly nobody could have predicted that his wife
would be called upon to bear such a public burden of humiliation,
whatever complicated private arrangement these people have in their
marriage.
</P>
<P>
   What's interesting, though, is this: While Bill Clinton's job
approval rating has soared past the 70 per cent mark, so has the
public's contempt for the man as a human being.
</P>
<P>
   Three in four Americans say they would be horrified if their
kids grew up to be a Bill Clinton _ somebody so fixated on
satisfying his own desires that he seems oblivious to the pain he
causes when he indulges his passions.
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Rodham Clinton's approval numbers, though, are shooting
through the roof.
</P>
<P>
   John Zogby, the pollster headquartered in Utica, N.Y., reports
that if she moves to New York when her husband leaves office and
runs for the U.S. Senate seat now held by Daniel Patrick Moynihan,
she's a cinch to nail down the Democratic nomination in a state
where Democrats outnumber Republicans by 5-3. She would beat every
other Democratic hopeful, including as prodigious a vote-getter as
State Comptroller Carl McCall.
</P>
<P>
   There's precedent for that sort of carpetbagging. Robert Kennedy
did it in the 1960s, and New Yorkers were delighted to provide him
with a U.S. Senate platform from which to launch his 1968
presidential bid.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy, though, had at least a tangential link to New York.
Hillary Clinton has none. So why the willingness of so many New
Yorkers to have her take over Moynihan's Senate seat.
</P>
<P>
   It's easy enough to write off such imposing political popularity
as mere evidence of the power of victimhood in this whiny,
self-absorbed culture of ours. But there's more to it than that.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody _ not a blessed soul _ would blame Hillary Clinton if she
moved out of the White House tomorrow and left her lecherous
husband to whatever fate might await him in the U.S. Senate now
that he has been impeached. It wouldn't cost her a single vote if
she chose to embark on a political career of her own.
</P>
<P>
   That she doesn't clear out says something about her _ that she's
either a saint or a fool, or some combination of the two.
</P>
<P>
   It says also that whatever becomes of Bill Clinton, we probably
haven't seen the last of his dogged, determined wife.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Lynch is a columnist for the Albany Times Union, P.O. Box
15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
