<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-31 17:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3829 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-PAC10-HNS &LR;      12-31 0880
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-PAC10-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAC-10 LOOKS STRONGER AND MORE COMPETITIVE THAN EVER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK FAINARU-WADA  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Such are the strides made by the Pac-10 over the
course of the last few years that some of the league's college
basketball coaches have taken to making bold, definitive
statements.
</P>
<P>
   University of California at Berkeley couach Ben Braun, when
asked a couple months ago whether one could argue that the Pac-10
is the preeminent conference in the nation, said, ``I don't even
think you want to say arguably. I think it is the top conference.
And I think you're hearing others around the country saying that.''
</P>
<P>
   Eddie Payne, the Oregon State coach who clearly has an
outsiders' view with regard to the NCAA Tournament, said the Pac-10
has ``maybe eight teams with a legitimate shot at making the
tournament.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, these aren't far-fetched statements. Sure, the ACC is
probably superior to the Pac-10, but there are those who would back
up the Braun. And, no, eight conference teams won't make the
tournament, but Payne is absolutely right that eight have a
legitimate chance.
</P>
<P>
   Given that setup, here's a best guess on how the race stands to
play out from top to bottom, with a quick look at each team:
</P>
<P>
   1. STANFORD (10-2 nonconference record): The Cardinal were the
overwhelming, nearly-unanimous media pick before the season
started, but now the gap has narrowed considerably in part because
of injuries to center Jason Collins, forward/guard Ryan Mendez and
point guard Michael McDonald.
</P>
<P>
   2. ARIZONA (8-0): Gone are starters Mike Bibby, Miles Simon,
Michael Dickerson and Bennett Davison, leaving Lute Olson _ the
Pac-10's longest-standing coach _ with a bevy of newcomers to cope
with.
</P>
<P>
   ``The good news is we have some very good young players,'' said
Olson, in his 16th season at Arizona. ``The bad news is they're
young.''
</P>
<P>
   But beyond the freshmen, the real key may be senior point guard
Jason Terry, who has the talent to be the league's MVP _ assuming
he's not exhausted from playing nearly every minute of every game.
</P>
<P>
   3. CAL (9-1): With their performance against North Carolina, the
Bears proved they not only belong in the Top 25 but they could do
some real damage in the Pac-10. Geno Carlisle clearly is a big-time
player, and Cal has several players who can hurt you.
</P>
<P>
   4. UCLA (7-2): Arizona has got nothing on UCLA when it comes to
youth. Of the Bruins' 14-man roster, 12 are either freshmen or
sophomores, but like Olson, Steve Lavin has some great young
talent. Lavin had perhaps the best recruiting class in the nation,
and he's jumping right in with post men Dan Gadzuric and Jerome
Moiso, plus forwards Matt Barnes and JaRon Rush and guard Ray
Young.
</P>
<P>
   Still, like Arizona, UCLA's key will be its top returning guard,
Baron Davis. Davis incurred a surgery-requiring knee injury during
the NCAA Tournament last year, and he's still not back to 100
percent.
</P>
<P>
   5. OREGON (8-1): The Ducks clearly are a program on its way up,
with coach Ernie Kent leading the way. Three starters are back from
a 13-14 team that tied for fifth in the Pac-10 last season, and
Oregon has been bolstered by the addition of junior college
transfers Alex Scales, a 6-4 shooting guard, and Darius Wright, a
6-foot point guard.
</P>
<P>
   6. WASHINGTON (7-3): The Huskies are much higher than this on a
lot of other so-called lists, largely because they return their
three best players _ Todd MacCulloch, Donald Watts and Deon Luton _
from a team that pushed the University of Connecticut to the limit
in the East Regional semis. But Washington has a big question mark
at point guard, and that could be enough to keep the Huskies from
challenging.
</P>
<P>
   7. ARIZONA STATE (8-4): The Sun Devils won their final six games
of the preseason, and if they come together under first-year coach
Rob Evans, they may make a move into the upper half. Mike Batiste,
Bobby Lazor and Eddie House are quite the scoring trifecta, though
Jeremy Veal will be tough to replace.
</P>
<P>
   8. USC (8-1): The Trojans, 9-19 last year, are off to their best
start since the 1991-92 season, and there are a lot of people who
see tem as the team most likely to make a move. Said Washington
coach Bob Bender: ``I think 'SC is a team that is capable of
surprising a lot of people.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Henry Bibby turned to mostly young players by the end of
last season to get them ready for this year, plus Bibby added
junior college transfer Brian Scalabrine, who is seventh in the
conference in scoring at 15.9 points per game.
</P>
<P>
   9. WASHINGTON STATE (6-5): The Cougars were in a lot of games
last season, they just didn't win many, finishing 3-15 in league
play. This year might not be much better considering they lost 16.1
points and 10.1 rebounds per game from Carlos Daniel and they've
spent much of this preseason coping with a series of injuries.
</P>
<P>
   10. OREGON STATE (6-3): Corey Benjamin and his 19.8 points per
game are gone, but, actually, the Beavers tended to play better
when he was hurt last season. Still, the Beavers don't seem to have
much, and Payne's likely response is to return to a deliberate
style in which he tries to slow down the game and keep his team in
it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
