<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOKO-MUSIC-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S GOOD TO BE THE QUEEN OF CHICAGO BLUES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RANDY CORDOVA  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - No wonder one of Koko Taylor's many albums is called
``Force of Nature.''
</P>
<P>
   The 63-year-old blueswoman can holler and shout with disarming
intensity. She's got a fiery, immediate way with a song. If some
singers give you the impression of whispering in your ear, Taylor
practically shouts in your face.
</P>
<P>
   But calling from her home in Chicago, Taylor sounds less like a
force of nature and more like the kindly grandma she is.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm so sorry I'm late,'' says the woman dubbed the Queen of
Chicago Blues. ``I was running a fever and had chills last night,
so I had to go to the doctor. But I think it's getting better.''
</P>
<P>
   Normally, Taylor is in pretty fine health. But being sick seems
like a terrible way to end what has been a banner year for the lady
who growls like a caged tiger in song.
</P>
<P>
   In blues circles in general and in Chicago in particular, the
woman is an institution. There was even a play mounted this year in
the Windy City about Taylor's life, ``Wang Dang Doodle.'' It
featured Queen Roy singing the songs Taylor made famous.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, I was involved in no kind of way with the play,''
she says, sounding both flattered and peeved at the same time.
``This woman was singing my songs and acting as much like me as
possible. It was a real nice show _ I really appreciated the fact
that they cared enough about me to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   But watching someone else do blues the Taylor way doesn't sound
like her idea of a good time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought the actress did a wonderful job,'' Taylor says.
``But any time you automatically sing anyone's else songs . . . Say
I pick a song of Aretha Franklin, like ``Respect.'' That track is
already laid, because she laid the foundation. You have to be a
blueprint. But this girl is trying to sound like me, to pass like
me.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you know what I'm saying,'' she continues, very
butter-wouldn't-melt-in-my-mouth. ``She is (begin ital) ``very''
(end ital) sweet.''
</P>
<P>
   Born and raised on a sharecropper's farm in Memphis, it's been a
long road to the blues heights for Taylor. Willie Dixon discovered
her in 1962 and helped her land a recording contract with the famed
Chess label. Since then, there have been 14 W.C. Handy Awards (the
blues equivalent to the Grammy), not to mention a Grammy itself.
</P>
<P>
   There were dry spells, particularly in the early '70s. But once
she signed with Alligator Records in 1975, she climbed back to the
top of the ladder. There have been seven albums for the label; an
eighth is due out next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I look back, I am really proud of everything that I have
done,'' she says. ``It has been a struggle over the years, and
everyone knows that blues music is always on the tail end of
everyone's totem pole. It's getting better, but I'm doing a lot of
things I've never done before.''
</P>
<P>
   That includes films, such as David Lynch's ``Wild at Heart,''
and TV spots on ``Night Watch'' and ``Late Show With David
Letterman.'' At an age when many performers slow down, Taylor is
like the Energizer Bunny: She just keeps going and going.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I have to say, I sing better now than I did on the old
records,'' she says, a woman proud of her accomplishments. ``It
builds and grows with experience. I've been doing it for over 30
years now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, I didn't start out as great as they say I am today. I
had to grow. I had to get there. The older I get, the better I get.
It's like fine whiskey _ the older it gets, the better it
tastes.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-31-98 1702EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
