<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-31 17:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3845 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Y2K-SIGNIFICANCE-2TAK     12-31 1255
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-SIGNIFICANCE-2TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPINIONS VARY ABOUT ECONOMIC DAMAGE FROM Y2K BUG 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DAVID IVANOVICH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Wall Street economist Edward Yardeni expects the
nation to plunge into its worst recession in a quarter of a
century.
</P>
<P>
   Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan anticipates ``some very
unusual things'' when computers try to comprehend the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Jean Staffen of Austin, Texas, has already bought herself a
backup generator, while Knight Ridder executive David Starr thinks
the whole issue is largely a big con.
</P>
<P>
   One year from today, our plugged-in world will know the
significance of the year 2000 or ``Y2K'' problem, the widespread
computer glitch that will prompt uncorrected software and computer
chips to misread dates in 2000 and beyond.
</P>
<P>
   Businesses and at least some governments are scrambling to root
out the computer bugs, checking millions of lines of computer code
and examining innumerable embedded microchips in an effort to head
off potential problems.
</P>
<P>
   But costs are mounting, and success is anything but assured.
</P>
<P>
   The consulting firm Gartner Group estimates that the world will
spend $600 billion _ 20 percent more than the cost of the Vietnam
War _ to deal with the Y2K issue. Merrill Lynch puts the price tag
closer to $1 trillion.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, Gartner estimates that one in five U.S. companies will not
be ready when the date turns over. The federal government is viewed
as the world leader in addressing the problem, but a congressional
oversight committee thinks that the State Department won't have the
Y2K problem licked until 2034.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the scope of the problem, at least some disruption in
our computer-laden society appears inevitable. Just how extensive
the fallout will be is anyone's guess.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are two camps,'' said Don Jones, Year 2000 product
manager for software giant Microsoft Corp. ``One says that
Armageddon is coming with the year 2000. Planes will fall out of
the sky. The other camp says that there really is no problem. The
truth is probably in the middle.''
</P>
<P>
   John Koskinen, President Clinton's Y2K czar, figures only 2 to 3
percent of the world's embedded computer chips are at risk of
failing. But with an estimated 50 billion microchips buried in
computers and machinery around the world, that could mean that as
many as 150 million chips could be problematic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not everything is going to get fixed,'' Koskinen warns. ``My
view is not to tell people there will be no inconvenience, and they
won't notice it. The chances are a lot of people will notice it.''
</P>
<P>
   Dubbed the ``millennium bug'' _ a somewhat inaccurate moniker
since the new millennium doesn't actually begin until Jan. 1, 2001
_ the Y2K problem stems from a practice begun more than 30 years
ago, during the early days of computer software writing.
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to save computing capacity and apparently never
suspecting their software might be used as late as 2000,
programmers typically abbreviated year designations as two digits.
</P>
<P>
   What that meant was, in some cases, their programs would
interpret ``99'' to mean 1999 but ``00'' as ``1900.'' In the case
of some personal computers, ``00'' will be interpreted as 1980 _
Year 0 for the PC, while some embedded controllers, computer chips
implanted in specialized devices, may not be able to interpret 2000
at all.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the approaching turn of the century, programmers
continued the practice until quite recently.
</P>
<P>
   ``We failed to manage the programmers,'' said Yardeni, an
economist with Deutsche Bank Securities who has emerged as the
leading Y2K doomsayer on Wall Street. ``We created a global
computer network without any adult supervision.''
</P>
<P>
   Businesses may get a strong indication of what's in store Sept.
9 _ that's 09/09/99 _ another problematic date since in Cobol, a
computer language used in many business applications, 9999 means
``quit.''
</P>
<P>
   The next moment to watch is 7 p.m. EST Dec. 31 _ midnight Jan. 1
Universal Coordinated Time. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Many operations are expected to take special precautions on
those days. Chevron Corp., for instance, has issued a directive
that no company-owned or contractor-operated oil tanker will be
permitted in narrow passages or restricted waters on either Sept. 9
or Dec. 31.
</P>
<P>
   Many Americans will run into the bug while working on their
personal computers. Houston-based Compaq Computer Corp., for
instance, was making personal computers as late as September 1997
that did not completely account for the Y2K problem. Even
Microsoft's popular Windows 98 operating software has a Year 2000
glitch.
</P>
<P>
   Both companies are offering consumers free software to fix the
problems.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers also may notice an incorrect date on their fax
machines and their camcorders, although the devices should operate
properly otherwise, consumer products makers say. And auto
manufacturers, after months of investigation, say motorists can be
confident their cars will run smoothly.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government is trying to swat down the most
pernicious rumors. Elevators won't stop between floors, regulators
say. The Federal Aviation Administration doesn't plan to ground
planes. Pacemakers won't malfunction in patients' chests.
</P>
<P>
   For Uncle Sam, the world's largest computer user, the Y2K
problem presents a daunting challenge. As of Nov. 13, 61 percent of
the computer systems deemed ``mission critical'' for the federal
government had been repaired and tested.
</P>
<P>
   The Defense Department, which Koskinen notes ``had cornered the
market on embedded chips'' with its ``smart'' weapons, must check
and test 2,581 systems, more than a third of all the critical
government systems. As of Nov. 13, the Defense Department had
corrected slightly more than half of its critical operations.
</P>
<P>
   Regulators also are concerned about the nation's Medicare
program, which pumps $250 billion into the nation's health care
system. The Medicare program actually is administered by 60 large
private insurance companies, some of which are chafing at the
government's insistence that their system be fully Y2K-compliant by
March 31.
</P>
<P>
   ``The risk is not that the whole system would fail, but that
some will have to have backup and contingency plans,'' Koskinen
said.
</P>
<P>
   Many have expressed concerns that the FAA won't be able to get
its antiquated computer systems in shape before the date change and
will be forced to either ground flights or greatly expand time
between landings.
</P>
<P>
   Koskinen has vowed to fly on Dec. 31 and Jan. 1 to demonstrate
confidence in the system, although 60 percent of the information
technology executives surveyed by CIO Magazine said they would not
fly on New Year's Day.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, attention to the Y2K issue is spotty. While the United
States, Canada and Britain are trying aggressively to deal with the
Y2K problem, even highly industrialized nations such as France and
Germany have been slow to take the threat seriously, while nuclear
powers such as Russia and China appear mystified.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Connie Morella, R-Md., head of the House Technology
Subcommittee, tells the story of a U.S. foreign service officer in
an unnamed country who had asked about the nation's efforts to
handle the computer bug and was allegedly told: ``Not to worry my
friend. We are prepared to spray anywhere and everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   The federal government, while trying to wake up much of the
world to the problem, is also busy waving the Y2K flag at home.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(MORE) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In October, President Clinton signed special legislation to
allow companies to share information on ways to handle the Y2K
problem.
</P>
<P>
   The Securities and Exchange Commission issued new guidelines
requiring companies to report on their Y2K activities, but critics
complain that companies have been loath to provide real information
about their efforts to correct the problem.
</P>
<P>
   The banking industry, prodded by regulators, is probably farther
ahead in dealing with the issue than any other industry.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. conducted on-site
inspections at 6,034 institutions regarding their Y2K efforts. In
June, 43 institutions received an unsatisfactory grade for their
activities, a number that had been pared to nine by November.
(Regulators refused to release the names of these institutions).
</P>
<P>
   As of Thursday, the nation's banks were required to have the
bugs worked out of their in-house systems. The idea was to give the
industry time to handle the more difficult problem of ensuring that
the links between institutions also work properly.
</P>
<P>
   As 2000 approaches, bank regulators are concerned that consumers
will begin withdrawing their funds from the nation's financial
institutions. In anticipation of that, the Federal Reserve is
increasing the amount of currency available.
</P>
<P>
   ``My suspicion is that we're going to run into a lot of
problems,'' Greenspan told a Senate committee last fall.
</P>
<P>
   The maritime industry is known to be woefully behind in
preparing for the year 2000 bug, while the health industry will
have a daunting task dealing with the numerous chips embedded in
increasingly sophisticated medical equipment.
</P>
<P>
   And many observers have expressed concerns about the nation's
electric power grid, fearful that power plants will be knocked out
of commission because of uncorrected problems in their own
operations or in equipment and services provided by outside
contractors.
</P>
<P>
   The nation's oil companies, meanwhile, must test for and correct
computer bugs in sophisticated equipment used from the wellhead to
the gasoline pump.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips Petroleum Co. was conducting a Y2K test on an oil
platform in the North Sea last year only to have a
contractor-supplied monitor used to detect natural gas releases
fail.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest impact for Phillips and a lot of large companies
is not going to be the stuff inside your fence,'' said Del Clark,
director of Phillips' year 2000 program. The real risk for
companies are the suppliers and contractors they must rely on to
ensure that their products are Y2K-compliant.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the uncertainty about the Y2K issue, expert opinions
about the economic damage from the millennium bug vary.
</P>
<P>
   Deutsche Bank's Yardeni estimates that the nation's gross
domestic product could drop by 3 to 5 percent. ``It's going to be a
wicked, nasty recession,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds Griffith, a professor of finance at Stephen F. Austin
State University in Nacogdoches, Texas, figures the economy stands
a 50-50 chance of plunging into a depression and a 12 percent
chance of suffering a major collapse.
</P>
<P>
   The pessimists, however, appear to be in the minority. Some Y2K
experts believe that all the computer upgrading being done by
businesses and governments will help improve productivity.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Reserve Bank of Philadelphia, surveying 33
forecasters about the effects of the Y2K issue, found that the
average prediction calls for a 0.3 percent gain in gross domestic
product in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The economic forecasting firm WEFA, in a report issued last
June, predicted that preparations to handle the Y2K bug would
actually boost economic activity this year. The group predicted a
slowing of economic activity in 2000 but does not expect a
recession to result from the Y2K problem.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill Lynch, after conducting an exhaustive study of
companies' efforts to deal with the Y2K problem, reported it was
``cautiously optimistic'' that industry was taking the issue
seriously.
</P>
<P>
   Not all are persuaded the Y2K bug represents a real threat.
David Starr, chief information officer for publishing giant Knight
Ridder, calls the uproar over the millennium bug ``the most
overblown thing I've seen in my 20 years of experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Starr believes many companies are being hoodwinked by Y2K
consultants, which are racking up fees correcting Y2K bugs that do
not really affect operations. He is urging companies to test their
systems before trying to fix the computer bugs, to make sure they
are worth bothering about.
</P>
<P>
   With government and business leaders unable to provide complete
assurances, the public debate over Y2K, as played out in Internet
chat rooms and on late-night radio, has taken on apocalyptic tones.
</P>
<P>
   So-called ``survivalists'' are bracing for what they fear will
be a technological breakdown, while numerous religious groups are
linking the millennium bug to an anticipated End Time.
</P>
<P>
   Staffen has organized an Austin-based group known as the Frog
Pond, named for the old adage that a frog dropped in a pot of
scalding hot water will jump out while one placed in tepid water
where the temperature is raised gradually will be boiled to death.
</P>
<P>
   ``We represent those who realize we're in hot water,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The 35 or so members of the Frog Pond meet weekly at a local
Denny's restaurant, where they discuss how best to store water,
preserve food and protect themselves against possible marauders.
</P>
<P>
   Christian broadcaster Jerry Falwell is hawking a $28 video ``A
Christian's Guide to the Millennium Bug,'' detailing possible Y2K
``catastrophes'' ranging from a failure of the military defense
system to a grounding of commercial aircraft worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   (Despite the intense religious interest in the new millennium,
historians point out that the 2000th anniversary of the birth of
Jesus of Nazareth has probably already occurred. The sixth century
abbot who invented our Christian system of reckoning time,
Dionysius Exiguus, miscalculated. Jesus likely was born no later
than 4 B.C., historians say).
</P>
<P>
   Some 13 percent of information technology executives surveyed by
CIO Magazine said they are upgrading security at their own homes in
the event of trouble _ including possible stockpiling of weapons.
</P>
<P>
   ``This building hysteria over Y2K is the result of a bunch of
fairly common strains in American life that are coming together,''
namely paranoia, fear of the unknown, a distrust of technology and
religious associations with the millennium, argued James Glassman,
a fellow at the American Enterprise Institute in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing to me that people are so frightened of these
things,'' Glassman said. ``In a way, this could become a
self-fulfilling prophecy, if you get enough people who are
hysterical and start withdrawing their money from banks and
hoarding water and hoarding ammunition and walking around with
guns.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Chronicle reporters Polly Ross Hughes and Dwight Silverman
contributed to this story.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
