<DOCNO> NYT19981231.0231 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-31 17:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3899 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SIBLEY-COLUMN01-COX     12-31 0645
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIBLEY-COLUMN01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Be it resolved: I'll watch for chance to say thank you
 &HT;    By Celestine Sibley
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   A form of New Year's festivity that has ever puzzled me is the
``watch party.'' What, I used to wonder when we assembled at the
country church on New Year's Eve, were we watching for? Would there
be some phenomenon in the sky to tell us that we were entering a
new year?
</P>
<P>
   Some of us would rush outside and stand, shivering in the
unexpected south Alabama cold, peering at the sky. We never saw
anything to mark the end of the 12 months and usher in a new
beginning. But we felt duty-bound to watch.
</P>
<P>
   When nothing came of it, we were inclined to pass over New
Year's as a day invented by parents and teachers to incite us to
make good resolutions.
</P>
<P>
   People joke about those resolutions nowadays, and I'm not sure
anybody, least of all children, sits down with pencil and paper and
draws a blueprint for doing better and being better.
</P>
<P>
   It's not a bad idea, though, is it? It's like the old rite of
spring housecleaning, a way of taking a look at one's life or house
or job and wondering if there's not some way of improving it. If
sins of omission and commission assail you at year's end, there's
something therapeutic about vowing to make a change.
</P>
<P>
   The timing is probably perfect. I know that after Christmas,
there's always a period of ``I should have, why didn't I?'' to
disturb your sense of well-being, to ruffle any smugness you may
have accumulated. It may be the presents you didn't send or the
ones you undeservedly received. It may be the Christmas cards you
didn't mail off. In my case, it's almost always the thank yous I
didn't say.
</P>
<P>
   There's always a moment or two in a day or a sleepless night
when you can scribble a note to thank somebody for what they have
done for you or meant to you. I made mental lists of those people
in the dark of several nights _ and then turned over and went back
to sleep.
</P>
<P>
   But when a thank you or an expression of love comes your way,
guilt knocks at your door. For several days, I have lugged around
in my sweater pocket a note from a good friend who simply scrawled
on a piece of scrap paper out of his office these words: ``I love
you. I love you. I love you. And so does Helen (his wife).'' I love
them both, but I didn't pick up scrap paper and pen and say so _ to
them or to many other people.
</P>
<P>
   A phone call from a friend in the mountains, who left a message
that he was just checking to see how I was feeling, took me back to
a friend who came and sat in my room for an entire day, listening
to a mentally ill relative purge his heart and soul of things he
had done wrong in his life. He went back to childhood, and he
poured out his guilt for failures and offenses he had committed.
</P>
<P>
   She listened patiently, and when it was over, he seemed clean
and at peace. He died tranquilly a few days later. I have never
forgotten the sacrifice she made to just sit and listen, and I
haven't ever thanked her enough, particularly when she fell ill
herself and could have used my help.
</P>
<P>
   Henry Wadsworth Longfellow, the old New England poet whose
bearded countenance hung in the second-grade classroom when I was a
child in Mobile, Ala., called New Year's one of ``the secret
anniversaries of the heart,'' one of the ``holiest of all
holidays.''
</P>
<P>
   It hasn't always been that for most of us. Balls and big
ballgames and eating and drinking fill the day for many of us. And
I wouldn't advise anybody to pass up black-eyed peas and rice,
those symbols of good luck a-coming to many of us. But more
important is to say ``Thank you'' and ``I love you,'' if you don't
write down another resolution.
</P>
<P>
   _ Celestine Sibley writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
