<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981231.0232 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-31 17:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3902 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NINTIES-NICKNAME03-CO     12-31 0957
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NINTIES-NICKNAME03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The race is on to encapsulate the last 10 years of the
millennium in one pithy phrase.
 &HT;    By Jill Vejnoska
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ We interrupt this decade to help you sum up this
decade. Prematurely, yes, but then, what isn't in this ``All News,
All the Time'' era in which we now live?
</P>
<P>
   It's a decade that's seen the resurrection of such 1950s
cultural icons as the martini _ although now they're mixed with
generous fingerfuls of Web surfing. A decade when we've revisited
and openly yearned for the simpler, nobler spirit of 1940s, World
War II America _ but wouldn't dream of turning off our cellular
phones and beepers while watching ``Saving Private Ryan'' in a
crowded movie theater.
</P>
<P>
   ``I call it the `Nervous '90s,' '' said Swarthmore College
history professor and pop culture expert Tim Burke. ``The
preoccupation is with the millennium and not with the '90s as
something in and of itself. People are looking to this decade to
summarize a lot that has come before and what will come to be.''
</P>
<P>
   As Burke's words suggest, the 1990s could turn out to be one of
those decades remembered largely for its lack of memorableness.
After all, there's not a big nostalgia market in nervousness, is
there?
</P>
<P>
   ``If the 1890s were the `Gay '90s,' then the 1990s have been the
`Gray '90s,' '' lamented Gerald Celenti, director of the Rhinebeck,
N.Y.-based Trends Research Institute. ``There was no social or
musical or entertainment glue to bind it together, no crusades,
nothing to galvanize people. It is a totally unmemorable era.''
</P>
<P>
   Others couldn't disagree more. If only we would stop going
online and checking voice mail for a while, they say, we might have
time to contemplate how much this decade has distinguished itself.
Even made a name for itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to be known as the information decade,'' said
Paul Levinson, a Fordham University communications professor who
points out that technology ranging from voice mail and FAX machines
to cell phones and even the Internet all were developed or
introduced into widespread use during this decade. ``It's only been
in the '90s that we've paid attention to information as a
commodity.''
</P>
<P>
   Only one aspect of the '90s isn't up for debate, it seems: In
due time, the decade will indeed be cut open and dissected by
cultural historians bent on ``putting it into perspective''; by wry
social commentators intent on inventing some pithy shorthand name
along the lines of the ``Me Decade'' or the ``Decade of Love'';
and, of course, by collectibles connoisseurs determined to corner
the market on this era's equivalent of Beatles ticket stubs or
goldfish-populated platform shoes.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the process has already begun. Maybe it's a sign of the
times (the Don't Blame Me Decade?), but it's really not our fault.
</P>
<P>
   ``In many ways, the 1960s reinvented the idea of the decade,''
Burke said. ``Long after we had the `Gay '90s' and the `Roaring
'20s', along came another period that seemed to tell a story. Since
then, we've become eager to identify our decades before they're
over.''
</P>
<P>
   And how. In Wilmington, Del., they've already dubbed the '90s
the ``.com Decade,'' courtesy of a contest conducted by the local
newspaper, the News Journal. Nationwide, time capsules are enjoying
a resurgence in popularity, said Oglethorpe University's Paul
Hudson, who says the approaching millennium has ``everyone trying
to write themselves into history'' by essentially predetermining
the collectibles or nostalgia of this decade. As head of the
International Time Capsule Society, Hudson hears from people who
are placing Tiger Woods memorabilia, e-mail artifacts and condoms
into their distinctively '90s containers.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the U.S. Postal Service is trying to figure out what
made the '90s so memorable. The ``Celebrate the Century'' program
asks the public to vote on ``cultural icons'' from each decade to
be commemorated on stamps. Previous decades' winners have included
such instantly recognizable items as the '60s peace symbol and the
'70s smiley face.
</P>
<P>
   Yet it may be a whole other story when '90s voting begins in
April.
</P>
<P>
   ``The subjects for the '90s aren't quite as exciting as those
for the rest of the decades,'' conceded the manager of stamp and
product marketing, Valoree Vargo, who cited the Persian Gulf War,
the Internet explosion and baseball's re-emerging popularity as
possibilities for inclusion on this decade's ballot. ``I don't
know, what is the smiley face of the '90s?'' she asked.
</P>
<P>
   It all depends on what you're looking for. It's easy to figure
out why we eventually fixate on or become nostalgic for objects or
ideas from a certain time period, said Swarthmore's Burke.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want things that exemplify a past lost to you,'' Burke
explained. ``Sometimes it's the earliest form of something. And the
most complicated thing is that which reminds you of where you were
personally at that time.''
</P>
<P>
   What's extraordinarily difficult, everyone agrees, is figuring
all this out ahead of time.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we could tell that in advance, we would all be rich,'' said
Tony Kirschner, a Western Maryland University assistant professor
of communications and expert on rock and popular music. ``The
things that become collectible later, or somehow `defining,' are
always from left field.''
</P>
<P>
   And while that might seem a fitting way to end the Instant
Speculation Decade (Remember the O.J. trial? Lewinskygate?), alas,
there's just no time.
</P>
<P>
   It's 1999, after all.
</P>
<P>
   Time to start summing up the next decade.
</P>
<P>
   _Jill Vejnoska is a staff writer for The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
