<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-31 17:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3903 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REVIEW-IMAX01-COX     12-31 0432
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-IMAX01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dinosaurs rage, story fades in IMAX's `T-Rex'
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Forty minutes is a strange running time for a movie. Long enough
to sketch in characters and a story, but not to develop them. Forty
minutes is more suited to a television ``Afterschool Special.''
</P>
<P>
   And that's how the new IMAX film ``T-Rex: Back to the
Cretaceous'' plays _ like an ``Afterschool Special'' with really,
really awesome special effects.
</P>
<P>
   Previous IMAX movies such as this summer's hit ``Everest'' and
other documentaries have been better suited to the shorter running
time. But ``T-Rex,'' which is fictional, takes too long revving up
its story and then isn't even sure what that story is. Then _ bang!
_ it's over.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the dinosaur lover(s) in your family will have
gotten what they came for, namely computer-generated thunder
lizards thrashing and stomping across an eight-story-tall movie
screen with a nearly 3-D intensity.
</P>
<P>
   Ally Hayden (Liz Stauber of ``Can't Hardly Wait'') is a budding
teenage paleontologist who wants nothing more than to go on a dig
with her dino-hunting dad (Peter Horton of Fox's
hanging-by-a-thread series ``Brimstone''). But he's too distracted,
so Ally hangs out back at the museum and mopes.
</P>
<P>
   Then Dad brings back what could be a dinosaur egg, which Ally
manages to crack accidentally the first time she's left alone with
it. Before you can reference ``Through the Looking Glass,'' she's
whirled back 65 million years and coming face to face with the big
beasts. What once were fossils are now living, breathing and
occasionally fighting dinosaurs, and pretty intense ones at that.
</P>
<P>
   Ally also time-travels back to the turn of the century for
run-ins with her real-life heroes, Barnum Brown, a famous dinosaur
digger, and Charles Knight, the scientist-artist most responsible
for our present view of how dinosaurs looked.
</P>
<P>
   And how is this multiple era-jumping accomplished? Don't ask.
``T-Rex'' is a little coy about it, but it appears to all just be
taking place in Ally's mind as a fantasy rather than really
happening.
</P>
<P>
   That isn't what kids want. We want a fantasy that purports to be
real, not a fantasy that appears to be just a hallucination. Even
an 80-foot-tall hallucination with discolored fangs.
</P>
<P>
   ``T-Rex: Back to the Cretaceous''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   40 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Big, but it could have been better.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Kloer writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-31-98 1722EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
