<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALLSTARS02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EMBARGOED UNTIL JANUARY 2
 &HT;    Growers pick top new garden plants for 1999
 &HT;    By Danny C. Flanders
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Just when you thought you'd made your last list of the
season, it's time to go shopping again.
</P>
<P>
   But forget the toys, clothing and electronics. It's time to
redirect your energy at the garden _ yes, in January, while you can
see the barren spots and make plans for dealing with them by
spring.
</P>
<P>
   Seed and plant catalogs are arriving daily, and if you're ready
to try something new but reliable among the array of spring- and
summer-blooming annuals and perennials, the All-America Selections
_ the Academy Awards for new plants _ are a good starting point.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're getting a very strong reaction to this year's winners,''
said Nona Koivula, executive director of the nonprofit organization
that annually tests never-marketed plants and selects a handful it
deems superior.
</P>
<P>
   This year's 12 winners, available now as seed by mail and in
spring as bedding plants at garden centers, include two Gold
Medals, the first the AAS has awarded in 10 years. And the winners
are . . . two zinnias, `Profusion Cherry' and `Profusion Orange'.
</P>
<P>
   ``We reserve the gold for what we call a breeding
breakthrough,'' Koivula said of the entries, grown in trial gardens
around the country and evaluated by a panel of unpaid judges.
``This is very unusual to have two.''
</P>
<P>
   The winners include five annuals, three perennials and four
fruits and vegetables _ a round zucchini squash called 'Eight
Ball'; an 8-ounce pumpkin, 'Wee-B-Little'; an elongated cherry
tomato that grows like grapes, 'Juliet'; and a bright orange
gourmet watermelon, 'New Queen.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the public is oblivious to these winners every year,
but they are unsurpassed for blooms, and disease and drought
resistance,'' said Becki Bowermeister of Hastings Nature &AMP; Garden
Center, who has worked at an AAS trial garden at the University of
Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Another resource for new plants is the National Garden Bureau, a
nonprofit organization that provides information on seeds and
bedding plants. (For information, call 630-963-0770.)
</P>
<P>
   But maybe ``new'' doesn't matter to you as much as reliability.
If so, the Perennial Plant Association, an international
professional organization of growers, retailers, landscapers,
educators and writers, has selected as its 1999 Plant of the Year
rudbeckia 'Goldsturm,' commonly known as black-eyed Susan. One of
the most popular perennials for the past 50 years, the
black-centered, golden-yellow flowers have become a staple in
commercial landscaping because of the plant's tolerance for drought
and clay soils, and resistance to insects and disease.
</P>
<P>
   The award can be presented to an old plant as well as a new one,
said the association's Steven Still.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some say why not pick something new,'' he said, ``while others
tell us to go for the tried-and-true.''
</P>
<P>
   The experts' advice? Shop for both. Go for what works _ but
experiment a little.
</P>
<P>
   Winning the gold:
</P>
<P>
   Zinnia `Profusion Orange', `Profusion Cherry'. Size: Flowers 2-3
inches. Exposure: Full sun. Judges: Tolerance to diseases such as
powdery mildew, bacterial leaf spot.
</P>
<P>
   Begonia 'Pin-Up Flame'
</P>
<P>
   Color: Large single flowers are yellow, edged in red-orange.
</P>
<P>
   Size: Bloom 2-4 inches.
</P>
<P>
   Exposure: Shade.
</P>
<P>
   Judges: A dramatic bicolor previously unavailable.
</P>
<P>
   Tritoma 'Flamenco' (Red-Hot Poker)
</P>
<P>
   Color: Creamy white, orange, yellow or red.
</P>
<P>
   Size: Stems up to 36 inches.
</P>
<P>
   Exposure: Sun.
</P>
<P>
   Judges: Each plant flowers the first year. Excellent cut
flowers.
</P>
<P>
   Marigold 'Bonanza Bolero' Color: Gold and red.
</P>
<P>
   Size: Large 2 1/4-inch double flowers.
</P>
<P>
   Exposure: Full sun.
</P>
<P>
   Judges: Irregular bicolor pattern. An early bloomer.
Osteospermum 'Passion Mix' Color: Pink, rose, purple or pure white.
</P>
<P>
   Size: Blooms 2-2 1/2 inches wide.
</P>
<P>
   Exposure: Full sun.
</P>
<P>
   Judges: Single daisylike flowers with azure centers. Relatively
pest free. Drought tolerant. Portulaca 'Sundial Peach' Color:
Glowing peach.
</P>
<P>
   Size: Blooms 2 inches wide.
</P>
<P>
   Exposure: Full sun.
</P>
<P>
   Judges: Larger blooms, more petals, great for containers.
Verbena 'Quartz Burgundy' Color: Deep wine-red with small white
eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Size: Large flower umbels.
</P>
<P>
   Exposure: Full sun.
</P>
<P>
   Judges: Blooms early and long. Mail-order sources: Park Seed
Co., 1-800-845-3369; Stokes Seeds, 1-800-263-7233; R.H. Shumway's,
803-663-9771. Danny Flanders writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
