<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DAY2-RESOLUTIONS02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Read up for fundamentals of fitness
 &HT;    By Lillian Lee Kim
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's Day Two of the Big Resolution, and you're determined to
keep it this time. So throw out the rest of the holiday sweets, put
on your sneakers and sweats, and . . . sit down and read a book.
</P>
<P>
   In all seriousness, you should educate yourself before you start
a diet and/or exercise program (preferably both, since they're more
effective in tandem). Reading books on the subject isn't an equal
substitute for consulting a nutritionist or a personal trainer, but
it's cheaper and will give you a head start on the fundamentals.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some tips on what to look for when you're at the
bookstore:
</P>
<P>
   Fitness books
</P>
<P>
   Ignore the covers; they're almost all cheesy. Many also have
self-indulgent
</P>
<P>
   photos of the author/celebrity working out at various ages, as a
sort of pictorial exercise autobiography.
</P>
<P>
   But it's all forgivable if the author has included large, clear
photos of basic strength and flexibility exercises, plus a
realistic week-by-week plan for gradually building up a workout
program that includes cardiovascular exercise.
</P>
<P>
   Some good books are:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Fitness for Dummies'' by Suzanne Schlosberg and Liz Neporent
(IDG Books Worldwide, $19.99). This member of the ``Dummies''
family provides a comprehensive overview of different fitness
programs and types of equipment, without the jargon many
workoutaholics throw around. It includes diagrams and explanations
of the major muscles of the body.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Let's Get Real!'' by Donna Richardson with Lauren David
Peden (Pocket Books, $16). Richardson, who stars in several fitness
videos, demonstrates plenty of exercises in her friendly, realistic
approach to getting physical. Like many fitness experts, she
presents a handful of her favorite recipes. Recognizing that most
of her readers aren't going to give up dining out, however, she
also includes a list of unhealthy and relatively healthy restaurant
dishes.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Firm for Life'' by Anna and Cynthia Benson (Broadway Books,
$23). The founders of the Firm, a hit video series that integrates
weight training and aerobics, include ``dos'' and ``don'ts'' for
proper form alongside each illustrated exercise.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Ultimate Workout Log'' by Suzanne Schlosberg (Houghton
Mifflin, $12). This 24-week exercise journal inspires and reminds.
Under each day heading there are spaces for noting cardiovascular
exercise, stretching and strength training. There's a chart showing
how many calories are burned per hour by various activities, and a
page for listing your personal exercise records.
</P>
<P>
   Diet books
</P>
<P>
   Finding a good diet or nutrition book can require a fair amount
of browsing, since diet philosophies vary widely. But a basic
reference is a calorie counter that breaks down foods by
nutritional content.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  One of the best is ``The Complete Book of Food Counts'' by
Corinne T. Netzer (Dell, $7.50). This book is alphabetically
arranged and includes brand-name foods. In addition to calories,
the guide lists protein, carbohydrates, fat, cholesterol, sodium
and fiber.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Ultimate Consumer's Guide to Diets and Nutrition'' by
James E. Marti with Dr. George L. Blackburn (Mariner Books, $16) is
a good introduction to dieting.
</P>
<P>
   The authors analyze more than 200 commercial weight-loss
programs, books and diet supplements, from Optifast to Weight
Watchers. The diets are categorized by their target audience, i.e.
women, children, diabetics, people with food allergies, people with
high blood pressure.
</P>
<P>
   As with exercise, recording your daily eating habits is an
excellent weight-control tool. Research has shown that people who
monitor their eating or exercise tend to be better at maintaining
their weight loss than people who don't record their habits.
Several fitness and diet books contain sample food diary pages, or
you can make up your own in a regular notebook or blank journal.
</P>
<P>
   Judy Helmold of Sandy Springs says her journal helped her lose
25 pounds last year. In addition to tracking her eating and
exercise habits, she records other issues in her life, such as
work-related stress, that might affect her motivation.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me it's a good analytical tool,'' said Helmold, who
started keeping a journal as part of Weight Watchers. ``Did I
exercise each day as I intended? If not, what got me off track?''
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't take much time, Helmold assures.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes you might have a sentence or two, sometimes half a
page,'' she said. ``Try it. You'll like it.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
