<HEADER>
A3910 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RIVER-RESTORE03-2TAKE     12-31 0830
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RIVER-RESTORE03-2TAKES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EMBARGOED UNTIL JANUARY 3
 &HT;    A project in a peaceful valley of Habersham County is restoring
part of the Soque River
 &HT;    By Charles Seabrook
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HABERSHAM COUNTY, Ga. _ For years, Justin Savage watched as the
tiny Soque River was literally gobbling up his farm in Habersham
County in northeast Georgia's mountains. ``I figured I was losing
60-100 tons of soil a year from erosion,'' says Savage.
</P>
<P>
   Over the decades, free-ranging cattle, poor plowing methods and
other harmful practices had stripped away trees and other
vegetation along the river's banks, making them highly vulnerable
to erosion. Channelization and dredging also had straightened out
curves in the river through his farm, causing water to rush at
greater force down the stream and scour away Savage's pastureland.
</P>
<P>
   In desperation, Savage in 1997 went to his regional Natural
Resources Conservation Service office for help. His timing was
fortunate, because the conservation service had just been contacted
by workers with the Upper Chattahoochee Riverkeeper, the U.S.
Environmental Protection Agency and others looking for a landowner
with an impaired stream on his property who would be willing to
participate in an ambitious project to restore the waterway.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was quite willing to participate; it was more than I hoped
for,'' says Savage.
</P>
<P>
   Now, more than a year after the restoration project began in the
peaceful Soque Valley of Habersham County, 1,500 feet of the
25-foot-wide Soque once again is a meandering waterway that runs
through _ instead of over _ Savage's farmland. Boulders and rocks
and tree stumps have been placed in and along the stream at
strategic spots to reduce the energy of the flowing water. The
stream banks have been stabilized by grass and thick mats made of a
biodegradable material. Native trees and other plants common to
stream banks in North Georgia are being planted to restore a
vegetative buffer.
</P>
<P>
   Erosion has been reduced. The stream is running clearer, and
trout, which require exceptionally clean water, are returning.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to bring this stream back to its natural condition
as much as possible,'' says Katherine Baer, who is helping conduct
the project for the Chattahoochee Riverkeeper. The Soque
(pronounced So-KEE) is a tributary of the Chattahoochee(GA.).
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to reduce erosion by reconfiguring the channel to a
natural shape and pattern, revegetating the banks and fencing
cattle away from the river,'' says Baer, noting the project is
being viewed as a model for easing erosion and preserving water
quality in headwater streams of North Georgia's mountains. ``In so
doing, we want to show people that severely degraded streams can be
restored and the water quality can be greatly improved.''
</P>
<P>
   Baer was hired by the Riverkeeper to help protect the many
headwater tributaries to the Chattahoochee in White, Habersham,
Lumpkin, Dawson, Forsyth and Hall counties. The work has direct
impact on metro Atlanta residents, whose drinking water originates
mostly in those counties.
</P>
<P>
   Not only does stream protection preserve a waterway's scenic
beauty and keep the water clean for fish and other aquatic life, it
can reduce metro Atlanta's costs of purifying the water for
drinking and industrial uses.
</P>
<P>
   The Soque project is one of about 90 EPA-sponsored river and
wetland restoration projects around the nation. So far, the Soque
restoration has cost about $80,000, most of which came from the
EPA. Those funds do not include free labor from community
volunteers and other support.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the restoration projects is different, because each
stream or wetland (including swamps and marshes) is not the same.
However, the aim of all the projects is to emulate a natural,
self-regulating river or wetland.
</P>
<P>
   The Soque winds and tumbles for more than 30 miles in Habersham
County before it joins the Chattahoochee. For most of its length,
the river is a scenic, fast-flowing mountain stream parallel to
Ga.197. Many Georgians and tourists have seen the Soque's beauty
from a balcony at the Mark of the Potter, a popular craft shop that
was once an old grist mill along Ga. 197. The Brigadoon lodge along
the river also is one of the most popular destinations in the South
for trout fly fishermen.
</P>
<P>
   Savage's farm is upstream, just below the Soque's headwaters.
The eroded soil that washes off his farm is transported downstream
along with other agricultural runoff. Restoring the 1,500-foot
corridor that runs through his property would also protect the
river downstream.
</P>
<P>
   But before the restoration could begin, the workers had to have
a concept of how the stretch of river should look and function
after the work was completed _ like a plastic surgeon who must have
a good idea of how his patient's nose will look and function after
a ``nose job.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   HABERSHAM COUNTY, Ga.: ``nose job.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A tremendous amount of background work was required,'' says
Jennifer Derby, a scientist in the Wetlands and Restoration
Planning Division of EPA's regional office in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   She and Baer studied several relatively undisturbed streams to
conceive an idea of what they should aim for on the Soque. In
particular, they scrutinized the crystal clear Duke's Creek as it
rushes and cascades through the state's Smithgall Woods preserve in
White County. Over the decades, Duke's Creek itself was the
beneficiary of a private, $20 million restoration effort by media
magnate Charles Smithgall, who later donated the property to the
state.
</P>
<P>
   Baer and Derby examined the widths and depths of Duke's Creek,
its meandering curves, and the sloping of its stream banks and
flood plains to determine how a stream establishes a natural
course. They examined what native vegetation grows along the stream
banks, and they scrutinized rocks and pebbles to see the natural
makeup of the stream bottom.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rivers, like energy, will follow the path of least resistance,
and thus a river is greatly influenced by the shape and texture
(width, depth, substrate) of its path,'' says Baer. She and Derby
took the knowledge gleaned from the other streams back to the
degraded stretch of the Soque on Savage's farm. With the help of
other stream experts and community volunteers, Baer and Derby
adjusted the width of the Soque from about 40 feet to 25 feet by
installing logs and rocks at key points in the river's path to help
dissipate its energy. They stabilized the stream banks with grass
and mats of a biodegradable material. Rocks and pebbles that would
be part of a natural stream were put on the bottom of the river
stretch.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps the most ambitious effort was to change the course
of the river as it ran through Savage's farm: Earth-moving
equipment was brought in to establish curves in the river and
eliminate its unnatural straight path. In so doing, the river's
energy was further dissipated, thereby lessening its capacity to
erode the stream banks.
</P>
<P>
   Not only are trout once again inhabiting the stretch of river,
but it is regaining its natural beauty.
</P>
<P>
   Still to come is the planting of several native species of trees
and plants to establish vegetative buffers on either side of the
river. Such buffers help control storm runoff, help prevent erosion
and filter out pollutants.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the restoration is not complete, important lessons
have been learned, says Derby. ``One lesson is that stream bank
restoration is costly,'' she says. Another lesson is that it takes
very little disturbance to upset a river system.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps the most important lesson of all, say the project's
leaders, is that prevention is the best medicine: Prevention of
pollution and degradation of rivers and streams in the first place
is far superior and cheaper than having to restore them.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
