<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EMBARGOED UNTIL JANUARY 2
 &HT;    Yes, Jesus was Jewish
 &HT;    By Gayle White
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _Over 2,000 years of spread and change, Christianity has
lost many of its ties to the Judaism of Jesus, says John D. Garr of
Chattanooga.
</P>
<P>
   Garr is founder and executive director of the Atlanta-based
Restoration Foundation, an organization founded to bring the church
back to its Jewish roots. It is one of several small pro-Israel
groups founded over the past 20 years that function on a
grass-roots level while big name religious leaders such as
broadcaster Pat Robertson and the Rev. Jerry Falwell make
headlines.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea is simply to bring back to Christian consciousness
the fact that Jesus was a Jew,'' said Garr, 54. He laughed. ``A lot
of people seem to think he was a Baptist.''
</P>
<P>
   Not only was he born Jewish, but Jesus practiced Judaism
throughout his life, Garr maintains.
</P>
<P>
   Because of Jesus' heritage, Christians have an obligation to
support Israel and the Jewish people, he said. Garr says he
recognizes that land in Israel is specified in God's covenant with
Abraham and plays a role in prophecy.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's definitely real estate involved in God's promises,''
he said, ``but how and when that works out is best left in God's
hand.''
</P>
<P>
   While Christians are obligated by their beliefs to witness their
faith to the Jews, Garr said, ``I find some people who love the
Jews but have a trophy mentality. It's like the moose head on the
wall if they convert one Jew.''
</P>
<P>
   Rather than focus on conversion, Garr said, he emphasizes
dialogue and interaction between Christians and Jews.
</P>
<P>
   And rather than support the Israeli government at all costs, he
says American Christians have an obligation to support both Jews
and Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think our position should be one of tolerance and support
for various people involved in the ongoing conflict,'' Garr said.
``When the Bible tells us to pray for peace in Jerusalem, that
means for everyone who's there.''
</P>
<P>
   Gayle White is a writer for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
