<HEADLINE>
MEDINA APPOINTED HEAD OF CALIF. STATE TRANSPORTATION DEPARTMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROBERT SALLADAY and RAY DELGADO  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ San Francisco Supervisor Jose Medina has
been appointed by Gov.-elect Gray Davis to head the California
State Transportation Department.
</P>
<P>
   Medina, 57, would take over the $6.4 billion-a-year agency at a
time when his political ally, San Francisco Mayor Willie Brown, is
fighting with the state over plans to place the new eastern section
of the Bay Bridge north of the current span.
</P>
<P>
   Brown wants the new bridge built to the south, so it won't
disrupt Treasure Island development, but Caltrans approved the
northern route Monday. Caltrans makes its formal decision in June,
which most likely will be followed by many lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   The $1.5 billion Bay Bridge project is Caltrans' biggest
endeavor, but Medina will soon have other responsibilities. At a
salary of $105,000 a year, he will supervise about 17,500 employees
and manage California's intricate and clogged transportation
system.
</P>
<P>
   Medina said he was honored to be working in the Davis
administration and would re-evaluate many of the projects on his
plate to fit with the new governor's visions. Medina said he had
not taken positions so far on many of the Bay Area's high-profile
and sometimes controversial transportation projects.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad that I can be part of his administration,'' Medina
said Wednesday night. ``My first priority is to sit down with Gray
Davis and go over his policies that he wants to implement. He wants
to take a common-sense approach to addressing transportation
issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis hailed Medina's experience in San Francisco politics and
transportation issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a San Francisco supervisor, he is no stranger to managing
infrastructure issues, and he understands the nexus between
transportation and the economy,'' Davis said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Some names were already surfacing as possible replacements for
Medina, including Police Commissioner Dennis Herrera and former
school board member Carlota del Portillo.
</P>
<P>
   Kandace Bender, the mayor's press secretary, said Brown was
happy for Medina but said he was unavailable for further comment.
</P>
<P>
   Medina, who was elected to the board in 1996 on his third try,
said he would meet with Brown Thursday to discuss his new job and
talk about a replacement. He also said he would strongly urge the
mayor to appoint a Latino to the board.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would want someone from the Latino community to fill my spot
because we certainly merit representation,'' he said, adding that
he was confident Brown would make such an appointment.
</P>
<P>
   Medina was quick to caution that just because he was a Brown
ally, that didn't mean the mayor would be calling the shots at
Caltrans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will be working for Gov. Gray Davis and implementing his
policies,'' Medina said. ``I'll be taking my direction from him.
But I will be sensitive to the needs of the city.''
</P>
<P>
   He said his new job in Sacramento would be an exciting challenge
but he was saddened to have to leave the city he had known for so
long.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get kind of mixed emotions,'' Medina said. ``I've raised a
family here, and my wife and I are very involved in city
government. We love this city. It's going to be hard to leave.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
