MOVIE-YEAR (Los Angeles) _ As national institutions go, Major
League Baseball and John Glenn were more impressive. But the movies
sure looked a lot better than, say, the national government in
1998, and that came as something of an unexpected surprise. (With
Top Ten picks of the year) By Bob Strauss. 
. 
FILM-YEAR (Los Angeles) _ During the gettin'-jiggy-with-it days of
1998, moviegoers kept trying to one-up themselves, and, in large
part, they succeeded. Blood and guts on Omaha Beach? Sign us up!
Private parts caught in a zipper? It hurts so good! A three-hour,
horrific tale of slavery starring our favorite television
personality? Um ... anyone want to see ``There's Something About
Mary'' again? (With Top Ten picks of the year.) By Glenn Whipp. 
. 
MUSIC-YEAR (Los Angeles) _ It was the year teen-age girls raised
the Titantic. Not only did the film break all box-office records,
the ``Titantic'' soundtrack _ spearheaded by the Celine Dion-sung
love theme ``My Heart Will Go On'' _ was the year's biggest seller.
By Fred Shuster. 
. 
TV-YEAR (Los Angeles) _ 1998 was the worst season in the history of
television. No, wait, 1997 was. Or next year will be. Every year,
naysayers complain about the quality of television. But, like
everything else there was good and bad in television. By Keith
Marder. 
. 
VANGOGH-FILM (Los Angeles) _ Madman? Genius? Tyrant? As a preview
to this month's opening of the ``Van Gogh's Van Goghs'' exhibit,
Los Angeles County Museum of Art's film department is hosting a
three-night Van Gogh series of motion pictures that look at him
from different angles. By Bob BcCarthy. 
. 
DISCS-MUSIC (Los Angeles) _ Herbie Hancocks's ``The Complete Blue
Note Sixties Sessions,'' is a thorough six-CD archive that finds
him in the first flush of his solo career in the '60s, when he cut
such sophisticated and highly rated hard-bop tunes as ``Maiden
Voyage,'' ``Dolphin Dance,'' ``Cantaloupe Island'' and ``Watermelon
Man.'' By Fred Shuster. 
. 
SIGHT-VIDEO (Los Angeles) _ Unfortunately, ``Out of Sight'' was
just that to most filmgoers when it was in theaters. The
comedy/crime caper is now landing on many critic's top-10 lists for
the year, and you'll have a chance to catch it on video starting
Tuesday. By Rob Lowman. 
. 

