<HEADLINE>
THE TINKERERS NEVER REST  
 `FABULOUS' IS MOVING  
 A DATE WITH DESTINY  
 ALONG THE WAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JESSE MCKINLEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Take two long weekends, add a couple of libational
holidays and stir in a little icy weather, and you've got a recipe
for the near hibernation evidenced in Broadway's corridors of power
this week.
</P>
<P>
   All across town, agents' offices were closed, producers were
away and the masters of spin were finding exciting new ways to fill
time.
</P>
<P>
   ``My office is the cleanest it has ever been,'' said Chris
Boneau of Boneau/Bryan-Brown, the theatrical publicity agency.
``And it's usually pretty clean.''
</P>
<P>
   Even actors were getting time off. At the Cort Theater, the cast
and crew of ``The Blue Room'' had scheduled four whole days off
last week, apparently in line with the desire of the cast (read
Nicole Kidman) to spend Christmas with family (read Tom Cruise and
their children).
</P>
<P>
   Still, if a sense of ennui was creeping in at home, in the
hinterlands, some intense tinkering was under way on a couple of
Broadway-bound revivals.
</P>
<P>
   In St. Louis, at the 4,500-seat Fox Theater, the cast of
``You're a Good Man, Charlie Brown'' began its final tryout run on
Wednesday before beginning performances at the Ambassador Theater
on Jan. 23.
</P>
<P>
   The musical's book, based on the ``Peanuts'' comic strips by
Charles Schulz, has been substantially rewritten since the first
tryout in late November in Skokie, Ill., with dated dialogue giving
way to new material culled from the cartoons by Michael Mayer, the
director.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was being more cautious early on to try to preserve a larger
percentage of the original,'' Mayer said. ``But I've found more
encouragement from the audience to rethink the material.''
</P>
<P>
   Mayer said he'd also minded some of the advice of critics, whose
reviews have been generally positive but who have quibbled over the
show's structure. To counter this, Mayer has added two new songs,
revamped arrangements and provided a new ending to Act 1 _ all
during the out-of-town run.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I've aged a little,'' Mayer, 38, said with a laugh.
``This cute little six-character musical has been a monster.'' He
added, ``In the best way, of course.''
</P>
<P>
   (The show's producing team has also changed. Columbia Artists
Management, a producer on the recent off-Broadway flop
``Trainspotting,'' has scaled back its financial stake in the $3
million production, leaving Michael Leavitt, executive producer of
Fox Theatricals, Fox itself and the clothing magnate Jerry Frankel
as majority partners. Jim Byk, a spokesman for the show, said the
full $3 million remained in place.)
</P>
<P>
   At the Kennedy Center in Washington, meanwhile, another revival
with a revamped script, ``Annie Get Your Gun,'' started its tryout
on Tuesday night. Gone are many of the embarrassingly off-color
references to ``Injuns,'' with new lines written by the Broadway
veteran Peter Stone.
</P>
<P>
   ``It went well,'' Stone said on Wednesday, sounding a bit
amazed. `'Surprisingly well.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that everything's perfect. ``There are jokes that don't work
yet,'' he said. ``Or will never work.''
</P>
<P>
   Stone said the show _ now two hours and 45 minutes _ needed some
trimming. Lloyd Rose, the chief theater critic of The Washington
Post, is scheduled to evaluate the production this week.
</P>
<P>
   As rocky as the road to Broadway might sometimes be, Stone said
he'd been schooled by his experiences with the rough early days of
``Titanic,'' which had no regional run. ``You're always in trouble
out of town, and we've had our share,'' he said. ``But the trouble
of not going out of town is greater.''
</P>
<P>
   `Fabulous' Is Moving
</P>
<P>
   One Off-Broadway cast received good (OK, fabulous) news this
week.
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 29, Paul Rudnick's comedy ``The Most Fabulous Story Ever
Told'' will transfer from the New York Theater Workshop to the
Minetta Lane Theater for an open-ended commercial run. Scott Rudin
will lead a consortium of six producers.
</P>
<P>
   The Minetta Lane was the home of Rudnick's last commercial run,
with ``Jeffrey,'' in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a lifetime fan of the Minetta Lane,'' Rudnick said. ``I
know where everything is. I know how to sneak backstage. I know
where the bathrooms are.''
</P>
<P>
   The production, which tells the story of two gay couples from
the Creation to modern-day Chelsea, will likely have the same cast
as at the Workshop, where it finishes Jan. 10.
</P>
<P>
   The script, however, may be ever-so-slightly different.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still tinkering a little bit,'' Rudnick said. ``I have a
deeply neurotic theory of comedy.''
</P>
<P>
   A Date With Destiny
</P>
<P>
   When ``Wit'' formally reopens at the Union Square Theater on
Thursday, Derek Anson Jones, the show's director, will have a date
with Margaret Edson, who wrote the play.
</P>
<P>
   It won't be the first time. Indeed, this creative friendship is
one that dates back all the way to ... the prom! And beyond.
</P>
<P>
   ``We met in seventh grade,'' Jones said. ``She was like this
major junior high impresario and I was this lowly actor.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Edson remembers it differently. ``He had this little tiny
part in `The Miracle Worker,''' she said. ``But I was doing props.
I didn't even have a part.''
</P>
<P>
   The time was 1974 and the place was the Sidwell Friends School
in Washington, the private school that was the recent scholastic
home of Chelsea Clinton. Ms. Edson and Jones bonded, and soon
became close friends. ``Both of us were very into individual
expression,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   So when prom time rolled around in 1979, the two decided to go
together. ``It's not like anybody else asked us,'' Ms. Edson said.
</P>
<P>
   Like any other important evening, there were snags.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maggie was _ and continues to be _ a head taller than me,''
Jones said. So in the requisite pictures, she went barefoot.
</P>
<P>
   After high school, the two remained close and in 1991 did a
reading of ``Wit'' at Ms. Edson's mother's house in Washington,
with Jones playing the role of the sick professor now portrayed by
Kathleen Chalfant. It was that reading that eventually led to the
Union Square Theater.
</P>
<P>
   The two friends stay in close touch, though Ms. Edson has moved
to Atlanta (where she lives with her partner ) while Jones now
lives in Brooklyn (with his).
</P>
<P>
   ``I was heartbroken when she moved down there,'' Jones said.
``But she's still one of my constants.''
</P>
<P>
   Along the Way
</P>
<P>
   _ ``All Under Heaven,'' Valerie Harper's one-woman look at Pearl
Buck, will close on Jan. 11 at the Century Center for the
Performing Arts.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``A Majority of One,'' a surprise hit on Broadway in 1959,
will be the second production of the season for the Jewish
Repertory Theater. Performances begin on Jan. 16.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
