<SLUG> BC-SIGHT-VIDEO-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIME TO KEEP `OUT OF SIGHT' IN MIND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROB LOWMAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Unfortunately, ``Out of Sight'' was just that to
most filmgoers when it was in theaters. The Steven Soderbergh film
was released during the summer blockbuster season and found itself
overshadowed by the likes of ``Armageddon.''
</P>
<P>
   But unlike the meteor disaster flicks, the film noir/romantic
comedy/crime caper is now landing on many critics top-10 lists for
the year and was named best film of 1998 by the Boston Film Critics
Society. But if you missed ``Out of Sight'' (Universal) in the
theater, you'll have a chance to catch it on video starting
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Based on the Elmore Leonard book, ``Out of Sight'' is more about
its characters than about the shoot-'em-up stuff. Nevertheless,
screenwriter Scott Frank, who already adapted another Leonard novel
(``Get Shorty''), and Soderbergh keep the story of bank robber Jack
Foley (George Clooney) flowing.
</P>
<P>
   Foley, after a misstep, finds himself in prison. There he
engineers a prison break that goes awry, and he finds himself in
the trunk of a getaway car with a sexy federal marshal, Karen Sisco
(Jennifer Lopez), he has taken hostage. Despite being on opposite
sides of the law, the attraction is immediate. It's an erotically
charged scene as Clooney snuggles up against Lopez within the
confines of the trunk, his fingers lingering on her thigh.
</P>
<P>
   Later, when the meet up at a hotel, a little boyish wave from
Jack is all it takes to trigger their eventual, well, you know. The
fun, however, is getting there.
</P>
<P>
   Clooney and Lopez have a sexy screen chemistry _ in an adult way
_ that is hard to create. ``Out of Sight'' also benefits from a
terrific supporting cast who bring to life Leonard's bizarre
characters, including Ving Rhames as Jack's partner, a man with a
conscience; Don Cheadle as a vicious ex-prizefighter named Snoopy;
Albert Brooks as a Michael Milken-ish financier; Dennis Farina as
Karen's dad, a retired cop who gives his daughter a gun for her
birthday; and Nancy Allen as Brooks' mistress/housekeeper.
</P>
<P>
   So even if you missed ``Out of Sight'' at the theaters, it will
probably be on your list of top videos in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   LOOSE ENDS: It seems like 1998 was just yesterday. So before we
forget and move on, here are a few noted releases that came out at
the end of last year.
</P>
<P>
   On the DVD front, Warner Bros. has delved into its vaults and
released two classics, ``My Fair Lady'' and ``Mister Roberts.''
Lovers of musicals will delight in the colorful ``Lady,'' which
sparkles in the digital format. Directed by the legendary George
Cukor, ``My Fair Lady'' took home eight Oscars and boasted a lovely
cast of Audrey Hepburn, Rex Harrison, Stanley Holloway and Wilfrid
Hyde-White. The DVD version includes a feature-length audio
commentary from those who worked on the 1964 film, notably Marni
Nixon, who was the singing voice for Hepburn; a behind-the-scenes
documentary; and two takes of Hepburn singing the songs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mister Roberts'' netted a Best Supporting Actor Oscar for Jack
Lemmon, but the World War II tale of the cargo ship USS Reluctant
had a high-powered cast. Henry Fonda, reprising his Tony
Award-winning performance on Broadway, played Lt. Doug Roberts, who
was dying to leave the backwaters of the war for the front lines.
James Cagney was his stodgy, by-the-book captain, and William
Powell played his last role as world-weary Doc.
</P>
<P>
   The DVD includes an audio commentary by Lemmon, who played
Ensign Pulver, and excerpts from a documentary on Fonda about his
involvement with the film. Directed by two Hollywood heavyweights,
John Ford and Mervyn Leroy, ``Roberts'' is stagey and cramped, but
it's meant to be a crowd pleaser and often is. &QL; 
ENDIT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-31-98 1748EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
