<HEADER>
A3989 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PBP-GO-SMOKE01     12-31 0758
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PBP-GO-SMOKE01 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Veteran's push to smoke indoors draws fire
 &HT;    By Dan Moffett
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ A Palm Beach County planner who is
demanding permission to smoke in his workplace has health
professionals fuming over what they regard as a bad idea.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Holloway can find better ways to relieve the post-traumatic
stress he has suffered since the Vietnam War, they say.
</P>
<P>
   Prominent among the opposition is the psychiatrist who treated
Holloway at the Veterans Affairs Medical Center in West Palm Beach.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing I have been quoted as saying in any way condones or
supports smoking on the job,'' Dr. Frederick Leppien, of the
Veterans Affairs Medical Center in West Palm Beach, said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Holloway, 54, has offered county officials a letter written by
Leppien as evidence that because of his stress, his fear of
harassment and his tendency to startle easily, he should be
permitted to light up inside his office building. But the letter
makes no mention of smoking and argues only that Holloway be given
an ``area to work in relative privacy.''
</P>
<P>
   While refusing to discuss the Holloway case specifically because
of patient-physician confidentiality, Leppien says it is his
practice to encourage smokers to quit _ not to continue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I refer patients to the smoking cessation program we have here
(at the VA hospital),'' Leppien said. ``We have group therapy. We
have medications. We have alternative methods of stress control. We
have many weapons _ many tricks up our sleeves.''
</P>
<P>
   None of them, Leppien says, involves telling people to smoke to
treat their psychiatric ills.
</P>
<P>
   A health policy planner for nine years, Holloway suffers from
skin and prostate cancer besides the post-traumatic stress. He
wants the county to make an exception to its 1993 rule that follows
the Florida Clean Indoor Air Act and seeks to move all smoking at
government buildings outside.
</P>
<P>
   Holloway says he will be subjected to the harassment of
nonsmokers if he is required to smoke outdoors.
</P>
<P>
   Medical professionals aren't buying it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll try to respond to this without expletives,'' said Dr.
John Hildreth, former president of the American Heart Association
in Florida. ``He needs to take his smoking out the door.''
</P>
<P>
   Cynthia Vallo, director of disease prevention programs for the
American Lung Society in Palm Beach County, believes too much
progress has been made in cleaning the air to take a step backward.
</P>
<P>
   ``We keep getting more and more information about the problems
that second-hand smoke causes,'' Vallo said. ``Smoke doesn't know
to stay in one particular part of a building. There's no reason to
expose other people to his health hazard.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Holly Hadley, a primary care physician in Jupiter, believes
Holloway's arguments are ``unsupportable and inappropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think you can make special exceptions for people to
smoke inside just because they don't like the glances they get
outside,'' Hadley said.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Thomas Kosten, president of the American Academy of
Addiction Psychiatry in Prairie Village, Kan., said it is possible
to treat post-traumatic stress and nicotine addiction
simultaneously with medication.
</P>
<P>
   ``Zyban, for example, is an antidepressant that can be used to
help people quit smoking,'' Kosten said. ``Smoking and
post-traumatic stress are difficult problems that often go
hand-in-hand. But you can work on them at the same time.''
</P>
<P>
   Leppien, himself a Vietnam veteran who served in the Army for 10
years, says he has treated hundreds of post-traumatic stress
patients in the last decade. He believes in treating addictions and
anxieties together.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, I take the total package approach,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Holloway has one supporter in a high place _ the 12th floor to
be exact, county Commissioner Carol Roberts.
</P>
<P>
   An unrepentant smoker, Roberts is known to enjoy her cigarettes
in her office and has expressed empathy for Holloway's position.
What to do about Roberts' transgression of county rules is
something no one is eager or fully prepared to address.
</P>
<P>
   ``Smoking in the building is a violation of policy and that
would be something the county administration would deal with,''
said Howard J. Falcon III, an assistant county attorney. ``We
wouldn't be involved in that.''
</P>
<P>
   As commissioner, Roberts is a ranking and elected part of that
county administration. Perhaps she would have to order herself to
stop.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
