<HEADER>
A3992 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-1998-DOW01-COX     12-31 0733
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-1998-DOW01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Big stocks post big gains
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The stock market ended a year of volatile trading on
Thursday, having rebounded from its worst sell-off in eight years
to post record-setting gains.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts cautioned, however, an historic fourth straight year of
high, double-digit growth for two major stock indexes failed to
reflect the weakness of a market deeply divided between big winners
and smaller losers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The U.S. stock market was nowhere near as strong as the gains
of the big-cap averages and Internet stocks indicate,'' said
analyst Michael Flament of Wright Investors' Service.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, two of the indexes by which markets are commonly
measured recorded their fourth straight year of 20 percent-plus
annual growth: 39.6 percent for the technology-loaded Nasdaq
composite and 26.7 percent for the diversified Standard &AMP; Poor's
500.
</P>
<P>
   And while the benchmark Dow Jones industrial average failed to
match that record, its gain of 16.1 percent would be regarded as
impressive any other time in market history.
</P>
<P>
   But the Russell 2000 index of smaller-capitalized stocks
declined 3.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Big stocks, with their proven track record, were attractive to
safety-conscious domestic and foreign investors in a nervous market
last year, explained A.G. Edwards &AMP; Sons strategist Anthony
O'Bryan.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the year's dichotomy in stock performance, O'Bryan said
1998 was ``certainly not a bad year.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody is complaining, since so few expected the market to go
up this much,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   By any standard, 1998 was an historic year, an amalgam of
foreign economic weakness and domestic strength, minimal inflation,
falling interest rates, declining bond yields, robust consumer
spending and the biggest corporate mergers on record.
</P>
<P>
   The downside was marked by the first decline in corporate
profits since 1991, during the third quarter. This was followed by
a host of warnings by companies of continued profit weakness in the
final quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eight of the 30 companies in the Dow Jones industrials have
pre-announced a shortfall in fourth-quarter 1998 expectations,''
said Charles L. Hill, research director of Boston-based First Call,
which tracks analysts' earnings estimates.
</P>
<P>
   Probably the most surprising events were the impeachment of
President Clinton and the related shrinking of Republican power in
Congress. So far, neither event has hurt the market.
</P>
<P>
   Neither did the resumption of air strikes against Iraq for
failing to cooperate with U.N.-mandated arms inspections.
</P>
<P>
   But foreign events generally dominated Wall Street's attention
this year, and it was Russia's debt default and currency
devaluation that triggered the biggest stock market correction
since 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Small in and of itself, that event came on top of accumulated
global distress. And in the presence of a frothy stock market, it
accelerated the decline of an already falling market. On its worst
day, Aug. 31, the Dow lost 513 points.
</P>
<P>
   While the Dow declined just short of 20 percent during the
correction, the Nasdaq composite dropped 30 percent and a majority
of all stocks dropped more than 20 percent _ prompting some
analysts to call it a bear market.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Reserve, concerned about the turn of events, ended
the correction by cutting interest rates on Sept. 29. That restored
investor confidence that the economy would not suffer a recession
and renewed hopes of future profit growth.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly thereafter, the market posted a spectacular rally that
gained momentum when the Fed cut interest rates again in October
and in November.
</P>
<P>
   The late rally left Wall Street gurus with a dilemma, however.
It restored the high stock market valuations they had feared so
much prior to the correction.
</P>
<P>
   Many analysts think the high prices in relation to earnings
makes the market vulnerable to a sell-off in 1999, although few
anticipate one as steep as last summer's 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson-Humphrey strategist Robert S. Robbins assigns only a
50-50 chance the Dow will suffer a correction of as much as 9
percent to 11 percent in the year ahead. He and most analysts are
confident the bull market will continue in the year ahead against
the backdrop of a slowing, but recession-free economy.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
