   &UR; NATIONAL-GENERAL &LR;  (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   GRAHAM-SUCCESSOR (Undated) _ At the turn of the new century,
with Billy Graham now 80, the question arises who, if anyone, can
take his place. A look at the potential successors. By Laurie
Goodstein and Gustav Niebuhr.
</P>
<P>
   DANCE-BALLROOM (State College, Pa.) _ The e-mail messages
arrived first in a trickle, then in a flood. Students at the
Pennsylvania State University were contacting their president,
Graham Spanier, with a desperate plea. Nearly 1,500 undergraduates
were languishing on waiting lists to learn how to cha-cha and fox
trot. By Ethan Bronner.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (Will move in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BELL-AIRTOUCH (New York) _ Bell Atlantic Corp., already in the
midst of a huge merger with GTE Corp., reportedly is nearing a $45
billion takeover of AirTouch Communications Inc., the nation's
second-largest cellular phone company.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETS-QUARTER (New York) _ It was a time when words like
``Technology'' and ``Internet'' were synonymous with almost instant
paper wealth. It was a time when the stock market staged as abrupt
and stunning a turnaround as any in recent memory. It was the final
three months of 1998, a three-month period that left many
professionals rubbing their eyes in disbelief. By Kenneth N.
Gilpin.
</P>
<P>
   With a graphic.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
