<SLUG> BC-MILLENNIUM-EVE2-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILLENNIUM FANATICS ALREADY MAKING EVE PLANS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Fixes copyright line)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MACQUARRIE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Before you forget this New Year's Eve _ or try to remember it,
for that matter _ put your party hat back on and start cogitating.
The turn of the cosmic odometer to the year 2000 has already
spurred a mind-jarring panoply of plans for global one-upmanship.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the fact that the third millennium does not officially
begin until Jan. 1, 2001, the serious groundwork is being laid for
next Dec. 31 _ when once-in-a-lifetime celebrations from the Fiji
Islands to Faneuil Hall will welcome in the next thousand years.
</P>
<P>
   So dust off those cobwebs and get to it. Travel agents say the
time to start planning is now.
</P>
<P>
   ``If people are thinking about going anywhere, they should call
us soon, even Monday,'' said Michael Sprague, director of leisure
sales for Garber Travel.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the urgency, Sprague said, is that once airlines begin
booking for New Year's Eve destinations, the seats are expected to
sell quickly. And even though many of those reservations cannot be
made until February, Sprague added, hotel and land packages can and
should be explored before then.
</P>
<P>
   The possibilities are limited only by the size of one's budget.
The Ritz-Carlton Hotel in Boston has tentatively booked a
four-night stay in its presidential suite for $100,000, an Air
France Concorde will take revelers around the world for $42,900,
and an Australian resort near the Great Barrier Reef will give the
well-heeled a bed for $4,000 per person.
</P>
<P>
   And if you know Mike Gauthier of Libertyville, Ill. _ and even
if you don't _ an Internet invitation beckons one and all to drop
by his home starting at 9 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Unless someone believes that the millennium will trigger the end
of the world, next New Year's Eve should stride toward midnight
much like any other. But don't tell that to the 3 million people
who are expected in Boston to celebrate a weekend-long First Night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Round numbers are very poetic numbers,'' said David Kessler,
executive administrator for the Center for Millennial Studies at
Boston University. ``A poet does not speak about 573 years. A poet
speaks about 1,000 years, a millennium _ and people listen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Round numbers have power over our imaginations. They're very
pregnant, and they're also very vague. You can attach just about
anything to them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   What most hoteliers and restaurateurs will attach to 2000 is big
dollar signs. Many of Boston's upscale destinations have yet to
decide what their millennium experience will cost, preferring
instead for competitors to ``set the bar'' for price and amenities,
according to Pat Moscaritolo, executive director of the Greater
Boston Convention &AMP; Visitors Bureau.
</P>
<P>
   One premier Boston setting that has taken a wait-and-see stance
is the Top of the Hub, where general manager Raphael Oliver already
is stockpiling champagne that he expects to become scarcer and more
expensive as 1999 rolls along.
</P>
<P>
   Even the band he booked for Thursday night wants five times as
much for next New Year's Eve, Oliver said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope I can work something out in conjunction with a city
event,'' Oliver said. ``I've called the Bay Tower Room, Boston
Harbor Hotel and the Meridien about their plans. They had no idea
yet, but they knew it would be breathtaking.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the snags in making early plans is airline availability.
Sprague, of Garber Travel, said that airlines generally will not
take reservations for next New Year's Eve until mid-February. So,
unless one is willing to roll the dice and guarantee a land package
without an airline reservation, the booking crunch will not occur
for about six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   But when it does, tourism officials expect airline seats to go
fast. The crush ``may be like when the rock stars come in and
tickets go on sale,'' Moscaritolo predicted.
</P>
<P>
   Sprague advised travelers to call their agents next week, chat
about possibilities, and add their names to waiting lists for
airline reservations.
</P>
<P>
   The options are boundless. The Sheraton in Fiji, for example, is
touting a chance to be among the first human beings to usher in the
millennium. Limited to 100 people, the experience begins at the
resort with a lunch brunch on Dec. 31, a special charter flight to
the island of Rambi, and a cruise aboard a ``circus boat'' that
will cross the international date line, or 180th meridian, exactly
at midnight.
</P>
<P>
   The Pyramids in Egypt also will be host to a party, as will
Times Square in New York, of course, where 1 million people are
expected to watch the famous ball drop in a celebration broadcast
around the world.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest festival may unfold in the low desert in the extreme
southeastern corner of California. There, according to Party 2000
co-founder Michael Johnson, 2.5 million people from around the
globe are predicted to turn 5 square miles ``in the middle of
nowhere'' into one of the American West's largest cities for five
days.
</P>
<P>
   As many as 40 of the world's top bands have been invited,
Johnson said, to provide 18-hours-a-day entertainment on five of
the largest stages ever built for a single event.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is we are putting this together so that when
people leave Party 2000 on Jan. 1, they'll know that they have been
at the party of the world,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   The options are also human-scale. On a list of millennium
parties compiled on the Internet, a group of South Africans is
inviting people to join a desert camping trip. ``Detail of the
exact longitude and latitude will follow shortly,'' the listing
reads. ``Bring lots of water. It's going to be VERY HOT.''
</P>
<P>
   Most millennium planning is geared toward the festive, but 4
million tourists and pilgrims are expected in the Holy Land next
year. And 13 million travelers are predicted to visit Rome in what
Pope John Paul II has declared to be a Jubilee Year.
</P>
<P>
   One thousand years ago, many Christians in Western Europe are
believed to have watched the approach of the millennium with dread.
The Apocalypse is associated with the millennium for many, and the
end of the world was considered a real possibility for them in the
year 1000.
</P>
<P>
   Scattered predictions of global catastrophe also have surfaced
for the year 2000. But the ancient images of the Four Horsemen of
the Apocalypse have been replaced for many people by the
possibility of a Y2K computer meltdown.
</P>
<P>
   Raucous or religious, the next New Year's Eve promises to be
indelibly memorable. And to some thinking, it could carry some
weight for the hereafter.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, Millennial Center director Richard Landes
interviewed a man who has claimed space on Jerusalem's Mount of
Olives in preparation for the millennium.
</P>
<P>
   If the world is about to end, the man was asked, why do you need
to be in Jerusalem instead of anywhere else on the globe? The
response: ``If I want to get up to the top floor of a building, I'm
going to stand in front of the elevator.''
</P>
<P>
   In retrospect, cancel those tickets to Fiji.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-31-98 1824EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
