<HEADLINE>
EUROPEAN UNION INTRODUCES SINGLE CURRENCY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (i and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ The most ambitious effort yet to create a united states
of Europe began at midnight Thursday when the euro, the continent's
new single currency, was born in 11 of the European Union's 15
countries.
</P>
<P>
   Although officially launched Friday, the euro will begin its
maiden voyage through the computers of European banks and
corporations on Monday, when all businesses start trading in it and
bank and credit card transactions can be recorded in it.
</P>
<P>
   Euro coins and bills will not begin to circulate until Jan. 1,
2002. Six months later, national currencies become void.
</P>
<P>
   The birth of the euro was celebrated Thursday at the European
Union's headquarters in Brussels in a display that mixed the
solemnity of a corporate board meeting with the festiveness of a
Super Bowl halftime show. After the finance ministers from the 11
countries formally locked their currencies together and made
speeches about the historic nature of the day, schoolchildren
released thousands of blue balloons with the ``e'' symbol that will
represent the new currency.
</P>
<P>
   Over the weekend, some 50,000 financial service specialists
across Europe will work around the clock to ready computer systems
for the changeover before the markets open Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
   The raison d'etre for monetary union is strength in numbers by
consolidating separate economies into a huge, competitive market.
Exchange rate fluctuations disappear. Manufacturers and retailers
are forced to simplify byzantine pricing, where the amount paid for
the same product can vary wildly from country to country. Trading
across national borders becomes easier. Mergers, once uncommon in
Europe, increase as former rivals seek to cut overhead and
capitalize on the new market.
</P>
<P>
   From Ireland to Italy, the euro has suddenly become a reality.
Monetary union is now the ultimate challenge for some 290 million
Europeans who must put aside language and cultural differences to
form one cohesive economic and political bloc.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Ireland and Italy, the euro became the official currency
today in Austria, Spain, Portugal, France, Germany, Finland,
Luxembourg, Belgium, and the Netherlands. Greece wanted to be among
those launching the euro but was unable to reduce its debt and
interest rates enough to qualify for membership. Three other
countries _ Britain, Sweden, and Denmark _ chose not to participate
largely because of concerns about loss of monetary control.
</P>
<P>
   But in other parts of Europe, the euro is already part of the
landscape. In Paris, open-air markets post prices of produce in
euros and francs. Fashionable restaurants from Barcelona to Vienna
have included euro prices on their menu for months.
</P>
<P>
   Adrian Lyons is one of those whose life changed irrevocably at
midnight. On Monday, when he arrives at his Allied Irish Bank
office in Dublin, he will turn on his computer terminal and begin a
new career as a euro banker.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a whole new world,'' said Lyons, who seems more excited
than intimidated by the most sweeping change in European daily life
since the end of World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Like everyone else who works in the financial services industry
in Europe, Lyons has trained to handle the new currency. But he
believes that the change is more historic than commercial. ``We're
all champing at the bit to get going,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While the euro will consume Lyons's professional life, his wife,
Denise, will barely notice its integration into daily life over the
next three years, except when she is handed a receipt at their
local supermarket listing what she spends in both Irish punts and
euros.
</P>
<P>
   The introduction of the euro is meant to cement European
integration, which has solidified incrementally over the last 40
years. But it also has unwittingly illustrated national differences
that cannot simply be wished away.
</P>
<P>
   The Portuguese, for example, complained bitterly when the
initial image of the continent minted on the euro coin didn't show
their border with Spain. While the European Central Bank relented
and minted a new coin, the euro is meant nonetheless to blur
economic, political, and, perhaps most importantly, psychological
borders within Europe.
</P>
<P>
   The integration process began in 1958, when the visionary French
diplomat Jean Monnet dreamed up the European Economic Community,
later to become the European Union, to create a single economic
bloc to rival the United States and Asia.
</P>
<P>
   But Monnet's plan was not just about money. It was also about
ending war among Europeans. Monnet's plan was to replace the narrow
and often belligerent nationalism that had pervaded the continent
with a more enlightened form of regionalism based on mutual
interest.
</P>
<P>
   The pragmatism of Monnet and the other founders of a united
Europe was born in part from the suffering endured on a continent
that has crumbled twice this century from world wars. ``You can't
eat a flag,'' said John Hume, the Nobel Peace laureate from
Northern Ireland who is among the most enthusiastic of Europeans.
</P>
<P>
   In exchange for membership in this new economic bloc, the 11
countries have ceded one of the core powers of the modern nation:
the ability to set interest rates and monetary policy. Those
decisions are now the domain of the European Central Bank based in
Frankfurt.
</P>
<P>
   Some worry that the single currency will further balkanize rich
and poor parts of Europe rather than spread the wealth around. As
in the United States, recession here is regional. Northern Europe
is faring better than the south.
</P>
<P>
   The two countries on the peripheries of Euroland, Ireland and
Italy, offer an illustration. Despite having just 3.5 million
people, the Republic of Ireland is second only to the United States
in its exports of software, and it has been Europe's most vibrant
economy for several years. Italy barely qualified for monetary
union because of a lagging economy that suffers from 12 percent
unemployment and an undereducated work force.
</P>
<P>
   Financial analysts also worry about Italy's ability to maintain
the discipline necessary to survive in the new euro club. Budget
deficits, for example, are to run no higher than 3 percent of a
country's gross domestic product. Less than three months before the
single currency was launched, Massimo D'Alema became Italy's prime
minister _ the first former communist to lead a Western European
government. At issue is whether he has the political will to keep
public spending such as social welfare programs in line with the
strictures of monetary union.
</P>
<P>
   Questions also surround the two engines that have traditionally
driven European integration: Germany and France. Both countries are
now led by leftist governments that have not moved to slash the
generous benefits from their workers. In Germany, for example, many
workers receive six weeks of vacation each year. And their French
counterparts are notorious for striking at the slightest
provocation.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts within both countries and elsewhere emphasize that
Germany and France, like Italy, must wring concessions from the
public sector to foster the necessary austerity.
</P>
<P>
   Doomsayers warn that Germany's record 11 percent unemployment
rate could get worse if the new government doesn't win concessions
from workers. They fear a strike to end all strikes if France is
forced to tighten its belt to conform with the requirements of
monetary union. Such concerns explain, in part, the wariness of
Britain about the euro.
</P>
<P>
   The debate over the future path of Britain, Europe's second most
populous country after Germany, is only beginning. The incipient
public relations battle between those who want to join, such as
Prime Minister Tony Blair, and those who don't, like former prime
minister Margaret Thatcher, is expected to cost more than any
political campaign in British history. Thatcher, a ``Euroskeptic,''
speaks for many when she equates integration with surrender of
British sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
   The ceding of their national currencies is indeed the most
visceral gesture to date that Europeans have made toward closer
integration. Like the language one speaks, the money one carries
has always separated one European from another. Germans, for
example, feel nostalgic about the deutschemark, which has long been
the strongest currency in Europe. It remains the currency of choice
in areas such as the former Yugoslavia where local currencies are
unstable.
</P>
<P>
   Holding a silver mark aloft and admiring it like a glass of
wine, Franz Brandt, a waiter in a restaurant in Berlin's Europa
Center, said wistfully, ``I will miss her.''
</P>
<P>
   Failure of the single currency would be disastrous. There are no
escape mechanisms should a country decide to bolt. Any failure
would probably turn Europeans against one another and destroy
monetary union as well as threaten the existing political comity.
But few business people expect such an outcome.
</P>
<P>
   Some 1,700 years ago, the Roman emperor Diocletian established a
single currency in an attempt to unite his disparate subjects, only
to see it fall in one of Europe's many bouts of bloodshed.
</P>
<P>
   Many Europeans are cautiously optimistic that they can avoid the
fate of Diocletian's noble effort. At the very least, they hope
that the lifespan of the euro will be considerably longer than the
16 years that the emperor's single currency lasted in the third
century.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
