<HEADLINE>
RUSH IS ON TO CONVERT SECURITIES TO EURO TRADING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER G. GOSSELIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   While American recover from their New Year's celebrations this
weekend computer programmers and finance specialists will be
engaged in a distinctly un-celebratory enterprise: Racing to
convert billions of dollars' worth of mutual fund holdings, trust
assets, and bank accounts from their original mark, franc, or lire
denominations into that of Europe's new currency, the euro.
</P>
<P>
   Their deadline is Sunday evening. ``That's when the trading day
begins in the Far East,'' said Richard A. Heckinger, senior vice
president with Boston's State Street Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say the entire effort will make little difference to
the typical American, even if he or she owns financial securities
from the 11 countries involved in the giant currency conversion.
That is because most people have their holdings through mutual
funds, whose value is calculated in US dollars.
</P>
<P>
   But that hardly means nothing is at stake in the conversion,
especially for a financial center like Boston. Any slip-up could
doom a company's _ and potentially even a city's _ reputation.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't get it right and you can't trade Jan. 4, you're
in big trouble,'' said an official with Putnam Investments in
Boston.
</P>
<P>
   That is why the region's financial giants are pulling out all
the stops, commandeering thousands of computer programmers and
finance specialists to work around-the-clock to ensure the switch
goes off smoothly.
</P>
<P>
   State Street has 1,000 people scheduled to work at its primary
processing center in Quincy, Mass., as well as another 600 at
satellite facilities in Sydney, Hong Kong, Munich, Paris, and
London, according to Heckinger. As chief record-keeper for $4.5
trillion in assets, a substantial fraction of them from the
European countries involved, the company probably has more at stake
in the conversion than many other firm.
</P>
<P>
   At Fidelity Investments, several hundred people will be working
to make sure assets like those in the $1.7 billion Fidelity Europe
fund are repriced in euros, according to senior vice president
Richard Spillane. A similar number have been called in by Putnam,
Fleet Financial Group, and BankBoston Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Spillane said one measure of the financial world's confidence
that the conversion will come off without a hitch is that European
and non-European investors have been making deals this week that
will not be settled until next week, something they would not do if
they thought the accounting system that keeps track of what they
bought or sold was about to break down.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been pretty routine,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On its face, the conversion to the euro does not seem that
complicated a task. ``Basically, you can just look at it as adding
another currency,'' said Charles M. Lewis, executive vice president
with Fleet Financial. But there are several complicating wrinkles.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, while all stocks and government bonds from the 11
countries involved will be quoted and traded in euros starting
Monday, the same is not true of corporate bonds or deposit
accounts. European companies are not required to convert their
bonds to the new currency until 2002. Neither are individual
deposit holders.
</P>
<P>
   That means banks and financial firms that handle European
securities will have to operate a dual-currency system for the next
several years, one that records the value of assets using the old,
so-called legacy currencies and that also uses the new euro.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, there is the question of whether the new currency
will catch on sufficiently to supplant the German mark, French
franc, and Italian lire.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis at Fleet Financial predicts the new currency will get off
to a ``somewhat tenuous start'' but will eventually take hold,
adding that the bank will provide its clients with whatever
currency they choose to use.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not out to chart someone's destiny here,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That's up to the customer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
