<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-31 18:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4019 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUS-Y2K-COMPUTER-BUG0     12-31 0951
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUS-Y2K-COMPUTER-BUG01 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Millenium Bug could arrive early
 &HT;    By Dick Stanley
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The Millenium Bug that's expected to chew up
some of the world's computers on Jan. 1, 2000, could take a preview
bite out of some of them today, and on six other days later this
year.
</P>
<P>
   Despite doomsday predictions, however, no emergency, or other
essential public services in the Austin area are expected to be
disrupted.
</P>
<P>
   The problems that could develop today, and throughout the year,
are the same ones forecast for Jan. 1, 2000. They could arise early
because many computers have internal calendars which look ahead one
year.
</P>
<P>
   When computers afflicted with the Millenium Bug, which makes
them incapable of recognizing any year beginning with a number
other than 19, try looking ahead one year today, they could trip
over Jan. 1, 2000, and crash or spew erroneous data.
</P>
<P>
   The city of Austin has spent months testing and fixing computers
and computer chips involved in the delivery of public services, and
officials don't expect any problems today. But, to be on the safe
side, technicians at Austin's electric utility were on call last
night and will be again today, to manually keep electricity flowing
to homes and businesses if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can mobilize quickly if there's any problem,'' said Carol
Gittinger, the Austin utility's Y2K, or Year 2000, project
director. ``But we don't anticipate anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials in Georgetown, Round Rock and other area
municipalities said they also have prepared for potential problems
and expect no disruptions in their services.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Looney, the city of Austin's Y2K coordinator, said essential
city services, such as water, fire, police, and medical emergency
ambulances, shouldn't experience any problems today because most of
their computers have been fixed and tested to be sure.
</P>
<P>
   The Austin water department appears to be ready to keep water
flowing, and lifesaving equipment of the city's and county's
Emergency Medical Services will function properly. So will the fire
department, ``our star performer with all their systems certified
now,'' Looney said.
</P>
<P>
   Computers of the police department's 911 emergency system still
need some work, Looney said, but the worst that's expected to
happen to it is that a two-minute old incident report might be
mislabeled as two years old.
</P>
<P>
   That's the sort of hassle most experts expect to develop quietly
today, without fanfare, in, say, the computer cash registers or
accounting systems of some businesses that haven't completed Y2K
fixes.
</P>
<P>
   Businesses and governments, large and small, have devoted
millions of dollars and years of work to finding and fixing
year-date references in trillions of lines of computer code, but
some are farther along than others.
</P>
<P>
   The date references are found not only in software running cash
registers and on desktop and other computers, but in so-called
embedded computer chips studded throughout control systems for
manufacturing, transportation, security, gas and oil pipelines,
medical and other mechanical equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Fixes by state agencies, for instance, are only 58 percent
completed, with 62,000 embedded chips left to be corrected,
according to Shannon Porterfield, the Y2K project director for
state government.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a possibility of some failures if (problems) haven't
been identified in advance testing,'' Porterfield said. ``Systems
won't necessarily crash. But you can get erroneous information. You
can have incorrect data and not know about it for a while.''
</P>
<P>
   Why would a computer that was not involved in accounting or
budgeting try to look ahead one year?
</P>
<P>
   Bob Boyer, a University of Texas professor of computer science,
said many computers and chips may have been programmed to keep
running calendars of events pertinent to their past and future
operations. So they might decide to update themselves today by
including Jan. 1, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Merely calculating that date might cause some sort of data or
arithmetic overflow,'' Boyer said. ``It is hard to predict what the
consequences of an overflow error might be.''
</P>
<P>
   Experts say the year-date problem began at the dawn of digital
computing when memory was scarce and much more expensive than it is
today. Software programmers, faced with limited space, used only
the last two digits of a year. Some of the software has never been
changed and even new software may contain some references to the
old year-date scheme.
</P>
<P>
   Today's preview may not be the end of computer hassles this
year. For various reasons, experts say the bug could bite again at
least six times in1999: on April 4, July 1, Aug. 21, Sept. 1 and 9
and Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
   April 4, for example, is the 99th day of the 99th year of the
20th century, which some early software was coded to regard as
``end of file,'' an order to shut down and await further
instructions. Sept. 9, likewise, is the 9th day of the 9th month of
the 99th year.
</P>
<P>
   ``But (end of file orders) won't be relevant for every system,''
Porterfield said.
</P>
<P>
   The other dates could be more problematic, for systems that have
not been fixed and tested, since some government and private
organizations begin their fiscal years on those days and their
computers will start budgeting into 2000.
</P>
<P>
   For area residents wondering what might happen to their bank
accounts, grocery stores and other important services, Looney said
city officials are planning a series of public forums this year.
</P>
<P>
   The first one is scheduled Jan. 20 in city council chambers at
309 W. 2nd St., at a time to be announced later.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
