<SLUG> BC-TAXES-GIFTS3-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAST-MINUTE PHILANTHROPY HAS TAX-PLANNING MOTIVE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Fixes hedline)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The US stock market's strong recovery in the last months of 1998
prompted a flurry of charitable giving in December, as ordinary
investors rushed to blend warm-hearted philanthropic motivations
with the cold calculus of year-end tax planning.
</P>
<P>
   Anecdotal evidence from national charities and gift-making
organizations Thursday suggested moderate to major increases in
donations before the New Year, when investors who feel financially
flush traditionally make contributions that can lead to a
wallet-fattening tax write-off come April.
</P>
<P>
   At The Jimmy Fund in Boston, staffers manned the phones from 7
a.m. to 8 p.m this week, fielding calls from people seeking to help
cancer research as well as secure a lesser tax bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very, very busy,'' said Fund spokeswoman Karen Cummings.
``It's more than last year. People are giving bigger gifts. And
there are more tribute gifts in the names of people who have
died.''
</P>
<P>
   Financial services professionals said Wall Street's year-end
upswing after months of volatility was partly to credit for the
increase in giving. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 Index, the broadest
measure of the stock market, closed Thursday up 27 percent for 1998
_ an unprecedented fourth year in a row of 20 percent-plus gains.
</P>
<P>
   Gifts are as much about the giver as the recipient, and
charitable donations are no exception. The market's robust returns
left Americans more flush with wealth _ and more anxious about the
tax consequences of all that cash and equity. While the two
feelings traditionally merge and grow in December, when charity
coffers swell on last-minute gifts before the new tax year sets,
donations _ and tax angst _ seemed a bit greater in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   A volunteer at CARE's toll-free number said that 20 percent to
30 percent of year-end contributions were motivated by tax
planning, slightly more than in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   At the United Way of Massachusetts Bay, communications director
Carmen Fields said last year was a banner year, with the agency set
to meet its target of nearly $48 million, an annual increase of 10
percent. ``We don't ask people why they're giving, but this is the
time of year when taxes are on the fore of people's minds,'' Fields
said.
</P>
<P>
   Financial planners said clients whose stock portfolios swelled
in recent months were using increasingly complex methods to benefit
both charities and themselves. J. Michael Martin, a financial
adviser in Ellicott City, Md., said he had one husband and wife
team each withdraw $100,000 from their Individual Retirement
Accounts, a taxable action. They each then awarded various
charities $100,000 in appreciated stock from another account _ a
tax-free move that saved them each about $40,000 that helped offset
the taxable IRA withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
   Other investors seek to dump underperforming shares by giving
them to charity and taking the loss but offsetting the taxable gain
_ an often unwanted gift. Martin said one client rebalanced his
portfolio and won a tax break by donating a large portion of his
shares in railway concern Norfolk &AMP; Southern.
</P>
<P>
   Even in Massachusetts, where an Internal Revenue Service study
showed residents to be among the stingiest givers in the nation,
donations swelled in recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
   At Fidelity Investments' Charitable Gift Fund, one of the
largest gift-making organizations in the nation, president Cynthia
L. Egan said 40 percent of last year's $530 million in donations
came in December alone, an increase of 16 percent on 1997's level.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tax planning is an important part of fueling charitable giving
at the year-end, but we also see surges in grant-making requests
when certain events, like Hurricane Mitch and Georges, happen,''
Egan said.
</P>
<P>
   At the American Red Cross of Massachusetts Bay, chief executive
Patricia Deacon said the past 90 days had been quite busy. ``It is
the season for many reasons,'' she said. `And we have had more
gifts of stock this year than ever before.'' Contributions through
stock gifts had nearly doubled, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, some investors, heady on expectations of gains both in
the market and before the taxman, apparently forget that charitable
donations actually cost money. ``The tax savings is always less
than what you give,'' said Martin, the financial planner. ``People
always forget this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
