<HEADER>
A4032 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOMEVIDEO-995(2TAKES)     12-31 1016
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOMEVIDEO-995(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOOKING BACK AT SMALL GEMS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By PETER M. NICHOLS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   At the end of the year some videos stick in the memory for one
reason or another. Here is a selection from 1998.
</P>
<P>
   PICNIC AT HANGING ROCK. But what happened to them? Back after 15
years out of distribution, Peter Weir's film about the vanishing of
three Australian schoolgirls during a picnic in the outback still
leaves one as achingly in need of an explanation of their
disappearance. During the film, however, one gradually comes to
realize that there won't be one. ``The challenge was to let the
audience know in a way that wouldn't upset them that there wasn't
going to be an ending,'' Weir said in an interview. Actually, what
does it matter?
</P>
<P>
   LAMERICA. Video's best answer to ``Where is it when we need
it?'' is the small gem of a film that comes along to relieve a run
of pretty bad bigger movies. This year perhaps the best of them was
Gianni Amelio's acclaimed movie about a young Italian hustler
(Enrico Lo Verso) who loses the clothes off his back, along with
virtually every shred of his identity, by trying to make a quick
buck off chaos in Albania.
</P>
<P>
   THE END OF VIOLENCE. In Wim Wenders' film, another of the year's
better finds, the movie mogul Mike Max (Bill Pullman) may not
understand why he is suddenly losing his studio, but he has the
good sense to stay calm, lie low and try to sort it out with the
moral support of Chicano gardeners who find him unconscious in a
flower bed. The result, Stephen Holden wrote in The New York Times,
generates ``more intriguing speculation about technology,
communications and the effects of mass media than a hundred
science-fiction fantasies.''
</P>
<P>
   PONETTE. A third small prize, Jacques Doillon's film is about a
4-year-old girl who desperately develops strategies to deal with
the death of her mother. One amazing thing about this movie is the
mesmerizing, unsentimental performance by Victoire Thivisol, who
was just 3 when she was chosen for the role after a talent hunt in
French schools and day-care centers. It is also unusual how such a
subject becomes a piece of high drama.
</P>
<P>
   MY SO-CALLED LIFE. Speaking of children, Claire Danes had barely
turned 14 when she began her run in Ed Zwick and Marshall
Herskovitz's bitingly strong but doomed 1994 television series
about a teen-ager and her family. (Three episodes of the 19 made
are available from BMG.) Ms. Danes has since moved on to the
movies. Back then ABC had misgivings about the show before it
started. But, said Winnie Holzman, its primary writer, ``Claire was
so charismatic, so much a star right from the get-go, it was hard
to turn away and say no.''
</P>
<P>
   TO KILL A MOCKINGBIRD. Robert Mulligan's adaptation of the
Harper Lee novel, with a screenplay by Horton Foote, was back in a
stunningly sharp black-and-white edition. When Alan J. Pakula, the
film's producer, first proposed the project, studio people seemed
puzzled. ``They asked, `What story do you plan to tell?''' he said
in an interview last year. ``I said, `Have you read the book?' They
said, `Yes.' I said, `That's the story.'''
</P>
<P>
   NEW RELEASES
</P>
<P>
   Out of Sight
</P>
<P>
   Don't ask how, but during his escape attempt from a Florida
prison, the suave bank robber Jack Foley (George Clooney) manages
to get himself locked in a car trunk with a voluptuous federal
marshal named Karen Sisco (Ms. Lopez). This being an Elmore Leonard
crime tale, and these being movie stars in their prime, the
confinement sparks a twisty attraction. As more or less faithfully
adapted from the Leonard book, Steven Soderbergh's film manages the
slippery plot maneuverings with panache. Characterizations have
been altered, however, with Ms. Lopez resembling a younger sister
of Jackie Brown and Clooney making a more playfully roguish Foley
than the book's seasoned, sad-eyed Jack. Considering that this is
Soderbergh's first commercial film, Janet Maslin wrote in The New
York Times, ``he makes it work like a dream.''
</P>
<P>
   1998. Universal. $107.37. 123 minutes. Closed captioned. R.
Release date: Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   How Stella Got Her Groove Back
</P>
<P>
   Stella (Angela Bassett), a beautiful, in-shape San Francisco
stockbroker and divorced mother of one repairs to a tropical resort
where she undertakes some torrid revitalization with an impeccably
courtly hunk named Winston (Taye Diggs), who is 20 years her
junior. Kevin Rodney Sullivan's first film starts as a rosy
rendition of a May-September relationship, but gets back to reality
when Stella meets Winston's brutally condescending mother, who is
just a year older than she, and Winston seems more interested in
junk food and playing video games than he is in adult pursuits.
While Winston is never more than a fantasy, ``Ms. Bassett portrays
this high-strung superwoman with such intensity that she makes her
almost believable'' (Stephen Holden).
</P>
<P>
   1998. Fox. $104.16. 124 minutes. Closed captioned. R. Release
date: Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Jealousy
</P>
<P>
   An articulate, self-defeating romantic who likes to thrash out
his troubles in coffee shops, the obsessively possessive Lester
Grimm (Eric Stoltz) anguishes over his girlfriend, Ramona Ray
(Annabella Sciorra), and her past relationship with Dashiell Frank
(Chris Eigeman), a wildly successful writer who is described as the
literary voice of his generation. Dashiell is the kind who sails
through multiple sexual exploits and has his best-selling book read
on audiotape by Tom Cruise. A schoolteacher with his own literary
ambitions, Lester is so thrown by the notion of the famous writer
and the frisky Ramona that he enrolls in Dashiell's therapy group,
the better to study the fellow close up.
</P>
<P>
   But with a fertile enough premise, Noah Baumbach's film would
have done better to cast the more naturally fretful Eigeman as the
neurotic Lester and the cooler Stolz as Dashiell, thereby stoking a
situation that ``could have been funnier if its actors weren't
playing against type'' (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   1998. BMG. $97.99. 105 minutes. R.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Other new titles of interest, some of which may have had a
theater release at one time or appeared on television.
</P>
<P>
   IT HAPPENED TOMORROW, ALIBI and LURED. Three older American
films get their first release on tape. In Rene Clair's ``It
Happened Tomorrow'' (1944, 84 minutes), a reporter (Dick Powell)
gets himself into difficulties when he finds a way to get the news
a day in advance of its happening. In Roland West's ``Alibi''
(1929, 84 minutes), Chester Morris is a Prohibition-era gangster,
but the art-deco sets are really the star. Lucille Ball serves as a
decoy to help track a serial killer in Douglas Sirk's ``Lured''
(1947, 103 minutes). Kino. $24.95 each. Information: (800)
562-3330.
</P>
<P>
   SAM SHEPARD: STALKING HIMSELF. Bits of his plays and interviews
with actors are capped by a close, revealing conversation with the
playwright himself, a notably private man who discusses his
troubled youth and relationship with his father. 1998. Fox Lorber.
$19.98. 60 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   SMASHING TIME. Set up as a comedy team, Yvonne (Lynn Redgrave)
and Brenda (Rita Tushingham) strive to become the Mod sensations of
'60s London, first doing some time as cocktail waitresses and
dishwashers before ascending to, respectively, recording star and
``face of the '70s.'' 1967. Anchor Bay. $19.95. 96 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   MIDAQ ALLEY. Jorge Fons' film, set in Mexico City and adapted
from the novel by the Egyptian Nobel Prize winner Naguib Mahfouz,
tells colorfully soap-operatic tales about a middle-aged family man
who finds he's homosexual, a beautiful young woman who falls for a
barber, and a spinster who longs for marriage. 1995. Fox Lorber.
$24.95. 140 minutes. Spanish with English subtitles. No rating.
</P>
