<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-31 19:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4046 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-IN-BRIEF-3TAKE     12-31 1083
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-IN-BRIEF-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOVIES IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here is a selective listing by critics of The Times of new or
noteworthy movies and film series playing this weekend in New York
City. Ratings and running times are in parentheses.
</P>
<P>
   `AMERICAN HISTORY X,' starring Edward Norton, Edward Furlong and
Beverly D'Angelo. Directed by Tony Kaye (R, 118 minutes). Flawed
but gut-slugging, renounced by its director yet still a showcase
for his effective style, this story of a neo-Nazi skinhead who
develops a heart of gold presses every possible hot button. And its
toughest images stick even when its lurid self-aggrandizing,
presented in the ersatz poetic idiom of videos and commercials,
spins out of control. In a show of De Niro-like fury and
versatility, Norton plays a savage, racist killer who learns the
error of his ways through simple-minded but brutally effective plot
devices and trying to protect his younger brother (Furlong).
Hotheaded and sensationalistic, but startlingly tough (Janet
Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `ANTZ,' starring the voices of Woody Allen, Sharon Stone,
Sylvester Stallone, Gene Hackman and Christopher Walken. Directed
by Eric Darnell and Tim Johnson (PG, 83 minutes). Computer
animation has advanced to the point where it can make a cute
romantic couple out of Allen and Ms. Stone. This and other surreal
tricks are shown off in a funny, ingeniously animated insect
picture that often reaches the anthropomorphic cleverness of ``Toy
Story'' and shows off Allen's sharpest comic timing with
one-liners. But ``Antz'' winds up overplotted in bizarrely
grandiose ways, with the threat of genocide invoked for a jarring
change of pace. Must every child-friendly adventure film, even one
with considerable potential to delight grown-ups, boil down to a
struggle for world domination? Surely a threat of bug spray in the
picnic basket would have done the trick (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `A BUG'S LIFE,' featuring the voices of Dave Foley, Julia
Louis-Dreyfus and Kevin Spacey. Directed by John Lasseter and
Andrew Stanton (G, 94 minutes). The best animated ant-colony movie
of the year. And this is a more clearly defined family film than
the verbally adult ``Antz.'' With the same anthropomorphism that
gave Lasseter's ``Toy Story'' so much spark, this pastel-hued,
visually ingenious feat of animation tells a tale of ant courage
while incorporating lively wit and an enchanting sense of nature.
And it's a showcase for the incredible range of facial expressions
that make this type of animation more and more invitingly lifelike
all the time (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `CENTRAL STATION,' starring Fernanda Montenegro, Vinicius de
Oliveira and Marilia Pera. Directed by Walter Salles (R, 115
minutes). In this quiet, luminous Brazilian gem, a joyless older
woman crosses paths with an orphaned young boy. There's plenty of
room for sentimentality here, but the wonder of Salles' film is all
in the telling. As these characters develop a fractious bond, then
embark on a road trip that takes them vividly to Brazil's
hinterlands in search of the boy's father, Salles brings great
tenderness and surprise to the events that punctuate their journey.
Ms. Montenegro's tough bravura performance is one of 1998's very
best (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `DANCING AT LUGHNASA,' starring Meryl Streep, Brid Brennan,
Michael Gambon, Kathy Burke and Catherine McCormack. Directed by
Pat O'Connor (PG, 94 minutes). Ms. Streep is grand, as are the
other principals here, in an actors' heyday of a film adapted from
Brian Friel's delicate play. And if O'Connor has lost some of the
play's intensity by opening it up so overwhelmingly, he's also
gained a good deal in the way of lovely Irish scenery and quaint
rural charm. Set in 1936, the story presents a family of five
unmarried sisters on the brink of change and revolves around the
return of their gently eccentric brother from many years'
missionary work in Africa. Rather than major dramatic events, this
beguilingly atmospheric film observes the sea changes that alter
these characters' lives (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `ELIZABETH,' starring Cate Blanchett, Joseph Fiennes, Geoffrey
Rush and Christopher Eccleston. Directed by Shekhar Kapur (R, 124
minutes). In this lurid costume drama depicting Elizabeth I as a
royal rookie, the impressive Ms. Blanchett plays the queen as if
her principal responsibilities were being bejeweled, selecting
consorts and saying ``Leave us!'' with a wave of the hand. For all
its putative concern with Roman Catholic-Protestant strife at the
start of Elizabeth's reign, this is historical drama for those
whose idea of history is back issues of Vogue. Intent on spectacle,
complete with burning at the stake and one dance scene reminiscent
of ``Saturday Night Fever,'' it winds up imagining the queen as a
glamorously stressed-out modern woman afflicted by a super-intense
case of having it all (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `ENEMY OF THE STATE,' starring Will Smith, Gene Hackman, Jon
Voight and Regina King. Directed by Tony Scott (R, 128 minutes).
Smith goes on the run in a paranoid thriller whose high-tech gizmos
are a main attraction. He also carries the story ably in his first
real leading role, that of a successful lawyer who suddenly finds
himself under surveillance by a sizable nerd squad at the National
Security Agency and a satellite in space. Fortunately, it all
hurtles by too fast for audiences to stop for plot questions.
Sterling cast members like Hackman as an eccentric technology whiz
and Voight as a chilly advocate of surveillance tactics bring an
additional touch of class (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `THE FACULTY,' starring Jordana Brewster, Clea DuVall, Laura
Harris and Josh Hartnett. Directed by Robert Rodriguez (R, 111
minutes). Like Frankenstein, ``The Faculty'' plunders the crypts of
cinema for its body parts. Here are the paranoia and parasitism of
``Invasion of the Body Snatchers.'' There are the slimy,
sharp-toothed creatures of ''Alien.'' And over there are the
movie-wise teen-agers of ``Scream.'' The list could be extended,
but the point is clear: This mediocre sci-fi horror film about an
Ohio high school being taken over by thirsty space aliens intent on
world domination breaks no new ground. But written by Kevin
Williamson, it has an engaging cast, with half a dozen appealing
young actors playing the roles of teen-agers who are all that stand
between the Midwestern monsters and the end of the world as certain
moviegoers know it (Lawrence Van Gelder).
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   `GODS AND MONSTERS,' starring Ian McKellen and Brendan Fraser.
Directed by Bill Condon (not rated, 105 minutes). In a performance
that well deserves to be remembered at Academy Award time, McKellen
becomes the deliciously urbane James Whale, the gay
``Frankenstein'' director, playing him late in life. Shaken by the
aftereffects of a mild stroke, this Whale finds his past coming
back to greet him just as the present offers new fascination in the
Adonis-like form of the gardener ( Fraser, also fine), whom Whale
finds mowing his lawn. This beautifully acted, witty and
heart-tugging film, from a Christopher Bram book, imagines what
Whale's final days might have been like while shaping a splendid
character study and a droll portrait of closeted gay Hollywood.
Lynn Redgrave provides ballast and comic relief as Whale's
perpetually scandalized housekeeper (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `HAPPINESS,' starring Jane Adams, Dylan Baker, Philip Seymour
Hoffman and Lara Flynn Boyle. Directed by Todd Solondz (not rated;
135 minutes). In a much bigger film than his ``Welcome to the Doll
House,'' this audacious, deadpan filmmaker explores loneliness in
his murderously funny fashion. Outrageous touches _ none more so
than its title _ come easily to ``Happiness,'' and so do the dark
secrets that would surely have brought it an NC-17 rating. No point
in cataloging this film's perverse details: What emerges most
clearly is a ruthless yet tender portrait of suburban characters
seeking romance, captured with enough acid precision to make this a
``Bob and Carol and Ted and Alice'' for totally dysfunctional
times. Ms. Adams plays the dartboard in a three-sister family with
hilarious tremulousness. Baker's gutsy portrayal of a bland-seeming
pederast who is also a respected doctor and a loving father is
impossible to forget (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `LIFE IS BEAUTIFUL,' directed by and starring Roberto Benigni
(PG-13, 122 minutes). Italy's most antic funnyman dares to find
humor and tenderness in the midst of the Holocaust, and his risk
pays off. This Cannes prize winner is as stubbornly entertaining as
its central character, a Jewish waiter named Guido who jokes his
way through the nightmare for the sake of his loved ones. Daring
also to combine an opening hour of romance and pranks with a more
somber second act, Benigni avoids all traces of the maudlin and
effectively creates a situation in which comedy is courage. In this
unpretentious, enormously likable film, he shines as a father whose
fibs and hilarious buffoonery know no bounds, and no fear (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `JACK FROST,' starring Michael Keaton, Kelly Preston and Joseph
Cross. Directed by Troy Miller (PG, 100 minutes). Keaton stars as
the title character, one of those rock-and-roll musicians who are
also great husbands and devoted dads. The film is about what
happens after Jack dies in a Christmas Eve automobile accident and
returns to his family as a large, wisecracking marshmallow man
parked on the front lawn. As one more Hollywood effort to look on
the sunny side of fatality, this one is so sugarcoated that it
makes other recent efforts in the genre look blisteringly honest by
comparison. The actors are as plausible and nice as possible in
displaying emotions as sincere as the soap-flake snow that coats
the sets (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `LITTLE VOICE,' starring Jane Horrocks, Brenda Blethyn, Ewan
McGregor and Michael Caine. Directed by Mark Herman (R, 99
minutes). The main attraction here is watching wispy Ms. Horrocks
put on a spectacular one-woman diva festival, with her phenomenal
mimicry of musical grande dames from Judy Garland to Marilyn
Monroe. What works less well is the broad and stagy story built
around her. As the timid title character, she is harangued by her
blowsy mother (Ms. Blethyn), latched onto by the talent agent who
is the mother's boyfriend ( Caine) and courted by a nice young man
who loves his pet pigeons. In that last role, McGregor makes a
telephone installer scintillating and once again shows that he can
do anything. Incidentally, the soundtrack is divine (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `LIVING OUT LOUD,' starring Holly Hunter, Danny DeVito and Queen
Latifah. Directed by Richard LaGravenese (R, 102 minutes). Making
his directorial debut, LaGravenese, a sensitive screenwriter,
remains very much a writer, constructing a talky, introspective
character study laced with flights of musical fantasy. Ms. Hunter
stiffly but passionately plays a newly divorced woman trying to
reinvent her life. DeVito is warmly credible as a lonely elevator
man who cares for her. Queen Latifah is the film's most
attention-getting figure in the small but glamorous role of a
torchy nightclub singer. Would-be Chekhovian touches abound in this
story of lonely people, but they don't make it jell (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `PATCH ADAMS,' starring Robin Williams and Monica Potter.
Directed by Tom Shadyac (PG-13, 110 minutes). As a maverick doctor
intent on making terminal patients laugh, Williams delivers a
little clowning and a lot of maudlin feel-good sentiment, along
with vulgarity left over from the filmmaker's ``Ace Ventura'' days.
He also spends a lot of time being congratulated for his good
works, as the film's minor players are kept busy marveling at his
antics. The real-life story of this doctor may sound like a fine
occasion for Williams to cut loose, but the film version proves
narrow and predictable. Ms. Potter, with a nostrilly resemblance to
Julia Roberts, figures in a romantic subplot with a bizarre twist
(Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `PLEASANTVILLE,' starring Tobey Maguire, Reese Witherspoon, Joan
Allen and William Macy. Written and directed by Gary Ross (PG-13,
116 minutes). This cleverly executed fantasy, with a
back-to-the-future trip into the small-town, squeaky-clean paradise
of a 1950s television show, tends toward the black and white,
visually and otherwise. The missionary zeal with which teen-agers
from the 1990s try to awaken benighted '50s types from their
slumber is an attitude that wears thin. But in the meantime there
are witty tricks integrating color into black-and-white images, and
nice little touches abound. The cast is poignant and amusing, with
Ms. Allen especially touching as a prefeminist housewife who's the
prime recipient of '90s hindsight (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `THE PRINCE OF EGYPT,' starring the voices of Val Kilmer, Ralph
Fiennes, and Michelle Pfeiffer. Directed by Brenda Chapman, Steve
Hickner and Simon Wells (PG, 93 minutes). First came the great
expectations for this animated magnum opus from Dreamworks. Then
came reality, in a film struggling mightily to balance animated
whimsy and biblical stature. The upshot is an admirably worthy
rendering of the Exodus story, even if Moses must initially be seen
as a playful young scamp. Biblical plagues and miracles serve as
special inspiration for the animators' reality-bending ingenuity
(Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   `PSYCHO,' starring Vince Vaughn, Anne Heche, William Macy and
Julianne Moore. Directed by Gus Van Sant (R, 100 minutes). It turns
out that the apparent rocks in Van Sant's head, as he contrived
this near-exact color replica of Alfred Hitchcock's 1960 classic,
were only pebbles. His remake (a modest term, but it beats
plagiarism) is artful and good-looking, faltering only when it
tries to improve on the brilliant original blueprint. The casting
of Vaughn as Norman Bates is the film's biggest Achilles' heel,
since the performance Hitchcock elicited from Anthony Perkins
remains an impossible act to follow. Still, Van Sant has tried an
outlandish experiment and come up with what are, especially for
fans of the original, intriguing variations on a theme (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `THE RUGRATS MOVIE,' starring the voices of E.G. Daily, Kath
Soucie, Tara Charendoff and Tim Curry. Directed by Norton Virgien
and Igor Kovalyov (G, 90 minutes). Dil Pickles is not the first
baby whose resentful older sibling wanted to return him to the
hospital, but he's probably the only one who has such an
interesting trip back. Dil (full name: Dylan Preston Pickles) is
the newborn hero of the first film starring the five talking babies
of Nickelodeon's hit children's series ``Rugrats.'' The pleasant
surprise is that the film is a delight, from encounters with
wolves, wizards and circus monkeys in the forest to musical numbers
at the ``baby store.'' There's material for grown-up moviegoers,
too, including a scene with some pathetic reporters who turn up at
the Pickles house when the children disappear, getting everybody's
name wrong and asking, ``Is it true a dingo ate your baby?'' (Anita
Gates).
</P>
<P>
   `STAR TREK: INSURRECTION,' starring Patrick Stewart and Jonathan
Frakes. Directed by Frakes (PG, 105 minutes). The latest movie
episode of the series that will not die finds Capt. Picard (
Stewart) and the crew of the Enterprise saving a tribe of utopian
space pioneers who live on a planet where everyone enjoys eternal
youth. The bad guys want to relocate the people forcibly and
exploit the planet's life-giving properties. Picard, standing up
against the admiral of Starfleet and risking court-martial,
delivers impassioned speeches about the ugly history of forcible
relocation and also falls in love with a 309-year-old beauty (Donna
Murphy). Although in its ninth movie episode, the series has
retained its sincerity and multicultural right-mindedness. It's
hokum, but executed deftly and with a warm heart (Stephen Holden).
</P>
<P>
   `STEPMOM,' starring Susan Sarandon, Julia Roberts and Ed Harris.
Directed by Chris Columbus (PG-13, 120 minutes). A man's ex-wife
and new girlfriend lock horns over who can be nicer to his two
children, in a sudsy story made livelier by its two female stars,
both in appealingly high gear. Ms. Roberts plays the nicest person
ever to wear black to a downtown photo shoot, while the especially
fiery Ms. Sarandon plays the suburban mother as mama lion. Even
when the prospect of mortality looms, the story manages to maintain
its big, lavish look and peculiar (under the circumstances) sense
of fun. As in ``Home Alone,'' Columbus directs with sunny
indifference to reality: medical, economic or otherwise (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `TOUCH OF EVIL,' starring Orson Welles, Charlton Heston and
Janet Leigh. Directed by Welles (not rated, 108 minutes). Anyone
familiar with Welles' 1958 film-noir landmark knows that it could
just as well have been called ``Truckload of Evil,'' and that its
crazily sinister plot turns and breathtaking camera work remain
astonishingly fresh. ``Touch of Evil'' is, among so many things,
the other film to find Janet Leigh at a lonely motel under
strangely menacing management, and the one in which Welles gave one
of his most droll, swaggering performances as a corrupt police
captain in an American town on the Mexican border. As visually
thrilling as it is sin-soaked, this artfully reconstructed version
of ``Touch of Evil'' remains one of the brightest lights on the
cinematic landscape this season (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `WAKING NED DEVINE,' starring Ian Bannen, David Kelly and
Fionnula Flanagan. Directed by Kirk Jones (PG, 91 minutes).
Delightful shenanigans greet the news of a winning lottery ticket
in a tiny Irish village. Especially after the winner turns out to
be dead. Bannen and Kelly are wonderfully funny as two old coots
who concoct a plot to claim the winnings and unite the town's cast
of hearty characters in the process. Jones' prize-winning career
directing television commercials means that everyone here is an
amusing eccentric with colorful quirks, and that the septuagenarian
stars' naked motorcycle-riding scenes are played for all they're
worth. This comedy doesn't have the tart edge of ``The Full
Monty,'' but it knows how to coax laughs from making a spectacle of
elderly gentlemen in the buff (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `YOU'VE GOT MAIL,' starring Meg Ryan, Tom Hanks, Greg Kinnear
and Parker Posey. Directed by Nora Ephron (PG, 110 minutes). This
cozy, inviting comedy romanticizes the rivalry between two
bookstore owners, while also finding time to fall in love with
books themselves, the instant intimacy of e-mail and a
picture-perfect rendering of Manhattan's Upper West Side. With a
feel-good ambiance much less forced than that of ``Sleepless in
Seattle,'' Ms. Ephron borrows adroitly from ``The Shop Around the
Corner'' while making this knowing, urbanely funny film very much
her own. Ms. Ryan is fresh and adorable without trying, while a
ruefully lovelorn Hanks proves that he can do anything. Again
(Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   Film Series
</P>
<P>
   THE STUFF THAT DREAMS ARE MADE OF: THE FILMS OF MARCELLO
MASTROIANNI. Before his death in 1996 at 72, Marcello Mastroianni
made more than 170 films, many of them for eminent directors like
Federico Fellini, Vittorio De Sica, Ettore Scola, Luchino Visconti,
Michelangelo Antonioni and Nikita Mikhalkov, and many of them among
the more memorable of the second half of the 20th century.
Beginning Friday and Saturday, with screenings of Pietro Germi's
``Divorce Italian Style'' (1962), De Sica's ``Marriage Italian
Style'' (1964) and Fellini's ``Dolce Vita'' (1960), the Film
Society of Lincoln Center in New York will pay homage to
Mastroianni with a retrospective. Spanning the years from 1962 to
1995, the series includes 22 films, among them Visconti's ``White
Nights'' (1957), Scola's ``Special Day'' (1977), Fellini's ``8
1/2'' (1963), Antonioni's ``Notte'' (1961) and Mikhalkov's ``Dark
Eyes'' (1987). The series continues through Jan. 16 at the Walter
Reade Theater at Lincoln Center. Tickets: $8.50; $5 for Film
Society members; $4.50 for the elderly at weekday matinees.
Information: (212) 875-5600 (Van Gelder).
</P>
</TEXT>
