<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: U.K., ITALY, ISRAEL, VA, CALIF., PA.) 
ART NOTES: A $244,135 `CARTHAGE' TESTA GOES TO ISRAEL AS A $7.2
MILLION  ` JERUSALEM' POUSSIN; HICKSES FOR SALE: CROWD CONTROL AT
THE MET 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISRAEL GETS AN APT POUSSIN  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A painting that Sotheby's experts attributed to the 17th-century
artist Pietro Testa and called ``The Sack of Carthage'' was
estimated to sell for $16,000 to $24,000 when it was included in a
London sale in 1995. But what began as a minor work in an Old
Master auction has ended up being one of the stars of the Israel
Museum's permanent collection, thanks to a combination of
scholarship and beneficence.
</P>
<P>
   The directors of Hazlitt, Gooden &AMP; Fox, a London gallery, bought
the painting at the Sotheby's auction for $244,135, more than 10
times its high estimate. The dealers suspected something Sotheby's
experts did not and were prepared to take a gamble.
</P>
<P>
   After considerable research and restoration, the gallery
discovered that the painting was in fact by Testa's friend and
colleague, the far more famous Nicolas Poussin, and that rather
than being called ``The Sack of Carthage'' it was titled ``The
Destruction and Sack of the Temple of Jerusalem,'' and is the first
of two works on the subject that Poussin painted in 1626.
</P>
<P>
   It was the English philanthropist Jacob Rothschild who, knowing
that the Israel Museum had no Poussin in its collection, offered to
give the institution a grant from Yad Hanadiv, the Rothschild
Foundation in Israel, to purchase the painting in memory of Sir
Isaiah Berlin, the philosopher and historian, who died a year ago.
The foundation paid $7.2 million for the work.
</P>
<P>
   Poussin based ``The Destruction and Sack of the Temple of
Jerusalem'' on the first-century historian Flavius Josephus'
eyewitness account of the sack of Jerusalem in A.D. 70, an event
commemorated each year as a day of mourning in the Jewish calendar.
It is one of three chaotic battle scenes he painted during his
first year in Rome.
</P>
<P>
   The work had been lost for 320 years, until its appearance,
misattributed, at Sotheby's. Its past unfolds a complex chapter of
17th-century history: it was commissioned by Francesco Cardinal
Barberini in 1625, and eight years later he gave it to the Duc de
Crequy. It was later given to Cardinal Richelieu, chief minister of
Louis XIII and a well-known patron of the arts.
</P>
<P>
   Richelieu then bequeathed the work to his niece, the Duchesse
d'Aiguillon, upon whose death in 1675 it entered the collection of
M. de Saintot, Maistre des Ceremonies. From there, its whereabouts
was unknown until the 1995 auction.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an early Poussin yet it shows all the things that mark a
mature Poussin,'' said James S. Snyder, director of the Israel
Museum.
</P>
<P>
   The painting is currently on view at a Poussin exhibition in
Rome, where it will hang until March 1. It will then go to London,
where it will be shown at the National Gallery of Art for eight
weeks before going to the Israel Museum.
</P>
<P>
   RARE SALES OF HICKSES AT AN INTERESTING MOMENT
</P>
<P>
   It is rare to see one great painting by Edward Hicks, the folk
artist, turn up at auction, but this month Christie's New York will
be selling two.
</P>
<P>
   Hicks, a Quaker leader who supported himself as a painter, was
best known for his depictions of the Peaceable Kingdom, parables of
the animal kingdom inspired by the words of the prophet Isaiah.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout his life, Hicks painted about 60 versions of this
theme. In the earliest, dating from about 1825, the artist uses a
child as the central character; around 1830 Hicks' paintings become
more complex, including every animal the prophet mentions. At the
end of his life, around 1840, the artist's work becomes less
lifelike and more brooding in character and heavy in composition.
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 15, Christie's will be selling a ``Peaceable Kingdom''
dating from around 1837, the middle period of the artist's career,
where the most prominent animals are a fierce lion and a docile ox
standing together and sharing straw.
</P>
<P>
   The painting comes from the collection of Robert S. Lee Sr., a
Philadelphia car dealer and art collector who died last year and
whose heirs sold a group of mostly contemporary art at Christie's
this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Lee bought the painting at a Philadelphia auction in 1980 for
$210,000, a record-breaking price for both the artist and a folk
art painting. While $210,000 may have seemed exorbitant 19 years
ago, today Christie's estimates that it will sell for $1.5 million
to $2 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's from his most optimistic period of his career,'' said
John Hays, director of Christie's American decorative arts
department. ``The painting, which is an icon of this artist's work,
is jampacked with animals.''
</P>
<P>
   That both Hickses are coming up for sale this season comes at an
interesting moment, Hays said. In February, the Abby Aldrich
Rockefeller Museum and Folk Art Center in Williamsburg is having a
Hicks retrospective, the first in more than 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   The second of the artist's paintings for sale at Christie's, on
Jan. 15, is a late work, dating from about 1849, of ``The Residence
of David Twining,'' as the artist remembered it in 1785. It is
being sold by Dr. Thomas Lincoln, a direct descendant of both
Abraham Lincoln and David Twining, whom Hicks adopted when he was a
child. The painting depicts members of the Twining family engaged
in farming activities. It has been passed down in the family since
the artist painted it.
</P>
<P>
   Lincoln, a retired physician, is donating the proceeds from the
sale of the painting, which is expected to bring $700,000 to $1
million, to the University of Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   MET CROWD CONTROL
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ If you see ropes down the front steps of the
Metropolitan Museum of Art, it's to control the crowds. The
institution has seen one of the five busiest days in its 128-year
history. On Tuesday, 47,165 visitors visited the Met, crowding its
great hall and jamming its gift shops, not to mention some of its
more popular shows like ``From van Eyck to Bruegel.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Tuesday after Christmas is traditionally our busiest
day,'' said Harold Holzer, the museum's vice president for
communications. ``The reason is a confluence of circumstances:
tourism, school holidays, family outings and the truly eclectic
exhibition schedule.''
</P>
<P>
   It also happened to be raining on Tuesday and, Holzer added, ``a
little drizzle goes a long way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
