<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-31 19:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4058 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POLICE-SHOOTING-BOS &LR;      12-31 1099
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLICE-SHOOTING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE ACTION THAT KILLED WOMAN ROILS BLACK SENTIMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds.: Dastmalchi is cq)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNDA GOROV  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   RIVERSIDE, Calif. _ Resident by black resident, the room swelled
with grief over a teenage girl's death in a hail of police bullets,
until John Dastmalchi stood to speak and was greeted with
foot-stomping, angry amens.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we don't take the beating, we won't be beat,'' he told a
community gathering of 100 or so. ``Let's not go for that nonsense
anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Where black leaders successfully urged calm, Dastmalchi gave
voice to an undercurrent of unchanneled outrage. Where they pressed
people to wait until Riverside police complete their investigation,
he demanded protest now. Their remarks received polite applause.
His approval bordered on the boisterous. Residents clearly heard
their own frustrations echoed in his remarks.
</P>
<P>
   Calm prevailed for another day in Riverside, about 65 miles east
of Los Angeles. But it appeared more tenuous than ever. Suddenly,
longstanding but underlying tensions between blacks and police were
at the raw surface.
</P>
<P>
   Three days after police shot 19-year-old Tyisha Shenee Miller to
death as she sat in her disabled car at an all-night gas station,
residents and her relatives were calling them murderers and
demanding a federal investigation. A national civil rights group
announced plans to picket in Riverside next week. Miller's family
said they hoped attorney Johnnie Cochran would press their expected
wrongful-death suit against the city and the officers involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's high time that these people with the power of god in
their hands, in their pistols, be held accountable,'' Miller's
uncle, the Rev. Bernell Butler, told the gathering. ``We need as
much power and pressure as we can to bring Tyisha Miller's killers
to justice.''
</P>
<P>
   The outrage, however, appeared confined largely to Riverside's
relatively tiny black community, which makes up about 7 percent of
the county's 238,000 residents. There was only a smattering of
whites and Hispanics at Thursday's community meeting, which lasted
several hours. Another divide was apparent among blacks themselves.
While no one advocated violence, the audience sounded far more
frustrated than black leaders, who one after another offered their
condolences to the Miller family before expressing confidence in
police.
</P>
<P>
   ``This community is about to explode,'' said Cheryl Brown,
co-publisher of the Black Voice News in Riverside. ``The leaders
want to keep a lid on it, because they know it could blow up.
People don't understand how five grown policemen could empty their
guns into a girl who was sick.''
</P>
<P>
   As Ameal Moore, Riverside's only black councilman, put it,
``Let's wait until all the facts are in and then decide what to
do.'' Kim Thomas, director of a violence-prevention program called
People Reaching Out, stressed that violence should not lead to more
violence, that Miller's death was already one too many.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, there is a cry of anger and rage. We needed to stand
together as a community to say enough is enough,'' said the Rev.
DeWayne Butler, another of the victim's uncles. ``(But) anyone
could have grabbed pistols and started shooting. ... I was grateful
that everyone decided to go about it in a more controlled manner.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, many in the audience _ and Miller's own family _ said
they did not trust Riverside police to police themselves. Instead,
they want a federal investigation and a civilian review. They said
they want answers, and they said they do not want to wait much
longer for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``People will be held accountable,'' Lt. Jim Cannon promised the
crowd. ``I cannot emphasize enough that we are not in a defensive
posture. . .We're in a fact-finding mode.''
</P>
<P>
   The facts, even police agreed, remained resolutely unclear
Thursday, with some more muddled than others. What is known is that
Miller's friends and family called police for help early Monday
after they could not rouse an unresponsive and possibly unconscious
Miller. No one disputes that those same officers ended up killing
the young woman they set out to save.
</P>
<P>
   What is unknown is what happened to Miller after she pulled her
Nissan Sentra into the gas station with a flat tire around 2 a.m.,
or where she got the .380 caliber semiautomatic handgun that was on
her lap. Initially police said Miller, who lived in nearby
Rubidoux, fired the first shot, touching off the fusillade of
police bullets. They have since backed off that statement, giving
locals another unknown with which to grapple.
</P>
<P>
   Autopsy results were due late Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of gray areas: How'd she lock the car, how'd she
end up foaming at the mouth, why'd the police break a window when
they couldn't wake her instead of waiting for someone to get a
spare key?'' said Don Bardo, president of the Urban League of
Riverside and San Bernadino Counties. ``At this point, we are
willing to say they used excessive force.''
</P>
<P>
   Sgt. Chris Manning, a Riverside police spokesman, declined
Thursday to say how many shots the officers _ four white and one
Hispanic, all now on paid administrative leave _ fired into
Miller's car. Rumors continued to put the number at more than two
dozen.
</P>
<P>
   He did, however, dispute residents' claims of repeated and
regular police misconduct. In 1998, there were seven shootings by
officers and four deaths, no more than usual, and police were
exonerated in each of the investigations completed so far.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things get clumped together and they want to make a nexus
where members of the `minority' community have been arrested and
hogtied and shot and killed, and it doesn't work out that way,''
Manning said. ``These are not related incidents.''
</P>
<P>
   Again and again, however, black residents of Riverdale insisted
there is a correlation between their daily interactions with police
and Miller's killing. Several men at the meeting related how
police, guns at the ready, regularly approached their cars. Women
spoke of mistrusting them so much that they would not call police
if their own cars broke down.
</P>
<P>
   ``We might be black, but we are definitely not animals,'' said
Lou Smith, whose granddaughter, a cousin of Miller's, witnessed her
killing. ``I don't want to take no more of this crap.''
</P>
<P>
   The anger, however, wasn't directed solely at police. Residents
spoke of underfunding of youth programs and a lack of educational
opportunities. People said they wanted more action from black
organizations before a crisis arises.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
