<DOCNO> NYT19981231.0329 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-31 19:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4089 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-FIESTA-FSU01-COX     12-31 0737
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-FIESTA-FSU01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Golden hands, moves set Warrick apart
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. _ As with any successful football program, Florida
State has its benchmark players _ those who set the standard that
all others at a position are judged by.
</P>
<P>
   At defensive back, the Seminole standard-bearer is Deion
Sanders.
</P>
<P>
   At quarterback, it's Charlie Ward, the 1993 Heisman Trophy
winner.
</P>
<P>
   Running back? Warrick Dunn. Middle linebacker? Marvin Jones.
</P>
<P>
   For more than a generation, Florida State's definitive wide
receiver has been Fred Biletnikoff. In fact, college football's top
award for receivers is named for the former Oakland Raider great.
</P>
<P>
   But Peter Warrick could change all that. For all the steadiness
Biletnikoff showed over his career, no receiver at Florida State
ever has put together a highlight reel to match the one belonging
to the junior from Bradenton, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is he the best wide receiver we've had? I don't know if we can
say that just yet,'' Florida State coach Bobby Bowden said. ``But
he's certainly the most elusive and explosive one we've had. Once
he gets in the open field, he is hard to stop.''
</P>
<P>
   Other Florida State receivers have had better seasons than
Warrick's 1998 statistics: 61 catches for 1,232 yards. But none has
made more plays that caused observers _ friend and foe alike _ to
shake heads in disbelief.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was watching film of him the other day and several times I
just caught myself going `Wow,' '' said Tennessee cornerback Steve
Johnson, who will take his turn against Warrick in Monday night's
Fiesta Bowl. ``He's got moves I've never seen before.''
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee's defense faces a dilemma as it prepares for Warrick.
The Volunteers have been successful all season by single-covering
receivers, freeing a defensive back to help against the run. But
teams who tried to single-cover Warrick have paid dearly, as
Tennessee coaches are aware.
</P>
<P>
   ``You watch film of the guy and afterward you aren't able to
sleep at night,'' Tennessee defensive coordinator John Chavis said.
``We've played against a lot of great receivers here, but this guy
is something very special.''
</P>
<P>
   Just a few examples from Warrick's video scrapbook for the 1998
season:
</P>
<P>
   _ Before an Oct. 10 meeting with Miami, several Hurricanes
suggested publicly that Warrick was overrated and promised to shut
him down. Warrick caught seven passes for 190 yards, including a
62-yard touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   _ In the showdown at Georgia Tech on Oct. 24, Warrick caught
touchdown passes of 44 and 8 yards, and scored on a 16-yard reverse
that featured several mind-boggling moves.
</P>
<P>
   _ During the summer, North Carolina cornerback Dre' Bly ran into
Warrick during a photo shoot for a preseason All-America team. Bly
called Warrick out, saying he would shut him down when they met on
Oct. 31. Warrick caught three passes for 126 yards against the Tar
Heels, including a 33-yarder over Bly that set up a touchdown and a
56-yarder for another score.
</P>
<P>
   _ With Florida leading Florida State 12-6 at halftime on Nov.
21, Warrick caught a 32-yard touchdown pass and then threw a
46-yard touchdown pass on a reverse to lead the Seminoles to a
23-12 win.
</P>
<P>
   ``In order to score points, sooner or later you have to get the
ball to the guys who can make plays,'' Florida State offensive
coordinator Mark
</P>
<P>
   Richt said. ``Peter can make plays as well as anyone we have
ever had here.''
</P>
<P>
   Warrick will have a better shot at displacing Biletnikoff if he
comes back for his senior season, but right now that return is very
much up in the air.
</P>
<P>
   ``I gave (leaving) some thought earlier, but now I've put it out
of my mind,'' said Warrick, who averaged 20.2 yards per catch this
season. ``I'm just thinking about winning the national
championship. I'll think about leaving or staying when the game is
over.''
</P>
<P>
   And when Warrick leaves, whenever that is, does he want to be
remembered as Florida State's greatest receiver?
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want people to say that Peter Warrick was a good person
off the field,'' the former high school quarterback said. ``I
really don't care what people are going to say about me in the
future, because once you're gone, you're gone.''
</P>
<P>
   For the defensive backs who had to cover him the past three
years, Peter Warrick can't leave soon enough.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
