<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-BISHER-COLUMN01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tech's had its moments against Irish
 &HT;    By Furman Bisher
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   JACKSONVILLE, Fla. _ The 54th Gator Bowl will be the 32nd time
Georgia Tech and Notre Dame have matched up on the football field,
and the books are seriously unbalanced on the Tech side _ 4-26-1. A
TKO in prize-fight terms, but for all the times the Yellow Jackets
have gone down for the count, they have been witness to some
historical stuff in this off-and-on series that began in 1922.
</P>
<P>
   That was the sophomore season of the fabled ``Four Horsemen,''
Layden, Stuhldreher, Crowley and Miller. They had not yet become
immortalized in print. That was to follow later when Grantland Rice
sat down to his writing machine after Notre Dame had upset Army and
began his story, ``Under a blue-gray October sky ... ``
</P>
<P>
   Tech managed to win one in 1928, but it was a freshman who had
just crossed town from Boys High who deflated the Un-fighting Irish
13-6 on their field in South Bend in 1942. Clint Castleberry, Bobby
Dodd said later, ``might have been the best of them all, had he
lived.'' Soon after his only season, Castleberry joined the Army
Air Corps and died in a bomber crash in Africa. But he left his
mark on this series, this clean-cut halfback playing only his
second collegiate game. Even now, his 19 is the only football
number retired at Georgia Tech.
</P>
<P>
   It was ages before Tech would beat Notre Dame again, again in
South Bend on a snowy afternoon in 1959. Marvin Tibbetts, another
local high-school lad, did the deed this time at quarterback. The
score was 14-10. And as a Gator Bowl sidelight, Tibbetts ran 51
yards for a touchdown against Arkansas the next year, the first
bowl game a Dodd team ever lost.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Tech finally beat the Irish the fourth time in 1976 at
Grant Field, a game as strange as a three-legged dog. Gary Lanier
was a tidy little quarterback from Savannah, short and plump. He
might have been the starter because he reminded Pepper Rodgers so
much of himself, no picturesque physical attributes but a
competitive spirit. Lanier bumbfuzzled the Irish, 23-14, throwing
not one pass. In fact, he threw only 16 the whole season.
</P>
<P>
   That was the game in which Dan Devine, irritated by the fish
thrown at him out of the Tech student section, walked out on the
field holding a mackerel in his hand, appealing to the referee.
That was when it was said, ``Give him a loaf of bread and let him
feed the multitude.'' The next season, Devine got even. He
pulverized Tech 67-14 at South Bend and Pepper Rodgers hasn't
forgiven him yet.
</P>
<P>
   The tie was probably the sweetest moment of all, coming at the
time and circumstance as it did. Notre Dame arrived in Atlanta
rated No. 1 in the national polls in 1980, Bill Curry's first
season. Tech had won one game and wouldn't win another. All eyes
were on the Georgia-Florida game in Jacksonville. Nobody was paying
attention to Grant Field. Georgia was on its way to a national
championship and, in time, would beat this same Notre Dame in the
Sugar Bowl to nail it down.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Tech clawed and scratched its way to lead by a field
goal. Three quarterbacks came down wounded, leaving Tech with a
freshman utilityman, Ken Whisenhunt, to finish it off. Notre Dame
got a tie only in the closing minutes with a field goal that
wobbled between the posts. It was as sweet as any game any Georgia
Tech team ever won.
</P>
<P>
   Another little dollop of minutiae here. Remember the movie
``Rudy,'' the Notre Dame scrub, and Rudy's one big play? He sacked
another Rudy, Rudy Allen from Columbus, Tech's quarterback in 1974.
Tech lost that one 31-7.
</P>
<P>
   So, you see, while Tech's record lists heavily to the losing
side, there has been some historic stuff registered between these
two teams. It's amazing how winning one like this Gator Bowl can
take the sting out of all the defeats that have gone before. That
said, Happy New Year.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
