<SLUG> BC-FBC-GATOR-ADVANCE01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jackets seek to reach elite
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   JACKSONVILLE, Fla. _ All season, the Georgia Tech Yellow Jackets
have talked about finishing strong, working a full 60 minutes and
taking every play as if it's the last.
</P>
<P>
   Today is the last chance for the seniors, Charlie Rogers, Jesse
Tarplin, Craig Page and Jerry Caldwell, who came in after Tech's
1-10 season in 1994 and now have the chance to reverse it to 10-2.
</P>
<P>
   A win over No. 17 Notre Dame (9-2) in today's Gator Bowl would
give the No. 12 Yellow Jackets their first 10-win season and their
first New Year's Day victory since 1990. It also would give them a
legitimate shot at breaking into the Top 10. Coupled with an ACC
championship shared with national-title contender Florida State and
the first victory against Georgia in eight years, a triumph today
also would place the 1998 team among the Tech elite.
</P>
<P>
   ``A win would really set this team as one of the special teams
at Georgia Tech,'' offensive coordinator Ralph Friedgen said.
``(With) a loss, it's another good team. A win puts them in a
bracket that few of our teams are in. You've won an ACC
championship, you've won 10 games, you beat Notre Dame on New
Year's Day. That's got to set you a little bit apart.''
</P>
<P>
   A loss would tarnish what the Yellow Jackets have accomplished,
at least in the mind of one senior.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would take away from having a great season,'' Rogers said.
``We've already had one big disappointment, losing to Boston
College. We don't want to have another one, especially when we're
favored....This is a big game. We took every game this year as a
championship game. This is just another championship game.''
</P>
<P>
   A victory also would bring the Yellow Jackets full circle from
last season's opening 17-13 loss at Notre Dame. That game had given
Tech its first opportunity to regain some national prominence since
it played Arizona when the Wildcats were Sports Illustrated's
preseason No. 1 pick in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was crushed by last year's defeat at Notre Dame,'' Rogers
said. ``I thought we had the game won. ... I don't want to feel
like that again.''
</P>
<P>
   Gator Bowl officials are expecting a sellout and the biggest
crowd since the 1989 Gator Bowl, when Clemson beat West Virginia
27-7 in front of 82,911 fans. That game was played before Alltel
Stadium was reconfigured to seat 72,433 for the Jacksonville
Jaguars. The Gator Bowl attendance mark hasn't gone over 54,000 in
the past two years.
</P>
<P>
   Notre Dame should be stronger than it was at the end of the
regular season, with quarterback Jarious Jackson ready to play
despite a partially torn right knee ligament. Jackson said
Thursday, ``I feel as close to 100 percent as I'm going to get.
It's real loose.''
</P>
<P>
   A 10th victory would not hold the same meaning for the Irish _
they have had five 10-win seasons in the past 10 years _ but it
still would mean something.
</P>
<P>
   ``Average teams win nine games,'' Notre Dame linebacker Kory
Minor said. ``Good teams win 10.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
