<HEADER>
A4101 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-MOORE-COLUMN01-CO     12-31 0557
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-MOORE-COLUMN01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The pluck of Irish lives, still puts foes on defensive
 &HT;    By Terence Moore
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   JACKSONVILLE, Fla. _ Peggy O'Leary wants everybody to know that
she bleeds white and gold for Georgia Tech instead of blue and gold
for those facing the Yellow Jackets in today's Gator Bowl. ``I used
to be a Notre Dame fan,'' O'Leary said, ``but not now.''
</P>
<P>
   It mostly is because O'Leary's son, George, coaches Tech's
football team these days. It also is because Peggy O'Leary joins
others in believing the myth that Notre Dame just doesn't ``Shake
Down the Thunder'' anymore in the psyche of the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Let's return to the latter 1980s, when those associated with the
University of Miami began a new tradition around Notre Dame known
as hearing opponents trash the Irish's old traditions.
</P>
<P>
   One Miami player was asking, ``What's a Gipper?'' Another was
threatening to torch Touchdown Jesus.
</P>
<P>
   There was more of the same after Florida State replaced Miami as
Notre Dame's Evil Empire. Even Notre Dame athletics director Mike
Wadsworth admitted Thursday that most recruits don't know much of
the Irish's storied past until they arrive on campus.
</P>
<P>
   That brings us back to Peggy O'Leary, whose former love affair
with Notre Dame was helped by both of her parents coming from
Ireland. Peggy said George joined her three other sons and four
daughters as Fighting Irish zealots during their youth on Long
Island.
</P>
<P>
   All of Peggy O'Leary's children will join her in Alltel Stadium
with their families for this one. Peggy said they'll spend the
three hours rooting only for the team with ``GT'' on the side of
their gold helmets.
</P>
<P>
   As for Notre Dame, Peggy said, ``A lot of what Notre Dame meant
to people is dying out now. They had something special with Knute
Rockne, and it lasted until about Ara Parseghian.''
</P>
<P>
   Others would extend Notre Dame's glory years through the middle
of the Lou Holtz era. Whatever. Here's the truth about the myth
that Notre Dame has lost its mystique: It's a myth.
</P>
<P>
   Courtesy of Notre Dame, the Gator Bowl is enjoying its first
capacity crowd in a decade. In fact, 109 of the past 126 games
anywhere involving Notre Dame have been sellouts. The Texas A&AMP;M
athletics department began promoting its 2001 home game against
Notre Dame five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Not only that, Notre Dame is the only football program with
contracts on national television and radio.
</P>
<P>
   And although Tech cornerback Kofi Smith said he joins many of
his peers in not knowing the Four Horsemen from a slice of
pastrami, Smith said that whatever Notre Dame had in the past still
exists.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, yeah. Definitely,'' said Smith, who helped Tech nearly
pull an upset last season at Notre Dame. ``I've never played before
a crowd like that. From the time you stepped into the stadium, you
could feel the sense of urgency from the players and the fans. It
was a unique experience.''
</P>
<P>
   ``For my generation, Notre Dame's reputation is more about the
great players they've had in recent years. It makes it more
desirable for you to want to beat them.''
</P>
<P>
   Weren't opponents saying the same thing about Notre Dame during
most of the 1920s, 1930s, 1940s, 1950s, 1960s, 1970s, 1980s and
1990s?
</P>
<P>
   Yep.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
