<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-31 20:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4105 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-2NDTAKE-NYT &LR;      12-31 0695
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 WASHINGTON: a trial.'' 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sen. Mitch McConnell, an influential Kentucky Republican and an
ally of Lott's, called the Lott-Daschle proposal a ``work in
progress'' and cautioned that it could change. Both Lott and
Daschle must present the idea to their colleagues next week.
</P>
<P>
   Gauging the Senate's response on the proposal will be difficult
until then, since senators are on vacation scattered across the
country and difficult to contact. But in several interviews
Thursday, the initial reaction seemed to serve as a warning that
the idea could be a tough sell.
</P>
<P>
   McConnell said he would back the Lott-Daschle proposal, arguing
that the Senate would, in effect, be voting on the articles of
impeachment and fulfilling its constitutional mandate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Under the Constitution, we have to dispose of the articles of
impeachment,'' said McConnell, who heads up the Senate Republican
campaign committee and will serve as chairman of the Rules
Committee in the next Congress. ``This motion sounds very much like
a disposition of the articles.''
</P>
<P>
   But others took a different view.
</P>
<P>
   Specter said he opposed the Lott-Daschle plan. ``I really don't
see how it could be done,'' Specter said. ``I don't see how
senators would be in a position to vote on that kind of an issue
without knowing a fair amount about the case by hearing evidence.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What they're really asking you to do,'' Specter continued,
``is make a preliminary vote on impeachment. But to cast an
intelligent vote on that subject would require senators to make a
determination whether there really is a factual basis for
obstruction of justice or perjury.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Larry E. Craig of Idaho, the fourth-ranking Republican in
the Senate leadership, said he was still thinking over the
Lott-Daschle plan.
</P>
<P>
   But in a telephone interview, Craig sounded skeptical,
underscoring the need to give the House managers latitude to
present their case.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think any judge or jury could effectively tell the
prosecution how they could present all their evidence,'' he said.
``I support our leaders' effort to support a timetable and a
process. But I reserve the right to adjust that timetable.''
</P>
<P>
   And Gary Bauer, head of the Family Research Council, a
conservative advocacy group, flat-out called it a ``terrible
idea.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If senators want to vote not to convict, then they ought to
have the courage to vote not to convict after a trial,'' Bauer
said.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill., the chairman of the House Judiciary
Committee who will serve as the chief prosecutor in the Senate,
weighed in on the idea on Wednesday, when he sent a strongly worded
letter to Lott, urging him to abandon the proposal and permit
witnesses to testify.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde said he was especially concerned with the notion that 67
votes, not a simple majority, would be required to initiate a
trial. With 55 Republicans and 45 Democrats in the Senate, the
resolution's success would hinge on at least 12 Democrats, many of
whom would be unlikely to support it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Senate rules and its impeachment precedents required only
a majority vote to dispose of impeachment matters other than
conviction,'' Hyde wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson voiced a similar concern, as did Sen. Craig Thomas,
R-Wyo.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're telling people in advance that you need a quick vote
and a super majority just to keep this alive, you're sending all
these wrong messages,'' Thompson said.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas said that 51 senators _ a majority _ may feel strongly
enough about the evidence to want to move to a trial and under the
current proposal, their wishes would be unjustifiably cast aside.
</P>
<P>
   ``There may be quite a few people, a majority of people, who
say, `Wait we need more facts,' '' Thomas said. ``If it took
two-thirds to go forward, Democrats won't vote for it, and it would
be over.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to abbreviate too much this final vote,'' he
added.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether the Senate could muster the 67 votes that would be
needed for a full trial, McConnell said, ``Who knows? We are all
operating under the assumption that there is not likely to be 67
votes to remove the president under any event.''
</P>
</TEXT>
