<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    49ers, Packers showing cracks
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Like the thick fog that blanketed the Bay area earlier
in the week, a veil of uncertainty hangs over the San Francisco
49ers and Green Bay Packers, two franchises that have defined NFL
stability in recent years. By Monday morning, both clubs could have
coaching vacancies.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, the imperial have become the imperiled. Franchises
that have operated with seamless precision have bared their
unseemly sides.
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers and the Packers meet in a first-round playoff game in
San Francisco on Sunday, and, certainly, few wild-card games have
been of this magnitude.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've always been teams that operated on an even keel,'' 49ers
strong safety Tim McDonald said. ``Now we're heading into choppy
waters, and it's a place that neither of us is accustomed to being.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a feeling,'' McDonald said, ``and I'm betting they
have it as well, that we're going into a game unsure how we'll come
out. It's like driving into a tunnel not knowing what might be on
the other side.''
</P>
<P>
   It is stunning enough that two teams with a combined nine
division titles in the '90s _ at least one has participated in the
past six conference championship games _ would be taken down a peg
in the same season. But compounding their problems on the field has
been a common concern about the future
</P>
<P>
   Only once in the 32 previous games in the wild-card round have
opponents combined for so many regular-season victories. Green
Bay's five-game winning streak in the series and the state of the
49ers' collective psyche provide plenty of fodder.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the pre-game buzz revolves around Steve Mariucci and
Mike Holmgren, and where each will be employed when the NFL
coaching carousel stops.
</P>
<P>
   Mariucci, in just his second season and with a .765 winning
percentage, might need a victory to keep his job. Holmgren, who
made clear his intention a year ago to leave the Packers for a
chance to run an organization, could be auditioning for 49ers owner
Eddie DeBartolo.
</P>
<P>
   ``To say it hasn't been a distraction would be a lie,'' Packers
receiver Antonio Freeman acknowledged. ``We're supposed to be the
model franchise, the team everybody else in the league wants to be.
I guess we're seeing a little of how the other side lives. There
hasn't been much change around here since I arrived (in 1995), but
the impression ... is that changes are coming.''
</P>
<P>
   The potential departure of Holmgren, who quietly courted suitors
at last year's Super Bowl, might be offset by the continuing
presence of general manager Ron Wolf, the man most responsible for
resurrecting the franchise.
</P>
<P>
   In San Francisco, however, change could be more sweeping. At
some point, the exiled owner, DeBartolo, will regain control of the
club and put his imprint on it.
</P>
<P>
   DeBartolo entrusted the day-to-day operations to club president
Carmen Policy, even before DeBartolo relinquished control of the
team to his sister while he battled federal racketeering charges in
Louisiana. When their longtime friendship deteriorated, Policy
moved to Cleveland to run the new expansion franchise.
</P>
<P>
   The conventional wisdom is that DeBartolo will purge the
remaining Policy loyalists when he returns. That means the return
of former 49ers coach Bill Walsh in a management capacity. And
since Holmgren is a Walsh protege, it could mean his return, too.
Whoever runs the team will have to cope with a budget $22 million
over the projected salary cap for 1999. Policy was the master at
manipulating the cap; general manager John McVay, a onetime 49ers
executive installed by the NFL to maintain some semblance of order,
is a novice at it. The 49ers' roster is one of the oldest in the
league, and the club's most irreplaceable player, quarterback Steve
Young, is 37.
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers' foundation clearly shows cracks, and a simple
patch-up job might not be enough to address them all. A loss on
Sunday could set off a tremor that, even along the San Andreas
Fault, would be considered a seismic event.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
