<SLUG> BC-LENDER-SCRAMBLING-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORTGAGE LENDER PACIFICAMERICA TRYING TO STAVE OFF DELISTING BY
NASDAQ
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ENRIQUE RIVERO  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- With the threat of stock-market delisting hanging
over its head and a recent default on a loan, mortgage lender
PacificAmerica Money Center announced it has taken a number of
steps to get its financial house in order.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said Thursday that the company recently completed the
sale of $104 million in loans to four unnamed institutional buyers,
is restructuring its debt and is taking other steps to improve its
liquidity and meet trading requirements to stay on the Nasdaq.
</P>
<P>
   PacificAmerica, based in suburban Woodland Hills, blamed the
weak subprime mortgage loan market for its woes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're taking steps to improve the position of the company,''
Executive Vice President Richard Fremed said in a telephone
interview. ``We're progressing to meet all our required
obligations.''
</P>
<P>
   PacificAmerica officials said management decided to sell a
``substantial amount of loans before the end of 1998 in order to
increase liquidity, pay off the remaining balance owed on the
company's warehouse line of credit and reduce the company's loan
inventory.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result of the loan sale, the company paid off the $46
million balance on a warehouse line of credit.
</P>
<P>
   In October and November, PacificAmerica sold an additional $60
million in loans through a prior agreement with Advanta, bringing
its total amount of loans sold in the quarter to $164 million.
</P>
<P>
   PacificAmerica now holds about $60 million in loans it also
wants to sell off.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the mortgage lender has defaulted on a $5.1 million
payment due to an unnamed lender, which it said at this point is
requiring only payments on the interest-only strips receivable
securing the financing.
</P>
<P>
   PacificAmerica has proposed a repayment schedule that would pay
off the debt by March 2001 and would let it keep a portion of the
cash flow from those strips during the payment period.
</P>
<P>
   Also, problems linked with the subprime market led the Federal
Deposit Insurance Corp. and the California Department of Financial
Institutions to take steps that prompted subsidiary Pacific Thrift
and Loan to stop selling loans for securitization, file a revised
capital plan and take other actions to keep regulators at bay.
</P>
<P>
   The company's stock has had a rocky year, during which it traded
at a high of $25 on March 6 but ended the year at 43.75 cents, its
lowest point.
</P>
<P>
   The company also reported Thursday that Nasdaq said on Dec. 24
it would delist PacificAmerica from its national market Feb. 26 if
its common stock does not maintain a market value of at least $5
million for the 10 days before Feb. 24, and on March 29 if its
stock price doesn't maintain a minimum $1 per share for the 10 days
before March 26.
</P>
<P>
   ``Management is currently uncertain whether it will achieve
either of these standards as required to avoid a delisting of its
common stock from trading on the Nasdaq national market,'' the
company said.
</P>
<P>
   If delisted, PacificAmerica stock would trade on the
over-the-counter market, which would reduce the ability of
stockholders to trade it.
</P>
<P>
   The weak subprime market forced PacificAmerica in October to
discontinue its wholesale loan division and led its proposed sale
to Santa Monica-based Fremont General Corp. to fall apart.
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
