A4122 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PBP-CHILD-SEAT01-COX     12-31 0692
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PBP-CHILD-SEAT01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Florida parents' good intentions not enough when it comes to car
safety seats
 &HT;    By Trebor Banstetter
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Tucking a child into a car safety seat
before a trip is one of the hallmarks of responsible parenting.
</P>
<P>
   But despite their good intentions, the vast majority of
Florida's parents aren't strapping in their children properly, a
new study says, putting them at greater risk of injury or death in
a crash.
</P>
<P>
   The study by University of Florida researchers found that 97
percent of the more than 1,500 child safety seats inspected
statewide weren't properly installed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very scary problem,'' said Morya Willis, a
University of Florida engineering researcher and director of the
Florida Child Passenger Safety Program, who oversaw the study.
``It's something that's not going away any time soon.''
</P>
<P>
   The Florida Department of Transportation paid for the study.
Researchers set up voluntary ``checkpoints'' where parents could
have their safety seats examined.
</P>
<P>
   ``We saw very, very few seats that were properly installed,''
said Mary Russell, a Florida Atlantic University instructor and
director of the Safe Communities Project.
</P>
<P>
   Russell conducted several safety checkpoints in West Palm Beach
last year for the study. ``Usually we found multiple errors,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Determining how many children are killed or injured because of
improperly installed safety seats is difficult, Willis said.
Accident reports typically don't record whether the safety seat was
correctly installed.
</P>
<P>
   But there is little doubt that cars can be dangerous places for
youngsters. Car crashes, especially those in which passengers
aren't correctly restrained, are a leading cause of death for
children, according to the National Highway Traffic Safety
Administration.
</P>
<P>
   The chief problem is that passenger seat designs vary widely
among car models, so installing the safety seat can be confusing,
Willis said.
</P>
<P>
   There are at least 900 car models, 1,000 types of child-safety
seats and 20 different seat belt systems, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The method of securing a seat in one car may be entirely
different in another type of car,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   According to the study, some common mistakes include:
</P>
<P>
   _ Placing child safety seats in the front seat of the car. If
the air bag inflates, it can smash into the child, causing serious
injury or death.
</P>
<P>
   _ Not using a metal locking clip on the seat belt. In a crash,
the clip, which sometimes comes with the child seat, prevents the
seat belt from sliding, which could throw the child forward.
</P>
<P>
   _ Loosely or incorrectly threading harness straps, which can
allow the child to pitch forward in a crash.
</P>
<P>
   _ Placing an infant in a seat designed for a larger child.
</P>
<P>
   Florida law requires any child under 4 years old to be in a car
seat. Older children are allowed to wear a seat belt _ but safety
advocates recommend safety seats for all children under 12.
</P>
<P>
   Even child safety seat manufacturers acknowledge there is a
problem with proper installation.
</P>
<P>
   ``With so many different types of car seats, it's difficult to
make them work,'' said Kirk MacKenzie, president of Snug Seat, a
Matthews, N.C., company that manufactures car seats for disabled
children. ``It's an ongoing problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Even car seat designers can have trouble correctly installing
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen car seats where it took me 45 minutes to hook it in
safely,'' said Mitchell Komisar, Snug Seat's vice president of
design and engineering.
</P>
<P>
   Safety seat manufacturers and auto makers are considering a
universal standard for child seats that would include a device to
tether the seat to the car's interior. Tethers would dramatically
decrease the chance of injury in a crash, Komisar said.
</P>
<P>
   But agreeing on a universal design will be difficult, he said,
because of the many types of seats in cars.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's also going to add some expense to new automobiles,'' he
said. ``But you have to remember, it would save a lot of lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
