<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PBP-WE-SMOKE01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fellow workers say planner is `blowing smoke'
 &HT;    By Ron Hayes
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ ``I don't even know if you can consider
me a smoker,'' the woman said, exhaling. ``I only do it when I'm
stressed.''
</P>
<P>
   She took another drag on her Capri 120. ``I don't even smoke in
my own home,'' she explained. said. ``Or in my car.''
</P>
<P>
   She does, however, smoke out here in the courtyard of the Palm
Beach County Governmental Center. For county employees, this paved
and shaded space with the splashing fountain and picnic tables _
several with large plastic ashtrays _ is that hallmark of modern
compromise, the ``designated smoking area.''
</P>
<P>
   Smokers puff through their lunch hours, nonsmokers lunch through
smoking breaks, and everyone, it seems, has an opinion about Ed
Holloway.
</P>
<P>
   Holloway, 54, a health planner for the county, is fighting for
the right to smoke inside the governmental center _ where smoking
is forbidden _ because, he says, he feels harassed out here in the
courtyard.
</P>
<P>
   Like most of the county employees taking a break in the
courtyard Thursday, the woman puffing the Capri didn't want her
name used. This is, after all, a burning issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``That building's not very well-filtered, and it's no place for
him or anyone else to be smoking because it is a health hazard,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   A sheriff's deputy who doesn't smoke was adamant. ``It's
ridiculous,'' he said. ``If he comes to work from the outside, he
can go outside to smoke.''
</P>
<P>
   One smoker who didn't mind being named was Tom McCombs, 55, an
information specialist in the Tax Collector's Office who was
relaxing with a Misty.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been here four years and I've never been harassed,'' he
said. ``When all the tables are full and people want to sit down,
we just tell them, `This is a smoking table because we were here
first.' If he can smoke inside, I think we all should be able to.''
</P>
<P>
   Fred Chatos, 58, smoked for 45 years and quit in 1992 by using a
nicotine patch.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's blowing smoke,'' the computer programmer said of
Holloway. ``He has the same right as anyone else to come out here
and smoke. Smokers choose to smoke, and they're also choosing to
leave the building when they want to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Not far away, a man and woman shared another table. She was
smoking a Merit menthol. He was puffing a Virginia Slim.
</P>
<P>
   ``Would he have his own private place to smoke?'' the woman
wondered. ``Boy, that would open a can of worms! I don't see how
they can do it for one and not everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Her partner, a smoker since he was 10, favored a smoking lounge
for all employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'd have us out here if it was snowing,'' he complained.
``Smokers are looked upon now as if you have some sort of defect,
like you're a leper. Are they going to outlaw people who eat too
much next? Some people are coffeeheads. Everybody's got
something.''
</P>
<P>
   At the headquarters of Smokenders in Vancouver, British
Columbia, vice president of operations Arnie Willcuts said the
problem isn't where people smoke _ it's that they smoke at all.
</P>
<P>
   Making people outcasts is counterproductive, Willcuts said. ``It
creates the opposite of what the nonsmoker is trying to
accomplish,'' he said. ``It creates resistance.''
</P>
<P>
   Willcuts, who's taught smoking cessation clinics for 20 years,
said: ``Ninety percent of smokers say they plan to quit, but not
today. They perceive themselves as failures because they're still
smoking, so rather than fail again, they make excuses about why
they need to smoke _ It's called denial.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
