<SLUG> BC-PANAVISION-PLUNGE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PANAVISION STOCK IN FREE FALL SINCE PERELMAN TOOK OVER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE McNARY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- 1998 turned out to be a year to forget for
shareholders of movie-camera specialist Panavision Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Shares have lost 53 percent of their value since billionaire Ron
Perelman acquired control of the company seven months ago. The
issue took a 9.8 percent hit on the last day of the year, falling
$1.375 to $12.0625 with more than 77,000 shares traded in its
heaviest volume since the takeover. At one point, the stock dipped
to $11.875.
</P>
<P>
   The activity prompted a request by the New York Stock Exchange
for a public statement about any developments that might have
caused the sell-off, which represented less than 1 percent of the 8
million shares outstanding. But Panavision, which tends to shun
publicity, made no comment and cited its policy of refusing to
respond to rumors.
</P>
<P>
   Perelman, one of the richest Americans with assets worth $6
billion, completed a $600 million buyout and recapitalization of
Panavision in early June that left him with 72 percent control. He
pledged to expand sales for Panavision, which has annual revenues
of nearly $200 million, and announced in September that he would
take over at the end of the year for longtime Chairman William C.
Scott.
</P>
<P>
   But Wall Street has been unimpressed, and the stock has slid
steadily. Panavision, which obtains most of its revenue by leasing
its cameras to studios and producers, reported in November that its
results had been hurt by declines in big-budget movie production;
third-quarter cash flow dropped 15 percent to $18.4 million and
revenues fell 9 percent to $50.7 million.
</P>
<P>
   A Panavision spokesman said employment levels of more than 300
in suburban Woodland Hills and 1,200 worldwide have not changed
significantly since Perelman took over.
</P>
<P>
   Perelman, a 55-year-old New Yorker, also controls Revlon,
California Federal, Coleman, Sunbeam and Consolidated Cigar.
Bloomberg News recently reported that investors in those companies
shifted holdings in advance of important disclosures at least five
times during 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The news service cited a two-session period in the early fall
when Revlon shares fell 18 percent for no reason, then fell an
additional 44 percent after the cosmetics maker issued a negative
earnings forecast on the third day. Investors who sold earlier were
spared the impact of the larger decline.
</P>
<P>
   However, officials at Perelman's McAndrews &AMP; Forbes holding
company told Bloomberg that they have strict policies against
insider trading and asserted there was no reason to believe that
violations had occurred.
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
