<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-CLINTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESISTANCE GROWS TO QUICK TRIAL FOR CLINTON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Several key Republicans have begun to show signs of
resistance to speeding up Senate impeachment proceedings, objecting
to a proposal that could end President Clinton's trial in less than
a week and repeating vows not to compromise on a censure deal.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal for a swift trial, floated this week by Senate
Majority Leader Trent Lott of Mississippi, drew support Thursday
from Democrats, particularly Senate Minority Leader Thomas A.
Daschle, who called the plan a blueprint for ending the matter
``fairly and expeditiously.''
</P>
<P>
   But as a number of Republicans compared opinions Thursday in
cross-continental phone calls from their home districts, it became
clear the deal was far from done.
</P>
<P>
   Among the most ardent detractors was Senator Arlen Specter of
Pennsylvania, who last November suggested Clinton should not face
trial at all before leaving office.
</P>
<P>
   By Thursday, Specter had reversed course, condemning the ``swift
trial'' proposal as logistically problematic and legally
irresponsible, and criticizing it for ``asking people to make a
decision when they're not armed with all the facts,'' according to
John Ullyot, his deputy chief of staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that the House has voted, he thinks the Senate has an
absolute duty to proceed in an absolutely judicious manner, one
that gets at the core facts and involves hearing from witnesses, if
need be,'' Ullyot said.
</P>
<P>
   Under the proposal, designed by Senator Joseph I. Lieberman, a
Connecticut Democrat, and Slade Gorton, a Washington Republican,
the Senate would hear abbreviated evidence on both sides, then hold
a vote sometime in the next few weeks on whether to proceed with a
full trial.
</P>
<P>
   If 67 senators voted in favor, a full trial could begin. If the
motion failed, they could start considering censure.
</P>
<P>
   Both Lieberman and Gorton plan to outline the proposal in
greater detail during television appearances over the weekend, and
in doing so may allay the fears of some Republican opponents,
according to Eric Federing, a spokesman for Lieberman.
</P>
<P>
   But some Republican senators and their staff members said they
expect roadblocks for any proposal that did not include at least
beginning a trial. They also said they remained firmly opposed to
censure, and the swift trial proposal, at least as they understood
it, seemed like an even lighter slap on the wrist.
</P>
<P>
   As one senior Republican Senate aide put it: ``In the current
form, it appears to accommodate the concerns of Democrats more than
Republicans.''
</P>
<P>
   A large part of the problem is the political hornet's nest Lott
is trying to avoid, according to both Democratic and Republican
staff members.
</P>
<P>
   While nearly everyone agrees there are not the 67 votes required
to convict Clinton in the Senate, and while most Democrats and some
Republicans say that is reason enough to quickly end the process, a
steady core of Republicans believes the Constitution requires a
trial without possibility of censure.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Lott) in a difficult place,'' said one Senate staff member.
``On the one hand, he is trying to avoid the partisan cut-up he saw
in the House. At the same time, he's got to please people on his
fringe as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Among those vehemently opposed to creating a censure resolution
is Senator Robert C. Smith, Republican of New Hampshire, who has
said he will vote for guilt or innocence, and nothing more.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Senate's constitutional responsibility is to hold a trial,
and, after hearing the evidence, either vote to remove the
president from office or leave him in office,'' Smith said in a
statement released through an aide. ``Where does the Constitution
give the Senate the power to do anything other than hold a trial on
the articles of impeachment?''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's objections from the Senate cane one day after some
House Republicans fired a round of criticism of their own. In a
letter to Lott, Henry J. Hyde, chairman of the House Judiciary
Committee, called on the Senate leader to allow witness testimony,
cautioning him against sacrificing ``substance and duty for
speed.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet it was unclear whether Hyde, who would act as prosecutor
during a Senate trial, was voicing the concerns of the Republican
majority in the House or simply airing his own opinions.
</P>
<P>
   Noticeably quiet was Representative J. Dennis Hastert, the
speaker-designate, who said simply that ``the House has done its
constitutional duty,'' according to his spokesman, Pete Jeffries.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is now up to the Senate to do its constitutional duty,''
Jeffries said Thursday. ``He (Hastert) is not going to get into
advising the Senate on how to do its job.''
</P>
<P>
   Daschle said Democrats are prepared to be flexible, ``But we're
going to stay within this framework,'' he said. ``We're just hoping
everybody understands our desire to deal with this fairly and
expeditiously.''
</P>
</TEXT>
