<HEADER>
A4148 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-LOCKOUT01-COX     12-31 0785
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LOCKOUT01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Final call rests with results of NBA, union meeting
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ If only to avoid a public-relations disaster, the NBA
and union negotiators will sit down in New York next week to hammer
out a labor agreement to save the season.
</P>
<P>
   While the league takes a hard-line stance, the union has toned
down the harsh rhetoric of previous weeks, is making conciliatory
gestures and has marked the specific areas required for accord.
</P>
<P>
   Players and agents will be startled if Commissioner David Stern
refuses one last chance for a deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are so close to an agreement,'' the Hawks' Dikembe Mutombo
said. ``We can write a number on the board, and they can write a
number on the board, and we can have a deal.''
</P>
<P>
   So, after nine months of discord and often strident speech, the
fate of the game rests on the good will of two groups of men who
have sought to bury each other.
</P>
<P>
   Who are they?
</P>
<P>
   The league's nine-member labor committee is made up largely of
tough, wealthy businessmen who built their own fortunes or greatly
expanded the generous hands dealt them.
</P>
<P>
   On the players' side, four of 19 members are clients of agent
David Falk, including association president Patrick Ewing and vice
president Mutombo. With Juwan Howard and Alonzo Mourning, nearly
one-fifth of the membership represents Falk's views, just one
reason the most powerful agent is seen as the union bogeyman.
</P>
<P>
   While the voices of Falk clients might ring loudest, the
committee also includes seven who earned less than $1 million last
season and a total of 10 who made less than the league average of
$2.6 million.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the accusatory Falk voices linger in the air, and the
deadline approaches with lingering animosities.
</P>
<P>
   For example, can Miami's Mickey Arison ever deal with the Heat's
Mourning in quite the same way after the player accused the owners
of being greedy, and racist besides?
</P>
<P>
   Verbally, Mourning has been the meanest bomb-thrower in this
bunch, although Seattle's Jim McIlvaine has been astonishingly
bellicose, considering his modest talent and relatively huge
contract. Players have speculated that McIlvaine, ridiculed for his
ineffectiveness on the court, is attempting to curry favor by
lambasting the owners who have made him rich beyond his skills.
</P>
<P>
   The players have spoken out often, to the public chagrin of
executive director Billy Hunter and to the detriment of their own
cause, while Stern has kept a tight rein on his people, threatening
six-figure fines for any club owner or executive who speaks out.
Only Dave Checketts of the Knicks did so, but Stern forgave his
inflammatory speech in New York. Not coincidentally, it contained a
message the league espoused.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Commissioner Russ Granik and lead counsel Jeffrey Mishkin
often speak for the league, but there is no question that this is
Stern's lockout, his list of proposals and his yea or nay on a
deal.
</P>
<P>
   The union might aim a pitch at one or more members of the
labor-relations committee, but it is Stern who orchestrates and
conducts for his side, the players say. He runs his show with an
iron fist.
</P>
<P>
   So when Hunter and various player agents wonder if Stern wants
to save the season, they are speaking of a genuine authoritarian.
It is believed that the commissioner told the owners to retain him
only if he had a free hand to retake control of their financial
destiny. And when two owners, Boston's Paul Gaston and Portland's
free-spending Paul Allen, bucked him on the lockout vote, they were
brought into line quickly. There has been no dissent since.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know David's in charge when you sit down to meet,'' the
Hawks' Ty Corbin says. ``He controls everything. You can be in the
middle of a pretty meaningful discussion with one or two of the
owners, thinking you're making progress, but if David doesn't like
the way it's going, he stops it by changing the subject or calling
for a caucus. When they come back from their caucus, the agenda
changes completely, and it's all his doing, his show.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, not all of the owners play by Stern's rules. On
occasion, committee members have shown flagrant disregard, as when
Jerry Colangelo of Phoenix attempted to broker a trade for Mutombo
during the moratorium of 1995 or when he made under-the-table
promises to Danny Manning. Only a few days ago, it was reported
that Utah's Larry Miller had agreed to give Karl Malone a $20
million annual extension starting with the 1999-2000 season.
</P>
<P>
   But on this issue, Stern makes the final call. ``You can bet on
that,'' Mutombo says.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
