<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-RECEIVERS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARDINALS' DUO FIND IT BETTER TO RECEIVE  
 MOORE-SANDERS TANDEM AT TOP OF THEIR GAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By TIM TYERS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. - Think of the great receiving tandems in the NFL,
and the mind goes directly to Minnesota and the 2,324 yards and 29
touchdowns compiled by Randy Moss and Cris Carter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each individual team in the league would give credence to
their own guys being the best, but I wouldn't trade our two for any
two,'' Cardinals Coach Vince Tobin said of wide receivers Rob Moore
and Frank Sanders. ``I know you would be hard pressed to find a
tandem that is any better.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, that is debatable.
</P>
<P>
   But Sanders, the fourth-year pro who played in a run-oriented
program at Auburn, leads the NFC in receptions with 89 and only
trails Miami's O.J. McDuffie by one for the NFL lead.
</P>
<P>
   And Moore, a product of Syracuse, needs no introduction after a
nine-year career with the New York Jets and Cardinals that has seen
him make 591 catches for 8,747 yards and 44 touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been lucky during my coaching career,'' Cardinals
offensive coordinator Marc Trestman said. ``I've had a chance to
work with Johnnie Morton and Herman Moore, Jerry Rice and John
Taylor and that group, and, in their early years, Carter and Jake
Reed, and Reggie Langhorne and Webster Slaughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frank and Rob are as a formidable group as any of those _
well, Rice and Taylor are kind of in a place of their own. But Rob
is a very experienced guy and Frank is just stepping up into his
own and still hasn't reached his potential. I know they're
certainly as good as any in the league.''
</P>
<P>
   Moore was slowed for much of the early season because of a
nagging hamstring pull that limited his performance. Sanders
suffered a bruised knee Sunday against San Diego and missed
Thursday's practice to undergo a precautionary magnetic resonance
imaging, basically just to ease his mind.
</P>
<P>
   While their combined yardage (2,127) and receptions (156) this
year are impressive, they've only produced eight touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think those numbers have been lost in a new system and a
young quarterback,'' Trestman said. ``I think the last half of the
season has been more like the production they want as a tandem, and
it will be carried on through the next couple of years.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Tobin, Trestman insists he wouldn't trade them for another
pair. Sanders is 6 feet 3, 203 pounds, and Sanders is 6-2, 200.
Trestman likes their size, strength, big-play ability and, better
yet, their character.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have big-play ability, but they can be physical at
times,'' he said. ``They're willing blockers, and we want them to
take pride in that. Eventually, we want to have the best set of
blocking receivers in the NFL, and we talk about it all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Both coaches and their teammates agree that the tandem's work
ethic has paid dividends in other areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Dave Brown came in from New York and saw them, he told
me, `You guys are lucky _ not to say the Giants' receivers aren't
good _ but those guys come out and bust their butts everyday,
whether it's mini-camp, training camp, practice or a game,' ''
Cardinals quarterback Jake Plummer said. ``You have to enjoy that
because it enables you to get quality repetitions yourself every
day throughout the season.'
</P>
<P>
   Perennial All-Pro cornerback Aeneas Williams says ``amen'' to
that thought.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have to be up there in the top three,'' he said. ``They
help me tremendously, going against the best receivers in the
league everyday.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
