<HEADER>
A4181 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-FBN-CARDS-AZR &LR;      12-31 0888
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-FBN-CARDS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ESPN'S MAGUIRE ADDS PERSPECTIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM GINTONIO  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Could  &UR; Eric Swann have lasted the whole season? Should  &UR; Deion
Sanders give it a try with his bad toe?
</P>
<P>
   ESPN analyst  &UR; Paul Maguire, who will be calling the
Cardinals-Cowboys game Saturday for ABC-TV along with  &UR; Mike Patrick
and  &UR; Joe Theismann, said it's all on a case-by-case basis, but when
he played . . .
</P>
<P>
   Maguire, who punted 11 seasons for the Chargers and Bills, let
out a little chuckle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what happened,'' he said. ``I do know that only
the people who are hurt know how badly they're hurt.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I played, you played hurt. If you didn't, they had
somebody else to take your job, no question about it. The trainers
would say you're hurt, and the coach said you could play. So I told
the coach, sure, I can play. You took a pain pill, a shot, and you
played. It doesn't work that way anymore. You've got guys making a
lot of money, and their careers are on the line, and they're not
about to jeopardize the remaining years of their careers.''
</P>
<P>
   Maguire worked last year's Super Bowl for NBC-TV. His move to
ESPN has served to solidify the broadcast, and he's able to add a
different perspective than Theismann, the former quarterback.
Maguire said it's been a great first year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we made some mistakes at the beginning, but we were
very fortunate to have four preseason games,'' he said. ``At NBC,
we had one and then got started.''
</P>
<P>
   The trio were in Tempe earlier this season to broadcast the
Cardinals-Eagles game, and the excitement level in Sun Devil
Stadium was nowhere near the current euphoria.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Cardinals didn't look like a playoff team in September,''
Maguire said. ``But you definitely could see potential. I think
during that game, and shortly thereafter, they let  &UR; Jake Plummer do
what he does best, and that's run and throw and improvise, and that
made the biggest difference in the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're turning the corner and going in the right direction
when you look at the way they won games. Good teams win when they
have to win.''
</P>
<P>
   And winning will continue to bring in the crowds, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to give fans a product, and we are talking about a
lot of money,'' he said. ``Dallas isn't always sold out. When you
talk about great support, it's anywhere that you win. They support
you when you win.''
</P>
<P>
   Plummer has triggered most of this year's excitement, and
Maguire said the Cardinals did the smart thing in giving him the
big contract. He pointed out that there are many teams in desperate
need of a top-line quarterback. And the terms of Plummer's contract
_ a four-year extension worth $29.7 million, including a $15
million signing bonus, the largest in NFL history _ didn't make
Maguire flinch.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Arizona, you have potentially a great quarterback,'' he
said. ``If you look at the Redskins, they signed two defensive
tackles for millions of dollars. Have you ever seen a defensive
tackle win a Super Bowl? I never have. I have seen quarterbacks win
them. To lock up a quarterback is the smartest thing any team can
do.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who's the youngest quarterback in the Pro Bowl?  &UR; Chris
Chandler, and he's 33. Jake's in now (third alternate). You've got
to make sure this guy is happy, I don't care what it takes. You
gotta do it.''
</P>
<P>
   This will be the third meeting of the season between the two
teams, but that doesn't make his preparation any easier, Maguire
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Cardinals have played Dallas twice and got beat twice,''
he said. ``That doesn't make the job any simpler. First of all,
what the Cardinals did in the first two games, they won't do in
this one.''
</P>
<P>
   Maguire's fear, and it's become pandemic around the country, is
that a bad call decides the game, as was the case when the Cowboys
beat the Cardinals earlier this season. He said on the air this
season that the only mistake made is an uncorrected mistake, and
that the technology is there to make the game better.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think any owner can look himself in the mirror and
vote against some sort of instant replay,'' he said. ``This has got
to be done to correct, not to embarrass. To allow some teams who
work 12 months and invest money, to have it all taken away by calls
that can be corrected . . . if you don't do that, something is
totally wrong with the entire system.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year, there were too many bad calls. The idea was always
that things level out. It won't ever level out.'' &QL; 
Note &QL; 
On the first playoff weekend, ABC has had the contract to televise
the Saturday games since 1990. CBS (AFC) and FOX (NFC) get one of
the Sunday games for their respective conferences.
</P>
<P>
   As for who got the 49ers-Packers or Cardinals-Cowobys, league
officials said there was no bidding between ABC or FOX for either
game. The NFL decided which game went to which network, according
to
 &UR; Dick Maxwell, the director of broadcasting services said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is going to be a great game (Cardinals-Cowboys),''
Maxwell said. ``Dallas is a big name, and the Cardinals are kind of
a Cinderella team. It's a great time to do a Cardinals game, and
it's a good story line.'' &QL; 
Jim Gintonio covers sports media. He can be reached at 602-444-8380
or at jim.gintonio(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
