<HEADLINE>
TEAMMATE DOES JOB WITH PEP TALK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM GINTONIO  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. - Cardinals wide receiver  &UR; Anthony Edwards, who has
been on the injured reserve list the entire season, gave the team
an emotional speech after Thursday's workout. It has been
traditional for a player to talk to the team after the final
practice of the week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I encouraged them and reminded them that we haven't reached
our ultimate goal, which is to make it to the Super Bowl,'' Edwards
said. ``I told them we have to work together as a unit and that we
shouldn't be happy to just make the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``God gave me the grace to be an inspiration, and if I can be an
inspiration, I'll do whatever I can to help the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach  &UR; Vince Tobin said that even though Edwards has not been
able, he is respected by teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anthony is a very emotional guy,'' Tobin said. ``He's been a
big part of our football team for many years. Your experiences are
based on what has happened in the past and when I first got around
a coach ( &UR; Ted Marchibroda at Indianapolis) that had players get up
and speak when we got into that playoff run. We had a guy who used
to be here,
 &UR; Freddie Joe Nunn, talk before our last game. That's what Anthony
did.
</P>
<P>
   ``Freddie continued to be the guy for us and continued to do a
great job. I just felt like Anthony would do the same thing. He's
going to be eventually a very good coach if that's what he chooses
to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Team owner  &UR; Bill Bidwill also tried the inspirational bit by
agreeing to  &UR; Tobin's request to take the nine players on injured
reserve, the four practice squad players and the four on the
inactive list to Dallas. The players can't be on the sideline but
will sit in the stands.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vince wanted them to come to this first game, and I said OK,''
Bidwill said. ``It is a reward, as long as they understand it's not
a party.''
</P>
<P>
   Bidwill's action thrilled Edwards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love it,'' Edwards said. ``It's `we' in this team. We all
should go. I feel we're all a part of this. The practice guys give
good pictures (to the regulars).'' &QL; 
His heart's in Arizona &QL;
</P>
<P>
   New York Giants Coach  &UR; Jim Fassel, the Cardinals offensive
coordinator two years ago, went through a strange metamorphosis
during Sunday's regular-season finale against the Philadelphia
Eagles. The Giants knew at halftime that Tampa Bay had defeated
Cincinnati and that they were eliminated from playoff contention.
</P>
<P>
   ``So at halftime, my emotions switched to Arizona,'' Fassel
said. ``I wanted them to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Fassel said he called Tobin to congratulate him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm genuinely happy for him,'' he said. ``The year I spent
there, he treated me fantastically, the whole organization did.'' &QL; 
Sanders, McWilliams hurt &QL; 
 &UR; Frank Sanders (knee) and  &UR; Johnny McWilliams (hamstring) are listed
as questionable for Saturday's game. Tobin said he believes
Sanders' knee is getting better, but that the hamstring injuries
bother him because ``they can go at any time.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanders underwent a magnetic resonance imaging Thursday, and it
was good news. He has what is basically a bruised knee. Tobin said
that he is optimistic that Sanders will play, although  &UR; Ronnie
Anderson is available as a fourth receiver.
</P>
<P>
   On the inactive list are defensive lineman  &UR; Jomo Cousins,
offensive linemen  &UR; Jerome Daniels and  &UR; Allen DeGraffenreid and
defensive back  &UR; Ty
 &UR; Howard. Three more will be declared on game day. &QL; 
Extra points &QL; 
The Cardinals and America West Airlines will hold a send-off today
before the team heads for Dallas. The event, which will last about
20 minutes, will be held at the west cargo ramp area of Sky Harbor
International Airport. Gates open at 10:30 a.m., and the Bandwagon,
from the Cardinals' flagship station, KSLX-FM (100.7), will provide
entertainment. The rally begins at 11:45 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's playoff celebration at the Cardinals' training
facility, from 1-5 p.m. drew thousands of fans. Players and
cheerleaders were on hand. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
