<HEADER>
A4185 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-CARDS-PAST-COACHE     12-31 0905
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-PAST-COACHES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAST COACHES PRAISE TOBIN'S SUCCESS WITH TEAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By TIM TYERS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. - Gene Stallings, Hank Kuhlmann, Joe Bugel and
Buddy Ryan share much in common.
</P>
<P>
   The four are known as football coaches to most, but Valley fans
know them as skeletons created by one of pro football's most futile
franchises, a coaching graveyard.
</P>
<P>
   They know the true meaning of frustration, each having been at
the controls of the Cardinals franchise since it was uprooted from
St. Louis and moved to the Valley for the 1988 season.
</P>
<P>
   With the exception of Kuhlmann, who now coaches Cardinals tight
ends and served as interim coach for five losing games after the
departure of Stallings in 1989, they each strived to be where Vince
Tobin and the Cardinals will be Saturday: in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Playoffs? This quartet coached a combined 189 games for owner
Bill Bidwill. They won 71 of them. Playoff games were a dream.
</P>
<P>
   But each, to a man, appreciates what Tobin has done in getting
to the next step.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have done an outstanding job,'' said Stallings, who was
fired with five games left in the 1989 season and then won a
national championship at Alabama. ``Not only with the way the
offense and (Jake) Plummer are playing, but with the way the
defense is playing, despite injuries. I'm very pleased for
everybody, and especially the fans.''
</P>
<P>
   It was no secret that Stallings and management never saw eye to
eye, especially Stallings and scouting director George Boone. He
was asked whether he is surprised the organization is spending the
money it is on talent now.
</P>
<P>
   ``Times change, and you have to keep up with them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Stallings' Cardinals carried playoff hopes into the final game
of the 1987 season at Dallas, but a 21-16 loss eliminated them.
</P>
<P>
   His first team in Arizona in 1988 was 7-4 and seemed destined
for a playoff berth. It had wins over Pittsburgh and Washington and
back-to-back victories over San Francisco and the New York Giants.
But a hip injury to quarterback Neil Lomax, combined with a series
of other injuries, sent the season into the toilet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we were close when Lomax got hurt, but it has been a
struggle ever since,'' said Kuhlmann, who was a Stallings assistant
at the time. ``It shows the importance of the quarterback, and now
we finally got a guy (Plummer) who can do it. What's good about
this is it shows people we are on the right track now.''
</P>
<P>
   Stallings lists those experiences among the most frustrating of
his coaching career.
</P>
<P>
   ``That (Lomax's injury) obviously was disappointing, but so was
not being able to finish my last year there,'' he said. ``That, and
losing the final game of the season in Dallas _ all those things
were frustrating. But you can't help injuries. Like I've always
said, the healthiest team at the end of the season is the one to
beat.''
</P>
<P>
   While oddsmakers give the Cardinals little chance in Dallas,
Stallings does.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to keep up with them the best I can,'' he said from his
ranch in Paris, Texas. ``I have a satellite dish, but I'm so busy
that I'm not here a lot and don't have a chance to watch.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have a shot. It might be a better one if the game was in
Phoenix, but the Cowboys are crippled up, too. Both teams have fine
quarterbacks, but Plummer has the ability to scramble and create.
That can be a big difference.''
</P>
<P>
   During Bugel's reign, he never saw a glass that was half-empty.
Or half-full, for that matter. It was always full, win or lose. The
community was split about his firing, believing the rebuilt
Cardinals were on the cusp of winning, but he harbors no grudge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was great,'' said Bugel, who was coaching San
Diego's offensive line Sunday when the Cardinals clinched a
wild-card spot. ``The excitement was unbelievable. I've never had a
doubt that the Phoenix area is a great sports city. The people who
live there understand the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was happy for them, and I'm happy for Mr. Bidwill and his
family, especially Michael Bidwill. He's a very bright young man
who has a lot of good ideas. He has done a great job. I'm happy for
guys like Aeneas Williams and Larry Centers, and their quarterback
is going to be a great one over the years.''
</P>
<P>
   Bugel, who also was fired after last season as the Oakland
Raiders coach, wishes he would have been allowed to see what he had
built on the field for another season with the Cardinals. But Ryan
was hired and went 8-8 with that team, then tore the roster apart
and was gone after the following year and a 4-12 record.
</P>
<P>
   So much for having a winner in town.
</P>
<P>
   ``I liked that team,'' Bugel said. ``We had (Steve) Beuerlein
and (Chris) Chandler, and the pieces were in place,'' he said. ``I
like their team now. They have a lot of good players who are close
to being great. They can give Dallas trouble because they have a
heck of a team for turf.''
</P>
<P>
   Ryan keeps track of the NFL via a satellite dish at his Kentucky
farm but says he doesn't go out of his way to follow Arizona. In
typical fashion, he manages to take a bit of credit for the
Cardinals' success.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great that they made it,'' he said. ``That Kwamie
(Lassiter) kid we picked up out of Kansas did a hell of a job. But
I'm glad they made it. Maybe it will help them with the stadium
issue. Tell Mr. B I'm happy for him.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-31-98 2107EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
