<DOCNO> NYT19981231.0371 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-31 21:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4186 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-FRIEND-SFCHRON &LR;      12-31 0644
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-FRIEND-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DICKENS WITH DARKNESS AND DETAIL 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: Check local listings for time and channel.)  
 By JOHN CARMAN  
 c.1999, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Felicitations from PBS and ``Masterpiece Theatre,'' which begin
the new year with a dark Charles Dickens tale of decay and
corruption.
</P>
<P>
   Love, too. It's sloshed in among the grime and muck of the
Thames River in ``Our Mutual Friend.''
</P>
<P>
   The six-hour miniseries, based on Dickens' last completed novel,
will be shown in three parts, on Sunday, Monday and Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   This excursion into deep, dark Victorianism is big, and it's
slow. The cast seems to include half the population of England.
</P>
<P>
   It's so big that screenwriter Sandy Welch's adaptation dwells
not only on the central love story in Dickens' novel but also pumps
a second, subsidiary love story into equal, center-ring
proportions.
</P>
<P>
   The usual objections to ``Our Mutual Friend'' also apply. One is
a plot ruse that's stretched past breaking. Another is the tendency
to lash the story onward with barely plausible coincidences.
</P>
<P>
   But it would be news if the BBC had mangled Dickens altogether.
``Our Mutual Friend'' divvies out some compensating rewards.
</P>
<P>
   Story A involves young John Harmon (Steven Mackintosh), heir to
a fortune amassed from treasures unearthed in one of London's
immense trash heaps.
</P>
<P>
   He's required to marry a stranger, Bella Wilfer (Heather
Tobias), before he can claim his inheritance. Returning to England
from abroad, though, Harmon apparently is murdered and his corpse
plunked into the Thames. It won't take long to guess that he's
still alive and determined to win Bella's love without the
distraction of the fortune.
</P>
<P>
   But Bella wants crown sterling. She tells her father (Peter
Wight) at one point, ``I made up my mind that I must have money.
And as I can't beg, borrow or steal it, I must marry it.''
</P>
<P>
   Story B is about a listless upper-crust lawyer, Eugene Wrayburn
(Paul McGann), who falls in love with Lizzie Hexam (Keeley Hawes),
the virtuous but unpedigreed daughter of a river scavenger.
</P>
<P>
   Wrayburn isn't Lizzie's only suitor. There is also a dour
schoolmaster, Bradley Headstone (David Morrissey), one of the
scarier wild and crazy guys ever to set foot on PBS. He's insane,
and he's insanely jealous of Wrayburn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Masterpiece Theatre'' host Russell Baker makes much of the
twin love stories. In truth, though, there's at least one more
that's worth comment. But these lovers aren't so young and
physically attractive.
</P>
<P>
   They're the ``dustman'' Mr. Boffin (Peter Vaughan) and Mrs.
Boffin (Pam Ferris), the kindly couple who end up with the
inheritance intended for John Harmon.
</P>
<P>
   Theirs is a settled but nevertheless palpable love. You can
almost spread your fingers and warm your hands on Mr. and Mrs.
Boffin. They're also the most recognizably Dickensian characters in
this late novel.
</P>
<P>
   The story has been pared from Dickens' weighty original but
surely could have withstood further streamlining _ maybe as much as
two hours of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our Mutual Friend'' is dark, too. And muddy. Water is a
recurring motif, and hardly a cleansing agent. At night, corpses
pop up out of the Thames, and rain seems to aid and abet dirty
dealing.
</P>
<P>
   The Brits pay customary attention to detail. If you don't mind
the thick plot and labored pace, ``Our Mutual Friend'' is the sort
of show a patient viewer can inhabit.
</P>
<P>
   The feel is always right; you can lose yourself in mid-19th
century London, with all its avarice, grime, social climbing and
snobbery. You might be treading all that water, but so be it.
</P>
<P>
   Dickens is in for a boffo few years on ``Masterpiece Theatre,''
by the way. A new ``Great Expectations'' is due in April, and
``David Copperfield'' and ``Oliver Twist'' are in the pipeline,
too.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
