r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-CARDS-PAST-PLAYOF     12-31 0823
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-PAST-PLAYOFF-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POSTSEASON HISTORY HAS BEEN SHORT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK ARMIJO  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. - It first happened in 1947. It last happened in
1982. In between, it happened four more times.
</P>
<P>
   That's six measly NFL playoff appearances in nearly eight
decades of gridiron warfare.
</P>
<P>
   And now it's happened again.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday at Texas Stadium, the Cardinals meet the unforgiving
Dallas Cowboys in a wild-card game, only the seventh time since
1920 the Chicago/St. Louis/Phoenix/Arizona franchise has ventured
into the land of the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   It's a short playoff history, yes. Short and sometimes sweet.
</P>
<P>
   In 1947, the Cardinals, coached by Jim Conzelman, went 9-3 and
edged Philadelphia, 28-21, for the NFL championship at Comiskey
Park in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals, behind long touchdown scampers by halfbacks
Charley Trippi and Elmer Angsman, grabbed an early 14-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're the ancient ones,'' said Bill Blackburn, a center and
outside linebacker on the 1947 team. ``We started it all.
</P>
<P>
   ``The greater majority of the team were just a bunch of guys out
of the service or out of college. I think we only had nine
leftovers (from the 1-9 1945 team) so we were all relatively pretty
new. But we were full of piss and vinegar.
</P>
<P>
   ``And (Conzelman) was a master at motivation.''
</P>
<P>
   The 11-2 Cardinals nearly returned to football's pulpit the
following season, again making it to the championship finale
against Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   This time, the game was played in snowy Philadelphia, where the
falling white stuff was so thick, Blackburn lost sight of the ball
several times throughout the game, won by Philly, 7-0.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seemed like every four downs both teams were having to
punt,'' said Blackburn, who lives in Richardson, Texas. ``As soon
as the ball got 20 feet in the air, we all just stood around
because we couldn't see it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember both teams agreed they wouldn't contest (referee's)
calls regarding first downs and if someone went out of bounds
because there was so much snow you couldn't see the lines on the
field.''
</P>
<P>
   Hall of Famer Marshall Goldberg, a running back and safety on
the 1947 and 1948 teams, recalls the game still was scoreless late
in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a terrible game because of the snow,'' said Goldberg,
who lives in Chicago. ``We ended up losing on a blocked punt. We
were on about our 15- or 20-yard line when they blocked our punt,
then ran it in about three or four plays later.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a good team, but I think the '47 team was better
because we were hungrier. We could taste the blood.''
</P>
<P>
   Another 16 years passed before the Cardinals' next playoff game,
a 24-17 win over Green Bay in the Playoff Bowl, a non-advancing
playoff game between second-place teams in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   ``It still was an important game for us,'' said Cardinals Vice
President Larry Wilson, a safety on the 1964 team. ``It was big
because it was in the Green Bay Packers' heyday and they had a hell
of a football team. We took the game dead serious.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals were 9-3-2 during the regular season (they split
two games against Dallas) and finished runner-up in the Eastern
Conference to eventual NFL champion Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a pretty good team,'' Wilson said. ``We had Charley
Johnson at quarterback, Bobby Joe Conrad (at flanker) and John
David Crow at running back. Defensively, we probably had one of the
best secondaries we've ever had with Pat Fischer, Jerry Stovall,
Jimmy Hill and myself. We really got along well together.''
</P>
<P>
   It was 10 years before the team's next playoff adventure,
capturing the NFC East title with a 10-4 record behind quarterback
Jim Hart, the NFC Player of the Year, and running back Terry
Metcalf, who was Hart's runner-up.
</P>
<P>
   It led to a divisional playoff game at Minnesota, where the
Cardinals lost, 30-14, on Dec. 21.
</P>
<P>
   Two days earlier, someone named Jake Plummer was born in Boise,
Idaho.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals again won the NFC East crown in 1975, going 11-3
and 1-1 against Dallas, only allowing an NFL-record eight sacks the
entire season. Seven players went to the Pro Bowl, including
Metcalf, now the offensive coordinator at Franklin High in Seattle,
Hart and linemen Dan Dierdorf and Conrad Dobler.
</P>
<P>
   In a divisional playoff game at the Los Angeles, however, the
Cardinals were beaten by the Rams, 35-23.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals again made it into the postseason in the
strike-shortened 1982 season, finishing 5-4 and losing, 41-16, in a
first-round playoff game at Green Bay.
</P>
<P>
   That year it was called the Super Bowl Tournament because 16
teams made the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   In the loss, quarterback Neil Lomax set a league postseason
record with 385 passing yards. It wasn't enough, just as none of
the Cardinals' regular-season records over the next 15 years was
enough to earn a return berth in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Until 1998. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-31-98 2108EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981231.0374 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-31 21:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4189 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SANFRAN-BOMB-ARREST-N     12-31 0565
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SANFRAN-BOMB-ARREST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOMB-MAKING MATERIALS REMOVED FROM SAN FRANCISCO UTILITY  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Police and fire investigators Thursday safely
removed an assortment of bomb-making materials, including 250
pounds of the type of fertilizer used in the Oklahoma City bombing,
from a Pacific Gas and Electric Co. service center and took an
employee of the company into custody.
</P>
<P>
   Police spokesman Sherman Ackerson said that the man, 44, who
works out of the service center in the city's Mission district,
told investigators about a storage facility a few blocks away,
where they found more bomb-making materials. The materials were
removed, but the officer would not specify what they were. The
man's home also was searched, but Ackerson said he did not know the
results of that search.
</P>
<P>
   Police did not release the name of the suspect.
</P>
<P>
   ``He obviously has a lot of charges hanging over his head,''
Ackerson said. ``But we cannot speculate as to why he was in
possession of these materials.'' He said police had no other
suspects.
</P>
<P>
   The substances found at the service center included five
50-pound bags of ammonium nitrate _ the fertilizer that was
combined with fuel oil to make the 4,800-pound bomb that killed 168
people in the Oklahoma City Federal Building in 1995 _ and a
33-gallon drum of calcium nitrate. At least one book about
bomb-making was also found at the scene, Ackerson said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the materials were discovered when an employee noticed a
puddle of water on a basement floor. An inspector traced the water
to an employee locker on the first floor of the building. Inside
the locker were the bags of ammonium nitrate, leaking because they
had been frozen and were thawing. Neither the police nor the
company would say whether the locker belongs to the suspect.
</P>
<P>
   The utility company employees notified firefighters stationed
across the street, who in turn alerted the police department. The
FBI and the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms also joined the
investigation, and bomb-sniffing dogs were brought in.
</P>
<P>
   In a larger locker on the second floor, police found broken
flares, fuses, blasting caps, the calcium nitrate and information
on how to make bombs.
</P>
<P>
   Ackerson said the frozen material was a concern because bomb
makers sometimes mix chemicals, then freeze the potentially
dangerous mixtures to stabilize them.
</P>
<P>
   Pacific Gas and Electric spokesman Scott Blakey said the
facility houses 115 employees.
</P>
<P>
   Police evacuated the two-story building, as well as 120
employees from a neighboring Pacific Gas building. By midafternoon
Thursday the employees had returned to work, and the fire
department's hazardous material crew prepared to remove the
chemicals from the site.
</P>
<P>
   Blakey said he had no information connecting the discovery of
the materials to any threats against the company. He also said that
all employees are required to wear photo identification cards, and
that other security measures are in place.
</P>
<P>
   The company has been the target of saboteurs in the past. In
October 1997, a third of San Francisco suffered a power outage
after someone deliberately turned dozens of knobs on a bank of
controls at an electrical substation. Investigators said in a
subsequent investigation that the vandal would have needed to be
familiar with the facility's operation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-31-98 2108EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981231.0375 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-31 21:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4190 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-CARDS-PAST-PLAYOF     12-31 0823
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-PAST-PLAYOFF-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POSTSEASON HIS TORY HAS BEEN SHORT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
