<HEADER>
A4192 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-CARDS-EX-PLAYERS-     12-31 1034
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-EX-PLAYERS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LONG TIME COMING  
 CARDINALS' LONG PLAYOFF CLIMB HAS BEEN BITTERSWEET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By TIM TYERS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   They sweated, felt pain and bled together. And, more often than
not, they all came up empty together.
</P>
<P>
   It's the legacy of being a modern-day Cardinal. Few, if any, can
appreciate Saturday's trip to the playoffs more than this
fraternity born of utter frustration.
</P>
<P>
   Missing the playoffs was often painful, as Larry Wilson, a
former Cardinal, NFL Hall of Famer and vice president of the team,
and Johnny Roland, the team's current running backs coach, can
attest.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the 1960s and early '70s when I played, we had good teams,
but we could never get over the hump,'' said Roland, the team's
fourth-leading career rusher with 3,608 yards. ``Making the
playoffs is significant for everybody who has put on the uniform
and tried to get where these guys are. I've had two dozen calls
from guys who are as pleased as punch.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, when San Diego scored a game-tying touchdown with 16
seconds left to set up a sure overtime period, Roland's stomach
twinged.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really melancholy,'' he said. ``In 1970, we had a
1{-game lead with three games left and lost all three. I said to
myself, `No, no, no . . . not again.' I get all choked up thinking
about it.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Getting this Cardinals team into the playoffs meant so much to
Roland that he passed up going to New York City three weeks ago to
be enshrined in the College Football Hall of Fame. Instead, he
stayed to help prepare the team for Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made the right decision,'' he said. ``Whether my presence
here was important or not, I thought it best to stay here with the
guys. They have rewarded me.''
</P>
<P>
   The closest Wilson, who is the team's all-time interceptor with
52, got to being in a playoff was a 1964 victory over Green Bay in
the ill-fated Playoff Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is fantastic, I'm so happy for everybody in the
organization,'' he said. ``People have waited so long for this; the
players, trainers, equipment guys and staff people. To them this is
special and meaningful.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we went to the runners-up bowl in '64, it was our
championship game, our Super Bowl. I feel good for every Cardinal
who has lived and died. It's never the intention to have a losing
season, and there are always a lot of factors involved.''
</P>
<P>
   He's speaking of former Cardinals like Roy Green, Ron Wolfley,
Joe Wolf, Ed Cunningham, Neil Lomax and even one-year guys like
Boomer Esiason.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm so excited, and it's probably my first time just as a
fan,'' Green said. ``I left Aeneas (Williams) a message telling him
how proud I was before Sunday's game and said I was for them _ win,
lose or draw.
</P>
<P>
   ``Down deep I was saying, `If you lose this game . . .' So many
of these guys have suffered for so long; guys like Aeneas and Larry
Centers, Rob Moore and Frank Sanders. I know how hard they work and
how difficult it is for them to keep hearing they're not winners.''
</P>
<P>
   Nobody bled Cardinals red _ literally and figuratively _ more
than Wolfley, the crazed fullback-wedge buster on special teams. He
never tasted the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like being vindicated and cleansed of the sins of the
past,'' said Wolfley, a Valley sports radio talk-show host.
``Seeing guys I played with, Aeneas and Larry, get there makes me
feel good in a weird way. We didn't always have good teams, but we
had a lot of good players who didn't win.
</P>
<P>
   ``But they got the loser tag collectively hung on them, which is
horrible. I've got to feel Larry feels the same way. He has been
positive about the organization going the right way.''
</P>
<P>
   Lomax had the Cardinals on a collision course with the playoffs
with a 7-4 record in 1988 when he injured his hip and his career
came to an end after back-to-back wins over San Francisco and the
New York Giants.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fantastic that they made it,'' Lomax said. ``In 1984, we
lost our last game to Washington and missed them. It happened again
in '87 when we lost to Dallas in our last game and we were on our
way in '88 when everybody got hurt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody pointed fingers for years at management, and rightly
so. When you're not successful, the buck stops at the owner. But
now there are new guys and new leadership, and things are going
right.''
</P>
<P>
   If you want frustration, try Wolf, the all-purpose offensive
lineman. He played under every coach the Cardinals have had since
moving to the Valley, but was released in the final cut of this
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I could've been a part of it, but I wouldn't say I'm
bitter,'' he said. ``I'm happy for a lot of my friends and all the
guys who have been through the bad times. It's what everybody plays
for. There are a lot of great football players who haven't reached
the playoffs during their careers. They will never experience what
these guys will.''
</P>
<P>
   Cunningham, a center turned CBS college football analyst, was in
the stands Sunday and said he was overjoyed.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the fun part for me, seeing the fans' reaction,'' he
said. ``This organization and Mr. Bidwill always treated me well,
and I can't be happier for everybody. Everybody talks about the
schedule and playing opponents with the worst records in the NFL.
The players don't make the schedule, they only play it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big thing is they beat the teams they were supposed to
beat, which the teams I played on didn't always do. They earned the
right to be there.''
</P>
<P>
   Esiason was not always on great terms with management,
struggling with contract clauses and such. His departure to
Cincinnati coincided with the draft of Jake Plummer, but even he
seemed pleased.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great and I'm happy for a lot of guys I know back
there,'' he said. ``The organization is much like the Jets, filled
with a lot of good people behind the scenes, who for so many years
watched the playoffs with envy.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can beat Dallas. But I don't know if they can beat anyone
else. It's tough to beat a team three times in a season, and the
last game was close. After that, though, I don't think they have a
chance in hell of beating anyone else in the playoffs.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
