<HEADLINE>
A NEW FLOCK OF CARDS  
 FLEDGLINGS DON'T KNOW ABOUT LOSING HISTORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LEE SHAPPELL  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. - Same old Cardinals?
</P>
<P>
   They are neither the same nor old.
</P>
<P>
   That they are preparing for their first playoff appearance in a
full-length season since Jake Plummer was a 1-year-old speaks to
that.
</P>
<P>
   The roster now is full of young guys who have come from winning
collegiate programs that played regularly in high-stakes bowl
games. They're not used to losing. There are 28 players who were
not yet in the league when Vince Tobin became coach in 1996 and 45
who have been added during the Tobin regime. Eight starters on
defense and five on offense are in their first, second or third
year. They are not tainted by Cardinals malfeasance past.
</P>
<P>
   They also are not the beneficiaries of any NFL playoff
experience, and that could be a factor Saturday when the wild-card
Cardinals (9-6) meet NFC East champion Dallas (10-6) in the opening
round at Texas Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``Earlier in the year, even before all the injuries, we were the
youngest defense in the league by a full year per man,'' said Dave
McGinnis, Cardinals defensive coordinator. ``Vince's philosophy is
that he is not afraid to play young people. They're not going to
get any better not playing. What we've gained from it is that now
we have guys who have stepped in and played, they've performed and
they've won. We can only benefit from that.''
</P>
<P>
   That's true on both sides of the ball. Complementing the young
defense that was among the league's best at forcing turnovers is an
offense guided by Plummer, in his second season. In his 26 pro
appearances, he has directed nine fourth-quarter comebacks. He's
working behind a line with three players in their first full year
as starters.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals reached the playoffs with three season-ending
wins, each decided by a game-ending field goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've been in so many pressure games now that I don't think
it's that big a leap for them to the playoffs,'' Tobin said.
</P>
<P>
   Chan Gailey, the first year coach of the Cowboys, whose roster
is loaded with players who have not only experienced the playoffs
but have won Super Bowls, knows that the Cardinals are reading
about it, hearing about it, and consequently thinking about it. He
said playoff inexperience becomes less of a factor once the team
gets locked away in the closing hours of preparation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big factor because everybody talks about it from Monday
to Saturday,'' Gailey said. ``But Saturday, I'm not sure it really
matters a lot. The team that has the best execution is the team
that wins. Now, maybe experience has a little bit of an effect on
that execution.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's like I told people here the other day: Every team
started somewhere. All of sudden experience just didn't show up
with the Cowboys. They had to win that first playoff game somewhere
along the line. After this game. Arizona will have playoff
experience, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Troy Aikman, the Cowboys quarterback who has three Super Bowl
championship rings, recalls when he was in Plummer's situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mind-set was to go out and be as mentally prepared as
possible and let the physical things take care of themselves,''
Aikman said. ``My first playoff game as a starter was in 1992. We
knew we were a good team, but we didn't know how good. Everything
we had accomplished that year was a first time, really, for all of
us. So we made up our minds we were going to play hard and see what
we could accomplish. The next thing we knew, we were playing in the
Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``Going from one level to the next to reach the playoffs is a
relatively easy step. But then going from playoff team to among the
very elite in the NFL and competing for the world championship is a
different deal. That's when it becomes tough, and it becomes tough
to maintain that each year.''
</P>
<P>
   The heart of the young Cardinals is a rookie class that is one
of the team's best ever, one that Tobin says ``will be the core of
our team for many years to come.''
</P>
<P>
   From first-round draft pick Andre Wadsworth, the starting left
defensive end who has five quarterback sacks, to seventh-round
draft pick Pat Tillman, who was an unexpected starter at safety the
first 11 games, they've been contributors. Second-round pick Corey
Chavous started the final five games at right corner, getting an
interception in each of the first two. Fourth-round draft pick
Michael Pittman made the key block last week that sprung Eric
Metcalf on a 46-yard kickoff return that set up the game-winning
field goal to secure the playoff bid. Sixth-round pick Zack Walz is
the special-teams leader with 71 blocks.
</P>
<P>
   Another second-rounder, Anthony Clement, who at 6 feet 7, 355
pounds is the largest player ever drafted by the Cardinals, was
pushing for a starting position in the offensive line before his
season ended in September with surgery on a herniated disc.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of rookies playing and contributing
significantly on this football team,'' Tobin said. ``I'm enthused
by our rookie class. They're not only good football players,
they're good people.''
</P>
<P>
   That speaks well for the future, according to Wadsworth.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just our first year together. There's no telling what
we can do next year, when I'm there in camp,'' said Wadsworth,
whose contract holdout lasted until the day before the first game.
</P>
<P>
   Chavous, who spent three months at safety before being moved
back to corner, where he played in college, said a reason so many
young players are performing so well is because they've been
accepted by the veterans.
</P>
<P>
   ``They took us under their wings, showed us the way,'' Chavous
said. ``It has really paid off for us. Now we have all these young
guys, just beginning to reach the upside of their careers, who have
NFL experience. Now all we need is NFL playoff experience.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
