<HEADLINE>
AIKMAN STILL HEART OF COWBOYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By David CASSTEVENS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas - It was the summer of 1989. Troy Aikman's first
training camp. The rookie quarterback's appearance in Thousand
Oaks, Calif. was such big news that my assignment was to provide a
detailed account of his first day as a Dallas Cowboy.
</P>
<P>
   It began:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 6:45 a.m.: Aikman wakes up. Yawns. Showers. Dial soap.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 7:19 a.m.: Aikman walks from dorm to cafeteria. Eats first
Cowboys breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 7:33 a.m.: Takes tray to dishwashing window, setting an example
for others.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 9:34 a.m.: Cowboys line up for calisthenics. Aikman is in
second row. Shows excellent rhythm in clapping drill.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 12:08 p.m.: Aikman signs autograph. `It's kind of a weird
deal,'' he later says of all the attention. ``That's the reason you
play, for the recognition. But I'm not comfortable with it. I'd
rather be a lineman and play in obscurity.''
</P>
<P>
   Fast-forward nine years. The Cowboys are preparing to play the
Cardinals. As the Dallas quarterback strolls into the spacious,
blue-carpeted locker room a half-dozen TV cameramen scurry toward
his locker and climb small stepladders that are arranged in a
semi-circle around No. 8's cubicle.
</P>
<P>
   He wades through. Faces his waiting audience.
</P>
<P>
   He has thrown 141 career touch down passes. Played in four NFC
Championship games. Won three Super Bowls. His playoff record is
remarkable, 11-2.
</P>
<P>
   A veteran, a celebrity, the claustrophobic crush doesn't faze
him. In fact, as he prepares to give his weekly
state-of-the-Cowboys address, a faint smile touches the corners of
his mouth. He appears amused by the media's hovering presence, the
jockeying for position, boom mikes overhead, hand-held mikes _ a
thicket of them _ thrust beneath his chin.
</P>
<P>
   They are waiting to hear from him.
</P>
<P>
   Everything he says is broadcast, printed, analyzed, discussed.
</P>
<P>
   Troy Aikman ``is'' the Dallas Cowboys. He would argue otherwise.
But it's true. Troy Aikman is his team's heart and soul. Its
leader. Its rudder. Its glue.
</P>
<P>
   In 1989 he took over a team far worse than the one Jake Plummer
inherited his rookie year. Dallas finished 1-15. Three years later,
the Cowboys won it all. In the Super Bowl, Aikman threw four
touchdown passes against Buffalo. Most Valuable Player.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone wants to know what he thinks because he is Troy Aikman
and this is his time, his favorite time of year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the playoffs,'' Aikman said. The klieg lights
illuminate his face. ``I like the finality of the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``As for why my numbers statistically might be better in
postseason'' _ no active NFL quarterback has a better passing
rating in the playoffs _ ``I don't know that I can give you a real
good answer.''
</P>
<P>
   He spreads the credit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think our offensive line drives our football team. I've been
part of some good teams.''
</P>
<P>
   He is questioned about the importance of playoff experience _ a
popular story line in advance of Saturday's first-round game. The
Cowboys have it; the Wild Cards don't.
</P>
<P>
   Aikman, Michael Irvin and Emmitt Smith have played in a combined
44 postseason games. For what it's worth, that's five more games
than all the Cardinals players with playoff experience combined.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a positive,'' Aikman said. ``But experience alone is
overrated.'' He paused, smiled. ``I'm sure Arizona will be happy to
read that.'' Playfully Aikman pictured the imaginary banner
headline in ``The'' ``Republic'' and said, ``Troy Says It Doesn't
Matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Listening to him, watching him, it is hard to believe nine years
have come and gone since the first player selected in the draft
took over a rock-bottom team that in 1989 lost to Arizona at home.
The Cards haven't beaten Aikman in Texas Stadium since.
</P>
<P>
   He isn't flashy, like Deion Sanders. He doesn't take off his
helmet after scoring as Smith used to do so the world could see and
share his smile.
</P>
<P>
   All he does is throw the ball on the money. All he does is win.
The Cowboy the Cardinals worry about most was talking about Jake
Plummer, but he could have been describing himself once upon a
time.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a very athletic guy. He's done a good job of giving them
a spark. I think he's going to be a great player if he gets a
little better supporting cast.'' &QL; 
David Casstevens can be reached at 602-444-8635 or at
david.casstevens(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
