<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-BICKLEY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAY IN SUN HAS ARRIVED FOR AENEAS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN BICKLEY  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. - Suffering is the pipeline to perspective.
</P>
<P>
   It runs through Bugel's bungling and Buddy's bloated ego.
Through fields of futility and humiliation. Through crude insults
and Leeland McElroy.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, after eight years and 78 losses, Aeneas Williams
will walk out the tunnel at Texas Stadium. And he'll finally see
the light.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be some excitement,'' Williams said. ``A chance to
go out there with the soldiers I've enlisted with and hear the
commander in chief _ Coach Tobin _ say, `Let's go.' Excitement,
yes. And I'll definitely be a prepared soldier.''
</P>
<P>
   He better be. Because for all the Pro Bowls and accolades, the
Cardinals have never needed him more than now.
</P>
<P>
   When he walks out of that tunnel, he will resume a spirited
rivalry with Michael Irvin. If not Ali-Frazier, they are the
Duran-Leonard of the NFC East. And when it's over, Williams alone
may decide how long this party lasts.
</P>
<P>
   ``A classic match-up,'' Cardinals safety Tommy Bennett said.
``Michael is a physical receiver, Aeneas is a physical corner. I've
been here two years, and I tell you what, it's been something to
watch. He has really been a thorn in Michael Irvin's side, and he's
shut him down more times than not.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, at Texas Stadium, Williams held Irvin to five catches
and 51 yards. In their rematch later that season, Irvin racked up
198 yards in receiving, including a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, in an overtime upset of the Cowboys, Williams earned
Defensive Player of the Week by shutting down Irvin over the final
36 minutes of the game.
</P>
<P>
   And this season, after Irvin lit him up in the opener, Williams
snapped Irvin's streak of 117 consecutive games with a reception.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the main things is having the ability to meet force
with force,'' Williams said. ``Knowing what to expect, knowing
you're going against someone who is going to play every down.''
Here's what else he can expect:
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals' defense will be dedicated to stopping the run at
all costs, a team that has been steamrolled by the Cowboys' ground
game in both match-ups this season. And the first priority is
taking Emmitt Smith out of the equation.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've had success running the ball against us, but I think
we're going to put an end to that this week,'' Bennett said.
``We're going to expect it and we're going to stop it.''
</P>
<P>
   Which means a secondary left to fend for itself, and no one will
be isolated as much as Williams. Against a prime-time receiver who
is starting to find his groove. A guy who was reportedly seething
over his streak ending in Week 10. A guy who will be looking for a
bit of retribution.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I hadn't thought about it in terms of my match-up,''
Williams said. ``Right now, my only thoughts are about the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course. Williams is a cornerback who plays hard, prays hard
and says very little, especially about himself. But here's what you
might not know: When Buddy Ryan came to town and made everyone
endure an 880-yard run, Williams was the only one to post a time
under two minutes. When Corey Chavous was moved to cornerback
midway through the season, Williams eased the transition, helping
the rookie at every turn.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, one of the most poignant, recurring sights of this
season is Williams and Chavous discussing the intricacies of their
craft immediately after a game has ended.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's allowed me to diversify my game,'' Chavous said. ``I've
always been a confident player, but he's helped me take that to
another level.''
</P>
<P>
   For years, he was the best the Cardinals had to offer, a
position they never had to worry about. And now the payoff is here,
the moment that always happened elsewhere, the moment that seemed
so elusive: a playoff game separating the regular season and his
annual trip to Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, I never lost belief,'' Williams said. ``I don't look
at things as permanent. I know things can change, and I knew were
going in the right direction. I knew this day was coming.''
</P>
<P>
   So the soldier is prepared. Now, if he can only be the best
player on the field, on a day when the Cardinals need him the
most. &QL; 
Dan Bickley can be reached at 602-444-8253 or at
dan.bickley(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
