<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELL ATLANTIC IN TALKS TO ACQUIRE AIRTOUCH
</P>
<P>
   In a move that could touch off a nationwide price war for
cellular telephone services, Bell Atlantic, the nation's largest
local telephone company, is in talks to buy Airtouch
Communications, the largest wireless telephone company, for $45
billion in stock, executives close to the companies said.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, which could be announced as early as Monday, would
bring Bell Atlantic, which offers cellular services along the East
Coast, one step closer to creating a nationwide and even
international wireless network. Airtouch serves the West Coast and
has partnerships in Europe and Asia that would expand Bell
Atlantic's network. Shares of Airtouch rose $3.0625, to $72.4375,
after the talks were first reported. Bell Atlantic fell $3.50, to
$54.
</P>
<P>
   EXCHANGE RATE IS SET FOR EURO
</P>
<P>
   After years of preparation, the 11 European countries locked in
the exchange rates of their currencies to the new single currency,
the euro, setting its value at about $1.17. In technical terms, the
action was perfunctory _ nothing more than plugging numbers into a
formula. But in political and economic terms, it was far broader
and signaled a new era in the integration of Europe.
</P>
<P>
   The dollar fell in the last day of trading before the euro took
effect. The dollar traded at 113.57 yen, down from 114.85, and at
1.6685 marks, down from 1.6717.
</P>
<P>
   WASTE MANAGEMENT CLOSES DEAL
</P>
<P>
   Waste Management, the largest U.S. trash hauler, completed its
$1.1 billion acquisition of Eastern Environmental Services after
agreeing to sell some assets to settle federal and state challenges
to the merger.
</P>
<P>
   STOCKS END LAST TRADING DAY MIXED
</P>
<P>
   Shares of large companies fell and shares of small companies had
their best day in two months as investors completed tax-related
selling. The Dow Jones industrial average fell 93.21 points, to
9,181.43. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index fell 2.70 points,
to 1,229.23, and the Nasdaq composite index gained 25.74 points, to
a record 2,192.69.
</P>
<P>
   In its quarterly adjustment of the so-called circuit breakers,
the New York Stock Exchange said that it had set the level for a
trading halt in U.S. markets at a drop of 900 points, up from 800
points last quarter.
</P>
<P>
   BIGGER LOSS SEEN AT NORTHWEST
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Northwest Airlines fell after an analyst said the No.
4 U.S. airline expected its fourth-quarter loss to be wider than
expected because of the effects of a 15-day pilots' strike and
higher maintenance costs. The shares fell 37.5 cents, to $25.5625.
</P>
<P>
   BANKAMERICA HURT BY HEDGE FUND
</P>
<P>
   BankAmerica's business dealings with D.E. Shaw, a securities
firm and hedge fund that suffered severe financial trouble over the
last year, are expected to reduce the large banking company's
fourth-quarter profits by about $100 million, analysts said.
Investor concern about BankAmerica's exposure to Shaw's problems
has caused a selloff in the banking company's shares. They fell
$1.5625 Thursday, or 2.53 percent, to $60.125.
</P>
<P>
   MANUFACTURING ON RISE IN MIDWEST
</P>
<P>
   Manufacturing in the Midwest picked up unexpectedly in December,
helped by rising production and an increase in inventories,
according to the National Association of Purchasing
Management-Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   The number of Americans filing for unemployment benefits rose
79,000 last week, to a seasonally adjusted 368,000, the Labor
Department said. That pushed total weekly claims to their highest
level since July.
</P>
</TEXT>
