<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-31 21:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4199 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-CARDS-PLUMMER-AZR     12-31 1388
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-PLUMMER-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLUMMER HAS GOT THE GOODS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. - Mama Plummer knew her baby boy was big in the
Valley, but when she peered down from her seat last Sunday, she
thought he had been cloned.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got my binoculars and looked down to see Jake and saw 100
red Number 16 jerseys,'' Marilyn Plummer said. ``I thought, `I'm
not going to find him.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The mother of the most popular athlete in the Valley couldn't
pick out her son in a crowd. That's quarterback Jake Plummer _
Boise, Idaho's, native son; Arizona State's Pac-10 championship
hero; and the savior of the Cardinals' franchise.
</P>
<P>
   Plummer took the Cardinals where 15 other starting quarterbacks
couldn't in 11 seasons in Arizona, to the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals (9-7) meet the Dallas Cowboys (10-6) on Saturday
at Texas Stadium in the team's first non-strike playoff game in 15
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Plummer is flying his mother from Boise to Dallas for the game.
He's also paying for the flights of his father, Steve, from Coeur
d'Alene, Idaho; brother, Eric, from Connecticut; and brother,
Brett, from Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, he can afford it. The Cardinals just made him the
second-richest player in the NFL, giving him a four-year extension
worth $29.7 million and the biggest signing bonus in league history
at $15 million.
</P>
<P>
   Think the money is going to change him? Ask his teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's 3 years old,'' center Aaron Graham said. ``I asked him
what he wanted for Christmas, and he said a remote-control car.
Yes, a remote-control car. So I bought him a remote-control car.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Have you seen how he dresses?'' asked reserve wide receiver
Chad Carpenter, another second-year pro from Idaho. ``He wears
flannel shirts and cotton long-sleeve T-shirts. He knows what type
of lifestyle he wants to live. He could live in the mountains.''
</P>
<P>
   The family did live in Idaho's Sawtooth Mountains for six years,
when Plummer was 3 to 9 years old.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Jake was 3, a family friend, Buzz Cheatum, took him
cross-country skiing and called him, ``Jake the baker, the money
maker,' '' Plummer's mother said. ``Who would have thought Buzz
Cheatum would be prophetic?'' &QL; 
Instant success
</P>
<P>
   Former San Francisco 49ers Coach Bill Walsh predicted Plummer's
success two years ago. He advised the 49ers to draft him, listing
17 positive features and six negative features.
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers ignored him, taking Virginia Tech's Jim Druckenmiller
in the first round even though Walsh, in scouting notes, compared
Plummer to Joe Montana six times.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this stage, he is almost identical to Joe,'' one of Walsh's
notes read.
</P>
<P>
   Another said, ``Expect a long-term future _ he seems to be
ideally suited to the 49ers' offensive system.''
</P>
<P>
   Walsh, who was a consultant to the 49ers at the time, told the
``San'' ``Francisco Chronicle'' this week that ``there's no
question (Plummer) is going to be a great player.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Plus, he's a dynamic player,'' Walsh added. ``He's going to be
the central figure whenever he takes the field, like Joe was.''
</P>
<P>
   It took former Cardinals receiver Roy Green one game to realize
that Plummer had a chance to be something special. Plummer drove
the team 98 yards for a go-ahead touchdown in his first possession
13 months ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``To do what he has done, plus carrying the burden on so many
other things is incredible,'' Green said. ``From his first series
against the Eagles, it was like people were saying, `Jake, take us
there.'
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like what (Washington cornerback) Darrell Green said,
``You just look at him and you can tell he likes to play the game.'
''
</P>
<P>
   In two seasons, Plummer has led the Cardinals to nine comeback
victories in 26 games. ``It's just a matter of believing, having
the attitude to get it done,'' Plummer said. ``That attitude is
different here than in years past.''
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, Plummer won twice in nine starts. He couldn't
believe the way some players accepted losing. He was determined to
hit the road if that didn't change.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year was tough,'' Plummer said of the 4-12 season. ``I
saw a lot of things I didn't like. There were guys laughing on the
plane after we got our butts kicked or lost a close one. I couldn't
believe it. If a salesman went out on the road and sold nothing, he
wouldn't be laughing.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the season, at a team meeting, I said somethings about
that. Some of the guys like what I said. A few of the guys knew
they had done it and didn't like it. But I just said what I felt.''
</P>
<P>
   This season, Plummer has led the Cardinals to seven
come-from-behind victories, including the past three weeks when
they won each game on a Chris Jacke field goal on the final play of
the game.
</P>
<P>
   Last Sunday, San Diego tied the score at 13, with 16 seconds
left. But after Eric Metcalf's 46-yard kickoff return, Plummer's
10-yard completion set up Jacke's game-winning 52-yard field goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way things have been going for us, you see 40 seconds and
go, `Sweet,' '' Plummer said. ``We've got a whole day working for
us.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past eight games, Plummer has completed 59 percent of his
passes for 2,515 yards and 11 touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   The last time the Cardinals played Dallas, he threw for 314
yards in the second half and 465 yards overall, the second most
allowed by the Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that got everybody's attention,'' Cowboys quarterback
Troy Aikman said, ``not only in that ballgame, but look at the
season the Cardinals have had, and the games they've been in, and
the close games, and the way they've been able to pull a number out
and win.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jake just starts playing on instinct as much as anything else,
realizing the situation, knowing that you've got to start taking
some chances and zip some balls in. . . . I think Jake is at his
best when able to get outside the pocket and put some pressure on
that defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Graham said Plummer is most dangerous when ``we play controlled
backyard football.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Ferguson, team vice president of player personnel, refers to
Plummer as Captain Choas.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you saw him at the combine after his senior year, you
looked at him, his measurables, you said, `He's fine but nothing
special,' '' said New York Giants Coach Jim Fassel, former
offensive coordinator of the Cardinals. ``Then, you watched him in
game-type situations, and he just made play after play after play.
. . . They may have gotten the steal of the whole draft that
year.'' &QL; 
Only just begun
</P>
<P>
   Plummer knows he's far from a finished product. After all, he
has thrown 20 interceptions and 17 touchdown passes this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has unlimited potential,'' offensive coordinator Marc
Trestman said. ``When he reaches that potential, I don't know. But
I do know that he's an extremely special guy. He loves ball. He
loves to play. He's a very charismatic young man. He's a natural, a
natural leader.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacke said Plummer's leadership skills remind him of former
Green Bay teammate Brett Favre, three-time Most Valuable Player.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you put both of them in different uniforms, they're almost
exactly the same,'' Jacke said. ``They're out there doing things,
and you scratch your head and wonder how they do them.''
</P>
<P>
   Carpenter thinks Plummer's small-town upbringing is a big reason
for his success. ``You're just like everybody else,'' he said.
``People there don't put you on a pedestal. They're grounded.''
</P>
<P>
   He said Plummer's brothers don't give him a break and try to
beat him in everything from pingpong to video games.
</P>
<P>
   Plummer has an eclectic background.
</P>
<P>
   His mother fed him carrot juice and home-grown basil. His
cousin, Susie Davis, toured with the artist formerly known as
Prince, Van Morrison and Billy Idol. His uncle, Norman Davis, was a
Bay area disc jockey who sent the family his favorite tapes _ Pink
Floyd, Bob Marley and Jimi Hendrix, among them.
</P>
<P>
   Then, there was Plummer's grandmother, who was a devout
Seventh-day Adventist.
</P>
<P>
   Plummer took it all in and it helped him ``hit it off with
everybody,'' according to Trestman.
</P>
<P>
   Just ask Ben Keller, 13, a fan who showed up at the team's
training facility Thursday wearing Plummer's No. 16 jersey.
</P>
<P>
   ``My brother (Lance) bought it for me,'' Keller said. ``It was
the best Christmas gift I received.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
