r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEIBOWITZ-COLUMN-AZR &LR;      12-31 0697
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEIBOWITZ-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LIGHT, A VOICE GONE OUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID LEIBOWITZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - They are burying him in a New York cemetery as I write
this. I cannot be there, do not belong. I never met the man in
person, only through his words. All the same, I stole from him,
learned from him, owe him. I figure making good on my debt requires
at least a few hundred words.
</P>
<P>
   They will be sad words, let me say up front. Mike McAlary dying
colors newspapers a deeper shade of gray. It is always that way
when brilliance quits the game.
</P>
<P>
   McAlary died Christmas Day, courtesy of colon cancer. He was 41.
He leaves a wife, four kids and a few thousand columns about a few
thousand city streets.
</P>
<P>
   God, what tales. What a voice, what rhythm. Scalpel-sharp,
pitch-perfect. Every sentence tugged like a finger crooked around
your conscience. I didn't read McAlary whenever I got the ``New
York Daily News''; I held each word tight as an infant. I needed
those words.
</P>
<P>
   This was in 1992, back East. Fresh out of journalism school, I
got a job in Trenton as a copy editor. It was a newspaper job,
yeah, but fixing other people's words wasn't my thing. I wanted to
tell stories. I dreamed of my face above a byline.
</P>
<P>
   Every day, I barged in on Gale Baldwin, the editor, and
volunteered to write columns. Every day, he sent me back to writing
headlines. Then one day he didn't _ he wanted some samples. I had
some in me he liked, and Gale had a thought: I could write columns
by day _ for free _ and edit copy by night. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Only 1 problem &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It was a great break. It presented a huge problem. Namely, I
sucked.
</P>
<P>
   I had no feel for the form, no sense of structure, no voice in
print. My true talent was saying in a hundred words what could've
been said in 10. Detail was the thing I missed that everyone else
saw.
</P>
<P>
   But I could read, and I could scavenge.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Royko for humor. Jimmy Breslin for street sense. McAlary
for style.
</P>
<P>
   I tore out every column, parsed it, memorized. Yes, some columns
fell short. Yes, McAlary himself found trouble _ with a car crash
that almost killed him in 1993, with a since-dropped libel suit in
1996. But most of his work sang. The clippings are deep beige now,
but I still read them whenever I feel lost on a story.
</P>
<P>
   The one about the 4-year-old stuffed down a garbage chute.
</P>
<P>
   The one about Jimmy Miracle, the junkie dying of AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   The one about a punk on trial for his role in the Crown Heights
riot.
</P>
<P>
   ``His defense,'' McAlary wrote, ``is that he was just another
rioter in a block of rioters _ just another clenched fist on a
headless body of rage.''
</P>
<P>
   Fine line, but not his best.
</P>
<P>
   McAlary saved those for 1997, for the story of Abner Louima and
Brooklyn's 70th Precinct cops.
</P>
<P>
   I was following from afar then _ my McAlary imitation having
evolved into writing columns for pay, then a spot on this page.
Last summer, an anonymous tip on McAlary's answering machine became
seven columns that seared a city: Louima, a 30-year-old Haitian
immigrant, had been sodomized by White police officers wielding a
plunger. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Other dreams &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   McAlary went from a chemo treatment to Louima's bedside. He
broke the story in print, got every interview that mattered. In
April, those columns won the Pulitzer Prize for commentary.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the pinnacle in journalism, but there is so much more
I want to do in life,'' McAlary said. ``I want to dance at my
daughter's wedding and walk old and gray on the beach with my wife.
See my son, Ryan, graduate from college.''
</P>
<P>
   Those spare phrases evoke deep dreams _ dreams denied. So it was
in McAlary's columns; so it was in his life.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't live to fulfill his every dream. He gave voice to many
of mine.
</P>
<P>
   This means I owe him. These words are partial payment. I will
read the yellow news clippings again on many days, up against many
deadlines. I will recite the best lines out loud. I will think
``God, if only.'' I will try like hell to measure up.
</P>
<P>
   It is always that way when brilliance quits the game. &QL; 
 &QL; 
David Leibowitz can be reached at david.leibowitz(at)pni.com. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-31-98 2115EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
