<HEADER>
A4202 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-MODESTI-COLUMN-LA     12-31 1057
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ECLIPSE RACES ARE CLOSE CALLS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARCADIA _ If you like the tingling headache that comes from
trying to pick tomorrow's winners, you'll love the challenge of
picking last year's champions.
</P>
<P>
   It was a rare season when strong arguments could be made for
more than one candidate in most Eclipse Award divisions.
</P>
<P>
   Balloting by racing writers and executives ends Jan. 5. Results
will be announced Feb. 16 at an awards dinner in Bal Harbour, Fla.
Until then, happy old year:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 2-year-olds: &LR;  Bob Baffert-trained Exploit is probably the most
talented of the group, and he'll get the votes of those who treat
this category as a Kentucky Derby future book. But Exploit skipped
the Breeders' Cup Juvenile, won by favored Answer Lively at
Churchill Downs. And we're rewarding achievement, not ability
(aren't we?).
</P>
<P>
   Who should win: Answer Lively. Who will win: Answer Lively or
Exploit.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 2-year-old fillies: &LR;  Baffert dominated with Golden Eagle Farms'
Excellent Meeting, who was best in the West, and Mike Pegram's
Silverbulletday, who beat her in the Breeders' Cup Juvenile Fillies
while winning 6 of 7.
</P>
<P>
   Who should win: Silverbulletday. Who will win: Silverbulletday.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 3-year-olds: &LR;  Wish we'd seen a race between Real Quiet, who
came within a nose of the Triple Crown, and Coronado's Quest, who
had a great run from April to August before flopping against older
horses. But Real Quiet was hurt after the Belmont and Coronado's
Quest was too much of a head case to face the big crowds at the
3-year-old classics.
</P>
<P>
   Who should win: Real Quiet. Who will win: Real Quiet.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 3-year-old fillies: &LR;  Flip a coin: Banshee Breeze led the group
in earnings, won at distances from 7 furlongs to 1{ miles, beat
elders in the Spinster and lost the Breeders' Cup Distaff by just a
nose to 5-year-old Escena. Jersey Girl went undefeated and beat
Banshee Breeze once but got hurt before facing elders.
</P>
<P>
   Who should win: Banshee Breeze. Who will win: Banshee Breeze or
Jersey Girl.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Older males: &LR;  There was an Awesome Again groundswell after the
Frank Stronach-owned colt completed an undefeated year by winning
the Breeders' Cup Classic. But reflective voters realize Skip Away
won major races in six states during a rugged campaign and was
simply worn out when he finished sixth in the Classic.
</P>
<P>
   Who should win: Skip Away. Who will win: Skip Away.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Older fillies and mares: &LR;  I'm supporting Wally Dollase-trained
Sharp Cat, who had to miss the Breeders' Cup Distaff, over Escena,
who won that race. This isn't a vote for what might have been. This
is a vote for what Sharp Cat achieved in her brief season: She
never trailed while going 4 for 4 by a combined 23 lengths and
earned a Beyer speed figure (119) in Skip Away's realm when she and
jockey Corey Nakatani ran away with the Beldame.
</P>
<P>
   Who should win: Sharp Cat. Who will win: Escena.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Turf horses: &LR;  Fascination with Da Hoss' two-race campaign may
net the Breeders' Cup Mile winner a couple of votes. But this looks
like a romp for Breeders' Cup Turf winner Buck's Boy.
</P>
<P>
   Who should win: Buck's Boy. Who will win: Buck's Boy.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Turf fillies and mares: &LR;  Fiji deserves to be the easiest winner
of the year after going 6 for 7 in Southern California for the
amazing trainer-jockey team of Neil Drysdale and Kent Desormeaux.
</P>
<P>
   Who should win: Fiji. Who will win: Fiji.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Sprinters: &LR;  Kelly Kip won up and down the East Coast but his
season ended in September. Affirmed Success was a deserving
favorite in the Breeders' Cup Sprint but turned out to be another
New York 7-furlong specialist. That leaves Craig Dollase-trained
Reraise, who led all the way in the Breeders' Cup race under
Nakatani to go 4 for 4 at the classic sprint distance of 6
furlongs.
</P>
<P>
   Who should win: Reraise. Who will win: Reraise.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Horse of the Year: &LR;  Those who vote for Awesome Again must ask
themselves: Do I mean to encourage campaigns like the one Patrick
Byrne plotted for Awesome Again, who ducked the big races until the
Breeders' Cup, or campaigns like the one Sonny Hine plotted for
Skip Away, who stared into the spotlight all year? Easy question.
We'll be lucky to see another horse like Skip Away anytime soon.
</P>
<P>
   Who should win: Skip Away. Who will win: Skip Away.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Jockeys: &LR;  The West's Gary Stevens leads the East's Jerry Bailey
in earnings and in Grade I winners ridden, was the hero of the
sensational Belmont Stakes and had two Breeders' Cup victories to
Bailey's one. If Stevens doesn't get the Eclipse this year, it's
only because voters can't break the Bailey habit.
</P>
<P>
   Who should win: Stevens. Who will win: Bailey, for the fourth
straight year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Trainers: &LR;  Santa Anita-based Baffert led the nation in earnings
with a barn topped by Silver Charm, Real Quiet, Silverbulletday,
Excellent Meeting and Exploit.
</P>
<P>
   Who should win: Baffert. Who will win: Baffert, for the second
straight year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Owners: &LR;  Assuming 3-year-old Real Quiet and 2-year-old filly
Silverbulletday win Eclipses, Mike Pegram will be the first person
in the '90s to be the outright owner of two champions in the same
year. Pegram's frat-boy personality rubbed the racing establishment
the wrong way, another reason to vote for him.
</P>
<P>
   Who should win: Pegram. Who will win: Pegram, Stronach or
Carolyn Hine (Skip Away).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Happy new era: &LR;  This is the day Californians will begin
wagering on full programs from out of state, in effect doubling the
menu for Santa Anita fans. Today, in addition to eight races at
Santa Anita and eight from Golden Gate Fields near San Francisco,
we can bet on nine from Aqueduct in New York and 11 from Calder in
Miami.
</P>
<P>
   After the Miami horses move from Calder to Gulfstream Park on
Sunday, we'll be able to follow the East Coast's classiest winter
track, with important 3-year-old races leading to the March 13
Florida Derby.
</P>
<P>
   A law passed last summer permits California tracks to take as
many as 20 races a day from out of state. Until now, they've been
limited to a few big-purse races.
</P>
<P>
   Gauging the popularity of the expanded simulcasting will take
more than a day. Fans will have to be at Santa Anita or a satellite
pretty early on New Year's morning to bet on the 9:30 a.m. first
races. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-31-98 2117EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
