<SLUG> BC-PHOTO-FULL-UPDATE-NYT </SLUG>
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving 12/31/98. Photo clients will
automatically receive these photos via AP's PhotoExpress or may
download them from either the Wieck Photo Database in Dallas at
972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 305-448-8411.
Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling (888) 603-1036
or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT31) NEW YORK -- Dec. 31, 1998 -- NEW-YEAR'S-FLOATER, 12-31
-- Revelers wait for the New Year on Times Square. Despite
temperatures in the low- to mid-20s, the party was expected to draw
500,000 people. (James Estrin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT30) STATE COLLEGE, Penn. -- Dec. 31, 1998 --
DANCE-BALLROOM-4, 12-31 -- Aimee Feist, 21, and Shawn Bonham, 22,
do the Jitterbug at Penn State University. Across the country
partner dancing, both traditional ballroom and swing, is sweeping
colleges. (Librado Romero/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT29) UNDATED -- Dec. 31, 1998 -- GRAHAM-SUCCESSOR, 12-31 --
Ever since the colonial era, America has had a pre-eminent preacher
who played an unofficial role as national evangelist. For the last
50 years, that role has been filled by the Rev. Billy Graham. But
at the turn of the new century, with Graham now 80, the question
arises who, if anyone, can take his place. Speculation focuses on,
from left, Rev. Greg Laurie, Rev. Anne Graham Lotz, Dr. Luis Palau,
and Bishop T.D. Jakes. (Monica Almeida, MJ Sharp, John Gress, Danny
Turner/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT28) UNDATED -- Dec. 31, 1998 -- FUGITIVE-PUERTO-RICO-B&AMP;W,
12-31 -- Part of an F.B.I. wanted poster showing Filiberto
Ojeda-Rios through the years. Ojeda-Rios, sought for his alleged
involvement in a 1983 armed robbery as well as involvement with the
Puerto Rican nationalist group, frequently voices his opinions on
the status of the island via news releases and video appearances.
(New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) UNDATED -- Dec. 31, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JAN. 3 --
INVEST-PSYCH, 12-31 -- Dr. Ari Kiev uses his background in
psychiatry to serve as a ``trading coach'' for Wall Street hedge
funds. Kiev says his services help traders change self-defeating
behavior. ``I've encountered a guy making $30 million a year who is
still afraid, who doesn't feel like a success,'' he says. (Ruby
Washington/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) LONDON-- Dec. 31, 1998 -- EURO-FATHERS, 12-31 -- Sir
Edward Heath, the former Prime Minister of Britain, in his office
recently. Heath was one of three world leaders who took some of the
earliest steps toward a single currency in the 1970's, and kept
promoting the idea even when it seemed to lose its luster.
(Jonathan Player/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) LHASA, Tibet -- Dec. 31, 1998 -- TIBET-YAKHERDS, 12-31
-- A yak meat vendor cuts up slices at the local market. Tibet may
be known around the world as a mountainous region where a devoutly
religious people have been persecuted by their Chinese landlords,
but everyone has to eat. In Tibet, shopping for food inevitably
includes a trip to the yak meat market. (Seth Faison/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) UNDATED -- Dec. 31, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JAN. 3 --
CAR-SMART-FORD-2, 12-31 -- Ford is knocking on wood with the new
Lincoln Blackwood. It looks much like a Lincoln Navigator from
front bumper to back doors, but behind those is a pickup bed lined
with stainless steel and covered by a metal top. The exterior is
accented with dark, trendy Wenge wood - not an applique - from
Africa. (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) UNDATED -- Dec. 31, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JAN. 3 --
CAR-SMART-FORD-1, 12-31 -- The new Ford Thunderbird is perfect for
baby boomers intent on taking a Sunday drive down memory lane. This
rear-drive, V8-powered two-seat roadster uses styling touches from
the 1955-57 and 1961-62 T-Birds and uses pastel colors from those
periods. Aluminum provides a modern touch. (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) NEW YORK -- Dec. 31, 1998 -- TRAVIATA-OPERA-REVIEW,
12-31 -- Marcello Giordani singing the role of Alfredo and Ainhoa
Arteta as Violetta in the new cast in ``La Traviata'' at the
Metropolitan Opera. Ms. Arteta has the high notes and agility for
the role as well, and although it took her a few moments to find a
comfortable level, she has the power to project into the hall.
(Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) UNDATED -- Dec. 31, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JAN. 3 --
ABOUT-CARS-GM-2, 12-31 -- The Pontiac Aztek is hard to
characterize, but it grabs attention. Starting with the 1999 North
American International Auto Show in Detroit, and continuing through
the other leading shows this year, GM wants the world to know that
a lot is going on behind the closely guarded doors of its design
center. (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) UNDATED -- Dec. 31, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JAN. 3 --
ABOUT-CARS-GM-1, 12-31 -- The Cadillac Evoq casts hints as to where
the division is heading. The Evoq (pronounced evoke) has sharp
edges and a retractable hardtop similar to that of the Mercedes
SLK. (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) STATE COLLEGE, Penn. -- Dec. 31, 1998 --
DANCE-BALLROOM-3, 12-31 -- A student puts on her dancing shoes
before a ballroom instruction class at Penn State University.
Across the country partner dancing, both traditional ballroom and
swing, is sweeping colleges. (Librado Romero/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) STATE COLLEGE, Penn. -- Dec. 31, 1998 --
DANCE-BALLROOM-2, 12-31 -- Penn State University students Alicia
Bandaranayake,19, is dipped by her partner Steve Kretzing, 22,
while learning the Tango in a ballroom dancing class. Across the
country partner dancing, both traditional ballroom and swing, is
sweeping colleges. (Librado Romero/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) STATE COLLEGE, Penn. -- Dec. 31, 1998 --
DANCE-BALLROOM-1, 12-31 --Students at Penn State University learn
to Samba in a ballroom dancing class. Across the country, partner
dancing, both traditional ballroom and swing, is sweeping colleges.
(Librado Romero/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) UNDATED -- Dec. 31, 1998 -- CARS-DESIGN-2, 12-31 --
Audi's aluminum accents. With basic transportation needs largely
sated and manufacturing technology giving auto makers the
flexibility of short-order cooks, car design is entering an era of
``creative anarchy'' in which individual customers have as much say
about what their vehicles look like as the designers. (New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) UNDATED -- Dec. 31, 1998 -- CARS-DESIGN-1, 12-31 --
Mercedes's colorful leather embodies a trend toward styles which
keep breaking the mold. ``These days, almost every car is safe,
reliable and performs well,'' says Gregory Brew, assistant chairman
of the transportation design department at the Art Center College
of Design in Pasadena, Calif. ``Now, the trick is to provide that
extra little something that creates attachment to an inanimate
object.'' (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) PEVEK, Russia -- Dec. 31, 1998 -- RUSSIA-NORTH-2, 12-31
-- A man walks past a communist-era hammer and sickle that has been
spray painted to read: ``The Exploited'' near the harbor to
Russia's most northern city. Trapped in Russia's frozen frontier,
many workers resemble the political prisoners who were brought here
decades ago. They are unable to leave and are often not even paid
-- at least not promptly, and not always with money. (Otto Pohl/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) PEVEK, Russia -- Dec. 31, 1998 -- RUSSIA-NORTH-1, 12-31
-- Frozen Russian naval ships fill the harbor of Russia's most
northern city. A winter's day here is two hours of cheerless gray.
Meanwhile, the temperature plunges to 40 degrees below zero
Fahrenheit. And delays in getting wages are measured in years, not
months. (Otto Pohl/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) LONDON -- Dec. 31, 1998 -- BORDERS-BOOKS, 12-31 --
Shoppers at the Border Bookstore in London. While Barnes &AMP; Noble
and Amazon.com are battling over the so-far unprofitable spoils of
the Internet, Borders is investing in terra firma. During 1999,
Borders plans to accelerate its expansion of stores in
English-speaking countries throughout the world. (Carlos
Lopez-Barillas/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEW YORK -- Dec. 31, 1998 -- NY-HOOTERS, 12-31 -- Empty
chairs predominate the scene at Hooter's in New York's West Side.
It may be a popular chain restaurant in the rest of the country,
but Hooters, known almost entirely for its waitresses, is failing
to attract customers in Manhattan and has filed for chapter 11
bankruptcy protection. (Dith Pran/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) MALIBU BEACH, Calif. -- Dec. 31, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN.,
JAN. 3 -- STOCKS-COLLATERAL, 12-31 -- Robert Kramer bought his
$965,000 home in Malibu Beach with no down payment - but $400,000
of stock as collateral. ``It's been highly favorable in my
situation,'' he says. (Kim Kulish/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) SAN FRANCISCO -- Dec. 31, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JAN. 3
-- INVEST-WITH-CALLINAN, 12-31 -- In managing his fund, Jim
Callinan keeps an eye out for companies that capitalize on small
slices of the markets in growing industries. ``Whenever there's an
IPO period that's pretty intense, we buy a lot of stocks, and then
we kind of, over the next six months, filter through them and get
rid of the bad eggs,'' he says. (Peter DaSilva/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) NEW YORK -- ADV. FOR SUN., JAN. 3 -- Dec. 31, 1998 --
BIZ-RETIRE-2, 12-31 -- Bill Price playing chess at home in Brooklyn
with his granddaughter, Eva Kamer, 8. Price joined McKinsey &AMP; Co.,
a consulting firm, as a secretary, eventually becoming a
communications manager. Recently, he asked to work three days a
week instead of five. ``I was approaching 59,'' he says. ``That's
when I said, 'I'd like to have more time for myself.' `` (Andrea
Mohin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) OAK PARK, Mich. -- Dec. 31, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JAN. 3
-- BIZ-PROFILE-FARR, 12-31 -- A retired Detroit Lions star who
built the nation's largest chain of black-owned auto dealerships,
Mel Farr is seeking investment capital for his business and, by
extension, black America. ``Auto manufacturers have abandoned urban
areas,'' he says. (Peter Yates/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) TRUTH OR CONSEQUENCES, N.M. -- ADV. FOR SUN., JAN. 3 --
Dec. 31, 1998 -- BIZ-RETIRE, 12-31 -- John Wheeler still practices
law, but now does so from an office in his home in Truth or
Consequences, finding time between recreational forays into former
mining country. ``I work when I want to,'' he says. (Cary Herz/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) MARKS, Miss. -- Dec. 31, 1998 -- FREEDOM-RIDER-3-BOS,
12-31 -- Robert Jamison, the Assembly man for National Community
Development Organization in Marks, greets prisoners in the local
jail on a Monday morning. He was able to help out William
Cunningham who was jailed over the weekend for having an open
container. (Bill Greene/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) ELBRON, Va. -- Dec. 31, 1998 -- FREEDOM-RIDER-2-BOS,
12-31 -- Walter Hardy, right, chats with Terry Lewis at a dinner.
Hardy, who had worked as a gardener and a chauffeur for a
well-to-do white family, was working at a packing plant when he met
Donald Anderson. Now, as a founding father of the Assembly in Surry
County, he serves on its Board of Supervisors. (Bill Greene/Boston
Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) EAGLE ROCK, Va. -- Dec. 31, 1998 -- FREEDOM-RIDER-1-BOS,
12-31 -- Donald Anderson, the head of National Community
Development Organization, stands inside his ancestors' burial
ground on a mountain owned by his family. Anderson, who is the
decendant of slaves, has transformed once disenfranchised men and
women in small, forgotten towns into leaders. (Bill Greene/Boston
Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NEW YORK -- Dec. 31, 1998 -- PERMANENT-COLLECTIONS, 12-31
-- Visitors to the at the Kennedy Galleries sit opposite works by
Charles Burchfield. In terms of material things, there's no place
like New York and no time like the Christmas holidays to see major
blockbuster art exhibitions. (James Estrin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) RANDOLPH, Mass. -- Dec. 31, 1998 --
UNIFORM-RECREATOR-BOS, 12-31 -- Henry Cooke works on colonial
uniforms in his studio. Today's high standards for uniforms used in
historical reenactments are as much the result of Cooke's
historical research as they are of his hand-sewn
craftsmanship.(Bill Greene/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
