u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OBIT-WRIGHT-NYT &LR;      12-31 0232
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-WRIGHT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAMON WRIGHT, 48, PLAYWRIGHT AND REPORTER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., N.Y.)  (js) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Damon Wright, a playwright, died on Monday at Beth Israel
Medical Center in Manhattan after a long illness, his family said.
He was 48 and lived in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Long Beach, Calif., and a graduate of Stanford
University, he was the author of ``Testimony,'' `` Baldwin Goes to
Heaven'' and ``The Quadroon Ball: An American Tragedy,'' among
other plays. He was a member of the Usual Suspects, a community of
artists at New York Theater Workshop, and had worked at the
Directors' Lab at Lincoln Center Theater. Both groups mounted
workshops of `` Baldwin Goes to Heaven'' in 1995 and 1996,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
   ``Testimony'' was presented at Dixon Place in 1996 and ``The
Quadroon Ball'' at La Mama E.T.C. in 1997, as well as at the
Crossroads Theater in New Brunswick, N.J., and the Alley Theater in
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Wright, who earlier had been an administrator at Sounds in
Motion, the choreographer Dianne McIntyre's company, worked for The
New York Times from 1985 to 1995, most recently in the news
department. His articles about experimental theater appeared in the
Arts &AMP; Leisure section.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his parents, Artis and Birdell, and two
sisters, Joni and Lydia, all of Long Beach, and a brother, Carter,
of Jefferson, Texas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
