<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASTRONAUT-DREAMS:EVANS-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOY'S ASTRONAUT DREAMS COME TRUE
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' is from this week's New America News
Service.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448; fax:
816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to the New America
News Service, a weekly diversity package of stories by and about
ethnic minorities, gays, women and disabled Americans.) 
 By JOYCE EVANS-CAMPBELL 
 &HT;    (Joyce Evans-Campbell, African American, is a columnist for the
Milwaukee Journal Sentinel.) 
 New America News Service 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    In 1996, when Travis Davidson was a student in a program called
the Leaves of Learning, he was introduced to space. Then one
morning while crunching on his breakfast cereal, he saw an
African-American astronaut on TV and declared that that was what he
wanted to do: become an astronaut.
 &HT;    Since then, Travis, now 11, has waited for the opportunity to
attend the program at the U.S. Space and Rocket Center in
Huntsville, Ala.
 &HT;    A column about Travis and his dream ran in the Milwaukee Journal
Sentinel on Dec. 23, 1996. And now, a generous donor is about to
make it happen. Jeff Richter, 36, a database administrator for a
Milwaukee company, was touched _ and inspired to pay for Travis'
trip.
 &HT;    The space camp is open to fourth- through 12th-graders and lasts
six to eight days. The tuition, which depends on the program and
time of year, ranges from $550 to $875 for hands-on training in
simulated space missions.
 &HT;    Vicki Davidson had told her son that he had to be 12 years old
and to keep his grades up. Only then, would she let him apply for
the Space Camp and Academy, knowing also that in order for him to
go, she would have to make a considerable financial sacrifice.
 &HT;    A single parent whose family roots are in Alabama, Davidson
wanted to give her son a goal to make sure he had something to look
forward to and to work toward.
 &HT;    Although Travis will be 12 on April 25, Davidson had to tell her
son he had to wait yet another year. ``I'm very interested in
letting him go, but I've just taken a new job. It won't be
financially feasible for us this year. I told him he had to wait,
and he said, `OK.'''
 &HT;    His heart sank a little, but he resigned himself to waiting
another year.
 &HT;    Meanwhile, he has developed another interest as well. He is
involved in the Youth Leadership Academy and the Youth Leadership
Academy Boys Choir and these have broadened his horizons. He's
traveled and performed with the choir, which is patterned after the
Harlem Boys' Choir, and has visited places that he would not
otherwise be able to. ``Next year, we'll be going to New York!'' he
said.
 &HT;    Travis has a mentor who's an engineer, and that connection has
opened his eyes to the possibility of becoming an engineer. ``I
still want to be an astronaut but if I don't become an astronaut,
I'll become an engineer. My mentor has told me some exciting things
about engineering.''
 &HT;    The middle school student entered a private Catholic school this
year, and he has continued to work hard. ``He's earned all A's and
two B's,'' his mother said. He's keeping those grade up: He hopes
to be able to get into historically black school, Morehouse
College, or Stanford University.
 &HT;    ``He's always doing school work and involved in something
constructive,'' she added.
 &HT;    Then, on hearing Travis' story, Jeff Richter stepped in. He
himself has attended the space camp three times as an adult and
loves the space program. ``I believe strongly in the space program,
as well as in the mission of the camp, which is education of
today's youth in science,'' he said.
 &HT;    When Vicki Davidson received the news about Richter's offer, she
was stunned _ and elated.
 &HT;    She is a program coordinator for a housing/apartment complex,
and when Travis visited the computer room at her office recently,
another employee let him surf the Net. He went straight to the NASA
site.
 &HT;    ``He has every possible piece of information about the space
program,'' said his mother. ``And he'll be able to pick a date
that's good for him to go.''
 &HT;    Now he is excitedly looking forward to going to the space camp.
His donor, who came in like Santa Claus, is already on a pedestal _
a man who was born a day before John Glenn's first fight ... a man
who had dreams of becoming an astronaut himself ... a man who's
making it possible for Travis to blast off at space camp.
 &HT;    ``I think it's pretty nice of him,'' Travis marveled. ``I'm
blown away,''
 &HT;    
 c. 1998 Joyce Evans-Campbell 
<TEXT>
 &UR; NEW AMERICA NEWS SERVICE &QC; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &QC;
