<HEADER>
A4240 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GAY-RIGHTS-MIAMI:COLB     12-31 1057
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAY-RIGHTS-MIAMI:COLBERT-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAY CIVIL RIGHTS VICTORY IN MIAMI-DADE COUNTY
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' is from this week's New America News
Service.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448; fax:
816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to the New America
News Service, a weekly diversity package of stories by and about
ethnic minorities, gays, women and disabled Americans.) 
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into ``k''
commentary and ``a'' general news files.) 
 By CHUCK COLBERT 
 &HT;    (Chuck Colbert is a founder of the Gay and Lesbian Alumni of
Notre Dame/St. Mary's College, and serves on the board of directors
of the National Lesbian and Gay Journalists Association.) 
 New America News Service 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    The Miami-Dade County Commission made gay civil-rights history
recently. By a vote of 7-6, commissioners agreed to add the
category of ``sexual orientation'' to the county's
anti-discrimination laws, thereby prohibiting discrimination based
on sexual orientation in housing, employment, credit, finance, and
public accommodations.
 &HT;    The new ordinance does not apply to companies with fewer than
four employees and rental buildings with fewer than four units.
There are exemptions for not-for-profit religious affiliated groups
and religious organizations.
 &HT;    The Miami-Dade County gay civil-rights ordinance enjoys broad
support from a variety of civic and political organizations,
including labor unions and business groups, the NAACP, the
Anti-Defamation League of B'nai B'rith, the Urban League, People
for the American Way, and the Spanish-American League Against
Discrimination, as well as a number of high profile religious and
secular leaders, including the chairman of The Miami Herald.
 &HT;    The vote was ``a turning point in this community,'' according to
Miami Mayor Alex Penelas, a strong advocate of the new law. ``This
was one of those moments when we were at a fork in the road. It was
a vote that would show whether we were the progressive, tolerant,
and mature community we believe we are, or whether we would take a
step backward,'' Penelas told The Miami Herald.
 &HT;    Dade County made history as well 20 years ago, passing what was
then one of the nation's first gay civil rights laws. But several
months later _ in a highly charged referendum campaign led by the
singer Anita Bryant _ voters repealed the new ordinance by a 2-1
margin.
 &HT;    Back then the turn of events in Florida, catapulted the issue of
gay civil rights into the national spotlight. Over the last two
decades there has been steady progress. As one measure of that
progress, 11 states, 27 counties, and 136 cities have passed
ordinances similar to the one passed in Dade County, according to
the Human Rights Campaign, the nation's largest gay political
organization. Fewer than 10 have been repealed.
 &HT;    But will the new ordinance in Dade County stand? Or will the
Christian Coalition, the ordinance's chief opponent, attempt to
repeal it? ``We are obviously disappointed at this point, and we
will regroup,'' Anthony Verdugo, chairman of the local chapter of
the Christian Coalition, told The Miami Herald, declining to say
whether the group will try to overturn the ordinance through a
referendum.
 &HT;    Still, this past weekend opponents of the new law held a rally _
``family indignation Saturday'' _ in the Orange Bowl. About 2,000
people attended although organizers had hoped for 100,000.
 &HT;    One thing seems certain this time: Anti-gay forces attempting to
repeal the ordinance will face an electorate that, according to a
recent public opinion poll, favors the new law by a wide margin: 20
percent.
 &HT;    Hispanics and African-Americans, two of the regions major ethnic
and racial groups, support the law. ``There are very few issues
upon which all of Miami's ethnic groups agree, but this is one,''
said Rob Schroth in The Miami Herald. Schroth, a veteran South
Florida pollster, conducted a telephone survey of 650 voters for
the Herald and the local NBC affiliate.
 &HT;    Another group that favors the new gay civil rights law is people
who attend church. ``Forty-six percent of the people who go to
church at least once a week said they support the ordinance,
compared with 38 percent who oppose it,'' reported the Herald.
 &HT;    Based on the results of the survey, Schroth said the Christian
Coalition would have to outspend the pro-gay side by a margin of 2-
or 3-to-1 in a referendum battle. ``If their campaign is
well-funded and their message is based on scare tactics and fear,
they could certainly make it very close, but victory would still be
an uphill climb in my opinion, based on this poll,'' Schroth told
the Herald.
 &HT;    Still, scare tactics and virulent anti-gay rhetoric are what
prevailed 20 years ago when Anita Bryant's ``save our children''
crusade succeeded in rolling back the Miami-Dade County gay
civil-rights ordinance, calling it a means to approval of a
``perverse and dangerous'' way of living.
 &HT;    ``Many people see 1977 as the beginning of the rise of the
extreme right in this country, with a real focus on anti-gay
rhetoric,'' Elizabeth Birch, executive director of the Washington,
D.C.-based Human Rights Campaign, said in an article in The New
York Times. ``This is a wonderful victory for Miami-Dade County,
but it's a watershed victory for gays and lesbians nationally. This
shows how far we've come toward basic fairness for gay Americans,''
she said.
 &HT;    Along the road to equal rights for gay Americans, there is
perhaps no sweeter victory than this one.
 &HT;    
 c. 1998 Chuck Colbert 
<TEXT>
 &UR; NEW AMERICA NEWS SERVICE &QC; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &QC;
