u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INDIAN-MUSICAL:GIAGO-     12-31 0907
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDIAN-MUSICAL:GIAGO-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN AMERICAN INDIAN MUSICAL IN NEW YORK
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' is from this week's New America News
Service.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448; fax:
816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to the New America
News Service, a weekly diversity package of stories by and about
ethnic minorities, gays, women and disabled Americans.) 
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into ``k''
commentary, ``a'' general news and ``e'' entertainment files.) 
 By TIM GIAGO (Nanwica Kciji) 
 &HT;    (Tim Giago, Lakota Indian, is publisher and editor-in-chief of
Indian Country Today. His Indian name is Nanwica Kciji.) 
 New America News Service 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    NEW YORK _ Whenever I come here, I always try to squeeze in a
Broadway show because it's not something that often comes to the
rolling hills of South Dakota.
 &HT;    This trip something special happened. Perhaps it was just good
timing or, as I would like to believe, pure fate.
 &HT;    I recently spoke at the Labor Department during a celebration of
Native American Heritage Week in Washington, D.C. The other guest
speaker was J. Reuben Silverbird, who told me about a musical
production soon to open in New York City, at the Henry Street
Settlement/Abrons Arts Center, with a cast of American Indians. It
sounded intriguing and I was elated to find I would be in New York
at the time.
 &HT;    The American Indian musical ``Red Sky'' was directed by Robert
Whitmore, an author and composer who also acted in ``Joseph and the
Amazing Technicolor Dreamcoat'' and starred as Judas in ``Jesus
Christ Superstar,'' which he also directed. His movie credits
include Kurasawa's ``Runaway Train'' and Bogdanvich's
``Texasville.'' The production of ``Red Sky'' marked his return to
the theater.
 &HT;    The theater at Abrons Center is small and intimate. It gets the
audience very close to the actors. Music for the production was
provided by Perry and Gil Silverbird, sons of Reuben. Both talented
musicians also acted in the production.
 &HT;    It was obvious this was a barebones production but it did not
deter the cast from giving a riveting performance. The play is an
Indian love story that turns out to be more of a triangle. Kyoko
MCrae as Anatah is torn between Kalani Queypo (Greyhawk) and
William Toll (Jeremiah), a man of mixed blood. In their argument
over her affections, a rifle accidentally discharges and Anatah is
killed. The first part of the play takes place during the wars
between the eastern tribes and the British.
 &HT;    The second part moves to more modern times with the same cast of
characters. It revolves around a land deal that would cost the
tribe its lands and Anatah, now working for her tribal government,
attempting to stop the corrupt action.
 &HT;    Rebecca ``Sami'' Yanes impressed me the most. As Eena, the
mother of Grey Eagle, she is a strong woman of the tribe. In the
second part, she plays the part of a bag lady living in the slums
of a city. But beyond all of that, she has a terrific voice and her
songs brought cheers and applause from the crowd who threw in some
traditional chants of appreciation for good measure. The audience,
by the way, must have included most of the Indian population of New
York City.
 &HT;    I wish I had been able to record some of the beautiful songs
from the production, but tape recorders are, of course, banned at
musical productions.
 &HT;    Having seen Broadway shows like ``Les Miserables,'' ``Cats,''
``Showboat,'' and others, it really made my day to see this small
cast of mostly American Indian actors standing on stage and singing
these beautiful songs about the culture and the traditions of the
Indian people.
 &HT;    Aside from the great piano renditions by Gil Silverbird and his
brother, Perry, the real stars of this production were J. Reuben
Silverbird and Rebecca ``Sami'' Yanes, whose performances came
straight from their hearts.
 &HT;    The show was a real learning experience for Robert Whitmore: he
learned much about American Indians as he worked side-by-side with
J. Reuben and his sons in planning and staging the show.
 &HT;    Alas, it closed after a 10-day run. The director and cast are
seeking additional funds to revive the production either on a New
York stage or to take it on the road.
 &HT;    The Indian dialogue in the show was in the Mohawk language and
the instructor, Jake Swamp, is an elder of the Wolf Clan of the
Mohawk people. Archie Cheeco, a Cree elder, also gave his support
and inspiration to the play.
 &HT;    The show deserves to be seen by many. It touches upon the
confrontation between the invaders and the indigenous people and
shows that Indian men and women can love and be loved.
 &HT;    
 c. 1998 Tim Giago 
<TEXT>
