from the production, but tape recorders are, of course, banned at
musical productions.
 &HT;    Having seen Broadway shows like ``Les Miserables,'' ``Cats,''
``Showboat,'' and others, it really made my day to see this small
cast of mostly American Indian actors standing on stage and singing
these beautiful songs about the culture and the traditions of the
Indian people.
 &HT;    Aside from the great piano renditions by Gil Silverbird and his
brother, Perry, the real stars of this production were J. Reuben
Silverbird and Rebecca ``Sami'' Yanes, whose performances came
straight from their hearts.
 &HT;    The show was a real learning experience for Robert Whitmore: he
learned much about American Indians as he worked side-by-side with
J. Reuben and his sons in planning and staging the show.
 &HT;    Alas, it closed after a 10-day run. The director and cast are
seeking additional funds to revive the production either on a New
York stage or to take it on the road.
 &HT;    The Indian dialogue in the show was in the Mohawk language and
the instructor, Jake Swamp, is an elder of the Wolf Clan of the
Mohawk people. Archie Cheeco, a Cree elder, also gave his support
and inspiration to the play.
 &HT;    The show deserves to be seen by many. It touches upon the
confrontation between the invaders and the indigenous people and
shows that Indian men and women can love and be loved.
 &HT;    
 c. 1998 Tim Giago 
