<HEADER>
A4245 &Cx1f; tab-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HISPANIC-TRENDSETTERS     12-31 2581
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HISPANIC-TRENDSETTERS-1998-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SETTING THE PACE: TOP 10 HISPANIC TRENDSETTERS FOR 1998
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' is from this week's New America News
Service.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448; fax:
816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to the New America
News Service, a weekly diversity package of stories by and about
ethnic minorities, gays, women and disabled Americans.) 
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into ``a'' general
news, ``s'' sports files and ``e'' entertainment files.) 
 By CHRISTINE GRANADOS 
 c. 1998 Hispanic magazine 
 New America News Service 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Here are just some of the standout individuals who have brought
Hispanic issues into the limelight this year. HISPANIC spotlights
10 exceptional people:
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Our Man in Washington
 &HT;    The highest-ranking Hispanic in the Clinton administration and
one of the most visible Hispanic politicians in the United States,
Secretary of Energy Bill Richardson leads the list of trendsetters.
The native New Mexican has been nominated two times for the Nobel
Peace Prize for his diplomatic efforts to free hostages in several
countries. His diplomatic successes did not escape President
Clinton's notice when he first appointed him UN ambassador.
Richardson held that position from Feb. 13, 1997 to Sept. 10, 1998
before being appointed secretary of energy.
 &HT;    He now must contend with protecting national security, advancing
the frontiers of science and technology, helping to solve the
challenge of global climate changes, making progress on the
environmental cleanup of the nuclear weapons complex, and ensuring
a balanced energy portfolio for the nation.
 &HT;    Richardson says that Latinos are becoming prominent players in
the international arena.
 &HT;    ``My goal as secretary of energy is to demonstrate to the
Hispanic community and all Americans how the Department of Energy
makes an extraordinary impact on their everyday lives,'' says the
50-year-old Mexican American. ``The department's scientists are
making spectacular breakthroughs in medicine, computers, and many
other fields. It is my hope that young Latinos will join with us
and that some day they will join Mario Molina [who received a Nobel
prize in chemistry in 1995] as a Nobel Prize winner the department
has sponsored.''
 &HT;    
 &HT;    La Guera
 &HT;    The Hollywood paragon that is Cameron Diaz is also Hispanic.
Dubbed the ``It Girl of '98'' by Entertainment Weekly, Diaz is
showing Hollywood her roots. The 25-year-old Cuban American actress
was born to Emilio Diaz, a second-generation Cuban American, and
Billie, his German-English-Native American wife.
 &HT;    Like some third-generation Hispanics, Diaz cannot speak Spanish,
but the ``There's Something About Mary'' star's family is
tight-knit like many traditional Latino clans. When she is not
working, she spends most of her free time with her sister, Chimene,
and her niece, Chloe. She even calls her mother every day.
 &HT;    Choosy about the types of roles she plays, the former model has
come a long way from her 1994 big screen debut in ``The Mask,'' a
film, in which she played Tia Carlyle, the girl who made Jim
Carrey's eyes pop out of his head. She can be seen as Laura in
``Very Bad Things,'' which came out this fall.
 &HT;    Diaz is the first Latina of her generation who has landed the
girl-next-door, bad-girl, and blond-bombshell roles without being
pigeonholed as a luscious Latina. Her stereotype is more of the
zany girl next door.
 &HT;    Except for her name, Diaz is not identifiably Hispanic, but
she's breaking new ground for Hispanic women in Hollywood,
commanding $2 million per picture.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Becoming a Role Model
 &HT;    Danny Villanueva made the trendsetters list for several reasons.
He was a successful professional football player. He is co-owner of
the country's only Latino-controlled venture capital firm. He is
also the second-richest Mexican American in the United States
according to the Los Angeles Times magazine. But it is his capacity
for giving to and teaching children and Latinos in the business
world that cemented his place on the list.
 &HT;    ``I have gone into areas where I had no role model and no
example,'' says Villanueva, recalling his days as a place kicker
and the only Latino in the National Football League (NFL). ``I did
it with the very conscious and very deliberate attempt to become a
role model. I was always very cognizant of what I was doing and
what impact it would have.''
 &HT;    Throughout his days as a football player, television
broadcaster, and businessman, Villanueva gave his time and money to
charity and nonprofit groups. ``At one point in my life, I made
about 150 appearances a year, talking to kids and groups,'' he
says.
 &HT;    He always remembers what his late mother, Pilar Villanueva,
instilled in him. ``She always thought service to the people was
our highest calling and our overriding obligation.''
 &HT;    
 &HT;    The Color Purple
 &HT;    The most exciting, provocative, and exploratory writing in the
United States is coming from the Hispanic community, and Sandra
Cisneros leads the pack of refreshingly unconventional talent.
 &HT;    The Chicago native has published six books and numerous short
stories, essays, and poems. Her works have won many awards and have
been translated into 10 different languages. ``The House on Mango
Street'' has sold more than one million copies and is included in
college, elementary, and high school curricula across the country.
 &HT;    She received a genius fellowship in 1995 from the MacArthur
Foundation which afforded her the time to work on her current novel
tentatively titled ``Caramelo.'' ``Genius has a responsibility,''
she commented in a 1997 article in the San Antonio Express News.
``I'd like to see us a legion of superheroes who come to the aid of
communities in peril.''
 &HT;    However, it's Cisneros' political savvy and controversial manner
that also make her a leader in the community. Her propensity for
using the national media, reminiscent of Spike Lee, to bring to
light Latino causes has catapulted her onto the trendsetters list.
In 1997 Cisneros clashed with her San Antonio neighborhood
association over her choice of color for her house, which is
purple. When reporters showed up at her doorstep to ask why she
chose to paint her house a color not offered by the King William
Historic District board, she explained that she was using her own
cultural palette that represents the first Texas settlers: Native
Americans and Mexicans.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Para Yucas
 &HT;    With a visionary's perception and a slacker's attitude, Cuban
America Bill Teck of Miami launched a successful niche magazine for
the Latino community: ``generation n.'' The magazine, targeting
generation-x Latinos living in Miami, made its debut in a 28-page
black-and-white format in 1996, with a circulation of 13,500.
 &HT;    Teck attributes the success of his venture to micro marketing.
``As we approach the millennium, mass marketing to Hispanics as a
whole will become less and less effective,'' says the 30-year-old.
``It's cool that we're empowered politically and economically, but
culturally we're all very different. There are fly-fishing
magazines and survivalist magazines out there, so we thought, let's
try to micro market to, say, Hispanics who grew up in Miami in the
last 10 to 20 years speaking English.''
 &HT;    His strategy has worked. Now 17,500 copies of the publication
are printed in full color with both local and national advertisers.
In addition, the magazine has a television show that is a spinoff
of the same title in Miami. Teck is also co-host of a radio program
titled El Mango Azul, which covers the same topics as the magazine
but with a lot more humor.
 &HT;    As for the future, Teck, a former record store manager with
plenty of college credits and no college degree, has plans to use
his regional strategy throughout the United States. He envisions
``generation n'' magazines in every large city in Texas, New York,
and California, covering regional topics that people in each state
can relate to.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Doctor in the House
 &HT;    Professor David Hayes-Bautista has spent 30 years trying to
correct misconceptions and stereotypes about the health of the
Latino community. The 54-year-old Mexican American is part
scientist, number cruncher, anthropologist, sociologist, lecturer,
and medical doctor. His research team at the Center for the Study
of Latino Health at the UCLA School of Medicine finds ways to
better serve the Hispanic community's medical needs by researching
the Latino culture.
 &HT;    ``What we find is that Latinos don't look like anyone else. If
we look at Latinos in California, Arizona, and Texas they look
virtually alike. In those three states, Latinos have low income,
low education, and low access to health care. That's nothing new,''
says Hayes-Bautista. ``However, Latinos have a longer life
expectancy than non-Latinos _ about three to four years longer. Yet
Latinos are using doctors and hospital services a lot less. This is
a mystery because the thought is, `Well, if they are a low-income,
low-education population, they're going to be sicker and have to
use services a lot more.' But Latinos do it differently.''
 &HT;    The difference, or deviation from the norm, is what
Hayes-Bautista terms the ``Latino Epidemiological Paradox.'' This
paradox exists in all aspects of Latino life, and Hayes-Bautista
wants America to know that it is this paradox that is the strength
of the Hispanic population.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Crossover Surprise
 &HT;    Many Latinos in the music industry hope to record a crossover
hit. Selena did it, as did Gloria Estefan and Jon Secada. But when
a whole musical genre crosses over to mainstream audiences, it's
called a phenomenon. The latest musical phenomenon is rock en
espanol and one of the bands leading that trend, albeit
reluctantly, is Los Fabulosos Cadillacs. The eight-person
Argentinean band doesn't like its label. ``We don't believe in the
phrase `rock en espanol,''' Flavio Cianciarulo, the band's bassist
and main songwriter, told Isaac Guzman, a writer for Newsday. ``It
doesn't exist as a movement.''
 &HT;    The band's music is a blend of ska, hip-hop, Afro-Cuban jazz,
punk, metal, rock, and a few other musical styles thrown in as well
_ something that cannot be easily labeled. What is easily labeled
is success. The band won the first-ever Grammy Award in the rock en
espanol category earlier this year for its 11th album, ``Fabulosos
Calavera.'' Although the band is already a major player in its
homeland and around the globe, Los Fabulosos Cadillacs is just now
gaining momentum in the United States. The group has come a long
way from the 1989 Los Angeles concert at which its eclectic brand
of music was greeted with showers of beer.
 &HT;    But the Latino rockeros' provocative sounds have helped enliven
and internationalize the music industry.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Couture With Soul
 &HT;    The wedding gown, a bias-cut pearl-silk crepe with subtle
draping in the font and back, that was worn by Caroline Bessette
for her wedding to John F. Kennedy, Jr., brought Latino designer
Narciso Rodriguez to the forefront of the fashion world. Since that
fateful day in 1996, Rodriguez has been setting fashion ablaze with
his soft, feminine designs.
 &HT;    The 37-year-old Cuban American from New Jersey struck out on his
own last year. He left the Cerruti Fashion house to start his own
ready-to-wear line, which drew raves from fashion critics. He was
nominated for the Perry Ellis Award for Womenswear at the Council
of Fashion Designers of America Awards ceremony earlier this year.
 &HT;    His fall/winter line wowed fashion critics with its cashmere
jumpers and strapless dresses with bustiers in flat dry wools worn
over fluffy sweaters. In the tradition of his predecessors, Oscar
de la Renta and Carolina Herrera, Rodriguez's Latino heritage
shines through his designs, especially when he plays with beading
and embroideries. ``A little bit of my Cuban roots came out in
beading and lace,'' Rodriguez told Elsa Klensch of CNN about his
latest collection.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Home-Run Hero
 &HT;    Standout performances by Latinos in baseball is no surprise, but
what finer example could one possibly find than Sammy Sosa? The
Chicago Cubs' right fielder hit a major league record of 20 home
runs in June, and his RBIs were the highest in the league this
season at 158.
 &HT;    However, it was the home run race in which he and St. Louis
first baseman Mark McGwire battled during the season that is his
most renowned accomplishment. He ended the season with 66 home
runs, to McGwire's 70. He worked hard during the entire season and
never once, despite all the hoopla, lost sight of the team goal of
making the play-offs.
 &HT;    After Sosa tied with McGwire at 66 home runs, he told an ESPN
reporter: ``[McGwire's] the one going to finish up there a little
bit higher than me. You have to remember, my situation is
different. I have to go out there and try to win the last five
games.''
 &HT;    But Sosa was chosen as a trendsetter for conducting himself with
poise and class throughout the season and the home run race. Who
would expect anything less from a man who wears Number 21 in honor
of his childhood hero: Roberto Clemente.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    No se Habla Espanol
 &HT;    Braving death threats, nasty telephone calls, and hate mail
because of her support and authorization of Proposition 227 (a bill
that ended bilingual education in California), Gloria Matta Tuchman
paved a road less traveled in primary and secondary education. With
the passage of Proposition 227 in June, she helped set the trend in
education toward English-immersion instruction for
non-English-speaking students. States such as Colorado and New York
are watching the outcome in California closely for ideas that could
help in reforming their bilingual education programs.
 &HT;    ``This whole issue is not about English-Only _ it is about
literacy for the kids. As a teacher, that is why I fought so long
and that is why Jaime Escalante [the math teacher dramatized in the
film ``Stand and Deliver''] fought,'' says the 57-year-old
elementary school teacher, who is running for superintendent of
public instruction in California. If elected, Matta Tuchman will be
the first Hispanic to hold that post.
 &HT;    Matta Tuchman says that California students have long been used
as guinea pigs in bilingual programs and that mandated bilingual
education has been tried and proved not to be effective. ``It
didn't teach English _ that was the intent and purpose of the
program, but that was not what was happening,'' she says.
 &HT;    
 c. 1998 Hispanic magazine 
