 &HT;    Crossover Surprise
 &HT;    Many Latinos in the music industry hope to record a crossover
hit. Selena did it, as did Gloria Estefan and Jon Secada. But when
a whole musical genre crosses over to mainstream audiences, it's
called a phenomenon. The latest musical phenomenon is rock en
espanol and one of the bands leading that trend, albeit
reluctantly, is Los Fabulosos Cadillacs. The eight-person
Argentinean band doesn't like its label. ``We don't believe in the
phrase `rock en espanol,''' Flavio Cianciarulo, the band's bassist
and main songwriter, told Isaac Guzman, a writer for Newsday. ``It
doesn't exist as a movement.''
 &HT;    The band's music is a blend of ska, hip-hop, Afro-Cuban jazz,
punk, metal, rock, and a few other musical styles thrown in as well
_ something that cannot be easily labeled. What is easily labeled
is success. The band won the first-ever Grammy Award in the rock en
espanol category earlier this year for its 11th album, ``Fabulosos
Calavera.'' Although the band is already a major player in its
homeland and around the globe, Los Fabulosos Cadillacs is just now
gaining momentum in the United States. The group has come a long
way from the 1989 Los Angeles concert at which its eclectic brand
of music was greeted with showers of beer.
 &HT;    But the Latino rockeros' provocative sounds have helped enliven
and internationalize the music industry.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Couture With Soul
 &HT;    The wedding gown, a bias-cut pearl-silk crepe with subtle
draping in the font and back, that was worn by Caroline Bessette
for her wedding to John F. Kennedy, Jr., brought Latino designer
Narciso Rodriguez to the forefront of the fashion world. Since that
fateful day in 1996, Rodriguez has been setting fashion ablaze with
his soft, feminine designs.
 &HT;    The 37-year-old Cuban American from New Jersey struck out on his
own last year. He left the Cerruti Fashion house to start his own
ready-to-wear line, which drew raves from fashion critics. He was
nominated for the Perry Ellis Award for Womenswear at the Council
of Fashion Designers of America Awards ceremony earlier this year.
 &HT;    His fall/winter line wowed fashion critics with its cashmere
jumpers and strapless dresses with bustiers in flat dry wools worn
over fluffy sweaters. In the tradition of his predecessors, Oscar
de la Renta and Carolina Herrera, Rodriguez's Latino heritage
shines through his designs, especially when he plays with beading
and embroideries. ``A little bit of my Cuban roots came out in
beading and lace,'' Rodriguez told Elsa Klensch of CNN about his
latest collection.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Home-Run Hero
 &HT;    Standout performances by Latinos in baseball is no surprise, but
what finer example could one possibly find than Sammy Sosa? The
Chicago Cubs' right fielder hit a major league record of 20 home
runs in June, and his RBIs were the highest in the league this
season at 158.
 &HT;    However, it was the home run race in which he and St. Louis
first baseman Mark McGwire battled during the season that is his
most renowned accomplishment. He ended the season with 66 home
runs, to McGwire's 70. He worked hard during the entire season and
never once, despite all the hoopla, lost sight of the team goal of
making the play-offs.
 &HT;    After Sosa tied with McGwire at 66 home runs, he told an ESPN
reporter: ``[McGwire's] the one going to finish up there a little
bit higher than me. You have to remember, my situation is
different. I have to go out there and try to win the last five
games.''
 &HT;    But Sosa was chosen as a trendsetter for conducting himself with
poise and class throughout the season and the home run race. Who
would expect anything less from a man who wears Number 21 in honor
of his childhood hero: Roberto Clemente.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    No se Habla Espanol
 &HT;    Braving death threats, nasty telephone calls, and hate mail
because of her support and authorization of Proposition 227 (a bill
that ended bilingual education in California), Gloria Matta Tuchman
paved a road less traveled in primary and secondary education. With
the passage of Proposition 227 in June, she helped set the trend in
education toward English-immersion instruction for
non-English-speaking students. States such as Colorado and New York
are watching the outcome in California closely for ideas that could
help in reforming their bilingual education programs.
 &HT;    ``This whole issue is not about English-Only _ it is about
literacy for the kids. As a teacher, that is why I fought so long
and that is why Jaime Escalante [the math teacher dramatized in the
film ``Stand and Deliver''] fought,'' says the 57-year-old
elementary school teacher, who is running for superintendent of
public instruction in California. If elected, Matta Tuchman will be
the first Hispanic to hold that post.
 &HT;    Matta Tuchman says that California students have long been used
as guinea pigs in bilingual programs and that mandated bilingual
education has been tried and proved not to be effective. ``It
didn't teach English _ that was the intent and purpose of the
program, but that was not what was happening,'' she says.
 &HT;    
 c. 1998 Hispanic magazine 
