<TEXT>
<P>
   BUSH ACTS ON BEHALF OF FARM WORKERS _ Even before taking office
in January, Florida's governor-elect, Jeb Bush, is fulfilling at
least one of his major campaign promises, notes columnist Bill
Maxwell, one that he made to farm workers. Under his
behind-the-scenes encouragement, two of nearly a dozen commercial
tomato growers have agreed to increase wages for pickers by about
13 percent _ ``the first increase farm workers have received in 20
years,'' Maxwell writes.
</P>
<P>
   Moved as BC-BUSH:FARM-WORKERS:MAXWELL-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF in ``k''
commentary and ``a'' general news files.
</P>
<P>
   BOY'S ASTRONAUT DREAMS COME TRUE. In 1996, when Travis Davidson
was a student in a program called the Leaves of Learning, he was
introduced to space, reports writer Joyce Evans-Campbell. Then one
morning over breakfast, he saw an African-American astronaut on TV
and declared that that was what he wanted to do: become an
astronaut. A column about Travis and his dream appeared in the
Milwaukee Journal Sentinel on Dec. 23, 1996. ``And now, a generous
donor is about to make the first step of Travis' dream happen,''
she says.
</P>
<P>
   Moved as BC-ASTRONAUT-DREAMS:EVANS-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF in ``a''
general news file.
</P>
<P>
   GAY CIVIL RIGHTS VICTORY IN MIAMI-DADE COUNTY. The Miami-Dade
County Commission made gay civil-rights history recently, reports
columnist Chuck Colbert. By a vote of 7-6, commissioners agreed to
add the category of ``sexual orientation'' to the county's
anti-discrimination laws, thereby prohibiting discrimination based
on sexual orientation in housing, employment, credit, finance, and
public accommodations. ``Along the road to equal rights for gay
Americans, there is perhaps no sweeter victory than this one,'' he
writes.
</P>
<P>
   Moved as BC-GAY-RIGHTS-MIAMI:COLBERT-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF in ``k''
commentary and ``a'' general news files.
</P>
<P>
   AN AMERICAN INDIAN MUSICAL IN NEW YORK. It was obvious this was
a barebones production but it did not deter the cast of the musical
``Red Sky'' from giving a riveting performance, writes columnist
Tim Giago. The musical, an Indian love story, recently played in
New York. ``It really made my day to see this small cast of ...
American Indian actors standing on stage and singing these
beautiful songs about the culture and the traditions of the Indian
people,'' he writes. ``The cast received standing ovations and
cheers; the show deserves to be seen by many.''
</P>
<P>
   Moved as BC-INDIAN-MUSICAL:GIAGO-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF in ``k''
commentary, ``a'' general news and ``e'' entertainment files.
</P>
<P>
   SETTING THE PACE: TOP 10 HISPANIC TRENDSETTERS FOR 1998. Ten
trendsetters within the Hispanic community _ and the impact of
their achievements _ are identified and examined by Hispanic
magazine's Christine Granados. From Sammy Sosa to Cameron Diaz, she
writes, each are Hispanics who are shaping the future.
</P>
<P>
   Moved as BC-HISPANIC-TRENDSETTERS-1998-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF in ``a''
general news, ``s'' sports files and ``e'' entertainment files.
</P>
