<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCLA-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA'S RUSH SUSPENDED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Freshman forward JaRon Rush has been suspended for
Saturday's game against Arizona after missing two practices and one
game because of homesickness.
</P>
<P>
   Rush spent Christmas with his family in Kansas City and did not
return to UCLA until Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have great empathy for what he's going through, but you
still have to be accountable for your actions,'' Bruins coach Steve
Lavin said. ``It was not a situation of active rebellion or active
defiance. (Homesickness) is a lot different from breaking team
rules.''
</P>
<P>
   Rush was homesick throughout the fall quarter but did not feel
its full force until he was surrounded by friends and family. His
return ticket was mistakenly purchased for Monday morning, and then
he missed his flight. At that point, the homesickness was in full
bloom and he remained in Kansas City for two additional days.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I would come back (to UCLA), it was just a matter of
time,'' Rush said. ``I had to spend time with my family. I went
home, and it hit me. It was hard to get back on that plane. But
I've only got three months left (until spring break), and I've just
got to get through it.''
</P>
<P>
   Rush is UCLA's No.3 scorer, averaging 11.1 points per game.
</P>
<P>
   The big fella returns: Freshman center Dan Gadzuric erased any
doubt about his importance to UCLA's success when he returned from
a one-game absence (tendinitis) to grab seven rebounds in 19
minutes against Loyola Marymount.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Jerome Moiso, who waits for the ball to enter his
airspace, Gadzuric pursues rebounds regardless of their distance
and direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``He gives us a space eater,'' Lavin said. ``Obviously, his
aggressive style gives us a lift.''
</P>
<P>
   Technically, he's the man: Sophomore forward Travis Reed has
improved his foul shooting dramatically, from 33.3 percent last
year to 66.7 percent this season.
</P>
<P>
   To reward Reed, Lavin let him shoot free throws after Loyola
Marymount coach Charles Bradley was assessed a technical foul.
Traditionally, a team's best shooter takes the technical free
throws.
</P>
<P>
   ``I forgot I was leading the team, but now I guess I've got to
shoot them,'' Reed said.
</P>
<P>
   Changing shirts: After several unsuccessful attempts to
rehabilitate his groin injury, sophomore guard Billy Knight has
decided to sit out the season. Because he played in the exhibition
games, Knight must apply for a medical redshirt after the season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
