<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUBLIC-LIVES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROCKIN' AND ROLLIN' AND DINING  
 E-MAIL WISHES FOR A TV FRIEND  
 ZERO-HOUR FOODIES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn., N.Y.)  (js) 
 By RANDY KENNEDY WITH COREY KILGANNON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROCKIN' AND ROLLIN' AND DINING
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Want a table at Rao's, the 10-table East Harlem
restaurant that's almost impossible to get into if you're not a
regular? It helps if you are the man who is on national television
broadcasting the New Year's Eve celebration from Times Square, the
way you've done for, oh . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``It's up there in the 20s,'' said DICK CLARK, trying to
remember how many years he has presided over the changing of the
calendar (it's 27). ``I'm just honored they keep asking me back,''
he said. (This year's ``Dick Clark's New Year's Rockin' Eve'' ran
Thursday night on WABC-TV.)
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday night, Clark managed to secure the power table at
Rao's _ the first booth near the bar _ which he shared with CHUCK
BARRIS, the creator of that 1970s television oddball, ``The Gong
Show.'' In the booths behind him were BOB GUCCIONE Jr., the
publisher of Gear magazine, and STEPHEN BALDWIN, the actor, who
dined with childhood buddies from Long Island.
</P>
<P>
   Clark was asked if he had made his New Year's resolutions. ``I
don't make them anymore,'' he said. ``I used to always have three
of them every year: to lose weight, to be a better person and _ I
forget what the third one was. So you see, I never could remember
them, so I just don't make them anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   E-MAIL WISHES FOR A TV FRIEND
</P>
<P>
   As one of his friends admits, ``Jack is not quite online yet.''
</P>
<P>
   But since having quadruple bypass surgery three weeks ago, JACK
PAAR, the late-night television pioneer, has discovered the simple
joys of E-mail _ at least the printed-out version.
</P>
<P>
   REGIS PHILBIN and CHARLES GRODIN, Paar's friends, have been
gathering electronic get-well cards for him as he recovers at his
home in Greenwich, Conn. On the Web site for Philbin's talk show,
``Live! With Regis and Kathie Lee,'' hundreds of fans have clicked
on a picture of Paar and written him short notes since the
operation.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are really cheering his spirits,'' said MICHAEL MACARI
JR., president of Eaglevision, a media production company in
Stamford, Conn., that is helping Paar, 81, compile his archives.
``We've probably given him four or five hundred so far.''
</P>
<P>
   Paar, who began the ``Tonight'' show in 1957, also got a more
conventional get-well wish last week _ on the telephone _ from
JOHNNY CARSON, who took over the talk show when Paar left it in
1962.
</P>
<P>
   Friends report that Paar's quietly ferocious wit has survived
the surgery intact. As he was being taken out of the hospital, he
nodded toward the heart surgeon and said to his wife, ``Miriam,
dear, please tip the man.''
</P>
<P>
   ZERO-HOUR FOODIES
</P>
<P>
   Porcini mushrooms at the last minute for that New Year's Eve
dinner-party risotto? Maybe some caviar, or just a couple of plain
old T-bones for that quiet get-together with friends?
</P>
<P>
   Balducci's, the gourmet store in Greenwich Village, had a line
snaking down Sixth Avenue by 10:30 a.m. Thursday just to get
inside. At Citarella on the Upper West Side, a line of more than a
dozen people stretched out the door by 12:30 p.m. (``They must be
giving something away,'' one passer-by said.) And inside Zabar's,
employees announced an express line ``only if you want caviar or
foie gras.'' Another express line formed for presliced Nova.
Otherwise the wait was more than 45 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess everybody had the same idea,'' said ALAN BUTZBACH,
vice president for operations at Balducci's. ``But you can't blame
people. You live in the city, you know. How big is your
refrigerator?  &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  Butzbach said Balducci's kept the lines outside to reduce the
crush inside. ``They don't really mind waiting on the line for 5 or
10 minutes,'' he said of customers, ``so they can get in and not be
crowded.''
 &QR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
