<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-31 23:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4427 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-COTTON-SHERRILL-T     12-31 1422
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-COTTON-SHERRILL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHANGED MAN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WHIT CANNING 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ As the Mississippi State Bulldogs ended a recent
practice session and began turning their thoughts toward an evening
of lavish Cotton Bowl entertainment, strength coach Mike Grant
stepped up with a brief announcement.
</P>
<P>
   Splendid news, he said. The weight equipment had arrived, and
now everyone could start busily toning themselves up for the game.
</P>
<P>
   Thrilled, the players started milling around Grant, then
suddenly began to chant, ``Hell no ... we won't go! Hell no ... we
won't go!''
</P>
<P>
   Standing a few feet away, viewing the episode, was the
impresario of this frothy little entourage, Bulldogs coach Jackie
Wayne Sherrill.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know,'' he said, smiling, ``I think I kind of agree with
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Hmmmm?
</P>
<P>
   This, presumably, is the same guy who, after a crushing loss
during his rebuilding phase at Texas A&AMP;M said, ``Everybody better
get their licks in now ... because the worm's gonna turn.''
</P>
<P>
   The same guy who, before his last meeting with Texas in 1992,
had a bull castrated on the practice field, then rolled into Austin
and beat the Longhorns _ for the seventh consecutive time _ by
three touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   And then announced, ``I've whipped these people enough. I don't
ever have to come back.''
</P>
<P>
   The same guy who, departing A&AMP;M in a cloud of NCAA controversy
10 years ago, said, ``At least nobody's telling Aggie jokes
anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   The same guy? Yeah, sort of.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's mellowed a lot,'' said Lynn Amedee, who is once
again Sherrill's offensive coordinator, just as he was in 1985-87,
when the Aggies made three trips to the Cotton Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Jackie is more at peace with himself now,'' Amedee
said. ``He's been to the big time, and I don't think he feels he
has to prove anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not as rough on people as he used to be, and I think he
has a lot better relationship with the media. In the early years at
A&AMP;M, he was kind of a hard guy to get to know. Sometimes, you
weren't sure what he was thinking about.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's always been someone you like to coach for _ I was
figuring I was out of it when he called me \Rin '96\S and talked me
into coming back. And players have always liked playing for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``But he has softened a lot. He gives people a lot more freedom
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed. While the Aggies of the '80s often seemed like a huge,
menacing commando squad out to destroy the world, the ``Hell no, we
won't go'' 'Dogs are just having fun with the strength coach.
</P>
<P>
   The star running back has a Batman tattoo on his arm and the
other coordinator _ Joe Lee Dunn _ is a man who arises at 4 a.m. to
munch popcorn and view film, shaves on infrequent whims, wears
socks only on special occasions, and has a contract that says he
runs the defense.
</P>
<P>
   Sherrill, once the master of button-down discipline, now shows
up for news conferences wearing exotic sting-ray boots. When
freshman quarterback Wayne Madkin moped for days after the loss to
Tennessee, Sherrill walked up, pushed Madkin's face back into a
smile, and said, ``The game's over _ forget it.''
</P>
<P>
   When the infamous castration incident came up this week,
Sherrill _ who withstood a withering storm of adverse publicity at
the time _ was ready.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, I thought of doing it again this year,'' he told a
stunned media gathering, then laughed and quickly added, ``Uh, just
kidding. What I was really going to do was bring a bull out to the
practice field, with a pair of shears, and let the photographers
shoot a picture or film it. But I decided against it.''
</P>
<P>
   Pausing, he added, ``A few years ago, I couldn't have laughed
about that.''
</P>
<P>
   This week, he has also cried. Asked for a Cotton Bowl memory,
Sherrill recalled the death of a close friend on the day of an A&AMP;M
victory over Auburn. When he finished the story, he was in tears.
</P>
<P>
   But the trademark of Sherrill's motivational technique is not
tears, but laughter _ a reflection of his lifelong love of clowns.
Or, as Madkin puts it, ``He does some really strange things.''
</P>
<P>
   There was the time, for instance, when the startled Bulldogs
looked up to discover a large green leprechaun wandering the
practice field. A quick check of the premises confirmed their worst
fears: it was Coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually,'' Sherrill said, laughing, ``at my age \R55\S, I
don't look that good in a leprechaun suit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Years ago when I was at Alabama we played Florida State; I
used to put on a loincloth and a headdress and do a war dance. The
players loved it, but I was a lot younger then.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just have to do something to break up the routine every
once in a while. I think I've got these guys to the point now where
they don't know what I might do on Thursday or Friday, and that's
good.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't go through a whole season just being dead serious
all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Defensive tackle Kevin Sluder has fond memories of Harpo the
Clown, a distinguished visitor at an Mississippi State practice
last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach Sherrill just brought him in one day, and it definitely
lightened up the mood for the week,'' Sluder said. ``It was fun,
and we kinda hoped he'd be back this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I heard he blew out a knee and had to have surgery. I
guess being a clown isn't as easy as it looks.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the clown routine has been a Sherrill favorite for
years _ he has spent countless hours entertaining at children's
hospitals _ there have been other, more recent influences on his
life, such as his seven-year marriage to his third wife, Peggy.
</P>
<P>
   And it is obvious that nothing the Bulldogs have accomplished
has thrilled him more than the first time he saw an entire stadium
full of people stand in a lengthy ovation for daughter Bonnie, 19,
after she delivered a dazzling rendition of the national anthem.
</P>
<P>
   She is actually Peggy's daughter by a previous marriage, but,
Sherrill said, ``In our family, there are no stepchildren _ it's a
word we never use. Bonnie is my daughter.''
</P>
<P>
   She is also a student at _ how shall we say this? _ the
University of Texas. In fact, she works in the office of Mack
Brown, whose brother Watson is a former Sherrill assistant.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, it's kind of a bribe,'' Sherrill said. ``She has a
great singing voice _ she can do opera and C&AMP;W, whatever you want _
and she's like a cross between Whitney Houston and, well, just pick
one. But we didn't want her going up to New York \Rto study\S fresh
out of high school.
</P>
<P>
   ``So we talked her into UT, and we talked Mack into giving her a
job. She's not a spy, honest. In fact, we're all losing her next
year because she's going to New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's done the national anthem at three games. People just
stood and cheered, and cheered ...''
</P>
<P>
   When Sherrill arrived in Starkville, Miss., in '91, the MSU
faithful were agog with dreams of stomping Ole Miss into mush, or
even winning a title. And athletic director Larry Templeton was
fielding criticism as a man who would risk NCAA probation to win.
And now?
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as I'm concerned,'' Templeton said, ``it was a great
hire for Mississippi State. He's been great for the program, a
great friend to the players and the community ... and I have never
really seen that person that was so often described in the media.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you had said back then that Mississippi State would ever
win a championship, people would have laughed. If you had said that
by 1998 Auburn would have gone through three coaches and we would
still have ours, they wouldn't have believed it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a building program under way to expand our stadium,
and we sold 15,000 Cotton Bowl tickets in 14 hours. The last time
we played in a bowl this big was in 1941.
</P>
<P>
   ``How do I feel? Great.''
</P>
<P>
   And so, Jackie Wayne Sherrill is back ... the jovial jokester
slapping Bevo's nose. Just another big game, you see, nothing
special. And if anyone is buying that, they don't play for
Mississippi State.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, he wants this one, make no mistake about that,'' Sluder
said, laughing. ``I think he's really a Texan at heart _ he has
great respect for this state and the people in it, and I think it
is kind of a yardstick for him. This isn't just another game.''
</P>
<P>
   And when someone made a remark about hostile territory,
Sherrill, treated to a Wednesday reunion with many of his old
players, just smiled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Come to the game Friday,'' he said, ``and you will discover
there are a lot of Aggies who aren't in New Orleans. And they won't
be wearing orange.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
