<SLUG> BC-FBC-SUN-RESPECT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TCU EARNS RESPECT WITH UPSET VICTORY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EL PASO, Texas _ In the space of three sun-splashed hours in the
Sun Bowl, the Southern California Trojans went from supremely
confident to stunned.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm at a loss for words,'' USC flanker and kick returner Jay
Soward said after the Horned Frogs' stunning 28-19 victory. ``It's
mind-boggling. We lost to TCU. We're better than that.''
</P>
<P>
   That attitude, some of the Horned Frogs said, was a big reason
why TCU pulled off the upset. The mighty Trojans, with their
storied history and Pac-10 pedigree, didn't take their lowly WAC
opponents seriously.
</P>
<P>
   ``A team like USC disrespected us, and at the end we had the
final word,'' TCU cornerback Andre Bruce said.
</P>
<P>
   USC coach Paul Hackett admitted that perhaps his team did take
the Horned Frogs lightly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have to say maybe we did,'' Hackett said. ``We just
weren't ready to go.''
</P>
<P>
   That would be a plausible explanation for the Horned Frogs'
domination in the first half, when they took a 21-3 lead.
</P>
<P>
   However, Hackett said there was another reason.
</P>
<P>
   The issue was not respect. It was speed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole problem is the speed they have is not something you
can simulate in practice, especially speed on the turf,'' Hackett
said. ``The option, the way they run it, the way they execute, is
tough to stop. After halftime I thought we had a handle on it, but
21 points was too much to overcome.''
</P>
<P>
   The Horned Frogs rushed for 314 yards, including 185 by Basil
Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a matter of us not respecting TCU,'' Chris Claiborne,
USC's Butkus Award-winning linebacker, said. ``We definitely
respected them. It's just a matter of getting it done on the field,
and we didn't get it done.''
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans also had trouble running themselves. They finished
with minus-23 yards rushing, the worst day in school history.
Tailback Chad Morton, who averaged 96.7 yards per game, was held to
21 on 11 carries.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't believe they were stopping it,'' USC quarterback
Carson Palmer said. ``I was completely surprised. They completely
shut us down, and made us throw the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans lost because they couldn't run, and they couldn't
stop the run. The respect issue, they said, was in the Horned
Frogs' minds, not on the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``They might have had a small man's complex, I think,''
Claiborne said. ``The point spread, them coming from TCU and us
being a powerhouse. They handed us our food, and we had to eat
it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
