<HEADLINE>
SNAKE HUNTING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF CAPLAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Seven times this season, Jake ``The Snake''
Plummer has rallied his team to victory in the fourth quarter, and
he has delivered the Cardinals into the playoffs for the first time
since 1982.
</P>
<P>
   ``He makes you feel no matter the situation, he's going to get
the job done,'' Cardinals coach Vince Tobin said.
</P>
<P>
   Slowing down Plummer, who is second in the NFC in total passing
yards behind Steve Young, is another story. Although the Cardinals'
rushing attack with Adrian Murrell runs hot and cold, Plummer
thrives off his ability to create in and out of the pocket.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the most dangerous time is when I'm out of the pocket
and making guys miss and getting out of there when you think you've
got a sack,'' Plummer said. ``Defensive guys and coordinators will
agree that any guy that has the ability to do that is dangerous.
It's frustrating for the defense.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys could find themselves in a quandary. Although Deion
Sanders is expected to play despite a toe injury, a bad pass rush
defense will play without injured sack leader Kavika Pittman. And
the Cowboys haven't forgotten Plummer's slice-and-dice job on a
depleted secondary Nov. 15 after Sanders left with an injured toe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if we can \Rcontain Plummer\S,'' Cowboys safety
George Teague said. ``Before right now, I would have said yeah, but
the way he is playing now, he's gotten a lot better.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Cowboys coach Chan Gailey: ``You always are trying to keep
things mixed up on him and then sit back. You just want to try to
keep him off balance if you can. When he gets in a rhythm, he's
like most quarterbacks, they're tough when they get in a rhythm.''
</P>
</TEXT>
