<HEADLINE>
IRVIN WOULD LIKE ANOTHER SHUTOUT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN LYONS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Michael Irvin does not lie awake at night
thinking about what happened the last time he faced the Arizona
Cardinals, when his consecutive games streak of catching at least
one pass ended at 117.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's gone out of my head,'' Irvin said. ``If I get the same
result and we get the same result then I'm fine. I'll take that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys took a 35-28 victory over the Cardinals with no
catches from Irvin, and no balls thrown to him until just over two
minutes remained in the game at Arizona on Nov. 15. Cardinals Pro
Bowl cornerback Aeneas Williams shadowed Irvin for much of the day
and occasionally had help from a safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``Studying the film, Aeneas did a great job and they had a great
scheme,'' Irvin said.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals do not expect another shutout. Irvin has more
career touchdown receptions against the Cardinals (eight) than he
has against any other club. Irvin did not get in the end zone in
the first Cowboys-Cardinals game on Sept. 6, but he burned Williams
for nine receptions for 119 yards, including a long of 37 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Michael is pretty hard to shut out; I don't think we'll shut
him out again,'' Cardinals coach Vince Tobin said. ``Michael is a
top quality receiver who will be in the Hall of Fame. You try to
control a guy like that and not let him be a dominant force.
Michael is going to make plays.'' TICKET INFORMATION As of 4 p.m.
yesterday, approximately 4,000 tickets remained for tomorrow's
Cowboys-Cardinals game. If the remaining tickets are not sold by 5
p.m. today, the game will not be seen on local television.
</P>
<P>
   Tickets, ranging in price from $52 to $72, can still be
purchased at all Kroger, Fiesta and Foley's Ticketmaster locations.
</P>
<P>
   Fans can purchase tickets by phone by calling Ticketmaster at
(214) 373-8000 or (972) 647-5700. Tickets can also be ordered by
calling the Cowboys at (972) 579-4800.
</P>
<P>
   Tickets purchased by phone through Ticketmaster can be picked up
at the Gate 8 box office at Texas Stadium today from 9 a.m. to 9
p.m. Photo I.D. is required to pick up tickets. INJURY REPORT
Strong safety Darren Woodson gave the Cowboys a scare near the end
of practice when he fell untouched while running. Turns out, he had
reaggravated his sprained left ankle. He walked off the field under
his own power and left practice early as a precaution. He said he
was feeling much better after practice. ``I just tweaked it a
little bit,'' he said. ``I'll be all right.'' ... Tight end David
LaFleur completed his third consecutive day of practice and appears
ready to make a start tomorrow for the first time since spraining
his right knee against the Saints on Dec. 16. Third time a charm
This is the fifth time that the Cowboys will have played a division
opponent three times in one season. In 1972 they were 1-2 against
the Redskins, with a loss in the NFC Championship Game. In 1980
they were 1-2 against the Eagles with a loss in the NFC
Championship Game. In 1992 they were 2-1 against the Eagles, with a
win in the divisional playoffs. And in 1995 they were 2-1 against
the Eagles, with a win in the divisional playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   In the Super Bowl era, there have been 12 playoff games between
division opponents in which one team had swept the other in the
regular season. The team that swept won seven games. The team that
was swept won five. The Cowboys-Cardinals game will be the 13th
such game. Here is a rundown of the previous 12.
</P>
<P>
   A rundown: Year Regular season sweep Team that won playoff game
1997 New England over Miami New England 1997 Green Bay over Tampa
Bay Green Bay 1994 Pittsburgh over Cleveland Pittsburgh 1994
Minnesota over Chicago Chicago 1993 Raiders over Denver Raiders
1992 Kansas City over San Diego San Diego 1991 Kansas City over
Oakland Kansas City 1989 Oilers over Pittsburgh Pittsburgh 1986
Giants over Washington Giants 1983 Seattle over Oakland Oakland
1982 Miami over Jets Miami 1969 Oakland over Kansas City Kansas
City
</P>
</TEXT>
