<SLUG> BC-FBC-FIESTA-VOLS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TENNESSEE'S WILSON HITS AS HARD AS HE DID IN THE RING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. _ He coulda been a contender. Instead, he's the
defensive leader of the nation's top-ranked team.
</P>
<P>
   Al Wilson is Tennessee's senior middle linebacker. When the
Volunteers take the field Monday night against No. 2 Florida State
in the Fiesta Bowl, they'll look to Wilson for inspiration and
direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not going to tell you how good he is; he's going to go
out and show you,'' Tennessee defensive coordinator John Chavis
said of Wilson. ``Playing football means a lot to him. He has a
passion for the game, a hunger.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson thinks that desire was inflamed as a youngster in
Jackson, Tenn. Wilson's first sport, his first love, was boxing.
And, according to his first coach, Wilson could have a future in
the squared circle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Al had more talent than anybody I've ever had,'' said Rayford
Collins, the 35-year director of the Jackson Boxing Club.
``Somebody with his skills you see maybe once every thousand
boxers. He could have been another Evander Holyfield. Even at that
age, his hand-eye coordination was so slick he could avoid getting
hit anytime he wanted.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Al had stuck with boxing he could have been an Olympic
gold-medal winner.''
</P>
<P>
   But when he was 14, after three years of boxing, Wilson saw two
of his friends die because of injuries suffered in the ring. He
quit boxing and started playing football. Wilson found his boxing
training transferred easily.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boxing meant a lot to me, and I was pretty good at it,''
Wilson said. ``It gave me the attitude and the mentality to give my
all in whatever I do.''
</P>
<P>
   Last season, Wilson played a supporting role to All-America
linebacker Leonard Little. This season, he moved from the outside
to the middle. A 6-foot, 226-pounder, he has become the epicenter
of the Volunteers' defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, he's the leader of the team,'' said junior outside
linebacker Raynoch Thompson. ``He plays with a passion, shows a lot
of emotion. I'm upset because this is going to be my last game
playing with him. It's been a great gift playing with a guy like
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of injuries _ separated shoulder and pulled groin muscle
_ Wilson missed three games this season. He played most of the
season even though his shoulder was often reinjured after a hard
hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Al is not going to let nicks and bruises stop him,'' Thompson
said. ``He's like the Energizer Bunny; he just keeps going and
going. He's inspired me, seeing him go out and play in pain.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson downplays his leadership role.
</P>
<P>
   ``I consider myself one of the veterans on the defense,'' said
Wilson, who had 77 tackles this season. ``We have a lot of leaders
on defense. I've been here for a while and know what's going on.
I'm just a guy who goes out and plays football. I'm not a guy to go
out and say I'm a leader.''
</P>
<P>
   So, he lets his play do the talking. In Tennessee's pivotal
game, a 20-17 victory over Florida, Wilson wrecked the Gators'
offense by forcing three fumbles that the Volunteers recovered.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson is known among his teammates for his split personality.
Off the field, he's quiet, religious, a guy who likes to hang out,
tell jokes and laugh it up. Then, at game time, he turns into a
tackling terror; his defensive teammates often keep one eye on the
ball carrier and one on Wilson so they don't absorb one of his hard
hits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love football. I go out to play, and I go out to win,''
Wilson said. ``I believe when you step between the white lines,
it's time to go to war, time to take care of our business. When I
go out on the field, I've got the mentality that I want to make
every play on defense.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-31-98 2328EST &QL; 
