<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-SUGAR-AGGIES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIGHTING AGGIES' FIRE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ At some point before kickoff in the Sugar Bowl
tonight, Texas A&AMP;M tight end Dan Campbell will address his
teammates one final time. Campbell isn't sure what he'll say, but
he knows his words will drip with emotion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to give some crappy speech I've planned. That's
not how you get people motivated,'' Campbell said. ``People want to
hear things from the heart.''
</P>
<P>
   The Aggies know they will hang on every word uttered by the
fifth-year senior from Glen Rose, who has emerged as the spiritual
leader for a group of overachievers with a chance to tie the
school's season record for victories. By knocking off Ohio State
(10-1), the No. 3 team in The Associated Press poll, the
eighth-ranked Aggies (11-2) would notch their 12th win of the
season and their third as a double-digit underdog.
</P>
<P>
   Teammates point to Campbell's work ethic and persuasive voice as
a big reason why a team that ``easily could have been 6-5,'' in the
estimation of coach R.C. Slocum, will carry a swagger into the
Superdome as a 121/2 point underdog against the Buckeyes.
</P>
<P>
   When teammates' concentration levels dip during practice, it is
Campbell who thrusts his 6-foot-5, 262-pound frame into the fray to
restore order.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll get in someone's face and say, `This is bullcorn. Let's
get it together,' '' tailback Dante Hall said. ``A lot of guys
might be feeling it. Dan comes out and says it. He'll get you fired
up.''
</P>
<P>
   When a teammate is down, Campbell is quick with a smile and some
encouraging words. When he makes a mistake, there is never an
alibi. Listen to teammates and they'll tell you that Campbell is an
embodiment of the warrior tattoo he wears on his right shoulder, a
replica of a tribal symbol etched on the faces of braves who
distinguished themselves in battle.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's definitely the outspoken leader of this team,'' strong
safety Rich Coady said. ``He's not afraid to say what he thinks,
and it's something this team rallies around. Guys feed off that,
especially the younger guys. As far as us doing what we've done, I
think a lot of it has to go to people like Dan Campbell. He's
almost like another coach out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Slocum, in fact, described Campbell as a ``player-coach'' for
the 1998 Aggies. Campbell's season statistics show only seven
catches for 68 yards, but Slocum shudders to think where the Aggies
would be without his locker room influence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dan has been one of those real inspirational, heart and soul
guys. That fieriness and emotional play, that's what allowed him to
be a good leader,'' Slocum said. ``If you had a team full of guys
like that, you wouldn't lose many games.''
</P>
<P>
   It is not by accident that Campbell, a player who never earned
all-conference credentials during his college career, plays as big
a role in directing the Aggies' fortunes as linebacker Dat Nguyen,
winner of the 1998 Lombardi and Bednarik awards. Campbell began
asserting himself in the wake of a 51-15 loss to Texas that ended
the 1996 season because he ``never wanted to go 6-6 again.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I absolutely cannot stand to lose. That day, I decided I was
going to do what I could do to be a leader on this team, and it's
kind of grown from there,'' said Campbell, who addresses the team
on a daily basis but saves his emotional appeals for big games.
</P>
<P>
   The last one he gave was before the Aggies' 36-33 victory over
then-unbeaten Kansas State in the Big 12 title game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just sitting there and I decided, `It's time for me to
say something,' '' Campbell said. ``So I called everybody into the
shower and told them that ... I loved them, that I'd do anything
for them. That I was going to give 110 percent of myself and
expected them to do the same. I told them that for big games,
you've got to have big plays. And we had a lot of big plays in that
game.''
</P>
<P>
   The Aggies also won, earning a trip to the Sugar Bowl. To knock
off the favored Buckeyes, A&AMP;M figures to need some extra emotional
ammunition. Campbell will be the guy to light the fuse. Nguyen said
he'll be listening, as always.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dan's a huge part of our success,'' Nguyen said. ``He's one of
those guys that, if you went to war, he'd protect us before he
protects himself. When he talks, everybody will listen because he's
been there. I respect him and everybody does. He was born to be a
leader, it seems like.''
</P>
<P>
   Campbell also is a hidden reason why an A&AMP;M team that is 5-1 in
games decided by a touchdown or less is in position to win its 12th
game of an improbable, yet unforgettable, season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
