<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-COYOTES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INJURED COYOTES WILL TEST STARS TONIGHT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Go ahead, admit it _ tonight's showdown
between the Stars and Phoenix Coyotes has lost a little bit of its
luster.
</P>
<P>
   With the Coyotes' top line of Jeremy Roenick (concussion), Keith
Tkachuk (broken rib) and Dallas Drake (suspension) not expected to
play, the battle between the NHL's two winningest teams isn't quite
the New Year's Day bowl-stealer it might have been.
</P>
<P>
   Just don't tell that to the Stars.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be honest, it could be an even tougher game without them,''
Stars defenseman Craig Ludwig said of the Coyotes' injured trio.
``Last year, when we had all of our injuries, we played some of our
best hockey of the season because everybody stepped it up a notch.
I'm sure they'll be the same way.''
</P>
<P>
   The latest injury twist only adds another layer to the quietly
rumbling rivalry that is building between the Stars and Coyotes
this season. Longtime divisional rivals who have squared off 78
times since 1979, the Stars and Coyotes will meet six times this
season. So far, they have split two games in Dallas _ a 2-1 Stars
victory on Oct. 11 and a 2-0 victory by Phoenix on Nov. 11.
</P>
<P>
   Since that meeting in early November, the Stars and Coyotes have
soared to the top of the NHL standings, with the Stars (22-5-6)
ranking first and the Coyotes (21-7-4) second in winning
percentage.
</P>
<P>
   That's enough to stoke any rivalry, but a little sticking point
in the NHL playoff scenario has both sides watching the standings
even closer. Because division winners receive the top three seeds
in each respective conference, the second-place team in the Pacific
Division can be seeded only as high as No. 4 in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   If the playoffs started today, the Coyotes would be seeded
behind the Northwest Division leading Colorado Avalanche, despite
having nine fewer losses.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a stupid rule, but it's a rule we have to play by,''
Stars defenseman Darryl Sydor said. ``I mean, we're not thinking
about the playoffs right now, it's too early. But we know it's a
four-point game, and it could be big at the end of the season.''
</P>
<P>
   By that, Sydor means that the Stars can not only take two
standings points with a victory, but also can take two potential
points away from the Coyotes. Conversely, a loss would mean Phoenix
is two steps closer to catching the Stars for first in the Pacific
Division. And that speaks nothing to the psychological implications
of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time we play against the Red Wings or Dallas, we've got to
compete with those guys,'' Coyotes winger Jim Cummins said of an
up-and-coming Phoenix team which is still trying to prove it
belongs among the NHL elite. ``And not only compete, but beat those
guys, so that when we do meet in the playoffs, we can play them
with confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Coyotes defenseman Oleg Tverdovsky said the Coyotes have much to
gain from a victory tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can get the job done against them \Rwithout our injured
players\S, it will mean a lot to the team,'' Tverdovsky said.
</P>
<P>
   Even Hitchcock is in on the mental edge of the game. The Coyotes
boast the league's second best home record at 11-2-1 and recently
had an 11-game home winning streak snapped by the Los Angeles
Kings.
</P>
<P>
   ``In some ways, we're disappointed that LA beat Phoenix,''
Hitchcock said. ``They hadn't lost in so many home games, and we
wanted to be the team to beat them.''
</P>
<P>
   It's that kind of logic that ensures this isn't just another
game, even if Roenick, Tkachuk and Drake are sidelined. The Coyotes
still have one of the most talented, free skating group of
defenseman in the league and have talented young forwards in Daniel
Briere and Brad Isbister. They'll be getting the Stars on the
second night of back-to-back games and there still is that matter
of a certain ``source'' quoted in the ``Arizona Republic'' a month
ago. The nameless accuser questioned the Stars' chemistry and said
one of the Stars players said he felt like taking a swing at
Hitchcock.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't forgotten that,'' said center Brian Skrudland, one
of the many Stars players who called the rumors bunk.
</P>
<P>
   ``In fact, I heard one of the Coyotes players was thinking of
taking a swing at Schoenfeld,'' he added sarcastically. ``Go ahead
and print that.''
</P>
<P>
   Let the rivalry begin.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
