<SLUG> BC-FBC-TCU-DEFENSE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIG PLAYS SACK UP THE SUN FOR FROGS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EL PASO, Texas _ A huddle of defensive players had formed on
TCU's sideline, waiting for a final word from cornerback Andre
Bruce before going in for another series midway through the fourth
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   He had a simple message.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just said that somebody needed to make a play,'' Horned
Frogs safety Curtis Fuller said. ``We needed a play.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, TCU got a couple.
</P>
<P>
   TCU got back-to-back sacks of Southern California signal caller
Carson Palmer and then a stop for no gain to wrest back control of
a game that until then seemed to be turning USC's way.
</P>
<P>
   Spurred by that defensive series, TCU held on for a 28-19
victory against USC in the Sun Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``A single play usually turns a game,'' Frogs defensive end
London Dunlap said. ``What that play is, you never know. I hope my
play had a little of that game-turning impact.''
</P>
<P>
   A little, and then some.
</P>
<P>
   TCU's seemingly invincible 28-3 lead had dissolved into a very
vulnerable 28-19 margin. Southern California had scored on
back-to-back-to-back series, and were passing at will on TCU's
secondary.
</P>
<P>
   So when TCU faltered again, necessitating another Frogs punt and
giving USC another chance, Palmer said he felt TCU dangling
dangerously close to collapsing.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could feel it,'' Palmer said. ``I thought we were going to
march right down the field and score. I got sacked a couple of
times and the momentum completely dropped.''
</P>
<P>
   Dunlap leveled him for a 2-yard loss, then combined with Raymone
Lacey to yank Palmer down for a 6-yard loss.
</P>
<P>
   So USC needed 18 yards, and went to where yards had been easy to
come by _ by throwing on Bruce.
</P>
<P>
   Palmer dumped a little screen pass to R. Jay Soward. He needed
only to get by Bruce for a big gain. Instead, Bruce leveled him for
no gain.
</P>
<P>
   He had followed his advice.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I said that, Curtis Fuller looked at me and said `You
make a play,' '' Bruce said. ``He was right. USC had been going
after me all game, and gotten some big plays. It was my turn to
make a big play.''
</P>
<P>
   TCU's defense had plenty of big plays until then, holding USC to
its worst rushing day in school history (negative-23 yards),
holding USC to a single field goal in the first half and mainly
holding USC at bay.
</P>
<P>
   Then the plays started to come, Palmer started to get warm, and
TCU looked to be close to folding.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be honest, I felt it slipping away,'' Frogs defensive
tackle J.W. Wilson admitted. ``Andre was right, though. We just
needed to make a play. He said it was in our hands and we grabbed
it back.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
