<HEADLINE>
SYDOR PLEASE TEAMMATES, BUT NOT HIMSELF
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Stars center Joe Nieuwendyk says teammate Darryl Sydor
is playing so well, he should garner consideration for the award
given to the NHL's top defenseman.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you watch Syd every game, he's been great,'' Nieuwendyk
said. ``Darryl Sydor is geting better and better every year, and I
think it's time the league has to start looking at him as a
potential Norris Trophy winner.''
</P>
<P>
   Sydor doesn't agree. While the 26-year-old leads the NHL in
defensemen scoring with 27 points before last night's game, he said
he's more concerned that his plus-minus is at minus-5.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe in the stat, and I believe mine should be better,''
Sydor said of the statistic that measures goals scored when a
player is on the ice in an even-strength situation. ``I've been on
the ice for far too many goals against.''
</P>
<P>
   Sydor's minus-5 is the worst on the Stars. Even more alarming,
it comes on the heels of last season's plus-17 and a career-best
plus-37 in 1996-97. SKRUDLAND RETURNS Stars center Brian Skrudland,
who missed two games with a strained back, returned to the lineup
last night and played on a line with Dave Reid and Guy Carbonneau.
</P>
<P>
   Brent Severyn still is sidelined by a back injury. Dan Keczmer
and Sergey Gusev were healthy scratches. WILSON PLAYS Bruins winger
Landon Wilson played last night for the fourth time in his career
against the Stars _ a somewhat special moment because he is the son
of Stars assistant coach Rick Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   Landon, 23, was called up recently from the Bruins minor-league
team In Providence, R.I. and played his second game of the season.
ROENICK RESTLESS Phoenix Coyotes center Jeremy Roenick told the
``Arizona Republic'' Wednesday that he would like to play in
tonight's game against the Stars in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope they let me,'' he said. ``They told me no, but you know
me, I'll keep digging.''
</P>
<P>
   Coyotes coach Jim Schoenfeld said he did not expect Roenick in
the lineup. When told about Roenick's desire to play, Schoenfeld
quipped: ``It sounds like he's suffering from post-concussion
syndrome.'' TICKETS AVAILABLE The Stars last night played host to
their 13th consecutive sellout of 16,928.
</P>
<P>
   They will on Monday open single-game ticket sales to games in
March and April. Tickets range from $14-$50. Call 214-GO-STARS.
NEXT FIVE Today at Phoenix, 8 p.m. Wednesday vs. Vancouver, 7:30
p.m. Jan. 8 at Calgary, 8 p.m. Jan. 10 at Vancouver, 9 p.m. Jan. 12
at Edmonton, 8 p.m.
</P>
</TEXT>
