<HEADER>
A4439 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-COTTON-TEX     12-31 0721
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-COTTON-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CUE THE QUARTERBACKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE JONES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ The week leading up to today's 63rd Southwestern Bell
Cotton Bowl kickoff has brought us snippets of a more relaxed and
personable Jackie Sherrill at Mississippi State. It has also
brought the ever-bubbly Mack Brown, who has been rewarded for a
magical first season at Texas with a new 10-year contract.
</P>
<P>
   Compliments and expressions of admiration for innovative and
productive schemes have abounded from the teams' respective
offensive and defensive co-ordinators. Players and coaches have
extolled the virtues of the Longhorns' Heisman Trophy-winning
running back, Ricky Williams, and his hard-hitting counterpart,
James Johnson, the leading rusher in the Southeastern Conference
despite injuries that limited his production during the final three
games of the season.
</P>
<P>
   All things appearing to be equal, despite Texas' status as a
touchdown favorite at this morning's 10:15 kickoff, center stage
belongs to Opie Taylor and Chris Rock look-alikes _ quarterbacks
Major Applewhite of Texas and Wayne Madkin of Mississippi State.
</P>
<P>
   Therein lies the key to today's game in the opinions of many _
Sherrill included.
</P>
<P>
   ``The two teams are similar in a lot of phases, and I really
feel it's going to be a good matchup,'' Sherrill pointed out.
``We're not going to stop Ricky Williams because no one else has.
The difference in the game is going to be which quarterback plays
the best.''
</P>
<P>
   Both have had remarkable redshirt-freshman seasons.
</P>
<P>
   The mobile Madkin unseated a senior, started the last nine games
and led the Bulldogs late when Johnson nursed a groin injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``His development has been much like Major's,'' Brown said.
``When they are that young, you can take a guy and build on what he
does. He's a much better player at the end of the year than he was
at the beginning.''
</P>
<P>
   Applewhite stepped in for injured fifth-year senior Richard
Walton and the Longhorns' passing attack blossomed. He set freshman
school passing records with 2,453 yards and 18 touchdowns _ both
No. 2 on the school's all-time list. Receivers Wane McGarity and
Kwame Cavil became Texas' most productive receiving tandem ever
(109 receptions for 1,862 yards).
</P>
<P>
   Combined with Williams' 2,124 yards rushing, the quarterback Big
12 coaches voted freshman of the year and the Bomb Squad turned the
Longhorns' offense into one of the nation's most balanced and
potent attacks that ranked 11th nationally in both total offense
(470.6) and scoring (36.3).
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone wants to make fun of Major,'' McGarity said. ``He's
short, a baby-faced freshman, red-haired and he looks like Opie.
But the guy performs. He's not a rookie anymore. Everyone's tried
to rattle Major. The way he's responded is incredible.''
</P>
<P>
   Everything the remarkably poised Applewhite has learned will be
tested by the Bulldogs' jumping-around, chaos-creating defensive
scheme led by all-out pass rushing defensive end Edward Smith (12
sacks).
</P>
<P>
   ``Major will get a chance to see probably more than he's ever
seen this year in one game,'' Sherrill predicted, tipping the
Bulldogs' defensive game plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``They base their defense on confusion and they have been known
to blitz a lot,'' Applewhite said. ``But both the Ryan brothers
\RRex, former defensive coordinator at Oklahoma and Rob, defensive
coordinator at Oklahoma State\S love to blitz. OU blitzed the whole
game. And I think \Rplaying those two teams\S gave me a good
preview of what it's going to be like in this game.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas defeated Oklahoma, 34-3, and won a shootout with Oklahoma
State, 37-34.
</P>
<P>
   Brown said he's given up worrying about Applewhite.
</P>
<P>
   ``UCLA \Rwhen he relieved Walton\S wasn't a problem because he
didn't think he was going to play,'' Brown said. ``We all worried
about how he would perform at Kansas State. And though it didn't
work out for us overall, he did OK.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then we all worried about Oklahoma, and I thought he did well
against every blitz known to man. We worried about Texas A&AMP;M, and,
gosh, on the \Rwinning\S drive he was about as good as you can be.
So, I don't think he'll be any different \Rtoday\S. He's got some
gray in that red hair now.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bulldogs are counting on adding a few more strands today.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
