<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-31 23:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4440 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-TCU-SUNBOWL-TEX     12-31 0657
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TCU-SUNBOWL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELIEF IN THEMSELVES GIVES FROGS A DAY IN THE SUN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EL PASO, Texas _ TCU coach Dennis Franchione paused for a
second, a crowd bustling behind him at Sun Bowl Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   At that moment, he looked so much like a little boy.
</P>
<P>
   His hands jammed into his pockets, his gaze focusing on shoes,
his eyes dancing mischievously, his smile flashing uncontrollably
as he talked of TCU's 28-19 upset of Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   Franchione had a little boy-like faith to go along with his
little boy-like look, saying he believed all along that TCU's Sun
Bowl victory against USC to be inevitable instead of improbable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we always believed we could win. I really do,''
Franchione said. ``We were like `The Little Engine That Could.' The
more people told them they couldn't do it, the more they believed
they could.''
</P>
<P>
   The little team that could did so again.
</P>
<P>
   They did so by rushing for more yards than the program with the
running back tradition, by playing better defense than the program
with the Butkus Award winner, by getting bigger plays than the
program that had built a season around them, by getting their first
bowl victory since 1957 against one of the winningest bowl programs
in the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm at a loss for words,'' Trojans R. Jay Soward said. ``It's
mind boggling. We lost to TCU. We're better than that.''
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday, the Frogs proved they were better than them.
</P>
<P>
   They say they did it by simply believing that they could do what
everybody told them they couldn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did anybody think we were going to win this game?'' Frogs
tailback Basil Mitchell said. ``We heard it all week, and we
finally figured we could either just give up or prove them wrong.
We decided to prove them wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   He rushed for 185 yards, second-best in Sun Bowl history,
including scoring TCU's first two touchdowns en route to earning
game MVP honors.
</P>
<P>
   TCU rushed for 314 yards while USC had a school-worst minus-23
yards on the ground. USC seemed befuddled as much by TCU's
defensive line as by its option.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to ask coach \RFranchione\S if I can come and study
his option game,'' USC coach Paul Hackett said. ``It's something
that's foreign to our conference.''
</P>
<P>
   USC covered Mitchell to prevent him from burning them, so Frogs
signal caller Patrick Batteaux simply took over. Batteaux finished
with 94 yards and two touchdowns, his last coming right after
halftime and giving TCU a 28-3 lead.
</P>
<P>
   USC (8-5) made adjustments, basically shutting down the Horned
Frogs option attack in the second half and peppering their
secondary with long passes. Trojans quarterback Carson Palmer threw
for two touchdowns to pull the Trojans to within 28-19.
</P>
<P>
   The Frogs (7-5) were challenged, but didn't fold.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we ever doubted whether or not we were going to
win this game,'' Frogs defensive end Kam Hunt said. ``You don't
come from where we came from and get to where we got to by
doubting.''
</P>
<P>
   TCU finished 1-10 last season, the single victory coming in Week
11 of a long, long season. Players feared another long season.
After all, a new coach was coming in and though nobody would say
so, it looked like a long rebuilding project.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Horned Frogs finished with six victories more than
last season. The Sun Bowl victory ended their season with a 7-5
mark. Only Louisville had a similar turnaround, going from 1-10
last season to 7-5 this season.
</P>
<P>
   The Frogs wrote the script that nobody thought was possible, and
then yesterday, they added the ending that nobody except for maybe
the Frogs themselves dreamed of.
</P>
<P>
   You see, they know how the story of the Little Engine That Could
ended.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't quit until you get to the top, until you've achieved
what you set out to achieve,'' Mitchell said. ``The obstacles just
make it that much sweeter.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
