<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-DEION-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW HOPE FOR DEION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ The prospects of Cowboys cornerback Deion
Sanders playing in tomorrow's NFC wild-card playoff game against
the Arizona Cardinals increased yesterday after his most
encouraging workout since straining his left big toe 61/2 games
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did Sanders do rehabilitation work on the practice
field under the watchful eyes of Cowboys trainer Jim Maurer for the
third consecutive day, but he participated in some drills with the
first-team defense _ even flashing glimpses of his old brilliance
by breaking up a couple of passes.
</P>
<P>
   After practice, Sanders said his toe felt fine, but wanted to
see how it felt last night and today to the workout. As for his
playing status, he reverted to the biblical passage he has been
pointing to all week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm always encouraged,'' said Sanders, who left practice
early. ``Remember what I said, with God all things are possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanders is still listed as doubtful for the game on the team's
injury report. Cowboys coach Chan Gailey said the team wants to see
how he feels today and at game time tomorrow before making a final
decision.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Smith is slated to start at Sanders' right cornerback
spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did some work on the field and moved around better than I'd
seen him in a while,'' Gailey said. ``It will be a game-time
decision as to what he will do.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Gailey tried his best to downplay the magnitude of
Sanders' progress, partly because ``you can't get excited, because
if you do that, you get too disappointed if he's not there.''
</P>
<P>
   Gailey's talking about having to make a decision about Sanders
just a few days after all but ruling him out of the game seems to
indicate progress. The fact that he is still listed as doubtful
shouldn't be looked at as a negative either _ considering that
Cowboys guard Everett McIver went from ``doubtful'' to the starting
lineup against Seattle last month.
</P>
<P>
   Maurer was also pleased with Sanders' work yesterday and said it
was all part of the plan that they established when Sanders
returned from being evaluated in Palm Beach, Fla., by foot
specialist Dr. Bill Hamilton on Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had to show that he can do the functional drills in a team
atmosphere,'' Maurer said. ``He did almost everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanders' return would certainly be a boost for the Cowboys'
defense against the Cardinals. The Cowboys have been a different
team since his absence.
</P>
<P>
   The defense ranked seventh in the league overall and 13th
against the pass during the first nine games with Sanders on the
field. Since his injury against the Cardinals on Nov. 15, the
Cowboys have dropped to 19th overall and 22nd against the pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you can see him out there practicing, it's
encouraging,'' strong safety Darren Woodson said. ``We learned to
play without him. And we've gotten better. We have to go into this
game prepared to play without him. But we are a better team with
him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
