<HEADLINE>
SOWARD LEANS TOWARD STAYING AT USC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EL PASO _ USC wide receiver R. Jay Soward told his father that
he would return to school following the Trojans' 28-19 loss to
Texas Christian in the Sun Bowl, but as is usually the case with
Soward, the final word will come later.
</P>
<P>
   ``He says he's staying... but I still need to talk to him,''
Rodney Soward said.
</P>
<P>
   R. Jay Soward told reporters Thursday that he wasn't sure if he
would return to USC for his senior season, although he tried to
fool everyone by flatly stating that he would turn pro. It was a
joke.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got a couple days, he'll change his mind,'' USC
linebacker Chris Claiborne said.
</P>
<P>
   Soward had six receptions for 64 yards, and one carry for 1 yard
against TCU.
</P>
<P>
   Although Soward told his father he wants to return, Rodney
Soward appeared less certain about what he will advise his son to
do. This is a departure from Tuesday, when he said he hoped his son
would return.
</P>
<P>
   Among Rodney Soward's concerns is that his son will be USC's
only veteran receiver next season, allowing teams to double-team R.
Jay every game. The elder Soward would also like his son's role to
expand beyond running deep pass routes.
</P>
<P>
   Soward must make his final decision by Jan. 8.
</P>
<P>
   Claiborne press conference set: USC linebacker Chris Claiborne
said he will hold his press conference Tuesday to make his official
announcement whether he will turn pro. Claiborne was having a hard
time masking his intentions following the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``My main thing is you only get drafted once and you may not be
able to make up that money if you drop down (the next year),''
Claiborne said. ``(Soward) might not be worried about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. 985: Tailback Chad Morton's seemingly sure bid to gain 1,000
yards was halted by TCU. Morton was held to 18 yards rushing, and
fell 15 short of 1,000 for the season.
</P>
<P>
   Injury report: USC not only lost but got beaten up during the
game. Linebackers David Gibson and Darryl Knight suffered
concussions, while defensive tackle Ennis Davis left the game with
a sprained left knee. Safety Ife Ohalete sprained his right ankle
and linebacker Mark Cusano sprained his right elbow.
</P>
<P>
   Bowl drought: TCU coach Dennis Franchione was asked how it felt
to be the first coach to win a bowl game at the school in 41 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has no significance to me. I haven't been here for 41
years,'' Franchione said. ``I can't carry that 41 years on my
shoulders. Maybe if I'd lost seven or eight bowl games, it would.''
</P>
<P>
   Sweet revenge: TCU wide receiver Michael Crawford grew up a USC
fan in Orange County, and still owns several USC sweatshirts. So he
was obviously elated by the Horned Frogs' victory. ``I always
wanted to play for these guys but beating these guys was even
better,'' Crawford said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
