A4449 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-USC-LADN     12-31 0890
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-USC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USC STUNNED BY TCU
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EL PASO _ After a week of receiving red carpet treatment from
the Sun Bowl, USC got run out of town Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Christian University ran the option left. The Horned Frogs
ran it right. They ran it up the middle. And they ran it for 314
yards, en route to a stunning 28-19 victory over the Trojans before
46,612 at Sun Bowl Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   As for USC, the Trojans did their best job running after the
game, sprinting off the field so fast, the teams didn't have much
of a postgame handshake.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans certainly didn't do much running during the game.
While TCU picked apart USC's defense like no other opponent this
season, the Trojans' offense amassed minus-23 yards net rushing,
the lowest total in school history.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just weren't ready to go,'' USC coach Paul Hackett said.
``They're offense's speed and quickness surprised us. I thought our
football team was startled in the first half. TCU, they took it to
us.''
</P>
<P>
   A bowl game many feared would be a dud _ because TCU was 6-5 and
a 16-point underdog _ turned out to be one but for the wrong
reasons. TCU built a 21-0 lead as USC seemed completely confused
defending the option and stretched it to 28-3 before the Trojans
mounted a futile comeback.
</P>
<P>
   TCU (7-5) won its first bowl game since 1957, and tied a school
record for most points in a bowl game. The Horned Frogs' team
rushing total was a bowl record and tailback Basil Mitchell's 185
yards ranked second in Sun Bowl history for an individual.
</P>
<P>
   Other than that, it was a pretty good game for the Trojans
(8-5).
</P>
<P>
   The embarrassing nature of the performance, before a national
television audience, quickly ripped open wounds that had seemingly
healed during a respectable regular season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole point in playing is to win. It's not about
individual stats or awards and all that. And we've got guys, some
guys, out there for themselves,'' cornerback Daylon McCutcheon
said. ``They're not ready to step up and give it to the game.
That's going to kill you. Some people came in and took it as a
vacation instead of playing a football game.
</P>
<P>
   ``You expect guys to have fun but there's a point where you
overdo it and I didn't think the guys did, but I guess they did,
because they weren't ready to play.''
</P>
<P>
   McCutcheon was dumbfounded how his teammates could completely
fall apart after spending nearly a month to prepare for TCU's
option offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had guys going out there and forgetting what they were
supposed to do,'' McCutcheon said. ``We should have had one guy on
the quarterback, and we'd have two and then somebody would be left
open.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost predictably, TCU's players felt they received little
respect from USC. ``I think they took us very lightly. We felt like
they didn't respect us a little bit,'' cornerback Greg Walls said.
</P>
<P>
   But more surprising, USC admitted that it either overlooked TCU
or failed to properly motivate itself for the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have to go back and look and say maybe we did (take
them lightly),'' Hackett said. ``But we didn't think so at the
time. Maybe we have to do the bowl experience differently. This may
inspire us.''
</P>
<P>
   The players were even more emphatic about their failure to
prepare for TCU as hard as they did against Notre Dame in their
regular-season finale.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lesson learned today is no matter who the opponent is,
respect them,'' wide receiver R. Jay Soward said. ``Don't be a
cheerleader during the week. We talked a lot during the week. I
talked a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Moments later, though, he said, ``It's mind boggling to me that
we lost to TCU.''
</P>
<P>
   Although TCU quarterback Patrick Batteaux passed just six times,
he dissected the Trojans' defense by tossing the ball to the
tailback at just the right moment, or keeping it and running for
part of his 94 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know they're going to run,'' linebacker Chris Claiborne
said. ``I told everyone he wouldn't pass. It's just about making
the play. We didn't set the tone of the game on defense. I think it
given the offense the feeling like, `Oh no.' ''
</P>
<P>
   USC did try to make a comeback, mainly behind freshman
quarterback Carson Palmer, who was sacked six times but passed for
280 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Palmer connected with Billy Miller on a 23-yard pass in the
third quarter, then led the Trojans on a 61-yard drive to cut the
lead to 28-16 entering the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Adam Abrams kicked a 46-yard field goal, and the Trojans defense
made a nice stand to hold TCU. The Trojans then had the ball at
their own 42-yard line, but Palmer was sacked twice and the drive
stalled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we would go back on the field and score again but I
got sacked a couple times and you could feel us lose the
momentum,'' Palmer said. ``We knew they would come after us. I had
a lot of time, but I couldn't get it to the receivers.''
</P>
<P>
   TCU took over and ran more than six minutes off the clock,
effectively sealing the fate of the Trojans.
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, it was just too much to ask to make up such a
large deficit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were down 21-0 and the offense couldn't do anything and
(TCU) scored every time they touched the rock,'' Miller said. ``It
was crazy and like a dream.''
</P>
<P>
   Or perhaps a nightmare.
</P>
</TEXT>
